<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNET-ADCAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CNET TURNS TO ADVERTISING  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Cnet has seen the enemy, and it is ... your geek
friend Joe.
<P>
   The San Francisco provider of computer-oriented Web sites and TV
shows is launching its first major ad campaign over the next few
days, the initial round in a $100 million, 12- to 18-month blitz.
But unlike most advertising, which is designed to steal business
from corporate rivals, Cnet believes that its main competitors are
the friends, co-workers and family members whom even computer
enthusiasts turn to first for tech advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main place people get their technology advice is from
tech-savvy people they know,'' said Annie Williams, Cnet vice
president of marketing. Magazines are another key source, she said.
``But there's a huge amount of frustration'' since those sources
don't always have a full range of information.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet (www.cnet.com), which features news articles and reviews of
hardware, software and other techie products, wants to be the first
place people think of when shopping for tech products or
information.
</P>
<P>
   It targets information technology professionals, only 53 percent
of whom currently turn to the Web first for tech advice; corporate
bean counters who sign off on their companies' tech budgets but
don't necessarily understand them; and computer enthusiasts who
want to learn about the latest gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   If those core groups are won over to Cnet's
``one-stop-shopping'' model, they will influence others to check it
out, said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The television spots feature a young man asking for tech
information from traditional advisers _ a doctor and a professor _
who are unable to answer questions about RAM, modem speed and DSL.
A narrator intones, ``Looking for computer information? There's
really only one place to go.'' The spots finish with the Cnet logo
and tagline, ``The source for computers and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cnet attracts more visitors than any other
computer-oriented site _ it is ranked 17th among all digital
properties by Media Metrix _ only 4 percent of regular Web users
know its name. Cnet archrival ZDNet is ranked 19th.
</P>
<P>
   Halsey Minor, Cnet's chairman and chief executive, hopes the
campaign will boost awareness to at least 10 percent of regular Web
users by the end of the year. The goal is to cement the site's
position as the leader in its niche, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minor expects the campaign to generate enough revenue to pay for
itself in 2000, and to add to profits in 2001. Seven-year-old Cnet
has $700 million in cash and stock on its balance sheet, so it
won't have to scrape to pay for the ads.
</P>
<P>
   By waiting until its seventh year to launch consumer
advertising, Cnet is starting quite late compared to, for example,
Amazon.com, the online bookstore. Amazon consistently posts losses
because it spends so much of its revenues on marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arguably, they should have done this earlier, but they wanted
to have some profitable quarters first,'' said Patrick Keane, a
senior analyst with Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   But Cnet doesn't appear to have been hurt by the late entry,
Keane added. ``If there's a firmly entrenched winner in this
category, it's Cnet, so they can only grow the audience they
already have. It's not like they're AltaVista, trying to get from
fifth to first and coming from absolutely nowhere.``
</P>
<P>
   Cnet's print and outdoor ads feature slogans such as ``Friends
don't let friends give tech advice'' with Cnet's signature yellow
and green colors.
</P>
<P>
   Web banner ads, the only type of consumer advertising Cnet has
done in the past, will constitute about 10 percent of the new
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marks the start of the blitz with radio spots and a
full-page ad in the Wall Street Journal. Next week consumers in the
country's 10 ``most wired'' markets will start to see ads on
network television shows like David Letterman and the X Files.
Magazine and additional newspaper ads will begin running next week
and billboards will go up in August.
</P>
<P>
   Williams expects the TV spots, which feature somewhat adolescent
humor, to offend some viewers, especially women.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, for example, a biology professor who cannot answer
a question about modem speed advises his student to look for
answers in ``nature'' and hands him a fetal pig in a jar. The
student is then shown holding the dripping, dead piglet and looking
at it quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   In the second spot, a doctor who cannot answer a question about
RAM decides to perform an anal exam on the patient instead.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said focus groups of men in their 40s and 50s loved the
spots. But Rob Enderle, an analyst with Giga Information Group,
said the ads could hurt the Cnet brand. ``When you're providing
advice, you need to be considered a trusted source. `Wild and
crazy' doesn't go with `trusted' very well,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
