A5467 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-FLAG-NYTSF &LR;      07-01 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-FLAG-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLAG AND THE 4TH OF JULY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RABBI ELI HECHT &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Williamsburg, N.Y., my neighbors were all European
immigrants. Most were Jewish survivors of the death camps of World
War II. They knew little English and kept to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   American holidays were not celebrated as they had no idea of
national holidays. They were still recuperating from their tragic
and painful European experience.
</P>
<P>
   However, one holiday that did ring a bell was the Fourth of
July. My friends would speak about their good mazal -- luck -- in
being in a free country.
</P>
<P>
   They may have not known the president's name or how the Congress
worked, but they knew that being free in America was the most
cherished gift a person could receive. Little American flags would
mysteriously appear.
</P>
<P>
   I had a friend who possessed an American flag that his father, a
survivor of the Auschwitz death camp, had kept. It was given to him
by an American G.I. during the liberation of the camp. It was his
most cherished possession.
</P>
<P>
   The flag was found in almost every Jewish house of worship. It
would be displayed next to the Ark containing the Torah, the holy
scroll. The message was to revere the flag and respect your
country.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite photo was the American Marines raising the flag on
Iwo Jima.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, supporters of the flag submitted a request to Congress
calling for a constitutional amendment to safeguard the flag. Much
debate is taking place on this issue. The amendment issue makes me
question our society.
</P>
<P>
   What is so disturbing to me is not whether we will pass the
constitutional amendment, but that there is even a need to debate
it. We should always respect our noble flag. It is the right thing
for an American to do.
</P>
<P>
   How did we ever come to this shameful level?
</P>
<P>
   When Patrick Henry said, ``Give me liberty or give me death,''
he never dreamed his words would be used as an excuse to desecrate
the flag.
</P>
<P>
   During the British assault on Fort McHenry, Francis Scott Key
saw the American flag flying triumphantly over the battlements and
was moved to write the Star Spangled Banner. The song later became
the official National Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   It concludes: ``Then conquer we must, when our cause it is just,
And this be our motto: `In God is our trust,' And the star-spangled
banner in triumph shall wave, O'er the land of the free and the
home of the brave!''
</P>
<P>
   During the 4th of July celebrations my family and I will give
respect to our great country by attending a service.
</P>
<P>
   It will give me great pride to recite the Pledge of Allegiance
to the flag.
</P>
<P>
   That is the least I can do for our great country. Maybe you can
include that in your 4th of July celebration.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
