<SLUG> BC-WELLSFARGO-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WELLS FARGO SETS UP NEW INTERNET UNIT  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Wells Fargo has created a new Internet unit and
named one of its top executives to run it, signaling the central
role that online services will play in the bank's future.
<P>
   In an internal announcement last week, the San Francisco bank
said Group Executive Vice President Clyde Ostler will head the
unit, called the Internet Services Group.
</P>
<P>
   Ostler is charged with making sure that every business unit in
the bank has an Internet plan and a staff to implement it. He will
supervise all Internet and online operations throughout the bank,
as well as other electronic commerce activities still to be
determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense to give one person an overview of such
an important area,'' said John Wilson, a San Francisco executive
recruiter with Korn/Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce experts say the Internet rapidly is becoming a key
channel for consumers to buy financial products and services. And
competition is heating up.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few weeks, E-Trade of Palo Alto, Calif., the No.
2 online broker, agreed to buy Telebanc, an Internet banking
company, and Chicago's Bank One unveiled an all-Internet subsidiary
called WingspanBank.com separate from its other operations.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo set up an online financial services division four
years ago to manage computer banking for consumers. It is now the
nation's largest Internet bank, with some 900,000 retail customers
registered to use its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But business units such as retail brokerage, small business and
corporate banking lag in building a presence on the Web. Those
units don't have separate organizations to manage Internet
operations, and some haven't yet developed coherent Internet plans.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ostler said his job was to make sure that each
business unit had a full-time staff to take charge of Internet
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had great success with our retail online-services
organization,'' Ostler said. ``I want to make sure that we have
equally dedicated and focused groups for every line of business.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo probably won't build a separate Web-based bank the
way Bank One did, Ostler said. Instead, the bank will emphasize
that it offers customers the choice of branches, automated tellers
and telephone service in addition to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer online banking chief Sharon Osberg, recently promoted
to executive vice president, will report to Ostler. He also will
supervise Internet managers in the bank's other business units, who
still are being selected.
</P>
<P>
   Ostler, who previously reported to President Leslie Biller, now
will work directly for chief executive Richard Kovacevich. ``It's a
signal of the commitment from the very top,'' Ostler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
