<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS TOP METS, 4-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The New York Mets had their chances to pull within two
games of the Atlanta Braves. But the Marlins' Mark Kotsay ruined
the Mets' night when he drove a fastball from Armando Benitez over
the right-field fence in the 10th inning for a game-winning home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Kotsay's two-out homer on a 3-1 count gave Florida a 4-3 victory
and dropped Benitez to 0-2 on the season. The Braves, meanwhile,
were beaten once again by the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   The homer was a little redemption for the Marlins' right
fielder, who had been thrown out twice trying to steal on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kotsay's at-bat, Benitez had retired all 22 Marlin
hitters he had faced this season.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mets Manager Bobby Valentine went over to console
Benitez, who was watching television on a couch, icing his arm and
drinking a beer. Benitez reassured Valentine that he was all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the right attitude,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a good pitch because he hit the ball,'' Benitez
said of the 98-mile-an-hour fastball that Kotsay hit. ``I tried to
throw it inside and it stayed in the middle. I'm fine. It's no big
deal. It's a normal game. Somebody has to win, somebody has to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit a homer, I give him a hat. We play again tomorrow. If I
have to pitch again, I'll pitch again.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez won't pitch again. ``It was his third day in a row,''
Valentine said. ``He was one pitch away from having a day off.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotsay's homer came an inning after Roger Cedeno had run the
Mets out of a ninth-inning rally. But the hustling Cedeno was
hardly at fault; it took a tremendous throw from foul territory and
across the infield to get him out.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno had drawn a leadoff walk from Matt Mantei. The situation
begged for a stolen base. Mantei was well aware of that. But he
skipped a pickoff attempt past first baseman Kevin Millar. And
Cedeno took off and did not stop.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a little too aggressive of a move. Cedeno,
the major league leader in stolen bases _ he got his 42d tonight _
was trying for third. But Luis Castillo's peg from a retaining wall
that lines the right-field seats was perfect. And Cedeno, who had
slipped rounding second, was an easy out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have made third,'' Cedeno said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets again threatened in the 10th, and again they could not
score. Edgardo Alfonzo led off against Antonio Alfonseca with a
single and was sacrificed to second by Melvin Mora. Mike Piazza
then drilled a pitch to deep right field. But it is 385 feet to the
power alley at Pro Player Stadium, and Kotsay ran the ball down at
the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura was given an intentional walk, but Brian McRae
eventually ended the rally by taking a third strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, trailing by 2-0, tied the score in the top of the
sixth inning on Matt Franco's single, Mike Piazza's double (there
might have been a play at second, but no one bothered to cover the
base), Robin Ventura's rbi groundout and Brian McRae's run-scoring
single.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' starter Rick Reed, who had pitched well after
surrendering a two-run homer to Millar in the second, fell behind
again.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lowell, who had come on to play third in the fifth after
Kevin Orie injured his left quadriceps muscle, led off with a
single. Lowell advanced to second on Preston Wilson's one-out
groundout and then scored on Millar's line single past Robin
Ventura as Rickey Henderson bobbled the ball in left.
</P>
<P>
   Millar was having some game. The second-inning home run, a
wallop over the scoreboard in left, was the second homer of the
season for the 27-year-old rookie first baseman, who was a teammate
of Rey Ordonez with the St. Paul Saints of the independent Northern
League in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first homer Millar had hit out of the park. His first
major league home run was inside the park at Wrigley Field with two
outs and two strikes in the top of the ninth to beat the Cubs on
May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who allowed three runs and seven hits in five and
two-thirds innings, came out of the game after allowing Millar's
run-scoring single. But the lead was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Henderson drew a two-out walk against Braden
Looper, who had relieved Alex Fernandez (6 innings, 5 hits, 2
runs). Henderson then stole second easily on Looper's first pitch
to Edgardo Alfonzo. And when Alfonzo slapped a single between
Millar and the first base bag, Henderson came home.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla grounded out as a pinch-hitter in the top of the
seventh, and Olerud came on to play first base in the bottom of the
inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
