<HEADER>
A5474 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEAT-VIDEOGAMES-SFCH     07-01 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAT-VIDEOGAMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SECRET CODES MAKE CHEATING PAY OFF FOR GAMERS  &HT;     By JEFF GREEN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. -- Forget everything you ever heard about
cheating.
<P>
   Cheating is good _ at least in the world of video-console and
computer games.
</P>
<P>
   Once a novelty feature in some games, ``cheat codes'' now are an
inherent, expected part of the video gaming experience. Almost all
games _ whether for Sony Playstation, Nintendo 64, GameBoy or
personal computer _ come with an array of cheat codes built in,
while an ever-growing number of magazines, guidebooks, and
commercial and amateur Web sites provide gamers with those precious
codes.
</P>
<P>
   A cheat code typically is just a series of button presses (on
console games) or keystrokes (on PCs) that players can invoke to
alter a game to their advantage. Codes can allow players to skip
levels, gain additional lives in an action games or become
invincible to attacks from enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``cheats'' are routinely built into every game by
programmers so that they easily can access all areas of the game
for testing and tweaking without having to play it themselves every
time they want to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   Originally secretive about such codes, game publishers now
realize that they are an attractive resource for consumers. Many
gamers simply don't have the time, skills or attention span to slog
through games _ many of which can take literally hundreds of hours
to complete _ without some kind of artificial aid . Now, if a
player finds a particular area of a game too difficult or boring,
he or she simply can plug in a cheat code to move on rather than
having to give up on the game.
</P>
<P>
   This can be useful especially to consumers who rent games at
stores like Blockbuster, where they are under a time constraint to
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll use cheats on the games I rent,'' said a gamer going by
the name of ``Dilbert'' in an informal poll on a Nintendo newsgroup
recently. ``I just want to see as much of the game as possible. On
games I care enough about to buy, like Zelda or Banjo-Kazooie, I
will try to play with absolutely no help at all until I'm
absolutely stuck.``
</P>
<P>
   Besides enabling players to move more quickly through a game,
cheat codes are a huge source of goodies and extra features not
available in the normal course of a game. Plugging in certain codes
in Electronic Arts' Need For Speed: High Stakes racing game, for
example, lets players race in vehicles other than those officially
listed on the box _ as well as a helicopter. In a game like
Midway's NFL Blitz, cheat codes can be invoked to (among other
things) give all your players giant heads, tiny heads or no heads.
</P>
<P>
   Al Amaloo of the Video Game Strategies Web site at About.com,
believes that codes can enhance a player's experience, thus making
the game more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some codes reward gamers with extra bonuses and features and
add more value to their purchase,'' he said. For example, San
Francisco Rush, a Nintendo 64 game, includes a bonus track of The
Rock. Gamers were able to unlock this well-hidden secret some time
after the game's initial release to extend the longevity of the
game, Amaloo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other codes are more like rewards and don't offer the cheap
thrill of immediately spoiling the game,'' he added. ``The cheat
system in GoldenEye 007 comes to mind, where the gamer is rewarded
with the ability to enable cheats based on their performance during
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Game publishers, savvy to this attitude, now actively encourage
their programmers to fill their games with hidden ``extras,'' so
that gamers will keep coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems to be working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use cheats after I've either beaten a game or it has totally
lost my interest,'' said a gamer with the moniker ``Paladin.'' ``A
nifty code can breathe new life into a game I haven't touched in
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Further enhancing the current cheat-code fever is the popularity
of a third-party hardware add-on called the GameShark, originally
developed by Datel Design and Development in the United Kingdom and
now distributed by Interact Accessories Inc. of Hunt Valley, Md.
The GameShark (and its various clones) plugs into a port on a
Playstation, Saturn, GameBoy or Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, part of a console system's memory is used to hold
certain information about a game in progress, such as how many
``lives'' a player has left or how much ammunition or shields the
player has. The GameShark essentially allows players to override
these values to make the games easier to play. It's especially
advantageous in games that don't have cheat codes built in.
</P>
<P>
   Such devices are neither licensed nor supported by the
console-makers themselves, but they are not actively discouraged
because, again, there's a growing awareness that such codes only
increase gamers' often-obsessive loyalty to certain titles.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, hundreds of Web sites _ both independent fan
sites and commercial ones _ have sprouted up where gamers post and
swap cheat codes, as well as general strategies and tips for
beating the games. Competition for attention is intense, so the
people running sites frantically will hunt down codes and
strategies and strive to get them up as soon as possible, often
before a game even ships. For PC titles (which also have cheat
codes but have less of a fervent subculture surrounding them), Web
sites actively compete to post hint guides and walk-throughs as
fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   For the gamer, it's an embarrassment of riches. A player who is
stuck can log onto the Internet and get the information in seconds.
Mini online communities form and swell with every new game release,
giving players instant free access to cheats, tips, codes and
strategies. The recently released PC role-playing game Might and
Magic VII from 3DO is a typical example, generating hundreds of
posts on Internet newsgroups within the first two days of its
release.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all that free information online, sales of magazines
devoted to cheats and strategies are still strong. Some of the
leading titles in console-game magazines include Expert Gamer,
Electronic Gaming Monthly and Official U.S. Playstation Magazine,
all published by Ziff-Davis; GamePro from IDG; PSM from Imagine;
and Tips &AMP; Tricks from Larry Flynt.
</P>
<P>
   Game guidebooks from book publishers like Sybex and Prima also
are in demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people expected strategy-guide demand to go down with
the rise of the Web,'' said Dan Brodnitz, acquisitions and
publications manager of game books at Sybex Computer Books of
Alameda, Calif., ``but sales are still strong across the board.
Even Internet-centric games like Everquest and Ultima Online have
spawned successful books. There's a basic convenience to having the
book open while you're in the game that's hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Green is a senior editor at Computer Gaming World in San
Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
