<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPOS-GAINS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAZZLING DEBUTS BY LOCAL IPOS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. -- The performance of Bay Area initial public
offerings in the first half of this year was as stunning as any
stunt performed at the X Games.
<P>
   Forty-two local companies, nearly all of them Internet stars or
startups, went public in the past six months, with an average gain
of 138 percent, according to IPO Monitor in Los Angeles. By
contrast, the 41 Bay Area companies that launched IPOs in 1998 saw
an average gain over 12 months of 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area contingent accounted for 20 percent of the 211 U.S.
companies that went public in the past six months. The average gain
for the local companies was more than double the 67 percent
nationwide average.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same six-month period, the Nasdaq composite jumped 22.4
percent, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 19.5 percent and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was up 11.6 percent. The local IPO results in
the past quarter are even more remarkable when one considers that
half the companies have been trading for less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest Bay Area IPO gainer was Healtheon Corp., which went
public February 10 at $8 per share and closed Wednesday at $77, up
862.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Clara, Calif., company, started by repeat entrepreneur
Jim Clark, who previously led Netscape, provides health care
information and services over the Internet. The well-publicized
company, which was an instant hit when it went public, received
another financial boost in May when it agreed to merge with rival
WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Although Healtheon lost $54 million on $49 million revenues last
year, it now has a market value of nearly $5.5 billion. That's on a
par with Golden West Financial, the S&AMP;L in Oakland, Calif., that
earned $434 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The only other newly minted local IPO worth more than Healtheon
is Juniper Networks. This Mountain View, Calif., maker of Internet
networking gear jumped $33.50 to $149 yesterday on growing
enthusiasm about its next-generation routers. The company, now
worth more than $7.3 billion, lost $32 million on $3.8 million
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   The combined market value of all 42 new local IPOs tops $56
billion but it is hard to find a moneymaker in the bunch. The 10
companies worth the most all lost money last year _ a combined $241
million.
</P>
<P>
   Profits are not what drives pricing of IPOs, especially the
so-called dot-com companies that promise to transform the way we do
business and buy products in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of IPOS01 (76172 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The public appetite for these stocks is astronomical,'' said
Bob Emery, president of BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``Investors
are paying for the future value of Internet-related stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of paying a multiple of last year's earnings or
estimated earnings for the current year, buyers of Internet stocks
are paying 10 or 20 times anticipated revenues two or three years
from now, Emery said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said companies like Amazon.com, Yahoo and eBay win even
greater valuations (perhaps as much as four times higher) because
they are the first to market or have the the dominant brand in
their niche.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six months, BancBoston Robertson Stephens was lead
manager of several local IPOs such as Critical Path and Mpath
Interactive. It also handled six of the nine largest Internet
mergers and acquisitions, including Healtheon-WebMD, ExciteAtHome,
E-Trade-Telebanc and CMGI-Alta Vista.
</P>
<P>
   Emery believes ``some of the valuations will be warranted over
time; others will not.''
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the Bay Area's 42 IPOs in the first half closed
below their offering prices Wednesday. The worst performer was
NetObject Inc., which went public May 7 at $12 per share and closed
yesterday at $8.063, down 32.8 percent. The Redwood City, Calif.,
company, in which IBM holds a majority stake, makes e-commerce
software.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, the underwriter with the best IPO performance has
been Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, according to IPO Monitor. It was
lead manager for the three top-performing local IPOs so far this
year: Healtheon, Brocade Communications Systems and Redback
Networks. Since January 1998, Morgan Stanley has managed 36 IPOs
that have gained an average of 140 percent in value since their
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs came in second with an average gain of 90 percent,
followed by Lehman Brothers, 85 percent; Merrill Lynch, 62 percent;
and BancBoston Robertson Stephens, 58 percent. IPOs managed by San
Francisco's Hambrecht &AMP; Quist gained an average of 32 percent
during the past year and a half, while those managed by NationsBanc
Montgomery Securities (now Banc of America Securities) lost an
average of 30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
