<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PG&AMP;E-PROBE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PUC URGED TO CONTINUE PG&AMP;E PROBE  &HT;     By REBECCA SMITH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. -- San Francisco City Attorney Louise Renne
is exhorting the state Public Utilities Commission not to drop its
investigation of last December's big PG&AMP;E blackout.
<P>
   Quitting now, Renne says, would amount to dereliction of duty by
the PUC following its dustup, earlier in the year, with a key state
legislator over who has jurisdiction to investigate major power
outages _ the 88-year-old PUC or the state's electric grid
operator, the 15-month-old Independent System Operator in Folsom.
</P>
<P>
   The matter is being taken up next Thursday when the five-member
PUC will consider the separate recommendations of two Republican
commissioners, both of whom want the PUC to terminate its
investigation into the blackout that afflicted more than two
million Bay Area residents, and leave any remedial action to the
ISO.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO previously fined PG&AMP;E $440,000 for the blackout, using
authority conveyed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Renne sent a letter to the commission last week urging it to
continue its probe. It was followed by written comments this week
stating that the record provides no basis for the PUC to delegate
its public-protection duties to the quasi-public ISO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to us like the commission is rolling over in the face
of political pressure,'' said Theresa Mueller, the deputy city
attorney assigned to the case and a former attorney for the
consumer group, The Utility Reform Network in San Francisco. ``If
they quit now, nothing has been accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Public advocates want the PUC to stay the course for two
reasons. First, they say the PUC _ not the ISO _ has the authority
to subpoena utility records and compel testimony under oath. And
they argue that the PUC, alone, adheres to decades-old rules of due
process that give the public equal access to the regulatory
process.
</P>
<P>
   They fear that ``capitulation'' now would set a dangerous
precedent for the investigation of future outages.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO is a ``nonprofit public benefit corporation'' created by
the Legislature 15 months ago to run the state's electric grid. It
has no power to subpoena utility records and is not subject to the
state's open meeting law or public records act, both laws that
guarantee public access. The ISO doesn't hold public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slow suicide for the PUC not to do its duty,'' says Emy
Youngsmith, a PUC staff attorney representing the agency's
enforcement division. ``The people deserve to have the PUC uphold
its authority and act as a public forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the proposals of commissioners Richard Bilas and
Josiah Neeper to close the investigation raise troubling questions
about how adequately the public's right to safe and reliable
service will be defended in the deregulated era.
</P>
<P>
   PUC President Bilas says deregulation means a change in
regulatory structure not just for utilities, but for regulators,
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in transition from where the PUC was the sole authority
over outage investigations to where it no longer is,'' said Bilas.
``That's hard for some people to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations that the agency drop its probe, however,
follows a lashing that the PUC took for allegedly overstepping its
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's 1996 electric deregulation law, the ISO has
responsibility to investigate major ``transmission'' failures that
involve the high-voltage power lines that connect generating plants
with major substations.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC was stripped of that duty but retains jurisdiction over
outages happening on the lower-voltage ``distribution'' system that
connects smaller substations with homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Because blackouts like the one that happened December 8 involve
both transmission and distribution systems, both agencies initially
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the PUC's enforcement division issued its findings in a
controversial report stating that PG&AMP;E had an ``error-prone'' work
culture that contributed to the December outage, which began when
PG&AMP;E employees made several bone-headed mistakes while working at
the utility's San Mateo substation.
</P>
<P>
   That report _ and the $300,000 paid to consultants to prepare it
_ aroused the ire of a powerful legislator, California Senator
Steve Peace, D-Chula Vista, the architect of the state's
deregulation plan that created the ISO.
</P>
<P>
   Peace held a hearing of the budget committee, which he chairs,
to probe the PUC's actions and the expenditure. In that hearing, he
lambasted the head of the PUC's enforcement division and said the
PUC's action was ``stupid'' and wasteful because it duplicated some
of the ISO's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of the PUC investigation say it was proper for the
PUC to take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there was some redundancy, so what?'' says Mueller of
the City Attorney's Office. ``The risk is that no one will do a
good job investigating events like this, not that too many people
will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, PG&AMP;E complained to state officials that it was
being double-teamed by the ISO and PUC. PG&AMP;E chief executive Gordon
Smith said the PUC's staff was acting ``irresponsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, ISO chief Terry Winter met with Mayor Willie
Brown to explain what his organization is doing to protect San
Francisco electric reliability. On Tuesday, Winter sent a letter to
the PUC's Bilas commending him for recognizing that ``no further
investigation ... is required.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
