<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSTATIONS-MICROSOFTINTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT, INTEL ARE UNITED ON ONE FRONT  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Microsoft and Intel may have bitter differences on some issues, but
they're united in their determination to keep pushing into high-end
territory once dominated by Unix workstations.
<P>
   The two companies rolled out their biggest guns _ Microsoft CEO
Bill Gates and his Intel counterpart, Craig Barrett _ to keynote
Wednesday's opening session of the Workstation Leadership Forum in
Burlingame, Calif. The conference, which the two companies jointly
sponsored, brought together some 600 corporate customers and
software developers in such fields as mechanical and electrical
design, financial services, animation and multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   Workstations, which start at about $5,000 but typically cost
upward of $15,000, are high-performance computers used for tasks
too demanding for ordinary PCs. Instead of Intel's chips and
Microsoft's Windows software, they've traditionally used the Unix
operating system and specialized chips based on a principle known
as RISC (reduced instruction set computing). Even though they add
up to a low-volume market compared with ordinary PCs, it's one
that's attractive to the Wintel duopoly because it offers higher
profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions between the two companies that surfaced during the
Microsoft antitrust trial were nowhere in evidence Wednesday as the
two leaders assessed _ and celebrated _ their progress in these
markets.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GATES01 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Barrett cited recent research by International Data Corp.
predicting that sales of ``Intel Architecture'' workstations
between 1998 and 2003 will grow 20 percent a year, while sales of
traditional workstations will decline by 5 percent annually during
the same period. Personally, he added, he considers those figures
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel Architecture'' workstations use higher-performance
versions of the same Intel chips that power ordinary PCs. They
typically run Microsoft's Windows NT operating system software.
</P>
<P>
   During the next year, each company will release major new
products targeted in part at the workstation world: Microsoft's
Windows 2000 is due out by the end of this year, and around the
middle of next year, Intel should be shipping a chip code-named
Merced, the first in a family of advanced chips that will run both
today's ``32-bit'' software and new ``64-bit'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   Even after it delivers Merced, Intel will continue to develop
new additions to its  &LR; c,12p2  &LR; 32-bit Pentium family (now known as
IA-32) for mainstream markets. Barrett said a 1-gigahertz
(1,000-megahertz) IA-32 chip will reach the market by the end of
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moore's law will continue for at least another 15 years or
so,'' he said, citing the computer-industry axiom that chip
capabilities double every 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of GATES01 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Most of yesterday's opening session was taken up by
demonstrations of programs that previously that were available only
for traditional workstations but now run on Intel chips and Windows
NT.
</P>
<P>
   Dassault Systems of France, for example, showed its new Windows
version of Catia, a software package widely used for product design
in the aircraft and automobile industries.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Foster, pony-tailed senior vice president for multimedia
at Sony Pictures Imageworks in Culver City, showed previews of
``Stuart Little,'' a Columbia Pictures movie slated for release
around Thanksgiving. Its star, a pet mouse, was created digitally,
then combined with conventional film of the family that adopts him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everyone in Hollywood has moved to IA/NT (Intel
Architecture workstations running Windows NT) or is trying to
figure out how to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Copeland, an analyst at International Data Corp. who helped
prepare the report Barrett cited, said animation and other
``digital content creation'' applications, as well as financial
services, are the market segments where Intel and Microsoft have
had the clearest success in displacing RISC workstations. He
cautioned, though, that in heavy-duty applications, such as design
of cars, planes, and microprocessors, most major manufacturers
still rely mainly on non-Intel workstations running Unix.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of GATES01 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
COL. 4 of GATES01 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
