<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIR JOHN WOOLF, 86 PRODUCER OF `AFRICAN QUEEN' AND `OLIVER' 
JAMES B. BOSKEY, 57; FOUGHT CHILD ABUSE
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sir John Woolf, who produced such films as ``The African
Queen,'' ``Oliver!'' and ``The Day of the Jackal,'' died on Monday
at his home in London. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Woolf, whose films won 13 Oscars, trusted his instincts so
resolutely that he put up half the money for ``The African Queen''
even though a friend, the director Sir Alexander Korda, warned him
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Korda is reported to have cautioned: ``Two old people going up
and down an African river . . . who's going to be interested in
that? You'll be bankrupt!''
</P>
<P>
   The 1951 movie, which starred Humphrey Bogart and Katharine
Hepburn, became a hit at the box office and a movie classic. Bogart
won an Oscar as best actor and Miss Hepburn was nominated for best
actress.
</P>
<P>
   Born on March 15, 1913, in Cricklewood, North London, John Woolf
attended Eton College and Institut Montana in Switzerland. He said
he learned about making films from his father, C.M. Woolf, who made
his fortune by financing, distributing and exhibiting films after
World War I.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s, Woolf's father formed General Film
Distributions after resigning from the Gaumont British Picture
Corp. in 1937. He is credited with bringing the producer J. Arthur
Rank into the film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Woolf became a managing director after his father died in 1942.
He and his brother, James, formed the successful independent
production company Romulus Films in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``The African Queen,'' Romulus Films produced
such popular movies as ``Richard III'' (1956), a co-production with
Korda that Laurence Olivier directed and starred in; ``Moulin
Rouge'' (1952) and ``Beat the Devil'' (1954); an adaptation of John
Braine's novel ``Room at the Top'' (1959), and the Oscar-winning
musical ``Oliver!'' (1968). In all, Woolf's films won 13 Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, Woolf extended his reach into television. He
founded Anglia Television, which produced more than 100 plays and
internationally broadcast series like ``Orson Welles' Great
Mysteries'' and ``Tales of the Unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolf was knighted in 1975 for his work in the British film
industry.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Ann, and a son.
</P>
<P>
   James Bernard Boskey, a children's rights advocate and an expert
on alternatives to the courts for resolving disputes, died on June
14 at New York Presbyterian Hospital. He was 57 and lived in North
Caldwell, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said a spokesman for Seton Hall
University. Boskey was a professor of family law at Seton Hall's
Newark, N.J., law campus.
</P>
<P>
   His skill in settling disputes out of court, like mediating
divorce cases, led him to create The Alternative Newsletter, a
dispute resolution guide for lawyers and mediators that is now in
its 10th year of publication.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote extensively on workers' compensation and the
rights of children and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   He edited the ``Manual on Child Abuse and Neglect,'' published
by the New Jersey State Bar Association in 1980. He was a founder
of the association's Children's Rights Committee and he helped
shape state legislation intended to protect the children of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Boskey was born in Alexandria, La.. He graduated in 1964 from
Princeton University, where he studied sociology and anthropology.
He received law degrees from the University of Michigan in 1967 and
the London School of Economics and Political Science in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Seton Hall faculty as an assistant professor in
1971. He advanced to full professor in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 29 years, Adele Ludin Boskey, and
their daughter, Elizabeth Boskey of Baltimore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0011EDT &QL; 
