<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FED-NYT &LR;      07-01 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FED MAKES A MINIMAL MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   William McChesney Martin Jr., the chairman of the Federal
Reserve Board during the great economic expansion of the 1950s and
1960s, once said that the role of the Fed was ``to take away the
punch bowl just when the party gets going.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the current Fed chairman, on Wednesday served
notice that he does not want to spoil the fun. While the Fed did
raise an important interest rate by a quarter of a percentage
point, as had been widely expected, it also said its policy was now
neutral, rather than biased in favor of a further increase. Wall
Street celebrated by sending the Dow Jones industrial average up
200 points in the first 15 minutes after the Fed announcement.
Greenspan and his colleagues seem to be betting that the economy
will cool down without much action by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has been expecting the American economy to slow for the
past three years, but the willingness of consumers to spend rather
than save has kept the economy roaring ahead. Now, with the
manufacturing sector strengthening as overseas economies rebound,
signs of inflation have appeared, as Greenspan noted in testimony
before the Joint Economic Committee two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market had expected the Fed to take stronger action on
Wednesday _ or at least not signal that it would probably forgo
another rate increase _ and the yield on long-term government bonds
slipped below 6 percent after the announcement. But that rate is up
from 4.8 percent late last year, a fact that has pushed mortgage
interest rates up and slightly slowed the strong housing market.
</P>
<P>
   Even with rates rising, however, consumer confidence has climbed
to a 30-year high. That suggests that neither the economy nor
consumer spending is likely to slow soon. If the American economy
continues to grow at the recent rate of above 4 percent, there are
substantial risks that inflation will accelerate and that, with the
record trade deficit continuing to expand, the dollar will
eventually come under heavy pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Those risks will be intensified if the White House and Congress
choose to ease fiscal policy now, either through large new spending
programs or by a big tax decrease. Should that happen, Greenspan
may have no choice but to push interest rates up again later this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5487 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      07-01 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW COALITION IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   Israel's next prime minister, Ehud Barak, is a career soldier
relatively new to civilian political deal making. But he has shown
great skill in stitching together a cabinet coalition. His
government will be broad based and generally united in support of
negotiating peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Agreements with some parties still need to be completed. But it
now looks as though Barak's government could command at least 75
out of the 120 votes in Israel's parliament and be able to count on
another 10 votes from Arab parties outside the government. That is
more solid backing than any recent Israeli prime minister has
enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Barak should use his first months in office to rebuild lost
momentum for peace. Arab leaders, including Syria's president,
Hafez al-Assad, have welcomed Barak's election and signaled their
desire to work with him. Syria's intentions should be tested, not
only by an early resumption of talks on returning the Golan
Heights, but also by seeking Damascus' cooperation in assuring a
peaceful Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has wisely indicated that he intends to treat the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, as a partner, not an adversary.
That was the approach followed by Yitzhak Rabin. Barak is prepared
to carry out Israel's commitments under last fall's Wye River
agreement, and then proceed to the difficult issues of Jerusalem,
Jewish settlements, water, refugees and possible Palestinian
statehood. Resolving these will require good will between the two
leaders and now is the time to build it.
</P>
<P>
   While all the coalition parties promise to support Barak on
peacemaking, they differ on domestic issues like the role of
religion in national life and draft exemptions for yeshiva
students. Barak has deferred several of those issues and opted for
compromise on others. He has allocated some of the cabinet's
religiously sensitive posts to ultra-Orthodox allies while
reserving others for resolutely secular politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, Israel's voters gave Barak a strong personal
mandate for peacemaking and reuniting a politically fractured
society. The broad coalition he has now assembled gives him a good
chance for success on both fronts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5489 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT &LR;      07-01 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: MR. McCAIN'S CHALLENGE TO MR. BUSH  
(sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain has delivered a critical challenge to his
fellow candidates for the Republican presidential nomination.
Speaking Wednesday in New Hampshire, he declared that any candidate
who promises to reform anything _ from education to the military to
the tax code _ must begin by fixing campaign finance. The current
system, he said, is ``nothing less than an elaborate
influence-peddling scheme in which both parties conspire to stay in
office by selling the country to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain picked a good day to take his stand. He had barely
finished his speech when George W. Bush, the Republican
front-runner, announced that having raised more than $35 million,
he will probably bypass the federal system under which candidates
agree to abide by spending limits in return for matching
contributions. This is a serious mistake for a candidate who
promises to practice a new and better brand of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush adheres to the Republican congressional mantra that the
defects in the present system can be cured with fuller and faster
disclosure of donations. But we know that neither party can be
embarrassed into forswearing special-interest money. Indeed, the
stunning totals Bush is amassing could goad Vice President Al Gore
into copying President Clinton's reckless methods. Both parties are
already gearing up to make record-breaking demands for the
virtually unregulated ``soft money'' donations that are the most
noxious feature of current campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's challenge inserts a hard note of truth into a
Republican campaign that has recently become a long-running
coronation tour for Bush. He is playing to the differences between
himself and Bush. But the Arizonan was pushing for campaign finance
reform before he became a presidential candidate in need of a
defining issue. When the Senate returns after its recess, McCain
and Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin plan to renew their attempts
to force a vote on their bill banning soft money.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate and House held fair votes on campaign finance
reform, a bill would become law in time to keep the 2000
presidential election from becoming yet another embarrassing
spectacle of money-grubbing. But the GOP leaders in both chambers
are determined to prevent such a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush could make the difference. His standing as the leader in
the presidential polls gives him the clout to shove his party's
leaders in Congress toward a fair and open vote on McCain's
legislation. If he chooses not to do so, voters will have a right
to question whether his brand of conservatism offers its compassion
first and foremost to big-money special interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACOG-CONGRESS01-COX     07-01 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACOG-CONGRESS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds to Atlanta Olympic official: Give up papers
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Congressional leaders, frustrated by stonewalling from
Atlanta Olympic officials, have threatened to issue a federal
subpoena for records if the local organization continues to refuse
to turn them over.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House Commerce Committee is demanding unrestricted
access to eight boxes of documents that Billy Payne's Georgia
Amateur Athletics Federation contends are personal and private.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Payne, after receiving word of the committee's
demands, said Wednesday a subpoena would not be necessary. ``We are
going to fully cooperate with the committee's wishes regarding the
access to these few boxes of documents,'' spokesman Lee Echols
said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional investigators say the documents are not personal
but are ``official corporate records'' relevant to their
investigation into improprieties in the Atlanta organization's
campaign to persuade the International Olympic Committee to stage
the 1996 Summer Games here.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the documents are ``relevant to the giving or soliciting
of gifts to or by IOC members and /or their families,'' according
to a harshly worded letter sent Tuesday to Payne by Rep. Tom Bliley
(R- Va.), chairman of the Commerce Committee, and Rep. Fred Upton
(R-Mich.), chairman of its subcommittee on oversight and
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your attorneys' suggestion that these records are somehow
personal documents ... is simply unfounded,'' the congressmen
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   They also demanded that investigators be allowed to copy any
papers they deem necessary without identifying the documents for
Payne's attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cannot agree to such terms,'' Bliley and Upton warned,
``we will consider all lawful means to secure the entire contents
of these eight boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne's attorneys had requested investigators identify any
record they believe is relevant and provide an explanation for that
relevance. The lawyers also said they would object if investigators
wanted to copy more than a handful of the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Such restrictions would slow the process, the congressmen said,
and undermine the committee's fact-gathering efforts by providing
Olympic officials with a blueprint of the direction of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The copying of the documents,'' Echols said, ``was an issue we
were simply trying to resolve in a balanced manner. However, we
will cooperate with the decision made by the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The House committee, which started its investigation of the
Atlanta bid effort in early May, intends to conduct interviews and
possibly hearings in early August.
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen denied Payne's request for a meeting, saying
their letter would suffice in explaining their position. They also
denied Payne's attorneys' request for reimbursement for the cost of
copying documents.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers with King &AMP; Spalding of Atlanta are representing Payne
and the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation in regard to the the
congressional probe. The same attorneys are handling litigation
involving The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and Georgia Attorney
General Thurbert Baker, who want the Olympic bid records opened to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   King &AMP; Spalding also is representing several of its own partners
in the Olympic records dispute. Several lawyers in the firm were
active participants in the bid team, including Horace Sibley, who
headed up the team's international relations effort and compiled
dossiers on IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's papers are believed to be among the records Payne and
the firm want to keep secret.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the eight boxes of disputed papers, the
congressmen demanded that Payne produce by July 9 some 30 complete
boxes of documents located at the Atlanta History Center and at the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games headquarters at the
Inforum.
</P>
<P>
   They asked for 20 boxes of files at ACOG offices already
assembled by Payne's attorneys and which contain written summaries
of IOC member gifts and travel; copies of checks, payment requests
and invoices; and correspondence and information about IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also specifically requested 10 boxes of documents
archived at the History Center that include correspondence written
by Payne, bid team official Ginger Watkins and Doug Gatlin, former
Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young's close aide and the paid executive
director of the bid team.
</P>
<P>
   The congressmen warned Payne not to destroy any documents
related to the Olympic effort, whether stored at the History Center
or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
