<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-WOMEN'S-SOCCER-N     07-01 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WOMEN'S-SOCCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MIA HAMM AND COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 1:
</P>
<P>
   The American Women's World Cup soccer team has burst into
national prominence in the last several weeks, selling out stadiums
and drawing the largest audience in the history of women's team
athletics at Giants Stadium in New Jersey. They will face off
against Germany this evening in the quarterfinals outside
Washington, with millions of new fans hoping they advance to the
semifinal round.
</P>
<P>
   The success of this charismatic team heralds a new era for
women's sports. Even though the United States won the first Women's
World Cup in 1991, the team has only now gained a mass following.
When the American squad took the gold medal in the 1996 Olympic
Games, NBC aired a mere 10 minutes of highlights. But this year
ABC, ESPN and ESPN2 are jointly covering all of the World Cup, and
the ratings have not disappointed. As the American team swept
through the preliminary games, one broadcast on ESPN drew more
households than the cable channel's typical major league baseball
game.
</P>
<P>
   The players are a new breed of athletes, born and trained under
Title IX, the 1972 federal statute that bars sex discrimination in
education. The women on the soccer team and in the WNBA are
products of competitive college sports programs that did not exist
before the law. Girls can now dream of a professional career in
athletics, something that seemed unattainable even five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup has also breathed a new freshness into a
sport that too often in international men's competition has been
marred by fan violence. In the women's tournament, sportsmanship
seems paramount and the grandstands are filled with exuberant fans.
The star American forward, Mia Hamm, reigns as the leading scorer
in international soccer history. Her photographs grace dozens of
young girls' Internet sites, where she is venerated as a hero. Hamm
even has a generous endorsement deal from Gatorade and appears in
an advertisement with Michael Jordan bearing the slogan ``Anything
you can do, I can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   More must be done to create real equity between men's and
women's college athletics, and the prize money for the Women's
World Cup is a fraction of what the men would make. But the
unfolding competition holds the promise of what women in America
can achieve in sports. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS01-CO     07-01 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-EXPOS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collapsing bullpen folds again
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ A position of strength is a sudden liability. There
is something afire in the Braves' bullpen and the smoke is
consuming the team.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive night, the Braves handed their relief
corps a late three-run lead and for the second consecutive night,
the Montreal Expos ripped out the club's hair by the roots, batting
through the order in a five-run eighth in a 7-5 comeback win
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The episode spoiled impressive work by starter Odalis Perez (two
runs in 6 2/3 innings), and catcher Eddie Perez, whose three-run
homer off a speaker in left field gave Atlanta a 5-2 lead. But also
in the past two nights, the bullpen has given up 10 runs on 10 hits
in just 1 2/3 innings, losing both games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to explain,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``You couldn't
do that if you went out there and put it on a tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kevin McGlinchy, who got out of a bases-loaded jam in
relief of Perez in the seventh, gave up three consecutive singles
to open the eighth, Vladimir Guerrero singling in Jose Vidro to
close the lead to 5-3. After Fernando Seguignol walked, loading the
bases, Rudy Seanez relieved McGlinchy and gave up a two-run double
to Orlando Cabrera, Seguignol also scoring on Brian Jordan's error.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, Seanez had stranded all but three of his 21
inherited runners.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Mordecai followed with a bloop single to right, bringing in
Cabrera for a 7-5 lead. Russ Springer then retired the side but the
devastation was complete. McGlinchy (4-3) took the loss, Seanez had
his second blown save of the season, and after John Rocker's
five-run ninth-inning meltdown the night before, this is an
official crisis of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's discouraging,'' third baseman Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not getting the job done,'' Jordan said. ``That's
the bottom line. When it counts most late in the game, we're not
coming through.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss blotted out Perez's three-run homer in the fourth, just
the third ever struck off one of the speakers hanging from the
ceiling around the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully (today) we can come back to do the same thing to
them,'' Seanez said. ``You can't take too much away from those guys
but you can't give them too much credit either.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
