<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-GLOVER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glover has prayers answered by Hawks
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dion Glover wanted to be far, far away from the
maddening NBA draft gathering in Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stay home and find something to do to relieve the
anxiety,'' said Glover, declining to join other first-round
prospects at the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   He found it on bended knees.
</P>
<P>
   Glover, the 6-foot-5 shooting guard who made waves as a Georgia
Tech freshman, then declared for the draft even though he missed
last season with a knee injury, spent the evening in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the 20th pick in the first round, the Atlanta Hawks
answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and surprised,'' Glover said. ``I felt confident
I would go in the first round, but I did not know I would go with
the 20th pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Lord works in mysterious ways. Considering I was hurt
and missed all of last season, it was a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Glover, 20, had an All-America career at Cedar Grove High while
leading his school to a state title, then averaged 18.4 points a
game as a Tech freshman. But he tore both ligaments in his left
knee on the first day of practice last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a scare,'' Dion's father, the Rev. Franklin Glover,
said. ``After an injury like that, sometimes when you're young,
things can be overwhelming and you can get down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we started this (draft) process because he was blessed to
be healed (through surgery), and the option was there.''
</P>
<P>
   By going in the first round, Glover _ who did not work out for
teams, stayed academically eligible and maintained his option to
return to Tech until the last minute _ will earn a guaranteed,
million-dollar contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any second thoughts (about going pro),'' Glover
said. ``I knew in my mind and heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to show people that, yes, you can do it the right
way,'' Franklin Glover said. ``I like to practice what I preach.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Atlanta's ultimate homeboy stays put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy with that,'' Dion Glover said. ``Everybody here
knows me. I'll still be around my friends. And I can still see Mom
and Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks say they will keep Glover, at least for now. They have
indicated not all draft picks will be retained.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
