<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-HAWKS01-COX     07-01 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-HAWKS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changing of the guard
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They wanted to get younger and faster for their
inaugural season at Philips Arena. And, with one swift move, the
Hawks did that Wednesday night, taking Jason Terry, a blazingly
fast point guard from Arizona, with the 10th pick of the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   After disappointing fans attending the team's draft party at CNN
Center with a player they didn't know at No. 17 _ center Cal
Bowdler of Old Dominion _ the Hawks pleased them by taking Georgia
Tech guard Dion Glover with the 20th pick. They made a point of
saying they will be patient and bring him along very slowly. Glover
missed last season with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as an act of mercy, the Hawks took a distraught Jumaine
Jones from Georgia with pick No. 27. The last player in the green
room at the draft site in Washington, he greeted the news
tearfully. The Hawks then traded him to Philadelphia for a future
first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   The final pick on a busy night for the Hawks was guard Roberto
Bergersen of Boise State at 52nd, but he was sent to Portland for
cash.
</P>
<P>
   There were nearly 2,000 people in the CNN Center atrium and,
when Terry was chosen, some roared approval. That reception marked
a first for a Hawks draft pick since Stacey Augmon was taken with
the ninth pick in 1991. Coincidentally, Augmon, like Terry, was
taken with a pick acquired for a steady point guard. Eight years
ago, it was Doc Rivers who left town.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Mookie Blaylock took the hit. The longtime starter
was sent to Golden State on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock said he wasn't surprised with
the reaction to Bowdler, however. ``I think they would boo if we
drafted Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Clouding all of draft work is the insistence by team president
Stan Kasten that there is the very real chance of a major deal that
cannot be completed before Aug. 1 because of league rules.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the night, the rumor swirled that shooting guard
Steve Smith would be the next Hawks starter to go, with Portland a
potential new home. Babcock said he would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the Hawks could look at their first-round picks
as a measure of their efforts to put a faster, more athletic and
more entertaining team on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks vice president Arthur Triche noted moments after the
selection that ``every young guy in Atlanta will be playing in high
socks before you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 10 pick, who wears his socks to his knees, then gave his
new town a glimpse of the future on the big TV screen when he
rolled down one of his dark socks and showed a glimpse of a white
athletic sock underneath, bearing the name CATS (for Arizona
Wildcats).
</P>
<P>
   Terry said he may leave his tall socks behind, however, ``to
show off my nice legs.'' Then he said he wants to put on 10 pounds
of upper body muscle so he can play in the rugged NBA Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said on the eve of the draft he would be happy with any
of the five top-rated point guards. When Andre Miller went to
Cleveland, Terry was there for the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   And while Miller is bigger, more mature physically and two years
older, Terry is capable of brilliance. The Cavaliers may have
soured on Terry when he refused at the last moment to participate
in a head-to-head workout against Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The twosome had done just that for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Seattle, Terry said he welcomed the chance to come
to Atlanta and play for Lenny Wilkens. ``I know all about him,'' he
said. ``I know he likes defense. I'm a defensive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said, ``Being a Seattle guy, he knows how we like to
play. He will help us. He's a fine young player.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Harrick was at UCLA when he scouted Terry,
first seeing him at a track meet. He said Terry is a terrific
choice for the Hawks. ``He has blazing speed. He gets to the
basket. He makes everybody better.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowdler, a 6-10, 250-pounder from Old Dominion, is a good
shooter and athletic. He would back up Dikembe Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   Glover, at No. 20, was surprising in a different way. In his one
season at Tech, he showed little concept of team play and
inconsistent shooting. Clearly, he is not a player who is ready to
step in.
</P>
<P>
   Although Glover passed a physical with a glowing report on his
surgical knee, Babcock tried to talk him into staying in school.
The Glover family was adamant, however, though he refused to work
out for any NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
