<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-JONES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waiting ordeal pains Jones, watchers alike
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ First-year Georgia coach Jim Harrick vigorously
lobbied Jumaine Jones to remain in school one more year and warned
the Bulldogs' star forward of the possible scenario that unfolded
Wednesday night as he dropped to the 27th pick of the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, though, Harrick wasn't saying I told you so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful for me to watch,'' said Harrick, who attended
the Hawks' draft party at the CNN Center and served as a radio
broadcast analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and an entourage that included his mother, an aunt and a
childhood friend from Camilla sat uncomfortably in the green room
of the MCI Center in Washington as pick after pick was announced
before him. Finally, the Atlanta Hawks selected the 6-foot-7
forward two picks shy of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks quickly traded Jones to the Philadelphia 76ers for
future considerations.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' goals of becoming an NBA lottery pick or even a top 20
selection went unrealized. But, like it or not, he insisted he
wouldn't change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like if I had to make the decision again, I would still
leave Georgia,'' said Jones, tears flowing down his face in a
television interview. ``God does things for a reason and he's
testing me now.... I've just got to go in there and work hard and
get some playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you go into the draft as a young player, it's a
gamble,'' Harrick said. ``I really disagree with the rules now that
say he can't come back if you've hired an agent. Rules are supposed
to help people and this doesn't help Jumaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope for the best for Jumaine because he's really a
good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the SEC's leading scorer last year (18.8 points per game)
and the Bulldogs' leading rebounder (8.7), was projected to go as
high as seventh and few analysts expected him to last past the
first 15 selections. But there were questions about Jones'
ballhandling and defensive skills and his ability to handle the
transition from power forward to small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Those uncertainties contributed to Jones slipping, as did some
surprise early picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every kid who is contemplating leaving school early should
have looked at the expression on that kid's face,'' TV commentator
John Thompson said of the tearful Jones. ``Stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
