<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT01-COX     07-01 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulls take Brand with 1st pick
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For all the questions about his height, or lack
thereof, and all the concerns about his judgment after being the
first player to bolt Duke before his senior season, it all came
back to Elton Brand's skill. It was undeniable to the meticulous
Jerry Krause, general manager of the rebuilding Chicago Bulls, who
made Brand the first pick in Wednesday night's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, speculation was that Krause wavered among
Brand; Steve Francis, who went No. 2 to Vancouver, and
multi-talented Lamar Odom, who worked out for the Bulls on the eve
of the draft and emerged confident he would be their choice.
</P>
<P>
   But Krause went for the 6-foot-8 Brand, last season's NCAA
consensus player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough decision. But we came to a decision that
Elton Brand is an outstanding player,'' Krause said. ``A lot of
players wanted to come here. But young Mr. Brand is tough with
great character and he works very hard. He plays a lot larger than
6-8 in that he has long arms and strong hands. . . And we feel very
good about him as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brand: ``I'm blessed. I didn't have the slightest idea (I'd
go No. 1). It'll be a lot of pressure in Chicago, especially being
the No. 1 pick. But I just have to face it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the unpredictable draft took shape after Brand.
Point guard Francis went to the Grizzlies, even though Vancouver
has Mike Bibby running the club. That left open speculation that
Francis would be traded for veteran help _ or that the 6-foot-3
Francis would play alongside 6-1 Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the high-flying Francis had one thing in mind:
``I want to do some of the things I did in college that made me a
great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom, whose stock my have been affected by his indecision to
stay in the draft, went to the Los Angeles Clippers with the fourth
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Odom did not seem concerned about where he landed _ or by his
actions in recent weeks. He fired an agent and tried to get
reinstated at Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it happened,'' he said. ``The situation
got chaotic. But it's over now and I'm looking forward to a great
year. I can't wait to get to L.A. and get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Many trades rumored before the draft did not materialize. There
was countless deal talk, but none of any magnitude that were
consummated. The big speculation was Indiana sending reserve
forward Antonio Davis to Toronto for the fifth selection, which
still may happen. The Raptors took high-schooler Jonathan Bender
from Picayne, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The first college senior taken in the draft went next. Wally
Szczerbiak of Miami (Ohio) was taken by Minnesota, where he wowed
the Timberwolves staff with his overall skill and shooting ability.
And they wowed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had a home there when I worked out there,''
Szczerbiak said. ``I want to be a winner, and I'm going to a
winner. Hopefully, I can bring them to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guard Richard Hamilton of national champion UConn went
to Washington at No. 7, followed by point guard Andre Miller, whom
the Hawks had an eye on, to Cleveland. When Phoenix took small
forward Shawn Marion from UNLV at No. 9, that left another highly
rated point guard, Jason Terry of Arizona, for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   An early surprise was Duke guard Trajan Langdon at No. 11 to
Cleveland. When Blue Devils teammates Corey Maggette went to
Seattle at 13 and William Avery to Minnesota at 14, Duke became the
first college to produce four first-rounders _ and the round was
not halfway over.
</P>
<P>
   The first foreign player was center Aleksander Radojevic, 12th
to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   He played one season at Barton County (Kan.) Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Another center, Frederic Weis of France, was the second player
from overseas. He went No. 15 to the New York Knicks, whose
starting center, Patrick Ewing, missed most of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks could have chosen local star Ron Artest of St.
John's, who went to the Bulls on the next choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat did go local, choosing University of Miami forward Tim
James with the 25th pick. The most obscure player was the Lakers
selecting Division III standout Devean George of Augsburg (Minn.)
College.
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see NBA, G9
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
