A5517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUS-SEATBELTS01-COX     07-01 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-SEATBELTS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seat belts on school buses among laws taking effect today
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida joins New York and New Jersey today
as the only states to require seat belts on school buses, a move
driven by a deadly Vero Beach crash and last-minute political
deals.
</P>
<P>
   The law's effective date is today, though its impact will be
spread over the next decade: Lap belts or other federally approved
restraints must be on new buses purchased after Dec. 31, 2000. Up
to 10 percent of the state's 18,000 buses are replaced each year.
Elementary schools will take priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd required seat belts on all buses right away it
wouldn't have passed,'' said David Cullen, a Florida PTA regional
representative in Sarasota and a leading advocate for the law. ``I
think it did pass this year because of increasing awareness, and
that had a lot to do with what happened in Vero Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Also effective today, police can stop an adult and give a ticket
if a child is not buckled up in a car. Previously, the law was not
clear and many law enforcement agencies gave tickets only if the
driver was stopped for something else.
</P>
<P>
   Tougher sentencing under ``Three Strikes'' and ``10-20-Life''
legislation takes effect today as well, though a parental
notice-of-abortion law will not be enforced until July 15 at the
earliest while a legal challenge plays out.
</P>
<P>
   Seat belt activists like Cullen had been trying for years to get
belts on school buses, but many lawmakers were reluctant to dictate
to districts that they must spend more. Lap belts cost $1,200 to
$2,200 to order on a new bus, and three to five times that to add
to an old bus. The cost of retrofitting the state's whole fleet
might run to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   In January, two months before the spring legislative session, a
school bus crash in Indian River County killed two and injured 14
when the bus driver ran a stop sign and collided with a truck. Seat
belts may not have eliminated all loss of life and injury, but they
probably would have greatly reduced injuries when students were
thrown violently around the inside of the vehicle as it rolled,
Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
   The horror of that crash helped keep alive the bill until the
final week of the session, but the Senate version remained stuck in
committee. Sen. Jim Sebesta, R-St. Petersburg, agreed to accept the
bus legislation as an amendment to his bill saying adults can be
ticketed if children aren't buckled up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Cynthia Chestnut, D-Gainesville, bartered to
save the bill in the House, according to legislative staffers in
both parties. Chestnut switched her vote to bring the parental
notice-of-abortion bill to the floor, earning her a ``chit'' with
the Republican leadership, which she used to move the bus bill up
the priority list, staffers said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker John Thrasher's aides do not recall it happening that
way, because ``he does not do quid pro quo,'' a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the bill passed despite misgivings in larger
districts, according to Cullen. The big districts feared they were
getting into a political minefield of deciding which neighborhoods
got seat belts first.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. James Hargrett, D-Tampa, who represents a largely black
district, expressed those worries on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, when there's a short end of the stick, some of
my constituents end up getting it,'' Hargrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County is ready to move ahead and spend up to $2,200
per bus on some 60 to 80 buses a year, said Bob Riley, director of
transportation for the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a real plus,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, bus drivers say they welcome anything that keeps
kids safely seated, though they worry about one more added
responsibility _ to make sure kids are actually strapped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea if the kids are going to do it,'' said Sharon
Munley, trustee for Local 1227 of the National Conference of
Firemen and Oilers, which represents about 600 drivers in Palm
Beach County. ``But how will the driver know?''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he will not expect drivers to leave their seats and
walk down the aisle checking seat belts. But it may be that if the
driver sees a student standing, and obviously not wearing a belt,
that the driver can write up the violation for administrators to
handle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The law says that neither the school nor the driver can be held
liable for an injury solely caused by a student's failure to wear a
seat belt. If past lawsuits are any indication, though, that
probably won't let schools off the hook for taking ``reasonable
care'' that kids are buckled in.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 to 1997, nearly 6,000 students were injured in school
bus accidents in Florida, with 242 of those injuries
incapacitating.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen admits seat belts cannot prevent all fatal accidents,
such as the tire that came loose from a vehicle in Miami-Dade
County in 1991 and smashed through a bus window, killing three. But
a properly fastened belt could have prevented, for example, a
Broward County girl from falling to her death out the emergency
door in the back of a bus in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has materially improved the safety of all Florida kids
riding on school buses,'' Cullen said. ``And it reinforces the
message of `buckle up' every time the child gets on the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
