<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5518 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     07-01 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON WANTS BULLS, NOT ROOKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Nothing resembling a Michael Jordan clone was
available to the low-drafting Lakers on Wednesday, but new coach
Phil Jackson had his mind on the original.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers begin retooling under Jackson, the former Bulls
coach admitted he'd like MJ to help the transition to the triangle
offense. Or, at the least, Scottie Pippen, Jud Buechler or B.J.
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson doesn't believe in playing rookies, so Laker draftees
Devean George of Augsburg College and John Celestand of Villanova
could be nonfactors this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson does believe the herd of ex-Bulls roaming the league
could greatly benefit a Lakers team that has no experience playing
the Bulls' system. They might pursue some in that herd today, when
teams begin speaking with free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest I've discussed everybody, including Michael
Jordan,'' Jackson said prior to the draft. ``You just discuss that
kind of stuff.... I don't think there's ever a chance of Michael
coming back, but I think everybody wants to know, even from the top
on down, is there a possibility you envision.''
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic possibility would be signing someone like
Buechler, the former Bulls forward who is a free agent after
playing in Detroit last season. And though the Lakers adamantly
deny trade rumors involving Pippen, Jackson has kicked his name
around too _ ``My options are wide open on that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'd be very important for this team to have a couple
guys on it that really know how to function inside the (triangle)
offense, so... they can learn by just following, copycatting on the
floor,'' Jackson said. Getting such a player ``would be a luxury.
Whether that's going to happen or not, I can't tell you. I just can
tell you we're staying in tune to it.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA teams cannot consummate trades or sign free agents until
Aug. 1, but the negotiating period opens today. Jackson's top
priority is a power forward, and he's strongly interested in
Toronto free agent Charles Oakley, who could sign here for the $2
million salary exception.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley could command millions more from the Raptors but has said
he's willing to take less to play for the Lakers. And Toronto has
prepared for his departure, reportedly trading for Indiana's
Antonio Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the time comes for us to be able to pursue Charles
Oakley, I'm sure we're going to have our hats in the ring,''
Jackson said. ``Charles Oakley will definitely fill a gap. He's a
player who gives you some power, gives you rebounds and is a Dennis
Rodman-type role player.''
</P>
<P>
   Buechler could give the Lakers depth at small forward and
shooting guard, and ``is a favorite player of mine,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   With Rick Fox probably returning, the Lakers will already be
deep at small forward, unless they trade Glen Rice _ whose
one-year, $7.1 million option they picked up Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is a free agent who has earned his early-Bird rights with
the Lakers, making him a good bet to re-sign. He's eligible for a
starting salary of $3.08 million and a six-year deal for $24.25
million.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Rice would be ``a great player'' in his system and
that Fox is ``a luxury player, a starter that's been able to adapt
to the bench. He's a very important part of this organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Also becoming free agents today are J.R. Reid, Derek Fisher and
Ruben Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made it clear he wants an upgrade over the inconsistent
Reid, and he was noncommittal on Fisher, last season's starting
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known newcomers, rookies George and Celestand, will
have a challenge just finding minutes. George provides depth at
shooting guard and small forward, Celestand at point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those old-school guys that say rookies have to sit
on the bench and learn,'' Jackson said, ``especially when they're
coming into the NBA and playing on a team that's as good as this
one is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
