<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DAVIS-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS CLIP DAVIS' DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets take rejection well.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by Baron Davis' refusal to work out for them before the
NBA draft, the Hornets selected Davis with the third pick Wednesday
evening and instantaneously shattered his Clipper dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his agent, Arn Tellem, had hoped that rejecting
Charlotte's workout invitation would serve as a turnoff. Instead,
the Hornets, desperate for a point guard, stuck to their plan and
made Davis the highest UCLA player drafted since David Greenwood
went second to Chicago in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great opportunity,'' Davis said. ``I'm on a
team that made a tremendous (but unsuccessful) run to the playoffs
last season. They have a lot of seasoned veterans. I think with me
coming in, I can bring a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets favored Duke power forward Elton Brand and Maryland
point guard Steve Francis; both filled needs and had high name
recognition in ACC territory. When Brand and Francis went first and
second, respectively, the Hornets turned to Davis, a 6-foot-2,
210-pound playmaker who left UCLA after his sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   After his union with the Charlotte became official, Davis
sidestepped the earlier rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The workouts I had were scheduled all over the place, so I
could never fit (the Hornets) solid in my schedule until last week,
when I got hurt,'' said Davis, who twisted his ankle. ``I really
didn't think they'd be interested in me, that's why I didn't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was disappointed to not be playing for the Clippers,
Davis said: ``No, not at all. I was going to be happy anywhere I
went. I'll make the most of my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis will compete with veteran David Wesley for the starting
point guard job alongside former Lakers wing man Eddie Jones, who
joined the Hornets in the Glen Rice trade last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's sweet,'' Davis said. ``Eddie played for the Lakers
and he played (pick-up games) at UCLA. We were in the backcourt a
couple times. Now, it's going to be permanent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
