<HEADLINE>
LAKERS EXERCISE OPTION ON RICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Lakers exercised their one-year option on Glen
Rice on Wednesday, preventing him from becoming a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who had sought a new multiyear contract that would pay $12
million to $14 million, will earn $7.1 million next season. The
Lakers knew Rice might be unhappy with a lesser deal, but they were
not allowed to negotiate with him until today and could not be sure
a long-term agreement would be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the awkward part of it for us is we can't negotiate
with anyone (until July 1),'' Lakers executive vice president Jerry
West said. ``We really value Glen a lot, and we were in a position
where if we put him out there as a free agent, we might not get him
back. But I think our intent is to have him finish his career here
in Los Angeles.... We gave up a lot (Eddie Jones and Elden
Campbell) to get him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
