<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN BOMBERS FACE OFF AGAINST AMERICAN FIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russian bombers flew close enough to Iceland and
Norway last week to cause the United States and Norway to scramble
fighter planes as a precaution, a National Security Council
official said on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He said the eyebrow-raising incident, reminiscent of the kind of
Kremlin muscle-flexing that was common during the cold war,
occurred as part of Russia's largest military exercises since the
breakup of the Soviet Union. The exercises, named West '99,
involved up to 50,000 troops, more than 30 ships and Russian air
force and naval aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Early last Friday, two long-range Bear bombers flew near
Iceland, prompting the U.S. military to send up four F-15 fighters
and a patrol plane to escort the Russian craft in a clockwise route
around the island and back toward Russian territory. The incident
was first reported in Thursday's Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   At about the time the Bear bombers were near Iceland, two
Russian Blackjack bombers flew along the Norwegian coastline.
Norway, like Iceland and the United States a member of NATO, sent
up interceptor jets, but Russian reports said they failed to reach
the bombers before the bombers turned for home.
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Council official said there was apparently
no violation of Iceland's or Norway's air space by the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what might have motivated the Russians to fly close to the
two NATO countries, he said, ``They reminded us that they're a
force to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Council official said that American
officials have no doubt that the incident was linked to the recent
tensions over Russia's early intervention in Kosovo and the debates
over what part Russia would play in the peacekeeping force there.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post quoted Moscow officials as saying the
flights near Iceland and Norway had been planned in advance.
``Nothing more, nothing less,'' said Col. Gen. Anatoly Kornukov,
commander of the Russian air force.
</P>
<P>
   The National Security Council official said he was sure the
Russian bombers were not carrying nuclear weapons, though they are
capable of carrying them into U.S. territory. ``They, like us, do
not exercise with live ordnance like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the incident was regarded in Washington as a
military matter, not a diplomatic one. American government
officials have no plans to protest to the Kremlin, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
