<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-FOSTER01-CO     07-01 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-FOSTER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SWT's Foster winds up with Pacers
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He wasn't included in very many mock NBA drafts.
And national talk radio shows rarely mentioned his name. Jeff
Foster just figured he knew something that wasn't obvious to
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Call the former Southwest Texas State star clairvoyant. Judging
by the number of teams that appeared interested in him, Foster
believed he would be selected somewhere between picks No. 19 and
25.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State used the 21st pick of the first round to select
Foster, the still-growing SWT center who was recently measured at
just a smidgen under 7 feet. Foster, aside from becoming an instant
millionaire, also made school history Wednesday when he became the
first Bobcat to be selected in the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't saying anything to anybody, but I knew where I'd be
going,'' Foster said from his parents' home in San Antonio minutes
after he was selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody mentioned me because I was a player who wasn't well
known to a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kris Clack, the former University of Texas standout, waited
longer to hear his name. Ten minutes before the draft ended, the
Boston Celtics selected him with the 55th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Clack had been forecast as a late first-round pick, but his
stock plummeted because scouts feared that his shot was too
inconsistent to be an effective shooting guard in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, despite playing for a low-profile school, was well-known
in NBA circles.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Commissioner David Stearn called his name,
Foster's San Francisco-based agent called to tell him he'd been
traded to Indiana. But the trade wasn't announced for another hour.
</P>
<P>
   To acquire Foster, Indiana sent Pittsburgh guard Vonteego
Cummings, whom they had selected with the 26th pick, and a future
first-round draft pick to Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   The trade wasn't that surprising to Foster, given that he had
spent most of Wednesday in Indianapolis, working out for the second
time for Pacers Coach Larry Bird. Foster made it back to San
Antonio about two hours before the draft started.
</P>
<P>
   He was told that Indiana made the trade, rather than waiting to
select him five picks later, because the Pacers feared Houston
would draft him at No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the draft, Indiana made room for Foster by trading
reserve center Antonio Davis to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's draft position guaranteed that he will be paid a total
of $2.3 million over the next three years, with salaries of
$714,800, $768,400 and $822,000.
</P>
<P>
   Teams tended to shy away from shooting guards such as Clack on
Wednesday night. But big men were at a premium, which gave Foster a
huge advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams are constantly in search of an agile 7-footer who can
at least rebound and block shots. The past six drafts have produced
only nine starting centers. And only 10 starting centers still
remain with the team that drafted them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
