<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-SPURS01-COX     07-01 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-SPURS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spurs save money by trading 1st-round pick
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ NBA teams are not allowed to say ``pass'' when
their turn comes during the annual draft, so the San Antonio Spurs
did the next best thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, drafting 29th _ last _ in the first round, did not
believe anyone available was likely to earn a spot on their team,
not to mention the three-year guaranteed contract all first-round
players receive. To circumvent having to pay the $1.8 million for
three years, the Spurs drafted 6-foot-10-inch Leon Smith of Martin
Luther King High School in Chicago and traded him to Dallas for two
second-round picks. Second-round picks do not receive guaranteed
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want it. We were thrilled to be able to get rid of
it,'' Spurs coach and general manager Gregg Popovich said of his
first-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had questions about whether we wanted to make a three-year
commitment to someone picked 29th,'' said Sam Schuler, the Spurs
director of player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Rockets, picking 22nd, drafted Kenny Thomas, a power
forward from New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas did not have a first-round pick. The Mavs traded that
pick to Phoenix in a deal that brought point guard Steve Nash to
Dallas this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs receive Gordon Giricek, a guard from Croatia whom
Dallas picked at No. 40 in the second round. Giricek, 22, can
continue playing in Europe and sign with the Spurs in the future.
The Spurs also will receive a future second-round pick. The Spurs
used their own second -round pick for 6-6 Emmanuel Ginobili from
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' primary goal is to keep the championship team intact
as best they can. Three Spurs are free agents _ reserves Will
Perdue, Malik Rose and Jaren Jackson. Perdue, a center, is the most
likely to leave. He said this week there is a 50 percent he will
re-sign. The Spurs, who paid Perdue $4.2 million last season, might
not want to spend that much again for someone whose playing time
was taken by Rose in the NBA Finals against New York. As scarce as
competent centers are in the NBA, Perdue is likely to receive
offers from several teams.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who will receive an opportunity to make the team
next season are 6-9 Gerard King, who spent much of the season as
the Spurs' 12th man; guard Brandon Williams, who spent most of the
season as a practice player assigned to the injured list; and guard
Derrick Dial, a second-round draft pick in 1998 who played in
Europe this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs are over the NBA's salary cap. Should they want, or
need, to add veteran players, the the Spurs are likely to have
three exceptions to the salary cap available _ $2 million, $1.2
million and $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were thin along the front line last season because
of injuries. Thin is not a word associated with the 260-pound
Thomas. Listed at 6-8 in college, Thomas measured only 6-6 1/2
without his shoes at the pre-draft camp in Chicago. Thomas, wo
averaged 17.8 points and 9.9 rebounds last season, will move into a
rotation that includes Hakeem Olajuwon, Charles Barkley and Othella
Harrington, if Barkley, a free agent, re-signs.
</P>
<P>
   With their second-round pick, No. 44 overall, the Rockets picked
6-9 Tyrone Washington from Mississippi State. Six picks later, the
Rockets took 6-8 Venson Hamilton of Nebraska, the Big 12 player of
the year last season.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is whether the Rockets will make a blockbuster
trade. The Los Angeles Lakers have offered Glen Rice and former
Rocket Robert Horry in exchange for Scottie Pippen. Since a trade
was not completed by midnight today, the Rockets and Lakers must
wait until Aug. 1 to make a deal. No trades are allowed between
July 1 and Aug. 1. Houston has already decided not to trade Hakeem
Olajuwon to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
