</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF WORKER ENCOUNTERS VAST DESTRUCTION, SUFFERING IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The finger was charred to the bone, but still wearing a gold
wedding band.
</P>
<P>
   American relief worker Kevin Cook calls it the saddest thing he
saw since returning to Kosovo on June 14 as communications director
for World Vision, an international Christian aid organization.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who graduated from Mesa High School and attended Arizona
State University, has seen more than his share of horror in 13
trips to the troubled region over the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to sit down and weep,'' Cook, 41, said by
telephone Friday from World Vision offices in the Kosovo capital of
Pristina. ``I've stopped trying to understand why it happened, how
individuals are capable of doing this to other people _ the evil. I
become worn out physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Cook left Kosovo and returned to World Vision
regional headquarters in Vienna, where his wife and two young
children were waiting.
</P>
<P>
   After a much-needed vacation, they will head for their next
posting in San Jose, Costa Rica, to work on a community development
project.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tragedies he has witnessed, Cook departed
war-ravaged Kosovo reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very sad to leave this place,'' he said. ``It's an
extraordinary place. I will come back, I just don't know how
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   World Vision first dispatched relief workers to Kosovo when the
conflict erupted there in February 1998. President Slobodan
Milosevic had begun a campaign to drive ethnic Albanians out of the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who finished his bachelor's degree in journalism at Kansas
State University and earned a master's degree in developmental
studies from the School for International Training in Vermont, was
one of the first three workers to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the last two to leave last March when NATO forces
advised all agencies to evacuate just days before NATO airstrikes
began.
</P>
<P>
   When the bombs stopped three months later, about a dozen
agencies returned, this time to clean up the aftermath of a war
that had displaced 80 percent of the 1.8 million Kosovars and left
the region in ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Like other relief agencies targeted by the Serbs, World Vision
offices had been attacked. The agency's building in Pristina was
partly burned and looted of its computers and furniture, sold on a
thriving black market.
</P>
<P>
   Before workers could resume their duties, bomb specialists swept
the building for booby traps and land mines, which remain a danger.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Cook had visited a 9-year-old boy hospitalized
when a land mine nearly blew off his leg. The boy's family had
recently returned to Kosovo after fleeing months before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so tragic,'' Cook said, his voice weary.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's anger is directed toward Milosevic, whom he calls an evil
man who exploited ethnic hatred for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cook said, ``his Greater Serbia is a country in ruins, a
blighted landscape of unemployment and despair, mass graves,
corpses, dead livestock, blocks of old shops and homes reduced to
rubble, wells poisoned by human bodies, mosques burned.''
</P>
<P>
   And although NATO bombs may have done some good, Cook said,
non-violent efforts to resolve the conflict should have been
started a decade ago when Milosevic came to power and foretold his
campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem got way out of hand,'' Cook said, ``and became a
humanitarian catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook, whose job is to comfort the afflicted, sometimes needs
comforting himself. Since returning to postwar Kosovo, he has been
overwhelmed by the sight of mass graves and flattened
neighborhoods, the horror stories told by refugees, reports of
friends and colleagues missing or feared dead.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's more than Cook can endure. He recently e-mailed
his father, who was pastor of Central Christian Church in Mesa for
10 years, acknowledging ``compassion fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook calls his father ``my principal mentor and best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cook is semiretired and now lives with Kevin's mother,
Barbara, a retired speech pathologist, in Baltimore. They winter in
Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Through his work with the international Christian Missionary
Fellowship, the elder Cook can empathize with his son's despair and
has tried to help him reconcile his faith with the brutality
visited upon the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragedy is a reality of life,'' the Rev. Cook said from
Baltimore, sharing the advice he gave his son. ``It's not an
intentional part of God's plan. The faithful and the faithless
experience it. It's part of God allowing us freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his son a man of ``high moral and ethical values'' who
has ``a compassion for human need.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proud of him and what he's been able to accomplish,''
he said. ``I didn't want him to leave (Kosovo) before he was ready.
I think he is now. He's seen this come full circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Cook sounds less satisfied with his accomplishments.
Although World Vision and more than a dozen other agencies have
banded to assist the needy of Kosovo, Cook is overwhelmed by the
magnitude of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done a lot of good, but the amount of evil and
violence has far outweighed any good we've done,'' he said. ``Now
it's a country totally wrecked.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook also worries that ethnic Albanians flooding back into the
country, protected by NATO-led peacekeepers, will exact revenge
against their former tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for Albanian Kosovars to get their
vengeance,'' he said. ``Some of them will not be peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vast majority of them can restrain themselves, there is
a hope for peace. I've said they can't live ``under'' the Serbs,
but they can live ``with'' them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook's memories of Kosovo, a region of lush, rolling countryside
that resembles Kentucky, are not all grim. He will remember acts of
kindness by the Kosovar people he calls intelligent and good,
people he came to love.
</P>
<P>
   He will remember nights sleeping in the woods with refugees who
had no food but found a way to bring Cook a cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the Albanian rescued by a Serb who, in turn,
promised to protect the Serb after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's most joyful moments have been discovering friends thought
dead but found alive. His closest friend was reported to have been
gunned down by Serbs at a Kosovar funeral. Cook was thrilled to see
the man on CNN, alive and well and meeting with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair in London.
</P>
<P>
   After Costa Rica, Cook would like to return to Arizona, which he
still considers home. He recently bought a house in Mesa. His wife,
Teresa, who is from Puerto Rico, feels at home with the Hispanic
flavor of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   But he will return often to Kosovo, he said, a province and a
people who have profoundly affected his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I come back, I hope to find a democracy here, where people
can live in peace and freedom, in the society they deserve,'' he
said. ``That's what I want to see. I pray I'll see it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
