<HEADLINE>
HEALTH PROBLEMS PERSIST FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ They are like two ships passing, or stalled, in the
night. Todd Hollandsworth goes one way. Devon White goes the other.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth's health is in question after he experienced
swelling in his left tricep. The Dodgers think it's the result of a
ball he dived for during the weekend series with San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   White, who missed the last two games with stiffness in his neck,
returned to center field, where Hollandsworth spent the last two
games. But White said he could have returned after missing just
Sunday's game in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to go (Tuesday),'' White said before Wednesday's
game at San Diego. ``I was fine. I'm the only one that knows if I
can play or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said White wasn't ready to play
Tuesday. He said White still had trouble turning his head enough to
get a good read on the pitchers. Johnson said he wouldn't put White
out there unless the center fielder was 100 percent, though White
pinch-hit in the 11th inning Tuesday and remained in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no beef (with Johnson),'' White said. ``I'm here. When
I'm called, I go.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a season of nagging injuries for White, who missed
seven games with a hamstring injury in May and three games in early
June with a groin injury. At least that's what the club says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I look up, someone's saying I'm hurt, and I'm
not,'' said White, one of the premier defensive center fielders.
``If they're giving me a day off, then give me a day off. There's
been some nagging things, the hamstring and groin.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, neither Johnson nor Dodgers physical therapist Pat
Screnar said they knew to what extent Hollandsworth would be out.
What it does, though, is offset Johnson's plan to use
Hollandsworth's left-handed bat to split up the righty-dominated
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he can swing the bat,'' Johnson said. ``I hope
he's going to get looked at Friday. They're trying to get the
swelling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hollandsworth's last stint on the disabled list began
as a day-to-day injury. It lasted three weeks and was finally
diagnosed as a strained oblique muscle. He began the season on the
disabled list with a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Back in a groove: Maybe nearly two weeks of Camp Dempsey were
enough to turn Todd Hundley back into the catcher he used to be
with the Mets. At the least, he's back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley hit a two-run homer Tuesday against San Diego, but more
impressive _ and more encouraging to the Dodgers _ were a pair of
throws he made to second base. He caught one runner trying to steal
and would have had the second one, but Jose Vizcaino dropped the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I figured it out,'' Hundley said. ``I was trying to
throw the ball too hard. Then it happened. No stress on the arm, no
nothing. I've been trying to throw the ball too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even though Hundley made two strong throws against a
team that stole nine bases the previous day, Johnson still pulled
him in favor of Angel Pena when the speedy Reggie Sanders walked
with one out in the 11th. Sanders still stole second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davey knows what he's doing,'' Hundley said. ``I'm cool with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he made the move partially because Hundley was
slated to catch Wednesday and if he continued to go longer, it
would have jeopardized that.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Injured right-hander Antonio Osuna is
scheduled to throw another bullpen session today and Johnson said
he could be shipped out for a rehab assignment soon after. Also,
Mark Grudzielanek took grounders at shortstop and could be ready
for a rehab stint as well.... Vern Troyer, who played Mini-Me in
``Austin Powers, The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' threw out the ceremonial
first pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
