<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY FIRST: BULLS TAKE DUKE'S BRAND AT NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
 790&AMP;ADD-NYT  
 (Subs for updating)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They passed up on the risk and potential of Lamar
Odom, the explosiveness of Steve Francis and an open invitation to
Wally Szczerbiak's world. In the end, the Chicago Bulls went
straight to the low post to rebuild their franchise, taking the
burly Duke University forward Elton Brand with the No. 1 pick in
tonight's National Basketball Association draft.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of speculation over who would emerge first from
this year's class, Bulls General Manager Jerry Krause went the
conservative route in picking the 6-foot-8-inch, 260-pound college
player of the year before a nearly sold-out crowd at the MCI
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know who would go one,'' Brand said after his
selection, echoing the sentiment of most NBA observers. ``Lamar
Odom, Steve Francis, Wally Szczerbiak, they're all great players,
so I didn't know exactly where I would fit in this draft.''
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore became one of four Blue Devils picked in the first
round. The others were Trajan Langdon, taken 11th by Cleveland;
Corey Maggette, taken 13th by Seattle, and William Avery, taken
14th by Minnesota. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the only big deal, made late in the evening, the SuperSonics
sent Maggette, Billy Owens, Dale Ellis and Don MacLean to Orlando
for Horace Grant and two future second-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver picked a disheartened Francis, the skywalking Maryland
junior, with the second pick, and Charlotte nabbed UCLA point guard
Baron Davis with the third pick. Odom, out of the University of
Rhode Island, was the draft's biggest enigma and was taken fourth
by the Los Angeles Clippers. Five point guards were among the first
14 selections.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise of the night involved the Toronto Raptors ignoring
Szczerbiak, the Miami of Ohio all-American, and plucking
18-year-old Jonathan Bender out of Picayune (Miss.) High School.
Bender, Raptor officials said, was reportedly headed to Indiana in
a trade for Antonio Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Raptors need to clear salary-cap room before the
deal is complete, the transaction may not be made before Aug. 1.
Still, their intention to acquire the 6-10, 205-pound Bender said a
lot about Indiana's desire to get younger and more athletic in a
changing Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Coach Larry Bird and the Lakers' team president, Jerry
West, tabbed Bender as the best athlete in the draft, and
apparently Bird became fixed on drafting the first high school
player taken.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak, the first senior taken, was drafted sixth by the
Minnesota Timberwolves. There was speculation that Cleveland might
try to make a deal to acquire Szczerbiak, whom the Cavaliers wanted
all along, in part because of his popularity in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   There was an absence of blockbuster trades, but the feeling
among many team officials is that with Aug. 1 the first date that
teams can sign free agents, more deals involving drafted players
would be made over the next month.
</P>
<P>
   The host Wizards had the seventh pick, and their selection of
the Connecticut swingman Richard Hamilton nearly brought the house
down. The only similar decibel level came when Francis raised his
arms as he walked up to the podium to shake the hand of
Commissioner David Stern; in one scintillating year at Maryland, he
had become a D.C. area favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Francis sounded too thrilled about going to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how long he planned to remain a Grizzly, he said: ``As
soon as I can get this hat off. I hear it's cold, rainy, far away
from here and they take all your money,'' an apparent reference to
Canada's tax system. Mike Bibby expressed the same discontent a
year ago as Vancouver's No. 2 pick, but eventually settled in.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Cavaliers took Utah's Andre Miller with the eighth
pick. The Phoenix Suns took the University of Nevada-Las Vegas
forward Shawn Marion with the ninth and the Atlanta Hawks, one day
after moving Mookie Blaylock to Golden State for Bimbo Coles, Duane
Ferrell and their No. 21 pick, took Arizona's Jason Terry with the
10th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Terry was one of five point guards taken in the first 14 picks
along with Francis, Davis, Avery and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks, with the fifteenth pick, passed on the
local player, Ron Artest of St. John's, and chose Frederic Weis, a
7-2 center from France.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, the first Duke player to ever be taken No. 1, seemed like
the logical pick, given his production last season and that the
Bulls' starting center was Dickey Simpkins. Frontcourt help was
clearly needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of pressure playing for the Bulls, with the
heritage and the championships,'' Brand said. ``I am looking
forward to meeting that challenge. I don't know what my role is
going to be yet, but I'm ready to get out there and find out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Odom created the most stir before the draft, especially after
his whirlwind interview tour on Tuesday. Working out in Miami in
the morning for Heat Coach Pat Riley, who was contemplating trading
up for Vancouver's second pick, Odom showed up at a Washington
hotel in midafternoon before catching a late flight to Chicago to
meet with Krause and Bulls Coach Tim Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been hectic for the 19-year-old sophomore, but it
was the only way he could push his value up after two weeks of
skipping scheduled workouts, missing the league's mandated
physical, firing his agent and briefly entertaining the idea of
returning to Rhode Island _ a notion that was scuttled by the
National Collegiate Athletic Association and by the school. ``Some
of the decisions I made might not have been the best decisions for
me at that time,'' Odom said. ``But hey, I'm 19 years old. It's a
good thing I didn't make those mistakes when I was 29.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
