<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RETURN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE FAMILY IN ARIZONA READY FOR RETURN TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Naim Berisha is going home.
</P>
<P>
   Home to a land he and his family were forced at gunpoint to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   To a land patrolled by armies, to a city rocked by bombs and
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Home to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how much I'd like to be in Pristina at this
moment,'' he said Monday night, tears welling in his eyes as he
thought of the capital city. ``I'd like to be in my job, in my
office, in my home, with my people.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Berisha and his family _ wife Besa, 35; son Dardan, 15;
and daughter Diana, 7 _ will fly home from the Valley. The Kosovar
refugees were on the run for two months in the Balkans before
spending the past month with relatives in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left, I said, `We'll never go back to Kosovo.' I never
believed in three months we can go back to a free Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Berisha knows there may be mines in quiet fields. A calm street
scene could become chaos at any moment. His Pristina home was
looted, gutted of his family's possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and neighbors may be dead.
</P>
<P>
   But, to Naim, it's time to go back.
</P>
<P>
   When the NATO bombing strikes began March 24, the family of four
moved to a relative's nearby home. Naim, a 46-year-old city
employee in Pristina, says police were placing bombs in the
neighborhoods to try to trick citizens. They would say the damage
from the bombs was the work of the Kosovo Liberation Army or NATO.
When police placed a car bomb nearby, he said, the Berishas fled to
the other side of the city.
</P>
<P>
   They stayed for days with 18 people in a two-bedroom apartment,
locked inside during the day and hiding in the basement at times at
night.
</P>
<P>
   They also watched through a window as police stopped a man in a
small car on the street below, asked him some questions and then
sprayed the car with machine-gun fire. Moments later, they shot the
man in the head with a pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Police toting machine guns and wearing black masks went
apartment to apartment forcing people out. The Berishas climbed in
their car and joined others headed for the border of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The drive normally would take about an hour. It took five days.
As they waited in the colony of cars trying to cross the border,
they had no food, slept in the car and could not leave the road.
They were afraid and humiliated, Besa says.
</P>
<P>
   They arrived at the Macedonian border April 5, where ethnic
Albanians they did not know took them in until they left for the
United States. The family arrived in Tempe in late May, getting a
taste of American life, but still with a thirst to return home.
</P>
<P>
   Home for Naim and his family was a second-floor apartment near
Arizona Mills. They would walk in the mall in the evenings. Dardan
tried tennis for the first time and walked around in Nike shoes.
Diana learned to say colors in English.
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't take long for them to realize that the apartment
complex's swimming pool is a nice answer to 105 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Naim even talked of how once the Phoenix Suns almost beat the
Michael Jordan-led Chicago Bulls to the NBA title. At times, they
almost seemed Americanized.
</P>
<P>
   But burning beneath the surface was a need to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sleep, I can't sleep,'' Naim said recently. ``I want
to go back to help my people. I have a `home, sweet home,' '' he
added after pausing for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Pristina home is a two-bedroom, one-bathroom house with a
front yard and a patio. Naim has a large garden where he worked for
hours, tending potatoes, tomatoes and more. It was part of life in
Pristina, a small but densely populated city with a few hundred
thousand residents.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives in Pristina have told the Berishas by phone that their
house appears fine structurally, but has been gutted. All the
kitchen appliances are gone. So is the television and other
electronics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' Naim said.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to return to reclaim his home, save the keepsakes that
may remain, and help the city rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The Berishas were brought to Tempe through the International
Rescue Committee, which resettles refugees. They likely could have
returned home for free if they had waited until procedures were in
place to get them home.
</P>
<P>
   Such procedures could be set in the coming weeks, local refugee
agencies said. Others said the delays were tied to the region still
being unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Naim Berisha couldn't wait.
</P>
<P>
   He worked through a New York travel agency to buy the tickets
home. Relatives said he paid $730 for each of the one-way tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The plans to return were set late last week, and the family
members prepared to go home. They began packing. Young Diana is
having a tough time leaving her relative, a newly found playmate,
in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Dardan says he feels ``very safe to go back'' because the Serbs
are no longer in control; Naim says as long as NATO is there, ``we
will feel free and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Besa isn't so sure, telling her brother-in-law that she is
``really, really nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   The family may be met at the Macedonian airport by friends, or
may have to hire a driver. The Berishas have a car that they left
in Macedonia; it may or may not still be there.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening, the family walked out of the Tempe apartment
they called home for the past month. They went to Naim's brother's
house and spent their last night in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They will leave Phoenix Thursday, though they will not arrive in
Macedonia until Friday about noon. When they board the airplane,
they will be heading home. But they know the journey is just
beginning. &QL; 
Chris Fiscus can be reached at (602) 444-7942 or at
chris.fiscus(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
