r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHPARK-ENFORCEMENT     07-01 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHPARK-ENFORCEMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHS DODGE RULES TO SEE R-RATED `SOUTH   PARK' 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At first, Rich Stone and Danny Berwick tried the
direct approach: The 15-year-olds walked up to the box office
Wednesday and asked for two tickets to the R-rated ``South Park:
Bigger, Longer and Uncut.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Like many theaters across Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, the
Fallbrook General Cinema upheld an industry agreement with
President Clinton to keep kids 17 and younger out of R-rated movies
unless accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been going to R-rated movies since I was 13, and this is
the most hassle I've ever had getting in,'' said Stone of Woodland
Hills. ``I don't want the government to be my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Other underage patrons had better luck.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Edward and Don Marshall, both 16, used a common tactic at
the Pacific Theatres at the Northridge Fashion Center: They bought
tickets to ``Austin Powers.'' Once inside, they worked their way
into the 3:25 showing of ``South Park'' amid the bustle of popcorn
sales and restroom crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to stop us from seeing it,'' Edward said.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers and theater officials said there's no way to fully
enforce the policy because you can't check everyone, and youthful
resolve will eventually prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been carding since 1968, when the MPAA guidelines came
out, but it doesn't always work,'' said Brian Callaghan, director
of communications for General Cinema. ``The ushers and ticket
clerks do all they can, but there are R-rated films like `South
Park' and `Scream' that kids want to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they will find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   The June 8 agreement between theater owners and Clinton came
after the Colorado school massacre and a long-running national
debate about the effect of violence in the media on children.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on `South Park'' is its bathroom humor and vulgar
deeds. The film itself thumbs its nose at the movie rating system:
It features a group of animated third-graders who sneak into a
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with raunchy sex jokes, juvenile displays of gross bodily
functions and wholesale profanity, ``South Park'' had to go through
several edits to get it down from from an NC-17 to an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the teen and young adult target audience balk at the
notion that ``South Park'' is bad for their brains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that TV and films are the only influence on youth
that shapes our actions is insulting. The real issues are lack of
gun control and parenting,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the attraction?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just funny as hell,'' said 17-year-old Christopher
Hussain.
</P>
<P>
   As for Stone and Berwick, after a parent bought them tickets,
they made it to the 12:45 p.m. show along with 16 other youths
high-fiving each other in victory.
</P>
<P>
   The duo had a second close brush with the sidewalk, narrowly
escaping an usher who noticed them in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just ridiculous,'' Berwick mumbled.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
