<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CARDS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-01 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Despite a modest offensive output that led to a victory Tuesday,
the Astros' attack was still on the most wanted list of local fans.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call off the posse.
</P>
<P>
   Suspects were popping up everywhere after an 11-3 victory over
the St. Louis Cardinals before 42,475 witnesses Wednesday at the
Astrodome. Almost everyone in the lineup was guilty of first-degree
slumping over the past two weeks, but perhaps Wednesday's 13-hit
outburst will be enough to overturn that verdict.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Astros' highest hit total since June 14, when they
got 13 hits against Atlanta. Four Astros had multiple-hit games,
including shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, who was 2-for-4 with three
RBIs and his first home run since last July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell was the only member of the starting lineup who did
not drive in at least one run.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored four runs in the first inning and four in the
fifth to make it a lopsided game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the type of game we needed,'' said third baseman
Bill Spiers, who had three hits to break out of an 0-for-17 slump.
``I just hope we can keep it going. Any time you're struggling as a
team, you hear about it, and you can't help but think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize that you're going to go through stretches like
that, but it's discouraging. If it doesn't discourage you, you're
not a competitor. Personally, I've been about to drive myself
crazy. It can put you in a bad mood. I hope this was a sign that
we're about to come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most runs the Astros have scored since beating
Montreal by the same score June 20. The support was plenty for Mike
Hampton, who cruised to his 10th victory, scattering eight hits
over eight innings and allowing three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who has a 2.45 ERA over his last five starts, joined
Jose Lima as the staff's double-figure winners. Shane Reynolds has
nine wins and one in waiting (a three-run lead with an inning to
play) as a result of the suspended game of June 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give credit where credit is due,'' Cardinals manager Tony La
Russa said. ``He's the best in the league, and he deserved the win.
Hampton didn't make one or two mistakes like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams struck out two of the three batters he faced and
extended his scoreless-innings streak to 8 by pitching a perfect
ninth inning to close out the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won their second in a row after four consecutive
losses to the Reds, who moved into first place in the National
League Central Division by a percentage point Sunday. Wednesday's
victory enabled the Astros to keep pace with the Reds, who beat
Arizona 2-0 for their ninth win in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an all-around good effort,'' Astros interim manager
Matt Galante said. ``It feels nice to get back-to-back wins after
what we've gone through. Hopefully, we're out of the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals starter Jose Jimenez had pitched a no-hitter in his
previous outing, but he lived on the opposite end of the spectrum
Wednesday, when just getting an out seemed like an accomplishment.
Jimenez allowed seven runs on seven hits and couldn't make it out
of the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have too much control,'' said Gutierrez, who had
gone two weeks without an RBI. ``He had pretty good control the
last time we faced him, but (Wednesday) he wasn't hitting his
spots, and that's what got him into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering how the Astros have struggled to score in recent
games, it almost seemed like a scoreboard malfunction when they
erupted for four runs in the first inning, equaling their biggest
first-inning output of the season. The Astros scored four runs in
the opening inning at Milwaukee on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some guys like it better when the game is tight, but I
like pitching with a big lead because I feel like I can settle down
and relax,'' Hampton (10-3) said. ``I was changing speeds and
getting ahead in the count. I felt like I got better later in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in games, I have a little more gas and my pitches don't
seem to move as much.''
</P>
<P>
   The first three batters reached against Jimenez, whose first of
two wild pitches allowed Craig Biggio to score the game's first
run. Carl Everett drove in a run with a sacrifice fly, and Spiers
and Richard Hidalgo each had RBI doubles in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a team gets a lead like that early and they sit on
it,'' Galante said. ``I was glad to see that we kept pushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals third baseman Fernando Tatis led off the second with a
double and scored on Edgar Renteria's double to left. Placido
Polanco singled home Renteria to cut the Astros' lead to two.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added a run in the third on Paul Bako's sacrifice fly
and four more in the fifth on Gutierrez's two-run infield single,
Hampton's sacrifice fly and Biggio's single up the middle. Solo
home runs by Gutierrez in the seventh and Jeff Bagwell in the
eighth closed out the Astros' scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, everyone knew we were going to snap out of
it,'' Bako said. ``You're going to have stretches like we had, but
over the course of a long season, the best team will prevail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
