<HEADER>
A5559 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBADRAFT-TEX     07-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAND TOPS DEVIL OF A DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it came to their massive reconstruction project, the
Chicago Bulls decided Wednesday night that it's better to be safe
than sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Passing on Rhode Island forward Lamar Odom, the Bulls made Duke
power forward Elton Brand the No. 1 overall pick in the NBA draft
and backed him up by taking St. John's small forward Ron Artest
with the 16h pick.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, 19, whose stock fell in recent weeks as he tried to
withdraw from the draft and re-enroll in school, dropped to No. 4
to the Los Angeles Clippers, Maryland guard Steve Francis went No.
2 to the Vancouver Grizzlies, and UCLA guard Baron Davis No. 3 to
the Charlotte Hornets. Odom spent yesterday at Washington's MCI
Center telling anyone who would listen that the Bulls were going to
draft him, but Chicago GM Jerry Krause selected Brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamar's a great player, but it came to a decision of Elton's
outstanding character and work ethic,'' Krause said. ``He's got
long arms, big hands and we feel very, very strongly about him as a
person. I envision him being a double-double (points and rebounds)
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Odom, ``My situation got a little chaotic, but hopefully
I'll be Rookie of the Year and prove a lot of people wrong about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   After forcing the departures of coach Phil Jackson and stars
Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen, the Bulls fell to 13-37 last
season and were the lowest-scoring team in NBA history at just over
80 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at both Lamar and Elton without fault,'' coach Tim
Floyd said. ``But combining (Brand) with Artest gives us two steps
toward where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft had a shade of Blue Devil as Brand was the first Duke
player to go No. 1 and the school had an unprecedented four players
taken in the first 14 picks. The Cleveland Cavaliers began their
draft by taking guard Trajan Langdon at No. 11, followed by
freshman sixth man Corey Maggette going No. 13 to Seattle and then
traded to Orlando, and point guard William Avery going No. 14 to
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-8 and with the wing span of a 7-footer, Brand is
expected to start at power forward despite his underdeveloped
face-up game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea I'd go first,'' said Brand, who was also leery
of Odom's presence. ``There's a lot of pressure being the top pick,
but I've got to face it. The Bulls say they needed a lot of things,
and a rebounder and solid defender in the low post was one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft didn't produce a flurry of major trades.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest one involved the Indiana Pacers trading veteran
power forward Antonio Davis to the Toronto Raptors for the fifth
pick and selecting 6-foot-11 Mississippi high-schooler Jonathan
Bender. The 18-year-old prospect gained national acclaim when he
broke Jordan's scoring record with 31 points in the McDonald's
All-American game last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, whom many compare to Minnesota's Kevin Garnett, joined
Garnett in '95 as the highest-drafted high-school player at No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we think a lot of this kid to trade away Antonio,''
said Pacers coach Larry Bird, who last year selected high-school
player Al Harrington with the 26th pick. ``He makes us younger,
more athletic and his potential is unlimited, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Magic coach Doc Rivers also pulled off a late deal,
acquiring Maggette and veterans Billy Owens, Dale Ellis and Don
MacLean from Seattle for power forward Horace Grant and two future
second-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Mavericks traded up to take Chicago high-school center
Leon Smith at No. 29 and then drafted 7-foot-1 center Wang Zhizhi
at No. 36, TCU star Lee Nailon dropped to the Hornets at No. 43.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the Bulls had the best draft by nabbing two
potential starters. The Cavaliers, despite owning picks No. 8 and
11, drafted guards backups Andre Miller and Langdon. Miller, not
considered a good long-distance shooter, will back up the similarly
skilled Brevin Knight. Langdon will vie for playing time behind
Wesley Person and Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Shawn (Kemp) and Zydrunas (Ilgauskus) inside we wanted to
stretch defenses with some shooters,'' GM Jim Paxson said. ``We've
got a little bit of a logjam in the backcourt, but you can never
have enough shooters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
