<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-01 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIKE Hampton usually celebrates crucial strikeouts the way Jose
Lima might fall into a deep, dark depression.
</P>
<P>
   He looks to the ground, shrugs his shoulders and looks almost
inconsolable. He tugs on the sleeve of his jersey and walks around
the mound with that deliberate, slow stroll of his, as if he just
got called to the principal's office and everyone knows he's
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Between innings, he'll walk to the dugout staring at his feet,
then carefully set his cap and glove on the bench next to him, fold
his hands in his lap and just sit there staring at the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as flamboyant (as Lima),'' Astros interim manager
Matt Galante said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is so much the anti-Lima. He is No Way Jose.
</P>
<P>
   But every time you look up, there has been Hampton this season,
making as quiet an All-Star Game statement as Lima has made a loud
one: Yes, way.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Lima has jiggled and slide-stepped his way to a big
win _ blaring merengue music in the clubhouse afterward _ Hampton
has marched methodically right with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night's 11-3 victory over the St. Louis Cardinals
might have been the perfect picture of how this guy with the
all-business approach somehow always has been left holding Lima's
drink, while Lima dances into the nation's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was precise, strong, sometimes even overwhelming on the
way to his 10th victory of the season. But even if he proved to be
the best player on the field and improved on numbers that in many
ways are better than Lima's, Hampton might have been hard to
notice.
</P>
<P>
   So many other stars and sideshows came to the Astrodome on
Wednesday night, it might have been difficult for the 42,475 fans
to realize there was an All-Star pitcher standing in the middle of
the field.
</P>
<P>
   There was Mark McGwire, the home-run king, slamming shot after
shot into the upper deck during batting practice as the crowd oohed
and aahed. But once the game began, Big Mac mostly slapped a bunch
of McNuggets on a 1-for-4 night.
</P>
<P>
   There was Cards starter Jose Jimenez, the guy whose last outing
was a no-hitter against Arizona's Randy Johnson. But once the game
began, Hampton quietly put up the big numbers while Jimenez's
no-hit bid this time fell 27 outs short, when Craig Biggio opened
the onslaught with a single.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the Astros' bats, living la vida loca and putting
on the kind of display that always steals the headlines. The
Astros' 13 hits and 11 runs, including a pair of doubles and a pair
of homers, were enough to overshadow anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But this guy with the serious stare and the fierce game face no
longer can be considered just another anyone.
</P>
<P>
   His eight-inning effort Wednesday moved Hampton to 10-3 for the
year, just behind Lima's 11 wins. His ERA of 3.04 is better than
Lima's 3.13 and second-best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   His innings pitched (118) are identical to Lima's. His
strikeouts (83) are more than Lima's 80. He has given up fewer
hits, fewer earned runs and fewer home runs than Lima. And
Hampton's victory Wednesday _ anonymous as it might have seemed _
was his fifth in his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   If San Diego Padres manager Bruce Bochy chooses Lima for the
All-Star team, he also should choose Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have an opportunity,'' Hampton said. ``But it's
rare to get two guys from the same team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton does it so differently from how Lima does it, but this
is the first time since 1969 the Astros have had a pair of
double-digit winners this early in the season. Both should get the
call.
</P>
<P>
   Lima dances; Hampton walks around the mound. Lima slide-steps;
Hampton stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to do it with a lot of antics,'' Hampton said.
``That's (Lima's) personality, but that's not me. I just want to
pitch. I always want to respect everybody, and the last thing I
want to do is show people up. I just have the attitude of `go do
your job and give yourself a chance to win.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lima shows up at the park smiling at everybody and talking a
blue streak. Hampton shows up with a focus that makes his teammates
keep their distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys used to tell me, `Man, you're such (a jerk) on the
days you pitch,''' Hampton said. ``But it was just a lot of focus
and concentration. It used to be an all-day thing. My wife would
throw me out of the house. But now, I'm more laid-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the Astros' clubhouse after his 10th win of the year,
there was no blaring music, no merengue beat. Hampton quietly
talked with teammates and reporters and tried to deflect all the
talk about All-Star Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just have to keep pitching and see what happens,'' he
said. ``It'd be nice, but I'm not going to make a big deal about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He never does. He just keeps winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
