<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-01 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES ROUT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ This is Dodgers baseball?
</P>
<P>
   The two games the Dodgers won in San Francisco last weekend to
harbor hope turned out to be nothing but an aberration because they
turned around and continued to do what they've done all season _
lose.
</P>
<P>
   A dubious month of Dodgers baseball ended with a dubious
distinction in a disastrous way.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown lost again to the San Diego Padres, getting pounded
for nine earned runs on 11 hits in an 11-2 loss Wednesday at
Qualcomm Stadium. The Dodgers concluded their worst month of
baseball in 20 years while the Padres are in the middle of their
best.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second-most earned runs Brown's allowed. He gave up 10
in 31/3 innings at Toronto on April 19, 1994. Brown's ERA went from
an NL-leading 2.92 to 3.43 and he fell to 9-5.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego won its club-record 12th straight game. They've beaten
the Dodgers six straight times and have won seven of eight against
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the they went 7-20 in June 1979 have the Dodgers had
as poor a June as the one that ended a few hours ago. The Dodgers'
third straight loss left them 8-17, and it is a glowing example of
why they remain in last place in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Even the one supposed given _ Brown _ couldn't accomplish
anything and didn't record an out in the seventh, though he did
give up four runs in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown gave up a season-high nine runs. Back in April, he was
yanked after 61/3 innings and three runs in a loss to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Brown pitched here he was greeted with venom from
nearly 50,000 fans and music designed to point toward the fact he
left San Diego for seven years and $105 million of security. This
time he was only booed (and cheered when he was pulled from the
game) as the Padres shellacked him.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Dodgers won only six games in August 1995 and began
last season 8-15 in April, their .320 winning percentage for June
is the lowest since their .259 winning percentage in June 1979.
</P>
<P>
   It brings up the question of whether it's been the toughest
month of Dodgers manager Davey Johnson's career. ``It's been a
tough !ital!three!off! months for me because I really want to be
able to make things easier on them and I really haven't been able
to do anything, and that makes it tough on me,'' Johnson said.
``It's more frustrating for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the perception sometimes is complacency. There's no
complacency on this ballclub. We're good enough defensively and we
should be good enough offensively. We haven't found the right key,
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the Dodgers (34-41) haven't found anything. They
continue to reside in the division cellar, the pitching hasn't
performed to expectations and the offense relies too heavily on the
home run.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Boehringer (5-1) allowed two runs in five innings for the
win. Reggie Sanders hit two homers and drove in five runs.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't start out poorly for the Dodgers. They led 1-0 on Eric
Karros' first-inning double and Brown struck out three of the first
four Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the second, and trouble for Brown after Damian
Jackson's two-run triple gave the Padres a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who doubled in a run in his first at-bat and singled in
his second, hit a solo homer to left in the fifth to tie it 2-2
before all heck broke loose.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres answered Karros' homer with a three in the bottom of
the inning. George Arias singled with one out and scored on Quilvio
Veras' triple to right-center. Eric Owens followed with a single to
score Veras. Owen stole second and scored on John Vander Wal's
double to give the Padres a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was laboring, allowed a leadoff singles to Arias,
Veras and Owens in the seventh as San Diego built a 6-2 lead.
Reggie Sanders then struck the most damaging blow, a three-run
homer to left for a 9-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
