<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5590 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-01 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS DISPOSE OF JUNK, BRING IN HEAVY EQUIPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It wasn't draft day at Sonics headquarters Wednesday
night. It was a house cleaning and, boy, don't those sorts of
things feel good?
</P>
<P>
   Out with all the junk, clutter and used parts.
</P>
<P>
   In with a solid piece of heavy equipment that can still get the
job done inside.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a too-young, too-unpolished NBA draft, the
Sonics sent grumbly forward Don MacLean, 3-point artist Dale Ellis,
eating guard Billy Owens and their teenage No. 13 pick Corey
Maggette to the Magic for power forward Horace Grant and two future
second-round selections.
</P>
<P>
   The best news about the deal is that popular Hersey Hawkins gets
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the deal was four players for one, and now there's a
little extra room on the Sonics bench, especially with Owens gone.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way that Wally Walker got rid of the evidence of
poor judgment when he traded Jim McIlvaine to the Nets last season,
Walker is off the hook now for Owens, too.
</P>
<P>
   Owens was supposed to be the answer for giving the Sonics more
scoring and ballhandling but he wound up being too out of shape and
too injured to contribute anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   And not only is Owens gone, but MacLean is, too, meaning the
last vestiges of McIlvaine have been eliminated from the Sonics
roster.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics need more muscle and scoring, does this mean Shawn
Kemp can come back now?
</P>
<P>
   Some things can't be undone, but maybe the specter of low- and
no-impact players such as Olden Polynice and Owens cast a spell on
Walker and Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the idea of repeating the disaster of 1999 proved too
alarming for the Sonics' president and head coach, who know they
must do better in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there wasn't any way Walker was going to risk having
All-Star guard Gary Payton doubt the Sonics' commitment to winning
right now.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Sonics' off-season has begun with a demonstration
that the club has some sense of urgency to make something happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do something drastic with our roster,'' Walker said
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   You wanted the Sonics to do something, and they did it.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics made a deal that turned some heads _ only this can't
be the end of the retooling.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief but nightmarish 1999 season in which the Sonics
failed to make the playoffs for the first time in a decade,
anything less than a high-visibility deal would have been
disastrous, or at least the wrong signal.
</P>
<P>
   What this NBA city needed was a sign.
</P>
<P>
   What this franchise needs is a kick-start toward putting a
tougher, more consistent team on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And, with an instant boost in height, rebounding and
credibility, the Sonics are also likely to be able to keep Detlef
Schrempf, too, who will be more likely to sign on for a last run
with a team that will win.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he was happy to be heading to a ``contender.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right, he used that word, because Grant said it is his
assessment that what happened to the Sonics this year was an
aberration.
</P>
<P>
   That statement demands that Baker reverts to All-Star form _ a
turnaround everyone is eagerly awaiting since Baker's almost
unfathomable disappearance last season.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said that in speaking with Westphal and Walker, he has
been told that the Sonics will sign Baker. That is why Grant was
not dismayed about moving cross-country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play power forward and I know with a guy like Vin Baker and
his offensive talent and with my defensive ability, I think we're
going to be a great combination,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   This draft-day trade could be the thing that starts to move the
Sonics back to within the realm of respectablility _ not that the
Sonics had any room to do anything less.
</P>
<P>
   Grant won three championship rings during his tenure in Chicago.
He then opted to head to Orlando, where the Magic went to the
Finals in 1995 and the expectation was to win.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question arises: What else will the Sonics do?
</P>
<P>
   Grant is only a one-time All-Star, and that was in 1994, when he
was running with Michael Jordan and the Bulls. He is about to turn
34. There was a question that his knee was bothering him, but Grant
said that diagnosis was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any problems,'' he said, adding that his seven
rebounds and 8.9 points per game this lockout-shortened season will
get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was because of the short season. I think if you
play 82 games and we're making the playoffs, you'll see my numbers
back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant even talked about wanting to go up against San Antonio's
Tim Duncan, who was nothing less than the Finals MVP. You have to
like that mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Grant, though, the Sonics need more help. A slasher. A
scorer. A backcourt guy who can handle the ball for Payton at
times. There are needs yet to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   But the upside of this cleaning-house day is there is room the
breathe now. Owens is gone. The Sonics did not have any intention
of keeping another 18-year-old draft pick on their roster.
</P>
<P>
   They are for the moment done with rookies and used parts and
their motto is something about ``getting back in the saddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ride 'em, Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
