<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS TURN TO ODOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks of acting like a dodger have turned Lamar Odom into a
Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief,'' said Odom, who can encourage officials from
his new team to exhale by showing up for today's getting-acquainted
press conference at the Convention Center. ``The situation got a
little chaotic.''
</P>
<P>
   This only proves the versatile 6-foot-10 ``small'' forward is
understated, if not underrated.
</P>
<P>
   After initiating a rip tide of ink for attempting to avoid the
NBA Draft, the shifty Rhode Island star was penciled in by the
Clippers with Wednesday night's fourth overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   For the Clippers, it represents another positive (not to mention
gutsy) move in what looks suspiciously like a perception-defying
draft roll. Two years after plucking power forward Maurice Taylor
at No. 14, and one year after landing 7-foot center Michael
Olowokandi, they select the player many hoop sharpies consider the
monster talent of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid can do it all,'' Clippers coach Chris Ford said. ``He
has star potential.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has stare potential. His recent itinerary of pre-draft
no-shows almost transformed the versatile Odom into urban myth. One
NBA scout who attended an impromptu audition Monday night in Rhode
Island joked that he was attending to see if Lamar Odom really
exists.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, in reality, is an impressive gathering of hoop molecules,
and the questions about his erratic behavior enabled his name to
exist past the first three picks on the draft board.
</P>
<P>
   If confined to basketball, the resume rocks.
</P>
<P>
   After posting national high school player of the year
credentials in 1997, the Odom odyssey rolled through an aborted
flirtation with UNLV, and an academic-hurdle-clearing redshirt year
for Rhode Island's first-year head coach Jim Harrick.
</P>
<P>
   In his first game for the Rams, Odom was a single dime away from
a posting a triple-double. His 19-point, 14-rebound and 9-assist
effort resulted in a victory over TCU. Four months later, his
buzzer-beating 3-pointer won the Atlantic 10 Conference tournament,
putting Rhode Island into the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Odom finished his only college season with averages of 17 points
and 9 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   After watching that near-triple-double vs. TCU, Jeff Weltman,
the Clips' director of player personnel, was socializing with a few
scouting peers and speculating on Odom and his anticipated impact
on '99 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy turned to me and said, `OK, who's going No. 2?'''
</P>
<P>
   After declaring for the draft and signing with an agent, Odom
decided to return to Rhode Island. That didn't fly, either, so he
slouched back into the draft as more suspect than prospect.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't slip too far.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers had expected UCLA's Baron Davis, their target for
their point-guard vacancy, to be chosen third by Charlotte. When
Hornets general manager Bob Bass sort of shocked the basketball
world by actually drafting Davis as he threatened to, the Clippers
zeroed in on Odom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think he's the best talent in the draft,'' Ford
said. ``A lot of players you can look at in the draft have question
marks.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Clippers are banking on the belief that ``Lamar'' and
``Odom'' aren't anagrams for ``Alarm'' and ``Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they aren't, the Clips also realize Odom will provide
plenty of angst for the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the court, he will create numerous problems for the
opposition,'' Ford said. ``What intrigues me is that he really can
pass the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor, the team's vice president of basketball
operations, decided Odom's vast basketball skills greatly
outweighed the attendant risk. After a phone chat with Odom on
Wednesday morning, the Clippers were sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels all this is behind him,'' Baylor said of Odom's
erratic off-court behavior. ``We think he's heading in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if he boards the proper flight, that direction will be
west.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) With their second-pick, the 31st overall, the Clippers
selected former Illinois State swingman Rico Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who grew up in Chicago and is considered a poor-man's Mark
Aguirre, was the Missouri Valley Conference's Player of the Year
two seasons ago. He didn't return for his senior year, and spent
the past season playing professionally in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a rare feel for the game,'' Weltman said. ``He has
heart and he has character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
