<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH NOT SERVING STERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern thinks he has just the right
medicine for what ails the NBA. He's prescribing a minimum draft
age of 20. He might as well be trying to get his constituents to
swallow castor oil.
</P>
<P>
   If Wednesday's draft proved anything, it's that the NBA front
offices aren't going to take their medicine unless it's shoved down
their throats.
</P>
<P>
   In Stern's world, Andre Miller and Jason Terry would have been
the first two point guards selected. The first forward picked would
have been Wally Szczerbiak. Evan Eschmeyer, Trajan Langdon, Todd
MacCulloch, Scott Padgett, James Posey, Tim James and Calvin Booth
would have rounded out the top-10. Seniors and seasoned players,
all.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a B.A. or B.S. degree to recognize that if you
want to discourage underclassmen from entering the draft, then save
your lottery picks for players who stayed in school long enough to
develop their minds and their games. The best way to produce
patience, after all, is to reward it.
</P>
<P>
   That said, what transpired at the MCI Center in Washington D.C.
was nothing to phone home about. Potential and athleticism were the
Harlem Globetrotters; poise and maturity, the Washington Generals;
the results, utterly predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The five first picks sported a combined six years of major
college experience. To a man their first professional contracts are
guaranteed to last longer than did their college commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago used the No. 1 overall pick on power forward Elton
Brand, a sophomore from Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver, picking next, selected Steve Francis, a point guard
who played two years of junior college ball and one year at
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte chose point guard Baron Davis, who graced Pauley
Pavilion for two years, which was like an eternity to him. Asked
after he donned a Charlotte cap about the knee injury that ended
his freshman season, Davis said with a perfectly straight face,
``It gave me a lot of patience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, selecting fourth, snatched forward Lamar Odom, who
put in one season at Rhode Island. Give Odom his due; he spent two
years in college (his first as a redshirt player) when he easily
could have jumped to the NBA straight out of high school, like
Jonathan Bender.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto took Bender, a spindly center out of Picayune (Miss.)
High, at No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The chronic youth movement was interrupted - but only for a
moment - by Minnesota, which selected Szczerbiak at No. 6. Miller
(eighth, to Cleveland) was the only other college senior to crack
the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The evening was neatly summed up by Seattle, which used the 13th
overall pick to take a sixth man, Duke freshman Corey Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the minimum draft age that Stern is pushing isn't
really about saving teen-age phenoms from themselves. It's about
saving his constituents from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Stern isn't the only one disturbed by the league's increasing
youthfulness. The talking heads watched the first round unfurl with
furrowed brows.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Georgetown coach John Thompson used his podium to pontificate
about staying in school, never mind this year's NCAA scoring
champion, Allen Iverson, was a Hoya for a whole two years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to lock the gate after the thoroughbreds have
been let out, the people bemoaning the impatience and impertinence
of today's NBA would do well to take a good look around.
</P>
<P>
   What they'd see is a lot of twentysomethings getting mighty
rich, mighty quick without the benefits of size or soft hands or a
sweet shot.
</P>
<P>
   The nouveau riche aren't just post-adolescent athletes, they're
day traders and Internet entrepreneurs and white-collar workers
with sizzling stock options. A lot of people evidently have found a
shortcut to the pot of gold their parents found, if at all, only
after years of sweat and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the stock market _ or a knee _ could buckle and just
like that the nouveau riche could be fingering fool's gold. That's
when poise and maturity will matter.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, the 19-year-old Clippers draftee, sounds like he already
has had to grow up faster than he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from the world I loved (in college) to one where I
didn't know who to trust,'' he said by way of explaining his
erratic behavior in the weeks leading to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Odom at one point fired his agent and tried to re-enroll at
Rhode Island. After that plan fell through, he then missed more
than one pre-draft workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation got a little chaotic,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, that's what No. 1 draft choices usually say on their way
out of Clipperland, not on their way in.
</P>
<P>
   Oh well, it's a whole new world. Someone should tell Stern today
the teens and twentysomethings own today. The rest of us are just
tenants. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
