<HEADLINE>
SONICS SWAP DRAFTEE, THREE VETS FOR MAGIC'S GRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Sonics promised an active offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they hope their busy work makes them better.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Wally Walker's idea of retooling a team that
missed the playoffs for the first time in nine seasons did not
include the 13th pick of Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Walker orchestrated a five-player trade that landed the
Sonics veteran power forward Horace Grant from the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics drafted Duke forward Corey Maggette, then immediately
shipped his rights to Orlando along with guard/forward Billy Owens,
guard Dale Ellis and forward Don MacLean.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the Sonics also received Orlando's second-round
draft picks in 2001 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had to do something pretty dramatic with our
roster,'' Walker said, who added, ``Keeping the 13th pick was Plan
E.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant, who turns 34 on Sunday, gives the Sonics a proven
rebounder and toughness inside. He is also a rugged post defender.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Grant can also get between 10 and 15 points when
left alone. Grant believes he will work well with Vin Baker, who
becomes a free agent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Grant and Baker are interchangeable, meaning they can play power
forward or center.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've heard from (Sonics coach) Paul Westphal, they
will sign Vin Baker back,'' said Grant, who has two years remaining
on his contract worth $6.5 million in 1999-2000 and $7 million the
following season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity to come to an established team and
play with guys like Gary Payton and Vin Baker. At his point in my
career, I'd like to go to a contender. ... The Sonics were just
lacking a couple of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant told Westphal he has ``four or five years left'' to play
defense and rebound with force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them playing together a lot,'' Westphal said of Baker
and Grant. ``I see Horace guarding the (other team's) best low post
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite averaging 8.9 points and seven rebounds last season with
the Magic, Grant is an experienced warrior. He was a big part of
the Chicago Bulls' first three-peat from 1991 to 1993. Grant again
played in the NBA Finals in 1995 _ his first season with the Magic.
He was unsure why Orlando wanted to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was just one of those things they couldn't pass
up,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics struck the deal with the Magic just after Toronto
selected 12th. Orlando wanted to make sure it could get Maggette,
and instructed the Sonics to make the pick.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he had other trades in the works if that deal fell
through. There were a number of deals for Hersey Hawkins on the
table, but Walker said he didn't feel comfortable moving the
veteran guard.
</P>
<P>
   Including Ellis in Wednesday's transaction was apparently tough
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big loss to lose Dale and we didn't do that lightly,''
Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   By trading Owens, the team admitted signing him last year to a
three-year contract was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Owens came into last season overweight and injuries mostly
rendered him ineffective. The Sonics never wanted the little-used
MacLean, and Ellis' salary made him expendable.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts of Ellis _ who turns 39 on Aug. 9 _ Owens, MacLean
and Maggette's expected earnings equaled Grant's $7.8 million
contract within the league requirement of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we ready to rebuild? No, we're looking to get back on the
saddle and go to war,'' said Billy McKinney, the Sonics' executive
vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   It was expected the Sonics would not retain the rights to their
13th pick. Even though they finished 25-25 and ninth in the Western
Conference, the Sonics are a veteran team with a goal of winning
now.
</P>
<P>
   They already have three young players _ Jelani McCoy, Rashard
Lewis and Vladimir Stepania _ whom they drafted last year. Adding
another prospect did not figure into the Sonics' immediate plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics still need a backup point guard to play alongside and
relieve Payton. They also want to acquire a player who can create
his own shot, and defend the shooting guard and small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's roster is still without a true center. The Sonics
hope to add another front-line player.
</P>
<P>
   Eligible NBA players officially became free agents Thursday.
While discussions can be held, no team can sign players until Aug.
1. The Sonics are expected to have $3.5 million under the salary
cap to pursue another impact player.
</P>
<P>
   They now have six players under contract, including Grant,
Payton, Lewis, Stepania, Hawkins, and James Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Their free agents are Baker, McCoy, Detlef Schrempf, Olden
Polynice, John Crotty, Aaron Williams and Drew Barry. The Sonics
anticipate re-signing Baker, McCoy and Schrempf. They are expected
to renounce rights to Polynice, Barry, Crotty and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have enough room under the cap to be a player in free
agency,'' Walker said. ``For now, we think we've satisfied one of
our needs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
