<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULES ALIGN FOR ZIMMERMAN, REUNION RESET FOR TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The schedule-makers must be big fans of Jordan
Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mariners' left-hander was sent down to Class AAA Tacoma
on June 18, he had a whole support group there to greet him the
next morning. The Class AA New Haven Ravens were playing in Akron,
Ohio, that weekend, and several of Zimmerman's former teammates met
him at the Mariners' Cleveland hotel for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The following weekend, the M's hosted the Texas Rangers, a
matchup Zimmerman had been anticipating for weeks. He would meet
his brother Jeff, a Texas reliever, for the first time since both
made the majors, and 30-40 family members and friends would be in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was playing for Tacoma, Jordan didn't have to
miss the reunion, because the Rainiers were also home. Further,
since the M's and Rangers played a day game Saturday, Jeff
Zimmerman even got to take in one of Jordan's games that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to dinner, and he told me, `Stay positive, you'll be
back,''' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   It was good advice, since Zimmerman returned to the M's Monday
when the club released Allen Watson. And the schedule had one more
treat: the M's and Rangers meet again in Texas Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully I'm still here for that,'' said Zimmerman, who has
learned the first rule of life in the majors _ it's easier to get
there than it is to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down there and thought about my job up here,''
Zimmerman said. ``I'm a lot more relaxed than what I was, and a lot
more confident. I have a better feel for everything _ knowing your
way around, the guys on the team. When you don't, you're going to
be nervous, and nervousness leads to loss of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's promotion of Damaso Marte from Tacoma (right-hander
Melvin Bunch was optioned back) gave the M's two left-handed
options in the bullpen, Marte for long relief and Zimmerman for
short.
</P>
<P>
   When the M's optioned Zimmerman, who had a 6.75 earned run
average in 10 games, they asked him to work on his slider. He
wasn't down long enough to change much, but barring a trade for a
veteran, he seems likely to stick around longer this time.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, 24, hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just depressed when I went down there,'' he said. ``It's
a good bunch of guys, but the only place to play is up here. When I
was down there, I was into it, but I just wanted to be up here so
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   HE'S BACK ... SORT OF: Shortstop Alex Rodriguez has had no
problem advancing on the bases since his return from knee surgery
nearly seven weeks ago. Going into Wednesday night's game,
Rodriguez had scored 50 runs in 44 games, an unheard-of ratio.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not stealing bases like he used to, with just six
swipes in 10 attempts. He feels all the way back as a hitter and a
fielder, but not as a baserunner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My speed is the only thing that's not there _ out of the box
and my first two or three steps from the base,'' Rodriguez said.
``I'm not the runner I was last year. You just don't want to run
into outs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez still couldn't believe the ball he dropped Tuesday,
when a would-be game-ending pop-up to short twisted in the wind and
fell for an error. The M's won the game, but Rodriguez was
smarting: ``That was the most frustrating play I've ever had in my
career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NO HANG-UP OVER SET-UP: Don't expect any complaints from Paul
Abbott about losing his starting role after one outing. The veteran
right-hander was a closer for Class AAA Las Vegas in 1996 and also
relieved extensively for Iowa in '95. The job, he said, is
essentially the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching's pitching,'' Abbott said. ``You've got to make your
pitches whether you're a starter or a reliever. Just because it's
the first or second run of the game doesn't mean the runs aren't as
important as they are in the seventh or eighth (inning). Basically
it's the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right there, so whatever's best for the team is what's
going to help us take over Texas. That's the most important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Abbott succeeds in the set-up relief role, he'll fill an
opening the Mariners have had since Mark Leiter went down in the
spring. The way manager Lou Piniella sees it, Abbott and Frankie
Rodriguez can be used as set-up relievers in tandem with Jose
Paniagua.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbott's really a good starter,'' Piniella said. ``I just need
him in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella prefers veterans in relief and young pitchers starting,
and when Gil Meche becomes the third rookie in the rotation next
week, that's roughly what the M's will have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get stronger as the game progresses, as opposed to
falling off,'' Piniella said.
</P>
</TEXT>
