<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND UNLOADS ON M'S PITCHING; FASSERO VICTIMIZED EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Mariners used four pitchers against the
Oakland Athletics Wednesday night, and each had a different
pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   The first was an old reliable, the next a returning rookie, the
third an old phenom and the last a rookie making his major league
debut.
</P>
<P>
   All had the same result: disaster. Oakland crushed Seattle 14-5
before 17,224 fans at the Coliseum. The Mariners, who were shut out
for seven innings by Oakland rookie Tim Hudson, fell to 5{ games
behind the division-leading Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer ignominy, Damaso Marte's effort stands out. The
left-hander, who became Seattle's 22nd pitcher this season, allowed
a homer on his first major league pitch, an opposite-field shot by
veteran John Jaha in the eighth inning. Three batters later, Marte
gave up another homer _ the first of Oakland rookie Ramon
Hernandez's career.
</P>
<P>
   The more important struggles Wednesday were Jeff Fassero's. The
old demons came back to visit the Mariners starter, and they got
there in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander, who seemed to have solved some problems after
three outings in the bullpen and one solid start, allowed four runs
in the first inning. Though he improved thereafter, the ugly
beginning and an uglier seventh inning doomed the M's to the loss.
</P>
<P>
   After Tony Phillips singled to start the game, Fassero (3-8) got
ahead of shortstop Miguel Tejada, 1-and-2. He threw a fastball low
and inside, and Tejada belted it over the left-field scoreboard for
his eighth homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 27th long ball Fassero has allowed this year _ nine
more than Anaheim's Tim Belcher, who is second in the American
League in that category. But it was not the only way Fassero
faltered in the first.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, the A's loaded the bases on two singles and a
hit-by-pitch. Then Fassero issued four straight balls to Hernandez,
walking in the third run. Another scored on a sacrifice fly by Ryan
Christenson before Jorge Velandia's force out ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Christenson brought in the Athletics' fifth run two innings
later. After consecutive singles by Jason Giambi and Hernandez, the
light-hitting center fielder singled up the middle, just under the
glove of diving second baseman David Bell, bringing Giambi home.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last baserunner Fassero allowed until the seventh _
when everything unraveled for the Mariners. They made three errors
in the inning, more than they'd made in any game this season, and
three pitchers allowed six runs on five hits.
</P>
<P>
   Tejada led off with a sharp bouncer just inside the third base
line. John Mabry got a glove on it, but it caromed into the vast
Coliseum foul territory, and Tejada raced to second on what was
ruled a two-base error.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines followed with a run-scoring double to the gap in
left-center, making it 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   After a walk to Jaha, Fassero was replaced by Jordan Zimmerman,
back with the M's after a 10-day stay at Class AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Olmedo Saenz greeted him with a smash down the left-field line _
Mabry had no shot this time _ to bring home another run, and an
error by Bell made it 8-0 Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   More trouble followed when Ken Cloude entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez crushed Cloude's first pitch to the same spot as
Raines' double, and this one gave the A's a 9-0 lead. The A's were
up 10-0 after Christenson made the first out of the inning, an RBI
sacrifice fly, and they added their final run on an infield single
by Tejada, who advanced to second when Bell threw wildly to first.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson (3-1) hardly needed the support. The A's right-hander,
who started the year in Class AA, came into the game with a 3.60
earned-run average, despite allowing 28 hits and 11 walks in 25
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Through five innings, the M's had seven hits and three walks _
but no runs, because they had left nine runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   They finally rallied when the game was out of hand in the
eighth, getting back-to-back doubles from Mabry and pinch-hitter
Charles Gipson, then reaching on back-to-back Oakland errors,
leading to four runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
