<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     07-01 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-UNEDITED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ROUTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- At least the Angels are saving some money on their
Edison Field electric bill.
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels lose, particularly when they lose big, the two
60-inch screen televisions and the stereo system in the clubhouse
are turned off.
</P>
<P>
   They've been turned off for the past three nights, including
Wednesday night after the Texas Rangers embarrassed the Angels with
an 18-4 thrashing, completing a three-game sweep and dropping the
Angels 9 1/2 games back in the A.L. West.
</P>
<P>
   While they're at it, they might as well turn off the stadium
lights. That way, (ital) both (end ital) teams would flail
helplessly at the plate. It would have saved the 23,450 in
attendance Wednesday night the chore of watching the debacle.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, it's just the Angels who are helpless at the plate.
Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Between Darin Erstad's two-out walk in the third inning Tuesday
night and Matt Walbeck's one-out walk in the third inning
Wednesday, Rangers pitchers retired 26 Angel batters in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's leadoff single in the fourth snapped a string of nine
innings without a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Before scoring two runs in the sixth inning Wednesday, the
Angels had scored one run in their previous 30 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the three games, the Rangers outscored the Angels, 32-5, and
have now outscored the Angels 57-8 in winning the last six games at
Edison Field, including the three-game sweep last September.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels pitchers, who have performed well most of the season,
finally fell to the level of the offense Wednesday, giving up the
most runs by an Angels staff in nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   Things are so bad for the Angels it's making Mo Vaughn sick.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had to leave the game after four innings with flu-like
symptoms. He went 0-for-8 with five strikeouts in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins, peppered with questions after the
game much like his pitchers were peppered by the Rangers hitters,
finally lost his patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's three games! he said. ``Three games ago we were in the
race. We got our butts kicked for the last three games. That
doesn't mean anything. We win 10 in a row and all of a sudden,
we're back in it. Every time something goes bad the season's over.
I'm tired of it. We have to regroup and take (today) off. Get our
bullpen some rest and hopefully the starters are OK. Let's move on.
End of story.
</P>
<P>
   Things aren't necessarily OK with the starters. Ken Hill, who
was pitching for the first time after elbow problems forced him out
of his last start June 23, gave up eight runs on eight hits in 3
1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   After the game Hill said his sore right elbow might keep him out
of his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to get better unless I rest, he said. ``It's
not a matter of if I want to rest. I need the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't stop battering the Angels pitchers after Hill
left. Nearly every time a Rangers hitter made contact, the impact
sounded like a cannon shot. They finished with 20 hits and their 18
runs was a season-high and the most against the Angels in nearly
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile had four hits, tying a career-best, and the Rangers
had at least one baserunner in 25 of their 27 innings in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers pitchers have enjoyed the Angels' futility the past few
days. Mike Morgan entered Monday's game with an ERA over five, but
threw a complete-game and came within one out of his first shutout
in six years.
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett allowed only one hit in seven shutout innings on
Tuesday despite a 7.20 ERA entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, it was Ryan Glynn's turn. Glynn, 1-2 with a 7.46 ERA
entering the game, didn't allow a hit until the fourth and didn't
allow any runs until Reggie Williams' RBI triple and Garret
Anderson's RBI single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Collins tried to shake things up before the game, putting Randy
Velarde in the cleanup spot. Seemed like a good idea, considering
the batters hitting cleanup for the Angels had driven in six runs
total during the month of June. And Velarde, hitting .296 going in,
was one Angel that had been hitting lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my most consistent hitter and put him in the middle of
the lineup, Collins explained.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde said he had never hit cleanup in his life before
Wednesday, including little league, and didn't particularly like
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassment, really, he said before the Angels were
embarrassed on the field. ``It speaks for how our team is doing.
It's an embarrassment. ... I take it as an embarrassment they need
to rely on me. I don't belong up there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
