<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALING OFF TOP OF THE DECK 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ The Toronto Raptors sent out a strong message
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night that they are tired of waiting. The Indiana Pacers
sent out an equally strong one that they are also tired of waiting.
Each team had what the other one wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, coming off their disappointing _ some would say
humiliating _ playoff loss to the Knicks, started their rebuilding
program by dealing longtime strongman Antonio Davis to the Raptors
for high-schooler Jonathan Bender, a 6-foot-11-inch small forward
who was chosen with the No. 5 pick in Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's NBA draft
and had several teams, including the Celtics, drooling about his
upside. He has even drawn comparisons to Kevin Garnett. Asked if he
had made any serious inquiries about Bender, Celtics coach Rick
Pitino said, ``Not really. No.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's deal won't be made official until
Aug. 1 for salary cap reasons, the Davis trade was a sign from the
Pacers that what they have isn't enough in a league that is leaning
more and more toward athleticism. They found that out in their
stunning loss to the Knicks. Antonio Davis, who makes $4.2 million,
became expendable when Dale Davis decided not to exercise an out
clause in his already substantial contract.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Davis was soon joined by Serbian center Aleksandar
Radojevic, taken by Toronto with the 12th pick. The Raptors still
don't have the point guard they want, but still may be able to do
something with their cap space, although Davis eats away at some of
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to send a message to our veteran players that we
want to win,'' said Toronto coach Butch Carter.
</P>
<P>
   More interesting is the Pacers' decision not to stand pat and
see their loss to the Knicks as an aberration. President Donnie
Walsh has long been seeking more athletic players, particularly at
small forward, which is where most NBA scouts say Bender will
eventually play.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have now added first-round high school players each
of the last two years, having taken Al Harrington last season.
Bender's stock had risen steadily as draft time approached and the
Lakers were trying to trade up to No. 2 to get him.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana-Toronto deal was the only one that impacted the top
half of the draft. Another biggie game later: the Magic sent Horace
Grant to Seattle for the rights to Duke's Corey Maggette, taken
13th, along with Billy Owens, Dale Ellis, and Don MacLean. Orlando
is rebuilding under new coach Doc Rivers and the Sonics need
toughness, inside players, and rebounders, a lot of which Grant
provides. The others were added largely for salary cap reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics, who didn't have a choice until No. 55, selected
Texas guard Kris Clack, whom the team had projected as a late
first-rounder. Kentucky guard Wayne Turner of Boston will be
invited to participate on the team's summer league clubs.
Meanwhile, Paul Pierce was working out at the club's facility
during the draft, under the eye of Pitino, who was on the
treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino also said there had not been any ``serious'' offers for
Ron Mercer, nor had the team made any. ``There's nothing in the
works right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls, meanwhile, were sitting on No. 1 and kept
everyone guessing to the end, finally settling on Duke's Elton
Brand. Ever-secretive general manager Jerry Krause said the
decision was a tough one, but added Brand has long arms and big
hands, a plus in any system.
</P>
<P>
   Brand was as much of a consensus No. 1 as possible in this
chaotic draft, but said, ``I didn't have the slightest idea,'' when
asked if he thought he'd be taken by the Bulls. He will play power
forward and will be joined along the front line by St. John's Ron
Artest, who was taken 16th. The Bulls added Lari Ketner of UMass in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest shocker in the first round was Cleveland's selection
of Duke's Trajan Langdon at No. 11. The Cavs had taken Andre Miller
at No. 8, the pick they got from Boston in the Vitaly
Potapenko-Andrew DeClercq trade. Langdon was not thought to be a
lottery pick _ he went ahead of more heralded college teammates
William Avery and Maggette _ and wasn't even present at the MCI
Center, where the top draftees were assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Maggette's selection by Seattle marked the first time since the
lottery was instituted in 1985 that one school had three lottery
picks. In addition, Avery went 14th to the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Lamar Odom, thought by many to be the most talented
player in the draft, ended rather quickly when he went fourth to
the Clippers. Odom had been rated No. 1 by many scouts, but saw his
stock drop in the last two weeks when he missed several workouts,
saw his agent resign, then toyed briefly with the idea of trying to
return to the University of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   This was a draft heavy in point guards and the top five were all
gone by the 14th pick. Steve Francis went immediately after Brand
to Vancouver and didn't look all that thrilled about it. The
Grizzlies rebuffed countless offers for the pick, and may
eventually deal Francis for the veteran power forward they feel
they need. Antonio Davis would have fit in nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis of UCLA (No. 3 to Charlotte), Miller, Jason Terry
(No. 10 to Atlanta), and Avery were scooped up quickly. Radojevic
was the first center followed by another foreigner, Frederic Weis
of France, who went to the Knicks at No. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
