</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASDIN LACKS PERFECT ENDING 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WASDIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ From Buzzards Bay to the Back Bay, the unmistakable
sound of flapping wings could be heard when John Wasdin emerged
from Boston's bullpen and swooped down on what appeared to be yet
another easy kill. With the Red Sox trailing, 9-8, Wasdin knew all
he needed was to put a stiff-arm on the Bedeviling Rays of Tampa
Bay, get some run support from his hot-hitting teammates, and _
voila _ he'd vulture his way to another win, No. 8 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   But not Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays shot down Wasdin, the bird of prey of Boston's
bullpen, by pinning him with his first loss of the season when they
scored two runs in the 10th to break a 9-9 tie and staved off a
last-gasp comeback by the Red Sox to score an 11-10 victory before
a Fenway Park crowd of 27,961.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right there, the opportunity was there for another
one,'' said Wasdin, whose perfect 7-0 record suffered its first
blemish as he went one-plus inning, allowing two runs on one hit
and a walk, a costly walk at that. ``But it's not going to happen
all year long. It's something to go undefeated or to be that lucky,
but, yeah, it came to an end and now there's a good chance to start
it all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin felt culpable for the collapse when he issued a leadoff
walk in the 10th to Tampa Bay right fielder Bubba Trammell. It
wound up haunting him when the next batter, Randy Winn, laid down a
bunt that was pounced on by third baseman Lou Merloni.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni scooped up the ball, threw across his body to second,
where Nomar Garciaparra fielded the throw for an apparent out.
However, second base umpire Lazaro Diaz declared Trammell safe when
he ruled Merloni's throw had drawn Garciaparra off the bag. Error
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was out, but I don't know, of course,'' Wasdin
said.
</P>
<P>
   The play wound up costing the Sox when Miguel Cairo rapped a
fake-bunt single up the middle that scored Trammell to make it
10-9. But Wasdin felt none of it would have occurred had he not
walked Trammell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially on a leadoff walk to start off an inning when
you're tied and you want to go up there and put up a quick
inning,'' lamented Wasdin, who wound up handing it over to Mark
Guthrie after Cairo's single. ``But he had a good at-bat. I threw
him some really good curveballs and, usually, that's what my pitch
is. But I walked him and they bunted over and all of a sudden boom,
boom, boom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were staring at an 11-9 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin, amazingly, almost got off the hook when the Sox pushed
across a run in the bottom of the inning and threatened to score
more when Garciaparra came to the plate with two out and runners on
second and third. But Garciaparra wound up grounding to third to
end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome, they never quit from the get-go,'' Wasdin said
of his teammates. ``We put up a five-run inning tonight (to tie it
in the fourth) and we battled tonight. We battled hard. It just
seemed that we'd get there and they'd get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But, coming out of the bullpen, Wasdin had to have visions of
snatching another win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in the making, but, again, I don't think there's anyone
that lucky,'' he said. ``It was bound to happen, and it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
