<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG NIGHT FOR DODGERS, BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ This is Dodgers baseball? Yuck!
</P>
<P>
   The two games the Dodgers won last weekend in San Francisco to
harbor hope were an aberration because they turned around and
continued to do what they've done all season _ lose.
</P>
<P>
   And a dubious month ends in a disastrous, deliciously ironic
way.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown lost again to the San Diego Padres, getting pounded
for nine earned runs on 11 hits in a 11-2 loss Wednesday night at
Qualcomm Stadium, concluding the Dodgers' worst month of baseball
in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second-most earned runs Brown has allowed in his
career. He gave up 10 in 31/3 innings at Toronto on April 19, 1994.
Brown's ERA went from an NL-leading 2.92 to 3.43 and he fell to
9-5.
</P>
<P>
   The insult added to the Dodgers' injury is that the Padres are
in the midst of their best run in history. San Diego won its
club-record 12th straight game. The Padres have beaten the Dodgers
six straight times and have won seven of eight against Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to tell you,'' Dodgers center fielder Devon
White said. ``We got our (butts) kicked with one of our better
pitchers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Dodgers went 7-20 in June 1979 have they had a
month like the one that ended a few hours ago. The Dodgers' third
straight loss left them 8-17 for the month and wallowing in last
place.
</P>
<P>
   Even the one supposed given _ Brown _ couldn't accomplish
anything and didn't record an out in the seventh, though he did
give up four runs in the inning. He was pulled after Reggie Sanders
hit a three-run homer to give the Padres a 9-2 lead. It was the
first of two Sanders home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Brown was yanked after 61/3 innings and three runs in
a loss to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Brown,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``I talked to him in the fifth and he said he just made a couple of
bad pitches (in the Padres' three-run fifth). I was hoping he could
keep us in there until the seventh. I hate to leave my ace in there
to give up nine runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In a nearly vacant clubhouse after the game, Brown wasn't around
to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's in the cards, so all we can do is ride it
out and not cause us to put our heads down,'' White said. ``Things
like (Brown's outing) happen. I don't care how good you are. The
aces get their butts whipped sometimes. That happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Brown pitched here he was greeted with music that
pointed toward the fact he left San Diego for seven years and $105
million of security. This time he was only booed (and cheered when
he was pulled from the game) as the Padres shellacked him to end a
disastrous 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Dodgers won only six games in August 1995 and began
last season 8-15 in April, the .320 winning percentage this June is
the lowest since a .259 winning percentage in June 1979.
</P>
<P>
   It brings up the question of whether it's been the toughest
month of Johnson's career. ``It's been a tough (begin
ital)three(end ital) months for me because I really want to be able
to make things easier on them and I really haven't been able to do
anything, and that makes it tough on me,'' he said. ``It's more
frustrating for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the perception sometimes is complacency. There's no
complacency on this ballclub. We're good enough defensively and we
should be good enough offensively. We haven't found the right key,
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the Dodgers (34-41) haven't found anything. They
continue to reside in last place in the NL West, the pitching
hasn't performed to expectations and the offense relies too heavily
on the home run.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Boehringer (5-1) allowed two runs in five innings for the
win. Along with his two homers, Sanders drove in five runs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
