<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5608 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBADRAFT-ODOM-BOS     07-01 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY 4TH: ODOM CHOSEN BY CLIPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-ODOM-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ University of Rhode Island forward Lamar Odom
wondered aloud on Monday if his recent indecision about staying in
school or entering the NBA would hurt his stock in
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's draft at the MCI Center. Early on, it appeared
it had. The Chicago Bulls, which worked out Odom as late as Tuesday
evening, chose Duke's Elton Brand, and Vancouver, the first team to
work out Odom, selected Steve Francis of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   When Charlotte chose UCLA guard Baron Davis with the third pick,
many at the MCI Center wondered how far Odom, who was once
projected as the No. 1 pick, would fall.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Los Angeles Clippers ended the speculation when they
selected Odom with the fourth pick. The Clippers were one of four
teams that worked out Odom at URI on Monday, and apparently they
liked what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kind of let me know if I was around they would pick me
up,'' said Odom, who became the ninth lottery pick for the
Clippers. He will try to lead the team to a consistent level,
something others _ including Danny Manning and Danny Ferry _ could
not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you have to start somewhere. Hopefully it will start with
me,'' said Odom. ``They have a lot of talent on the team. Hopefully
I can come in and add something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling and blinking his eyes to hold back tears, Odom said
being selected by the Clippers makes up for a most tumultuous
postseason. He committed to the NBA draft, signed with an agent,
then parted ways with his agent and expressed interest in returning
to school. He also skipped a workout with the Chicago Bulls and
failed to show up at the pre-draft camp.
</P>
<P>
   Odom's waverings _ and failure to show up for workouts _ soured
many NBA officials. URI held a workout Monday that was attended by
four NBA teams, but several teams previously interested in Odom
opted not to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Some interest still remained. Odom worked out in Miami Tuesday
morning after the Heat attended Monday's workout. After flying to
Washington Tuesday afternoon, Odom flew to Chicago for a workout
Tuesday night. In Chicago, Odom was quoted as saying he had a gut
feeling he would be selected by the Bulls as the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who grew up playing with Brand in the New York City area,
said he wasn't discouraged when he wasn't chosen by the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been 50th,'' he said. ``This is the NBA. It
really didn't matter. I might have been a little disappointed (if
he slipped further) but by the next morning, I would have been all
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Bulls picked (Michael) Jordan, they weren't the best
team in the NBA, either. I think you have to make the most of the
situation, play hard, be devoted to your team and the coach, and
everything will work out fine. They have a great new arena and I'm
going to be living in the city of Los Angeles playing basketball.
If you ask for more than that you are being greedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom did not shoot well at his Monday workout, but Clippers
officials were impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good prospect,'' said Clippers scout Jim Mitchell. ``He
has size, speed, and quickness. As for his position, we're at a
point where we could play him in a number of places.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom said he will put the waverings and other issues he endured
at the amateur level behind him. However, he did blame himself for
any ill perceptions he may have prompted among NBA officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some degree, some decisions I had to make may not have been
the best decisions I could have made at the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would have done differently, Odom said, ``Some of
the decisions I made would have been different so that my ride
would have been a little smoother. But you make mistakes and I know
that. I just want to put it behind me and play in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   At URI, the 6-foot-10-inch Odom played every position but
center, and was named Atlantic 10 Conference Rookie of the Year,
averaging 17.6 points, 9.4 rebounds, and 3.8 assists per game. It
was his only year of college ball.
</P>
<P>
   His skills are best suited for the perimeter, but Odom says he
does not have a preference. He added, however, that he hoped to
build his strength to improve his post game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play in the post and I think if I can play in the
post, I can create some mismatches for other teams because of how
well I handle the ball. But it doesn't matter if I play the four,
the five, the six, seven, eight, or the coach's pet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
