<HEADER>
A5617 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     07-01 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH COLLECTS $36 MILLION FOR CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and ROBERT B. GUNNISON  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Buoyed by a record $36.3 million in
contributions to his presidential campaign, Republican George W.
Bush began showing off his conservative credentials Wednesday as he
declared his opposition to abortion and gay marriage.
<P>
   On the second day of his trip to California, Bush appeared
amazed at the amount he has raised so far _ nearly 10 times as much
as his closest Republican rival and twice as much as Vice President
Al Gore, the Democratic front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled by the response,'' said. ``I am amazed at the
outpouring of support.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he will announce in July whether he will accept matching
federal funds for his campaign _ a move that would limit his
contributions. But he hinted that his windfall would mean he would
decline them, saying ``it makes the decision easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor added to his bounty last night in San
Francisco with a money-raising dinner. He addressed an overflow
crowd of 1,100 at a $1,000-a-plate dinner at the St. Francis Hotel.
After his Silicon Valley fund-raiser Thursday morning, Bush's Bay
Area take from the two events is expected to hit $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending were Charles Schwab, the stock market
heavyweight; Don Fischer, chairman of the Gap clothing company; and
Halsey Minor, head of the internet firm Cnet and a major financial
supporter of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the latest contributions figures were announced, the
wealth of the Bush campaign gave it the flavor of a full-bore
presidential trip, although the California primary is still eight
months away.
</P>
<P>
   And he provided the scent of victory for California Republicans
shell-shocked by two Democratic presidential victories in
California since 1992 and the crushing defeat of Dan Lungren last
year in the race for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous feeling, an energy even among independents
and Democrats,'' said Secretary of State Bill Jones, the state's
highest-ranking Republican. ``It's such a tremendous difference
between this year and last.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his schedule is packed with fund-raising opportunities
at every traditional mealtime, Bush began to define his positions
on a number of issues critical to California voters at press
conferences in Los Angeles and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   About abortion, Bush said, ``I've been a pro-life governor since
I got elected. I believe the goal of America ought to be to (have)
every unborn child welcome in life and protected by law. That's an
ideal world, and we don't live in an ideal world.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would rule out a running mate who supported abortion
rights, Bush said, ``I take nobody off the table.''`
</P>
<P>
   About gay marriage _ a ballot measure to ban same-sex marriages
is on the state's March 2000 ballot _ Bush said, ``I don't believe
in gay marriage,'' but he added, ``I'm not going to support any
initiative in any state, but I believe marriage is between a man
and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said pleasant words about former California Gov. Pete
Wilson, even though he has previously disparaged two of Wilson's
favored ballot initiatives, Propositions 187 and 209.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should distance myself from Gov. Wilson,''
Bush said Wednesday. ``He's a friend. I hope he gets me elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also took a page from Wilson's playbook, stating his
opposition to oil drilling off the California coast _ a position
that won Wilson favor among environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush dismissed the idea that a Republican can antagonize
voters by embracing Wilson's opposition to government benefits for
illegal immigrants and affirmative action. ``Maybe the state is not
as liberal as you think,'' Bush told reporters. ``This is a state
that Ronald Reagan built a great political machine in.''
</P>
<P>
   If Wilson himself is not involved in the Bush campaign yet, many
of his closest aides and associates already are. His former chief
of staff, Bob White, sat in the front row at the Sacramento
luncheon. In the audience were many former Wilson aides and
lobbyists with close ties to the former governor.
</P>
<P>
   Between fund-raising events, Bush managed a few traditional
public campaign stops _ at a teachers' symposium in Los Angeles and
with youngsters at a football camp in Sacramento, where he shared
the stage with Oakland Raiders receiver Tim Brown, also a Texan.
</P>
<P>
   In the 102-degree heat, Bush tossed a few wobbly football passes
and bantered with young boys before heading for San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's skillful campaign techniques ``send a shiver down the
spines of a lot of Democrats,'' said political analyst and former
White House spokeswoman Dee Dee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Myers pronounced Bush's campaign already ``at the White House
level,'' employing all ``the feeling'' _ rope lines, security men
with special lapel pins, press corraling _ of a presidential
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has even made a play for Clinton's core supporters in
Hollywood, meeting in the Bel Air home of Warner CEO Terry Semple
with such Democratic heavy hitters as actor Warren Beatty and
Paramount executive Sherry Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to appeal to people from all parts of society, to
call on all of us to do our part to usher in the responsibility
era,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shows an easy, relaxed manner much of the time, masking his
relative inexperience as a candidate for national office.
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked by a reporter what he is doing to ensure that
he is ready for the job, Bush said: ``I'm going to listen and
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I happen to mispronounce the name of a country
doesn't mean that I don't understand how to lead,'' he said. Bush
recently called Kosovars ``Kosovarians'' and Greeks ``Grecians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters,'' Bush said, ``is do I know how to set clear
goals? Do I know how to lead? Do I shoot straight? And that's all I
know to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will travel to Silicon Valley Thursday, where he is
expected to raise $300,000 at a breakfast for technology
supporters. He then travels to Fresno for a fund-raising lunch
expected to raise $150,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
