<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASPAROV-CHESS-SFCHRO     07-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASPAROV-CHESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE WORLD'S A PAWN FOR KASPAROV  &HT;     By STEVE RUBENSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The entire world, which may not know what it's doing, voted to
move its queen's knight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was sensible decision, but it may not be enough against the
world's opponent, chess champion Garry Kasparov.
</P>
<P>
   For the next several months, Kasparov is playing perhaps the
world's most unusual chess match _ a game via the Internet against
every player on Earth who wants to play. Each side gets one day to
make its next move and, when it is the world's turn to play, the
move chosen by the most players is the one made against the champ.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2 million computer users have logged onto the site
(www.zone.com/kasparov) to view the match, and about 10,000 players
are actually casting votes for the moves, a match spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been five moves on each side. Wednesday, the
world moved its queen's knight to the c6 square and hoped for the
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going OK so far,'' said Chronicle chess editor George
Koltanowski. ``The world is holding its own. For how much longer,
it's hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The world will probably lose, Koltanowski said, because average
players play like average players _ alone or together _ while
Kasparov plays like Kasparov.
</P>
<P>
   The match began last week when the 35-year-old world champion,
who is playing the white pieces, advanced his king's pawn two
squares forward. The world pondered, then voted to advance its
queen's bishop pawn two squares, an opening known as the Sicilian
Defense. (The moves so far: 1 e4 c5; 2 Nf3 d6; 3 Bb5+ Bd7; 4 Bxd7+
Qxd7; 5 c4 Nc6).
</P>
<P>
   The match is being sponsored by Kasparov, an Internet gaming
site and a bank that provides a steady stream of online ads for its
credit card while players are trying to think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make the right move,'' say the ads, ``and receive a free chess
set with your card.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasparov, who has soundly beaten his mortal foes, suffered his
most crushing loss two years ago in a six-game match against IBM
supercomputer Deep Blue and is clearly still smarting from the
defeat. In an online chat with players before the current match,
the champ grumbled that IBM has still refused to publish
information about the computer's workings, so that the scientific
value of the match was zero.
</P>
<P>
   As to his chances in the current match, Kasparov, not known for
his modesty, said there was a ``chance I could lose, but it's
highly unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the world is having its problems with sportsmanship,
too. In the chat rooms, players are griping about how lousy the
average Internet player is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget to take into account that the vast majority of
chess players are beginners,'' wrote a player calling himself
Timber Wolf. ``Seems expected that eventually the wrong move will
be voted, after which Kasparov will clean house. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the world's players debated their choice of move via
chat room messages, politely at times. About 72 percent favored the
Nc6 move that was selected, while 11 percent wanted to move the
other knight, 4 percent wanted to advance the king's pawn and 3
percent wanted to try a bold, risky assault with the queen.
</P>
<P>
   Koltanowski, the 95-year-old grandmaster whose daily column has
appeared in The Chronicle since 1947, called the online match a
``gimmick, but a good gimmick.'' He himself tried a similar stunt
against Chronicle readers in the 1940s _ tallying moves by
postcards instead of computers _ and polished off the competition
with no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does Kasparov have to be afraid of?'' he said. ``If you
have 2 million opponents and most of them play like schmoes, then
it's not really so tough, is it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
