<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5716 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-PLUS-CORRECTI     07-01 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PLUS-CORRECTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLUS IS NOT A MINUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charity Shields, a young single mother, was shopping in a Kansas
City store when she was mistaken for another person _ a model. At
size 18, Shields was a bit taken aback, but the idea so intrigued
her that she went searching for a modeling agency.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later she is working regularly for such clients as
Wal-Mart, Lane Bryant Stores and the Jones Store in addition to
holding down a job as a workers' compensation claims adjuster and
caring for her 5-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Shields is among a growing number of models caught up in the
explosive energy of a profession that used to stigmatize large
women.
</P>
<P>
   Mauria Stonestreet, size 14 and a special education teacher in
Lawrence, decided to investigate modeling at the urging of her
brother, Los Angeles actor Eric Stonestreet. She has been so
successful in the Kansas City area that in September she will move
to Chicago to pursue a full-time career.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Smith answered a classified ad for a plus-size model
two years ago. Now Julie Wolf, owner of the Agency, a Kansas City
modeling representative, says, ``I wish I could clone her.'' And
Kim Hoffman, owner of Hoffman Models in Overland Park, says she is
actively scouting for plus-size talent, encouraging people at
weight-loss centers to watch for potential models.
</P>
<P>
   It has not always been so. Christine Alt, a celebrity plus-size
model and frequent spokeswoman, says when she started as a model in
1981, ``there was no such thing as a plus size.''
</P>
<P>
   When she gained weight and moved into large sizes in 1986, there
were only ``two or three agencies and a handful of models.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are hundreds out there, instead of just a hundred,''
says Alt who appears on the July//August cover of BBW (Big
Beautiful Woman) magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The plus-size model field probably has quadrupled in most major
cities in recent years, says Catherine Lippincott, director of
public relations for Lane Bryant, the Limited's retail chain that
specializes in large sizes. ``Now you can find just any look you
need,'' in any size, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Plus-size images are gaining prominence. Emme, the stylish blond
model, appears on the cable channel E's ``Fashion Emergency.'' The
high visibility of such celebrities as ABC Television's Star Jones,
Rosie O'Donnell, Cybill Shepherd and Kate Winslet is providing
positive ego reinforcement for many women.
</P>
<P>
   Mode magazine, a publication devoted to large women is in its
third year of publication and added Girl for teens earlier this
year. BBW magazine relaunched on the West Coast earlier this
summer. Anjellika recently was the first plus-size model voted to
an international models' association hall of fame, notes Gary
Dakin, a plus-size model booker for the Ford Agency in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The field of large-size modeling has grown ``beyond my own
dreams,'' says Susan Georget, the founder and director of
Willhelmina Models' Plus Size division, which is now getting
requests from major European fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, credit in part goes to the apparel industry. Designers
and manufacturers have suddenly awakened to a massive untapped
market of fashion-conscious consumers who until recently had
limited choices beyond pull-on pants and tunics. More and more name
designers including Emanuel Ungaro, Gianfranco Ferre, Givenchy and
Giorgio Armani have added plus-size collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a growth area for us,'' says Tina Hodak, the
St. Louis-based fashion director for Kansas City's Jones Store Co.
The store will debut Lauren by Ralph Lauren in large sizes this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Alt says the clothing industry boom is also a result of
consumers raising their voices. ``The reason it happened is because
of the women,'' she said. ``They wrote letters. They complained.
They let them know they were sick of stretch green polyester pants.
They were heard.''
</P>
<P>
   And manufacturers are responding in a big way. Lane Bryant has
launched a major promotional effort to address a young, hip
customer. The company contracted with Camryn Manheim of
television's ``The Practice'' to be a celebrity model and broadcast
a New York fashion show on the Web last week.
</P>
<P>
   Today's fashion essentials such Capri pants, drawstring pants
and skirts, cargo pockets and camisole sweater sets are now
flooding stores in all sizes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, plus-size models did not always enjoy the same
glamorous image as other models. They didn't get paid as much,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Alt says that in her early days, some photographers simply
refused to shoot plus-size models. And smaller models made a point
to ignore them on jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has changed dramatically now and ``the industry is
one big happy family,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the stigma has mostly disappeared. Rates have almost
closed ranks, says Ford's Dakin, and discrepancies in treatment
have dropped if not totally disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica La Voie, a young Kansas City area woman, is working
quite happily as a size 14 with New York's Wilhelmina Agency. But
she recalls her move there two years ago, when no budget was
provided to help her find housing, unlike with other models. She
found herself living in a rodent-infested hotel for a time.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ford agency, Dakin says all the models, regardless of
size, are ``handled with kid gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, requirements for plus-size models are comparable to
those of other models. They must be at least 5 feet 9 inches tall
and well-proportioned. (Most work out to stay toned.)
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, larger sizes such as 16 and 18 seem to be most
in demand. ``Julie encouraged me to gain weight,'' says Elizabeth
Smith of her agent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, size 14 may be the most prevalent, but Lane
Bryant's Lippincott says the company uses most sizes in their
shows, and 14 to 16 for shoots because those are the sample sizes.
Mode tends to use models size 12, 14 and 16, says Nancy LeWinter,
publication director.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond size, all models should have ``an inviting personality,''
as Kim Hoffman calls it, or ``a certain energy,'' says LeWinter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 0946EDT &QL; 
