<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5726 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX     07-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bush manufactures a fight over sex ed
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the run-up to his presidency _ for he seems to regard his
election in 2000 as a gimme _ George W. Bush has promised to spend
as much of the federal budget to promote sexual abstinence as is
spent promoting contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   As sops to the religious and cultural right go, this one is
fairly benign, but even so Bush is making up a fight where none
need exist. He is buying the conservative charge that sex education
is ``Do it!'' education.
</P>
<P>
   It is not. Sex education courses routinely emphasize the obvious
fact that abstinence is the only sure-fire pregnancy prevention,
and an independent study presented to the conservative American
Enterprise Institute a few years ago confirmed that sex education
does not excite sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says, too, that he wants to fund a study to determine the
effectiveness of abstinence education, but we already know the
answer. Repeated studies have shown that the most effective
education combines abstinence and contraceptive information with
tutoring on how to resist social pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still being briefed on issues, trying to crank what he
knows up to speed with what he says, and here the lag is apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Teen pregnancies have declined nearly 20 percent in the '90s,
but the rate is still nearly double the rate of European teens, who
are at least as sexually active as American teens _ evidence that
Europe's easy openness about sexuality pays off in a sharply lower
rate of unwanted pregnancies. We muddle along with an incoherent
combination of smirky sexual titillation and prissy ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans beat ourselves up uniquely over sex, not least
because we don't know our own history. We imagine a past of Edenic
innocence, but we have never been especially chaste.
</P>
<P>
   A study of family-bible marriage and birth dates found that
about a third of the brides in early Colonial times were pregnant.
A 1953 study showed that 47 percent of men born between 1900 and
1919, and 23 percent of women, had had sexual intercourse before
marriage. Today, only 10 percent of adult men and 22 percent of
women have had their first sexual experience with their spouse.
</P>
<P>
   The abstinence education Bush is touting tries to scold and
frighten the young out of all sexual activity before marriage, but
the age of puberty has dropped by about two years for boys and
girls in this century, and to accommodate extended education and
career starts, marriage has been delayed by several years.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there was only a short gap between the hormonal
tsunami and its legalization, long years now stretch. To suppose
the young are properly prepared for that by being limited to
abstinence is simply silly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself openly admits to a wastrel past and seems only
officially chagrined about it. A little humility, born of his own
experience, might lead our putative president to save us the $73
million he proposes to spend to treat abstinence and sex education
as cultural enemies rather than as the natural allies they are.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5737 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV04-C     07-01 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GAUGE THE EBBING POLITICAL TIDE
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (p) political categories for
release Sunday, July 4.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal campaign finance laws call for the
taxpayers to pick up virtually the entire tab for next summer's
national political conventions. If the presidential nominees are
known in advance, as has been more or less the case since 1952, the
national TV networks will virtually ignore these events.
</P>
<P>
   Next time around, even the cable networks that specialize in
political news intend to duck gavel-to-gavel coverage, seeking to
outflank their rivals by offering their own branded reports. These
coverage decisions reflect two trends as similar as peas in a pod:
falling public interest in the political process and falling public
confidence in government.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington is not a pea plant. As Elizabeth Drew notes in
her new book, ``The Corruption of American Politics,'' this is the
place where ``law and policy are made on taxes, medical care, the
quality of our air and water, Social Security, the national
defense, foreign involvements, the safety of airplanes, abortion,
securities regulations, the release of new drugs, gun control, the
soundness of our banks, disaster relief, continuing education and
training, to name just some.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, fewer and fewer Americans have any real say over
such key policy decisions. If you define insiders as those who
regularly contribute $250 or more to political campaigns at any
level, then you're talking about roughly one-half of 1 percent of
the adult population.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the 1996 presidential election, by far the most
costly in U.S. history, registered the lowest percentage turnout in
72 years. In the 1998 midterm elections, with presidential
impeachment in the wind, the overall turnout fell to 36 percent.
That was the lowest participation since 1942, which came in the
midst of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Those dreary statistics are reflected as well in the number of
taxpayers who choose to fund presidential campaigns through their
annual returns. Since 1980, the downward trend in participation
remains unbroken. It now hovers at around 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since the check-off plan draws scarcely any favorable publicity
from its intended beneficiaries, it's little wonder that some tax
filers wrongly believe they're opting out of an extra $3 payment,
rather electing not to earmark their money.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission estimates that the $200 million
diverted through check-offs between 1997 and 1999 will be
sufficient to cover next year's conventions and general election.
But, for the first time, it projects a shortfall in matching funds
for the presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why George W. Bush, the Republican
front-runner, is currently weighing whether to waive federal
campaign matching funds, a step that would allow the Texas governor
to shun spending limits in primary states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's legitimate,'' Bush said a few months ago. In the
same vein, Vice President Al Gore, Bush's presumed Democratic
rival, might note that there's no controlling legal authority that
compels him to accept a federal subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Bush and Gore campaigns overflow with cash, the
moral tide continues to ebb.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
