 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2553 -- July 1, 1999  NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2553 -- July 1, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. RIDING THE BUBBLE OF THE INTERNET BOOM Adventure in venture
capital firms resides with Internet start-ups - high-flying,
wealth-multiplying, crazy-idea companies that may start with 12
people working in the founder's living room. Here's the story of
Steve Jurvetson, Silicon Valley folk hero, who is a hot arrival on
the scene, just as the seas are growing choppy. By Po Bronson. From
The New York Times Magazine. 3,100 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
THE EAGLE HAS LANDED Thirty years ago, at 4:17 and 40 seconds p.m.
Eastern Daylight Time on the afternoon of July 20, 1969, the Apollo
11 lunar landing module Eagle touched down on the moon's bone dry
Sea of Tranquillity. Seconds later, the Eagle's 38-year-old
civilian commander, Neil Armstrong, radioed back to Earth what was
to become the second most memorable broadcast from outer space :
``Houston, Tranquillity Base here. The Eagle has landed.'' By
Howard Means. Washingtonian. 3,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
THE SERBS ARE NOT INVISIBLE Historian Aleksa Djilas, author of
``The Contested Country,'' writes that even the partitioning of
Kosovo, where Serbs would keep about 25 per cent of the territory
and Albanians the rest, would be fairer than the complete expulsion
of the Serbs, which is now taking place. By Aleksa Djilas. New York
Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
DEADLY KNEE BENDS When Mr. Kelly said his legs were killing him, he
was right. A prisoner in New York City jail, Mr. Kelly participated
in a deep knee-bend competition judged by fellow inmates. His
winning lift : 1,134 pounds. What he didn't realize was the damage
he had done to his leg muscles and consequently his kidneys. Tony
Dajer, who is at work on a book about medical mistakes and the
science of diagnosis, reports. Discover magazine. 1,100 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
RUSSIAN PUBLIC OPINION AND PARLIAMENT AGAINST THE ABOLITION OF
CAPITAL PUNISHMENT The death penalty has to all intents and
purposes been abolished in Russia. Yet it is still on the statute
book - a contradiction that is increasingly taxing the patience of
the Council of Europe. By Frangois Bonnet. Le Monde. (English
translation available.) 1,000 words. 6. FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   A. Researchers Explore Treating Cancer With Cancer It may seem
illogical at first to treat cancer by injecting proteins taken from
tumours. But researchers have discovered that certain proteins
found in every cell of the body play a role in alerting the immune
system when something goes awry. 500 words. B. Sleep Researchers
Uncover Human Internal Clock Contradicting long-held scientific
thought, researchers now report that the natural human clock runs
on a very tight 24-hour schedule. 500 words.
