<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Clinton's refugee policy still a work in progress
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 4, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI - The TV news program showed a single-engine plane towing
a banner that read: ``Iraqi Soldiers Were Treated Better.'' The
evening before, professional-looking signs that called the Coast
Guard ``Murderers'' waved from a bridge opposite the U.S. Coast
Guard station here.
</P>
<P>
   They were boorish and divisive gestures toward our most passive
branch of service, in a day when there were so many other boorish
and divisive gestures that the Miami area, once again, was required
to show its political colors. Those colors were Cuban flags waving
in ire at the Coast Guard base earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   What brought this was about was the Coast Guard interception of
six Cubans in an 18-foot rowboat attempting to illegally enter the
United States just off Miami Beach. That's where Bill Clinton's
floating rules and regulations came into place. If the refugees
touched U.S. soil, they would be admitted. If they never got their
feet dry, were kept offshore, they would be sent back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Two touched, four didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Activities such as this take place every day but usually out of
sight of people on the beach. This one did, about 100 yards off the
beach. The tourists gathered to watch the drama unfold, to welcome
the two who made it to shore, and to harass the police who took
them into custody.
</P>
<P>
   The hours-long scene was played out live for camera helicopters
of the three principal local TV stations. Had TV not been there,
and the interdiction taken place further out to sea, no one would
have known anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   But they did. The treatment of illegal refugees is a passionate
subject in Miami because so many Miamians _ including the leading
politicians _ were illegal refugees themselves (now legitimized) or
are the children of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   What horrified most, even those who favor a stricter immigration
policy toward Cuban rafters, was the use of pepper spray on some
the Cubans in the water. The Coast Guard, under heavy pressure from
the Cuban-American community and media, admitted they made a
mistake in the pepper spray, although I have no idea why they issue
pepper spray if they can't use it.
</P>
<P>
   What other resources have they? Guns? Can you imagine if they
used guns? What does a Coast Guardsman, under orders to prevent
refugees from reaching shore, do about refugees swimming toward the
beach?
</P>
<P>
   Not a simple answer anywhere, other than don't use pepper spray,
or a gun. Maybe a big fish net will do it.
</P>
<P>
   The furor of the Cuban-American community spread throughout the
Miami area, blocking causeways and expressways, and infuriating
people who were trying to go anywhere in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong to use pepper spray, wrong to block highways.
</P>
<P>
   But this all comes back to U.S. policy toward Cuban refugees,
begun in Lyndon Johnson's administration as an open door policy,
later amended to fend off the flood of illegal aliens floating
ashore.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Clinton administration that, in 1995, made a deal with
Fidel Castro. We keep whomever makes it to shore, you get back
those who don't. Left wide open is interpretation of this
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Coast Guard supposed to physically prevent rafters from
touching shore, and what exactly is ``shore?'' Doesn't ``shore''
differ with the tides? Is ``shore'' reached when you can stand in
the water?
</P>
<P>
   The White House, the Immigration and Naturalization Service and
the U.S. Coast Guard need to get on the same page. Define ``shore''
and define to what extent the Coast Guard should go to prevent the
rafters from reaching it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the angry protesters won their day, with word coming
from high up that the four who didn't make it to shore be released
as well. U.S. immigration policy, therefore, is malleable _
depending upon how angry is the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   There remains questions of the six escaping Cubans. When they
were intercepted, they were wearing bathing suits or shorts and
were using paddle-sized oars to row in the ocean. All the way from
Cuba? How about a smuggler ship taking then to within a couple of
miles, then placing them in the rowboat? Happens every day around
here, has become a cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
   I have a problem with one of the two who made it to shore. The
guy's a commuter! It was his third sea journey to Florida. He
admitted that he lived in the Florida Keys for a year, returning to
Cuba voluntarily to be with his ill mother. Now he wants to come
back, doesn't take the legal immigration route, challenges the
Coast Guard, claims he got hit with the pepper spray, and becomes
some sort of folk hero on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Is the U.S. a country without borders? It would seem so. This
not to protest Cubans fleeing Castro's Cuba. But there's got to be
a semblance of order and understanding by all factions. We need to
control our borders and not have it run by angry mobs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ``dry feet-wet feet'' policy is a mixed bag of piffle
that creates rather than solves the problem.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
