<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5772 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-COLUMN02-COX     07-01 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMS never knows what a call will bring
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Note to readers: Last week, I gave you a glimpse of Austin as
seen through the eyes of then Sr. Patrol Officer Wayne Vincent.
This week, we're going for a ride with Dr. Ed Racht of Emergency
Medical Services.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was close to 2 a.m. when Dr. Ed Racht decided
things were so slow, he was going to call this Friday a night. It's
abnormally quiet for a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   According to EMS statistics, the program had four units and
would run about 50 calls on a busy day in 1976 when the system
became active. Today, EMS has 20 ground units on the streets along
with a helicopter, and call volume in last the few months has often
exceeded 200 a day.
</P>
<P>
   This is one business where that kind of volume increase is not
good news. So, the crews will take a slow night anytime one
presents itself.
</P>
<P>
   The medical director of EMS was winding up a long day at the
office and a relatively short night cruising the city in his sports
utility vehicle festooned with the appropriate decals and
equipment, and sporting a souped-up engine, emergency lights and
siren.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cruisin' machine that beats anything those Friday-night
heroes put on the streets. But Racht isn't in it to show off. He
cruises on Friday nights because he likes it, and it shows the EMS
team that even a big wheel can roll on an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   And roll he does. I accompanied the doctor on his rounds
recently and quickly discovered that the hardest calls don't
necessarily involve bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after we hit the streets a little after 6 p.m., Racht
responded to a psychiatric call at a downtown hotel. Security there
had reported a woman threatening to kill herself.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived with the paramedics and were greeted by the two
police officers who had also been dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   Everything appeared fine, though. ``I couldn't find my rosary
and I got excited. I started screaming ... Well, I did tell the
security agent that I was going to kill myself if I couldn't find
my rosary, but that's just an expression,'' the woman explained.
</P>
<P>
   It all made a semblance of sense on the surface, but Racht kept
asking questions. Something about her wasn't right. ``As long as
we're here, why don't you let us take your blood pressure and
pulse? Just to make sure everything is all right,'' Racht asked.
</P>
<P>
   The woman wanted to know why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my blood pressure checked. Don't you have better
things to do? Aren't there people out there who need your help more
than I do? What did I do wrong? I didn't do anything wrong. I want
to know what I did wrong,'' she declared.
</P>
<P>
   Racht would try to reply and she would dive headlong into a vat
of redundancies, sounding like one of those old vinyl records with
a huge scratch in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did I do wrong? I want to have my meal. I don't know what
I did wrong. I'm not going to kill myself. My mother killed
herself, but I'm not. I can't kick out the window. I can't hang
myself in the bathroom ... `` she told Racht in earnest and
continued to catalog the possible ways she could do herself in but
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   She was literally talking herself into the system.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations were fruitless. The woman became adamant even
after intervention by an Austin Police Department's crisis team.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Racht had an ultimatum: You're going to the hospital to
be examined. You'll either walk out with the paramedics or be
carried out on the stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   She relented and climbed on the stretcher clutching a stuffed
bunny. She was quiet all the way down to the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the SUV, Racht said those kinds of calls are the
toughest.
</P>
<P>
   The woman wasn't stabbed, burned or bleeding, but she was
hurting. The path of least resistance might have been to leave the
woman to her rosary, room-service meal, television and her torment.
</P>
<P>
   Racht just wanted to be sure she was all right.
</P>
<P>
   He was on that call for two hours and we were about to eat
dinner at a place in Hancock Center when he got the radio call
about the three-vehicle, multiple-injury wreck on East William
Cannon.
</P>
<P>
   Flying down Interstate 35 with lights flashing and sirens
blaring is an experience. It's exhilarating without a doubt, but
the creepers and the drivers who won't move out of the way make it
a little scary _ or hairy to borrow the word we used when I was
cruisin' in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   We get there and Racht springs into action. The scene is a mess
_ the air smells of anti-freeze and gasoline. Police, EMS and
firefighters break up the task of cleaning up the accident scene
into their respective specialities.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles are a mess as well. Broken plastic, metal and glass
all over the place. The people inside those vehicles fared only
marginally better. StarFlight takes off with the most seriously
injured. The rest are taken away by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   This call was much easier. There was no doubt about what needed
to be done, no ambiguity. If it weren't for the human suffering,
you might even say that it was a relief after the encounter with
the anxious woman in the hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
