<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Timing is everything when it comes to taxes
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ During all the hoopla surrounding Gov. George W.
Bush's presidential campaign, he'd be wise to remember that
incredible luck and timing are worth a lot _ more than $22 billion
in his case.
</P>
<P>
   George W. gave serious consideration to running for governor in
1990, but finally decided not to. The reasons had more to do with
the fact his dad was president, and the ages of his twin daughters,
than any lack of ambition.
</P>
<P>
   But had he run, and won, instead of Democrat Ann Richards, he'd
have faced something quite different from the relatively ho-hum
agenda of the three legislative sessions since he took office in
1995. He'd have been plunged into a money crisis in his first days
on the job. He might even have had to raise taxes, not cut them.
</P>
<P>
   He owes Richards a lot, because she bit the bullet, dealt with
problems and left her successor a revenue stream that provided a
cushion that will leave Texas more than $22 billion richer by the
end of the coming two-year spending period than it might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Problems facing Texas in 1991 included:
</P>
<P>
   _ A budget shortfall of several billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   _ A court mandate to fund school districts equally.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crowded prisons that led to early releases to avoid running
afoul of a federal court order.
</P>
<P>
   _ The fratricidal bloodbath of legislative and congressional
redistricting that followed the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   _ Public clamor to change the Texas Constitution to permit a
state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Not a happy time. The economic downturn in Texas in the
mid-1980s caused enough special sessions that some years the Texas
Legislature, normally limited to meeting 140 days in odd-numbered
years, actually met more days than the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Responses in 1991 by Richards and the Legislature included:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing taxes to generate an additional $1 billion-plus per
year. And that was after the comptroller's office instituted the
Texas Performance Review, which sought to find ways the state could
save money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Imposing a new school finance law, known by opponents as
``Robin Hood'' and supporters as ``share-the-wealth'' because it
required some property-rich school districts to share their local
tax revenues with property-poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Embarking on a prison-building binge that roughly doubled the
number of Texas prison beds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arguing over and finally approving the lottery. Richards was
convinced that Texans wouldn't pay significant attention to
education spending or other budget needs until the lottery issue
was resolved. So she cajoled, pressured and twisted arms to get the
100 votes in the Texas House necessary to put the matter before
voters. They happily added it to the Texas revenue package.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was eager for the Legislature to cut taxes in 1999,
and it did so, he owes Richards and the 1991 Legislature thanks.
Without the Texas Performance Review savings, plus the additional
taxes that continued in later years, plus the lottery revenues,
Bush might well have faced a budget shortfall this year.
</P>
<P>
   Additional taxes passed in 1991 will produce an estimated $10.4
billion through the 1999 budget year that ends Aug. 31. The
lottery, since it began in 1992, produced almost $6.9 billion
through May 17. That's a total of $17.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming two-year spending period that starts Sept. 1,
those 1991 taxes will produce an estimated $3.1 billion. The
lottery will produce another $2.2 billion. That's $5.3 billion _
just $1.2 billion less than the so-called budget surplus of $6.5
billion Bush and the legislators spent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Had Richards and the legislators not already put those revenue
generators on line, the $1.7 billion teacher pay hike, and $1.8
billion tax cut, wouldn't have been possible. The state would have
been $2.3 billion short.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father pledged in 1988 that if Congress asked him to
raise taxes, he'd say ``Read my lips: no new taxes.'' Two years
later, he allowed a tax hike, some say contributed to his defeat in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   A second President Bush, already talking about cutting federal
taxes, could see the economy, and his luck, turn downward _ just
like Dad's. What then? Conservatism? Or compassion?
</P>
<P>
   Will he refuse to raise taxes _ even if it means cutting
necessary services? Or raise taxes, to make sure no one is left
behind?
</P>
<P>
   As with much about the Texas governor-who-would-be-president,
time and circumstances will tell.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
