r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBMD02-COX     07-01 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBMD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medcast to join WebMD deal
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ WebMD Inc. and Healtheon Corp., which are slated to
merge in September, Thursday announced an agreement to buy
Atlanta-based Greenberg News Networks and its Medcast subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said their plans call for purchasing Medcast
with Healtheon stock, completing the acquisition in September as
soon as the WebMD-Healtheon union is complete. At Wednesday's stock
price, the deal is worth about $215 million, and for Healtheon and
WebMD, the purchase is a potential breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The two plan to link complementary businesses: Healtheon, based
in Santa Clara, Calif., can provide big institutions with an online
way to do millions of transactions now done on paper. Atlanta-based
WebMD offers a gateway for physicians and consumers. The two
companies have racked up impressive stock values and scored a
series of big-name partners while taking criticism for overselling
themselves. For instance, WebMD is seen as merely an
``aggregator,'' a gatherer of data from others. That is apparently
about to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not an aggregator,'' said Medcast founder, Chairman and
Chief Executive Alan N. Greenberg. ``We are the source.''
</P>
<P>
   Medcast is one of the Internet's premier providers of health
care information. The well-heeled company functions like a wire
service and has plans to syndicate stories, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   To get rolling, Medcast has inhaled about $22 million in venture
capital, including a hefty chunk from Noro-Mosely Partners.
Greenberg has been relatively low-key about the venture, but he is
not new to high-profile business. His resume includes Esquire,
where he was publisher, and Whittle Communications, where he was
vice chairman. The company has a staff of 230, including
biostatisticians, medical illustrators, 11 doctors and 70
reporters, many with solid journalistic backgrounds and training in
health care. Medcast's managing editor is Marjorie Martin, formerly
of CNN. That staff churns out a daily dosage of stories _ many
based on original reporting, others pegged to medical articles
published that day.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a medical advisory board that includes the
chairman of cardiology at Cleveland Clinic Foundation, the chief of
internal medicine at Boston City Hospital and Louis Sullivan,
president of the Morehouse School of Medicine and a former Cabinet
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We add authority, credibility and daily content,'' Greenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Medcast is pitched at doctors, but the company plans to launch a
consumer service. It's also not a Web company _ not yet. Stories
are delivered to computers overnight.
</P>
<P>
   However, Medcast now plans to reshape itself so that its
software, as well as some stories, can be downloaded from the Web.
The price _ only $10 a month now _ will also rise to match the $30
a month that WebMD charges doctors to subscribe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Medcast now has just 2,200 doctors on its network, but 6,000
more have signed contracts and, even before today's expected deal,
it believes it will have 50,000 customers by year's end, Greenberg
said. With its acquisition, Medcast hopes to add tens of thousands
of others _ and its staff can provide enough data for millions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nan-Kirsten Forte, president of Medcast programming and
development, said the idea is to offer doctors a way to mesh with
patients, who increasingly arrive with up-to-date, if not always
reliable, information gleaned online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors are saying that the biggest problem with the Internet
is that 'we are the last to know,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between WebMD and Medcast started several months ago.
However, Greenberg said he had not founded the company to sell it.
He had explored an initial public offering of stock, only to
discard other plans after talks with WebMD grew serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The model when we began was to go it alone,'' Greenberg said.
``We basically made a business decision that this was a better
thing for our shareholders and our employees. This is as good a fit
as you can expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the Healtheon-WebMD merger fall through, there is a
``blowup'' clause that would see Medcast sold to WebMD, whose stock
is still privately held, according to Jeffrey Arnold, WebMD's
founder and chief executive. ``But that won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold said he is not surprised to find 1-year-old WebMD in this
position, hefting a multibillion valuation and swallowing the likes
of Medcast. ``We have high expectations. We believe in the vision,
and we believe we can convince others that this is the right
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold ticks off five keys to succeeding on the Net: forging a
brand name, having top technology, cementing powerful partnerships,
constructing channels to distribute your product and having content
that will lure users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every deal we make fits into one of those five buckets,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although fewer than 10,000 physicians are online with WebMD,
Arnold dismissed concerns about finances. He cited commitments from
DuPont, Microsoft and others to pay for doctor subscriptions as
they sign up. The company has also notched deals that will provide
$140 million worth of advertising, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a number of questions have been flung at WebMD. Skeptical
analysts have granted WebMD its skill at closing deals, its
expertise at public relations and self-promotion. But mostly, they
ponder the notion that the company's value has far outpaced its
product.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnold argues that the company has only been racing to keep
abreast of competition in a sector _ the Net _ where change occurs
at stunning speeds. Analysts admit that the Healtheon deal has
handed WebMD a multibillion currency that can perhaps buy the
missing pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Like content.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take care of the partnerships and distribution,'' Arnold
said. ``Healtheon can take care of the office transactions. Alan
and Nan can take care of the content.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
