A5775 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN02-COX     07-01 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bills on flag, commandments couldn't be more un-American
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ If the political symbol were the swastika and the
religious document came from ``Mein Kampf,'' more Americans would
see the two wrongs the U.S. House of Representatives has committed.
</P>
<P>
   That the symbol in question is the U.S. flag and the document is
the Ten Commandments makes the House no less wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A government that orders its citizens how to behave around a
graphic political symbol _ an image printed on cloth, paper, name
your medium _ is not one based on symbolic freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   A government that can decree religious commandments _ be they
translations of Muhammad, Mao or Moses _ can call itself just, and
moral, and God-empowered, but it cannot call itself free.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people in the middle rationalize such mischief, along
with theoretical kin like organized school prayer, with ``What harm
would it do?''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty. Say it. These proposals are fundamentally wrong. Most of
all, they are fundamentally un-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? Wrong to punish people for vandalizing the symbol of
America?''
</P>
<P>
   America has laws against vandalism. Against theft. Against
arson. Against inciting a riot.
</P>
<P>
   What the House of Representatives has proposed is an amendment
to prohibit the defacing of a political idea. An idea is all the
flag is, something abstract sketched on something concrete. Someone
burn the flag? We make another. The idea remains. The idea never
left. The concrete thing (made of cloth in these beholders' eyes) a
constitutional amendment would protect is no more real than fog on
the mirror. We make one. We make millions. It means what our minds
say, just like the symbols on this paper, these Xs, Ys, and Os. Is
our government in the business of telling you how to perceive them?
</P>
<P>
   The most insidious thing about the anti-flag-desecration
amendment is that it is such an easy sell, striking back at
something so repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   But to the Supreme Court the public affront this amendment would
forbid is nearly sacred: It is political speech.
</P>
<P>
   Some speech is not protected. Child porn, for instance. Some
speech can be prohibited because it is obscene and has no socially
redeeming value. But here the issue is speaking symbolically about
our government and how it works. When that's the case, the Supreme
Court says government cannot tell critics, ``Knock off the
symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitler could. Mussolini could. Khomeini could. Saddam Hussein
can. Slobodan Milosevic can.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representatives, by a disgraceful 305-124,
asserts, ``We want to join the club.''
</P>
<P>
   For the totalitarian club the posting of religious commandments
would help you keep your franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The House vote to allow schools to post Judeo-Christian
commandments is quite possibly the most grievous assault against
religious liberty on these shores in modern times.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to try to sneak state-established religion into
the classroom with ``voluntary'' school prayer and a silent moment
meant for group prayer. Here the House has sanctioned the posting
of ``thou shalt have no other Gods before me'' and ``remember the
Sabbath day to keep it holy'' (which will confuse some Jewish
students who'll assume it means the state has declared Friday-night
football blasphemy).
</P>
<P>
   And what will have been accomplished? By government decree, the
Ten Commandments will be elevated to the stature of the ``Exit''
sign, the door jamb and the label you don't tear off the mattress.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years after we first planted the American flag on the
moon, the U.S. House of Representatives has launched two of the
world's most meaningful emblems on a mission to the Sea of
Triviality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must pray to the Almighty not to refuse His blessing to
this change and not to abandon our people in the times to come.''
_Hitler, ``Mein Kampf.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
