<P>
   FLORIDA KEYS TRAVEL PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Photos and graohics are available with the following Travel
package on the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-KEYS _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ It's hard to keep up with what's
new in the Keys. Legendary hotels and restaurants change hands and
before you know it, your favorite hangout is now a trendy French
cafe with an adorable name and an expensive menu. But there's one
change that is just the opposite _ a landmark inn on Duval Street
has returned. (Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-LIGHTHOUSE _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ Want the best view of the
Keys? Step this way all 88 steps to the island's lighthouse. with
sidebar depicting other Florida lighthouses. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-HISTORY _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ The cast of characters who came
through this harbor couldn't be better if you made them up. And
Ernest Hemingway tried. First, there were the Spaniards who wrecked
offshore and made a few treasure hunters very wealthy 400 years
later. Then there were salvagers who made fortunes in the 1800s
stripping the vessels wrecked on nearby shallow reefs. And the
spongers who came from Greece, and were run off to Tampa when they
became too successful here. And the shrimpers who sought ``pink
gold.'' And, of course, Henry Flagler, who brought the railroad,
and the moneyed passengers from the north. They took the Key West
ferries docked in Key West to Cuba. The ferries stopped when
Americans quit going to Cuba and Key West's seaport became an ugly
working port most tourists avoided. But with the completion of a
five-year, $5.4 million revitalization, Key West's Historic Seaport
is now bringing back tourists. (Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-INNS _ KEY WEST _ Curiously, this island city is not known
for its waterfront inns. It's famous for the historic inns in Old
Town that are within easy walking distance of the water, but
definitely landlocked. But there are a few inns and modern
high-rise hotels next to the water, some with marinas. (Palm Beach
Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-TARPON _ LOWER MATECUMBE KEY _ Hungry tarpon tarpons gather
at Robbie's Marina next to the Hungry Tarpon restaurant. The fish,
ranging from 60 to 100 pounds, pounce on the sardines people throw
into the water. And, no, you can't fish here. (Palm Beach Post).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-HENRY _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ Take a ride on the Henry Express
-it's a journey back into Henry Flagler's heyday. (Palm Beach
Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-GETTINGTHERE _ Want to the the Keys the right way? Go by
boat. It's the best way to see this string of mangrove-covered
islands. (Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-BOATS _ Looking for a place to stay while boating in the
Keys? Here are some places to slip away, with a slip for your boat.
(Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KEYS-HEMINGWAY _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ Ernest Hemingway's house in
Key West still has his furniture, and descendents of his cat roam
the grounds. Check out this must-see tour when you're in the Keys.
(Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Getaway feature from Wednesday paper. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
