<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ There is an audience, almost a congregation,
for whom the work of Patricia Hampl is received with something
close to devotion. It is not the largest audience in publishing,
but you wouldn't call it a cult of any sort. Cults gather round
shamans and sorcerers, conjurers of sundry mysticisms. But
mysticism _ need it be said? _ is not mystery, anymore than mere
reminiscence can claim to be a memoir. The personal mysteries on
which the memoir draws are Hampl's abiding subject, and, as she
writes in ``I Could Tell You Stories,'' they lay upon us an
impossible command. They impel us to find in our experience a
meaning whose truth is provisional at most, never final and often
in doubt. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 26. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Savannah prepares for the paperback launch of
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' and John Berendt will
revisit Atlanta; Joyce Carol Oates to write ``novel'' about Marylin
Monroe; ``Tuesdays With Morrie'' subject gets a second chance.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-KIDS _ Roundup of new books for kids: ``They Saw The
Future: Oracles, Psychics, Scientists, Great Thinkers, and Pretty
Good Guessers,'' ``Bark, George,'' ``Moon Ball,'' ``We Were Tired
of Living in a House,'' ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of
Secrets.'' (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not
for use by NYTNS clients). 16.BOOKS-REDBONEPRESS _ AUSTIN, Texas _
If you are a gay black woman with a story to tell, how can you get
it printed in a tight publishing industry? You do what Lisa C.
Moore did. You start your own press. (Woolridge, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service)
</P>
