 Thursday, July 1, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-POLITICS (San Francisco) _ Stepping up his attack on
San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, candidate Clint Reilly has
announced his answer to a problem no mayor has succeeded in
unraveling _ homelessness. Reilly's plan includes conducting a
homeless census, opening day shelters for the mentally ill and
encouraging public aid recipients to take vouchers instead of cash.
By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FUNDRAISING (Los Angeles) _ An impish-looking George W.
Bush took the podium at a charter school in Los Angeles to dispel
some rumors about his fund-raising abilities. ``We've raised as of
right now $35.5 million,'' Bush said with a quick laugh, as if
almost embarrassed. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BULL-MARKET (San Francisco) _ Eying the stock market has become
America's newest spectator sport. Millions of investors follow
their holdings as closely as the World Series. Everyone from
high-powered traders to short-order cooks eagerly awaits interest
rate pronouncements from the Federal Reserve. It's the great
democratization of the market. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader wants to know what kind of
grasses is good for her dog, who seems to love to graze. Assorted
Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The Warriors teased the Bay Area
shamelessly on Wednesday night. They picked Todd Fuller II in the
NBA draft, and their apoplectic fans couldn't dial up talk-radio
hosts fast enough. It was time for whining, groaning, hair-pulling,
time for a wake. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Just when I was getting used to
the idea of dueling Clintons in the Senate and a guy named George
Bush wowing conservatives by pretending to be Bill Clinton, I learn
the world is going to end on Sunday. Nostradamus, a 16th century
French apothecary, astrologer and the second-best-selling author in
history after God, predicted that ``In the seventh month of 1999,
from the sky will come a great King of Terror.'' It's Y2K too soon.
Maybe all those computer designers weren't so dumb to make room for
only two digits in their computer clocks. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I went to Alice Adams' memorial
service because she was a terrific American fiction writer and
because she once showed me a profound personal kindness. Through
the remembrances of a cadre of people who knew her intimately and
loved her deeply, I learned that her treatment of me _ a mere
acquaintance _ was a microcosm of her life. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
