<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MIXEDCOUPLE-$A     07-01 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MIXEDCOUPLE-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A KOSOVAR LOVE STORY: MIXED SERB-ALBANIAN COUPLE DEFIES HATRED
IN TROUBLED PROVINCE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., July 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ When Bafti married Gordana 35 years ago,
their love was unremarkable. Today, it seems unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   He is an Albanian and she is a Serb. They are both Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Very infrequently in Kosovo one hears of mixed couples. They are
almost always in their 60s, married in an era when secular
Communism papered over ethnic and religious divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most fear that any discussion of their love will channel
toward their doorstep the ethnic hatred that has left in its wake
dozens of mass graves and burned villages throughout the
war-ravaged province.
</P>
<P>
   But, Bafti and Gordana Miftari, both a sturdy 60, are proud
grandparents with a lot to say. Their simple words seem to defy the
hateful gravity of a place where people matter-of-factly toss out
blanket racial/ethnic epithets about ``wild animals'' or
``terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of people, good and bad. It's not
important, Serb or Albanian. What's important is good or bad,''
Gordana says, as she lays out cola, coffee and pictures of
grandchildren for a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   The pair stayed here in the provincial capital, Pristina, during
the campaign of atrocities committed by Serbs against ethnic
Albanians as NATO warplanes dropped bombs on Yugoslavia for 78
days. They heard the gunshots near their apartment and heard of
Bafti's cousins being murdered. Their 32-year-old daughter fled to
Austria to escape, as her Serb mother puts it, the potential of
``rape and other bad treatment'' at the hands of Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   During the carnage, they tried to explain to their Serb friends
what was happening and that the hatred was unnecessary, but to
little avail. Somehow, what would be considered progressive views
of tolerance elsewhere have become outdated in today's violent
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Bafti and Gordana said they have had no problems bridging the
cultural gap. They laugh off comparisons to Romeo and Juliet. But,
then they reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it is the same sort of love. The play was a love story
and we have our own love story,'' Gordana says.
</P>
<P>
   Born outside Kosovo near the Yugoslav city of Leskovic, Bafti
was one of three Albanian students in Gordana's Serb high school.
She thought he was handsome and of strong character. He wooed her
in Serbo-Croatian, since she spoke no Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Yugoslavia's socialist code eschewed ethnic
differences and mixed couples sometimes even had an advantage as
the model of an egalitarian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were dating, my mother had seen him and I asked if she
liked him,'' Gordana recalls. ``I told her, 'Do you know he's
Albanian?' and she said, 'Your husband will be my son-in-law.' She
was happy because I was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bafti's mother was less pleased. She spoke no Serbo-Croatian and
would not be able to speak with Gordana for years, until Gordana
would learn Albanian. His mother was worried about religion, since
Gordana is Serbian Orthodox Christian and Bafti is Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   But, they had the typical civil wedding and their ethnic
differences mattered little.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about it,'' Bafti says. ``It was a different
time, a different place.''
</P>
<P>
   They both worked in a textile factory and he would rise to
director. He notes that he oversaw 200 employees of 23 different
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was essential that both partners appear to be staunchly
indifferent to criticism. Gordana said people have asked her why
she did not ``find any Serb to marry,'' but she never cared. Bafti,
small but strong and trim, never noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't have the courage to say anything to me,'' he
says with a slight smile.
</P>
<P>
   But things started to change, even as their three children grew
and married Albanians. Communism fell and, like many older
Kosovars, the Miftaris blame Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
for stirring up ethnic hatred as he clawed his way to power.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Yugoslavia, many strange things are happening,'' Bafti
says. ``Instead of developing our economy like other Western
nations, we are looking at Bosnia and Croatia and Kosovo ... where
we are burning bodies at the end of the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   As the death toll mounted in recent months, Gordana tried to
tell her relatives and friends what was happening to the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said things at my church. I told the father that you should
educate people not to hate,'' she says. But, she said, people would
argue with her.
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs, not only in Belgrade but even in Kosovo, still claim
they are unaware that Albanians were massacred by their army in
their name. The Miftaris say some Serbs truly do not know because
they get a skewed view from government television. Others know, but
are covering up.
</P>
<P>
   Bafti resorted to numbers and hard facts during the Serbs'
ethnic cleansing campaign this spring, to persuade others of the
people killed and villages destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when we were with friends, hers or mine, we tried to
speak of figures,'' Bafti says. ``When we would persuade them that
it was true, they just shrugged.''
</P>
<P>
   They are both glad NATO undertook a bombing campaign against the
Serb-led Yugoslav government -- even though Gordana's relatives
were theoretically at risk in Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as NATO has chased the Serb troops from Kosovo and some
ethnic Albanians seek revenge against even elderly Serbs, Gordana
acknowledges she could be confronted by angry Kosovar Albanians who
see her only as another Serb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I can explain to them that they should not be like
that. The Bible says to treat others like you want to be treated,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   And, while there is little disagreement between the Miftaris,
they differ slightly when asked if a young couple today could brave
a mixed marriage. No Kosovo high schools dare even mix Serbs and
Albanians in the same classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love has no borders,'' Gordana says. ``It needs a little time,
but it could happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bafti is less optimistic: ``If it's going to continue like this,
I don't think it can be possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5817 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LOLA-TEX     07-01 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOLA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOLA' RUNS AT WARP SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Run Lola Run'' is definitely not a slacker picture. Its
protagonist, Lola (Franka Potente), spends most of the movie on the
move, feet pounding through the streets of Berlin with a single
purpose: to find enough money to keep her dour-faced boyfriend
(Moritz Bleibtreu) from having to rob a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   He lost dough belonging to the mob _ which has ended up in the
hands, and shopping cart, of a homeless man _ and a thug is waiting
to collect. Lola has 20 minutes to find the cash and stop her man
from taking the ruinous path.
</P>
<P>
   But, wait _ there's more. Not only is ``Run Lola Run'' a
video-game movie, but it must be the first PlayStation picture to
come with its own reset button. The movie offers several possible
scenarios for Lola to bounce through _ a swift and sophisticated
version of motifs played out less successfully in movies like
``Sliding Doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Lola bumps into someone, we see a flurry of freeze
frames, a fast forward of what will happen to whomever she's
crashed into as she hurtles through Berlin. Because she runs into
the same people, we get alternate scenarios of how their lives will
turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Agile and light on its feet, ``Lola'' will be considered an art
movie only because it's in German and with subtitles. Otherwise,
its sleekness, speediness and carefully accessorized techno song
score would make it a much bigger deal than it may turn out to be.
Too bad, because its primary-colored buoyancy will make it one of
the most imitated pictures around. (It's probably fitting that the
movie is coming out on the eve of the millennium, although
``Lola's'' been a hit on the festival circuit since last year's
Toronto Film Festival.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it may well be the first movie to have absorbed the
attention-deficit throb of techno music into its bloodstream, the
kind of movie ready-made for a fan base that runs the gamut from
Orbital to Atari Teenage Riot. (Yes, I know _ it's to believe that
techno encompasses a gamut, but, like the poet says, it's vast: It
contains multitudes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Lola's'' graphic, novel color scheme and energetic precision
will be aped. But no doubt imitators will wrongfully ignore
``Lola's'' dope-slap to capitalism and the poignant portrayal of
the middle class. Her run-ins with her father and his mistress
feature an almost heartless contempt for the bourgeoisie.
</P>
<P>
   The film is breathless, breathtaking and smart _ an
international, pop-fixated cousin of Quentin Tarantino and his
infatuation with Jean-Luc Godard. More than Tarantino, ``Lola''
director Tom Tykwer is truly what Godard called one of the children
of Marx and Coca-Cola _ the movie bounds along fueled by caffeine
and cigarettes and sheer pop adrenaline. (Tykwer understands the
Godard quote, ``All you need to make a movie is a girl and a
gun.'')
</P>
<P>
   And since the film wears its politics and impatience with the
status quo on its sleeve _ it takes its revolution to the streets _
this movie offers subtext.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Run Lola Run''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Tom Tykwer
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Franka Potente, Moritz Bleibtreu
</P>
<P>
   Length: 81 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ (in German, with subtitles) violence and adult
situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchelsl is film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
