<P>
   &UR; THE GREAT WHITE'S WAYS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words plus a 200-word sidebar) &QL; 
 &UR; By GLEN MARTIN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Orr will never forget that breezy Saturday in September
nine years ago. While spearfishing 50 miles up the coast from San
Francisco, he decided to kick away from his paddleboard. Suddenly
he felt as if a boat had run over him. ``All I heard was a big
crunch, kind of like a garage door closing,'' Orr says. White teeth
pierced his eyelid and cheekbone on the left side of his face and
ripped across his nose. Orr's entire head was in the grip of a
shark. But 10 seconds after the attack began, it ended. Orr
survived _ as do most human shark-attack victims. Why? This is just
one of the mysteries surrounding the great white shark, reports
Glen Martin, who covers the environment beat for the San Francisco
Chronicle. A fascinating sidebar titled ``Shark Avoidance'' is
included.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-BEWARE-OF-SHARK-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SHOT OF SANITY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE B&AMP;W SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By KAREN WRIGHT &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Crack may be the most addictive substance used by humankind. Its
effects are so potent and immediate that a single hit can hook you.
There's no approved medical treatment for cocaine addiction.
Instead there are rehab centers, Narcotics Anonymous meetings, a
shrink in the afternoon, group therapy at night. However, the U.S.
National Institute on Drug Abuse is now testing a time-honored
approach to controlling disease: vaccination.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-ENDING-CRACK-ADDICTION-NYTSF. Sent to category codes
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Both stories are also available in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
