<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5866 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SUMMEROFSAM-TEX     07-01 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SUMMEROFSAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAOS IN THE CITY: BROOKLYN'S SUMMER OF 1977 WAS MURDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spike Lee has grown enormously as a filmmaker, and in ``Summer
of Sam,'' he attempts an almost touching dramatization of a doomed
humanity. The problem is that Lee hasn't evolved nearly as much as
a storyteller. The movie feels distended and poorly worked out, and
the material needs a shaping as much as any subject he has ever
filmed.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, he knew exactly where he wanted to go when he last
explored New York during the meanest season, summer, when he wrote
and directed ``Do the Right Thing.'' Here, he dramatizes the
freedom, fear and anger in the air around Brooklyn in 1977, the
year of a miserably hot summer and the year that David Berkowitz,
better known as serial killer Son of Sam, terrorized the city.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz turns up here, played by Michael Badalucco of ``The
Practice,'' wrestling with the turmoil in his head. It should be
said that this adult movie, which doesn't shy away from violence
and sex, isn't about Berkowitz specifically _ it's ``Summer of
Sam,'' not ``Son of Sam.'' (Dissatisfied moviegoers grumbled about
that apparent disappointment as they filed out of the screening I
attended.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer'' starts with New York newspaper legend Jimmy Breslin
delivering a monologue to the camera, reminding us that things are
better now than in 1977. ``There are 8 million stories in the Naked
City,'' he says, ``and this is one of them.'' (Breslin was the
columnist who got letters from Son of Sam during his homicidal
spree.)
</P>
<P>
   1977 was definitely the year of a shift in the wind, the year
that punk took off. Newly hatched punk Ritchie (Adrien Brody), with
his spiky hair reaching up to the sun, is shocking the neighborhood
of pompadoured goodfella wannabes, despite his sad eyes and sweet
nature. This rebel is visibly horrified _ his face is set on
stunned _ when he wanders in on his mom (Patti LuPone) and his new
stepfather (Mike Starr) while they're making love, even though
Ritchie is in his 20s. (The stormy aftermath is one of the funniest
and most touching scenes Lee has ever filmed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer'' is about a series of Pandora's boxes being opened.
Ritchie's boyhood friend Vinny (John Leguizamo) loves his wife
(Mira Sorvino), but can't help seducing women outside his marriage.
Vinny is trapped in the old-school attitude of wanting what he
considers to be dirty sex but thinking getting it from his wife
will sully his marriage; he's racked with guilt and hunger.
</P>
<P>
   In this undercooked part, Leguizamo works as hard as any actor
ever has in a Lee film, and his low-key clowning with Sorvino has
the rudiments of a believable relationship. This Mutt and Jeff pair
belong together.
</P>
<P>
   When Vinny proudly dances around his towering, beautiful wife at
the local discos, his cock-of-the-walk assurance makes him the star
of the joint. But Vinny's compulsive womanizing is leading him to a
fall. Her pert features crumple when his adultery slaps her in the
face. The sick looks on their faces when they find themselves
taking part in the action at Plato's Retreat, the Manhattan club
where couples swapped partners, is heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Lee's ability to direct actors emerges, even
when he sabotages things by going for obvious irony; during a long,
gripping single-take scene when Leguizamo and Sorvino fight to save
their marriage and heroically strip away their defenses, ``Don't
Leave Me This Way'' plays on the soundtrack. (He pulls this
cheapening trick several times during the picture.)
</P>
<P>
   Confident in his own filmmaking style _ the hot saturated colors
in some shots and Lee's patented character-traveling-on-a-dolly
shot are featured here _ Lee works to blend elements of Martin
Scorsese and the late, great actor/director John Cassavetes into
his work.
</P>
<P>
   Cassavetes-film veteran Ben Gazarra turns up as a local mob
figure to whom the cops turn to get help in tracking down Son of
Sam. But Cassavetes' powerful approach toward delving into the
workings of middle-class machismo noisily _ happily, even _
embraced messiness. Lee is, among other things, an incredibly
fastidious director.
</P>
<P>
   Even the flash cuts of the squalor Lee shows in Berkowitz's
home, reflecting the chaos in the killer's head, has the flamboyant
nihilism of a Nine Inch Nails video. (Lee sneaks in a joke from the
1959 Vincent Price schlock horror film, ``The Fly.'')
</P>
<P>
   So, Lee's efforts to display what's going on the heads of the
Italian overgrown boys hanging out in the streets fail, even though
capturing the ripe, funny and slightly pathetic chatter of guys on
the hang is perhaps the director's greatest gift. (It's one he
shares with Cassavetes.) In this case, Lee's contempt for the men
in his movie turns them into sweat-stained, gold-chain-wearing
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a movie that is, in its own way, a mess. ``Summer
of Sam'' is both naive and glum, a combination that grows out of a
filmmaker stretching beyond his talents and not quite measuring up.
</P>
<P>
   Leguizamo is stranded, as much by the way the role was conceived
as for his Hispanic appearance. (Leguizamo looks like the kind of
guy these Brooklynites would beat up when they hit the streets as
vigilantes, looking for their own Son of Sam suspect to pound into
submission.)
</P>
<P>
   Lee gets particularly good performances from some of his cast,
especially Brody, whose hawkish features mask his deftness, and
Sorvino. And an unusual one from Leguizamo, who's still to be
well-used in a movie. ``Summer of Sam'' melts into a lump of failed
melancholy before your eyes, but it's an honest swing at the fences
for grown-ups, something that deserves notice in this summer of
same old thing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Summer of Sam''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Spike Lee
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Adrien Brody, John Leguizamo, Mira Sorvino
</P>
<P>
   Length: 137 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, nudity, sexual situations, drug use and
adult content
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
