<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COOPSIDE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDEBAR TO TRAVEL-COOPERSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are expecting 50,000 people to show up for George Brett's
induction into the Baseball Hall of Fame July 25, which might make
it a tough trip to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   But during the year, Cooperstown, N.Y., is actually a pretty
easy trip, especially during the week.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   You probably want to fly into Albany, N.Y., which is about 95
miles from Cooperstown, or about a 11/2- to 2-hour drive. The
locals will tell you it can be done in 75 minutes, but no actual
human being has accomplished it.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   There are several bed and breakfasts in town, and a few hotels,
including The Inn at Cooperstown, a beautiful refurbished hotel
first built in 1874. Summer rates are $105-$138. Call (607)
547-5756.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Front Motel, right on the water, is just a block away
from the Baseball Hall of Fame. Rates in July and August run
$95-$135. Call (607) 547-9511.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of hotels in bigger cities within a fairly
short drive, including Utica, Syracuse and Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on travel or accommodations, call the
Cooperstown Chamber of Commerce at (607) 547-9983 or look them up
at cooperstown.net.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   If you're feeling a bit risky, the Hamburger Hall of Fame on New
York 28 doesn't look like much, but it serves a mean burger.
Unfortunately there are no plaques on the wall recognizing great
burgers of the past (Winstead's would have been inducted long ago),
and the miniature golf course that was once next door has closed.
</P>
<P>
   Back in town, the Cooperstown Diner on Main Street has solid
diner food and excellent shakes. Locals will tell you some of the
best food in town is at Black Bart's B-B-Q, which apparently is not
a barbecue joint at all. It serves Tex-Mex food.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall
</P>
<P>
   The National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum is open from 9
a.m. to 9 p.m. every day from May through September and 9 a.m. to 5
p.m. pretty much the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Adult tickets cost $9.50, children 7-12 get in for $4 and
children younger than 7 get in for free. But be warned, children
under 7 might not appreciate the charm and history of the Hall of
Fame and might, instead, want to wander up the block to the
Cooperstown Bat Company and have a miniature bat made with their
name on it.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Hall, call 1-888-425-5633 or check
out its Web site at www.baseballhalloffame.org.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere
</P>
<P>
   Away from baseball, the hottest spot is probably the Fenimore
House, built on the site of author James Fenimore Cooper's home. It
houses one of America's largest collections of Native American art.
Call 1-888-547-1450.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fun, though, comes from wandering about, checking
out the various diners and used bookstores, taking in the
spectacular scenery that makes central New York a big spot for
bicyclers.
</P>
<P>
   A few words about memorabilia: It's all here. And it will cost
you a bundle. Along Main Street you can get anything from a 1963
Kansas City Athletics cap to a replica uniform of the New York
Knights, the team Robert Redford played for in ``The Natural.'' But
as the line goes: Bring your love for the game and bring your Visa
card. Nothing is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame: Whaddya say, George?
</P>
<P>
   George Brett talks about the thrill of going to Cooperstown on
July 25 to be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame:
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it doesn't really sink in until you walk into the
Hall of Fame and you see all the history of this great game. It's
the dream of every player to make it into the Hall of Fame, but
even then you don't really know what it's like until you see those
plaques of all the great players on the walls, Babe Ruth and Lou
Gehrig and Ty Cobb and all those guys and my hero, Carl
Yastrzemski. That's when you really understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it's going to be like up there at the Hall
of Fame that weekend. Everybody knows that when I first got voted
in, I couldn't say anything without crying. But I've been
practicing. I've been getting better. I'm thinking maybe if I
practice enough, I won't cry. But when I start thinking about all
the people who helped me _ my father, Charlie (Lau), my brothers,
Whitey (Herzog) _ I'll probably start blubbering like a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to say. I never write down my
speeches. I just write down a few words. You know, if I write down
`Charlie Lau' (Brett's longtime hitting instructor and dear
friend), I will know what to say, believe me. If I write down
`Dad,'' I will know what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's going to be amazing. Cooperstown is a special place,
and this is a special time in my life. It's the most special
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5870 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COOPERSTOWN-KA     07-01 1734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COOPERSTOWN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPERSTOWN GEARING UP FOR SPECIAL WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ The Village of Cooperstown is quaint and
precious and so utterly American that you might want to bring along
some recordings of John Philip Sousa marches. The marches are not
provided by Cooperstown. Everything else American is.
</P>
<P>
   The Baseball Hall of Fame sits on Main Street, of course, right
next to the Cooperstown General Store, across the street from the
Cooperstown Post Office. Trees and American flags line the streets.
On Main Street, you can get a chocolate malt, an apple pie or a new
baseball bat with your name carved into it. There are inns and
charming bookstores and a national bank and a Mickey Mantle Wax
Museum and little shops that close at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On the road to Cooperstown (``The Alfred Bleich Expressway,''
New York 28, named for the former VFW Commander) you see the
mountains and the prairies, wheat and the Hamburger Hall of Fame.
There's a plaque for James Fenimore Cooper, America's first
novelist, who died here. Nearby, there's Yogi Bear's Jellystone
Park for campers. Talk about American. Heck, the first building you
see when entering village limits is a large supermarket called
``Great American.'' And like all Great Americans, it's open 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   As you move around, you're not sure whether this is real or just
an elaborate advertising gimmick for a Washington's Birthday white
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Then, that's the point of Cooperstown. America. Cooperstown is
more American than ``Hee Haw.'' And Cooperstown is where George
Brett will finish off his all-American baseball career on July 25,
when he will be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame. Brett will
go into the Hall of Fame with another American icon, Nolan Ryan,
and when you toss in Robin Yount, you have the most star-studded
cast since at least ``Towering Inferno.'' Fifty thousand people
figure to stuff into this town of 2,100. Traffic into Cooperstown
that weekend figures to back up to Manhattan's Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you can't make it for the weekend, Cooperstown will be
here for the viewing year round. That's the beauty of the place.
The weather may change, but it's always '55 in Cooperstown, 1955,
every day, all the time, except perhaps at a store called ``The
Latest Obsession,'' where they sell, well, whatever happens to be
the latest obsession. You have to love a store like that. It's
almost as if the owner got tired of trying to keep up with an
ever-changing country. ``Yeah, yeah,'' you can imagine her saying
to the delivery person trying to explain America's newest fad.
``Just put it on the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to history, Cooperstown's claim on baseball is
pretty tenuous. A museum display says that according to cave
drawings, they were playing baseball in one form or another in
Egypt back in 2,000 B.C., or even before that if you believe the
old joke that the Bible itself starts with the baseball phrase ``In
the big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, practically every country on earth has laid
claim to being the birthplace of baseball. In England, many believe
the game is just a spinoff of rounders. People in the old Soviet
Union asserted that baseball was actually developed in Russia.
Chinese historians have said plainly that the game was invented in
ancient China, but they did not like it much.
</P>
<P>
   Even in America, historians now say baseball's origins are more
closely tied to Hoboken, N.J., than Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   But then, history hardly seems the point. Baseball has always
touched sentimental strings in us, and Cooperstown is as poignant
and corny as an old Jimmy Stewart movie. The Cooperstown story of
baseball may be sketchy, but it's beautiful. The story goes that
the game was invented by Abner Doubleday, the same man who fired
the first gun for the Union at Fort Sumter, S.C. Seems one day he
was playing a game of ``Town Ball'' with the boys in Cooperstown
when, suddenly, in a jolt of inspiration, he grabbed a stick and
marked out a diamond in the dirt, plopped down some bases and,
essentially, invented the game of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Then he invented the infield fly rule.
</P>
<P>
   The story has taken a beating from historians ever since _ at
least partly because it appears to be completely untrue _ but truth
is really not the point. Maybe baseball really was first played in
Hoboken as in the latest theory, but let's face it, Hoboken, for
all its charms and Sinatra connections and refurbished apartments,
would be a lousy place for the Baseball Hall of Fame. Baseball is
about myth and lore and fairy tales, about ghosts coming out of the
cornfield and Babe Ruth calling his home run and fathers playing
catch with sons.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Cooperstown may not be where baseball was
actually invented, but it's exactly where baseball should have been
invented.
</P>
<P>
   Small things
</P>
<P>
   Skip the movie. The first thing they tell you when you wander
into the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum (a brick
building on the corner of Main and Fair that looks a bit like a
school) is what time the movie starts. People build their entire
days around the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother. The movie is fine _ it's a collage of baseball
photographs with pretty music swirling in the background _ but it's
short. Real short. Some years ago, a group of us went to Disneyland
and waited two hours in 108-degree weather to go on some frog ride.
When we finally made it in, it was, like, BRRRP, ride over, four
seconds at most, and that's exactly what it's like for the movie at
the Hall. Huge buildup, you wait in line, finally make it in, and 5
minutes later you're sitting there going, ``That's it?''
</P>
<P>
   No, the Baseball Hall of Fame isn't all that interactive. It's
really not about videos and little games and talking statues. It's
about small things. The most esteemed room is, of course, The
Members Gallery, and it has the spirit of a church. There are 237
members who have been inducted so far, and only three spots are
left along the main wall, which means Brett, Ryan and Yount will be
the last to get into the big hall. The others will be around the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much that means to me,'' Brett says.
``You walk into that room and it's incredible. You can feel the
power of the place, you know? I mean, there they all are, all the
greats. To get into that room, it's, I don't even have any words
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   People have different reactions to The Members Gallery because
it's so elegant and so simple. Many are wowed by the names _ Ruth,
Aaron, Gehrig, Cobb, Musial, DiMaggio, Mays, Clemente _ and the
almost religious grandeur of the place. Others look around and
think ``Uh, this is it? Where are the rides?''
</P>
<P>
   This carries throughout the Hall of Fame. The thrills of the
place are in tiny details, in seeing the bat Bobby Thomson used to
hit the most famous home run in baseball history, in looking at the
beat-up catcher's mitt that Yogi Berra wore the day he caught Don
Larsen's World Series perfect game, in studying the way uniforms
have changed through the years.
</P>
<P>
   A quick warning: Kids often get bored fast here. You often see
dads and moms gawking forever at Mark McGwire's 70th home run ball
or George Brett's pine-tar bat (go ahead, measure how high the pine
tar goes; everyone else does) while their kids run around, bumping
into walls, nearly knocking off the photo of Bill Mazeroski.
</P>
<P>
   You definitely should not miss the baseball movies room. It's
not all that easy to find; you actually have to go past the
sportswriters wing of the Hall of Fame (which includes the eminent
former Kansas City Star columnist Joe McGuff) and into a little
room, where there are posters of a bunch of baseball movies and a
television playing wonderful trailers from such classics as ``It
Happens Every Spring'' and ``The Kid From Left Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, the Baseball Hall of Fame is there to be
enjoyed at your own pace. There is so much memorabilia, so much
history, that a rabid baseball fan _ one of those people who knows
exactly how many runs batted in Hack Wilson had in 1930 _ can spend
two days there. A casual fan can spend several happy hours. A
non-baseball fan will be in and out in 20 minutes, and that
includes 10 minutes buying $48 shirts in the gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   A pace of life
</P>
<P>
   During the Baseball Hall of Fame induction weekend, there's this
guy from Ohio who dresses up like Babe Ruth and walks up and down
Main Street. That's not the amazing part, though. The amazing part
is that the guy doesn't have a full-time job here, because every
time you walk among the shops and street lights, you expect to run
into Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   There are other things in Cooperstown besides baseball.
Virtually everyone you meet will ask if you've gone to the Farmer's
Museum, where people weave and craft and blacksmith and whatever
else they used to do in the 19th century. The Fenimore House has a
wonderful collection of American art, from Native American to folk.
There's a classy Belgian brewery _ Brewery Ommegang _ and boating
along Otsego Lake and all sorts of nature to wow at.
</P>
<P>
   There are also $30 baseball caps and tacky tourist places and
such things. No town, not even Cooperstown, can fully escape from
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   But even so, Cooperstown is about baseball, and it's about a
pace of life long gone in most places. It's about shutters and
picket fences, cars waiting for you to cross the street and people
window shopping and used bookstores. Baseball has always had this
dreamy quality, this ability to take you away from the rush, even
for a few moments. That's what Cooperstown is all about. America
probably was never really quite this quaint or this charming _ just
as baseball's good old days were never really that good _ but we
all want to believe it. And we all want to go back now and again.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, after his election, George Brett went to
Cooperstown. They wanted to show him around, show him where
everything would happen. As he looked around, he felt overwhelmed
by the history, by the names, by the fact that he would become a
part of this place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `This is amazing; I don't belong here,' '' Brett
says. ``But then I thought `You know? I could get used to being
here. I definitely could get used to being here.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
