<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FANATIC-TEX     07-01 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FANATIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SON' PROVES MISERY LOVES COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My Son the Fanatic'' is the oddest thing, a comedy about
misery. What's most odd about it is that it works, and works
magnificently. Hanif Kureishi, adapting his own fiction for the
screen, has written a film about the folly of good intentions and
the necessity of delusion.
</P>
<P>
   It's his best work for the screen since his screenplay for ``My
Beautiful Laundrette'' was produced and made a movie star out of
Daniel Day Lewis. ``My Son the Fanatic'' is Farid (Akbar Kurtha),
the child of Parvez (Om Puri), a Pakistani cabbie whose face is
split with pleasure when he smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Parvez is happy about his son's impending marriage to
a charming British girl, the daughter of a police officer. But the
boy dumps her when he turns suddenly to Islamic fundamentalism.
``He said my father is the only pig he wants to eat,'' Farid's
stunned and jilted fiancee explains to Parvez.
</P>
<P>
   Parvez is deeply conflicted, a man who wants to create a
comfortable home for his wife and son, whom he loves. Yet he
alienates himself from his family by shutting himself away in the
basement with his decadent good taste for scotch and R&AMP;B records (a
great group of songs selected by the R&AMP;B historian Charlie Gillett,
who was music consultant on the film).
</P>
<P>
   He also disdains ``low-class people,'' his fellow gossiping
cabbies. Yet he brings in extra money by setting prostitutes up
with clients. One particular client is a crude, pale lug of a
German (Stellan Skarsgard) who flings himself happily into affairs
with the hookers. He treats Parvez like a working-class puppy,
patting him on the head and calling him ``little man.''
</P>
<P>
   Skarsgard is almost too perfect a symbol of capitalist
crassness, a straw piggy for the picture to play off. Almost
everyone in ``My Son'' is lusting for a kind of purity. Even
Bettina (Rachel Griffiths, last seen in ``Hilary and Jackie'' and
showing a lovely worn dignity that softens her edges), the hooker
with whom Parvez spends the most time and is starting to fall in
love. Only he gets to see her without her streetwalker's armor, the
wigs and fanny-hugging PVC outfits.
</P>
<P>
   This corrosive comedy is fluidly directed by Udayan Prasad, who
gives the British industrial town a midnight-blue cast, a brooding
color scheme that perfectly complements the moodiness and the mood
shifts. Kureishi's gift for the amiable haze that assimilation can
create causes a delirious potency here, despite his letting Parvez
off the hook with his wife after an incident that shouldn't make
him sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   The script is packed with terrific dialogue that doesn't score
at the expense of its characters, because much of it is soaked with
telling observation. ``You always said there were more important
things than `Stairway to Heaven,''' Farid tells his disbelieving
father, ``and you were right.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the father and son descriptions of a
local landmark, a steel mill chimney, are so sharp and varied they
could come right out of a short story. The copyright date on ``My
Son, The Fanatic'' is 1997, which means someone may have been
afraid to release this film. To its credit, it has aged extremely
well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``My Son the Fanatic''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 5 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Udayan Prasad
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Om Puri, Rachel Griffiths
</P>
<P>
   Length: 86 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ sexual situations, drug usage, mild violence and
adult language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
