<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY B-DAY WHENEVER, SATCHMO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday will mark the anniversary of one of the most significant
events in this nation's history: Louis Armstrong's birth.
</P>
<P>
   Well ... maybe.
</P>
<P>
   You see, no one is quite sure of the exact date of Satchmo's
entry into this mortal realm. Some say he was born sometime in
1898. But he said he was born July 4, 1900. And if that's the way
that cat wanted it, he earned the right to go down in history as
being born on the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is that he got here whenever he did. And
that has been exceedingly good for America, the world and music.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rags-to-riches stories that spangle the fabric of this
nation's star-adorned history, none is more spectacular than
Armstrong's.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in poverty in and on the fringes of New Orleans'
notorious Storyville red-light district, Armstrong came early to
hard work, to privation, to exposure to the seamy underside of
urban life.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping out of school after the fifth grade, he hauled coal,
worked on a milk truck and did whatever menial work he could find
to help support his sister and ailing mother.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he struggled to survive, Armstrong's sensibility
absorbed the robust rhythms of his New Orleans environment, and his
mind's ear soaked up the sounds of the rich and vibrant music _ the
marching bands, the parades, the funerals, the pulsating juke
joints and the great trumpeters.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Bergreen, in ``Louis Armstrong: And Extravagant Life,''
quotes Satchmo reminiscing this way on his old New Orleans days:
</P>
<P>
   ``I could go on talking about my home town like mad because I
love it. I always will. It has given me something to live for.
Those millions of memories. Even with those hard times I'd be
willing to live them all over again if I could run into some more
Joe Olivers and those fine prostitutes and pimps and gamblers who
told me, `Son, you don't want to live this kind of life.'''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for him and American culture, he didn't have to live
that kind of life. His turning point came when (if we believe him
about his birthday) Armstrong was 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's morning 1913, young Louis fired a pistol into the
air in celebration and was arrested, tried and sent to the New
Orleans Colored Waifs Home. He became the school's bugler, was
inducted into the school's marching band and got his first
extensive lessons on the cornet.
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Armstrong grew up to play with bands and orchestras on
riverboats traveling up and down the Mississippi River between New
Orleans and St. Louis, played in clubs in Chicago and New York, and
was proclaimed the world's greatest trumpet player _ cutting
records that became nationwide hits, carrying jazz into new
frontiers, breaking sound barriers with his horn, becoming an
international celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the current generation think of Satchmo (short for
``Satchel Mouth'') as just a popular singer because modern jazz
took off in another direction from where he took it. He was
condemned in some quarters for his blending of pop and jazz music.
</P>
<P>
   Satchmo is known today to millions by his gravely voice; his
singing career did not take off until he caught a bad cold that
left him with that distinctive raspiness. A number of singers tried
to catch colds to get that voice quality.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly Satchmo's best-known song today is ``Hello, Dolly.''
Ironically, he was pressured by his manager to record it. He
thought the recording session was a bomb. When it became a hit, he
and his touring band had to have sheet music sent to them from New
York so that they could do it on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Satchmo's international prestige boosted him into the role of an
American ambassador of good will, a part he delighted in playing.
But there came a time when he refused to play that part. It was
when he saw on television a white man spitting on a little black
girl who was trying to enroll in school in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Satch canceled his international tour. He called
President Dwight Eisenhower a ``two-face'' with ``no guts'' and
Gov. Orville Faubus of Arkansas an ``uneducated plow-boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Armstrong: ``The way they are treating my people down South
the government can go to hell .... The people over there ask me
what's wrong with my country, what am I supposed to say?''
</P>
<P>
   That was stunning coming from Satchmo, who had always projected
the image of the smiling, contented performer with no serious
nonmusical thoughts in his head. A lot of people didn't like that,
especially down South. He was widely criticized, and letters were
sent to FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover calling for an investigation
of the musician.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI did start a file, but after reviewing it, Hoover said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Armstrong's life is a good argument against the theory that
Negroes are inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   His unpopularity was short-lived, and Armstrong soared to new
heights of adulation both for his musicianship and his citizenship
during the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering the last of a series of heart attacks in June
1971, Satchmo celebrated his last birthday party on July 4 at his
home in Corona, N.Y., telling reporters that he would resume
performing soon. He died in his sleep two days later.
</P>
<P>
   On this last Fourth of July of the 1900s, it would be fitting to
sing a chorus of ``It's a Wonderful World'' in honor of an
extraordinary red,-white-and-blue-and-black American who was born
on that day.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
