<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING A GREAT WRITER, FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I went to Alice Adams' memorial service because
she was a terrific American fiction writer and because she once
showed me a profound personal kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Through the remembrances of a cadre of people who knew her
intimately and loved her deeply, I learned that her treatment of me
_ a mere acquaintance _ was a microcosm of her life. As Anne Lamott
put it: ``If she loved you, boy, you knew it, and her generosity
knew no bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice's books _ 17 novels and short story collections _ speak
more eloquently (and accurately) than any person could about her
work. Her stories were selected 22 times for inclusion in the
annual O'Henry Awards Collection. Her novels, among them
``Listening to Billie,'' ``Superior Women'' and ``Southern
Exposure,'' are a mainstay of contemporary literature and stand as
bright, lucrative feathers in the cap of her publisher, Alfred A.
Knopf Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But something clearly evident at her memorial service in the
barn-like Golden Gate Club of the Presidio struck me as perhaps the
ultimate tribute to Alice's soul: Scores and scores of
fabulous-looking women of substance came to pay her homage.
</P>
<P>
   I say fabulous not because they were Miss Universe-pretty or
``done'' or draped in expensive clothes. Young, middle-aged or old,
the women in attendance all seemed to have what they used to call
in Hollywood ``A Face'' _ a visage with profound experience (both
awful and ecstatic) written upon it.
</P>
<P>
   Each moved and held herself in a way that promised: ``My story
would take your breath away.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Alice's son Peter Linenthal and a handful of other
men, more than a dozen women took the podium to praise Alice.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them _ like best-selling authors Lamott and Mary
Gaitskill _ are successful writers and poets; most are younger than
Alice, who died May 26 at the age of 72.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an inconsequential pair of facts.
</P>
<P>
   A proud, serious, vulnerable artist, Alice repeatedly exposed
her insecurities and doubts to _ God forbid _ other writers. She
formed deep, intimate, joy-filled friendships with them.
</P>
<P>
   A beautiful, highly sexed female who breathed in the attention
of men as if it were pure oxygen, she gathered other beautiful
women around her. She did this not to neutralize or pull rank on
them, but to encourage their talents, to teach them and to be
taught.
</P>
<P>
   The more beautiful and gifted they were, the closer she seemed
to hold them to her heart.
</P>
<P>
   The words most often used at Alice's service were ``beautiful,''
``elegant,'' ``fierce'' and ``generous.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamott told how Alice had paid her rent for several months after
Lamott's son Sam was born and Lamott was a broke single mom.
</P>
<P>
   On Sam's first birthday, Alice gave Lamott a check for $1,000 in
his name and told her to give it to the next desperate young writer
she encountered, ``somebody who needs the money right now.''
</P>
<P>
   That may have been my favorite thing said about Alice Adams at
her memorial. But here are some other fine words:
</P>
<P>
   ``She never gave up on love or friendship.'' _ Fran Kiernan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the years I knew her (nearly 25 as her editor), she
never complained or talked about how hard it was to write ... She
was a spiritual woman though not remotely religious ... She was a
true bohemian.'' _ Victoria Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   As a friend, ``she was as fierce in her defense of you as a
hockey player on speed. ... She was wild, a great beauty and she
drove men nuts _ some who are in this room. She was an elegant,
old-fashioned sexpot. I don't think she ever wanted to be friends
with men, she wanted to knock their socks off.'' _ Carolyn See.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved Trollope and Chekhov ... (but) the writer she read
over and over was Iris Murdoch. ... When we talked about writers
being jealous of other writers, she said, `I'm never jealous of
someone who writes better than I do.'' _ Millicent Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was opinionated and could be pretty judgmental, but she
could allow her friends to be exactly themselves. So many people,
you can feel them in your face, thinking as you talk, `I wouldn't
do that. You shouldn't have done that. You sure were stupid.' I do
that. But if Alice liked you in any way, she had the grace to stay
in her own skin and not get caught up in whether or not you were
thinking or living as she would. She could just let you be.'' _
Mary Gaitskill.
</P>
<P>
   This is my Alice story: We met at a party in early 1989. She _
THE Alice Adams _ not only tolerated me, she seemed interested in
me as a writer and as a person, and she laughed at my jokes.
Although the place was packed with good-looking men and literati, I
couldn't leave the exciting-but-comfortable space around her.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, she sent me a complimentary note about
something I'd written. It was like a missive from a goddess. I
wrote her back and carried her note around in my purse as if it
were a magic amulet.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1989, I was mugged and knifed in front of my house.
</P>
<P>
   Alice read about it in the newspaper. With only that one
previous meeting and one exchange of notes, she sent me an
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   She could only imagine that I must be very afraid now to come
home and be alone, she said. If I wanted, I could come live with
her until my physical wounds healed and I got back my confidence.
</P>
<P>
   As Alice's friend Sheila Ballantyne said at the memorial: ``When
I think of Alice, I think, `Generosity. Generosity. Generosity.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
