<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5951 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SAM-BOS &LR;      07-01 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUMMER OF SAM,' SPIKE, AND 1977 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty-two summers ago, Shelton Jackson Lee came home
to murder, mayhem, and mercury boiling in thermometers.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1977, and the 20-year-old had just completed his
sophomore year at Morehouse College in Atlanta. He returned to
Brooklyn without a declared major, no summer job, and an apartment
with no air conditioning. With little else to do, he bought a Super
8 camera, walked around the city, and recorded what he saw _
neighborhood block parties fueled by homemade lemonade, malt
liquor, and WKTU's Disco 92 pouring from a boombox; people, young
and old, frolicking in the cooling spray of an uncapped fire
hydrant; a city turned looter's paradise, when a lengthy blackout
draped everything in darkness.
</P>
<P>
   It was the summer when Lee, now best known by his childhood
moniker, Spike, decided to become a filmmaker _ and the time when a
chubby postal worker calling himself the Son of Sam seized the city
by its sweaty throat with a series of execution-style shootings.
Lee's latest film, ``Summer of Sam,'' examines that memorable New
York season when Reggie Jackson was king, sex was unprotected,
every tabloid headline screamed of heat or homicide, and 8 million
people shuddered with the unholy roar of a .44-caliber gun in the
hands of a madman named David Berkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a crazy summer where all these energies, good and bad,
came together. It was an exciting, dangerous, scary time,'' said
Lee recently on a New York day toasty enough to recall that brutal,
bludgeoning summer. ``Disco, the heat, the Yankees, the blackout,
Son of Sam _ what you see in the film are all of my memories of
that summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which opens Friday, stars John Leguizamo, Mira
Sorvino, Adrien Brody, Jennifer Esposito, Ben Gazzara, Patti
LuPone, and Anthony LaPaglia.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a midtown Manhattan suite _ just a hop, skip, and
limousine ride away from his courtside seat at Madison Square
Garden where he would later see his beloved New York Knicks lose
game four of the NBA Finals against the San Antonio Spurs _ Lee was
playful, pugnacious, and talkative despite a day's worth of
interviews for his 14th film. With his trademark glasses and
goatee, he was snazzily dressed in a dark suit, well-shined
loafers, and diamond stud in his left ear, a far cry from the
Latrell Sprewell jersey, Knicks cap, and orange team towel he would
don at the Garden later that night.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one gets the impression thatLee, 42, would be just as
happy talking about the Knicks' near-miracle season of 1999 as his
film about the mean season of 1977. That summer is viewed through
eyes of a group of friends and neighbors in an Italian-American
community in the Bronx. They are preoccupied with finding the Son
of Sam, convinced he's someone from their neighborhood. It captures
the madness and mania of the time _ from the women who cut and dyed
their hair because many of Berkowitz's victims had long dark hair,
to the restaurants and clubs that suffered when patrons were too
frightened to leave their homes at night.
</P>
<P>
   As Lee remembers it, there wasn't a palpable sense of panic in
his Fort Greene neighborhood. Simply put, Berkowitz wasn't
murdering people of color. But while there was grief for the
victims, Lee recalled some felt a certain relief even before
Berkowitz was captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they identified this guy as white, a lot of black
people were praying to God that he was not black,'' said Lee, who
recently moved from Brooklyn to Manhattan's Upper East Side. ``It
was like, `Well, at least that's something they can't blame on us.'
''
</P>
<P>
   There's a scene in the film addressing that sentiment. Yet
``Summer of Sam,'' written by Michael Imperioli, Victor Colicchio,
and Lee, is not a film about Berkowitz, who began his killing spree
in July 1976 and murdered six people and wounded seven before his
arrest in August 1977. Such a project would not have interested
Lee, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the script Michael and Victor brought to me had been just
about David Berkowitz, just the Son of Sam, just the .44-caliber
killer, I would have rejected it right away,'' he said, crossing
his legs. ``They had the vision to see that would have been a
terrible movie. That movie has been done a million times before,
about a psychopath or serial murderer. That's not the movie they
wanted to make, that's not the movie they wanted to make, and
that's not the movie we made.''
</P>
<P>
   As with such Lee films as ``Do the Right Thing,'' ``Clockers,''
and ``Jungle Fever,'' ``Summer of Sam'' presents the Atlanta-born
Lee's singular love-hate view of his adopted city. It's a hard
slice of life about a city where nothing seemed to work. In 1977,
New York was unraveling. Teetering on brink of bankruptcy, it
suffered through one of its deadliest years, with more than 1,500
murders. The July 14 blackout _ which Con Edison officials had
assured customers would never happen _ cost the city millions in
damages when looters smashed into stores and stole everything from
bikes to television sets to sneakers to baby diapers. Even Studio
54, with its velvet ropes and fascist door policy, turned
nightclubbing into a battle between the haves and the have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for anyone who lived in the city at the time, it's
impossible to remember that summer without a tug of nostalgia. The
airwaves percolated with great music from Barry White, The Who,
Talking Heads, and Marvin Gaye. The city, starved for a World
Series champion, rooted for the Yankees of Reggie, Catfish, Munson,
and Nettles. Here were the years before AIDS, before crack, before
Reaganomics and its trickle-down economics left many high and dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember people used to think cocaine was not addictive, that
it was not harmful?'' Lee said with a laugh. ``I don't know who
told them that lie, but back then people believed it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Lee captures the era's decadence, especially when
Leguizamo and Sorvino's characters visit the notorious sex club,
Plato's Retreat. Though that scene remains sexually graphic, the
Motion Picture Association of America _ those mysterious folks who
dole out movie ratings _ demanded Lee makes cuts to secure an R
rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in my contract (to deliver a film with no more than an
R rating), and it's a policy at Disney that there are no NC-17
films,'' Lee said. ``So we had to trim some frames in the Plato's
Retreat scene. We had to zoom in slowly past John Leguizamo's
naked, pale . . . buttocks. The MPAA just couldn't deal with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the MPAA did not ask for trims of violent scenes, which Lee
called, ``a sad commentary. Violence never troubles the MPAA. It
always has to do with sex, and don't let (MPAA president) Jack
Valenti tell you any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film's recollections of that violent summer do
trouble some of the victims' survivors; a number of them have
protested the project since it began production last year and
lament that the film unearths painful memories. Michael Lauria,
whose 18-year-old daughter Donna was Berkowitz's first victim,
recently told The New York Times that Lee ``is making money off my
sorrow and my family's hurt. He has got no compassion.'' Neysa
Moskowitz, the mother of Berkowitz's final victim, Stacy, called
Lee ``a piranha.''
</P>
<P>
   On that subject, Lee has adopted a policy of don't ask, don't
tell _ if you don't ask, he won't tell you off. But at the Cannes
Film Festival last May, Lee said, ``I feel deeply for the parents
of the victims of Son of Sam. At the same time, I'm an artist, and
this is a story I wanted to tell. Even if I didn't make this film,
that was not going to bring their daughters, their loved ones back.
They got buried by a psychopath. We do not feel that the film is a
glorification of David Berkowitz.''
</P>
<P>
   What Lee will discuss is The New York Times' interview last
month with Berkowitz, who is serving six consecutive life sentences
in an upstate New York maximum-security prison. Berkowitz, who once
claimed he received his orders to kill from a neighbor's black
Labrador retriever, and, before his capture, sent literate,
taunting letters to then-New York Daily News columnist Jimmy
Breslin, denounced Lee's film for exploiting ``this madness, the
ugliness of the past.'' But Berkowitz, who says he is now a
born-again Christian, also made a creepy comment in the story about
Lee, saying he monitors ``everything there is'' about the filmmaker
and his family, naming Lee's wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he was not only outraged by Berkowitz's comments, but
the newspaper's decision to print them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was 100 percent (expletive) up. Why would you go to
a mass murderer and ask him about a movie? What validity does he
have?'' Lee asked. ``What, this guy is an expert? To quote a phrase
I got from (former Georgetown University) coach John Thompson, `I'm
not drinking the Kool-Aid.' If The New York Times thinks David
Berkowitz is an ideal talcum-powder-smelling American citizen (the
Times' article described Berkowitz as smelling ``pleasantly of
talcum powder), they can. I'm not drinking the Kool-Aid, and
neither are a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a summer dominated by Adam Sandler, Will Smith, and Mini-Me,
Lee's serious meditation on a decades-old New York summer could get
overshadowed. In the modestly budgeted ``Summer of Sam,'' there are
no dazzling special effects, no potty-mouthed cartoon kids, no
annoying computer-animated creatures _ things that often translate
into summertime success. But Lee contends that, unlike many of his
contemporaries, he doesn't judge the success of his films based on
opening-weekend tabulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael and Victor brought me a great script that had a
riveting story. It was something I felt passionate about, and I
have to feel passion for anything I choose to direct,'' Lee said.
``Box office has nothing to do with it. It has to do with whether
I've been successful in getting on screen the vision I had in my
mind. With this film, I definitely got that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
