<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SOLSTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLSTICE APOCALYPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some thoughts on the solstice: Life isn't fair. New England
gardeners get used to cold, wet springs and hot, dry summers, but
so far it's been a hot, dry spring, and with unfortunate results.
</P>
<P>
   The spring drought, as droughts do, crept up on us. Lawns
suddenly looked like they do in late July _ brown, crinkly,
crunching underfoot. Shrubs and trees took longer to show the
effect, but when the loopers struck, the combination of being eaten
by the tiny green inchworms and not having water to help regenerate
leaves was too much.
</P>
<P>
   Roses are barren. Our Golden Showers yellow climber, usually
frothy with bright yellow flowers, came up dry, and our lovely
Zephirine Drouhin rose, which drapes a fence with pink, scented
beauties, was bare of flowers and leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The early-flowering hyacinthiflora lilac got its show in, but
when I went to dead-head the spent flowers, I found the leaves
curling, withering. I think it was the drought, but I also spent
some time looking for borers, though I didn't find any. I further
suspect some unknown disease.
</P>
<P>
   And worst of all, an ornamental plum, already short of leaves
because it is beset with black knot, lost the rest of its foliage
to the drought and loopers. I fear I may lose the tree, which is
underplanted with Japanese painted ferns and various kinds of
campanula and tradescantia, none of which would appreciate losing
the plum's protection from full sun.
</P>
<P>
   Well, enough is enough. I already had been spraying fungicide
for the black knot. Now it was time to kill bugs and water and
fertilize (and pray for the plum). My supply of Bt (Bacillus
thuringiensis, a natural organism that kills caterpillars) was too
old to trust, and I felt I should not wait, so I loaded the sprayer
with Sevin (a chemical insecticide) and let fly. I prefer organic
methods, but the birds weren't eating enough of the little green
culprits.
</P>
<P>
   I have been watering steadily, have reapplied fungicide to the
plum, have fresh Bt on hand, and have fertilized to help the
weakened plants recover. While they all look terrible, only the
plum is likely to succumb.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we dwell on misfortune, there are bright spots. There
always are, though sometimes we have to look closely.
</P>
<P>
   So, we find the wispy California poppies have returned,
self-seeding, beneath a cherry. Their bright orange flowers are a
delight with the deep blue of Siberian iris and fronting the purple
balls of alliums.
</P>
<P>
   Also wispy and welcome are a handful of lupines. A clump by the
road has been magnificent, and I plan to harvest its seeds to help
it spread. Others hide, some in a tangle of ornamental grasses and
rugosa roses, one among the cherries.
</P>
<P>
   In another bed, Japanese blood grass is spreading, finally,
lending season-long color, slashes of red, by a transplanted
hydrangea that is at last settling in.
</P>
<P>
   In our front bed, along the road, a line of baptisias burst into
foliage and bloom, their flowers pea-like and a soft blue. They
were glorious this spring and hold great promise for next. Fronting
this are the brilliant yellow flowers of a coreopsis. Next to that
is a fringe tree, still under 3 feet tall but this year sporting
feathery white flowers, with the green foliage developing outside
the blooms. The plant fairly glowed.
</P>
<P>
   The small, year-old lime-yellow hostas in the Lucy bed out back
survived the depredations of the bed's namesake Newfoundland dog
(although one of the new ones I planted does appear to have been
stomped or sat upon). And after I had a dreadful battle to rip down
the Rosa multiflora that was strangling it, our heirloom red
climbing rose emerged, in bloom, and to thank me for my bloody
efforts, has thrown out some more blooms.
</P>
<P>
   As we mark the solstice and enter summer _ temperatures noted
the passage by plunging into the 40s the night before _ we can only
wonder at the vagaries of our climate and nature as a whole and
ponder whether we ever will learn all its lessons and tricks.
</P>
<P>
   The most important lesson is to breathe deeply, relax, and enjoy
what is given, not mourn what is taken away. On to July!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
