<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-SQUAD-2TAKES-AR     07-01 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-SQUAD-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLIMPSE AT A WAR CRIMES MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ Even though the Serb wielding the machine gun
and barking orders was masked by green grease paint and a
camouflage bandana, Liria Gashi knew he was ``Zvonko.''
</P>
<P>
   The eyes and the nervous hitch in his walk told Gashi, 38, an
ethnic Albanian mother of six, that the gunman descending upon her
rural hamlet was Zvonimir Svetkovic, an old neighbor and friend.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up together in Pec in a time before ethnic hatred in
the Balkans exploded into war. And now the 42-year-old man she
always called by his nickname ``Zvonko,'' and once considered
``like a brother,'' was leading a local unit of the feared and
murderous Serb paramilitaries known as ``Frenkis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go. Let's get this done,'' she heard Svetkovic tell his
militia, moments before 45 men from her village were lined up, shot
at close range, and then set ablaze with gasoline-soaked rags the
morning of May 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they become so capable of so much evil?'' she asks amid
charred ruins littered with bone fragments where 12 of her
relatives were executed.
</P>
<P>
   Svetkovic, 42, was just one cog in the machinery of
state-sponsored hate and killing unleashed by Serb forces who NATO
officials say killed up to 10,000 Kosovar Albanians and burned and
terrorized some 800,000 people out of their homes. Investigators
say that nowhere did this machine operate more effeciently than in
Pec, a city that represents holy ground for the Serbian Orthodox
Church, and one that Serb ultra-nationalists were willing to
destroy to make their own.
</P>
<P>
   Documents and photographs obtained by The Globe begin to paint a
picture of how Pec's local Serb paramilitary units operated in
concert with the Yugoslave Ministry of Interior Police, known as
``MUPs,'' and with special units within the Yugoslav army. It also
offers a glimpse into the connections between the local killers and
the regime of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, as well as the
network by state-owned businesses that helped finance the groups'
systematic rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The documents comes primarily from KLA sources, along with
prominent Kosovar lawyers and doctors turned human rights
investigators, all trying to cobble together the first draft of a
horrible chapter in history. But the paper work is butresses the
claims of many witnesses, whose accounts in the refugee camps in
Albania and Macedonia seemed at first to strain belief.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging evidence suggests that some 500 people were killed
by the Serb forces here during the war, and 80 percent of the
housing stock was destroyed, all in an effort to rid Pec of its
overwhelmingly ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the worst killing during the Serb campaign to drive
ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo. More died in Kosovo Liberation Army
strongholds such as Djakovica and Drenica, where the Yugoslav
military hit the ethnic Albanian fighters where their families
lived. But what took place in Pec was a crusade, led by civilians,
to reclaim a cherished land, and it was in many ways less of a
bloody conflict but more of a methodical hate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Connecting the dots in this criminal enterprise is a daunting
task that now falls on the shoulders of hundreds of human rights
workers and investigators who will be funneling a torrent of
information to the International War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague.
The tribunal hopes to build on the indictments already issued for
Milosevic and four of his regime's top officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Pec, the investigators have a rich harvest of hate to
unearth.
</P>
<P>
   Javad Zekaj, an ethnic Albanian lawyer turned investigator for a
municipal tribunal taking shape at the Kosovo Liberation Army's Pec
headquarters, pored through piles of documents and photographs last
week. They had been seized in recent days by the KLA from homes and
offices of Pec's most feared paramilitary leaders. Weeks earlier,
Zekaj and other community leaders had begun by taking testimony
from witnesses in the muddy refugee camps in Albania and Macedonia,
working to build a body of information that they are now in the
process of bolstering before they hand it over to the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Documents from police headquarters, hundreds of witness'
testimonies, and photographs put faces and names on the evils
perpetrated in Milosevic's name.
</P>
<P>
   Svetkovic and others like him were bit players in a
well-orchestrated campaign. There were dozens of civilians like him
in Pec who went neighborhood to neighborhood to inflict terror on
their ethnic Albanian neighbors and drive them from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   They became the local guides for the more professional killers
in paramilitary groups like the shadowy ``Frenkis,'' who were
recruited among veterans of the 1992 war in Bosnia for their
well-honed skills at ``ethnic cleansing.'' The ``Frenkis'' got
their name from Franko ``Frenki'' Simatovic, a leader of covert
operations in the Interior Ministry police. Rumors abound that he
was killed by the KLA in Pec, but they have not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   They call themselves ``Frenki's Boys,'' and Svetkovic was proud
to be one of the boys. He was a mechanic in the state-run public
transportation garage. Despite his friendship with Liria Gashi, he
was a man long known for his virulent hatred for the few ethnic
Albanians whom he had not yet fired from their positions at the
garage, according to those who worked with him. He had a penchant
for playing loud Serbian nationalist songs in his neighborhood, and
screaming at children playing near his courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Svetkovic and his minions were organized by a regional commander
of the MUPs, Col. Vlahovic Boriskiv, according to Atem Qeku, the
KLA's chief of logistical operations in Pec and the newly appointed
municipal prefect of Pec's provisional government. He is among
those piecing together the operational structure of the
paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Boriskiv became the liaison with the Belgrade regime's Minister
of Interior, Vlajko Stojiljkovic, who was indicted along with
Milosevic by the Hague tribunal last month, Qeku explained.
</P>
<P>
   The minister's signature appears on hundreds of police reports
documenting the arrest of ethnic Albanian civilians who were pulled
off of tractors and buses in late March as they tried to flee to
refugee camps amid the stepped-up NATO bombing. There are hundreds
of these men and women still missing, and their families hope they
are being held in Serb prisons, and not among those killed and
dumped in the mass graves being unearthed around Kosovo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A ``terrorist suspect''
</P>
<P>
   Agim Shoshi, a 62-year-old farmer, was among those whose arrest
warrant Stojiljkovic signed. Shoshi was among 87 people from Pec
who were pulled out of a convoy that left Pec on March 27. The
police reports on the arrests are all stamped ``terrorist
suspect,'' but offer no supporting information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were beaten. We were not fed for weeks,'' he said of the
three months of captivity that began in Pec before he was
transferred to a prison in Serbia. ``I think there are many who
have been killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pale and gaunt, with his head shaved, Shoshi was among 166
prisoners released earlier this week by the International Committee
of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
