<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE SURE YOUR CAMPER KEEPS SMILING AFTER VISITING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though this will be the eighth year she's gone to an Aloha
Foundation camp in Vermont, Lizzie Owens of Boston still looks
forward to Parents' Weekend practically from the moment she
arrives. She also anticipates the night after the weekend is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always hear girls crying into their pillows,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Even Lizzie, who is 15 and loves camp, has succumbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having your parents visit has gotten easier as I'm older,''
she says, ``but I'm always a little sad afterwards. I don't usually
cry right away after they leave, but that night it usually hits me
that I won't see them again for 3 1/2 weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the overnight camp season has barely begun,
anticipation of a reunion is already building for campers and
parents alike. For all the joy visiting day brings, there is also
potential for unhappiness: a sense of loss for parents at not
witnessing a child's growth and of sadness for a child who has to
muddle through yet another goodbye. Unfortunately, parents can
inadvertently set the stage for difficulty, sometimes long before
we get there, sometimes at the onset of a visit.
</P>
<P>
   The typical mistake we make is in response to an early homesick
letter when we write back something like this: ``Hang in there
until visiting day, honey. If you're still sad, we'll take you
home.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a problem for two reasons, says Christopher Thurber, a
University of Washington/Seattle psychologist and researcher who
has tracked 4,000 campers over six years:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Resisting parental urges
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --It fails to acknowledge how normal homesickness is. ``It's the
rare child who doesn't feel some homesickness during a camp stay,
ranging from fleeting feelings he can manage on his own to dramatic
upset that needs staff intervention,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a camper manages it alone, sadness may resurface on
visiting day. ``Kids have settled into a routine as well as a
mindset of functioning autonomously. As much as they want to share
everything with you, as much as this is a day of celebration, it is
also a day of interruption,'' says psychologist and camp consultant
Bruce Muchnick, of Glenside, Pa. Even if you don't talk about
what's going on at home _ and it's best to keep such conversation
very low-key _ you are a reminder of what they are missing out on,
from favorite food to family fun.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true for first-time campers, says Posie
Taylor, executive director of the nonprofit Aloha Foundation, which
operates five summer camps and a year-round outdoor program in
Fairlee, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first said goodbye to parents, they had heard of
homesickness, but they didn't really know what it was,'' she says.
``Now they do. As visiting day approaches or as it comes to an end,
they worry: `Am I going to have that awful feeling again?' '' The
anticipation can click in any time during the visit, making a child
clingy, scared, and unhappy to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   --It undermines the goal of camp to foster independence and
undermines a child's self-confidence. ``It's as if you are saying,
`When you experience this developmentally normal feeling, you won't
be able to cope. I'll rescue you,' '' says Thurber. His advice,
which is echoed by other psychologists and camp directors, is
simple: Don't make deals or promises.
</P>
<P>
   It's equally inappropriate, however, to make light of
homesickness in a letter _ ``It'll pass'' _ or to brush it away on
your visit: ``You'll be fine as soon as we leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Davis, New England director of parent education for the
American Camp Association, says the best response validates a
child's feeling and expresses confidence in her ability to handle
it: ``I know you've had some moments of sadness. Camp is full of
ups and downs; that's part of the learning experience.'' ``I can
tell saying goodbye is stirring up feelings for you. You coped
pretty well the first time. How did you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting on the right foot
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How the visit begins can often determine how it will end.
</P>
<P>
   Timeliness is critical. ``Children attach meaning to it if you
are late,'' says Thurber. ``It feels like you aren't making an
effort. This is not like being late to a soccer game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lizzie Owens remembers being 8 or 9 and waiting and watching
while everyone else's parents arrived. ``I started to have thoughts
that maybe they weren't coming or didn't want to come or that
something bad had happened,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor says there is nothing sadder than a child whose parents
are late. ``If the visiting time starts at 10 and your flight gets
in at 12, make sure your child knows that in advance. If you're
running late that day, call,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Inappropriate expectations can also ruin a visit for you or your
child, says Muchnick: ``If a kid is expecting to see the dog and
you don't bring him, that's disappointing.'' For parents, he warns,
``Don't look for dramatic changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Because one of the goals of overnight camp is to empower a child
to make his own decisions, Muchnick also tells parents to keep it
to yourself if you're unhappy about his choice of activities or
surprised he hasn't made more progress in an activity. ``If you
voice those thoughts,'' he says, ``it's like saying, `I thought you
could make good decisions, but obviously you can't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Thurber urges avoiding judgmental comments of any kind,
even seemingly factual ones like, ``I can't believe how dusty
everything is!'' At one extreme, you run the risk of putting
distance between you and your child: ``There goes Mom again . . .''
At the other, you could dampen his enthusiasm: ``Dad's right. How
could I ever have thought this was fun?''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is convinced that what's hardest for parents is seeing
that their child can thrive without them. ``It feels as if you
aren't important,'' she says. As human as that response is, it's an
inaccurate perception. Don't act on it, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you feel a sense of loss, avoid saying something like,
`I'm so sad I wasn't there to see your first no-hitter,' '' she
says. ``On the other hand, there's nothing wrong with saying, `That
makes me so proud of you, I'm tearing up!' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visiting day is here to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite the many challenges to visiting day, no one seems
interested in doing away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an excitement in the air for days beforehand,'' says
Lizzie Owens. ``I kinda like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor says the benefits _ giving children a chance to share
growth and experiences with parents and reassuring parents that
children are safe, healthy, and thriving _ far outweigh the
challenge of having to redo the departure. And she says the
departure doesn't have to be hard if parents keep it loving, brief,
and firm.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a child is not sad as you leave, but definitely if she
is, Taylor urges parents to let a counselor know that you're going.
``I never like to see a child standing by herself waving goodbye,''
she says. ``I like to see her waving goodbye with a counselor
standing at her side with an arm around her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --If you know in advance you can't attend visiting day, your
child should know in advance, too. Can someone go in your stead? If
not, let the camp know.
</P>
<P>
   --If you have something sad to tell your child _ a relative is
sick, a pet has died _ do it at the beginning of the visit. Not
wanting to spoil your time together and thus waiting until you're
leaving to tell him isn't respectful, and it means a counselor is
the person helping your child process the information instead of
you. (If something really dramatic happens at home, a death of a
grandparent, for instance, most directors prefer that parents come
to camp to tell a child and temporarily take him home if that's
appropriate.)
</P>
<P>
   --While a child who has been homesick at the beginning is most
likely to be sad to see you leave at visiting day, Pam Cobb,
director of Camp Runoia in Belgrade Lakes, Maine, says her staff
anticipates a temporary change of mood in most children after
visiting day. ``It can be challenging even for a kid who has been
well integrated,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   --If anything worries or upsets you during the visit, from how
equipment is used to the choice of activity, talk to the counselor
or director. Don't share misgivings with your child.
</P>
<P>
   --Follow the camp's guidelines about visiting day, including
whether and what kind of food to bring. Don't arrive earlier than
requested, don't visit unexpectedly, and think twice before
bringing an extended-family member with you, especially someone who
needs your attention or help. It can make the visit frustrating if
you feel torn, having to tend to this person.
</P>
<P>
   --Many camps make accommodations for parents who are divorced
and prefer not to visit at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   --What to say to a child who wants to go home with you: ``I'll
miss you, too. I'm looking forward to seeing you in two weeks.''
``Saying goodbye is hard, but we all made a commitment for you to
stay for four weeks.'' ``I'm not surprised part of you feels as if
you'd like to spend more time with us. I'll be anxious for your
next letter to see how tennis is going.''
</P>
<P>
   --If you are seriously considering taking your child home,
consult with the camp director first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ A minimum of 20 minutes' reading a day helps
children of all ages not lose ground academically over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
