<HEADLINE>
IF MONEY WERE NO OBJECT, 50 DREAM MACHINES TO BUY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm very rich. So rich, Bill Gates asked me to cosign the
construction loan on the palace he is building in Washington State;
Michael Jordan asked for a loan after a bad round of golf; Tiger
Woods called to see if I could front him some walking-around money
when the Ryder Cup comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   So rich, my accountant just told me, I should go spend a bunch
of money on cars, trucks and motorcycles. Fifty of them, he
recommended; the 50 I'd take from this closing century.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go shopping, not by rank but just what might look good in
the big barn we'll build to store them all:
</P>
<P>
   1. 1925 Ford Model T.
</P>
<P>
   2. 1928 Model A Ford Roadster pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   3. A 1932 Ford three-window highboy coupe _ turned hot rod. Just
saw one for sale with a 433-cubic inch engine that delivers 750
horespower.
</P>
<P>
   4. 1934 Ford five-window coupe.
</P>
<P>
   5. 1953 Hudson Hornet with Twin-H power, twin carbs, set up for
210 horsepower, just like at Daytona way back when.
</P>
<P>
   6. 1951 Henry J. No glove compartment, no trunk, two doors.
Spartan and ahead of its time.
</P>
<P>
   7. 1957 Thunderbird. In '58, it got ugly.
</P>
<P>
   8. 1957 Corvette. A nice bookend to above.
</P>
<P>
   9. 1959 BMW 507 Series II 3.2 liter. Two seats, ragtop, heaven.
</P>
<P>
   10. 1957 Cadillac Eldorado Brougham. Four doors, but pillarless;
sharp tailfins, brushed aluminum roof.
</P>
<P>
   11. 1936 Harley-Davidson EL, the wonderful Knucklehead engine
and a springer front end.
</P>
<P>
   12. 1952 Vincent Black Shadow. Top speed, 125. Danger.
</P>
<P>
   13. 1937 Indian Chief, made in Springfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   14. 1969 BSA 441-cc Victor. A one-lunger with yellow and brushed
aluminum tank.
</P>
<P>
   15. Another Springfield bike, the Indian 442, last of the
four-cylinder Indians.
</P>
<P>
   16. 1932 Auburn Boattail Speedster.
</P>
<P>
   17. 1937 Cord 812 Phaeton.
</P>
<P>
   18. 1930 Duesenberg Model J Derham Tourster.
</P>
<P>
   19. 1930 Bugatti Royale. Spitting in the face of the Great
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   20. 1946 MG TC. Electrical woes? What, me worry?
</P>
<P>
   21. 1956 Mercedes Benz 300 SL Gullwing
</P>
<P>
   22. 1962 Jaguar XKE 3.8-liter roadster. In British Racing Green,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   23. 1958 Ferrari 250 Testa Rossa.
</P>
<P>
   24. 1944 Volkswagen Schwimmwagen. Did you know VW made a car tht
floated and had propellors?
</P>
<P>
   25. 1950 VW Hebmueller. Only 750 of these two-seat convertibles
survived after the factory burned and the line was discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   26. 1958 Volkswagen convertible. Hey, this Bug was my first car.
Paid 95 large for it. I want it back.
</P>
<P>
   27. 1947 John Deere Model B tractor, the ``Late Styled B.''
We'll cheat here and add a second vehicle, the 1939 Model H Deere _
smaller, good for the kids to play on.
</P>
<P>
   28. 1946 Ford Woody Wagon.
</P>
<P>
   29. 1957 Willys wagon.
</P>
<P>
   30. 1965 Dodge Dart GT with the indestructible Slant-6 engine.
</P>
<P>
   31. 1967 Chevelle SS 396 with 350 horspower. Work those muscle
cars.
</P>
<P>
   32. Out of the Mustang corral: a 1969 Shelby GT 350.
</P>
<P>
   33. 1966 Plymouth Hemi Satellite. Looks innocent, but try to
beat its 426 cubic inches away from a light.
</P>
<P>
   34. 1970 Plymouth Barrcuda, 440 Hemi Convertible. An
underappreciated automobile.
</P>
<P>
   35. 1965 Pontiac GTO hard top, with the 389, please.
</P>
<P>
   36. 1966 Shelby/AC 427 Cobra.
</P>
<P>
   37. Slow down. Peace, love and understanding (plus large bucks):
a 23-window, 1967 Volkswagen bus.
</P>
<P>
   38. 1999 Land Rover Defender. Still has that old Land Rover look
to it.
</P>
<P>
   39. 1972 Toyota Landcruiser, back when it was a short box.
</P>
<P>
   40. 1999 Porsche 996 Cabriolet.
</P>
<P>
   41. 1999 BMW M Coupe. Ugly, but a blast to drive; so ugly it
will be a collector's item some day.
</P>
<P>
   42. 2000 Toyota Tundra; V-8 power, Toyota reliability, in a
pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   43. 2000 Ford SVT F-150 Lightning. When is a pickup truck not a
pickup truck, despite that bed on the back? When it does 0-60 in
5.6 seconds, riding 360 horses and 440 lbs./ft. of torque.
</P>
<P>
   44. 1999 G500 Gelaendewagen by Mercedes-Benz. The $150,000-plus
SUV. Hey, I'm rich.
</P>
<P>
   45. 1999 Dodge Viper RT/10
</P>
<P>
   46. 1997 Aston-Martin DB7.
</P>
<P>
   47. 1998 Saleen Mustang
</P>
<P>
   48. 1998 Lamborghini Diablo roadster. Just to go to the store
for bread.
</P>
<P>
   49. 1999 Ferrari F355 Spyder. Oops, forgot the milk.
</P>
<P>
   50. 1955 Porsche Spyder 550. A reminder that speed can kill.
See: DEAN, JAMES.
</P>
<P>
   If you have read this far, you are a car nut. So let's spend
some more money. Write or e-mail me, including your name and
hometown, with the car you think I should never have left off my
list or the car or cars you'd buy. We'll have a fanatasy shopping
day for readers.
</P>
