<HEADLINE>
JAIR: BACK IN THE MIDDLE OF THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether the subject is politics or soccer, Jair seems like
anything but a right winger.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where Jair found himself at the start of the year.
Nearly half the Revolution season has gone by, but Jair finally
finds himself back where he belongs as the team prepares for
Sunday's game against the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two games, a 3-2 win at Tampa Bay and a 2-0 loss at
Dallas, Jair has been in a central midfield position, the best
platform for him to display his creativity.
</P>
<P>
   And with Edwin Gorter having been traded to Miami, the position
appears to be Jair's for the duration of the season _ especially if
he continues to develop a rapport with John Harkes, who is
questionable to return from a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches haven't told me anything,'' Jair said. ``But I'm
willing to take responsibility for wherever I play. For me to be at
my best, I have to get the ball. But we all are doing whatever we
have to do for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Revolution game plan is about sacrifice. Strikers
are defending, midfielders are pressing. But there have been
moments of inspiration, and Jair has been involved in a couple of
them with Joe-Max Moore in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Against Tampa Bay, Jair finished a move in which Mutiny
defenders were tripping over themselves as he scored his first goal
of the season. At Dallas, though, the Burn's Leonel Alvarez
displayed a little more savvy and ruthlessness. After Jair and
Moore played a skillful give-and-go in a tight space, Alvarez
simply hacked down Jair from behind, short-circuiting the
connection and taking Jair out of action for several minutes early
in the second half. (The combination of Jair's moderate
personality, Alvarez's eccentricity, and a refereeing blunder led
to no foul being called.)
</P>
<P>
   The play might have produced painful reminders of last season,
when Jair broke his left ankle in May and missed three months of
action.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the type of treatment to expect once a player
becomes a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of the responsibility,'' Jair said. ``I feel
very comfortable playing where I am and very confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for me at the beginning of the season. But
things are better now and I'm 100 percent. I don't think about the
injury any more at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution are in third place in the Eastern Conference with
15 points in 15 matches. They have won only four games in
regulation time but they have lost only four times in regulation.
They will be expected to win against the MetroStars, who have
earned only 8 points and have a six-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``In soccer, you can never say there is a weak team,'' Jair
said. ``The important thing is to respect the other team, and for
us it is important to win at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important game for us because if we win we will
have 18 points, 10 more than they have, halfway through the season.
We are understanding each other better now and we all want to be
there in the final game, Nov. 21.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who leads the Revolution with six goals, has been
selected to a 27-player US national team roster to prepare for the
Confederations Cup, scheduled July 24-Aug. 4 in Mexico. Moore will
remain with the Revolution through the July 11 match against Los
Angeles, then join the US for an exhibition against Derby County
July 13 in Denver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
