<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARNISH WON'T HELP PAINT LAST LONGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I just finished painting my porch floor with two coats of
latex decking paint. Can I varnish that finish to protect it? Also,
the stairway to the porch is pressure-treated, and the 2 x 8
railings are splintering. The railings are made in such a way that
I cannot substitute a smaller or properly shaped railing. Right now
they are a hazard to anyone using them. My painter suggested
sanding, staining, and varnishing the rails.
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY FLANNERY, Canton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can varnish the latex paint, but it won't do any good
because the paint is its own protection. And, it might do some
harm, because any varnish (exterior polyurethane, spar or marine
varnish) is notorious for peeling and doesn't stand up as well as
the paint. The paint may peel, too. If it does, remove it all and
apply a semitransparent stain; only one coat is needed every five
years or so, and it will not peel.
</P>
<P>
   As for the railing, it splintered because it shrank when it
dried out, and I don't think any treatment will help much. However,
you can try one of several approaches:
</P>
<P>
   --Substitute the rail with a 54 pressure-treated floorboard.
This board is only 5 1/2 inches wide but a full inch thick, and
while it is 2 inches narrower than the 2 x 8, it still might be
appropriate as a substitute. It is of a better quality wood than
most other pressure-treated boards, and may splinter less or not at
all. Apply one coat of a semitransparent stain every five years.
</P>
<P>
   --Substitute a quality pine 2 x 8 for the rail, and stain it. A
good piece of pine like that, with rounded edges and kept stained,
will be much less likely to splinter.
</P>
<P>
   --Buy a regular hardwood rail, usually made of oak or birch, and
designed for indoor staircases. Get the one that is higher than it
is wide, and mount it on the 2 x 8 rail. It is much more easily
grabbed, without splinters. Keep such a rail stained with
semitransparent stain because it is made of glued laminates;
unprotected, these laminates will come loose in wet weather. If you
can find a rail that is not laminated, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I lighten my knotty pine paneling, which has become
quite dark over the years?
</P>
<P>
   IN THE DARK
</P>
<P>
   A. Wood will darken with age, whether it is under varnish,
stain, or paint, or left bare. You could paint it, but painting is
iffy because you would have to shellac all the knots to keep them
from bleeding through the paint.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to keep the wood looking natural, you have to remove
the old finish, usually by sanding, to the bare wood. Then apply
two thin coats of a water-based or oil-based polyurethane varnish.
The water-based varnish is OK to use in this instance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a number of windows in my cellar for summer
ventilation to prevent moisture buildup, but the inside grates
(burglar bars) prevent me from getting to the inside latches. Can I
cut out a glass panel and make an outside door?
</P>
<P>
   VERA GROPPER, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You also need screens to keep out bugs in summer, which
complicates the opening and closing of the windows. But opened they
must be in summer. You could install a door in one of the glass
panels; it might work if the window frame is wood, not metal.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, try attaching a hook to a short pole, so that you can
reach and turn the latch. The windows do not have to be open fully;
halfway will be sufficient. Or, reverse the latch so it can be
opened from the outside. The burlgar bars will still keep out
unwanted critters, two- or four-legged.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5986 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-SQUAD-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     07-01 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-SQUAD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 PEC, Yugoslavia: ... Red Cross.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As of Friday, he was the only prisoner from Pec to have
returned.
</P>
<P>
   One of Stojiljkovic's top henchmen in the MUPs was Marinko
Jukic, who was also president of the Pec branch of Milosevic's
Socialist Party of Serbia. He is alleged by the investigators to
have been a conduit for financing the paramilitaries' weapons,
ammunition, and logistical support. Seized from his home, in a file
marked ``financing,'' was a red plastic-bound collection of
business cards of Belgrade's top executives in state-run industries
ranging from food processing to construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb thugs who were supported by and took orders from these
men are profiles of sadism and hate.
</P>
<P>
   One was Vidosav Shalipur, a police officer in his early 30s, who
waged a Ku Klux Klan-like campaign of beating, terror, and killing
against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   He is alleged by KLA investigators to have tortured a crippled
youth from Pec after he was kidnapped off the streets as a
suspected KLA supporter. Shalipur is alleged to have made the
youth, who is missing a leg, dance to Serbian nationalist songs in
a detention center before beating him so hard he is now missing
most of his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The detention center was raided by NATO last week and revealed a
torture chamber with a wooden chair fashioned to inflict pain and
connected by bicycle brake cables to an electrical generator. But
Salipur is believed to have had his reckoning. The KLA claims it
assasinated him with a rocket propelled-grenade during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Serb paramilitaries had a taste for cheap sunglasses
and black leather jackets, and a fondness for Mercedes Benz
convertibles and four-wheel drive vehicles stolen from Pec's
prosperous and sophisticated upper class of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Shalipur was hardly unique. Documents, witness accounts, and
photographs yield portraits of many other Serb paramilitary figures
in Pec, most of whom have fled to Serbia and Montenegro. One of
them was Predrag Vlavoic. &QL; 
 &QL; 
With a gun and a cross
</P>
<P>
   Predrag Vlavovic, 25, was the local leader of a loosely
organized paramilitary group made up mostly of civlians and known
as the ``Black Hand.'' The group operated on the fringes and was
particularly sadistic. Known for wearing a large Serbian Orthodox
cross around his neck and executing his victims with a 9 mm pistol,
Vlavovic has been accused of dozens of killings and rapes. The KLA
claims he assisted Zvetkovic's ``Frenkis'' unit in killing 45
people at the village of Cushk.
</P>
<P>
   Zekaj, the Albanian lawyer, said several women have told him and
investigators for the Hague tribunal that Vlavovic was among the
men who raped them at a two-story, stucco house of horrors that was
once an ethnic Albanian-run establishment in Pec known as the
Karagaq Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In a room in the back of the hotel is a black leather-padded
door and a sign marked ``private.'' Behind it are piles of debris
that include a white lace women's undershirt stained by dried
blood, womens' underwear, pornography, paramilitary uniforms, and
condoms, which KLA soldiers say they're leaving in place for
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neshad Asllani, a prominent Pec physician and vice president
of the Council for Defense of Human Rights and Freedom founded 10
years ago, said, ``It will take time for the women to come forward.
But the evidence is mounting. We may not apprehend these criminals,
but if they ever return they will be brought to justice.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The man known as ``death''
</P>
<P>
   Nebojsha Minic _ known by his nickname ``Smert,'' which
translates as ``Death'' _ a 38-year-old, native of Pec, was the
local leader of the paramilitary unit known as Arkan's Tigers. The
group is headed by the Zeljko Ravnatovic, a war criminal convicted
in absentia by the Hague tribunal and better known as ``Arkan.'' He
has close ties to Milosevic and a large financial interest in
various state-run businesses, especially hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Minic was also a active in Milosevic's Socialist Party, known as
SPS. One photograph shows him raising a bottle of plum brandy with
a menacing smile and long curly hair.
</P>
<P>
   He moved from neighboring Montenegro back to Pec around 1989
along with his father and brother, as Milosevic's campaign of
against ethnic Albanians began. Arrest records found in his home
show he had been convicted of fraud and assault, including the
beating of an ethnic Albanian woman in Djakovica in 1988. His
father and brother were members of the MUPs, the investigators say,
reflecting a pattern in which civilian paramilitaries were often
recruited from police families. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Why Pec?
</P>
<P>
   The reason the campaign against Albanians was so unsparing here
lies in Pec's history. Set in the dramatic landscape of the Rugova
Gorge, the city is the seat of the Serbian Orthodox Church. Serbs
frequently call it their Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Serb homes in the rolling hills of wheat fields clustered around
historical churches were untouched, even by the NATO bombing. The
devastation was all in the center of Pec, a jewel for the ethnic
Albanians, and is generally regarded as the seat of Kosovar
Albanians' rich heritage as well.
</P>
<P>
   The methodical campaign to remove Kosovar Albanians from Pec
began years ago, as Milosevic ordered them fired them from their
jobs and replaced them with Serbs. Belgrade ordered construction of
new churches around Pec as part of an effort to reclaim the land
for Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The killing began in December 1998. The paramilitaries started
with Pec's most prominent doctors, lawyers, and business men. They
were abducted, killed, and their bodies dumped on the main street
and left for hours before police responded. It was meant to send a
message. By the time the NATO raids began on March 24, the killing
was becoming wide-scale, a slaughter of whole families and
villages.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian Kosovars are begining to return, but they come at a
pace much slower than the rest of Kosovo because there is simply
nowhere to live. Only 15 percent of greater Pec's 120,000 residents
have come back, compared to the 50 percent who have returned to
much of the rest of Kosovo. They come home to a city more ravaged
then they expected, and to haunting nightmares of the men who
carried it out.
</P>
<P>
   But those who have returned are turning their rage on the few
remaining Serbs in perhaps the most intense revenge campaign in
Kosovo. Every night this week, Serb villages and homes, especially
those owned by paramilitaries, have been engulfed by flames. They
lit up the night, and by morning left smoldering plumes of smoke in
the Serb hill towns that surround Pec.
</P>
<P>
   And now Pec, a beloved homeland to both Serbs and ethnic
Albanians, has been nearly burned to the ground _ by both sides in
the conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
