<HEADER>
A5987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-     07-01 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOGGING ON TO THE LOVE-IN AT WOODSTOCK.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Woodstock.com is more than just a Web site: It's a virtual
nation-state, complete with its own population of preachers and
politicians, leaders and latchers-on, hawkers and hooligans. And by
the time they get to Woodstock '99, these cybercitizens will be
connected in ways that the hippies who trudged to the legendary
festival in upstate New York 30 years ago could never have
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The live concert, featuring more than three dozen bands and set
for July 23-26 at Griffiss Park in Rome, N.Y., is a still a month
away, but pilgrims whose starting points range from Methuen to
Milwaukee are already forging friendships, sparking romances, and
building miniature communities.
</P>
<P>
   It's the '90s equivalent of a love-in, and it's happening on
line.
</P>
<P>
   Folks are convening in the Woodstock.com chat room, dishing out
the usual ``What are you wearing?'' and ``Where are you from?''
inanities. They're carping about concert management and complaining
about Aerosmith cancelling. They're forming car pools and arranging
rendezvous. And they're organizing ``tent circles,'' a phenomenon
that belongs to the cyber generation.
</P>
<P>
   A tent circle is a community of like-minded people who meet on
line; at the concert campground, they will pitch their tents in a
circle. One group plans to mark its site with a Winnie-the-Pooh
flag; another group will display a giant Gumby doll. There's a tent
circle for sober celebrants and another congregation of people over
25; both groups have adopted rules to maintain sanity and safety.
``I want to go and have fun, but I don't want to hang around with a
bunch of 18-year-old puking idiots,'' says Lynne Taylor, 28, of
Methuen, who signed up with the Over-25 Road Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   One group calls itself the Milwaukee Party Swingers; another
crowd of Jim Morrison fans goes by the name the Lizard Kingdom. ``I
don't want to say the music takes a back seat, but it's all about
meeting people,'' says Chris Myden, 20, a Calgary native who
launched an on-line Woodstock registry where people can post their
photos and profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Few of these concertgoers wax nostalgic about peace, love, and
tie-dye or about music that aims to change the world. Most of them
weren't even born in 1969, the year of the first festival, and many
of them didn't attend the 25th anniversary extravaganza in 1994.
The only throwback to the '60s era comes from the Lizard Kingdom
folks, who describe their tent circle as a place ``where everyone
can experience and celebrate their soul, a place where you can be
your true self...free from the confines of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Misty metaphysics aside, both the concert and its official Web
site are places where everyone, even the Lizard King, is a
potential consumer. On the Web site, you can buy your camping
equipment from a local hardware store, purchase a transportation
package, or buy T-shirts and other concert paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   No, McLachlan isn't appearing at Woodstock '99, and the ``live''
performance was recorded last year. The site is positioning itself
for a life after Woodstock, and the pay-per-view event is a way to
lure festival groupies to come back when the tents are folded up
and the concert is over.
</P>
<P>
   The times, they are 'a changing, and we're not talking about
music or politics. We're talking about the Internet. Back in 1994,
when the World Wide Web was dawning, there were a few sites and
bulletin boards devoted to Woodstock II. Today, they seem terribly
quaint, grainy text pages counting down to the event.
</P>
<P>
   But now everything on the Web is about commerce: Woodstock.com
is a thinly disguised launching pad for a music portal site that
will combine commerce, news, and entertainment. ``Think of it as an
environment full of rich content that people will enjoy,'' says
Rand Bleimeister, chief executive officer of Music now, which owns
Woodstock.com. In the near future, the site is going to start
offering free e-mail and free home pages, along with an on-line
radio station.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the site is incredibly popular with pilgrims seeking
companionship; Bleimeister says it gets about 20,000 hits a day.
But it's not without its detractors. One user who calls himself the
Minister of Edutainment says he doesn't care about ``songwriter
news or all the boring music stuff.'' The organizer of the over-25
group is boycotting the site's bulletin boards because they are
riddled with profanity and personal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The nation state is already having its own little rebellion of
sorts, but for the most part, the site is embraced by its avid
population. The tent circle phenomenon is a first, a harbinger of
future festivals. But the members of this cyber community aren't
naive; they grew up on-line, and they know that cyber dreams are
easily burst. ``Everyone is beautiful in the virtual world,'' says
Steve Julius, organizer of the Milwaukee group, laughing. ``It
doesn't always work out that way in real life.'' Send that man to
the Lizard Kingdom circle, where he can be freed from the
``confines of reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
