   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   SUPER: Kansas City superintendent-designate Jay Edwards ponders
whether he will accept a contract with the Kansas City school board
and meets the public at a series of community meetings. Photo.
Tanika White.
</P>
<P>
   FIFI (with SUPER): Board member Fifi Wiedeman has emerged as the
whipping girl in deliberations to pick a new superintendent. She's
criticized her fellow board members and called for an appointed
board. They passed a resolution, agreeing to write a letter asking
Judge Whipple to censure her. And district lawyers have written the
board, saying that if members don't stop making controversial
statements, he just might put the district in receivership. Tanika
White and Lynn Horsley.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE: We look at all the shake-up in University of
Missouri-Kansas City's administrative ranks, and the university's
outside searches for the two top leaders _ chancellor and provost _
and why the change is occurring and what it will mean for the
faculty and students, as well as the university's reputation in
Kansas City. Lynn Franey. 25.
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGE. The 151st Street bridge over I-35 in Olathe, Kan., has
serious problems and may need a $3 million fix; kind of steep for a
bridge that cost less than $4 million when it opened in 1994; seems
the bridge, which sits on rockers to allow for expansion and
contraction, is being pushed by slippage in its abutments;
engineers fear the bridge won't be able to handle normal stresses
if it slips much more. Robert A. Cronkleton. Graphic, Photos.
</P>
<P>
   CHERN. It was a struggle for 9-year-old Tonya Khvitko to walk
two years ago when she first visited Kansas City. Tonya, of
Belarus, was born with one leg that ended at the ankle and one that
stopped above the knee, probably the result of radiation from the
Chernobyl power plant disaster in 1986. Now she enjoys running and
riding bikes, thanks to more than $12,000 worth of prostheses from
Project Restoration. Stacy Downs. 18. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ISLAM: To celebrate its success in Kansas City, Kan., the United
Nation of Islam is having a three-day Unity Festival, centered
along Quindaro Boulevard this weekend. The group is using KCK as a
pilot project for other central city developments and has several
businesses operating, including a diner and gas station, and is
opening a donut shop soon. Steve Nicely. 20 to 25. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR. This month's weather has caused more than inconvenience
to Kansas City drivers. It probably also means Kansas City won't be
watching NASCAR drivers here next year. Because of the inclimate
weather, it appears the KCK track will not be completed in time for
officials to lobby for a 2000 race. With reaction from track and
city folks. Pedley. 15-18.
</P>
<P>
   WWC. Women's World Cup quarterfinal game: United States vs.
Germany. 6 p.m. at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium. Another victory and the
Americans will face off Sunday in San Jose for a chance to play in
the World Cup final. Mechelle Voepel. 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Chicago White Sox at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m. Dick Kaegel.
16-18.
</P>
<P>
   1STGAME. Carl Amen of Brookfield, Mo., is 93 years old and has
never been to a Royals game. That will change Thursday. For his
most recent birthday, Amen received tickets from his granddaughter,
and the family is heading out to Kauffman to watch the Royals play
the White Sox. Heather Dinich. 14-16.
</P>
