<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WIN FOR GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gambling has triumphed. This is what one takes away after
reading the report of the National Gambling Impact Study
Commission, which two weeks ago released the results of its
three-year inquiry into the state of gambling in America.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, gambling of one form or another (usually lotteries and
derivative games) is now permitted in 47 states and the District of
Columbia. It is thriving on Indian reservations. And regulations
and restrictions on the gambling industry have been dramatically
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, gambling is now seen as just another form of
``family entertainment,'' like going to the movies or visiting a
theme park. This did not happen by accident. Private gambling
interests have spent hundreds of millions of dollars reconfiguring
the industry's image (it's ``gaming,'' not gambling, and it's fun).
These efforts have been successful beyond expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, state governments have become addicted to the
revenue gambling provides. In the last 25 years, those revenues
have grown from $2 billion to $34 billion. Based on the reliability
of this stream of money, states now use these revenues as
collateral for bond issues.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in public opinion toward gambling is so profound that
state governments are now its single largest promoters. They spend
more than $400 million annually advertising lotteries and other
``card'' games. ($400 million is roughly the same amount of money
that Budweiser spends to advertise all of its various beers every
year). And these advertising budgets will only increase in the
years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows this is wrong. Lotteries are regressive taxation
at its worst. Gambling brings with it a host of social pathologies
that have real and sometimes devastating consequences for those who
get caught up in its maelstrom. And the promise made is entirely
false. To paraphrase the ad for E Trade: ``Someone's going to win.
It just won't be you.''
</P>
<P>
   But knowing something is wrong and doing something about it are
two different things. The Commission made 76 specific
recommendations regarding gambling in the future. They include an
outright ban on Internet gambling, a prohibition on college and
amateur sports wagering and a tax on gambling activities to help
cover medical costs for ``problem gamblers.'' The Commission's
recommendations, however, carry no legal weight and are unlikely to
be adopted by the Congress and the current Administration. Both the
Republican Party and the Democratic Party have become dependent on
gambling industry campaign contributions. The likelihood that
either party will try to curtail the future growth of gambling is,
as they say in Las Vegas, a loser's bet.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph of gambling represents a stunning political and
cultural shift.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, gambling was a deadly political issue.
Liberal activists in the Democratic Party opposed it because it was
regressive taxation. Conservative activists in the Republican Party
opposed it on moral grounds. Any candidate trying to win a major
party nomination understood the politics and steered well clear of
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the only question is whether the gambling industry can
achieve its ultimate goal, which is to bring its games of chance
into every household in the world. Internet technology enables the
industry to do this and already it is hard at work developing this
capability.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an enormously attractive package, particularly for
non-gamblers. Gambling corporations would provide free Internet
access service, high-speed modems and a host of other
Internet-related perquisites _ all for free _ in exchange for some
minimum amount of money wagered on a monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
   They could package this with clever marketing and advertising as
a boon to the Internet industry and the economy as a whole. And
using the precise targeting methods that the Internet allows, they
could identify the most active gamblers across the country and
around the world and single them out for special treatment.
Eventually, of course, this would allow them to reach a much wider
audience on a more or less constant basis and thus triple and
perhaps quintuple their annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, non-gamblers would benefit from the very low-cost
or free Internet services provided by the gambling industry. Paying
$21 a month to America On Line may be worth it, but getting
Internet access and a high-speed modem from Harrah's for free is a
much better deal.
</P>
<P>
   Having erased the line in the sand that once kept gambling in
back office parlors and bookie joints, the gambling industry now
embarks on its greatest marketing effort ever; the expansion of
gambling through cyberspace. Judging by the industry's success over
the last twenty-five years, it is safe to say that Internet
gambling will be a reality by the end of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   This is not good news. It is not good for society. It is
antithetical to what used to be called ``the work ethic.'' And it
will reek havoc on millions of people who are dependent or related
to pathological gamblers. But it will happen, as surely as it is
true that you'll never win the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
