<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING GRAPHIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Like most journalists, I'm irresistibly drawn to tales of
conflict. I reveled in the browser wars between Microsoft Corp. and
Netscape Communications Corp. I thrill to Advanced Micro Devices
Inc.'s desperate campaign to seize a share of the microprocessor
market from mighty Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But for sheer blood-on-the-wallpaper viciousness, it's hard to
top the competition in 3D graphic accelerators _ the chips that let
fans of computer games like Quake slaughter one another with
maximum realism.
</P>
<P>
   Good computer 3D used to cost tens of thousands of dollars.
Today it's so cheap any home PC owner can afford it, and it's
getting cheaper and better by the month. Unlike the processor chip
market, where everybody waits for the next new idea from Intel,
there are a host of firms all trying different techniques to serve
up better graphics at lower cost. The result is a market that
resembles an old ``Mad Max'' movie. It's an apocalyptic struggle of
all against all, where even the product names radiate an aura of
menace.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, a firm called Cirrus Logic Inc.
practically owned the market with its ViRGE chips. Today, the
company barely has a pulse. S3 Inc. dominated for a while, then
cratered last year when the public rejected the company's Savage 3D
products. Up came ATI Technologies Inc. of Canada, with its Rage
accelerators. But ATI's reign is now imperiled by 3Dfx Interactive
Inc., whose Voodoo 3 products are presently number one at retail
stores. And S3, once given up for dead, is launching a massive
counterattack with its new Savage 4 chip, which is getting good
early reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The winners in this fearsome struggle are those who do the best
job of deceiving the rest of us. Graphic accelerators draw images
on a flat, two-dimensional computer screen that appear to have the
three-dimensional depth of the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Any sketch artist can trick your eye by drawing two-dimensional
objects that seem to have depth. A computer can do the same. But
what if you want to create the illusion of 3D images that move?
Your problem suddenly becomes a few million times more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Just move your own head and you'll see why. The relative
position of everything in the room changes, because your point of
view has changed. The only way a computer can emulate this effect
is by recalculating the position of every single dot of light on
the screen, using extremely complex math equations to make it all
look right.
</P>
<P>
   It gets far, far worse if you want the objects to move quickly
and smoothly, because then the computer must make all of these
calculations almost instantly. As a Quake player runs down a
virtual corridor, his computer must redraw every image on the
screen dozens of times a second, with no flicker, no delay.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop microprocessors couldn't begin to handle this kind of
load. So graphics firms make chips designed solely to do
three-dimensional math. They run at speeds once found only in Cray
supercomputers, yet graphics cards using these chips generally cost
well below $200.
</P>
<P>
   And as the leaders keep introducing newer and better chips, the
smaller players find it ever harder to keep up. A few years ago,
Number Nine Visual Technologies in Lexington seemed to be within
striking distance of the top-tier graphics players. Today, Number
Nine is only number 31 in market share, according to PC Data Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But the company hopes to pick up a few share points by basing
fewer products on its own accelerator chip and building more of
them around the Savage 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a smaller company, it's hard for us to come out with a
sustainable product,'' said general manager William Ralph.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to Number Nine, I got a glimpse of the
company's Savage 4 board working its magic on Quake. The 3D images
had all the murky grimness anyone could want, with smooth,
realistic movement. The price seemed even more impressive _ $109
list.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, compared with the computer images in films like ``Toy
Story'' or the new ``Star Wars,'' the Savage 4 and its desktop
rivals are still at the Model T stage.
</P>
<P>
   So graphics chip makers continue their relentless campaign of
improvements, constantly leapfrogging their rivals with even better
performance. It's like one of those computer games where victory
simply means staying alive _ my favorite kind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
