<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILLED-SPARERIBS-LAD     07-01 1845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLED-SPARERIBS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STICK TO YOUR RIBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(HAS ART)  
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Get ready to grill some succulent, tender, finger
lickin' good ribs for Independence Day feasting fare _ and make
them any way you like them. The most die-hard barbecuers generally
favor pork rather than beef ribs, but some grillers and diners will
put their money on big, meaty beef ribs. Suit yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Ribs have a certain mystique. Although messy and not the most
healthful of foods, they have a feverish following. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Few other smells are as welcoming as the smell of ribs slowly
cooking on the grill, roasting in the oven, or bubbling in a
delectable sauce,'' write Hugh Carpenter and Teri Sandison in ``The
Great Ribs Book'' (Ten Speed Press; $14.95).
</P>
<P>
   But lots of controversy surrounds rib cooking. Preferences,
cooking techniques and smoking times vary from cook to cook and
diner to diner, as well as among rib restaurants and different
regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Some like their ribs a bit chewy and crispy with just a hint of
sauce and lots of hickory flavor, while others like them moist and
tender, falling off the bone and laden with barbecue sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Some say slow, indirect (away from the heat), covered cooking on
a grill is the only way to go, while others rely on parboiling the
ribs stove-top before finishing up on the grill. Still other cooks
rid the ribs of excess fat _ known as degreasing _ by baking them
in the oven before grilling. Others rely on wrapping the ribs in
foil and slowly cooking them on the grill before turning them out
to finish grill-top.
</P>
<P>
   Some favor spice and herb rubs rather than sauces, but the
ultimate decision lies with the rib cook and the amount of time and
effort he or she wants to expend. Have patience, and don't rush the
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever route you take, keep this in mind. ``Rib meat is tough,
and it requires low heat and long cooking to break down the meat
fiber, render the fat and make the meat succulent and tender,'' say
Carpenter and Sandison. While the authors personally prefer pork
baby back ribs, which they refer to as ``the king of ribs,'' they
encourage cooks to feel free to substitute their favorite cuts in
recipes, regardless of what rib type is specified.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Alters Jamison and Bill Jamison, in their cookbook ``Born
to Grill, An American Celebration'' (Harvard Common Press; $27.95),
write: ``After testing a range of approaches to grilling ribs, we
finally settled on baking them first in an oven (generally wrapped
in foil with seasonings) or covered gas grill _ and then finishing
them over an open outdoor fire. Don't do the pre-cooking by boiling
or microwaving, as some people suggest, because you'll leave much
of the flavor in the kitchen in a pool of grease.''
</P>
<P>
   Both pork and beef ribs come in different styles and from
different sections of the animal. If you're undecided about which
cut to use, here's a quick primer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORK &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Spareribs come from the underside or belly of the pig; the word
never refers to beef or lamb. A full slab or rack weighs from 3 to
5 pounds. The ribs should have some fat, but avoid those that are
too fatty. Smoke, grill, roast or braise them. Allow a pound of
ribs per person for an entree serving.
</P>
<P>
   ``For meatiness and succulent pork flavor, you can't beat
spareribs, the 13 ribs from the belly of the pig,'' recommend Bruce
Aidells and Denis Kelly in their ``The Complete Meat Cookbook''
(Houghton Mifflin Company; $35). ``If you've ever wondered how they
make those great spareribs in the world-renowned barbecue joints of
Kansas City, the South Side of Chicago or Memphis, the secret is a
flavorful spice rub and long, slow cooking with a spicy sauce
slathered on just before serving. With a covered kettle barbecue,
you can create equally wonderful results in your own back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Pork baby back ribs are cut from the loin or back section. They
take less time to cook than spareribs. They are small, lean and
make good finger food. Quality varies, so check with butchers to
find out who sells those with the most meat. A meaty slab weighs
about 1 1/2 to 2 pounds and has about a dozen ribs. Figure on at
least a pound of baby back ribs per person for an entree.
</P>
<P>
   Country-style ribs are cut from the shoulder or the blade end of
the loin, with each containing a small bone. Boneless country-style
spareribs are cut from the pork butt. Smoke, grill, roast or
braise. Allow half a pound per person if boneless, a little more
with bones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEEF &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Beef back ribs (also known as beef spareribs) come from the rib
portion of the steer and are the most tender beef ribs for
grilling. Often beef back ribs are referred to as dinosaur bones or
long ribs. Smoke, grill or roast them. As an entree, allow six ribs
per person.
</P>
<P>
   Beef short ribs come from the rib, chuck or short plate
sections. They are rectangular in shape with alternating layers of
lean and fat. For the meat to be tender, hours of smoking or
braising over low heat is necessary. Figure a pound of short ribs
per person.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ribs you select, trim off all exterior fat before
cooking. To keep ribs from drying out, do not cut the sides or
racks of ribs into individual rib servings before grilling.
</P>
<P>
   For the best-tasting, juicy results, Carpenter and Sandison
suggest marinating the ribs in the fridge eight hours. However,
they add, you might get by with a quick five-minute marinade if you
baste them periodically with the marinade. Never brush any marinade
that has come in contact with the raw meat on ribs during the last
15 minutes of cooking time to be sure all the bacteria has been
killed. Additionally, if you want to accompany the finished ribs
with a marinade or sauce, be sure it has never come in contact with
the raw meat. If in doubt, simply whip up a new batch of sauce or
marinade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basting ribs is essential when grilling, oven roasting or
smoking ribs, as it keeps the meat moist and creates a thicker
coating on the ribs,'' advise Carpenter and Sandison, adding that
you can use dry rubs, marinades and slathers for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, flavor ribs with wood chips available at hardware
stores and supermarkets. Soak chips in cold water half an hour,
drain and scatter over charcoal or place on a sheet of foil on lava
rocks in one corner of a gas grill until they begin to smoke. Add
ribs, close the grill and let them cook.
</P>
<P>
   For general grilling information, see the story inside.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of rib recipe options follow. Peruse the various creations
and mix and match the parts of each recipe you like the best to
make a personal statement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BASIC BACK RIBS &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; This recipe is a starting point for rib cookery.
</P>
<P>
   4 slabs pork back ribs, well-trimmed of fat and silver skin
removed from back side
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue sauce, either store-bought OR homemade
</P>
<P>
   Season ribs with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Soak wood chips or chunks in water (if using) and place directly
on charcoal or in a smoker box.
</P>
<P>
   Place ribs in center of cooking grate. Cover grill and cook
until done and meat pulls away from bone, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 minutes before serving, baste ribs with barbecue sauce.
Serve additional barbecue sauce at the table. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY-STYLE BARBECUE RIBS &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1 cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 tablespoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   5 large garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds country-style back ribs
</P>
<P>
   For marinade, in a food processor, combine all ingredients
except ribs; process until well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Pour marinade over ribs and marinate several hours or overnight
in fridge.
</P>
<P>
   Heat grill until hot. Drain meat, place on hot grill and cook 8
to 10 minutes. Turn and brown other side, 6 to 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with Dinah's Sweet Barbecue Sauce (recipe follows), if
desired. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Nathalie Dupree's Southern Memories'' (Clarkson Potter). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DINAH'S SWEET BARBECUE SAUCE &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chili sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dark corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken bouillon cube, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh herbs
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a heavy skillet; add onions and garlic and cook
about 10 minutes or until onions are a burnished brown. Transfer to
a food processor or blender. Process until smooth (see Note).
</P>
<P>
   Put puree in a medium saucepan. Stir in chili sauce, corn syrup,
bouillon cube, vinegar, soy sauce, lemon juice and Worcestershire
sauce. Add herbs and pepper to taste. Bring to a boil, stirring,
then reduce heat. Simmer, uncovered, 30 minutes. Doubles easily and
freezes well. Makes 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: For a chunkier sauce, do not process onion-garlic mixture.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Nathalie Dupree's Matters of Taste'' (Alfred A. Knopf). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN COUNTRY-STYLE RIBS &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 3 pounds pork loin country-style ribs
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mango chutney, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Heat ribs and enough water to cover to boiling in a 5-quart
saucepan over high heat. Reduce heat to low; cover and simmer 1
hour or until ribs are fork-tender. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to medium or preheat oven to 450 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, combine chutney, Tabasco sauce, oil, chili powder,
cumin, salt and thyme in a medium bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Place ribs on rack on grill or broiler pan. Brush ribs with
chutney mixture. Grill or bake 20 minutes or until brown and heated
through, brushing occasionally with chutney mixture and turning
once. Makes 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-STYLE PORK SPARERIBS &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 4 pounds pork spareribs
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Heat spareribs and enough water to cover to boiling in a 5-quart
saucepan over high heat. Reduce heat to low; cover and simmer 1
hour or until ribs are fork-tender. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat honey, ketchup, vinegar, orange juice, garlic,
Tabasco sauce and salt to boiling in a 1-quart saucepan over high
heat. Reduce heat to low; simmer, uncovered, 5 minutes or until
mixture is thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill to medium or preheat oven to 450 degrees F. Place
ribs on rack on grill or broiler pan. Brush ribs with honey
mixture. Grill or bake 20 minutes or until heated through, brushing
occasionally with honey mixture and turning once. Makes 4
servings. &QL; 
(SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
