<HEADLINE>
--RISKS OF HEART VALVE WOE SEEN GREATLY EXAGGERATED  
 --UNDERAGE SMOKERS FUEL TAX HAUL, REPORT SAYS  
 --WOMAN'S TOMATO CRAVING WAS RIPE FOR CLOSER LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Risks of heart valve woe greatly exaggerated  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid all the news about unsuspected health risks, here's the
opposite: a problem that's far smaller than experts thought.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people have been told they have a heart valve
problem called mitral valve prolapse, which puts them at risk of
stroke at an early age or a potentially fatal heart infection
called endocarditis. But two studies published in the current New
England Journal of Medicine show that the size and gravity of the
problem were vastly overstated.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1980s, researchers have estimated that from 5 to
35 percent of adults have leaky mitral valves, a disorder that
allows blood to flow backward from the heart's main pumping chamber
to the left atrium, the chamber above it that collects newly
oxygenated blood from the lungs. Young women were thought to be
especially at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis has bred anxiety among otherwise healthy people,
who have been told they needed antibiotics to prevent heart
infections whenever they had dental procedures. Some have been
unable to get health insurance because of their presumed higher
risk.
</P>
<P>
   But the research shows that mitral valve prolapse affects only
about 2.4 percent of adults, half of whom may have a harmless
variant of normal valve function. The conclusion emerges from a
study of 3,500 middle-aged offspring of the original Framingham
Heart Study participants.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the disorder does not appear to be related to the risk
of stroke, according to a companion study of 213 Massachusetts
General Hospital patients who had strokes before age 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message is that mitral valve prolapse is a real disease
but it occurs far less commonly than previously thought,'' said Dr.
Robert A. Levine, an MGH cardiologist and coauthor of both papers.
``And we don't find any evidence of a stroke risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitral valve prolapse carries a risk of heart problems, but only
if the leakage is severe, which is true in a minority of cases.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been told they have mitral valve prolapse,
especially those informed more than about five years ago, should
ask their doctors if the diagnosis should be reevaluated, Levine
said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason earlier studies were mistaken, he said, is that
researchers assumed the mitral valve was supposed to be a flat disk
when it was shut. Newer imaging methods show that it's
saddle-shaped, like a Pringle's potato chip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Underage smokers fuel tax haul, report says &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Concern about teenage smoking over the past decade has led to
new prohibitions in all 50 states, a federal law requiring states
to enforce laws against underage smoking, and increases in state
and federal cigarette excise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not slowed sales to underage smokers. Tobacco
industry profits from illegal sales of cigarettes to minors have
more than doubled, according to a study published in the current
American Journal of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The industry reaped at least a half-billion dollars in profits
from illegal sales to youths under age 18, estimates Dr. Joseph R.
DiFranza of the University of Massachusetts Medical School and John
J. Librett of the Utah Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   They estimate that 16 percent of youths between ages 12 and 18,
or 3.8 million, smoked daily in 1997, accounting for nearly 4
percent of total US cigarette sales. That generated $431 million in
taxes, a 33 percent jump since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   DiFranza said that taxes derived from cigarette sales to
adolescents should be devoted to enforcing laws against selling
tobacco to minors and to antismoking education.
</P>
<P>
   The money that most states ``are bringing in from these illegal
sales is more than enough to do an excellent job of enforcing the
law,'' said the UMass family physician.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Woman's tomato craving was ripe for closer look
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unusual food cravings, sometimes called pica, are usually a
tipoff to anemia caused by iron deficiency. But one Ohio woman had
an especially odd case.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old woman had been eating up to 10 whole tomatoes a
day for two months, enough to turn her palms orange from the
pigment in the vegetables, Dr. Mark Marinella of Wright State
University in Dayton, Ohio, wrote in a letter to the New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Marinella found the woman was severely anemic from the bleeding
caused by daily use of anti-inflammatory pills for arthritis. After
blood transfusion and iron supplements, her anemia was cured. So
was her tomato craving.
</P>
</TEXT>
