<HEADER>
A6009 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-DARING-BOS &LR;      07-01 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL WAR WAS WOMEN'S WORK, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ALL THE DARING OF THE SOLDIER 
Women of the Civil War Armies 
By Elizabeth D. Leonard 
Norton, 368 pp., illustrated, $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The women who served in the Civil War armies were not only as
daring as the men, but, in historian Elizabeth D. Leonard's
accounts, had to be even more daring just to join up. And there
were more than a few such women. For beyond the hundreds who
``dressed as men, adopted male identities, and enlisted'' in the
Union and Confederate armies, there were scores more who served as
spies, an uncountable number who took up rifles in defense of their
homes and farms, and yet others who accompanied husbands into camp,
and sometimes into combat.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, a professor of history and director of women's studies
at Colby College in Waterville, Maine, touches in ``All the Daring
of the Soldier'' on the social issues facing women in the early
1860s and their aspirations beyond home, hearth, and nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Sarah Rosetta Wakeman, a New York farm girl who served
as ``Private Lyons Wakeman'' with Company H of the 153d New York
Volunteers from August 1862, her gender apparently undetected until
she died of acute chronic diarrhea in June 1864 after the battle of
Pleasant Hill, La.
</P>
<P>
   Wakeman had some formal education, Leonard writes, but was
working as a domestic servant when, at age 19 and with marriage
``not in the offing,'' she ``seems to have determined that assuming
the garb of a man would provide her with a wider range of
employment opportunities.'' She worked briefly as a boatman on New
York's Chenango Canal where she met some soldiers who encouraged
her to enlist, ``and so I did,'' she wrote home.
</P>
<P>
   She seems to have adjusted easily to a soldier's life, writing
that she slept ``as warm in the tents as I would in a good bed.''
After noting other details of army life, she added, ``I like to be
a soldier very well.'' And in another letter, Wakeman wrote that
she was ``enjoying myself better this summer than I ever did before
in this world. I have good clothing and enough to eat and nothing
to do, only to handle my gun and that I do as well as the rest of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She apparently never directly wrote about her masquerade,
although she did mention encountering one other woman who had, like
her, enlisted as a man, but whose sex had been detected. Her last
letter home provided details of the battle at Pleasant Hill, during
which she was ``under fire for about five hours and laid on the
field of battle all night.'' Barely two weeks later, she fell sick
and died shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that other women soldiers, like Wakeman, reported
encounters with still other women posing as men suggest that
Leonard is not far off in her estimate that ``between 500 and a
thousand women disguised themselves as men and enlisted as
full-fledged soldiers during the Civil War.'' From their accounts,
their experiences seem to have been so similar, even routine, that
they seem almost as unexceptional as those of women serving in the
military today.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptional stories are of the women who served as spies,
such as Confederate Belle Boyd, ``a precious rogue,'' as she was
described by one Union officer, and Pauline Cushman, who spied for
the Union and was described in a contemporary biography as having
``all the daring of the soldier.'' They were typically women of
``physical beauty and personal appeal'' _ which they used in the
course of their work.
</P>
<P>
   Of even more interest are women like Lucy Williams, the young
wife of a Confederate soldier, who had strong Union sympathies.
When the Confederate cavalry commander John Hunt Morgan spoke too
openly of plans to attack a nearby Union encampment while dining at
the home of Williams's mother-in-law, Williams duped him into
granting her a pass through the Confederate lines so that she could
return to her own home _ and even into lending her a horse. But
instead of heading home, Williams rode through the rain to the
Union camp where she exposed Morgan's plan of attack. She then
``reportedly led the federals via a winding secret route'' back to
the Confederate camp where ``they killed Morgan preemptively and
sent his troops in all directions.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard chose not to turn what is a lively account of women in
the Civil War into a broader and slower-paced study of the social
context and implications of their decisions, and of their actions.
She does attempt to provide a historical context, citing as models
the few women known to have served in the Continental Army during
the Revolution. But the documentation there is even more
speculative than that for the women of the Civil War, and the
social context unclear. Leonard might well have found the social
context that her story lacks among the young women from Waterville
and elsewhere who have entered military service for many of the
same reasons as Sarah Rosetta ``Private Lyons'' Wakeman: adventure
and a wider range of opportunities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
