<HEADLINE>
CARNIVAL CRUISE SHIP MAKES GALVESTON ITS HOME PORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As is often the case in Texas, bigger is better. Why do anything
any other way?
</P>
<P>
   So it shouldn't come as a surprise that Galveston landed not
just any cruise line but the world's largest to offer trips
year-round from its port. After almost eight years of negotiations,
the Port of Galveston lured Carnival Cruise Lines to its new cruise
pier.
</P>
<P>
   The Celebration, a Carnival SuperLiner, will begin its program
of five- and four-day cruises from Galveston in October 2000. No
other cruise line offers a regular sailing schedule from Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big, big, big deal,'' says Diane Falcioni, cruise
promotion manager for the Port of Galveston. ``The timing was right
and the market is the right fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The market was ready, says Bob Warren, director of the Galveston
Island Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, with more than 4,000 hotel
rooms in place and a tourism business that already brings 7 million
visitors to the island annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnival brings us a much broader scope of sales and
tremendous exposure in the travel agent and tour operator arena,''
Warren says. ``We think this will dramatically improve our
out-of-state visitor business.''
</P>
<P>
   The ship carries 1,486 passengers and offers 72 cruises a year,
Warren says, adding that the 85,000 potential new visitors should
have a $21 million impact on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The five-day trips will feature stops at Playa del Carmen,
Cozumel and Cancun, Mexico, while the four-day voyages will skip
Cancun. The shorter cruises will sail from Thursday to Monday,
designed to appeal to long-weekend vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   Four-day cruises begin at $389 per person, based on double
occupancy; five-day sailings will start at $479 per person. Air
fare to Houston Hobby, about 40 minutes away, is extra, and Warren
says his office is already working on pre- and post-cruise packages
for vacationers who want to spend time in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Other visiting cruise ships have included the Stella Solaris,
which makes calls to Galveston from February to April; the Delta
Queen, a replica steamboat that visits from New Orleans during
Galveston's Dickens on the Strand celebration in December; and
RiverBarge Excursion Lines, which calls during early spring.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
