A6012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNITED-CHURCH-BOS &LR;      07-01 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-CHURCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED CHURCH OF CHRIST HOPES FOR UPSWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HERMIONE MALONE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was once one of America's most prominent Christian
denominations, whose history stretches back to the Puritans and
Pilgrims and whose familiar white steeples are staples on New
England postcards.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past three decades, the United Church of Christ has
been in steady decline. From a highpoint of 2.1 million, the
mainline Protestant denomination's rolls have shrunk to 1.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Some church critics and scholars say the church's strong liberal
tilt, including its welcoming attitude toward gays, has turned off
members who are more interested in spiritual nourishment than in
political or social causes.
</P>
<P>
   As the denomination targeted particular issues such as poverty,
racism, or hunger, these critics say, some churches came to
resemble advocacy groups more than houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   Against this sober backdrop, about 700 denominational leaders
and members are gathering in Providence, R.I. for a national
convention to grapple with issues that will shape the church's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the church's direction in recent years, social and
economic concerns will dominate the agenda, including international
debt forgiveness, the downside of welfare reform, and teen suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some folk the UCC represents a kind of liberal
Christianity to which they can relate,'' said the Reverend Bennie
E. Whiten Jr., president of the Massachusetts Conference of the
United Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Whiten and others are hopeful that the denomination's fortunes
can be reversed and are heartened by some signs that the membership
drain is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   But the church will not likely experience the same kind of
success it enjoyed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Like other mainline Protestant denominations, the church was a
major player on the American religious landscape, lending its moral
pulpit and its Christian values to the struggle for civil rights
and the movement against the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But along with other mainstream Christian groups, its influence
has been eclipsed, at least in the political arena, in recent years
by conservative Christian denominations who seized the spotlight on
issues ranging from abortion to family values.
</P>
<P>
   Some United Church of Christ members have voted with their feet,
leaving denominational churches for evangelical congregations that
emphasize more purely religious themes such as salvation and a
personal relationship with Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the recent downturn, there are signs of hope.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, after losing members for several years, the
state's 433 UCC churches are actually starting to see their
membership rise. More than 2,000 people have joined Bay State
congregations in the past two years, bringing the denomination's
statewide membership to nearly 105,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``After many years of decline, that's very encouraging for us,''
Whiten said.
</P>
<P>
   And state church officials say it's precisely the UCC's liberal
views that are fueling the increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are looking for churches that are run
democratically, that do ordain women, that do listen to the
laypeople,'' said the Reverend Donald Whitcomb, pastor of First
Congregational Church in Paxton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Mathers of Leverett, Mass. is one of those who has
returned to the United Church of Christ after years of being an
inactive member, bringing her husband and young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my first thoughts sitting in that church was this
church needs me,'' said Mathers of the First Congregational Church
in Leverett.
</P>
<P>
   After her 5-year-old son Ryan was born, Mathers said she and her
husband both felt it important that he be exposed to church. What
began as a plan to visit several churches and stay where she felt
most welcomed ended with the first church on her list _ First
Congregational.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, it seemed like a dying church. It has really come
back and it's because of the congregation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At this week's convention, the Massachusetts delegation will try
to push a resolution on welfare reform. Whiten wants churches to
look at what is happening to people whose welfare benefits have
expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they caught in a kind of limbo between a job that doesn't
pay benefits and leaves them with lots of issues as far as their
children are concerned?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the UCC, which is a product of the merging of
the Congregational Christian Church and the Evangelical and
Reformed Church, has fought prison expansion in the United States
and apartheid in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   It has also advocated for the acceptance of homosexuals,
bisexuals, and transgendered people as members in the
denomination's churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of the UCC indicates that it will always be on the
forefront of social issues, that it will be a denomination that is
not afraid to face the issues of the day,'' Whitcomb said.
</P>
<P>
   UCC officials maintain that the social and economic issues the
church tackles are quite spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these are based on a very strong theology and often
they cite biblical passages,'' said William C. Winslow, a church
spokesman. ``They all come out of a sense of justice, which is what
Jesus was calling for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-SECURITY-BOS &LR;      07-01 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-SECURITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTORS LOSING SACRED GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Connecticut clergy buried a priest, and then used holy water
to purify the church where he was slain, their ancient ceremonies
symbolized a modern truth: Churches are not sanctuaries anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The murder of the parish pastor, beaten to death last week with
a candle-holder allegedly wielded by a delusional man who bought a
newspaper ad seeking the Virgin Mary's aid, was a senseless act
that supports no clear pattern of violence against the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   But theologians, academicians, and clerics say that the Bristol,
Conn., murder of the Rev. Robert J. Lysz underscores troubling
tensions between ministering to life's less fortunate _ including
those deeply troubled _ and the need to take care when dealing with
the potentially violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clergy have to become more street-smart and many of them
have,'' said the Rev. Robert Friday, who teaches moral theology at
Catholic University. ``It's the kind of thing that has, at times,
moved some Catholic clergy to remove their Roman collars when they
travel because you can attract people you don't want to attract in
an airport or at a bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's too bad. But you just don't know today.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Monsignor Francis Scollen of St. Peter's Church in
Worcester put it: ``It's a fine line. You don't want to exclude
people. But you don't want to get knocked on the head either.''
</P>
<P>
   Scollen said he feared that might happen to him two months ago,
when he met a man in his church parking lot in an encounter
frighteningly similar to the murderous sequence described by police
in Connecticut last week.
</P>
<P>
   Scollen said he was approached by a 6-foot-5 man who wanted to
sleep in the rectory that night, noting all its empty rooms and his
homelessness. When the priest suggested a shelter, the man, who was
not cogent, angrily refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I had to go to a wake and he said, `Forget the
wake. That person's dead. And I'm here and I want to stay at the
rectory.' I finally talked him out of it,'' Scollen said.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of quick thinking and fast talking apparently did not
work with the 32-year-old drifter who allegedly bludgeoned Lysz,
50, to death June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Michael L. Ouellette, the ex-Marine who has been charged with
the murder, told police he asked the priest for permission to sleep
in the church but was told instead to go to a homeless shelter.
Ouellette hid in bushes and followed Lysz into St. Matthew Church
several hours later, police said.
</P>
<P>
   There was a struggle. Ouellette struck the priest on the head
with a heavy candlestick ``three or four times,'' dragged the body
behind a pew, dressed himself in Lysz's clerical garb, and then
went to sleep in the rectory, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said Ouellette, who was baptized and received his
Holy Communion at St. Matthew before he moved away, was being
treated for a psychiatric condition called bipolar disorder and had
become obsessed with religion.
</P>
<P>
   As efforts to treat the mentally ill have moved increasingly
away from walled-off institutions, specialists say those with
delusions sometimes seek counseling and solace from priests and
ministers, who often lack the training to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the cutback in mental health care, the church is
certainly a place where people go to for a recourse,'' said Dr.
Nancy Kehoe, a psychologist and a Roman Catholic nun who has
organized monthly sessions for religious and mental-health
professionals in Cambridge. ``The clergy traditionally has not been
trained or has been minimally trained in psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't stop the rectory doorbells from ringing, said
the Rev. Jorge Reyes, a priest at St. Mary's Church in Lawrence,
Mass., who one day found himself sitting across his desk from a
visitor who said he heard the devil's voice in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started going into a rage,'' Reyes said. ``He was flopping
on the floor, hitting himself, and I was wrestling him on the
floor. I thought he was going to hurt me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to deal with. You feel in some way you can
help. They come in and they want God or for us to pray for them,
and they think they're going to be healed. At the same time,
they're suffering from a mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Such encounters and the acts of criminals have changed the way
churches operate. After microphones, candlesticks, and other church
property began to disappear with regularity several years ago, many
churches locked their doors. Church alarm systems are commonplace.
Steel bars obscure many stained-glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeffrey L. Brown, pastor of Union Baptist Church in
Cambridge, Mass., said that if he encounters a parishioner who
needs mental-health professionals he is quick to refer them there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that the pastor or the priest know where that
fine line is drawn between spirituality and psychology _ where they
intersect and where they diverge,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor William C. Francis, pastor of Holy Family Church in
Boston's Dorchester neighborhood, said his church has turned its
basement into a shelter run by the Pine Street Inn _ a move he
called the greatest security system possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people around all the time,'' Francis said. ``If
you're going to worry about it, you don't belong here. That guy in
Connecticut was just unstable. He would have killed that poor
priest whether he was a priest, a rabbi, or a minister. There are
crazies all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At St. Peter's, Scollen said his doors are locked, his grounds
are well lighted, and the parish hands out bus tickets and food _
but never cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``A church is sometimes the only place that will take these
people,'' Scollen said. ``It can be scary. But on the other hand,
if you become afraid, you can't work in a place like this. If I
ever got to a place where I was afraid, I'd leave. I have no fear,
but I am cautious. The lights are on. The doors are locked.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold I. Schwartz, a psychiatrist and the director of the
Institute of Living in Hartford, Conn., said it is not uncommon for
people afflicted by bipolar disorder or schizophrenia to become
hyper-religious or suffer from religious delusions.
</P>
<P>
   They may believe they are Jesus Christ. They may recite the
Bible on street corners. There often is an acute sense of
grandiosity that may lead them to believe they are God's only true
representative on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely, he said, do people who suffer from the disease such
as the one that afflicts Ouellette become dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to jump to the notion that this person who looks a
little odd is to be feared,'' Schwartz said. ``It would be a
terrible misperception if people were to come away with that
impression. But there is a subset of people who don't get adequate
treatment or are not taking their medication who can become
violent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
