<HEADLINE>
DESPITE APATHY, NEWSPAPER SALE IS HIGH STAKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Maine's Portland Press Herald was up for sale last year,
nervous employees tried to purchase the paper and concerned
citizens formed a lobbying group to ensure that it would be sold to
a benevolent independent owner.
</P>
<P>
   No such outpouring of interest has greeted the news that the
Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette (T&AMP;G), with roots that go back 115
years, is on the auction block after parent company Chronicle
Publishing's recent decision to sell its media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that after you've changed hands once, (another sale)
doesn't have the overbearing specter it had the first time,'' says
publisher Bruce Bennett, referring to the T&AMP;G's transfer to the San
Francisco-based Chronicle Publishing in 1986. Former mayor and
local radio show host Jordan Levy says, ``I haven't had a single
solitary caller talk about,'' the sale. Inside the paper ``people
are just going about in their summer haze,'' says T&AMP;G reporter
Chris Pope. ``The operative word is fatalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the prospect of new T&AMP;G owners has not stirred Worcester
out of its dog-day doldrums, the battle for control of a monopoly
daily newspaper (107,405 weekday circulation, 134,067 on Sunday) in
New England's second largest city (population: 162,000) could
become a high-stakes chess match between some very powerful media
companies. With analysts setting the price tag in the
quarter-billion range, possible buyers run the gamut from MediaNews
Group to The New York Times Company (which also owns The Boston
Globe) to Fidelity's Community Newspaper Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some names we've heard who are little better than
bandits and there are those who are widely respected in the
industry,'' says Tim Schick, administrator of the Providence
Newspaper Guild, the T&AMP;G's editorial union.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, one thing seems certain. As Bennett puts it:
``It's a wide open game.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale, expected by early next year, is part of the
divestiture of Chronicle Publishing's three television stations,
two book publishing companies, one cable news outlet, one Web site,
and three newspapers _ the T&AMP;G, The Pantagraph in Bloomington,
Ill., and the flagship San Francisco Chronicle. Observers believe
the empire will be parceled off in pieces and estimates of its
value have ranged as high as $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Three industry sources put the T&AMP;G sale price in the $200-$300
million range, proving that even in the era of new media and
declining circulation, papers in major markets can fetch a pretty
penny. Newspapers ``make a lot of money,'' says media analyst John
Morton, noting that the average profit margin for publicly
reporting newspaper companies was a robust 20 percent last year.
Papers are ``still a huge presence, particularly in the local
advertising market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healthy market,'' adds Chronicle Publishing spokesman
Don Solem. ``The predicted tanking of all media for the sake of the
Internet did not occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the question isn't who is interested in the Chronicle
sale. It's (itals)who isn't interested.(unitals) According to news
reports and the rumor mill, Gannett, Hollinger, Knight-Ridder,
Journal Register, The New York Times, A.H. Belo, Times-Mirror, and
Hearst are among the conceivable contenders for one or more of the
papers. (Hearst _ which owns the San Francisco Examiner that shares
a joint operating agreement with the Chronicle _ has the right of
first refusal on the Chronicle.) These corporations declined to
comment on any acquisition plans. But two other companies seem to
have thrown their hat in the ring for the T&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elfers, chairman of the Community Newspaper Company that
owns scores of area weeklies and The Metrowest Daily News, says he
is ``definitely'' eyeing the T&AMP;G. ``Worcester is an extraordinarily
attractive franchise.'' According to a story in the June 17 T&AMP;G,
Bennett sent a memo to employees indicating that MediaNews Group
has expressed a clear interest in the paper.
</P>
<P>
   In this cost-conscious world of regional newspaper
``clustering,'' a number of potential contenders already have New
England publications. But the king of clustering is MediaNews
Group's controversial president William Dean Singleton, who owns
about 50 dailies including the Fitchburg Sentinel &AMP; Enterprise,
North Adams Transcript, The (Lowell) Sun, and The Berkshire Eagle.
Famous for cost-cutting and layoffs, Singleton is a name that
invariably creates newsroom jitters. Last year's grass-roots effort
to keep the Portland Press Herald in friendly hands was aimed at
fending off more bottom line-oriented buyers like Singleton,
Gannett, and Journal Register. To the city's relief, the paper was
bought by the Seattle Times Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope in the newsroom is that The New York Times . . . will
be a serious contender and block any sale to Singleton,'' noted
Worcester Magazine political editor Martha Akstin in a recent
column.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that it's Billy Dean's to lose,'' says Dave Cole,
publisher of the News Inc. media newsletter. ``He's building
clusters (in Massachusetts) and he likes New England.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever emerges will acquire a paper that is considered adequate
but not great and that is often criticized for being too
conservative for its lunch-bucket Democratic readers and too
closely aligned with the city's business elite. But its local
dominance and power is indisputable.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester market is a ``wholly owned subsidiary of the
T&AMP;G,'' says McCormack Institute senior fellow Lou DiNatale, a harsh
critic of the paper. ``It had a great captured market that it
regularly abused.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A new publisher,'' he adds, ``can't do anything but help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
