<SLUG> BC-HOME-BEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE BEACH, IT'S LIGHT HOUSEKEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN, Mass. _ If you fall off the deck of the home of
Richard DiFrummolo and Donald Winter here, you could drown. At low
tide, you'll still get wet. Set as it is inside the first knuckle
of the hand that is the narrow tip of the arm that is Cape Cod, the
house is so close to being in, and not on, Provincetown Harbor that
you couldjust as well be sailing when you're in the living room,
for all the sea ambience. To describe it as waterfront property
does not do justice to the feel, the smell, and the sight of the
ocean onto which this house opens so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the wood deck, filled with potted flowers and metal
sculpture from local artists, DiFrummolo points out the new
Provincetown-to-Boston high-speed ferry wending its way toward the
Long Point lighthouse and out toward open ocean and says, ``It
gives us a lot of joy and pleasure to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   When you enter the home, the light from the sunlit water floods
the living room and kitchen/dining area, which make up the entire
first floor. Everything, from the bleached pine floors to the
burlap walls and painted wood ceiling, is white, with touches of
sea blue. Some of the blue is in the plaid fabric on chairs, and
some is on the art on the wall, and the rest is from the blue of
the water, seen from every angle, which seems to match every blue
in the house. The entire front wall of the house consists of
floor-to-ceiling French doors, painted white. In front of them, a
small porch gives onto the sizable deck, which can be reached by
stairs on either side of the porch.
</P>
<P>
   This might be a standard, if wonderful, blue-and-white beach
house, were it not for the dramatic pieces of art everywhere,
inside and out. There are paintings by noted Provincetown artists
such as Paul Risika and his student Chet Jones; a
Michelangelo-style bronze torso made from old car parts by Judith
Browne; in the living room, works by Anne Packard and Dimitri
Hadzi; on the deck, a sculpture by Dan McNeil; and, perched on the
pilings just off the deck, a sea gull made from fenders by Jack
Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   Their art-filled home hints at the avocation of this talented
pair, and at their art-related philanthropic activities. These two
are on personal first-name terms with most of the well-known
artists represented throughout their home. Winter, who is in
semiretirement as a partner at Palmer &AMP; Dodge LLP, is a trustee of
the Provincetown Art Association and Museum. DiFrummolo for many
years owned a Boston antique shop called Upstairs Downstairs, and
Winter is an adviser to the Provincetown Fine Arts Work Center,
which provides a residence program for 10 artists and authors to
live and work here during the quiet winter months.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the two gave a party in this home to benefit the work
center, hosting Sebastian Junger, the author of ``The Perfect
Storm,'' as their celebrity guest. ``We practically had a perfect
storm during the party, too,'' Winter says with a laugh _ but,
DiFrummolo adds, the storms are just as wonderful to view from this
house as the sunny times. This summer, they will host author
Michael Cunningham, whose 1998 novel, ``The Hours,'' was published
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are on the board of the Provincetown Repertory Theatre,
and last summer they hosted a large benefit party with an all-white
theme. There were too many guests for them to hold the event at
home, so it took place on the hilltop outside the Pilgrim Monument,
within walking distance, under a white tent with hundreds of white
lights, and everyone wore white. They are already at work on this
year's benefit, which will be a masked ball on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love giving back,'' notes DiFrummolo of their many
charitable works. He calls Winter, who was at one time chairman of
the Back Bay Architectural Commission, ``a frustrated architect''
who was only too eager to help redesign and reconfigure the
worn-down house when they bought it in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renovating ``a wreck''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When they bought the gray-shingled little home, which they call
The Beach Box because of its foursquare shape and style, it was, in
Winter's words, ``a wreck.'' But, says DiFrummolo, ``we knew the
area well _ Donald had owned two cottages nearby and I had owned
two houses in the east end of town, and we had had our eyes on the
property, hoping it would someday be for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, when it came on the market, Winter said, they bought it
from a broker over the telephone from Boston without seeing the
inside. ``The bones were good,'' says Winter, ``and the size was
right and the layout was good. As far as its condition, we expected
it to be a wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Their expectations were met big time. The house came furnished,
with ugly '50s furniture and smallish '50s picture windows on the
wall facing the sea. It was dark, and the plumbing was in very bad
shape. The couple, who have, in Winter's words, ``l'embarras du
choix,'' which includes homes in the South End of Boston and also
in Woodstock, Vt., decided, upon seeing the interior, to spend the
first two summers after buying the house away from it, thinking
about it, and renting it out, furnished as it was, while they fled
to Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman who rented the house said afterward, `You gentlemen
should be ashamed of yourselves,' while telling us about the shower
that leaked through the floor below, so we hired a contractor,''
DiFrummolo says. ``First, he was to reshingle the gray exterior of
the house and to reshingle and put a new peak on the roof, and redo
the porch and deck.''
</P>
<P>
   Winter picks up the story. ``Because of the expense, we told the
contractor to work just on the outside of the house at first,
figuring that we could continue on the inside at a later date,'' he
recalls. ``Due to a misunderstanding, when we came back to the
house in summer, we discovered that he had gutted the entire
house!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the spots where the hoppers had been,'' DiFrummolo
adds, ``there were just holes.''
</P>
<P>
   They gritted their teeth and started then to remake the entire
house. That included turning the gutted second-story space into
three small bedrooms and two baths, and the ugly little dank '50s
cellar, which is on the level of the deck, into a beachside cabana,
with a bar and a couch filled with comfortable pillows. The
stairway from bedrooms to first floor was reconfigured so that it
goes two separate ways at the bottom, ``to catch a glimpse of the
sea'' explains DiFrummolo _ even when you're heading toward the
kitchen, which is at the back of the house and looks out on the
quiet one-way residential street nearby. There is practically no
yard, which is typical of property in this beach town. The few feet
on either side of the house, between its neighbor house on one side
and a small restaurant on the other, are planted with rugosa roses,
clematis, and other flora, but no labor-intensive grass. The front
yard is essentially liquid, and to use it even more, the couple has
a Chris Craft boat, called the Beach Bucket, moored near the deck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the furnishings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DiFrummolo's training as an antiques dealer served him as
collector of the home's furnishings, a mixture of antiques, white
wicker, and contemporary couches and glass tables. He bought some
old chests, which he then had a friend, the late Romolo del Deo,
decorate and paint with a blue wash for the bedrooms, which are
carpeted in natural-colored sisal, the only carpeting in the home.
In the master bath, he decided to use the same white, brick-shaped
tiles as are used in the Paris Metro because, he said, ``they have
a wonderful three-dimensional architectural element'' of light and
shadow. When they saw the leftover painted white burlap that was
used on the walls, the men thought it might make interesting
valances, and there they are: stiff, white-painted valances draped
over the side windows, looking on closer inspection more like
pieces of art than curtains.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered among the valuable artwork are found pieces of no
specific value, such as a piece of interesting driftwood that a
guest brought up from the water. It is hung next to the
better-known pieces, in a whimsical sense of democratic integration
that the men say causes some interesting comments from unsuspecting
visitors, who view it as critically as all the rest of the works.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the house are pieces from DiFrummolo's collection of
periwinkle-blue Richard Robinson Ransbottom pottery from Ohio. On a
cozy window seat in the kitchen next to the stove is the same blue
plaid fabric as on the cushions of the living room's wicker
furniture, but this cushion has been laminated to protect it from
cooking spills. Also in the kitchen is the 50th birthday present
given to DiFrummolo by Winter and his three sons from a former
marriage. It is a narrow, vertical painting called ``Takeout
Boxes,'' a picture of white Chinese food cartons stacked on top of
each other, painted by Peter Palumbon. ``Those boys,'' says
DiFrummolo of the young Winters _ Andrew, 33, Matthew, 31, and
Tony, 27 _ ``are my family, too, we are so close.''
</P>
<P>
   As he speaks, the sound of bagpipes can be heard from the water.
A nearby resident often plays them at sunset, DiFrummolo notes, and
once in a while, at low tide, the couple also see horseback riders
riding bareback across the wet sand in front of their house. This
summer, Winter commutes back to his city job for three days at
midweek. Next year, he looks forward to living here full time from
May to September. After that, he says, ``Every fall, we have to go
to the Vermont house; it's so beautiful in October.'' It also
houses a whole different set of artwork, from Vermont artists who
live near that home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the December house, too, with all the children there,''
DiFrummolo adds. ``That's definitely the Christmas house.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is definitely the beach house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
