<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LINES OF DEFENSE IN THE GREAT BUG WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eek, an ant!
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing how just a few ants can send a homeowner into a
tizzy, mainly because he or she doesn't know what kind they are
(maybe they're carpenter ants!), or what to do about them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the homeowner reports seeing one or two ants a day.
The ``cure'' is to sweep them up and throw them away.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes the infestation is major, with dozens of ants
skittering here and there, and sometimes those ants are huge ( 1/2
inch and bigger), which may indicate they are indeed, carpenters,
and major action must be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Ants are just one of the pests that invade houses in spring and
summer, adding to the homeowner's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Other insects that can be a problem in the house are roaches,
which have been around, virtually unchanged, for 400 million years.
Honest. That indicates how well they can survive. Termites are
another pest. Even honeybees can invade the house, but rarely do.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors, problem pests are wasps and carpenter bees.
</P>
<P>
   To meet these menaces, major or minor, the Raid Center for
Insect Control, a branch of S.C. Johnson Co., makers of Raid and
Pledge among others, has launched a campaign called ``Don't get
mad, get even!''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign suggests using Raid products, but that is not
always necessary. Other ways may be just as effective.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ants
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with ants.
</P>
<P>
   There are several types that invade houses; some are common all
over the country, others are in specific areas. As a rule, they are
harmless, and the invasion is a matter of aesthetics.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions to these harmless invaders are carpenter ants and
fire ants (in the South).
</P>
<P>
   What to do about them?
</P>
<P>
   Little ants come into the house for warmth, moisture, and food.
The first line of defense is to keep food off floors, counter tops,
and other areas where ants will make a beeline to the food. Quick
cleanup and proper storage of food will help a great deal. Regular
cleaning of counter tops and other surfaces will also help. Ants
will eat almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Also helpful is to caulk cracks, holes, and other places where
you see ants coming from. It is not easy to build barriers against
ants, especially in old houses, but it is possible. You can have a
wonderful time caulking with a caulking gun.
</P>
<P>
   One good thing about these small ants is that most nest
outdoors. And many eat other insects, making them beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   For a severe ant invasion, a quick wipeup with a
detergent-loaded sponge will kill large numbers. Or squirt a
teaspoon of liquid detergent or soap into a quart-sized spray
bottle, fill with water, and spray the critters, wiping up with a
wet sponge.
</P>
<P>
   You can use a pyrethrum spray for severe infestations, but this
handyman recommends against spraying indoors if you can help it.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the ants at bay, put down ant baits, commonly called ant
cups. Use as many as practicable, and put them in cabinets, under
stoves and refrigerators, and other areas, but keep them away from
people and pets, and do not put them where food and dishes are
stored.
</P>
<P>
   A good insecticide is boric acid that comes in dust and spray
form. Apply it to baseboards and other areas where you suspect the
ants. Very little is needed to be effective. Boric acid is toxic;
do not breathe the dust. When applying dust, wear a mask and
goggles to protect eyes and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter ants
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If your house invaders are carpenter ants, you have to do
something different.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter ants are very large, but the only way to identify them
is by an entomologist or an exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   One way to detect carpenter ants is to check the house; do a
Cook's tour of the house, from basement to attic, looking for
little piles of dirty sawdust. Carpenter ants do not eat wood, as
termites do, but rather shovel it out of the nest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you put your ear to the wall near where you found
the sawdust, you may hear a rustling sound _ the sound of those
busy ants at work.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, call an exterminator. An exterminator should
locate and destroy the nest, and the queen with it. Carpenter ants
tend to nest in damp, punky, decaying wood, so the nest may not be
that difficult to locate. In addition, all damp, punky wood should
be replaced with sound wood. And, of course, fix any leaks that
caused the decay in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cockroaches
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's an old saying: It's not a disgrace if you get
cockroaches, only if you keep them.
</P>
<P>
   Roaches usually come into a house on the groceries. Once in the
house, they can proliferate if nothing is done. Most common roaches
in this country are the German cockroach, which is small ( 1/2
inch) and repulsive, and the Amrican roach, which is large (up to 1
3/4 inches) and repulsive.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in a single-family house, there are ways to get rid
of roaches, and keep rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment buildings and other multi-unit buildings present a
special problem: You can get rid of your roaches, but if your
neighbor does not bother, the roaches will migrate from his place
to yours in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Repulsiveness is one thing, but a health hazard is another.
Cockroaches carry diseases, and also can cause asthma in city
children.
</P>
<P>
   Defenses against roaches are similar to those against ants. Keep
all surfaces free of food. Wipe spills quickly. Sanitation is the
key word.
</P>
<P>
   Several sprays are available for roaches, and boric acid,
applied as it is for ants, will be effective. But it is a
never-ending battle, especially if your unit is in an apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   As with ants, caulk up a storm to keep the critters out.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, a vacuum cleaner or shop vac is great for pulling
roaches from their hiding places. Use the open hose to pull them
from under stove and refrigerator. Use the wand to suck roaches out
of crevices and small openings. Fill the vac bag, tie it, and
dispose of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of bait stations you can buy. Place these
carefully around the house, especially in kitchen and bathroom.
Again, keep these stations away from kids and other human beings
and pets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wasps and hornets
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vespa is the genus of wasps and hornets, which many persons
often mistake for bees, genus Apis.
</P>
<P>
   Wasps and hornets are beneficial insects, feasting on many other
insects and also pollinating plants. They almost always stay
outdoors, rarely going indoors, and usually don't sting unless
provoked.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem with wasps and hornets is that about 1 percent
of the population is allergic to their stings, resulting in a
severe reaction or death. Many persons know they are allergic, and
take proper precuations, but others may not know they are allergic.
So, in any case, wasp and hornet control should be left to the
pros.
</P>
<P>
   The most common wasps and hornets are the paper wasps, the ones
that build paper nests shaped like footballs; hornets or yellow
jackets, which nest outdoors; and mud daubers, which nest in the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Paper wasps build their nests outdoors, but sometimes nest in
attics, where they are likely to get into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, a wasp's nest is best left alone, if it is far enough
away from the house and away from kids and other yard denizens. A
nest in the attic can be left alone, too, if wasps are not in the
living space.
</P>
<P>
   Leave mud daubers or ground-nesting wasps alone, too, unless
their nests are close to the house.
</P>
<P>
   While it is best to have a professional deal with wasps and
their nests, the Raid Center for Insect Control makes a spray for
shooting down nests and colonies when necessary, usually when the
nest is over the front or back entry or in a nearby shrub or tree.
</P>
<P>
   The insecticide is in an aerosol can that shoots a stream some
20 feet, making it a little safer to attack the nest. Do so in the
cool of the evening, when the insects are less active and most are
in the nest. Try to hit the opening, but map out an escape route to
safety in the house after firing a burst, because survivors will
chase you with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   A similar treatment can handle ground-nesting wasps. Be sure in
all cases to wear as much protective clothing as possible and make
sure that the escape route is unobstructed. If you can see where
the wasps are coming out of the ground, you might be able to close
the opening after hitting it with the insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow jackets sometimes nest in small openings in the house.
Plugging those or making proper repairs will keep them out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bees, too
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of beelines (they are never straight, you might
notice), bees (Apis) are rarely a problem, because they generally
mind their own business. Even bumblebees are more scary than
hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   Honeybees are beneficial, making great honey and pollinating
plants, and very rarely build hives in a house wall. If they do,
you will have a whole wall full of honey, and often the hive is so
big and bulging that it will push the wall inward or outward. If
that happens, call a beekeeper, who will remove the hive, its
queen, and thousand of bees who must be relocated. Then rebuild the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   The only bee that is a nuisance more than a menace is the
carpenter bee, which drills a hole in wood siding and trim, turning
a corner and depositing eggs in the drilled tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   If you are plagued with such critters and their holes, you can
spray insecticide in the hole and plug it with a piece of glazing
compund or pliable putty.
</P>
<P>
   We won't talk much about termites because termite treatment is
best done by professionals. If you have termites or think you have,
call an exterminator. Most do-it-yourself termite treatments are
not very effective, and since subterranean termites nest in the
ground, not in the house, they are relatively easily treated.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to keep termites away is to keep any wood off the
ground; there should be at least eight inches between wood
structural members and the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
