<HEADER>
A6019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-01 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIPS WE TAKE FOR GRANTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does a life-changing experience look like? At our
Unitarian-Universalist Church in Marblehead the other Sunday, my
friend Jim gave this account of an event that happened 32 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Having left the military to move into the field of
organizational development, Jim was required to participate in a
two-week training program with the National Training Labs,
participating in long daily sessions with almost no agenda except
that the trainees share their feelings, respond authentically, give
honest feedback to others, learn to really listen, and, by focusing
upon relationships within the group, come to understand group
dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   At first Jim found the process ``weird,'' but a few days into
the program he noticed something unfamiliar happening to him. Used
to communicating about issues, he'd never been comfortable talking
to others without an agenda. Now he found himself wanting to engage
people in personal conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Friday,'' he recalls, ``I was really tuning in to people.
It was like a window had opened and I could see, for the first
time, the seductions, the competition, the reaching out _ how open
some people were and how closed others were. It was like coming out
of a sleep and beginning to function on a level I had never before
experienced. It was clear that my normal state to that point was
pretty unconscious. I had been functioning on the surface and now I
was going much deeper, like going from black and white to
Technicolor to 3-D. There was so much going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Jim's wife came to visit, bringing their
18-month-old son. When Judy drove up, Jim went out to her car.
After they kissed, she flipped on the inside light, and there was
his son John, standing in a playpen in the back of their wagon,
peering at his dad over the railing.
</P>
<P>
   As a dad, Jim had occasionally spooned food into John's tiny
mouth, wiped drool off John's damp chin, tucked blankets around
John's sleeping form. This encounter was surprisingly different.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was my son,'' Jim says. ``His eyes shone with pure
happiness to see me. This was not a partially formed human being,
but a fully formed person, with all the emotional equipment fully
functioning. I met my son for the first time. And he was responding
immediately, instantaneously, fully. I thought I was going to drop
in my tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, Jim and Judy spent time with other members
of the group. Jim figured his socially-competent-enough wife could
hold her own with strangers, but he had totally underestimated her.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my amazement,'' he continues, ``Judy was right there, open,
present, getting all the nuances, the stuff that was going on, and
forming relationships. Here I had come this great distance and she
was already there. I could hardly believe it. Before this evening I
hadn't really realized who I had married.'' There is obviously more
to this story, but Jim's admission that up to that point he'd had
very little idea that he'd married an extraordinary woman stopped
me in my tracks.
</P>
<P>
   I think we may all be admirationally impaired.
</P>
<P>
   There are two deathbed tragedies that I'm desperately trying to
avoid. The first is the pain of realizing, when it's far too late,
that although you were unaware of it at the time, there were
periods in your life when you were miraculously happy. The second
is to die without ever having recognized how remarkable the people
in your life were.
</P>
<P>
   The reason it's so difficult to see the exceptional talent, the
amazing creativity, the profound humanity, or the immense goodness
of those around us is because we're blinded by a culture that
insists that fame and fortune are the only measures of worth we can
trust. We think that anyone local _ teacher, minister, musician,
neighbor, friend _ must fall short of the greatness that is always
somewhere else, never within our circle of acquaintances, and
certainly never within us.
</P>
<P>
   We are so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to argue that anyone, even Jim's wife, is perfect. I
know Judy well enough to tell you she is merely magnificent and
astonishing. Like Jim, I am lucky enough to have recently shed the
psychic filters that misled me all my life into believing I was
seeing nothing special. Now, at rare and precious times, I look at
those with whom my life is tightly interwoven and no longer
perceive only the shadow of their true selves.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with powers of observation once beyond my ken, I sense
them blazing from within like a star and am dazzled by their
radiance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
