<HEADLINE>
MOUNT RUSHMORE: AMERICA AT ITS GRANDIOSE BEST AND TACKY WORST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEYSTONE, S.D. _ When viewing Mount Rushmore on a brilliantly
sunny summer day, it's inevitable that several thoughts cross your
mind.
</P>
<P>
   The new parking lots, entrance way, visitors center and walking
paths are efficient and attractive.
</P>
<P>
   George Washington looks so distinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson's carved stone visage is the most
weather-beaten of the four.
</P>
<P>
   From some angles, Teddy Roosevelt seems to be whispering in
Abraham Lincoln's ear.
</P>
<P>
   You sure have to pass a lot of hokey, pseudo-attractions on your
way to and from Mount Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   That is the paradox. In frantic efforts since its 1941 opening
to capitalize on one of America's foremost patriotic shrines,
entrepreneurs in the Black Hills area have surrounded
architect/sculptor Gutzon Borglum's masterpiece with a chaotic
collection of waterparks, reptile farms, chintzy ``Old West''
tourist trap towns and other eyesores.
</P>
<P>
   This is America at its grandiose best and tacky worst.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors from afar should keep in mind that Mount Rushmore's
remote location makes it difficult to reach.
</P>
<P>
   By air, you can fly to Minneapolis or Denver and connect to a
smaller aircraft for another hour's flight to Rapid City. Then you
would have to rent a car and drive 45 minutes to the massive
monument.
</P>
<P>
   By then you have invested so much money and time that it doesn't
make sense to look at Washington &AMP; Co. for 30 minutes, turn around
and go right back home.
</P>
<P>
   So you consider these options:
</P>
<P>
   _You spend several days sulking in a Black Hills motel room,
venturing out for repeated looks at Mount Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   _You visit the Crazy Horse Monument, or enjoy the natural
wonders of Custer State Park and the nearby Dakota Badlands, which
shimmer with ominous beauty.
</P>
<P>
   _You give in to the temptation of tackiness.
</P>
<P>
   But without question, Mount Rushmore is a grand place and where
you will want to start your trip.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have visited before will be pleasantly surprised by
new amenities added since the early 1990s. There are two vast
parking lots. One is free but a half-mile hike from the entrance;
the other costs $8 for an ``annual pass,'' but is more accessible
to the new monument entranceway, whose clean granite lines offer a
breathtaking frame to the four famous faces. Admission is free,
although donations are encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   A brisk walk down the Avenue of Flags leading to the massive
viewing deck is tempting, but postpone it for a few minutes to
wander through the new visitors center. It includes fascinating
displays that tell the story of how the monument was commissioned
and constructed. Learn why Borglum insisted that Teddy Roosevelt be
the fourth president represented while Roosevelt's detractors
believed it was premature to etch his memory in stone.
</P>
<P>
   The viewing deck is perfect for gawking. Mount Rushmore is a
tremendous sight. But now newly constructed footpaths make it
possible to get a closer look. You still can't pat Washington on
the nose, but you get a clearer view of his nostrils.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Rushmore gift shop is exactly what you'd expect _ an
eclectic mix of tasteful and tacky. Elegant knit shirts are on
shelves next to garish glow-in-the-dark neon T-shirts. There are
expensive carved Indian artifacts as well as $2 plastic keychains.
Snacks are available, too.
</P>
<P>
   Borglum's on-site studio is open to visitors, with interesting
displays chronicling how the famous faces were blasted out of rock.
</P>
<P>
   Too many Mount Rushmore neophytes forget to return after
sundown. Every night at 9 o'clock, there is a simple but moving
lighting ceremony when Washington, Jefferson, Roosevelt and Lincoln
seem to suddenly spring in ivory tones from the pitch darkness. The
crowd inevitably oohs and aahs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, like a great painting in a museum, Mount Rushmore can be
looked at only so long before there is an urge to move on. Although
they receive far less publicity, there are other natural and
man-made wonders in the Rapid City region that are well worth
visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ATTRACTIONS, LIKE CRAZY: The Crazy Horse Memorial, located 17
miles from Mount Rushmore on U.S. 16, is a logical place for
monument devotees to visit. The 9-story rendering of Crazy Horse
and his mount has been under construction for several decades, ever
since sculptor Korczak Ziolkowski was asked by Lakota chief Henry
Standing Bear to carve a mountain monument so ``the white man
(will) know the red man has great heroes, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been obstacles, foremost among them Ziolkowski's
death (his family has continued the work) and the fact that Crazy
Horse never allowed his photo to be taken.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
