<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULL-MARKET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISTS SEE NO QUICK END TO THE MARKET PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Watching the stock market has become America's
newest spectator sport.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of investors follow their holdings as closely as the
World Series. From high-powered traders to short-order cooks,
people eagerly await daily market reports and interest rate
pronouncements from the Federal Reserve. It's the great
democratization of the market.
</P>
<P>
   And the excitement that stretches from Wall Street to Main
Street may not go away just yet, investment specialists say. The
economic climate is sweet, and the money is flowing easily.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers keep pouring billions of dollars into retirement
funds. Financial Web sites have opened up investments to millions
of people. Cyber traders have turned on-line investing into a new
growth field. The brawny U.S. economy keeps charging ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party's still here,'' said Jonathan Horton of the Horton
Investment Advisory Group in San Francisco. ``We might go into a
slow dance now and then, but the party should keep going for at
least eight to 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite gloomy predictions of a bear market, stock indexes in
the United States have enjoyed strong gains during the first six
months of 1999. If the trends continue, the market may post
double-digit gains for the fifth straight year _ an all-time
record.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell the story. In the first six months of the year,
the Dow was up to 10,970.80 from 9,184.27 at the end of 1998. The
S&AMP;P 500 rose to 1,372.66 from 1,228.10. And the Nasdaq 100 was at
2,686.12 from 1,993.58 six months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of Wall Street's good health, baby boomers
concerned about their retirement kept mutual funds going strong.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this year, the total assets of the nation's
7,000-plus funds grew to $5.9 trillion from $5.5 trillion _ a 6.3
percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some 70 million people have moved into their prime saving
years, and they're in it for the long term,'' said John Collins, a
spokesman for the Investment Company Institute, a trade group in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Even recent stock market declines have not scared investors, who
are mostly middle-aged, middle-class people with $60,000 in median
household income. During market plunges they stop pouring money
into mutual funds, but resume their investing within weeks or
months, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't pull the trigger and panic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the rosy scenario, market specialists are split into
two camps. Some are mildly bullish, advising their clients to keep
taking profits on hot stocks, while guarding against a sudden
crash. Bearish investment pros are telling their clients to
hibernate and pour money into safe bonds and low-risk stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree the key economic signs still look good.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity and employment are up, while inflation is in check.
And the Federal Reserve didn't jack up interest rates too much _ a
big hike might chill the economy and pop the stock market bubble.
The explosion of the Internet and other wireless technologies
should keep the economy healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But bears warn that the market is at the cusp of a long-term
correction or a crash. Internet mania will die soon, they predict.
Stocks on the S&AMP;P 500 are dangerously overvalued, trading at 35
times earnings. The market is too narrow and concentrated, with
investors pouring too much money into a small number of large, blue
chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The raging bull market has created unrealistic expectations
among investors, warned Joe Turner, co-founder of Pring Turner
Capital Corp. in San Ramon, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's mentors taught him long ago to grow cautious when
everything looks too good, when business can't get any better. The
signs are too positive, he said: Consumer confidence is at an
all-time high. President Clinton announced a $1 trillion federal
surplus earlier this week. And many analysts believe the stock
market will keep soaring into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   To play it safe, Turner advises his clients to pour money into
safe bonds and so-called ``value'' stocks that boast cheap prices
and solid earnings potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at history, the stock market has suffered 25
percent corrections every three to four years,'' Turner said. ``The
bull market has got people thinking that investing is fun and
easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
