 Thursday, July 1, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUTS (Washington) _ The chairman of the tax-writing Ways and
Means Committee unveils the broad outline of a Republican-sponsored
tax cut measure that includes breaks for married people and cuts in
estate and capital gains taxes. But such a package face legislative
hurdles from President Clinton and the fact that House Republicans
are divided over the size of the total tax-cut package. By JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-KILLER (Washington) _ A top federal official says the
Immigration and Naturalization Service was alerted by the Houston
police department last year that Rafael Resendez-Ramirez was wanted
for murder in Houston. Six months later, INS officers had the
39-year-old drifter in custody but released him because they didn't
know he was suspected of murder. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ With Texas Gov. George W. Bush awash
in an astounding $36 million in campaign cash after only four
months of fund-raising, the question arises: can this be too much
of a good thing? There is a danger that he may look as though he is
buying the election. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-RURAL (Washington) _ To win back the House in 2000,
Democrats will have to rely on Democratic anti-abortion and pro-gun
conservatives running in rural districts that were fertile
Republican turf for decades. This strategy, which helped Democrats
chip away at the GOP majority in 1998, was thrown into doubt
recently when a prominent Democrat, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I.,
said the party had ``written off the rural areas'' in 2000. By DAN
FREEDMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6026 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSHMORE-PARADOX-2ndT     07-01 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSHMORE-PARADOX-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
KEYSTONE, S.D.: to be taken. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sculptor rendered the chief's likeness from written and oral
descriptions, and now a huge head glares out of the mountainside.
There is no firm date for when the sculpture will be completed, but
estimates are in the 40-to-50-year range. It costs $20 a car to
visit the monument-in-the-making, but it's worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   Custer State Park is in buffalo country. You cannot help but
encounter some of the shaggy creatures, and jeep rides are
available where the herds roam thickest. But much of the fun is
getting there. The tiny mountain highways offer frequent vistas of
glimmering lakes, towering pines and occasional Rocky Mountain
Goats who like to walk alongside the road.
</P>
<P>
   To the north of Rapid City, the towns of Deadwood, Lead and
Spearfish re-create reasonably accurate Wild West settings.
Although selling cap pistols and T-shirts are a priority, the staff
is well-versed in town lore. Authentic period entertainment is
available, too; on July 12-21 in Spearfish, for instance, Texas
musician/historian Bobby Bridger performs his ``Ballad of the
West'' trilogy. Call (605) 642-5890 for information.
</P>
<P>
   Because it has the most available motel rooms, Rapid City will
probably serve as a home base. Its eight-block downtown is replete
with antiques stores and western clothiers. Rapid City also boasts
a half-dozen free attractions, which is welcome in a place where a
buffalo burger can set you back $8.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Geology is worth seeing, although youngsters will
prefer Dinosaur Park along Skyline Drive. The seven life-size
reptiles look phony to the adult eye, but they're perfect for
climbing and picture-posing, so kids who have a passion for
make-believe and are bored easily are likely to love them.
</P>
<P>
   Another Rapid City-area attraction is the helicopter ride around
Mount Rushmore. The price increases the closer you get to the
monument. It starts at $20 per person, jumps to $40 for a view from
200 yards, and skyrockets to $120 for a really up-close and
personal look.
</P>
<P>
   Other attractions include the Sitting Bull Crystal Caverns,
which are like shiny holes in the ground; waterslides and ``the
Black Hills Maze'' (a few square yards of shrubbery with pathways
cut in the greenery); and Keystone, a town with apparently no
purpose other than siphoning your money when you're heading to or
from Mount Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   To the east of Rapid City, only an hour's drive on Interstate
90, is the Badlands. What you're likely to remember most about the
Badlands is Wall Drug Store, which is promoted with more roadside
signs than it is possible to count. From food to frolic to toys,
the signs promise that Wall Drug has everything. And if it's junk
you're looking for, it does. Curiosity will make you stop to see
what all the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre, the state capital of South Dakota, is another 200 miles
away. It is pleasant but undistinguished and the Capitol building
pales when compared with Austin's, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But filmgoers may recognize the surrounding landscape because
Kevin Costner filmed much of ``Dances With Wolves'' in the area.
It's fun for a little while to park by the side of the road where
signs mark where scenes were filmed and try to remember which
scenes these might have been.
</P>
<P>
   To the west, across the Wyoming border, is the staggeringly
beautiful Devil's Tower National Monument. Spielberg fans will
recall that Devil's Tower figured prominently in ``Close Encounters
of the Third Kind.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've got the time and a car that gets good gas mileage, you
may also want to drive to North Dakota or Canada. Be warned that
both states named Dakota are huge, and maps disguise actual drive
times.
</P>
<P>
   You're going to be in your car eight to 10 hours before nearing
our neighbor to the north, but once there, Canadian border guards
seem uniformly friendly and enjoy suggesting scenic spots on their
side.
</P>
<P>
   American guards are less chummy. Smaller U.S. crossing points,
for instance, are open only from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m., and even if you
arrive at 8:55 in the morning, you will have to wait until
regulations allow you to drive across the invisible divide between
the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The identification necessary to travel between the two countries
is minimal; a U.S. driver's license will do.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you decide to spend your time enjoying nature's wonders
or mankind's tourist traps, though, you'll undoubtedly conclude
your Black Hills visit with one last, lingering look at Washington,
Jefferson, Roosevelt and Lincoln. It says a lot that the chance to
gaze up at their chiseled rock faces on Mount Rushmore makes
anything else superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
