<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYORAL CANDIDATE TACKLES HOMELESS ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayoral candidate Clint Reilly has announced his
answer to a problem no San Francisco mayor has succeeded in
conquering _ homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   In a 48-page booklet entitled ``Homeless Solutions,'' unveiled
Wednesday, Reilly details a plan that includes conducting a census
of homeless people, opening day shelters for the mentally ill and
encouraging public aid recipients to take vouchers instead of cash.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposed a no-tolerance policy for graffiti, aggressive
panhandling and public urination. The incumbent mayor, Willie
Brown, and his predecessor, Frank Jordan, have both been criticized
for cracking down on such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown has mismanaged the homeless issue just as badly
as he has mismanaged Muni,'' said Reilly, referring to the city's
transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, owner of a commercial real estate business and a former
political strategist, launched his campaign four months ago with an
indictment of Brown's handling of Muni.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Johnston, spokesman for Brown's re-election campaign, said
Reilly's proposal contained no fresh ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a sensible, thought-out solution to the homeless
problem,'' Johnston said. ``This is a political candidate who has
no credibility on the issue of poverty since he's been largely the
reason for the escalating rents that landlords have been able to
collect in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston noted that a census was unnecessary because officials
already had a clear idea of who made up the homeless population and
what their needs are. For example, he said, 70 percent of people on
the streets have substance-abuse problems, and 50 percent have
resided in San Francisco less than one year.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Gillis, coordinator of the Coalition for Ethical Welfare
Reform, said Reilly's idea to give people vouchers for food,
shelter and services rather than cash would not help people out of
homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That to me is saying homeless people are not responsible folks
just because they're homeless,'' she said. ``We know a lot of the
folks that are homeless are actually working, but because the rents
are so high in San Francisco, they can't afford a place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly also has proposed turning unused city buildings into day
shelters for the mentally ill. Gillis said what that population
needed were services for their problems, not places to go during
the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
