   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i`` code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Kosovo Polje) _ The destruction inflicted by tens
of thousands of NATO bombing flights is evident in this ragged
central Kosovo town, where the bleary Serbian faces speak of a sea
change in the Balkan equation: A decade after Slobodan Milosevic
envisioned it here in a speech that whipped up Serb nationalism and
helped cement his power, Greater Serbia is dead. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO's military commander, Gen.
Wesley K. Clark, testifies before the Senate Armed Services
Committee, his first appearance before Congress since before the
air war; the Army commander of the Apache helicopters testifies
before House committee on his internal memo criticizing the pilots'
lack of training time; and two top Pentagon officials brief the
House Intelligence Committee on the military's role in Chinese
Embassy bombing. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ Northern Ireland talks resumed on
Thursday after a midnight deadline passed. Tony Blair, the British
prime minister, stays for more talks, canceling his scheduled
appearance in Edinburgh for the opening of the new Scottish
Parliament. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CABLE-CAR (Paris) _ At least 20 people plunged to their
deaths on Thursday when a cable car to an Alpine observatory fell
after a cable snapped. It was the worst such accident in France in
three decades. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton meets with President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ Indian officials say the Kashmir
talks with Pakistan are dead. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-EXPORTS (Washington) _ Commerce Secretary Daley gives a
briefing on computer export controls, announcing that the
administration will liberalize exports, including those to China.
But the relaxation is not as much as the industry has asked for. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE-CONFRIM (Washington) _ Developments as the nomination
of Richard Holbrooke as U.N. envoy moves to the full Senate. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-REPUBS (Washington) _ Republicans consider tax cut
alternatives in the wake of the new surplus estimates, as the
official announcement of the Congressional Budget Office's
calculation is issued today. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PROGRAM (Washington) _ How President Clinton's Medicare,
Social Security and budget proposals will play politically _ for
Presidential and Congressional elections _ is a question many here
are asking; and while no candidate would want to say so on the
record, many believe the package would work better as a campaign
issue than as a deal. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIF (Fresno, Calif.) _ George Bush ventures into Al Gore
territory as he raises money in Silicon Valley. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-MEDICARE (Washington) _ HMO's announce plans to pull out of
Medicare, reduce benefits and raise premiums next year. They say
that federal payments are inadequate. This move undercuts a key
part of the Clinton Medicare proposal, which depends on competition
among low-priced HMO's to make the whole program more efficient. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-POKER (Atlanta) _ Voters in South Carolina will get to
decide whether to get rid of video poker or regulate it as
Louisiana cuts off the machines at midnight in those parishes that
had allowed them. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-BEATING (Washington) _ Two teen-age girls are accused of
attacking a 25-year-old woman, smashing her head against the ground
repeatedly in front of her two young children during a traffic
dispute in a suburb. The victim is in a coma. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Washington) _ Religious leaders debate the moral
issues related to human stem cell research. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washington) _ The House is expected to vote on
legislation that overhauls the nation's financial system, repealing
the Glass-Steagall Act and the barriers that have restricted banks,
insurance companies and securities firms from going into each
other's businesses. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   LIQUIDITY-TRAP (Undated) _ For years, the economics profession
has refused to entertain the idea that Americans could have money
in their pockets and not spend it, or that they could have access
to no-interest loans, as in Japan, and not borrow. There is a name
for such unexpected behavior: liquidity trap. Now an economist
suggests that a liquidity trap is a distinct possibility. The
concern is that a market crash or another big hedge fund failure or
another big debt default, like Russia's, will so shock Americans
that they will pull back sharply on both spending and investing. By
Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   STARBUCKS (Undated) _ The stock of Starbucks falls 32 percent in
the wake of an analyst meeting on Wednesday in which the company
disclosed that earnings would be 10 percent short of expectations
and that costs had risen for labor and for its Internet venture. A
look at the company's strategic direction. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 39
points, or 0.4 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 18 points.
Elsewhere, prices were up 1.9 percent in Tokyo and markets were
closed in Hong Kong. Stocks rose 1.9 percent in Frankfurt, gained
2.7 percent in London, rose 1.3 percent in Brazil and increased 1.8
percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was
down 1 and 4/32 point, with the yield back up to 6.05 percent. By
Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-SURGE (New York) _ A look at why somebody paid $90 on
Wednesday for the stock of ABR Information Systems, which will be
bought on July 19 for $25.50. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-AMERITECH (Undated) _ Reaction to the SBC-Ameritech merger.
By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Cyrysler and Honda report June sales. By
Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-DISNEY (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong extends talks with Walt
Disney on building a theme park here until the end of October. In
March, Disney and Hong Kong confirmed they were in negotiations to
build the company's second theme park in Asia. While officials say
they have made significant progress in the talks, they were not in
a position to sign an agreement by the deadline of June 30. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
