<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOLING FANS ALONG WITH THE DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Golden State Warriors teased the Bay Area
shamelessly Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   They picked Todd Fuller II in the NBA draft, and their
apoplectic fans couldn't dial up talk-radio hosts fast enough. It
was time for whining, groaning, hair-pulling, time for a wake.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Fuller, the cardboard cutout that the Warriors
chose with the 11th pick three years ago. Big guy. Good student.
Had a deadly game. It killed the career of Dave Twardzik, the
general manager who drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Foster was this year's Fuller, a giant nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's not fair, but Warriors fans have every right to
leap to certain conclusions. They have endured Joe Barry Carroll.
They have survived Chris Washburn. By now, they know how to use the
word ``bust'' as a noun, verb, adjective, adverb and decorative
potholder.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Warriors needed this year was another big
man, not on their roster. And a big man available at the 21st spot?
This is where the ``you can't teach height'' becomes ``some teams
never learn.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Warriors were trying something new here. Five picks
after they took Foster/Fuller, they dumped him on the Indiana
Pacers. The Pacers gave up a future first-round draft pick, plus a
point guard, exactly what the Warriors need _ Vonteego Cummings,
the 26th player taken this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings may or may not be a point guard of the future.
</P>
<P>
   He may or may not last three years in the NBA. But, by taking
him, the Warriors dodged some of their own ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time anyone reviewed a Warriors trade and
questioned the judgment of the other team in the deal? In recent
years, negotiating with the Warriors has been like winning a
sweepstakes. Minnesota, Miami, Indiana, New York, Sacramento _ one
way or another, they all picked Golden State clean.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Pacers appear to be the dupes.
</P>
<P>
   But even if they turn out to be geniuses and Foster turns out to
be the next Patrick Ewing, the Warriors have some insulation
against second-guessing. They just have to save the tapes from
those radio shows. And let's admit it: Everyone, even if we didn't
call in, was thinking the same thoughts: ``Todd Fuller, stiff, not
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way this draft day turns into another nightmare is if
Jason Terry becomes the next Jason Kidd. The Warriors could have
had him at the 10th spot, but they traded the pick to get veteran
Mookie Blaylock and move down to 21. Terry was first-team
All-American. Cummings was third-team all-Big East. Blaylock, at
32, was off his game this year. Add this all up the right way, and
you have an equation for regret.
</P>
<P>
   What the Warriors really did was bow out of this draft. By the
time the draft hits the 21st spot, no one expects to find a player
who can contribute right away. The Warriors dropped down that low
because this draft, even in the top five picks, was woefully short
on talent. It's hard to blame them, even if Terry turns out to be a
star. After all, he went behind three other point guards, including
UCLA's Baron Davis, who never would have been the No. 3 pick in a
good year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Warriors have a first-round choice from Indiana, to be
used in a year when there is more talent. Also, over the next five
years, when that pick comes due, the NBA may have figured out a
plan to farm teen-agers out to a minor league.
</P>
<P>
   Then taking one won't be such a gamble. But Jeff Foster still
has a chance to hurt the Warriors. He could be the star of an
Eastern Conference power that never earns a draft pick higher than
25.
</P>
<P>
   It's a convoluted scenario, one that requires Warriors fans to
wind through a maze in search of trouble. In the past, they found
plenty without even trying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
