<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6058 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-WORKERS-1400(2     07-01 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-WORKERS-1400(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAST NETWORK INVOLVED IN RECRUITING IMMIGRANTS FOR BOOMING U.S. JOB
MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARISA TAYLOR, 
STEVE STEIN 
and DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six undocumented immigrants, huddled a few yards from the
U.S.-Mexico border in Brownsville, snap to attention when a
stranger in a pickup slows to a halt. If the men want work, the
stranger can ship them to jobs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   At a recruiting office in McAllen set up by meatpacking giant
IBP, company employees offer the promise of good-paying jobs and
benefits at plants in the Midwest _ and transportation there.
</P>
<P>
   At an El Paso homeless shelter, job counselors hand out fliers
advertising job openings in everything from food processing in
North Texas to tire recycling in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   All along the Southwest border, a sophisticated system is
supplying a steady flow of immigrants _ documented and undocumented
_ for U.S. industries desperate for workers in an era of low
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The system, which has evolved from the U.S. tradition of
recruiting Mexican farm laborers, involves a broad network of
people, including ``coyotes'' who smuggle in undocumented
immigrants, businesses that house and transport workers, recruiters
who comb the border and Mexico for workers, and the companies that
hire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gringos arrive here from all over: Texas, Mississippi,
North Carolina, Illinois and Florida. They find illegal workers who
are willing to work,'' said Enrique Pena, one of the few U.S.
citizens who goes to the Brownsville street corner daily to seek
work.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is usually to hire legal immigrants. But across Mexico
and Central America, undocumented workers know they can hook into
the U.S. job market by paying a smuggler $200 to $5,000 to cross
into the United States, resting up in a homeless shelter or a hotel
along the border and buying counterfeit documents such as passports
and ``green cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Some come after seeing ads by companies eager for workers.
Others have a U.S. relative with job connections for those without
proper immigration papers.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number connect with recruiters at the border _ on
street corners, at bus stations or at the Texas Workforce
Commission office, where companies can get space to recruit. They
sign up for jobs, then often board a bus, a plane or a company van
for the trip north.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the waves of immigrant workers going north,
several bus lines have been formed from Texas to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The charter business for Houston-based El Expreso accounts for
$15,000 in monthly business at its Brownsville station alone, said
Alberto Gutierrez, the Brownsville terminal supervisor for the
company, which offers direct service to Fort Worth and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, El Expreso, a Coach USA company, has taken
15,000 workers from Laredo to the tobacco fields of Raleigh, N.C.,
Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the workers are sought for backbreaking manual labor and
unskilled service jobs in industries such as meatpacking,
landscaping, construction, restaurants and hotels, where turnover
is high and transience is common.
</P>
<P>
   ``We import every type of worker but prostitutes into this
country,'' said Armando Alvarez, an El Paso recruiter who said he
has sent legal immigrants to jobs for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Each month, Ana Maria Gandara, an El Paso recruiter for the
nonprofit Opportunity Center, sends 25 to 50 people to Dallas-Fort
Worth for jobs in construction and food processing. Many employers
pay to fly the workers to Dallas/Fort Worth Airport or to Dallas
Love Field, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must have a real need. They ask for 50 people a month,''
she said, adding that she is careful to check documents.
``Companies are starving for workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some recruiters known as headhunters seek out undocumented
workers because they are vulnerable and because many will take on
any task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many recruiters take anybody who has a pulse,'' said Bob
Wingfield, a Dallas recruiter who checks workers' Social Security
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Mexican worker, whether he is legal or illegal, will get a
job. Mexican workers have become a commodity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo, a Mexico City native waiting to cross the Rio Grande in
Ciudad Juarez, said the most recent time he had traveled to the
United States, he easily found an employment office in Fort Worth
where he was recruited to remove asbestos for six months at an Army
base in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The fit, middle-age man said that for 10 years he has removed
asbestos in 39 states as an undocumented worker, sometimes using a
counterfeit document.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone guesses that I wasn't legal. I think even the Army
knew,'' he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   In Agua Prieta, Mexico, Honorio D. waits for his patron, or
boss, to send him to his next construction job in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't worry about your documents,'' he said. ``You just
show up for work and they tell you what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Mexican boss tells me where to cross, and then my American
boss finds me work,'' he said. ``Sometimes they take us and we have
no idea where we are going. They take us somewhere in America and
we work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked for all the big U.S. home builders, especially
in San Antonio,'' he said. ``The next time I will work in San
Antonio, Houston, and my boss tells me there is work for me in
Dallas and Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   DEPENDING ON SMUGGLERS: The first step toward a U.S. job is to
get into the country. To do this, many illegal immigrants seek out
smugglers on both sides of the border who help them cross and find
fake documents.
</P>
<P>
   Some coyotes, who often are immigrants themselves, offer the
newcomers help in finding jobs and give them information about safe
passageways. Others are profiteers who exploit their clients.
</P>
<P>
   In the central Mexico city San Luis Potosi, polleros _ immigrant
smugglers known as ``chicken catchers'' _ set up scam agencies near
consul offices to appear official when they sell documents and
promise work, Mexican consul officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the smugglers are customer-savvy and shrewd, providing
food and diapers for babies while waiting for U.S. Border Patrol
agents to switch shifts at checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Some coyotes will do anything to avoid being caught, including
leaving behind those who slow them down. In May, Border Patrol
agents found a 15-year-old Honduran boy curled up and crying in a
desert 15 miles southwest of Deming, N.M., with an empty water jug.
A smuggler had abandoned him because he couldn't keep up with a
group of undocumented immigrants crossing from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The coyotes' work does not end at the border. They transport
clients to safe houses or to hotels, where they hide until the path
is clear. In mid-May, the INS got a tip and found 126 undocumented
immigrants in a small Phoenix house where they shared one bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
