<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKER'S SON NOW TAKIN' CARE OF BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Even though he grew up surrounded by music and
musicians, Tal Bachman wasn't sure he wanted to pursue a pop
career.
</P>
<P>
   Bachman's dad is Randy Bachman, member of the Guess Who and
Bachman-Turner Overdrive and author of such hits as ``Takin' Care
of Business.'' Through his dad's massive record collection, the
younger Bachman became acquainted with 50 years of pop music.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when he turned 18, he essentially stopped listening to
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my favorite band _ U2 _ had gone off the deep end,''
Bachman, 27, said. ``My other favorite groups, like the Smiths, had
long since broken up, the Cure were redundant and I hated
hair-metal bands.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Bachman realized his talents were in music and moved
back to his hometown near Vancouver, British Columbia. Soon, a
self-produced demo was making the rounds, eventually catching the
ear of a Columbia Records executive.
</P>
<P>
   Bachman's self-titled debut, co-produced by Bob Rock (Metallica,
the Cult, Veruca Salt, Aerosmith), was recently issued while the
hook-laden ``She's So High'' is currently among the Top 30 album
tracks at both the adult alternative and hot adult contemporary
radio formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting airplay is very important if you care about other
people hearing your music, which I do,'' Bachman said. ``But I
don't have control over whether a radio programmer adds my song or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachman says the current state of pop worries him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's bands just can't seem to write more than one good
song,'' he offered. ``I don't blame radio for that. I lament the
decline in the number of bands who can sustain the attention of the
audience.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; FRED NEIL REDISCOVERED &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; It's ironic that the guy who penned the song ``Everybody's
Talkin''' should be so under-recognized, but Fred Neil remains one
of the last great undiscovered Greenwich Village folk legends.
</P>
<P>
   A contemporary of Bob Dylan, David Crosby and Paul Kantner, the
melancholy Neil, whose haunting songs have been covered by Harry
Nilsson and Tim Buckley, has had absolutely nothing in print on CD
and has not been seen or heard from musically since 1971 _ until
now.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the recent release of ``The Many Sides of Fred Neil''
(DRG) is such an event. The engaging two-CD set, which contains
testimonials from Crosby and John Sebastian, includes the three
sought-after albums Neil cut for Capitol, plus the two sides of his
rare single with the Nashville Street Singers and six unreleased or
alternate tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Neil's low, rumbling voice and chiming 12-string guitar make for
perfect late-night contemplation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6061 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-WORKERS-2ndTak     07-01 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-WORKERS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: shared one bathroom. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RECRUITERS HEAD TO BORDER: When the owners of InStaff Personnel,
a Plano-based employment agency, realized that they couldn't find
workers locally for two food processing companies, they decided to
head to the border.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the company began sending workers hired in El Paso
to Delta Daily Foods in McKinney and to Tyson Foods in Union City,
Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than not to come through for our clients, we thought we
needed a creative way to find employees,'' said Randy Burkhart, one
of three partners who owns InStaff. ``El Paso has such a high
unemployment rate, we thought it would be a good place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has sent 12 workers to McKinney and 140 to the
Tennessee plant. By year's end, Tyson wants 400 to 500 more
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the success, Burkhart said he has concerns because
counterfeit documents often appear authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing things the right way,'' he said, adding that the
company checks each worker's Social Security number. ``But anybody
who tells you that they're not concerned is fooling themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all recruiters are as careful. Some, paid as much as $300
per worker they sign up, seek workers at bus stations, private
offices and busy street corners. Fliers and radio, television and
newspaper advertisements ask, ``Busca trabajo?'' or ``Looking for
work?''
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, Ark., many immigrants arrive penniless at the
immigrant shelter Centro Hispano, carrying only slips of paper with
names of people who they say are friends or family members, said
Edwin M. Vasquez, the center director.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I call for them, it turns out the person isn't a friend
or relative, but an employer or recruiter,'' Vasquez said. ``The
recruiters tell them if you make it over here, then you have a job
_ just don't tell anyone who you are working for.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recruiters search for undocumented workers to take
advantage of them. Some pocket money that employers send for
workers' transportation and don't tell immigrants that they will be
charged later for the trip. Some misrepresent wages and housing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   One Mississippi recruiter hired several workers to burn tires
that were being recycled, but didn't provide masks or pay the
workers for several days of work, Gandara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recruiter told me he didn't want to hire blacks or Anglos,
he just wanted Hispanics,'' she said. ``He didn't want them to know
English.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, companies use as many as three or four recruiters to
find workers. With each layer of recruiting, it becomes more
difficult for the INS to prove that employers knowingly hired
undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a contractor or recruiter is going to deny that he
had any knowledge that the worker was undocumented,'' said Lynn
Ligon, an INS spokesman in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies handle their own recruiting at the border.
</P>
<P>
   Fliers displayed at Texas Workforce Commission offices in the
Rio Grande Valley attracted several applicants to an IBP recruiting
office in McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   One woman gets news via a telephone that she is eligible to work
at an IBP meatpacking plant in the Midwest. Company literature
states that she has the option of getting reimbursed 20 cents a
mile if she drives to the plant, or IBP will pay her bus fare from
the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   To meet its labor needs, IBP also has recruited in Mexico. The
company says that workers it hired there already had the
appropriate documentation, such as temporary visas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding adequate supplies of labor has become an uphill battle
for most businesses these days, including IBP,'' said Gary
Mickelson, a spokesman for IBP based in Dakota City, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   IBP has never been sanctioned for knowingly hiring undocumented
workers, Mickelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at IBP feel strongly about the issue of illegal
immigration, partly out of our own self-interest,'' he said. ``The
removal of undocumented workers by the INS costs IBP hundreds of
thousands of dollars in lost production, overtime pay and training
of replacement workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company acknowledges that meatpackers struggle to
screen out undocumented workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an employee claims to be a U.S. citizen and supplies
documents to support that claim, IBP must by law accept that claim
as true,'' the company said in a written statement. ``The problem
lies in the ease with which false documentation can be obtained
that purports U.S. citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   In an INS review of 24,148 employees in Nebraska meatpacking and
processing plants from May 3 to June 3, the agency said it found
4,495 ``record discrepancies.''
</P>
<P>
   After the problems were found, 3,152 employees chose to leave
their jobs, 303 were no-shows or excused absences, and 1,040 were
interviewed by the INS. The investigation resulted in 34
undocumented workers being apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS HAVE HIGH TURNOVER: Mesmerized by the prospect of
prosperity, immigrants are willing to take on the most demanding
work to fulfill simple dreams. They want to buy houses, cars and
educate their children.
</P>
<P>
   But many immigrants stay a short time in the jobs that U.S.
citizens often won't take. Grinding manual labor, culture shock and
the inability to meet their expenses lead to high turnover and a
constant need to recruit more workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel, a native of Guerrero, Mexico, left California three
years ago to find work in the Mississippi chicken industry. Earning
$350 a week, he chased and caught chickens sent to plants for
butchering and processing. But he quit because the work was so
grueling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fingers and hands got swollen,'' he said. He now is a
maintenance worker.
</P>
<P>
   Two to three weeks into poultry jobs in Scott County, Miss.,
workers start looking for other jobs, said Sally Del Castillo, a
missionary who assists immigrants at the Trinity Mission Center for
Hispanic Ministries in Scott County.
</P>
<P>
   Annual turnover in the poultry processing factories in Delaware,
Maryland and Virginia is approaching 100 percent at one facility,
according to an industry study. That creates a constant need for
new workers.
</P>
<P>
   After wearing out from arduous work, some immigrants use their
employment as a springboard to better-paying jobs in metropolitan
areas such as Fort Worth-Dallas, Chicago and Atlanta. They often
feel more comfortable settling in areas where their language is
more commonly spoken, their native dishes are served and their
traditions are understood.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas, who came to the United States to do fieldwork with a
temporary visa, later worked in a turkey processing plant and now
works in the Metroplex. He is a foreman pouring concrete for
sidewalks and driveways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working to eat and live, not to make money. In Mexico,
it's the same, but the refrigerator is empty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalia, a 33-year-old undocumented immigrant, came with her
husband to pick cucumbers. He tired of the long hours and low pay
and found a better job in construction, she said. Rosalia now works
in a doughnut shop. Recently, she urged her brother to come live
with the couple, although they still feel pangs of nostalgia for
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think it would have been better if I hadn't come.
It's difficult here,'' she said with a sigh. ``But it's better than
home, because I can find work.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
