A6084 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     07-01 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP EXPERTS PROVIDE INSIGHT INTO HOW MONEY GAME IS PLAYED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for investment ideas, consider picking the
brains of the best.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you would like to chat with John Bogle, who founded he
Vanguard Group, the second-largest mutual fund in the world; or
Mary Zweigt, chairman of a $9 billion mutual fund bearing his name;
or maybe Mario Gabelli, chairman of a $10 billion mutual fund that
bears his name. Foster Friess, manager and owner of the Brandywine
Fund, the best-performing no-loan mutual fund, may also have a few
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   For a different point of view, you may want to talk to some of
the information specialists in investing: Louis Navallier, who
edits the MPT Review, a highly rated investment newsletter; or
William O'Neil, founder of Investor's Business Daily. Don Phillips,
who heads Morningstar, the leading firm for rating and tracking
mutual funds, also has his own take.
</P>
<P>
   Round that out with a talk with Harry Markowitz, Nobel Prize
winner for developing the Modern Portfolio Theory, and you would
consider yourself well-educated in investment.
</P>
<P>
   Or you would have a book.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kenneth A. Stern thought when he interviewed all of
those people for ``Secrets of the Investment All-Stars'' (Amacom,
301 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   This tome offers the investment insights of nine top
investors/market information specialists. Each brings a unique
perspective to the complex world of investing.
</P>
<P>
   A simple question-and-answer format brings the reader into the
room where Stern is interviewing the investment stars, making the
material easy to breeze through.
</P>
<P>
   And the information is specific enough to be useful, yet doesn't
get bogged down in mind-numbing number-crunching and graphs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each all-star has very distinct and different views from that
of their peers,'' Stern writes. ``This is revealing in many ways.
Most importantly, it confirms to an investor that there is more
than one way to skin a cat, and more than one way to make money at
investing. It also provides a whole array of different styles and
disciplines for you to greedily absorb.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Zweig. He has been named by ``Forbes,'' among others, as a
legend in market forecasting. Stern says he is meticulous in his
constant market analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``To forecast the market, Zweig has probably probed, measured,
monitored ... and created more forecasting models than anyone you
will ever meet,'' Stern writes. ``Zweig would say that forecasting
the market is not so much about understanding money as it is about
creating a model, about finding a trend and sticking to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zweig has 70 factors in his market model, Stern writes. The most
important are monetary indicators, (mostly interest rates);
sentiment indicators (flows into mutual funds); and momentum
indicators (price and volume of stocks).
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli looks at the stock market in a totally different light,
Stern writes.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than changing his model to keep up with Wall Street
trends, Gabelli makes his decisions based on something called value
investing, a strategy of picking bargain stocks that have not
reached their potential.
</P>
<P>
   But Gabelli adds a kicker that he calls a catalyst. An
undervalued company will probably stay there, he believes, unless
an active ingredient, an event of some type, is triggered. Then
stock will rise to its true value. The catalyst can be anything
from the death of the founder to regulatory changes, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Stern concludes with a 20-point checklist, summing up how to use
``the best of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Investing can be hard work. Stern shows us how it can be
intriguing and fun as well.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``High-Tech Careers for Low-Tech People''
</P>
<P>
   By William A. Schaffer
</P>
<P>
   Ten Speed Press, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   Communication is the most important skill required by the
high-tech industry, author William Schaffer found when talking to
industry sources about his premise that people with arts degrees
can find a home in the high-tech world. Schaffer is a good example.
He has a degree in government and French literature from Columbia,
but he works as an international business development manager for
Sun Microsystems. Schaffer offers a career option that many people
may not realize they have and shows them how to pursue it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``52 Weeks of Sales Success''
</P>
<P>
   By Ralph R. Roberts
</P>
<P>
   Harper Business, $21
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agent and author Ralph Roberts _ he says he
generates 600 sales a year _ creates a sales teaching program based
on a yearlong weekly seminar he created for his Detroit company.
Roberts, who previously wrote ``Walk Like a Giant, Sell Like a
Madman,'' discusses the many tricks of selling in this, his latest
book. Ideas on customer retention, time management and getting out
of a slump are included.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Business the Rupert Murdoch Way: Ten Secrets of the World's
Greatest Deal-Maker''
</P>
<P>
   By Stuart Crainer
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   This is one of a series of four books highlighting the business
practices of Murdoch, Bill Gates, Richard Branson and Jack Welch.
All are well-written by English business author Stuart Crainer, who
has also written such bestsellers as ``The Ultimate Business
Library.'' Crainer has done his homework on these business moguls
and offers not only detailed backgrounds, but also insights into
their business practices.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
