<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISING-HNS &LR;      07-01 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAT CHECKBOOK ADDS TO AURA OF BUSH CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An impish-looking George W. Bush took the podium
at a charter school in Los Angeles to dispel some rumors about his
fund-raising abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've raised as of right now $35.5 million,'' Bush said with a
quick laugh, as if almost embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   A gasp went through the audience. Just that morning the New York
Times reported that the Texas governor had raised ``at least $20
million.'' Two hours later, the Bush campaign would revise the
figure to $36.25 million, and it seemed like money was falling from
the hazy Los Angeles sky.
</P>
<P>
   And at a San Francisco fund-raiser later on Wednesday, so many
people wanted to toss money at the early Republican front-runner
that Bush aides had to add a half-dozen tables outside the ballroom
at the Westin St. Francis Hotel. The $1,000-a-person event was
expected to net $800,000, but when the checks were counted, the
tally was $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The understatement of the day came when Bush's national finance
chairman, Don Evans, said of the three-day fund-raising trip to
California, which raised at least $4.5 million: ``The low-hanging
fruit has been plucked.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a heavy tree.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush has raised more money in four months than 1996
presidential candidate Bob Dole raised during his entire primary
campaign. And Bush has raised nearly twice as much as Vice
President Al Gore, who has a powerful Democratic fund-raising
machine, White House clout.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, which raised half as much as Bush in the
first six months of the year, was shocked at the Bush haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding me?'' Roger Salazar, Gore's campaign
spokesman, said when told of the Bush total. ``We will get back to
you to see if we want to have anything to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Marla Romash, Gore's deputy campaign chairman, said,
``Republicans always have more money than Democrats. That is a fact
of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush wrapped up his California trip Thursday after attending
seven fund-raisers over three days.
</P>
<P>
   The money flush has clearly jazzed Bush. During a Sacramento
event Wednesday, where he played football with a group of
youngsters in a mentoring program, his signal calls were: ``77! 36
point 25!'' before the handoff. It was an obvious reference to his
new fund-raising figure _ $36.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson of the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan group in Washington that tracks campaign contributions,
said of Bush's record-breaking fund-raising mark: ``This is the
political equivalent of hitting 90 home runs in a season.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Bush sounded like a candidate in the final
days of a general election race, not like someone who still sends
out press releases on ``Bush Presidential Exploratory Committee''
stationery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to carry your state,'' he told 1,100 supporters at
the event, ``and I intend to be the next president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of the fund-raising has added to the aura that the
candidate is already on the road to the presidency, a year before
the party nominating conventions and 17 months before the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   One difference between a traveling Bush and a traveling
President Clinton is that freeways are closed for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, just moments after Bush made his fund-raising
announcement, the Los Angeles police blocked off surface streets to
allow Bush's 12-car motorcade to pass and make it more swiftly to
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Even the protesters at the Bush events have added to the
presidential air of his trip. Outside the Westin St. Francis, 30
supporters of abortion rights railed against Bush while a dozen
environmentalists attacked the governor for doing little to protect
endangered sea turtles on the Texas coast. Would such a crowd have
turned out for Steve Forbes or former Vice President Dan Quayle,
both candidates for the Republican presidential nomination?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who's been coronated by the media and the
donors,'' Kelly Hayes-Raitt, an executive at California Abortion
and Reproductive Rights Action League, said of her group's decision
to protest against Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked during the California trip whether he would
consider a vice presidential running mate who supported abortion
rights. He cracked a wry, downturned smile and said: ``It's a
little presumptive for me to be selecting a running mate before I
have secured the nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would not rule out a pro-choice running mate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
