<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6088 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-SUPERTHIN-AND-SU     07-01 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-SUPERTHIN-AND-SUFFERING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HUNGER: THE DARK SIDE OF HOLLYWOOD'S SUPERTHIN, SUPERSTARVED
SUPERSTARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of actresses
Calista Flockhart of ``Ally McBeal'' and Lara Flynn Boyle of ``The
Practice.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Boys with breasts,'' Tom Wolfe calls them.
 &HT;    If you want to know what he means, tune into television's hit
legal series ``The Practice'' and take a look at Lara Flynn Boyle
as Deputy District Attorney Helen Gamble.
 &HT;    What you'll see is a beautiful face atop the body of a
12-year-old boy, except with mammary glands.
 &HT;    And Boyle is no exception. Just ask any fan of television's
other hot legal show, ``Ally McBeal.'' When star Calista Flockhart
turned her back to the camera in a recent episode, she looked like
a refugee from some POW camp.
 &HT;    Flockhart has had to answer repeated allegations of anorexia, a
potentially lethal eating disorder especially common in young
girls. Predictably, she denies it, with explanations that have
included ``I'm just small-boned,'' ``I've been working too hard''
and ``I have a fast metabolism.''
 &HT;    But her high-school pictures tell a different story: Yes, she
was a slim, pretty cheerleader, but in those days her bones were
amply covered. She looked, dare I say it, normal.
 &HT;    To Boyle and Flockhart add ``Friends'' star Courtney Cox,
Oscar-winner Helen Hunt, singer Celine Dion and model Kate Moss,
any of whom makes 1960s icon Twiggy look morbidly obese.
``Frasier's'' Jane Leeves, ``Jesse's'' Christina Applegate and
``Dharma &AMP; Greg's'' Jenna Elfman have all been photographed looking
rake-thin.
 &HT;    Even 37-year-old Meg Ryan, mother of a 6-year-old child, looked
much thinner than normal in her most recent film, ``You've Got
Mail'' (l998)
 &HT;    And if you think they look skinny on camera, which traditionally
adds 10 pounds, you should see them in real life.
 &HT;    ``I was on `The Howie Mandel Show' with Ms. Boyle,'' says
novelist Jackie Collins, ``and when she turned sideways I swear she
vanished.''
 &HT;    Once upon a time, the Duchess of Windsor decreed ``You can never
be too rich or too thin.'' But as recently as the 1950s, Hollywood
stars such as Marilyn Monroe, Jane Russell and Jayne Mansfield were
anything but pinched.
 &HT;    But times change, according to Sharlene Hesse-Biber, a sociology
professor at Boston College and author of ``Am I Thin Enough Yet?
The Cult of Thinness and the Commercialization of Identity''
(Oxford University Press, 1996).
 &HT;    ``By the time the '60s came along, women were beginning to close
the education gap and seeking out careers,'' she says. ``And, just
as in the flapper '20s when they were out campaigning for the vote,
the ideal body image for women started to shrink.''
 &HT;    But Twiggy and the other bone-thin ``dolly birds'' of 1960s
Britain were teen-agers, Hesse-Biber adds.
 &HT;    ``What's new today,'' she says, ``is we've got 10-year-olds and
postmenopausal women trying to be Twiggy.''
 &HT;    And the way they do that is by starvation _ there's no other
word for it.
 &HT;    ``This may be politically incorrect, but I find it fascinating
how ugly, starved, bony women can be considered attractive,'' says
Dr. Arnold Anderson, director of the Eating Disorders Unit at the
University of Iowa College of Medicine in Ames. ``When you see them
during examination, they are skeletons for hanging expensive
clothes on. It's extraordinary that people can be convinced they're
glamorous.''
 &HT;    According to Hesse-Biber, the current trend is merely the
extreme manifestation of a longtime, cross-cultural emphasis on the
attractiveness of tiny, childlike women.
 &HT;    ``Cinderella was the one tiny enough to fit into the slipper,''
she says, ``and the Chinese footbinders used to have smallest-foot
contests. In the late '60s there was Barbie with her
Victorian-sized waist and big chest. It was an impossible goal, but
it influenced all those little girls who between them had enough
Barbies in their toy box to circle the globe.
 &HT;    ``Now these actresses and models are taking the fantasy and
playing it out to its logical conclusion.''
 &HT;    And these days, thinness is big business, with huge sums being
spent on advertising that sends the worst possible message to women
and especially young girls.
 &HT;    ``Weight Watchers, the Jenny Craigs, the gyms, the beauty
products, the low-fat-food manufacturers, the diet gurus, the
plastic surgeons all conspire to convince us that we need to be
skeletal,'' Hesse-Biber says. ``They've done it so well that they
now have a growing population that will spend any amount of money,
endure any medical risk, in pursuit of the impossible.
 &HT;    ``We have women dying under anesthetic after nine and 10 hours
of surgery, trying to be perfect,'' Hesse-Biber adds, ``and others
spending their salaries on expensive diet products.''
 &HT;    It's a vicious circle: Young girls tune in to ``Ally McBeal''
and see an ideal they're supposed to measure up to _ presumably
with the help of the upcoming ``Ally McBeal'' line of health and
beauty products for young women.
 &HT;    The actresses themselves are trapped in the same spiral, knowing
that no one ever fired an actress for being too thin. On the other
hand, to be ``full-figured'' is _ except for rare exceptions such
as Roseanne or Camryn Manheim _ a ticket to the unemployment line.
 &HT;    As a result, they feel pressured into the kind of crash diets,
cosmetic surgery and, often, eating disorders which their own
example make so dangerous to their young fans.
 &HT;    Writer/producer David Kelley, who created both ``The Practice''
and ``Ally McBeal,'' is well aware of the controversy over his
stars' appearance, as he showed in a recent episode of the latter,
in which Ally and Gamble cross paths.
 &HT;    After giving Ally a cool once-over, Gamble sniffily remarks,
``Maybe you should eat a cookie.''
 &HT;    ``Maybe we should share it,'' Ally responds snidely.
 &HT;    In another episode Ally is accosted in a courthouse hallway by a
pushy woman who says she wants to nominate McBeal as a feminist
role model.
 &HT;    ``We'll have to fatten you up,'' she adds as an afterthought.
``And you'll have to drop that skinny, whiny thing.''
 &HT;    It turns out it's just Ally having a nightmare, of course.
 &HT;    Funny stuff, to be sure. But the reality behind the jokes is
something that Kelley, Flockhart, Boyle and their peers had better
take a good look at.
 &HT;    Otherwise it is their fans, young girls and teen-agers across
America and beyond, who may be the ones who die laughing.
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site
at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood
Stars and other features. &QL; 
