<HEADER>
A6117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-KILLER-SUB-BOS &LR;      07-01 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-KILLER-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR SEES FRIEND LEAD RAID ON HER VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects time reference in lede)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUSHK, Yugoslavia _ The first time the Serb paramilitaries
encircled this tiny rural hamlet was April 17, less than than a
month after NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia started.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you will be killed if you don't leave,'' said the man
in the distinctive blue uniform of the feared Ministry of Interior
Police, known as MUPs, the chief agents of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's vision of ethnic hatred.
</P>
<P>
   A band of paramilitaries accompanied them in a mix of camouflage
uniforms, along with some Yugoslav army soldiers. They went house
to house, stealing jewelry, demanding money, and stealing most of
the cars.
</P>
<P>
   As the paramilitaries ransacked their way through the village,
Liria Gashi, 38, saw her former neighbor, Zvonimir Svetkovic, 42.
They had grown up together. He was a of her older brothers and they
all attended the Ramiz Sadiku elementary school in downtown Pec.
</P>
<P>
   She could tell by his nervous movements and the wavy, dark hair
tucked under an Australian bush hat that it was the neighbor she
knew by his nickname ``Zvonko,'' she said in an extended interview.
He was a father of three girls. Their families had been close. It
was before the hatreds of Kosovo spilled into war.
</P>
<P>
   Gashi, more out of surprise than courage, said just before he
left the village, ``Zvonko? Is that you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not from here,'' he said, but his voice made her certain
it was him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zvonko, it's me. It's Liliana. We grew up together for 18
years. I know your whole family,'' she remembered saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you here?'' he asked, looking stunned, then angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is from this village,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have children?'' he asked coldly.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't take it as a friendly inquiry by an old neighbor. She
thought she was trying to find out if she had sons in the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have five daughters,'' she lied, not telling him of her
16-year-old son hiding in a chicken coop behind the barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave here,'' he said as he jumped into an idling military
``It's the only way I can save you.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after the NATO bombing began, the Serb forces _ this
time there were nearly 100 _ again encircled the warren of stucco
farm houses. The village of about 400 had been too proud and
defiant to leave, as most ethnic Albanian Kosovars had.
</P>
<P>
   While Gashi hid between the headboard of her bed and the wall,
peering through a crack in the window frame, the men were separated
from the women.
</P>
<P>
   She saw Svetkovic, his head shaven and his face covered in green
paint and a camouflage bandana. He seemed to be leading the men.
She stared in horror and shook in fear. She was afraid he was
looking for her.
</P>
<P>
   The last time she saw Svetkovic, he was taking two male members
of her family to a house down a dirt path next to hers. Moments
later there were bursts of gunfire. Then the sound of crackling
fire. Later she learned that 45 people from the village had been
shot at close range, and their bodies set ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   This atrocity, confirmed by three men who miraculously survived,
photographs of charred bodies taken by family members before they
buried them, and investigators for the war crimes tribunal at the
Hague, was one of dozens of such attacks throughout the Pec area,
and as many as 100 throughout Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And Gashi has been left to grieve and to wonder about
``Zvonko's'' descent into depravity.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who knew him say that in 1989 he began attending
Serbian ultranationalist rallies in town. He stopped talking to his
ethnic Albanian neighbors about soccer and his passion for cars. By
1992, he was listening to loud Serbian nationalist music in his
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   When his ethnic Albanian neighbors' children played too close to
his side of the garden, he screamed at them and insulted them. When
an Albanian family left an outdoor light on near his bedroom
window, he would reach out with the butt of a rifle and smash it.
His house beaome a local headquarters for the paramilitary unit
known as the ``Frenkis.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the house was looted by ethnic Albanian neighbors who
had returned, and large wooden crates of ammunition and a dozen
paramilitary uniforms lay in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   Sali Seremeti, 46, was once a close friend of Svetkovic. But on
the morning of March 25, he was not surprised when Svetkovic banged
on his door with the butt of a rifle and told the family to leave
their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had gone mad. He changed into something very ugly,'' said
Seremeti. ``We all watched it happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
