<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6129 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BILTMORE04-COX     07-01 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BILTMORE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A suite bonus for those who visit Biltmore
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 4
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four newly restored bedrooms on the third floor of Asheville's
circa-1895 Biltmore Estate are included in the tour of George
Vanderbilt's grand chateau in the Blue Ridge Mountains.
Collectively known as the Artists' Suite, the rooms' names _
Watson, Van Dyck, Morland and Madonna _ allude to artists and works
represented in Vanderbilt's collection.
</P>
<P>
   When the meticulous floor-to-ceiling restoration began three
years ago, Biltmore curators found mostly bare walls, scraps of
wallpaper and holes where prints once hung _ few clues as to the
former grandeur of the rooms. Extensive research by design
detectives revealed the look of the original wallpaper, textile and
architectural details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was essential to interpret how these rooms might
have been furnished and how they were used in daily life at the
turn of the century,'' says Ellen Rickman, staff collections
curator. Visitors to the Biltmore Estate this summer will find
other enhancements including:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Explore Biltmore Estate: This environmental adventure program
puts visitors in touch with Biltmore's land, history and outdoor
culture. Activities offered through Sept. 4 include a 90-minute
float on the French Broad River; a 90-minute, moderate off-trail
hike; and a 30-minute carriage ride through Biltmore's agricultural
areas. One-day admission plus additional fee.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden Treasure Walks: These 90-minute strolls provide a
historical overview of the grounds, with an emphasis on seasonal
flora, and offer advice for the home gardener. Three walks daily;
$11.95 per person.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Conservatory: The centerpiece to Frederick Law Olmstead's
75 acres of formally landscaped gardens and grounds has reopened
after a two-year, $2.5 million restoration. The 7,500-square-foot
facility boasts a 12,000-square-foot basement as its most unusual
feature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Summer Evening Concerts: Music will ring from the South
Terrace on Saturday nights in August as Biltmore hosts orchestral
and jazz bands. ``An Evening With Roberta Flack'' is the season
finale on Aug. 22. Tickets $35-$40.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-922-0018 or www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
