<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6130 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-GETAWAY02-COX     07-01 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GETAWAY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A sampling of Southern celebrations that mark Independence Day
with red, white and blue panache
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stars rise
</P>
<P>
   over Alabama
</P>
<P>
   Country stars Billy Dean and Martina McBride (left) will warm up
the holiday crowds for a rip-snortin' fireworks display Saturday
during the Albertville Freedom Festival. The party begins Friday
evening with a concert by Pat Upton and the Downtown Horns,
followed by the Classic Rock All-Stars. Saturday's daytime
festivities include competition between area fireman brigades, arts
and crafts exhibits, concession booths and Kids Stuff events.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Gates open 4 p.m. Friday, 8 a.m. Saturday.
Tickets are $5 per day; free for ages 10 and younger and 65 and
older. 256-878-3821.
</P>
<P>
   Red, white
</P>
<P>
   and blues
</P>
<P>
   Memphis' Beale Street Historic District _ home of the blues _
will roll out the red carpet for revelers Sunday during the Fourth
on Beale celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment will begin at 4 p.m. in Handy Park, with acts
including O'Landa Draper's Associates, the Boogies Blues Band and
Kevin Page, and the Average White Band. AWB is known for its funky
hits such as ``Pick Up the Pieces,'' ``Schoolboy Crush,'' ``If Ever
I Lose This Heaven'' and ``Queen of My Soul.'' Fireworks will
follow the concert. Food concessions will be available throughout
the evening.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Music starts at 4 p.m. Free. 801-526-0110.
</P>
<P>
   A Disney blast
</P>
<P>
   Fireworks are an everyday experience at Disney World with more
than 1,000 shows a year _ but things really explode on the Fourth.
Leave it to the Mouse to plan the most eye-popping party in the
Southeast with special events and fireworks resortwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic Kingdom will be open 9 a.m.-1 a.m. Sunday. When night
falls, Fantasy in the Sky, the nightly fireworks show, gives way to
``Red, White and Blue,'' an 18-minute show of patriotic music and
more than 900 pyrotechnic devices. The Main Street Electrical
Parade sparkles at 10:30 p.m. and midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Epcot, which will be open 9 a.m.-10 p.m.,
IllumiNations celebrates Independence Day with music, lasers,
lights, fireworks and a grand finale that explodes nearly 500
shells in less than two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And at Disney-MGM Studios, open 9 a.m.-11 p.m., ``Sorcery in the
Sky'' fires up at 10:30 p.m. with famous movie music. Disney's
Mulan Parade is at 4:30 p.m.; and the ``Fantasmic!'' shows are at
9:15 p.m. and 11 p.m. More festivities are planned at Downtown
Disney's Pleasure Island, Disney Marketplace and the resort's water
parks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 407-824-4321 or www.disneyworld.com
</P>
<P>
   Mountain midnight
</P>
<P>
   madness and more
</P>
<P>
   Stifle a yawn, and be among the first to celebrate Independence
Day at Gatlinburg's 23rd Annual Fourth of July Midnight Parade,
which begins promptly at 12:01 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The theme is ``Smoky Mountain Millennium.'' Among the featured
participants are Louise Mandrell, the Blackwood Quartet, Boyds
Creek Heavenly Choir and entertainers from area attractions
including Dixie Stampede, Fanny Adams Theatre and Harrah's Cherokee
Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Nine new helium balloons include a UFO, an American Eagle,
Christopher Columbus and his three ships, and an Earth globe. Plus,
Gatlinburg's shops and restaurants will be open for night owls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Entertainment begins at 11:45 p.m. The 1.4-mile
route begins at the Brookside Resort on U.S. 321 and ends at
traffic light 10 on the Parkway at the south end of Gatlinburg.
1-800-267-7088 or www.gatlinburg-tennessee.com
</P>
<P>
   Hot time in the old town
</P>
<P>
   The rockets' red glare and bombs bursting in air will light up
the 17th century Castillo de San Marcos during the Fourth of July
celebration at St. Augustine, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A Dixieland band will get the evening off to a toe-tapping start
with a 5 p.m. performance at the Downtown Plaza gazebo. At 7 p.m.,
the 13th Army Band, the official band of the Florida State National
Guard, will play patriotic tunes on Fort Green in front of the
Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-minute fireworks extravaganza that follows the
performance features more than two tons of colorful explosives that
will be launched from a barge moored in Matanzas Bay near the
Bridge of Lions. Optimum viewing is from the downtown bayfront
area, along the Vilano Causeway, Conch Island, Vilano Beach and the
walkways of bridges crossing the Intracoastal waterway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Music begins at 5 p.m.; fireworks at 9:15 p.m.
Free. 904-825-1010.
</P>
<P>
   Earth-shattering event
</P>
<P>
   We feel safe in saying that the only place you can see a
125-pound anvil shot into the sky this Fourth of July is at the
Museum of Appalachia in Norris, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The anvil will be fired by Sen. Nancy Kassebaum Baker, who will
be carrying on a tradition that dates to pioneer America. Here's
what happens: A blacksmith's anvil is placed upside down on the
ground, its cavity filled with fine black powder. A second anvil is
placed upright on top. The powder is ignited and the top anvil is
blown from 50 to 150 feet in the air as the earth shakes. The boom
can be heard for 15 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-acre farm/village complex will be abuzz all day with
demonstrations of other traditional activities such as sawmilling,
sheep herding, rail splitting, crosscut sawing and buggy rides.
Old-time musicians will play and sing on the porches of the cabins
and in the old log church. Home-cooked food will be available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 8 a.m.-8 p.m. Sunday. Anvil shootings at 10 a.m.,
noon and 2, 4 and 5 p.m. (Baker will light the fuse at 2 p.m.) $7;
$4 ages 6-15; under 6 free. The museum is 16 miles north of
Knoxville, one mile off I-75 (Exit 122). 423-494-0514.
</P>
<P>
   A 116-year-old
</P>
<P>
   tradition
</P>
<P>
   The first official celebration of the Fourth of July in North
Carolina will be relived when Old Salem, a restored Moravian town,
holds its 34th Annual Torchlight Procession on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The records of Salem Diary show that on July 4, 1783, the
Moravian settlement of Salem held a full day's events ``for the
restoration of peace.'' The day ended when the congregation
gathered after an 8 p.m. service to process through illuminated
streets with music, antiphonal choral singing and a blessing before
returning to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The re-creation of this procession will highlight historic
interpretive events Saturday and Sunday in the living history
village.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Exhibit buildings will be open 9 a.m.-4:30 p.m.
Saturday, 1-7 p.m. Sunday; the procession begins at 9 p.m. Sunday
at Salem Square. Two-day tickets $15; $8 ages 5-16. 1-888-653-7253
or www.oldsalem.org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
