<P>
   &QR;  RESOURCE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Food Lover's Companion to Tuscany'' by Carla Capalbo
(Chronicle Books, $14.95). If you are driving around on your own,
this book is nearly indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frommer's Food Lover's Companion to Italy'' by Marc and Kim
Millon (Macmillan Travel, $19.95). An authoritative guide, with
detailed glossaries to help you translate those Italian menus. Very
helpful to those interested in learning about the various pastas,
cheeses and cured meat products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Splendid Table: Recipes From Emilia-Romagna, the Heartland
of Northern Italian Cuisine'' by Lynne Rossetto Kaspar (Morrow,
$35). Winner of a James Beard award and an International
Association of Culinary Professionals/Julia Child cookbook award,
this is the definitive source on the region's recipes and foodways.
It belongs in the kitchen of anyone who cares about Italian food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italian Food'' by Elizabeth David (Penguin, $14). A classic by
the grande dame of British culinary letters. No one writes more
lyrically about food. Just turn to Page 49 and see what she has to
say about olives.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Italian Government Tourist Board, 630 Fifth Ave., Suite 1565,
New York, NY 10111; 212-245-5618, fax, 212-586-9249;
www.italiantourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
