<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6132 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ITALY1STTAKE04     07-01 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ITALY1STTAKE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Italy: The art of eating well
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 4.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLOGNA, Italy _ Before I went to New York or New Orleans,
before I went anywhere really, I went to Italy. Fresh off the farm,
20 years old, a classics student on his first trip abroad, I wore
white tennis shorts, pink Izods and plastic glasses as big as
diving goggles. Most of the time, I was in ruins. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Pompeii and Paestum. The Pantheon. The Forum. We read Virgil's
``Aeneid'' and kept the Blue Guide to Rome in our hip pockets.
</P>
<P>
   And the food? At that age, Bologna meant sandwiches, and
Parmesan cheese came out of a shaker. ``First, we were served pasta
with meat sauce,'' says my journal entry of June 30, 1980, the day
of my first Italian meal, at a pensione in Rome. ``Then, we had
fried veal and a salad. Of course, there was plenty of bread and
water, too.''
</P>
<P>
   I had come here to study the arts, but the art of eating well
escaped me. I was more interested in how Caravaggio's light
transformed a bowl of peaches and grapes than I was in tasting the
ripened flesh. Ecstasy was Bernini's Santa Teresa, an arrow at her
heart, swooning in yards of cloth cut from marble. I didn't know
that pasta-making could be a form of sculpture, too, that moistened
flour could be folded around a lump of meat and cheese,
miraculously transformed into the bright yellow, bellybutton-shaped
pasta known as tortellini.
</P>
<P>
   All this changed recently, when my best friend gave me a ticket
to Bologna and suggested that we explore Emilia-Romagna, the
northern region known as ``the belly of Italy.'' Over 10 bright
days and cool nights this spring, we explored Italy's other Holy
Trinity: prosciutto di Parma (Parma ham); Parmigiano-Reggiano
(Parmesan cheese); and the balsamic vinegars of Modena and
surrounding towns.
</P>
<P>
   This is a culture that rightly sings the praises of its lusty
cuisine, which embraces every kind of combination of cheese, meat
and pasta under the sun. And in Emilia-Romagna, the purest balsamic
vinegars are kept in tiny flagons, coveted like heirlooms or holy
relics, even used as dowries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only one word could describe Emilia-Romagna, it would have
to be `rich,''' says Lynne Rosetto Kaspar in ``The Splendid
Table,'' a paean to the region's food. ``Not rich in the sense of
fat, but rich in dishes of deep, layered tastes. Even at its
simplest, Emilia-Romagna's food tastes as if it has evolved from a
long tradition. Yet there is always a spontaneity to what you
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly our approach. With a rental car and a few
guidebooks, but no advance reservations, we wandered the
countryside and found some of the loveliest scenes _ and
best-tasting food _ in unexpected places.
</P>
<P>
   Did we make it to nearby Ravenna, site of those ravishingly
beautiful Byzantine mosaics that inspired William Butler Yeats?
Heck, no. We even zipped past Florence, to the Tuscan wine country,
to sip some of the best reds in the world. Imagine a 2,000-year-old
Napa Valley, and you get the idea of this green, undulating
landscape, where you can buy acacia honey, fresh-made pecorino
cheese and pungent olive oils straight from the source.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason why this food tastes better, and it has little
to do with best-selling travelogues, decaying villas or romantic
light. It has everything to do with the farmers I saw handing
purple-tinged artichokes and bunches of green-silver sage to their
neighbors. In this land of exquisite produce and baaing sheep, the
time between field and table is but a minute. The flavors never get
a chance to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   But you do.
</P>
<P>
   At a shop in Pienza, we watched a man carve porchetta (whole
roasted pig seasoned with rosemary, garlic, wild fennel and lots of
salt and pepper) and stuff it between thick slices of Tuscan bread
to make a sandwich. The flavor was amazing.
</P>
<P>
   At the idyllic Locanda dell'Amorosa, a hotel-restaurant-wine bar
near Sinalunga, Tuscany, I had the best risotto I've ever tasted _
a perfect amalgam of rice, nettle, ricotta and chopped tomatoes:
emerald green, red, white. Before lunch, we sat in the garden
sipping wine and admiring an explosion of purple irises, roses and
wisteria. Afterward, we returned to take grappa. An Italian woman,
her gray hair knotted on her head, sat under an umbrella with her
husband and two sons, drinking in the luminous day. We were certain
we'd found la dolce vita.
</P>
<P>
   Another day, we rambled along a cypress-lined dirt road from
Montalcino to Montepulciano, through a bucolic landscape
upholstered with sheep. In tiny Monticchiello, we asked the locals
to point us up the hill to Taverna di Morando. We'd heard it was
good, and it was. Chicken livers _ sauteed in a little butter,
white wine and garlic _ were the best I have ever tasted. Dessert
was a glass of vin santo (the local after-dinner wine that's as
sweet as honeysuckle) and a pair of oaty, almondy biscotti. This
was simple food at its best.
</P>
<P>
   But even as you follow your gut, you cannot escape the pull of
history, time, art, architecture.
</P>
<P>
   In Parma's massive museum _ with its cantilevered galleries
suspended in a hulking old Farnese palace shattered during World
War II _ you look around to see a beautiful Leonardo girl on an
easel. In Modena, well-buffed medieval churches are stacked like
wedding cakes. From dawn to dusk, their colors change like
evanescent lozenges _ white, pink, gray.
</P>
<P>
   Bologna is a never-ending cavalcade of columns, block after
block of arched porticoes, under which society has mingled through
the ages. This city reputedly has the oldest university in the
world, founded in the 12th century. Today, observing kids push
money into sidewalk cigarette machines today, you imagine the
civilization that preceded them: Did Renaissance brides, feuding
lords, nuns and soldiers once tread here? In the town center, two
red brick medieval towers lean like upset chessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Emilia-Romagna may well be Italy's best-kept secret. It's a
worthy alternative for travelers wishing to skirt the busy grand
tour destinations of Venice, Florence and Rome. I put it off for 20
years, thanks to the train station bombing that killed 85 people
within days of my passing through, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But we made up for the lost time _ and managed to feel like
innocents abroad once again. And since the authorities didn't
declare us personae non grappa (wink, wink), we'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, is a city-by-city guide. Recommended establishments
are highlighted in bold. Addresses and phone numbers are provided
in the accompanying sidebar.
</P>
<P>
   BOLOGNA
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is fully-fully,'' said the voice over the phone from
the hotel. We were about to leave Atlanta for Bologna, and to our
horror, the city was completely booked by a convention of
cosmetologists (we were to witness some great hair and fashion,
though). We had no choice but to wing it.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, we got a place at Agriturismo Cavaione, a pair
of rambling farmhouses in the hills just south of Bologna. The
agricultural-tourism concept allows visitors to rent rooms in a
hands-on environment (on fruit and vegetable farms, or with makers
of olive oil, honey or cheese, for example). In our case, we were
surrounded by grapevines and rolling fields of wildflowers. Davide,
our spritely, smiling host, let us try the house Lambrusco, the
spritzy local red wine. Not a bad tonic for jet lag. Suddenly, we
felt like Patsy and Edina on ``Absolutely Fabulous'' _ remember the
segment in which they drive a rental car to the rustic farmhouse in
the South of France?
</P>
<P>
   At La Felina, a two-story country trattoria down the road, we
ordered our first affettati misti, a platter of mixed regional
meats, including prosciutto, salame, pancetta and copa. The
waitress brought us warm crescenti (crescents of fried dough). We
stuffed them with the cold cuts and butter and inhaled. And it was
here that we tasted our first _ and only _ mortadella (bologna
sausage), cut into cubes and mixed with rice at the antipasto
table. And on it went: fat little tortellini in a creamy sauce;
gramigna con salsiccia (spiral pasta with sweet, crumbled sausage);
a huge slab of steak with a rich, balsamic vinegar sauce. Talk
about ``fully-fully.''
</P>
<P>
   Intown, our favorite perch was Bar Pasticceria San Domenico, an
old-fashioned confectionary shop across from Basilica San Domenico.
The 12th-century cathedral is the center of the Domenican order,
and it sits on a handsome square with pillared Victorian-style
crypts off to the side. We took coffee in the bar, and wondered at
the shop's immense cases of sweets; its tall, drugstore jars of
fancy hard candies; those cute little grappa sets. According to the
press on the walls, this is one of Italy's best bars. We agree: The
bartender sure knows how to shake a martini. At happy hour, the
kitchen puts out all sorts of nibbles, from nuts and olives to
boiled eggs and little anchovy-flavored pastries. It's a great
people-watching place, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1518EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6134 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ITALY2NDTAKE04     07-01 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ITALY2NDTAKE04-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLOGNA, Italy: people-watching place, too.
</P>
<P>
   MODENA
</P>
<P>
   I'll never forget the saleslady at the food shop off the main
square of town. Trying to sell us an $80, 3/4-ounce bottle of aceto
balsamico tradizionale di Modena, she kissed her fingers, smacked
her lips and said that you haven't lived until you try it with ice
cream. She was speaking Italian, but we understood.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the balsamic vinegar capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes northwest of Bologna, on the Via Emilia _ the
old Roman road that connects the region's most notable food
destinations _ Modena is a spic-and-span jewel box of medieval
architecture, fashion boutiques and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to chef Massimo Bottura's inventive use of local
ingredients, Osteria La Francescana is beginning to get
international press. We loved-loved-loved the trio of
Parmigiano-Reggiano preparations: a custard, a creme and a crisp.
House-made gnocchi was green with herbs, and coddled in cream. With
dessert, we had our first sip of nocino, a regional digestif made
from crushed green walnuts. Emilians pour the sweet liqueur with
pride and hospitality. We liked it, and the excellent wine list,
very much.
</P>
<P>
   One of our favorite stops of the entire tour was Ristorante
Lancellotti, a family-run inn and restaurant in Soliera, a little
town just outside Modena, where we checked in for a night.
</P>
<P>
   It isthe place to sample the rarest of cured meat products,
which the kitchen strews with herbs from its garden. Lardo _ which
is little more than thinly sliced (and disguised) fatback _ is
aromatized with fragrant herbs. It melts on the tongue. We also
sampled our first culatello, a sliced cured ham with a richer,
redder, more intense flavor than prosciutto. To cleanse the
palette, we loved the apple salad, tossed with fresh chives and
other herbs.
</P>
<P>
   And, boy, does Mama Ida Lancelloti know how to roll out the egg
pasta. Tortelloni, vibrant with yolk, was stuffed with ricotta and
spinach and tossed with butter. Delicious. The baby roast pig was
one of the best pieces of pork I've ever tasted. We asked Emilio
Lancellotti if we could have one to go.
</P>
<P>
   We were too embarrassed to mention our pig-nic plan the next
morning, but we sure bought a bottle of the house-label nocino and
traditional balsamic vinegar. Emilio explained how the vinegar is
aged in smaller and smaller barrels until it has achieved its
purest state _ a process that takes 12 years, often longer. You can
buy lesser balsamics all over the region, but if you want the best,
look for the tradizionale label, which is
</P>
<P>
   the sign that it's certified by the producers' consortium.
</P>
<P>
   REGGIO
</P>
<P>
   Tucked between Modena and Parma, this foodie destination is
where the other half of Parmesan cheese _ Parmigiano-Reggiano _
gets its name. Here, at Trattoria Della Ghiara, we stumbled upon
another memorable meal, where balsamic vinegar and local cheese are
front and center on nearly every dish.
</P>
<P>
   Elegant, cool, thin slices of rabbit filet were fanned out
across a salad of radicchio and fresh field greens. It was an easy
segue to the fusilli with puttanesca sauce, a delicious marriage of
anchovy, tomato, garlic and olive oil. Were we full yet? Of course,
but we still had to try the rosemary-scented veal and the steak
with Parmesan shavings and balsamic vinegar. Before departing, we
struck up a conversation with our sweet-natured waiter, and it
turned out that he's a beekeeper and member of the balsamic
consortium of Reggio.
</P>
<P>
   PARMA
</P>
<P>
   A lovely city with an abundance of art galleries, Parma turned
out to be a timeless and evocative place. The Duomo and baptistry
are the apotheosis of the region's distinctive Romanesque
architecture. In an old convent, the Camera di San Paolo is an
exquisitely restored chamber of rooms with frescoes by Corregio.
The Palazzo della Pilotta, built by the Farneses at the end of the
16th century, is the home of the National Gallery (where we saw the
Leonardo). Another treasure within its monumental walls is the
Farnese Theater, a perfect wooden copy of a Palladian original.
</P>
<P>
   About the food: Skip the highly touted La Greppia, and go to La
Filoma. Its pasta ranked among the best of our journey.
Particularly good were the strozzapreti (literally, ``priest
stranglers''), a somewhat hard-to-find regional gnocchi. I won't
speculate on the etymology of that name, but I adored these
dumplings, stuffed with ricotta and spinach. Those bold enough to
try the veal cheeks will discover that it's the tenderest part of
the calf. With its attentive service and stylish clientele, this
place was a find.
</P>
<P>
   MONTEPULCIANO,
</P>
<P>
   MONTALCINO
</P>
<P>
   AND ENVIRONS
</P>
<P>
   Wine and roses. Honey and pecorino cheese. Purple skies and a
range of mountains that's as arresting as a quilt of emeralds.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the best, the only, balcony at Caffe Poliziano at the
very top of Montepulciano at sunset, I thought we'd finally gotten
everything right. This is where you go when you need to unclutter
the mind _ be it a two-day purge or a six-month sabbatical.
</P>
<P>
   You probably know about the friendly, go-with-anything Chianti
Classico. It's got its own region nearby. But the Vino Nobiles of
Montepulciano and the Brunellos of Montalcino are in a league of
their own. Conveniently, the towns are only about 45 minutes apart.
That we were able to taste freely, eat well and happen upon such
picture-perfect scenery made for a bittersweet ending to a
well-nigh perfect escape. Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montepulciano. Get a room on a hill in the ancient walled
city, park the car and take the walking wine tour. Start with an
espresso drink at Caffe Poliziano (I don't recommend dinner at the
adjoining restaurant). From there, it only takes about a half-day
to hit the major vintners. One of the best is Contucci, with its
cavernous, cobwebby cellars in a 16th-century palazzo off the main
square. On Saturdays, go down to the street market just outside the
old city walls and watch the local farmers put out those awesome
melons, peaches, asparagus, artichokes _ whatever's in season.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pienza. This town is synonymous with the sheep's milk cheese
called pecorino. Just outside the main road between Montepulciano
and Pienza, stop at Formaggi Silvana Cugusi, where the view's
wonderful and the cheese is even better. The brown-crusted wheels
set the standard for the region; some are rubbed with tomato paste,
which imparts an extra layer of flavor, others dusted with ash or
wrapped in walnut leaves. Ask for a crumb of the ``reserved.'' This
sour-salty granddaddy of them all is remarkable. And yes, you may
photograph the sheep.
</P>
<P>
   We hit Pienza proper in the throes of May Day, so all the
restaurants were overbooked. But this being a food lovers' mecca,
we didn't go hungry. La Cornucopia food shop is a good place to
stock up on truffles, olive oil, pate and honey. I even found a
dreamy sandalwood cologne made in Florence. Haven't tasted it yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montalcino. Strolling into the Fattoria dei Barbi, a winery
and tavern on the outskirts of town, I was reminded of the Mondavi
estate in California. The place has impeccable style, yet it's very
low-key. Besides the Brunellos (which you can find at Atlanta's
Sotto Sotto), they make a grappa that is both firm-gripping and
complex. And a mighty sweet little Vin Santo. We bought one of each
to take home.
</P>
<P>
   Montalcino is an oenophile's dream.
</P>
<P>
   I particularly liked Enoteca Osteria Osticcio, where
English-speaking owner Tullio Scrivani set me up with a couple of
bottles of hard-to-come-by Gravner. The place also has a glassed-in
view of the valley that makes an inspiring nook for sitting and
sipping.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monticchiello. Heading back to Montepulciano for the night, we
took Scrivani's advice and wended our way through this
speck-on-a-map town to try the home cooking at Taverna di Morando.
A cozy, romantic hideaway, it had a kitchen that could do no wrong.
Alice Waters and Atlanta's own Anne Quatrano (Floataway Cafe) would
probably weep over the simple, straightforward roasted rabbit and
lamb, redolent of garlic and rosemary. Best of all, everybody in
the place seemed to be having fun. And when we asked our waitress
to explain one dish (a pasta with duck), she quacked.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sinalunga. How did I love Locando dell'Amorosa? Let me count
the ways. Veal steak in a black olive crust with fried celery.
Grilled sea bass with red chicory salad. I could loll on the
grounds of this hotel-restaurant compound _ there's even a chapel _
for a very long time. It's the sort of place where you hope
tomorrow will never come.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
