<HEADER>
A6135 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-01 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME DOGS _ AND CATS, TOO _ LIKE TO EAT GRASS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: My dog is eating grasses whenever we are in rural
settings. What grasses can I plant for her? How do I care for them?
</P>
<P>
   A: I can't say which grasses a dog prefers, and from what I've
read, no one is really sure why dogs even eat grass. Pet columnists
are often asked why dogs eat grass and then sometimes throw up.
Some theorize the animal does so because of a nutritional
deficiency; others believe it is to calm an upset stomach. A third
answer: Dogs graze for pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   A diet of high-quality food and multiple vitamins, of course,
will ensure there is no nutritional deficiency. I've heard of dog
owners adding cooked green vegetables to the pet's diet to
discourage his eating grass.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be that some dogs _ and cats, too _ like to eat
grass because they like the taste or that it does actually calm
irritated stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen our pets munch on various ornamental grasses,
including Mexican feather grass, Japanese silver grass and purple
fountain grass. These grasses, especially the purple fountain
grass, are often available at nurseries. Avoid pesticide use on
``grazing'' grasses.
</P>
<P>
   I've also seen cats and dogs eat other grasses, even ``weedy''
types.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a winding flagstone walkway in our garden. The spaces
between the stones are filled with sand. After most rains the sand
washes out and must be refilled.
</P>
<P>
   A ground-cover book suggests Irish moss, and a local nursery
suggested Corsican grass. I cannot find either of these plants.
</P>
<P>
   Can you recommend something locally available that will tolerate
foot traffic, or can you tell me where I may find the two suggested
plants?
</P>
<P>
   A: I do not have a source for either suggestions. Nor do I know
if they would even be good for your growing area. I would consider,
however, one or more of the following to plant between flagstones.
They should not be too difficult to find.
</P>
<P>
   The dense, dark-green, 3-inch tufts of dwarf mondo grass
tolerate sun or shade and various soils but thrive in soil that
drains well. To ensure a little nutrition, work some humus into the
sand around your flagstones.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial herbs such as thyme and oregano will grow between the
stones in sun or partial sun, as will clumping sweet violets and
the diminutive, spreading Australian violets, which display small
leaves inches above the ground and tiny white and purple flowers on
slender stems. The soil need not be too rich but must drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Knotweed, ``Polygonum capitatum'' `Pink Buttons', hugs the
ground, spreading by jointed stems to form a mat of oval,
bronze-green foliage that turns red or orange in fall. Small, pink,
globelike blooms appear for months. I use this reliable creeper
between stones in bright shade and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Spotted leopard tongue, ``Mazus reptans,'' has narrow, toothed
leaves and violet or white flowers. This perennial ground cover
forms a mat in sun to bright shade.
</P>
<P>
   Ajuga, or bugleweed, is another consideration. This clumping
spreader is only 3 to 4 inches tall. It prefers partial sun to
light shade, and though ajuga likes water, this per- ennial needs
good drainage. Foliage coloring varies with cultivars; flowers may
be white or blue.
</P>
<P>
   Creeping Jenny (``Lysimachia nummularia'') is a low-grower that
accepts sun or shade. The small, rounded leaves are light green,
and as the plant spreads it roots at the nodes. Creeping Jenny is
approximately 4 inches tall and has yellow flowers in summer. It
likes a moist soil.
</P>
<P>
   There are several low-growing sedums that would work in a path.
The succulent leaves would provide a nice contrast to the stones.
In spring you would have a mass of tiny flowers. You could use more
than one type to heighten interest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The roots that appear on top of the ground around my red
maple trees make it difficult to mow. Is there something I can do
to keep these roots below the soil surface? I have tried chopping
the roots on top of the ground, but this is hard work.
</P>
<P>
   A: As with some trees, red maple roots may rise above the
surface as they mature and thicken. I would not chop the roots for
fear of damaging the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Tree roots generally are within the top 18 inches of soil. It's
possible to remove a larger root on some trees, but this should be
done one root at a time and only once a year. And I would only do
so under the guidance of an arborist.
</P>
<P>
   Water your trees deeply during long, dry spells so the soil is
moist several inches down. Shallow watering encourages roots to
rise to the moisture.
</P>
<P>
   I have a maple with a considerable root system, and because of
this and the shade the tree creates, I found it easy and attractive
to just use a ground cover beneath the tree's canopy.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider some of the following ground covers or simply
use a layer of mulch beneath the canopies of your trees.
</P>
<P>
   Variegated ``Vinca major,'' commonly called periwinkle, works
nicely under our large red maple. It has a loose and airy look, and
the white on the foliage brightens the shade. The trailing stems
root where they touch the ground, and before long the new plantlet
becomes a mound. But if you're after an instantly full look, buy
several 4-inch pots and pack them in beneath the tree. This plant
produces pretty blue flowers that appear among the white and green
foliage in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ajuga and ardisia are among the most dependable ground covers
for use beneath shade trees. Others are Asian jasmine and liriope.
With variegated liriope you could vary the height by planting the
regular 12-inch size and the giant variegated liriope, which
matures to about 3 feet. I think the use of dwarf mondo grass is
attractive, too. I like the 3-inch-tall, dense, dark-green tufts.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider using ferns, either alone or with another
ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   Creeping Jenny (``Lysimachia nummularia''), mentioned earlier,
is a low-grower (4 inches tall) that accepts sun or shade and has
small, rounded, light-green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Australian violets, also mentioned previously, would work well.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever ground cover you choose, remember to monitor the
moisture while the plants take root. If you go with a
moisture-lover, you'll need to make sure the big trees don't take
too much away from the ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to arrange plants in front of the fireplace
while it is not in use. There is no direct light and not much
reflected light in this area, but the room is well-lighted at
night. Which plants would be most suitable for such an area?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first plant that pops into my head as something that can
tolerate moderate light and low humidity is the mother-in-law
tongue, ``Sansevieria trifasciata.'' I'm sure you've seen this
plant _ it has vertical, fleshy foliage with light or dark-green
cross stripes; one variety has yellow margins.
</P>
<P>
   Mother-in-law tongue needs less-than-average watering and
biweekly to monthly applications of a standard liquid houseplant
food when actively growing. Water sparingly during winter.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese evergreen, ``Aglaonema commutatum,'' produces a
dome-shaped clump of gray-green leaves. Some have variegations.
While this plant tolerates less light than some, it does like
humidity and is best when its pot stands on a tray filled with
moist pebbles.
</P>
<P>
   Pothos ivy is an easy-to-grow standby. You might try aspidistra,
which produces its large, deep-green leaves in the shadiest spots
in the garden. Indoors it is tolerant of low light as well.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide the light is just too low for even these plants, a
large basket of dried flowers and foliage would be an easy
alternative. Large bouquets of hydrangea blossoms always look great
in baskets or vases. Dried poppy-seed pods and other seed pods also
make nice arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you please tell me why my bougainvillea does not bloom?
It was in full bloom when I bought it a year ago. It has no
evidence of any disease and has put on a lot of growth.
</P>
<P>
   A: Bougainvillea brachts seem to color best after repeated dry
periods, so watch the watering. Many people say the plants bloom
best when somewhat pot-bound.
</P>
<P>
   Apply a potash-rich (represented by the last number in the
formula) fertilizer at least twice a year _ in late spring and
midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners use hibiscus fertilizer, which has a high potash
number. One expert gets good color by applying 1 tablespoon of
hibiscus food and 1 tablespoon of Epsom salt each month. Always
water before and after fertilizing. There also are special,
controlled-release bougainvillea fertilizers on the market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
