<SLUG> BC-TREK-NICOLE-DE-BOER-IN-CUBE-ART-ADV12-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV12 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 SQUARE DEAL: NICOLE DE BOER AND `CUBE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JULY 12, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Nicole de
Boer with Maurice Dean Wint, David Hewlett and Andrew Miller in a
scene from ``Cube.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The only thing smaller than the splash made by a microbudgeted
American movie is the one made by the same movie if it's from
Canada.
 &HT;    Ask Nicole de Boer, recent survivor of ``Star Trek: Deep Space
Nine.''
 &HT;    In 1998, just before she got her big break on the show, de Boer
co-starred in ``Cube,'' a nifty, futuristic drama about six
prisoners struggling to escape from a booby-trapped cube floating
in space. With a tiny $500,000 budget, the Canadian production
received rave reviews, raked in a few million dollars at the box
office and attracted a cult following.
 &HT;    ``Cult following,'' in this case, meaning that a lot of people
heard it was good but hardly anyone saw it.
 &HT;    That may change on Sat., July 24, however. At 9 p.m. (EDT)
``Cube'' will make its television debut on the Sci-Fi Channel. It
will almost certainly be seen by more people in that two-hour span
than have seen it in its entire existence to date.
 &HT;    ``I always knew it was a good film, but a lot of people never
see a lot of good films,'' de Boer says. ``Everybody was shocked at
how well `Cube' did. I guess it just really appeals to that kind of
a cult audience.
 &HT;    ``Now, with the film on video and on the Sci-Fi Channel, even
more people will get to see it,'' she adds. ``That can only be a
good thing.''
 &HT;    Anyone tuning in can expect a tense, taut affair, with de Boer
cast as Leaven, a math brainiac who just might help her fellow
prisoners get out alive. But that's only if the prisoners'
intensifying paranoia and frustration don't drive them to kill each
other as they trek from room to identical room in the
multidimensional cube.
 &HT;    ``It's basically about people, our existence and how we move
through this maze of life,'' the Canadian actress says by telephone
from a Toronto hotel, where she's staying while shooting ``Rated
X,'' an upcoming Showtime movie.
 &HT;    ```Cube' is also about how we deal with each other under
pressure, with the obstacles that come up in our lives,'' she says.
``Then, for Leaven, there's the whole math element, which I suck at
but find very cool. If I were in that cube, I'd probably just stay
there and never move.''
 &HT;    The film arrives on the small screen two months after ``DS9''
concluded its seven-year run. During the show's final season de
Boer played Ezri Dax, an untested Trill brought aboard the space
station as a counselor but thrust into the Federation-Dominion War.
 &HT;    By the series finale, ``What You Leave Behind,'' Ezri had earned
the respect of her crewmates and something more than respect from
Dr. Bashir (Alexander Siddig).
 &HT;    ``In some ways the year went by very quickly, and in some ways
it felt like a good, long year,'' says de Boer, a sci-fi veteran
whose credits include guest shots on ``The Outer Limits,''
``TekWar'' and ``Psi Factor,'' as well as a stint as a regular on
the Sci-Fi Channel series, ``Mission Genesis.''
 &HT;    ```DS9' was a very special experience, just to be on a `Trek'
show and be part of the whole `Trek' phenomenon,'' she says. ``I
was glad I got the opportunity. It's weird for me to sit here and
think I may never get to do it again, and it's when I think that
way that I think the year went by incredibly fast.''
 &HT;    As for the pairing-off of Ezri and Bashir _ whose first scene in
the finale featured them in bed together _ de Boer couldn't sound
happier.
 &HT;    ``They make a very cute couple,'' she says. ``The last scene
with them was very sweet, but that first scene was not so sweet _
it was pretty sexy, I thought!''
 &HT;    Though the future might hold some kind of ``DS9'' reunion
project, de Boer isn't waiting around. After ``Rated X,'' she's
already signed to star in ``Stalk,'' a dramatic thriller that goes
before the camera in August.
 &HT;    ``I can see on my fan sites that everybody is freaking out
because they think `Rated X' is some sort of porno movie,'' she
says, laughing. ``It's not a porno movie, but it is about the
Mitchell brothers, who sort of got the porno industry going in
California.
 &HT;    ``Charlie Sheen and Emilio Estevez play the brothers, and Emilio
is directing the movie,'' she says. ``I play the wife of one of the
guys _ and there are a bunch of actresses playing wives, because
they went through a number of marriages.
 &HT;    ``It's a good little part,'' she says. ``I'm happy to be working
and to be up here in Toronto and to be paid for working up here in
Toronto.''
 &HT;    And not to be doing science fiction, she adds.
 &HT;    ``I've done so much sci-fi in my career,'' de Boer says, ``and I
don't want to get too locked into it. I just want to keep working
and finding different roles in different kinds of projects.'' 
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Renny Harlin, director of ``Deep Blue Sea,'' talks about the
film they're calling ``Jurassic Shark.''
 SIDEBAR: CONVENTION CALENDAR  
 July 23-25: Vulkon at the Hilton in St. Petersburg, Fla., featuring
James Darren and Peter Jurasik. For information, call (954)
441-8735.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
