<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OCALAN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 Turkey after Ocalan  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The death sentence a state security court handed down this week
for the leader of the violent Kurdish Workers Party, Abdullah
Ocalan, represents a temporary triumph against separatist and
terrorist forces. It also illuminates an identity crisis that
Turkey will have to resolve wisely if it wishes to fulfill the
modernizing aspirations of Kemal Ataturk, the founder of the
Turkish nation-state that succeeded the Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Impassioning as the fate of the convicted terrorist Ocalan may
appear to Turks and Kurds alike, it signifies but a dramatic high
point in Turkey's unacknowledged conflict between a rigid
definition of what it means to be Turkish and a conception of
nationality that includes the linguistic and cultural shadings of
diverse peoples.
</P>
<P>
   The terrorist forms of resistance adopted by Ocalan's party,
known as the PKK, were made possible by the harsh denial of Kurdish
particularity within Turkey. Kurds who assimilated completely were
allowed to exercise the same civil rights as other Turks, but Kurds
who wanted their children to learn Kurdish in school or wanted to
broadcast and publish in their language were treated as enemies of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in the poor, rural areas of southeastern Turkey,
the PKK's provocation has been great and the army's repression
savage. Kurdish terrorist attacks have killed thousands, and the
security forces have destroyed scores of villages and employed
torture and death squads.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish government of Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit is
embarked on a modernizing program that includes reforms in banking
laws, social security, and the state security laws. For its own
sake and not merely to please members of the European Union who
have been hypocritical in their reluctance to grant Turkish
membership in the EU, the government of Turkey should undertake a
modernization that would allow the Kurds to become Turks without
ceasing to be Kurds. That would solve the problem of which Ocalan
was an effect, not a cause.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MARKETS-$ADV0     07-01 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MARKETS-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEIGHBORHOOD'S REBIRTH IS SYMBOL OF NEW CLINTON ECONOMIC PUSH
 &HT;    With CLINTON-MARKETS-DATA. For release Sunday, July 4.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ By the time President Clinton gets to Phoenix this
week, the abandoned Rainbow Market, an adjoining deserted liquor
store and Wong's To Go Chinese Food will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Good riddance, say local residents and city officials. The
market, liquor store and carry-out are the last remains of the
city's most notorious intersection, 24th and Broadway, long a haunt
of drug dealers and crack heads, speakeasies and prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   The intersection is the future site of the ``Four Corners''
development, a project that city planners believe is the key to the
economic revitalization of south Phoenix, the
wrong-side-of-the-tracks community in this booming southwestern
city. The planners envision professional and government offices,
shops, restaurants, a community center and movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But to be successful, ``Four Corners'' is going to need more
than the mix of federal start-up money and local tax dollars that
has nurtured the project so far. It will need the kind of private
investment the president is hoping to spur with his so-called ``New
Markets'' initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton unveiled the ``New Markets'' initiative last January in
New York at the Rev. Jesse Jackson's ``Wall Street Project,'' an
effort to steer private investment to inner cities and rural areas
of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposal, a mix of tax breaks and loan
guarantees to businesses that locate in economically deprived
areas, has yet to be introduced in Congress. Even so, the
president, with corporate executives in tow, leaves Washington on
Tuesday for a six-state, four-day tour of economic trouble spots to
promote the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Phoenix, the group will visit Appalachia, the
Mississippi Delta, the inner cities of Watts and East St. Louis,
and the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation in South Dakota, where
unemployment currently stands at 72 percent. The trip will end with
a conference in Anaheim, Calif., where Clinton will exhort
executives to invest in these and similar communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the strongest economy on record, all right, but
there are still too many poor neighborhoods and rural communities
where prosperity is something you read about, not experience,''
Clinton said recently. ``We want to shine a spotlight on the
pockets of poverty that remain in America, and on the potential
they have for new investment, new jobs, new hope, new
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of his administration, Clinton has marched to
the Rose Garden to trumpet one happy economic development after
another. But this week's trip is an acknowledgement that not every
boat has risen with the tide of the largest economic expansion in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the unfinished business of the Clinton agenda,'' said
Al From, the Democratic Leadership Council (DLC) official who was
one of the architects of the ``New Democrat'' initiatives that
Clinton rode to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix seems an unlikely stop for Clinton's ``New Markets''
tour compared to the other stubborn pockets of poverty he'll visit.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is a hub for manufacturing, technology and financial
services. It has grown from less than 6,000 in 1900 to 1.2 million
today, the 7th most populous city in the country and the
fastest-growing large city since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But despite its travel-brochure image of swaying palms,
shimmering pools, lush golf courses and major league sports
franchises, some areas of the city are anything but an oasis.
Crime, unemployment and poverty are pervasive.
</P>
<P>
   Especially in south Phoenix, and especially around 24th and
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real battlefield _ shootouts almost every night,''
said Melissa Rider, 34, a police officer and lifelong resident of
south Phoenix. Sitting in her police cruiser in front of the
Rainbow Market, she recalled the gun fights she often witnessed
there as a teenager while driving home from high school dances.
``Everybody raced through because nobody ever wanted to get caught
by a red light,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But things began to change in 1989, when neighborhood activists,
organized as the Community Excellence Project Inc., presented a
plan to the Phoenix City Council for reclaiming their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The effort accelerated in 1994 when a 19.9-square-mile area of
south and central Phoenix was declared an ``enterprise community,''
or ``EC,'' under one of the major anti-poverty programs of the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The designation provided the city of Phoenix with a $3 million
grant to create jobs and spur private investments. And two EC
``success stories'' were suggested by city officials to the White
House to be included on the president's south Phoenix itinerary:
the Moreno Welding Inc. and the I.G. Homes Boys and Girls Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out with a $100 bill in my pocket,'' said Leonard
Moreno, standing in the 108-degree heat of the dusty back lot of
Moreno Welding, the business he started 20 years ago in this
worn-down industrial area located less than two miles from 24th and
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a boast, but Moreno is clearly proud of his success.
Moreno Welding grosses nearly $2 million a year today and employs
between 15 and 20 workers who make between $14 and $20 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But what really boosted Moreno's business was a $75,000 loan
guarantee he got in 1995 under the EC program, allowing him to buy
equipment he desperately needed in order to compete for larger
contracts. ``That let me be able to do what I've done,'' he said.
Now he needs additional financial backing to expand his shop.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Moreno Welding may not appear to be a success
story. The parking lot is gravel and the trailer that once served
as offices is surrounded with a chain-link fence topped with razor
wire.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in the neighborhood surrounding the I.G. Homes Boys
and Girls Club, the streets are pock-marked with dilapidated houses
that the city is trying to reclaim.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the club is a state-of-the-art computer learning lab
and an on-site dental clinic that provides virtually free care to
10 children a day, four days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The club received $75,000 in EC funds two years ago and has
leveraged an additional $465,000 to refurbish the facility and add
the learning center and the dental clinic. It is one of only two
Boys and Girls Clubs in the country that provides dental care for
nominal fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could I be a millionaire somewhere else? Probably,'' says
Richard Landgren, or ``Dr. Rick,'' as he is known to the kids at
the club. ``Can I make a difference here? Absolutely,'' he adds.
``But there's a whole conglomeration of people here who are
dedicated to making a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way it's supposed to work _ not just government
but a public and private partnership,'' says Gail Knight, executive
director of the Community Excellence Project. All south Phoenix
needs now is for private investors to look beyond the area's
reputation and recognize its market potential, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
