   RUSHMORE-PARADOX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KEYSTONE, S.D. _ You sure have to pass a lot of hokey,
pseudo-attractions on your way to and from Mount Rushmore. That is
the paradox. In frantic efforts since its 1941 opening to
capitalize on one of America's foremost patriotic shrines,
entrepreneurs in the Black Hills area have surrounded
architect/sculptor Gutzon Borglum's masterpiece with a chaotic
collection of waterparks, reptile farms, chintzy ``Old West''
tourist trap towns and other eyesores. This is America at its
grandiose best and tacky worst. By JEFF GUINN. Story has moved in
``t'' travel category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
