<SLUG> BC-LOVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOVE ETC..': A MILLENNIUM ROMANTIC TRIANGLE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAERENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to the philosophical French to re-examine the romantic
triangle in the light of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But because the new epoch has yet to arrive, the conclusion
reached by the inquiry that is ``Love Etc.,'' opening Friday in New
York City, can only be speculative.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the triangle remains eternally fascinating, and
whether or not the viewer is convinced by the resolution reached by
``Love Etc.'' in its final scene, on Jan. 1, 2000, getting there is
more than half the fun; pondering what one would do in the shoes of
its principal characters adds more.
</P>
<P>
   This film, reminiscent of Truffaut's 1961 classic, ``Jules et
Jim,'' tells the story of Benoit, a shy, staid bank employee who
falls in love with Marie, a young woman he meets through a
personals ad (using as bait a picture of Pierre, his best friend),
marries her and slowly realizes that his friend has mounted a
campaign to win her away.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Marion Vernoux from a screenplay by Dodine Herry and
Ms. Vernoux adapted from ``Talking It Over,'' a novel by Julian
Barnes, ``Love Etc.'' makes the most of convincing performances by
Charlotte Gainsbourg, who won a Cesar nomination for best actress
as the torn Marie; Yves Attal as Benoit, who finds and loses the
greatest happiness he has ever known, and Charles Berling as
Pierre, the feckless, egocentric teacher of literature who has been
Benoit's friend since their school days.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Benoit, in his early 30s, is overjoyed at his
good fortune at winning Marie, a pretty art restorer in her mid-20s
who is taken with his innate decency if not exactly swept away by
love.
</P>
<P>
   On their sunny wedding day, Benoit is pleased that things worked
out for him. Marie tells herself that Benoit is good and kind and
that he loves her. And Pierre suddenly realizes that he is in love
with Marie.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to happen now?'' he asks himself.
</P>
<P>
   Artfully treading a fine line between operatic tragedy and
romantic comedy as it drips the poison of betrayal into the heady
elixir of love, ``Love Etc.'' proceeds unwaveringly and with rising
tension until it reaches its debatable denouement on the Channel
coast at the advent of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Etc.'' is at its best at raising questions and depicting
how three ordinary people approach a solution to the personal
mathematics of an age-old problem in relationships.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   LOVE ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Marion Vernoux; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Dodine Herry and Ms. Vernoux, based on the novel
``Talking It Over'' by Julian Barnes; director of photography, Eric
Gautier; music by Alexandre Desplat and Leonard Cohen, with
additional music by Giacomo Puccini from his opera ``Turandot'';
produced by Patrick Godeau; released by Phaedra Cinema. At the the
Screening Room. Running time: 105 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Charlotte Gainsbourg (Marie), Yvan Attal (Benoit), Charles
Berling (Pierre), Susan Moncur (Susan) and Thibault de Montalembert
(Bernard).
</P>
</TEXT>
