A6204 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAIN-RADAR-(NEW-SCIEN     07-01 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIN-RADAR-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANTAGE, BBC, THANKS TO THE RAIN RADAR  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JULY 5, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By BARRY FOX  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few radar operators from RAF airborne early-warning aircraft
have taken their annual leave to coincide with the Wimbledon tennis
matches so that they can help the BBC anticipate rain at the
championships. The operators are working for David Morton, who runs
RaceNet Radar Systems of Marlow, Buckinghamshire.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't stop the rain coming. But we can predict when it will
arrive to within a couple of minutes, so the BBC can reschedule its
programs,'' Morton says.
</P>
<P>
   RaceNet has developed a local weather radar based on the
hardware used on supertankers, but it needs skilled operators to
work with the proprietary software. A 2.5-meter antenna, mounted on
top of the 75-meter crane that the BBC uses for bird's-eye camera
shots, sends out a 9-gigahertz radar signal. The signal bounces off
any clouds that are heavy with water, which are displayed on a
computer screen as yellow patches. As a cloud moves, it leaves a
blue tail across the screen which shows which direction it is
moving.
</P>
<P>
   After plotting a cloud and its tail for six minutes, the team of
five operators calculates its speed and direction, and predicts
where it will be in 45 minutes and how long it will take to move
on. If the Wimbledon courts look a likely target, the team alerts
the BBC's Television Center in London, where staff line up
prerecorded programmes to fill the gap. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
