<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6214 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRATS-RURAL-$ADV0     07-01 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-RURAL-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RURAL RACES ARE KEY IN 2000 BATTLE FOR CONTROL OF CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a remark that Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I.,
the Kennedy family scion on Capitol Hill, would later regret.
</P>
<P>
   On June 18, the day House Democrats and moderate Republicans
rejected gun control legislation that they argued was too watered
down, Kennedy was asked how his party's strategy would play in
rural districts that traditionally frown on gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee, which organizes and supports Democratic candidates for
House seats, replied that his party had already ``written off the
rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy statement came as a shock, especially in light of
the fact that Democrats succeeded in 1998 in slimming the
Republican House majority to six seats by electing three
conservative, anti-abortion and pro-gun Democrats in rural areas in
Mississippi, Kentucky and southern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy quickly backed off his dismissive statement and has
since talked up Democratic prospects in conservative rural areas
that increasingly have gone Republican in the past few decades.
Later he called his comment an ``emotional response'' uttered amid
controversy over guns, an issue close to a family that suffered the
assassinations of President John F. Kennedy in 1963 and New York
Sen. Robert F. Kennedy in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But the damage had been done and Republicans gleefully called
attention to his gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the chairman of the committee charged with electing
Democrats says in essence moderate-to-conservative Democrats need
not apply, that sends a chilling message for candidate
recruitment,'' said Rep. Dave Camp, R-Mich., whose far-flung
16-country district is based in Midland, Mich. ``I hope they pursue
that political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp is a leader of the Republicans' organization to win GOP
House seats.
</P>
<P>
   The uproar over Kennedy's remark underscores a crucial factor in
the Democrats' bid to retake control of the House after five years
in the minority: Democratic conservatives are the party's only hope
for winning rural districts, particularly in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't run as a Massachusetts Democrat down there,'' said
Merle Black, a political scientist at Emory University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, rural America would seem an unlikely site for a
political battleground. More and more, the U.S. population is
concentrating itself in urban areas _ a category that incorporates
cities, suburbs and exurbs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, 54.4 percent of the U.S. population of 92.2 million
lived in rural areas and 45.6 lived in urban areas, according to
Census Bureau figures. By 1990 with the population at 248.7
million, those percentages were 75.2 percent urban and 24.3 percent
rural.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the Republicans holding a thin 223-211 majority (and
independent Rep. Bernard Sanders usually siding with Democrats),
every district counts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats theoretically could retake the House without victories
in rural districts. But party activists and political experts see
that as highly improbable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to take back the House without
winning rural districts,'' said Giles Perkins, executive director
of the Alabama Democratic Party. ``And we're optimistic that some
of those wins will be in Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama, in fact, is a good measure of how far Democrats have
fallen in rural areas over the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, the state _ which has no purely urban congressional
districts _ had five Democratic representatives and two
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the year before Republicans seized control, the
Democratic margin was 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Republicans control the delegation 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 election, ``it's very difficult to see much
potential for Democrats given the incredible success of
Republicans'' in these districts, said Q. Whitfield Ayres, an
Atlanta-based Republican pollster and political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   To have a chance of winning, he added, a Democrat would have to
be facing a non-incumbent Republican in a district with a
significant percentage of votes from African-Americans, a
traditional Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts in the South said the region is particularly
keen on returning incumbents to office.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an incumbent, you get to know your constituents so well
that they will overlook your partisanship (if they disagree with
it),'' said Charles Bullock, a University of Georgia political
science professor. ``In the past, this worked for Democrats. Now it
helps Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, who chaired the 1998 Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, made a virtue out of recruiting
conservative Democrats who could win rural districts by proclaiming
that they, like their Republican adversaries, also were
anti-abortion and pro-gun.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy produced victories by Rep. Ronnie Shows, D-Miss.,
Rep. Ken Lucas, D-Ky., and Rep. Dave Phelps, D-Ill., all of whom
ran as conservatives on social issues. At the same time, they
argued that as Democrats, they were more committed than their GOP
adversaries to propping up bedrock government programs such as
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Kennedy took the reins of the DCCC for the 2000 election
cycle, political observers wondered whether a New England liberal
would maintain the same recruitment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to DCCC spokesman John Del Cecato, is
``Yes.'' He cited several examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Louisiana, Marjorie McKeithen, anti-abortion and pro-gun
granddaughter of a former Democratic governor, is set for a rematch
against Rep. Richard Baker, R-La. Baker beat McKeithen in 1998 by a
margin of 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Texas, conservative rice farmer Loy Sneary will again
challenge libertarian-minded Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas. It's an uphill
battle for Sneary, having lost to Paul in 1998 by 11 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Pennsylvania, conservative Pat Casey, son of anti-abortion
former Gov. Robert Casey, will take another crack at Rep. Don
Sherwood, R-Pa. Sherwood won his first term in 1998 by beating
Casey by 515 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say the success we've had in recruiting
candidates who are a good fit for their district will continue, Del
Cecato said.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one incumbent says the key is to avoid social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Texas, whose district stretches from
Beaumont to Galveston, describes himself as a supporter of abortion
rights and an opponent of gun controls. But he concentrates on
bread-and-butter issues such as trying to help out his district's
economically troubled rice farmers by lifting U.S. food embargoes
against nations such as Cuba and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe (social issues are) not so much on (rural
constituents') minds as their way of life, continuing to have an
opportunity to earn a living on the land,'' he said. ``That's the
most important thing to them, bar none.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
