<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHILOH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHILOH 2': SEQUEL TO A BEAGLE'S TROUBLED PAST
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be so easy to make fun of Friendly, W.Va., where the
little yellow school bus rolls by, reading ``Friendly Elementary
School'' on the side. And it would be easy to ridicule the
Prestons, who live there and are so down home that their television
set doesn't even have a remote.
</P>
<P>
   The Prestons are wise, hard-working parents; the town has a
kindly country doctor; the new schoolteacher is too sweet to be
true. ``Shiloh 2: Shiloh Season'' could have turned sappy or
simple-minded in many ways, but it never does _ despite the
numerous close-ups of the title character, a soulful-eyed beagle
with a troubled past.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, ``Shiloh'' introduced young filmgoers (at least
those who had not already read Phyllis Reynolds Naylor's Newbery
Medal-winning book) to the Prestons and their son, Marty, who
befriended an abused dog and worked hard to make the dog his own.
</P>
<P>
   The dog, which Marty named Shiloh, had belonged to Judd Travers,
a solitary, tobacco-spitting, beer-drinking misanthrope, the
meanest man in town.
</P>
<P>
   In the wise, engaging, truly heartwarming sequel, Judd, again
played by Scott Wilson, is up to no good, drinking a lot, reneging
on his deal with Marty, shooting his hunting rifle when and where
he shouldn't, and driving his pickup truck all too recklessly.
</P>
<P>
   Marty, a seventh grader at this point, is now played by Zachary
Browne, who bears a major resemblance to the actress Frances
Fisher. Michael Moriarty and Ann Dowd return as Marty's parents.
Rod Steiger returns as Doc Wallace, who saved Shiloh's life in the
first film.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the plot is that it is made up of little
terrors, the thousands of near-tragedies that make up most people's
real lives. Oh my God, where's Becky? She was just here playing
hide-and-seek. Oh my God, where has Shiloh run off to now _ and
isn't that the sound of gunfire in the woods? Oh my God, isn't that
Jake's truck heading straight for the dog?
</P>
<P>
   When something does go terribly wrong and Shiloh starts barking
wildly, it's a refreshing touch of reality that no one can figure
out what's wrong. (None of that ``What's that, Lassie? Timmy's in
the well?'' stuff for these people.)
</P>
<P>
   The moral question in ``Shiloh 2'' is whether people really can
change _ specifically, whether anything could affect Judd enough to
``wipe a whole life of meanness away.'' But this is a smart,
sensitive movie _ based on the second book in Ms. Naylor's trilogy
and written by Dale Rosenbloom, who both wrote and directed the
first ``Shiloh'' film _ about morality in general.
</P>
<P>
   When Marty's friend David (Joe Pichler) wants to spy on Judd,
Marty doesn't want to, for two good reasons: because he's afraid
they'll get caught and because he said he wouldn't. David and Marty
actually talk about whether Judd is mean because his parents were
awful to him or if he was just born that way. And when they ask
adults for wisdom, they don't get pap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tests of life, they get harder,'' Doc Wallace tells Marty.
Later, Doc explains: ``Kindness in life is something you have to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   At school the teacher discusses the important difference between
truth and gossip. And in the end, kindness does pay off, with just
a dash of sentimentality and the touch of a little paw.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest shock in the sequel is Marty's visit to David's
house for a sleepover. The house has a high-ceilinged marble foyer
with a chandelier, and the household has a cook. Who knew there was
money in town?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   ``Shiloh II: Shiloh Season'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). It includes one mild vulgarity and gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   SHILOH 2
</P>
<P>
   Shiloh Season
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sandy Tung; written by Dale Rosenbloom, based on the
novel by Phyllis Reynolds Naylor; director of photography, Troy
Smith; edited by Tom Seid; music by Joel Goldsmith; production
designer, Joseph B. Tintfass; produced by Carl Borack and
Rosenbloom; released by Legacy Releasing. Running time: 96 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Michael Moriarty (Ray Preston), Scott Wilson (Judd
Travers), Zachary Browne (Marty Preston), Ann Dowd (Louise
Preston), Caitlin Wachs (Dara Lynn Preston), Joe Pichler (David
Howard), Rachel David (Becky Preston), Marissa Leigh (Samantha),
Bonnie Bartlett (Mrs. Wallace), Rod Steiger (Doc Wallace) and
Frannie (Shiloh).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
