<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX     07-01 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Promised greenhouse rekindles orchid interest
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Barbara Davis made it crystal clear. She'd
pick up and leave her beloved Savannah (Ga.) for a home here in the
hills on one condition: Her husband, Ed, had to build a greenhouse
for her orchids.
</P>
<P>
   So, in June 1998, the couple moved into the big house on a rise
that affords an inspiring view of the mountains. Soon after they
joined our neighborhood, I'd drive by and see them marking the land
_ planting a tree here, another there, putting in a flower patch
that now includes a great stand of hollyhocks. On some days, the
red Corvette would stand out on the driveway next to the pickup,
top down, sunning.
</P>
<P>
   Little did I know that behind this idyllic scene, Barbara was
metaphorically tapping her feet, waiting for her orchid house.
After a decent interval, Barbara recalled the other day, she
reminded her husband: ``You promised me a greenhouse; what about
that promise?''
</P>
<P>
   We've all been there. Part of the rhythm of relationships is
finding a way to balance two competing needs: the need for
do-nothing time and the need to keep the household chores done in
timely fashion, thus keeping family ties harmonious. So prevalent
is this tug of opposing interests that the expression ``honey do
list'' is part of the language, always inspiring snickers and great
rolling of eyes. I mention that here, knowing that my own list
contains a glaring item that has remained undone for many months: I
just cannot get around to fixing that shelf under the sink.
</P>
<P>
   But compared to Ed's big-ticket chore, mine is mercifully
paltry; fortunately, for Lyn and for unhandy me, I never promised
her a greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With such a big commitment hanging in the air, Ed had no choice
but to deliver. And, he did so with skill and enthusiasm. On my
drives by, I noticed the framework rising next to the house. And,
in what seemed an amazingly short period, a whole greenhouse
greeted me one day as I drove past.
</P>
<P>
   This was months ago. Since then, I had wondered about the
greenhouse _ who was its prime keeper, what plants it grows.
</P>
<P>
   I decided not to just drop in, but I did think of practicing the
old country custom that prevailed before telephones allowed us to
call ahead: Walk to a neighbor's home and stand in the front yard.
If someone looks out, sees you and comes out to chat, you visit. If
no one does, you go away. Ed's ``Why don't you come over and see
our greenhouse'' made that unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Walking into the hot humid greenhouse on a recent Saturday made
me understand. It was Barbara's Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Ed had delivered on his promise _ really delivered. He not only
built his wife a home for her orchids; he built her a coastal
climate, its air regulated by both a heater and cooling system.
``He's prouder about this than anything,'' says Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   And so is she. Guiding us through her lush collection, she
caressed the names. Dendrobium, cymbidium ... some producing tiny
blooms, others largish ones. Yellows, pinks, whites. There seemed
to be hundreds of them. In fact, there are, says Barbara _ about
500. Their elegant, delicate-looking flowers persist with iron
will. In June, she pointed to flowers that had been around since
March and showed no signs of faltering.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing her wealth, Barbara, whose talents include painting
evocative botanicals, sets aside some of the plants and tags them
with names of friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, this visit to Barbara's Savannah inspired me to think
about giving orchids a go, again, something I haven't done in a
while. Over the years, I have had no problem growing them; it's
getting them to bloom again that gives me trouble. My greatest
re-blooming success was with a phalaenopsis that I set in a shady
spot outside after watching it languish indoors for a year or so.
</P>
<P>
   I forgot about it for months, letting it take care of itself,
drinking from the rain, until I noticed blooms on it. What a lovely
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Now, abandoning neglect, I'll go in another direction. No, I
won't even attempt to build a greenhouse. Instead, I'll try
providing orchid essentials _ high humidity and good air
circulation _ by stashing the plants where they feel the breezes
along the ridge and the humidity from Fightingtown Creek. And if
this works half as well as Barbara's greenhouse, I'll call it my
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay(at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
