<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEDESIGN-TIPS02-COX     07-01 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDESIGN-TIPS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lights, mirrors, mood: Decorators share tips
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few trade secrets of model home decorators:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To make the house look larger, designers use light-colored
carpeting and flooring. They use furnishings judiciously, keeping
them on the perimeter of rooms. And occasionally they use mirrored
walls as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paint colors and furnishings generally reflect the way people
live now. Some designers mine ideas from shelter magazines and
catalogs such as Crate &AMP; Barrel. They purchase furnishings and
accessories where their target market is likely to shop, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Decorators seek to inspire envy. A model home isn't just about
how you live today; it's about the lifestyle to which you aspire in
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Designers put together a few looks that visitors can re-create
inexpensively at home. Conversely, they showcase a few things that
visitors don't have at home and probably won't add: spa baths,
separate showers, built-in cabinetry, updated kitchens. That way,
they'll start thinking about buying a new house with all those
features.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  To make visitors remember the model, designers tap into
nostalgia and community interests. For example, Kaye Graham Designs
put together an airplane-themed child's bedroom for a Southside
community aimed at pilots with families.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Color palettes vary depending on the cost of the house and its
potential buyers. Homes aimed at first-time buyers usually have
brighter colors. The look turns more neutral for upper-income
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Designers accessorize, accessorize, accessorize. Details
create a mood and make a house more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   _Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
