<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODELHOMES02-COX     07-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODELHOMES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A passion for home fashion drives many to tour models, show
houses
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just looking,'' you say as you breeze through the
door, past the price sheets and floor plans, the community map and
the agent eager to take down your phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Just looking for decorating ideas. Just looking for an
entertaining, free way to fill a weekend afternoon. Just looking to
see how the other half lives.
</P>
<P>
   Designer show house tours are hard to find this time of year.
But day in and day out, no matter the season, there are always
dozens of gussied-up model homes to see around metro Atlanta _ and
thousands showing up to tour them. Model homes exist to sell
subdivisions, but on any given weekend, many of the people walking
through them are not home-buyers, but budding Martha Stewarts just
looking for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   People like Karin Meyer, 36, who took photos of the paint on the
dining room picture molding during a recent visit to Pathway
Communities' SummerGrove in Newnan (Ga.), a model home nirvana with
nine decorated homes from eight builders.
</P>
<P>
   People like Claudia Vital, her daughter, Sabra LeBlanc, 26, and
granddaughter Quianna LeBlanc, 3, who visit model homes once a
month for some air-conditioned window-shopping. At SummerGrove,
they puzzled over why some walls in a master bedroom were painted
dark green and others beige (the paler walls face the windows, to
reflect light, they decided) and admired the accessorizing that had
matched a straw chair with straw matting around a zebra print.
</P>
<P>
   The Newnan residents have spent years comparing notes on houses
in Fayetteville (Ga.), Peachtree City (Ga.), LaGrange (Ga.) and
farther afield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked in Texas as well,'' Vital says. ``Everywhere we
go, we look.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Vicky Foster, 47. On trips to Disney World and the
Florida Panhandle, she's toured houses at Celebration and Seaside.
In metro Atlanta, she's ranged as far north as Cherokee County to
tour the gigantic planned community of BridgeMill and hits all the
big show home tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a compulsion,'' Foster says. ``I think I should have been
a decorator, but I didn't know it when I went to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she teaches business at Forest Park High School and
satisfies her decorating urge by watching HGTV, shopping for
furnishings she spots in model homes and gleaning ideas to spiff up
her Fayette County house. Like many, she's searching for
window-treatment inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   And that's OK with the developers who set up model homes. They
figure that today's looker might be next year's buyer, or have a
friend in the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people come in and bring cameras and measuring
tape,'' says Heidi Carr, marketing manager for Centex Homes'
Atlanta division. ``I walked in on a lady one day who'd torn apart
the bedding in the master bedroom and was measuring and taking
pictures and writing down colors. She was so embarrassed, but I
told her `don't be.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kaye Graham, owner of Kaye Graham Designs of Alpharetta (Ga.),
just might be the queen of model home tours. Her company
specializes in models, decorating between 30 to 50 annually in
Atlanta and elsewhere. They get many of their ideas from
California, where the staff of four visits as many as 40 models in
a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants what they can afford today,'' Graham says. ``You
have to romance them with things they could do in a house, or
things they would want to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the master suite of the model at Garrison Oaks, a
Williamscraft Community in east Cobb (Ga.), romance is what it's
all about. A champagne bottle and two wine glasses sit next to a
whirlpool tub for two. In the bedroom, a fireplace faces a tester
bed covered in velvet and silk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being on a honeymoon,'' says Buzzy Keith, 51, as he
eyes the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could just move right in,'' says his wife, Bitsy, 50.
</P>
<P>
   The Keiths are removating their east Cobb County (Ga.) kitchen
and looking for countertop ideas. But Bitsy is picking up a few
tips upstairs, too. The neutral Window treatments in the master
bedroom would make it easy to change the colors of other
furnishings in the room, she notes.
</P>
<P>
   The basement is fitted out with a wet bar, pool table and home
theater, complete with eight easy chairs and a clicking marquee
announcing the current show.
</P>
<P>
   But Durwin Mitchell, 37, ignores the blandishments.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of today's visitors to the home, he and his wife,
Joanne, 38, are actually consideringbuying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Models are designed to lure you in,'' Mitchell says. ``I'm one
of those people that if I go to the mall and I'm looking for a
shirt, I look for a shirt. I don't look in the slacks section.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
