<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWGARDEN02-COX     07-01 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWGARDEN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thinking ahead is key ingredient to ensuring success when
creating a garden
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (A gardener's journal
</P>
<P>
   Planning plays a big part in creating a successful garden. But
even the best-laid plans are subject to the challenges of nature.
That's what makes gardening a matter of trial and error. For the
next year, Home &AMP; Garden will follow the development of one garden,
revisiting it each season to show what worked, what didn't and what
the gardeners learned.)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sam Schwartz and Lynn Goldowski want to make their
yard an inviting place to relax, but their busy lifestyles leave
little time for gardening.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike most young homeowners who do well to create an
attractive landscape in spring and summer, the husband and wife are
determined to have a garden for all seasons _ one they can enjoy
from indoors on hot or cold days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goals were to have a livable outdoor space that is
free-flowing and accessible from the house,'' Schwartz says. ``We
also wanted things to look good in winter, with lots of different
colors, heights and texture, but still be a low-maintenance
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, who travels often on business, and Goldowski, a
physician turned stay-at-home mom, are parents to a 3-year-old and
an infant, so gardening ranks low on their to-do lists these days.
But after building an addition to their Decatur (Ga.) house three
years ago, the couple was left with a back yard that screamed for
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years, this was just a pit,'' Schwartz says of the
large clay area. Once they'd settled into their family room
addition, the couple, realizing how landscaping increases property
values, was ready to tackle part of their 1 1/2-acre wooded lot.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz had done some vegetable and flower gardening. He plans
to maintain the garden. But the couple decided to call in a design
expert on the front end to avoid costly mistakes. Atlanta landscape
architect Dottie Myers spent hours last winter talking with them
about their needs and lifestyles. She took them to nurseries and to
the Southeastern Flower Show to show them plants before developing
a design that encompasses areas closest to the house. (They plan to
take on outlying areas in later phases.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also doing the yard in phases because they have kids,
whose needs will change as they grow up,'' Myers says. ``And with
two small children, it's going to be hard for them to keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners wanted a variety of trees, shrubs and perennials _
especially less common varieties _ yet the garden had to be
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   A big challenge will be watering. Myers recommends soaker hoses
or hand watering over irrigation systems so that the ground, not
the foliage, benefits most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam's made the commitment for the first year to be the
waterer. But what we have done to help is to do incredible soil
preparation,'' Myers says, noting the amendments will help beds
retain their moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the project evolved:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Building the garden's bones. After drafting a site plan, Myers
and the owners settled on a budget, about 70 percent of which went
to building a retaining wall and stone patio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardscaping is usually the biggest outlay of money,'' Myers
says. ``In the beginning, there were little things they had to give
up, like a cap on the retaining wall, which they can put on later
but saved them thousands of dollars by not doing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In late winter, Ed Castro Landscape was hired to push tons of
soil some 28 feet away from the house and build the 4 1/2-foot high
granite wall. A set of steps rises to an upper terrace, where the
remnants of an old stone surface became more evident.
</P>
<P>
   Myers designed a lower terrace as a transition between the house
and garden. The centerpiece is a crab orchard stone patio that
flows casually around the back of the house. ``The house is
perfectly symmetrical on the back, but we didn't want anything that
formal in the garden,'' Schwartz says. ``We wanted the wall to be
curved and for friends to be able to sit on it when we're out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted to incorporate a water garden, but with young
children, feared a pond at this stage. So Myers designed a bed,
outfitted with electricity, where a water garden can be installed
later.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  First stop: Improving the soil. The most crucial step in
creating any garden is soil preparation. Typically, Georgia's
heavy, rock-laden clay requires amending to provide nutrients and
to improve drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Organic Landscaping and Design Implementation
weeded and cleared the yard of ivy and other existing plants,
rocks, roots and debris. For several days the crew did the work by
hand to avoid further compacting the soil with heavy equipment.
``The upper part was so incredibly hard we had to use a mattock to
break up the soil,'' says company owner Jerry Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Workers then tilled the soil a depth of 8 to 13 inches before
topping it with a 3-inch layer of Mr. Natural Complete Landscape
Mix, which contains expanded slate, fine granite sand, coarse river
sand, bark humus, worm casings and composted chicken manure. ``It's
been our experience that when we do good soil prep like this, we
get a three-year look within a garden's first year,'' Allen says.
</P>
<P>
   After tilling in the amendments, the crew raked the soil toward
the center of beds to create a contour for ensuring proper
drainage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Let the planting begin. Because the property is wooded, Myers'
design includes few new trees. Instead, she emphasized shrubs and
perennials that offer an attractive feature _ flowers, berries,
foliage, fragrance _ during various seasons. ``I've tried to have
something blooming at every stage of the year,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For summer, she planted hydrangeas, banana shrub, ornamental
grasses, Margarita and Blackie potato vines, and copper fennel _ a
host plant for butterflies that she included ``just for the kids.''
For fall, there's the brilliant foliage of Mt. Airy fothergilla,
Japanese maples and fragrant plants such as an orange-flowering tea
olive. In winter, the family should appreciate a variety of
evergreens, conifers, Gilt-Edged elaeagnus, Peggy Clark flowering
apricot, variegated daphne and several camellias. And come spring,
there will be small perennials, such as astilbe, irises, coreopsis
and dianthus.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are complemented by calm spots of mondo grass, a
low-growing dark green ground cover. ``Sam didn't want any grass to
mow,'' Myers says.
</P>
<P>
   And all of the plantings have been mulched with hardwood bark to
help the soil retain moisture and discourage weeds.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the young garden is sparse but holds plenty of promise,
despite a first summer that's expected to be hotter and drier than
ususal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already anticipated that to be a problem,'' Allen says.
``The good thing about amending the soil the way we did is it will
now hold a great deal of moisture.''
</P>
<P>
   Success, after all, comes with planning _ and a little luck from
Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   G A R D E N P O I N T E R S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have a plan. Whether you hire a landscape designer or do it
yourself, list your priorities for a garden, considering how you
want to use it, how much time you have to maintain it. Then sketch
a design on paper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Learn as much as you can about plants appropriate for your
area. A good starting point is ``Georgia Gardener's Guide'' by
Erica Glasener and Walter Reeves (Cool Springs Press, $18.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take into account the seasons, incorporating plants that will
offer something interesting in winter, such as evergreen foliage,
berries, bark, fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start a photo file of features from gardening magazines that
you like.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't let a large yard overwhelm you. You don't have to
implement your plan at once; tackle one area at a time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't plant until you amend Georgia's heavy clay soil. Two
amendments popular with Atlanta horticulturists are Mr. Natural
Complete Landscape Mix and Nature's Helper Organic Soil
Conditioner, available at area garden centers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep a journal, noting which plants failed, which flourished _
a do's-and-don'ts reminder for the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
