A6224 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-HOLIDAYTABLE02-     07-01 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-HOLIDAYTABLE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    July 4th Tabletop options
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celebrate in style this July Fourth _ the quintessential summer
holiday for family, friends and festive meals. From picnics to
patio buffets, America's big birthday party is an unabashed tribute
to all things patriotic, including stripes and stars and those
spirited colors of the flag. With a bit of time and savvy, you can
create a fun red, bright and blue table for your guests.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might take an entirely different approach to the holiday
and simply set a pretty table that incorporates those delicate
summertime shades of greens and roses, pinks and yellows. To get in
the celebration mode, guests can sip champagne or lemonade while
watching fireworks or playing with sparklers.
</P>
<P>
   A party table is an expression of yourself, a chance to show
your creativity, according to Atlantan Liz Schimpf, who plans
parties for a living. ``Yet that table _ and the food _ should be
simple,'' says Schimpf, who's the marketing director for Glorious
Events, a catering and party design firm. ``People feel the need to
impress their guests, which is simply not true. Your guests love
you for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   When planning your table, Schimpf suggests you ``build and
layer,'' like an architect. Start with color, then texture. Keep in
mind, she says, that busy colors will clash with the food. Next
come table coverings, layered on top with place settings and,
finally, other accessories.
</P>
<P>
   To keep you independent on the Fourth _ to enjoy your guests _
we asked Schimpf to create two settings. One is the traditional
rah-rah patriotic look; the other is a summer-themed table that can
be set on Independence Day or any other time you want to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   Let freedom zing
</P>
<P>
   For this colorful look, Schimpf chose a red-and-white-checked
plastic tablecloth on which she put Martha Stewart's blue plaid
cotton tablecloth. Next, she chose bamboo plate holders, which she
topped with red-and-white-
</P>
<P>
   checked paper plates and napkins and smaller, solid blue paper
plates. If you're doing a buffet table, blue acrylic tumblers make
perfect holders for the flatware _ in this case, clear plastic
spoons, forks and knives. Other accents: a round cobalt blue vase
filled with just-picked blue hydrangeas (you could also use
sunflowers or red and white carnations), citronella candles in red
and blue glass holders and an oil lantern. The final touch? Tiny
flags for each guest. ``Remember,'' she says, ``disposable flatware
is appropriate for an informal party. So is stainless or
silverplate. It's your choice.''
</P>
<P>
   COST OF TABLE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Party City: Red-and-white-checked plastic tablecloth
($2.75); bamboo plate holders ($1.29); red-checked dinner plates
($2.29 pack of 12); solid blue salad plates ($2.55 pack of 24);
red-checked napkins ($1.99 pack of 20); clear plastic flatware
($1.79 for pack of 24 forks, knives or spoons); citronella candles
in red and blue glass holders ($1.39 each); citronella candle in
large tin ($4.99); tiny American flags (29 cents each).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Kmart: Blue acrylic tumblers (59 cents each); Martha
Stewart blue plaid cotton tablecloth ($14.99).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Williams Sonoma: Oil lantern ($20).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Pottery Barn: Cobalt blue bubble vase ($15).
</P>
<P>
   A taste of independence
</P>
<P>
   To ``build'' this summery-looking spread, our stylist first
covered the table with an ivory damask cloth, then added green
woven place mats. For the place setting, she chose Villeroy &AMP;
Boch's mix-and-match china from the company's ``Summerhouse''
collection: bowls and plates trimmed with roses or a green
Florentine border. Note: To hold the cost down, you might wish to
select paper products in similar colors or patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Complementing the china is a wooden bar tray _ great for holding
drinks and flowers _ tiled in green and yellow. Other touches:
bright yellow resin flatware, clear glass pitcher and gold leaf
wine bucket.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to flowers, Schimpf suggests snipping roses,
peonies, pink stock or anemones from your garden. Or ask a friend
if you can raid hers and casually stick them in a glass vase.
``Stylized arrangements are dead,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   COST OF TABLE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Fragile in Sandy Springs:
</P>
<P>
   Xochi green woven place mats ($6 each); green striped cloth
napkins ($4.20 each); Villeroy &AMP; Boch's Summerhouse Collection
includes ``Arabesco'' dinner plate ($20.80 each); ``A Rose'' salad
plate ($13.60 each) and ``A Rose'' vegetable bowl ($44.80);
``Acacia'' bread-and-butter plate ($12) and ``Acacia'' chowder bowl
($22.40 each); bar tray ($47.20); Villeroy &AMP; Boch flatware ``Play''
in yellow ($21 for five-piece place setting); Nautilus pitcher
($24); Zrike oversized goblets ($10 each).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Macy's: Ivory damask cloth ($39.99).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Pottery Barn: Gold leaf wine bucket ($36); clear bubble
vase ($15).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
