<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-WESTASSURED04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Style has timeless appeal, but a little goes a long way
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 4
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How crazy is the notion of cowboy accouterment suddenly gaining
favor among the clothes-conscious? No more far-fetched, really,
than the idea of a black actor (Will Smith) reprising the role of a
turn-of-the-century cowboy-sleuth in the movie version of ``Wild
Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people may say that wild horses couldn't drag them into a
Westernwear store. But they'd be missing out on some style points
that cutting-edge dressers have been scoring for the past several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, fashion magazines targeting both men and women
touted ``Vegas chic'' _ fringed and beaded jackets, skirts and
pants, for instance _ as the style to mimic. The industry's
affinity for all things Western carried over into the fall and
winter, when people attending the fashion shows in New York, Paris
and Milan turned out in dark denim outfits accented with scrunched
cowboy hats and gleaming black boots.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the wardrobe in Smith's new flick serves as a
reminder that there's a timeless appeal to Westernwear. It connotes
strength, courage, self-assuredness, Americana.
</P>
<P>
   And a little bit of it goes a long way. Just one of the look's
central components _ the hat, belt or boots _ is all one really
needs to transform an ordinary outfit into something endearingly
reminiscent of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   So, unless you're going someplace to dance the two-step, rein in
that inclination to don Westernwear from head to toe. Leave the
wearing of complete cowboy costumes to the characters in ``Wild
Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKSHOP-TERRACE02-CO     07-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-TERRACE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stone terrace a compromise for lawn lovers
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tired of mowing that lawn but don't want a
high-maintenance garden? Brad Murphy might have just the solution.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the Atlanta resident created a terrace in his front
yard that's half patio-half grass. The patio part consists of
square steppingstones arranged in a diamond pattern; the grass part
is dwarf mondo planted between the stones. The result is a
checkerboard surface that can be walked on and requires no mowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted some green but not just grass,'' said Murphy, a
hairdresser who discovered gardening four years ago. ``This way, I
never have to mow.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had seen similar designs using stones and pebbles but
opted for bluestone and mondo, a matty ground cover that grows only
2 to 3 inches tall.
</P>
<P>
   He began by killing what was left of a lawn already in poor
shape. Then he leveled the area by filling low spots with topsoil,
grading the yard slightly to ensure proper drainage. Next, he added
a 2-inch layer of sand to create a smooth surface for positioning
the stones.
</P>
<P>
   After measuring the space, Murphy chose 18-inch-square stones.
He'd planned to lay them in a grid but ended up placing them
diagonally, which required more materials. Finally, he bordered the
terrace with a cobblestone coping.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy then filled the square gaps between stones with a mixture
of soil and compost to prepare for planting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dwarf mondo doesn't grow very fast, and I'm very impatient. I
wanted the terrace to look like it's been here for years,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   So to speed things up, Murphy bought 25 flats of grass
containing 18 plugs, each of which he divided into several plants.
He then placed the plants only about 2 inches apart. He also
applied a slow-release fertilizer and mulch to help the soil retain
moisture and prohibit weed growth.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy figures it will take at least a year for the grass to
cover their squares, forming a dense carpet capable of withstanding
foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   And although the weekend project cost about $500 for the stones
(about $7 each) and another $300 for the plants, less expensive
stones and fewer plants can be used.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the low-maintenance terrace now allows him to do what
he likes best _ gardening _ instead of mowing.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLIES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Measuring tape
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Square steppingstones (12, 18 or 24 inch)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mondo grass (or other ground covers, such as ajuga)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sand
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Topsoil
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Compost
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fertilizer
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pine bark mulch
</P>
<P>
   Step 1: Measure the area to be terraced to determine how many
stones will be needed. Clear the area of weeds, level the soil at a
grade so it will drain and cover with a 2-inch layer of sand. Begin
positioning the stones so they don't rock when stepped on.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2: Fill in the gaps between stones with a mixture of
topsoil and compost that's level with the stones.
</P>
<P>
   Step 3: Plant plugs of mondo grass several inches apart. (Plugs
can be divided into several plants to cover more area.) Then mulch
around the plants to ward off weeds.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second installment in our Summer Workshop series, a
step-by-step guide to inexpensive weekend projects for the home or
garden. If there's a project you'd like to suggest or if you want
more information about this series, call 404-222-8689 or e-mail
dflanders
</P>
<P>
   (at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
