r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-TUITION-REVOLT     07-01 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TUITION-REVOLT-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH REVOLUTIONARY ZEAL, STUDENTS SEEK TO BLOCK TUITION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Wearing camouflage fatigues, his waist-long hair
in a ponytail and a Fu Manchu mustache offsetting dark eyes, Ivan
Alcantar looks the part of a moody young revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   But as he chain-smokes cigarettes and guzzles an orange soda,
Alcantar says he is just a student who wants to make a difference
in an undemocratic world ruled by bankers and financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 20, the history and philosophy major has been part
of a student strike that began over changing a venerated aspect of
Mexican higher education: plans to charge tuition at the National
Autonomous University of Mexico, or UNAM, the largest in Latin
America with nearly 270,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of us are striking because we think we have a
just cause,'' said Alcantar, 24, the son a physician. ``I am doing
my part against a global economic system that is being imposed on
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded during the first eruptions of the 1910 Mexican
revolution, UNAM has near-mythical repute and is often regarded as
a mirror of Mexican society.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years it has had its share of controversy. But not
since 1968, when dozens of UNAM protesters were killed, allegedly
by government snipers, have students voiced such discord and spread
such upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   UNAM, known as ``the maximum house of studies'' in Mexico, has
been a virtually free university since its inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   A new constitution drawn up in 1916 envisioned it could provide
a free higher education for all, regardless of class or social
status, a principle still alive today.
</P>
<P>
   Often compared to Harvard and Yale for its quality of education,
the university has produced three Nobel laureates and has several
presidents of Mexico among its alumni.
</P>
<P>
   So when university dean Francisco Barnes announced plans to
raise tuition costs, but only for those who could afford to pay, he
touched on a sacred cow.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to raise the tuition from a symbolic 2 cents per
semester to about $60 per semester, a fee intended to offset a
reduction of government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other university in the world with such low
tuition fees,'' Barnes said during a trip to San Antonio in April.
``We don't think increasing it slightly is an unfair proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes later backed down, saying the tuition would be voluntary.
But it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   A Pandora's box was opened that touches on the core of Mexico's
past and what the country is becoming today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of charging tuition at UNAM is taboo. You cannot
touch the subject. It is just not done,'' said Primitivo Rodriguez,
a historian and theologian. ``The only way to do it, and you would
not have been able to, is to consult students.''
</P>
<P>
   The students seem to be volatile brew of leftist ideologues,
in-your-face punk rockers and malcontent Generation Xers. They have
nicknames such as ``El Mosh'' and ``El Marx.''
</P>
<P>
   Some groups are called the ``Ultras,'' radicals who adorn their
faces with war-like red paint and stage noisy demonstrations that
block highways for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are Marxist, Leninist, extremists. But most are
democratic and independent of any political parties,'' said
Alcantar, a student of Mexican Marxist historians.
</P>
<P>
   Although many have undefined philosophies, they share a deep
mistrust of Mexico's accelerated push from a welfare state to a
market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Another common trait is a deep admiration for the Zapatista
guerrillas demanding better living conditions for Maya Indians in
the southern state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   The now-dormant 1994 Zapatista uprising is led by the romantic
figure of the masked, pipe-smoking Subcommander Marcos, himself a
UNAM philosophy graduate and one-time professor at another school,
the Autonomous Metropolitan University in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas emerged just as the North American Free Trade
Agreement was going into effect in the last year of the
administration of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the market
reformer who privatized banks and other government-controlled
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us '94 was going to be a wonderful for Mexico, but
when that (the Zapatista uprising) happened, it was an awakening
for our society,'' said UNAM student Manuel Ponce, 21. ``They
wanted us to believe Mexico would become a wonderland, a country of
dreams come true, but that was not the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although shaky talks began last week with student leaders and
UNAM officials to end the walkout, the end seems far off. The
university remains closed with rocks and debris blocking the entry
to sprawling Ciudad Universitaria campus, which resembles a ghost
town.
</P>
<P>
   As the strike drags on, it is wearing on the patience of many
people. Last week, about 5,000 demonstrators packed a downtown
plaza to call on classes to restart.
</P>
<P>
   And President Ernesto Zedillo, who had remained silent through
most of the strike, called the student movement a ``brutal
aggression'' on the university.
</P>
<P>
   Students, meanwhile, complained of government repression after
video cameras were installed around the university and they said
they feared soldiers would try to crack down.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout all this there is the specter of the massacre of
1968, the year the country was staging the Olympics and one the
darkest periods in Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, the question of who fired on the students _ up
to 300 of whom were killed _ remained a mystery. But explosive
excerpts from a book citing the papers of a former defense
secretary said officers of the Presidential Guard fired the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Although that scenario is unlikely today, many here wonder if
the revelations will add to student discontent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
