u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VESSELS-FILM-REVIEW-N     07-01 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VESSELS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BROKEN VESSELS': STONELIKE DESCENT INTO DEPRAVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often, at moments of high stress, Tom (Jason London),
the Los Angeles paramedic who narrates ``Broken Vessels,'' has
dreamlike flashbacks to the pastoral world back East that he fled
in a big hurry. In these sequences Tom, who grew up in Altoona,
Pa., and is nicknamed Tuna Fish by his boss, remembers speeding in
his car through a bright-green landscape of farms and woodlands
that look infinitely more wholesome than the place where he has
landed. Whatever drove Tom to abandon such a pretty environment for
the concrete wilds of Los Angeles, we wonder. Might he be fleeing
some terrible personal blunder?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it turns out. But exactly what he's running from isn't
revealed until the end of the movie, which traces Tom's rapid
disintegration from idealistic medical worker to loathsome,
creepy-crawly drug addict. And when that revelation arrives, it is
too perfunctory to illuminate Tom's stonelike descent into
depravity.
</P>
<P>
   The chief agent of Tom's destruction is Jimmy (Todd Field), his
cynical, poker-faced, ambulance-driving partner and tutor in
corruption. Jimmy is a stout, mustachioed blob of trouble who
through most of the film is able to consume vast amounts of drugs
and alcohol without cracking any facial expression beyond appearing
terminally glum. He is a human cement mixer who numbly grinds along
through life with an all-purpose chip on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Directed with some flair by Scott Ziehl, ``Broken Vessels'' is
so eager to rub our noses in drugs (both snorted and injected) and
psychotic behavior that it forgets to give that behavior a wider
context. Tom's efforts to resist succumbing to his colleague's
lifestyle are at best feeble, and the movie is one long swatch of
increasingly joyless and desperate sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   First come the bar girls and cocaine. Then Tom's roommate throws
him out after he vomits (while high) into his aquarium, killing all
the fish. Tom moves in with Jimmy, and the pair hang out with Susy
(Susan Traylor), the twitching, motor-mouthed speed freak who lives
next door. Jimmy's one friend in the world is his grandfather, a
lifelong addict whom he supplies with heroin. Jimmy also feels no
qualms about stealing from clients when the whim strikes him and
sexually molesting unconscious women in the back of the ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broken Vessels'' also takes us to the sites of horrendous car
crashes and other human disasters, but the movie is so intent on
delivering successive shocks that after a while they seem dull and
repetitive. The story gives Tom one shot at redemption in his
romance with Elizabeth (Roxana Zal) a sweet, too-good-to-be-true
young nurse, but their scenes together seem false and wooden.
</P>
<P>
   If Ziehl shows poor judgment in balancing the elements of a
story, he has talent at directing actors (Ms. Traylor's strung-out
Susy is especially scary) and at sustaining a queasy, vertiginous
atmosphere of all-out craziness.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BROKEN VESSELS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Scott Ziehl; written by David Baer, John McMahon and
Ziehl; director of photography, Antonio Calvache; edited by David
Moritz and Chris Figler; production designer, Rodrigo Castillo;
produced by Roxana Zal and Ziehl; released by Unapix
Films/Zeitgeist Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Todd Field (Jimmy), Jason London (Tom), Roxana Zal
(Elizabeth), Susan Traylor (Susy), James Hong ( Chen) and Patrick
Cranshaw (Gramps). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is rated R (under 17 requires parent of adult
guardian). It has sexual situations, strong language and graphic
scenes of drug taking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
