<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-HAITI-0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SENATE SEEKS MORE ACCOUNTABILITY ON CLINTON HAITI POLICY
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Seeking more control over how U.S. taxpayer money is
spent in Haiti, the Senate has instructed the Clinton
administration to report to Congress every six months on the
Caribbean nation's progress -- if any -- towards achieving economic
and political stability.
</P>
<P>
   If sufficient progress is not achieved, Congress could block
U.S. funding for the hemisphere's poorest nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also has spelled out, on paper, its priorities in
Haiti, which include continued U.S. support for both the Haitian
National Police and for the holding of parliamentary elections in
Haiti later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, passed late Wednesday as part of a foreign aid
bill, still has to make it through the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the administration to spend money effectively, and we
also want to list our priorities because this is a democracy that
is having very significant problems so that the jury is still out
on it,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   It's been nearly five years since President Clinton ordered
20,000 troops to Haiti to oust a brutal military regime and restore
Jean-Bertrand Aristide to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A Cox Newspapers series earlier this year, showed that the
Clinton administration has poured more than $2.2 billion --
including $669 million in nonmilitary aid -- into Haiti with
little, or no progress in key areas such as elections. This year,
the administration has requested another $105 million for Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, today, many in Congress still harbor concerns over Haiti's
stability and over what role the United States should continue to
play in the small, troubled nation.
</P>
<P>
   The country has been in turmoil since April 1997, when Haiti's
most-recent election was held. That election attracted a derisory 5
percent of the electorate, and was never validated due to charges
of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, political bickering has paralyzed Haiti's
government, rendering it unable to accept nearly $1 billion in
loans and grants from international agencies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, crime has grown, as has the number of violent
street protests, many of which have been aimed at Haiti's mostly
U.S.-trained police force.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian government officials have promised to hold elections in
November or December, raising hopes that the political stalemate
will soon end.
</P>
<P>
   ``International support and assistance is needed to help
maintain a secure environment in which all parties and candidates
can organize and campaign without fear of intimidation and
violence,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But many Haiti experts doubt that the country -- sorely lacking
in funding -- can pull the elections off.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has asked the Clinton administration to report to
Congress on its efforts to help Haiti hold fair elections,
privatize state-owned businesses, investigate various political
killings, and remove members of the police force involved in human
rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hahn, a State Department spokesman, said it's not
unusual for Congress to place reporting requirements on an
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But what is unusual is the amount of frustration mounting in
Congress over a place often cited as one of Clinton's foreign
policy successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep a close watch on Haiti,'' DeWine said. ``What
we do there could affect the number of boat people coming in and
the amount of drugs coming in (to the United States).''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
