<HEADER>
A6247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MARINES-HNS &LR;      07-01 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MARINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MARINES STRUGGLE TO KEEP LID ON HATE-CHARGED SECTOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ohio, Pa.) 
 
By RICHARD MERTENS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GNJLANE, Yugoslavia _ A scratchy call over a walkie-talkie sent
a jolt through the headquarters of Lima Company's 1st Platoon. Four
men, three of them in uniforms of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army,
had been spotted on a rooftop just down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're on top of the freakin' theater, and they're waving,''
reported a breathless young Marine who burst into the office of the
platoon commander, Lt. Randall Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines had been shot at in Gnjlane twice already, and their
first thought was snipers. Then they learned that the ethnic
Albanians on the roof had climbed there because three Serbs with
pistols had entered the building.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, a tall and unflappable 24-year-old from Danville,
Ohio, slipped on his flak jacket, picked up his M-16 rifle, and
sent a squad down the street at double time.
</P>
<P>
   Some Marines took up positions around the theater, while others
slipped through the main door and disappeared. They searched the
building and found no Serbs with guns, only four frightened men on
the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes if no one is armed, we don't know if the stories are
made up or true,'' Johnston said afterward. ``There's no way to
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to make their section of Kosovo safe for both
returning ethnic Albanian refugees and the frightened Serb
minority, the U.S. Marines who arrived here less than two weeks ago
are coping with guns, with people who carry guns, and with people
who fear guns. It is not an easy task. The Marines of Gnjlane find
themselves in the middle of an ethnically mixed population that is
heavily armed and charged with fear and hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in town has weapons,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines have confiscated hundreds of guns, most of them
AK-47 assault rifles, the weapon of choice not only for military
forces in the Balkans but also for household protection. But
hundreds is a small number compared to the arsenal that the U.S.
peacekeepers believe remains in the hands of ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines know this not only from intelligence reports but
also from the spatter of gunfire at night from nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
   The danger that these guns pose was impressed upon Johnston's
platoon last Friday when at least one person, and possibly as many
as three, fired on Marines manning a checkpoint on the main street
outside the platoon's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The shootout that followed lasted more than an hour. When it was
over, one Serb was dead. No Marines were hurt, but their building
was pocked with bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways the Marines were given an easy assignment in
Kosovo. The violence and destruction around Gnjlane, the largest
town in the American sector in Kosovo, was mild by comparison with
much of the rest of the province.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the war is over, the tensions are rising.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who fled the province are returning in large
numbers, and many are angry and vengeful. They have taken over
public buildings and hoisted the Albanian flag. In some places they
have burned and looted Serb houses. The Serb minority, finding
itself suddenly out of power, is feeling itself backed into a
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Every day the Americans in Gnjlane are beset by frightened
citizens reporting threats, looting and kidnappings, or more often
just asking for protection. Often, the Marines can do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person in town would like a Marine standing in front of
their house,'' said Johnston. ``It's just impossible to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Marines do is make frequent patrols around the city and
into nearby villages, just to remind people that they are there.
They also have set up dozens of checkpoints along the roads, where
they search any car that looks suspicious. Cars with women and
children are usually waved through; a car with young men is almost
certain to be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are actually getting pretty good at pulling over the
right cars,'' said Lance Cpl. Michael Fritz, 22, of Lancaster, Pa.,
who commanded a checkpoint on the outskirts of Gnjlane. ``We're
still getting stuff. That's what kind of keeps you going. When you
find a weapon you're thinking maybe you saved somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   While he talked, a small car approaching the checkpoint caught
his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey! Check those guys,'' he ordered. Five young men, some
wearing partial uniforms of the Kosovo Liberation Army, got out.
The Marines frisked them and searched the car. Fritz found a pair
of license plates in the trunk and, suspecting they had been
stolen, tossed them on the grass. After a conversation with the
men, he gave them back. The Albanians smiled, shook hands with the
helmeted and heavily armed Americans, and sped away.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is pleased with the job the Marines are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Many ethnic Albanians want the soldiers to ferret out weapons
more aggressively from the Serbs living around Gnjlane, who were
armed with AK-47s by the Yugoslav security forces in the past
several years. Other people, of both nationalities, want greater
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Naser Zymberi, the head of Gnjlane's theater, asked the Marines
for a guard in front of the building. He said his ethnic Albanian
workers were afraid to come to work. The Marines were sympathetic
but not obliging.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't live in fear,'' Capt. Jerry Morgan told him. ``You
just have to go out and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Zymberi listened politely but went away dissatisfied. ``We're
afraid of the Serbs,'' he explained. ``They will shoot at us. We
don't have the courage to go out and do our jobs. We're not feeling
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear in Gnjlane points to one of the limitations of the
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo. KFOR, the international military
force to which the Marines belong, is expected to act as the local
police. The United Nations plans to set up a civilian police force
of 3,000 in Kosovo, but it hasn't done so yet. In the meantime, the
peacekeepers must fill the gap. In the eyes of many people, they
aren't doing the job.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the Marines' headquarters, through a back
gate, is the office of Gnjlane's Serb mayor, Bogdan Peric. On a
recent afternoon, he and several colleagues were taking calls from
frightened Serbs. One woman complained that ethnic Albanians had
entered her home looking for guns. Another called to report a
kidnapping. Most of the callers were told that there is little the
mayor can do these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we're not satisfied with the security situation
in the area,'' said Peric, a tense and fast-talking man. ``We've
had many threats to people. And many people have been beaten. But
KFOR always arrives too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans often dismiss the fears of the Serbs in Gnjlane as
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   But their inability to make the Serbs feel safe has left the
impression that the Americans are less even-handed than they claim
to be.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Marines' chief worries is just to protect themselves.
On Gnjlane's main street, three Marines with automatic rifles sat
in a sand-bagged outpost and watched the passing traffic.
</P>
<P>
   They were looking at the faces and hands of pedestrians,
scanning the rooftops and windows, staring at the passing cars.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Cpl. Sean Holcomb, 22, peered down the street with a pair
of binoculars. Days earlier, he had dashed across the street as
bullets from an unknown shooter, one of several that lashed out at
the Marines, had struck close behind him and another Marine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wakes you up and makes you realize the threat is always
there, never to relax,'' he said, not looking up from his task.
``It makes you realize that people will retaliate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
