<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4-KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS MOTHER IS AN APE, AND HE'S A LITTLE SWINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TARZAN
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver, Glenn Close, Sir
Nigel Hawthorne, Alex D. Linz, Rosie O'Donnell, Brian Blessed,
Lance Henriksen, Wayne Knight, Taylor Dempsey &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris Buck &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Freed visually by Disney animation and computer-generated
motion, the 48th Tarzan movie bounds spontaneously through the bush
if not across virgin narrative territory.
</P>
<P>
   With his parents done in by a leopard, the Greystoke baby is
gathered up by the gentle ape Kala (Ms. Close) over the misgivings
of her husband, Kerchak (Henriksen), leader of the pack, who can't
be argued with when he points out that the hairless one is not
their kind.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Tarzan, who morphs from a jungle sprite into
a lean machine slipping and sliding among the tree tops as if he
were liquid. Add good looks, a cheerful disposition and,
mercifully, only two Tarzan yells all movie long.
</P>
<P>
   The first triumphal bellow follows his defeat of the killer
leopard. Soon afterward, gun shots announce the arrival of a
species Tarzan never knew existed. Professor Porter (Sir Nigel) and
his daughter, Jane (Ms. Driver), have come from England to study
the apes for the furtherment of science.
</P>
<P>
   With another agenda, Clayton ( Blessed) shoots at anything that
moves and can scarcely contain his self-satisfaction over a scheme
to capture the apes and ship them home for a pretty fee.
</P>
<P>
   But Tarzan has met Jane. From her he learns that he needn't only
grunt when communicating; from him she learns to hop on a vine.
Together they face Clayton and the ultimate question about their
relationship: his habitat or hers?
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The fight with the leopard is plainly to the death.
Later the ape round-up goes none too gently.
</P>
<P>
   SEX None.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 The film is slightly more violent than the G rating
might indicate, but Tarzan and Jane are good people and the animals
make sweet, upbeat company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-10 Just right. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 It depends on the child, but this is a sleek,
sophisticated piece of animation that should appeal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP Only if they, like many adults, enjoy animated
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH PARK: BIGGER, LONGER AND UNCUT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Trey Parker, Matt Stone, Mary Kay Bergman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Trey Parker &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 88 minutes
</P>
<P>
   And now, exactly on time for the current flap over children's
admission to R-rated movies, comes an almost complete textbook
case: an R-rated obscenity-laced movie about children hooked on an
R-rated obscenity-laced movie.
</P>
<P>
   Had Parker's film, which calls on the gang from his and Stone's
``South Park'' show on Comedy Central, been a little heavier on
graphic violence, it would have presented a perfectly rounded R
specimen to consider.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the issues are enough to start a war between the
United States and Canada. In the ``redneck, white-bread'' mountain
town of South Park, Cartman, Stan, Kyle and little Kenny trot off
to the latest R-rated import starring two obscenity-spewing
Canadians, Terrance and Phillip.
</P>
<P>
   At the theater they are firmly thwarted by a ticket seller who
reminds them that no one under 17 is admitted without a parent or
guardian. A homeless man and the promise of a $10 bottle of vodka
quickly remove that impediment and the children settle in front and
center.
</P>
<P>
   Profane to begin with, Cartman emerges from the movie unable to
stop himself from speaking almost exclusively in four-letter words.
Stan and Kyle aren't much better off, nor are their third-grade
classmates who soon finagle their way in.
</P>
<P>
   Rallied by Kyle's mother, Sheila Broflovski, an outraged town
and nation spare no freedom to cleanse potty mouths. A professor
invents a V-chip that gives children an electrical shock every time
they curse.
</P>
<P>
   Looking beyond censorship and parental guidance, Sheila proposes
another remedy: ``Blame Canada!'' President Clinton buys that
approach and the military is assembled. Sheila places Terrance and
Phillip under citizens' arrest and they are scheduled to be
executed during a USO show.
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation, Canadian smart bombs wipe out the Baldwins.
Finally, Satan takes a hand _ and all over a rating system that
proclaims, according to Sheila, ``horrific, deplorable violence is
OK as long as people don't say naughty words.''
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Bullets fly and war rages among cartoonish stick
figures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Many crude references to various sex acts and prominent
displays of sexual organs, or representations thereof. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY See above and include a good amount of general raunch,
scatology, and racial and ethnic slurs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER 14 They will yowl in disappointment, but this isn't a
movie for young children (only about them). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14-17 Obviously the film has immense appeal for viewers
under 17. Given theater owners' announced intentions to check ages
at R-rated films, the situation should be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   BIG DADDY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adam Sandler, Joey Lauren Adams, Cole and Dylan Sprouse, Steve
Buscemi, Jon Stewart, Rob Schneider, Kristy Swanson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Dennis Dugan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A highway toll taker named Sonny Koufax (Sandler) finds himself
in custody of 5-year-old Julian (alternately played by Cole and
Dylan Sprouse). Julian, it seems, is a result of a liaison between
Sonny's friend Kevin (Stewart) and a woman he met during the
Toronto-Philadelphia World Series in 1993. About to die of cancer,
the woman ships Julian off unannounced to his father.
</P>
<P>
   But Sonny volunteers to take care of the boy after it is pointed
out that shouldering such a responsibility will make a favorable
impression on his girlfriend, Vanessa (Ms. Swanson). Nevertheless,
fretful about Sonny's one-day workweek and lack of ambition, she
drops him for a 60-year-old with a five-year-plan.
</P>
<P>
   A cut above the imbecile Sandler usually portrays, Sonny
dribbles milk down his chin but apparently has enough of an I.Q. to
have gotten through law school and enough heart to stick it out and
bond with the boy. That helps attract a woman after all: a young
lawyer named Layla (Ms. Adams), who finds Sonny's jaunty sloth as
appealing as Vanessa found it off-putting. But custody problems
loom, requiring all the legalistics and courtroom emoting Sonny and
friends can muster.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Other than continually talking about it, none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Lots of cursing, bathroom vulgarity and references to
women's breasts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 They won't be stunted, but the film is coarse in
places and there are better things to do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 Ah, the call of Sandler. This is not to suggest
children routinely ignore parental wishes about films like this,
but young viewers will congregate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP Fine unless parents have an objection.
</P>
</TEXT>
