<HEADER>
A6249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-ARCHITECTURE-2T     07-01 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ARCHITECTURE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE UNPRIVATE HOUSE': 26 THOUGHT-PROVOKING DESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it comes to architecture exhibitions, nothing
hits home like a show about houses. It is a subject to which
everyone brings an intimate familiarity, strong opinions and
feelings both buried and exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home is Where We Start From,'' as the English psychoanalyst
D.W. Winnicott put it in the title of one of his books. At once
inescapable and irretrievable, it affects all future decisions
about where and how we live. The philosopher Gaston Bachelard
defined the childhood home as our ``first universe,'' the adult one
as ``a nest for dreaming, a shelter for the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequently one echoes the other. It is not surprising that I
love the proportions of my New York apartment: They recall the
low-slung lines of the house I grew up in, which was also of early
1950s vintage.
</P>
<P>
   From a more esthetic viewpoint, the private house can seem like
the architectural equivalent of easel painting, both of which are
about half a millennium old. Like painting, the house is the most
intimate and familiar, continuous and contested, malleable and
beloved form of its discipline, although its death is not nearly so
regularly announced.
</P>
<P>
   So ``The Un-Private House,'' the Museum of Modern Art's swank,
thought-provoking exhibition of 26 houses designed in the last
decade, is almost guaranteed to attract a large interested audience
inclined to think for itself. Happily, it will reward this audience
in ways that range from superficial to profound, from physical to
visual. But it also falls short in certain respects. Sometimes the
universes these houses define seem a little too complete and,
despite the show's title, cut off from the world.
</P>
<P>
   After clothing design, there is probably no more accurate
physical measure of changes in a culture's mores, customs,
demographics and taste than the design of its domestic dwellings.
When it explores the consequences of this, the show can trigger
complex, opposing responses.
</P>
<P>
   One minute it seems you are seeing successive waves of the
future, worthy of big attention-getting headlines. Postmodernism as
an architectural style is really over. Computer technology is
changing everything. The nuclear family is not what it used to be.
Ditto for domesticity.
</P>
<P>
   At other points the show simply seems to provide voyeuristic
glimpses of how the other half _ or an elite 10 to 20 percent,
maybe _ lives. As in a high-end shelter magazine, it is rife with
examples of drop-dead beauty and luxe, ingenious design,
cutting-edge electronic gadgetry and spacious interiors with that
pristine unlived-in look. It proves several times over that people
with money, imagination and self-knowledge can end up with stunning
domiciles.
</P>
<P>
   The two reactions, of course, are not unrelated. Inventions
popular with the rich tend to become less expensive, witness indoor
plumbing, color television and cell phones. Just because you
currently can't afford a house with video or computer screens for
walls doesn't mean that you never will.
</P>
<P>
   And there are special needs that turn out to be inspiring. A
large collection of video art results in a Northern Californian
house whose walls are, in effect, video screens. Some 10,000 books
lead to a house in New York state where the library is shut away
from the sun yet windowed on four sides. A desire for
round-the-clock trading facilities yields a New York loft-apartment
designed for two brokers that not only has its own trading room but
also monitors to display market activity in every room.
</P>
<P>
   The most brilliant design solution may be found at the core of
Rem Koolhaas' handsome Corbusier-flavored Maison a Bordeaux, with
its glass-enclosed living room supporting a slab of brown concrete
rooms _ the bedroom wing. Designed to accommodate a client in a
wheelchair, it has a central wall-less office, powered by a
hydraulic lift, that moves up and down to three floors.
</P>
<P>
   Geared to needs we don't have quite yet is the Digital House
designed by Hariri &AMP; Hariri on a commission from House Beautiful,
to be built with liquid-crystal-display blocks (just like a laptop
computer screen). Inhabitants would be able to simply log-on and
call up famous chefs for cooking tips on the kitchen wall, replace
the house's surroundings with views of their own choice, or see
their dearest fantasies played out larger than life in the bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Un-Private House'' has been organized by Terence Riley,
chief curator of the Modern's department of architecture and
design, and it is the museum's first exhibition in 30 years devoted
exclusively to domestic architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's first premise is that the best, most adventurous
architecture of the last decade has been domestic. (Given the state
of recent commercial and public architecture, the opinion seems
irrefutable.) His second is that this vitality stems from the way
the house is being reshaped on every side, rendered porous and
permeable _ ``un-private'' _ in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   One way is by new definitions of public and private space: Many
of the houses here have enlarged and opened bathrooms or moveable
walls; others make extensive use of new transparent or translucent
materials, like polycarbons. Another way is by technological
advances: Computers, which allow more and more people to work at
home yet remain plugged into the outside world, are also making the
houses themselves increasing interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Also an impetus reshaping the house is the rise in the number of
childless couples, same-sex couples and people who live alone: The
house is no longer centered on marriage, raising children or the
traditional family.
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, Riley has brought together a stylistically
eclectic selection of houses designed since 1988. All but six of
the 26 have been or are being built, at locales that range from
downtown Tokyo, New York City and Los Angeles to the French,
English and Northern California countryside, to the residential
suburbs of Brussels, Belgium; Minneapolis, and Buenos Aires,
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the architects, like Koolhaas, Bernard Tschumi, Steven
Holl and the Swiss firm of Herzog &AMP; de Meuron, are well known, if
not world famous. Others, like Diller &AMP; Scofidio, have growing
reputations. But most are unknown outside architectural circles.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They work in styles ranging from the circling, destabilized
intersecting forms of the Mobius House, designed by UN Studio/Van
Berkel &AMP; Bos in the Netherlands, to the undulating, organic lines,
a mixture of Gaudi, Goff and Gehry, of Preston Scott Cohen's Torus
House under construction in Old Chatham, N.Y.; from the solid
rectilinear volumes of Francois de Menil's Shorthand House in
Houston to the shimmering, translucent ones of Scogin Elam and Bray
Architects' 64 Wakefield in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There are several show-stoppers: Shigeru Ban's Curtain Wall
House in downtown Toyko, whose floors can be as open to the street
as a couple of shelves or cloaked in fabric like a Christo; the
T-House in Wilton, N.Y., by Simon Ungers with Thomas Kinslow, which
includes that 10,000-book library. Symmetrical as an alter, clad
entirely in Cor-Ten steel, the T-House suggests what Richard Serra
might do if he suddenly became obsessed with Stonehenge.
</P>
<P>
   And yet an odd kind of coherence prevails. Overall, the designs
suggest that the houses of the late 20th century may be closer in
spirit to the modernist houses of the early part of the century
than has been the case in several decades. Flat of roof, exposed of
structure, distinguished by the simple use of new materials,
frequently adhering to a grid in both plan and elevation, they
evoke the spirits of Mies van der Rohe, Le Corbusier, Richard
Neutra, Gerrit Rietveld and the Case Study Houses of postwar Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The only sign of postmodern quotation is Clorindo Testa's
jarring, nonsensical renovation of a Tudor-style house in Buenos
Aires, which includes a cut stair bannister that appears to bleed.
The only hint of a peaked roof is found on Neil Denari's unbuilt
Massey House, whose gently sloping enamel steel roof curves and
continues down the structure's sides, creating a sleek floating box
top that hovers ambiguously between house, Quonset hut and factory.
</P>
<P>
   It should be pointed out that there are exceptions to the
general spare-no-expense atmosphere. Michael Bell's 900-square-foot
Glass House at 2(DEG) may resemble Philip Johnson's glass house,
but it was designed and built to conform to the strict requirements
of a federal housing program. Similarly modest is Workhouse in Los
Angeles, designed by the architects Danelle Guthrie and Tom Buresh
for themselves: Its split-level interior is made entirely of
plywood, its exterior clad in a smooth skin of polycarbonate
panels, which glows softly when the lights are on.
</P>
<P>
   Riley's use of the same material for the exhibition's
freestanding walls gives the show some of the see-through
transparency that is one of his themes. The overall appearance here
is part graphic design studio, part architect's atelier, part comfy
living room. The walls are papered with big color photographs,
texts and well-labeled floor plans _ all over a pale band of
William Morris wallpaper that signals the Arts and Crafts Movement,
one of the points of origin of the modern house.
</P>
<P>
   The houses are also represented by detailed, often beautiful
scale models that, taken together, form an elaborate exegesis on
the state of the art of model building. There are also a couple of
eerie virtual-reality house tours.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the main themes and ideas, domesticity reigns:
There's not a museum pedestal in sight. All the models are
displayed on the big, plain-spoken, solid wood dining, kitchen and
drafting tables and the metal tables and shelving designed by David
Schaefer and others for Furniture Co., his New York City company,
which is in effect having its first solo show.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture Co. is also responsible for many chairs and stools and
for the big cushy lounge chairs and couches, grouped on rugs and
around coffee tables, that count as the most comfortable museum
seating in recent memory. It should be added that these designs,
which evoke the Arts and Crafts Movement by way of Donald Judd, are
considerably more old-fashioned than anything found in the houses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, visitors can experience firsthand the increasingly
interactive nature of the contemporary house and of the computer's
growing invisibility _ its absorption into walls and familiar
objects. The show's interactive component, thanks to a system
designed by the Media Lab at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, is embedded in a big round dining room table (seating
for 12) with a lazy susan. From this revolving surface, a visitor
chooses one of 26 coaster-size discs and places it on a circle in
front of her (roughly where a glass of water would be); a
programmed screen displaying the floor plan of one of the houses
instantly pops into view, like a digital place mat, ready for
browsing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fullness of Riley's treatment of his theme, one
leaves this show with several questions, both about what is here
and what is not. First of all, despite their open interiors and
integration of work and living spaces, the majority of these houses
seem decidedly private. In photographs, they are usually plopped in
the middle of large, parklike acreages, seemingly far from towns,
streets or even neighbors, related only to the natural landscape
and the invisible fabric of cyberspace. They are beautiful esthetic
objects, but with the exception Bell's glass house and possibly
Denari's metal one, none could be a prototype for a larger
community.
</P>
<P>
   Riley maintains that throughout the century, the house has been
the site of important architectural experimentation. If so, its
successful innovations can't be applied fast enough to the larger
architectural and social situation _ to the building of apartment
houses and commercial and public buildings that directly and
indirectly shape the lives of more and more of the world's
population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
