<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6257 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT &LR;      07-01 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: `HIGH NOON'; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `HIGH NOON,' FRAME BY FRAME
</P>
<P>
   Watching films on digital videodisc, one gets into the habit of
stopping the film suddenly to look at scenes in freeze frame. There
may be no other reason for this than to use the disc's sharpness
and clarity to see what any one second in a movie, especially a
famous one, looks like as a still picture. Do it often and randomly
enough in ``High Noon,'' Fred Zinnemann's classic western, released
last week on DVD and in a new videocassette edition by Artisan, and
the exercise reveals a production that, even caught unawares, so to
speak, stays steadily on its game from first frame to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not forsake me,'' begins the famous song at the outset of
the film, about a town marshal, Will Kane, portrayed by Gary Cooper
in the latter stages of his career, whose sense of principle and
honor won't let him flee when four gunmen come to kill him. Grace
Kelly, in her first starring role, is his bride, a Quaker who
because of her own principles can't bring herself to stay and face
the bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   In a documentary included on the disc but not on the tape, film
critic Leonard Maltin notes that the movie was unusual for its time
_ 1952 _ in that it was shot in black and white, brought something
of a Shakespearean flavor to its sense of moral struggle and
impending tragedy, and held all its action to the end.
</P>
<P>
   As with many special editions, the Artisan disc and tape are
``digitally remastered from the film negative,'' which has lent the
black-and-white ``stills'' within it a wonderfully fresh, vivid
feel. In any one of them involving Cooper there is a man whose
every expression, from resolve to hurt and bewilderment, is not
only a dead-on evocation of emotion but also a reflection of
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Noted himself for an economical style, Zinnemann (``From Here to
Eternity,'' ``A Man for All Seasons'') shot the film in 28 days for
$730,000. Accounts usually mention that not a frame was wasted.
Stop any one of them and the entire story, written by Carl Foreman
(``The Bridge on the River Kwai''), seems served by that instant
and propelled by it.
</P>
<P>
   A Viennese, Zinnemann, who died in 1997, was considered an odd
choice to direct a western. In the documentary he says that the
universality of Kane's plight drew him and lists three elements he
kept in the film's forefront: the stark reality of the railroad
tracks that would bring evil to town at high noon, a man (Kane)
asking for help from a town that deserts him, and the unstoppable
march of several clocks toward the dreaded hour.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who died in 1961, put up with physical ailments during
the shooting, which lends a gauntness to the stills. Before a
packed church, Kane asks the people to help him defend the town he
has long defended for them. In a stream of equivocation they turn
their backs, leaving him standing dead alone looking by turns
imploring and embarrassed. In the stills, his discomfort is even
more immediate than it is in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper liked westerns. ``The good ones are real,'' he said in an
interview used in the documentary. ``You feel real when you're
making them.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `AFFLICTION'
</P>
<P>
   About to fly out of control, the small-town policeman Wade
Whitehouse (Nick Nolte in the performance of his career) realizes
that his hardest job is to police himself. For Wade, a brutal
boyhood under the thumb of a drunken savage of a father (James
Coburn) has led to a life of anguish. Botched relations with his
daughter (Brigid Tierney) and former wife (Mary Beth Hurt) don't
help, nor do the depressed conditions in Lawford, N.H., where he
works. A final, ghastly confrontation leads to Wade's particular
undoing, but in its universality, Paul Schrader's quietly stunning
film, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``succeeds in
finding something larger than one man's misery.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $99.36. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `HILARY AND JACKIE'
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't have that cello to prop you up, you'd be
nothing,'' says Hilary du Pre (Rachel Griffiths) to her sister
Jacqueline (Emily Watson). Resentment goes with a complex, troubled
relationship that ends with Jackie, the acclaimed cellist, dead of
multiple sclerosis at age 42. A kind of concerto in three
movements, Anand Tucker's film follows the sisters through
childhood, then into a period of separation when Hilary marries and
Jackie goes off to become famous. In Act III, Jackie returns
wanting to take over Hilary's husband (David Morrissey) and life,
in ``one of the most insightful and wrenching portraits of the joys
and tribulations of being a classical musician ever filmed''
(Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $108.81. 124 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `THE HI-LO COUNTRY'
</P>
<P>
   British director Stephen Frears tries his hand with the story of
two young cowboys (Billy Crudup and Woody Harrelson) who go into
the cattle business together in New Mexico after World War II. Big
Boy (Harrelson) is the ferociously exuberant type while his friend
Pete (Crudup) just tends to the livestock. Sam Elliott is the
sinister cattle baron in their way and Patricia Arquette is the
married woman Pete and Big Boy fall for, in a film that in its best
moments ``feels like an epic hybrid of `Red River' and `The Last
Picture Show''' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $108.81. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `THE MIGHTY'
</P>
<P>
   Two boys, the big, hulking Maxwell (Elden Henson) and his
disabled next-door neighbor, Kevin (Kieran Culkan), form a
fortuitous friendship. Max does the walking (Kevin is locked in leg
braces) and Kevin makes him feel less obtuse by being smart and
funny. Together they develop a sort of medieval fortress approach
to life in Peter Chelsom's film, whose ``sense of visual
enchantment easily accommodates the boys' preoccupation with all
things Arthurian'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 100 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   `SIBERIAN LADY MACBETH'
</P>
<P>
   `FATHER'
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED AND THE WHITE'
</P>
<P>
   Three films from the so-called Eastern European New Wave, two of
them available on video for the first time, reflect the outlook of
filmmakers in the Soviet bloc of the 1960s. In ``Siberian Lady
Macbeth'' (1962, 93 minutes), a Yugoslav film by Polish director
Andrzej Wajda (``Ashes and Diamonds''), a woman driven by her
passion for a drifter faces her own destruction. In Serbo-Croatian
with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Istvan Szabo's ``Father'' (1966, 85 minutes), also new on tape,
is the story of a young boy named Tako (Dani Erdelyi), who has
visions of his dead father as a freedom fighter and hero. As a man,
Tako (Andras Balint) tries to live up to that image, which now
includes the fantasy that his father protected Hungarian Jews from
the Nazis. ``A beautiful study of the need for heritage,'' Richard
F. Shepard wrote in The New York Times. Hungarian with English
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red and the White'' (1968, 92 minutes), by Miklos Jansco,
follows a young Hungarian revolutionary in central Russia after
1918, recording arrests, imprisonment and escapes in a struggle in
which one side often seems to mirror the other.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are $24.95 each. Release date: Tuesday. Information:
(800) 562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   `THE UNQUIET DEATH OF JULIUS AND ETHEL ROSENBERG'
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Goldstein's film chronicles the case of the couple put to
death in 1953 for passing atomic secrets to the Soviet Union (1974,
83 minutes). Facets. $29.95. Release date: Tuesday. Information:
(800) 331-6197.
</P>
</TEXT>
