<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      07-01 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE HOOP LIFE': NO SURPRISES. NO SWEAT. 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at and of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the NBA season is over, basketball fans are invited to
turn their attention to the UBA No, that's not the women's league.
It's the fictional outfit at the center of ``The Hoop Life,'' a new
Showtime series that begins with a two-hour episode on Sunday
night. (Future shows will be an hour each.)
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's drama sows the seeds of a garden of subplots as it
introduces the central characters: the people on and around a
single team, the New England Knights. While elements of the show
are promising enough to encourage another look, the opener fails to
capture, even metaphorically, the electricity of basketball. It has
neither the game's driving pace nor its surprising turns.
</P>
<P>
   Generously sprinkled with salty language and naked, willing
women, the show seems to be proclaiming its gritty reality. But
proclaiming isn't the same as delivering. A world in which
basketball stars don't seem to work up a sweat, on the court or in
private, hardly feels real.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting among the regular characters is the
Knights' weary and wary coach, Leonard Fero, played by Dan Lauria.
Most familiar as the gruff father on the series ``The Wonder
Years,'' Lauria here plays a father figure who is more rounded,
literally and figuratively, a man who is trying to grasp a handful
of dignity in a life filled with compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard has a complicated relationship with the team's general
manager, Eliot Pierce (Dorian Harewood), who once played for the
coach. Harewood, of the television series ``Seventh Heaven,''
offers a man still trying to redirect an athlete's energy into the
demands of his job and of his boss, the team owner, Emily Yeager
(Linda Thorson). These front-office dynamics could prove
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hoop Life'' also focuses on three of the Knights' players,
each with his own circle of family and hangers-on. Curtis Thorpe
(Cirroc Lofton) is the high school phenom who is drafted by the
team after he decides to forgo college.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton, the captain's son on ``Star Trek: Deep Space Nine,''
will no doubt be called upon to morph from boy into man as the
series moves along. He seems appropriately overwhelmed by what he
finds in Sunday's episode. Curtis' saintly grandmother (Lynda
Gravatt) and greedy uncle-manager (Raymond Anthony Thomas) are
easily the most interesting among the dozens of secondary
characters who are dangled before the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   The team's two veteran stars, Marvin Buxton (Mykelti Williamson)
and Greg Marr (Rick Peters), should be the show's stars, too. But
so far they seem like a pair of selfish overgrown babies, and not
very interesting ones. Their love lives are complicated. Isn't
everybody's?
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's episode, written by Sean Jablonski and directed by
Kevin Hooks, has so much ground to cover that it can barely spare a
moment for any hint of wit. Yet it often feels sluggish, even
during its opening sequence, a montage meant to convey the Knights'
narrow loss in the seventh game of a league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   As the team looks ahead to its next season, all eyes are on
young Curtis, who sunnily tells the coach he has been waiting for
this chance his whole life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coaching longer than you've been alive,'' Leonard
replies. ``That doesn't impress me. (italics)De(end italics)-fense
impresses me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hoop Life'' is another rookie that still has to prove it
has the stuff. As a television series, it may be pro material. But
if you want basketball, head for that women's league.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   HOOP LIFE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, Sunday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   Written by Sean Jablonski and directed by Kevin Hooks. Steve
Wakefield, producer; David Herrington, director of photography;
Larry Andries, co-producer; Judith McCreary, Grace McKeaney,
supervising producers. Music by Bennie Wallace. Joe Cacaci,
executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mykelti Williamson (Marvin Buxton), Dorian Harewood (Eliot
Pierce); Rick Peters (Greg Marr), Cirroc Lofton (Curtis Thorpe),
Dan Lauria (Coach Leonard Fero), Linda Thorson (Emily Yeager),
Raymond Anthony Thomas (Kenny Williams), Robert Hooks (Willis
Barry), Reno Wilson (Owen Davis) and Lynda Gravatt (Celia Thorpe).
</P>
