<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CIVIL-$ADV04-1     07-01 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CIVIL-$ADV04-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in lede, changes 'is sure' to read 'agrees'; 3rd graf, adds
to read 'human and livestock corpses . . . '
 &HT;    TAMING THE KOSOVARS: U.N. RUSHES TO BUILD A COUNTRY
 &HT;    1350&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. July 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ There's no real police force here yet,
which may explain why children have been seen driving cars. No one
agrees who owns what, so people are staking their claims to the
tractor next door, the house down the street and the factory in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   There are no trials, elected officials or tax collectors.
Official records -- those that remain -- are under guard to prevent
their being destroyed by retreating Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   And, last week, aid groups started confronting a new question:
Who is responsible for removing human and livestock corpses that
are contaminating hundreds of water wells?
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to U.N. Country, also known as Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Government institutions are nonexistent in this Serbian province
torn apart by ethnic hatred and war. In the absence of any central
authority, it's up to a few hundred U.N. workers to set up a
government for a divided public that craves structure.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Sergio Vieira de Mello, the special representative from
the United Nations, will decide which laws and people rule the
land. He runs the show from a badly looted Yugoslav army building,
where doors don't lock and employees are urged to take their
computers home with them at night.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is a Kosovo that will hold elections and govern itself
as an autonomous region within Yugoslavia. The United Nations will
oversee the slow transfer of institutions and property from the
hands of ethnic Serbs to the majority ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   But, whether and just how that will be done is still under
contention between the two enemies. The NATO bombing has stopped,
but the battle for Kosovo, which had an estimated 1.8 million
people before the massive refugee flight started in March, will
continue with each ministry, company, house or cow that is
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has run parts or all of countries before,
from Bosnia to Cambodia to Rwanda. But, it has never started with
such major issues unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``A major complication is that, in other U.N. peacekeeping
operations, you had an agreed upon settlement,'' Eric Morris, a
senior official overseeing the formation of the U.N. Mission in
Kosovo (UNMIK) said. ``Here, you will be dealing on a daily basis
with questions of sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty is a recipe for chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a race, if you don't have some fundamental rule
of law and institutions operating, that (chaos) could be the
result.'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   For help, the United Nations is delegating reconstruction duties
to the European Union. Democracy-building tasks, such as organizing
elections and training police, fall to the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees asked for $106 million
for its work in June and UNMIK, with about 400 staff and rising,
needs $60 million to get started.
</P>
<P>
   The actual reconstruction of the country, with thousands of
homes and businesses burned, will take billions of dollars and
possibly 10 years. At least 50 private aid agencies are at work.
</P>
<P>
   But, the United Nations is already running to catch-up. Last
week, U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan urged foreign ministers and
officials from 18 nations and three regional organizations to
provide the manpower they have promised. For example, only half the
55,000 NATO troops planned have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is worse for police, which U.N. officials say is
the top priority. But Annan secured promises for 1,938 of the 3,110
civilian police needed from U.N. countries.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, only 36 had arrived. But the United States
pledged 450 officers, the first 100 of whom would be sent by July
15, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said. The United States
also offered another 100 police trainers. Germany offered 200
officers and Italy, Turkey and Canada also announced increases in
offers they had already made.
</P>
<P>
   A major issue still dividing countries and delaying the police
deployment is whether the civilian police should be armed. The
Netherlands said it preferred the police to be unarmed as most U.N.
civilian police are. Britain as well indicated it would have
trouble contributing to an armed police mission because the bulk of
its own police force was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Albright agreed with U.N. officials that at least some of the
police would have to be armed and have the authority to make
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In their race, U.N. officials have one major advantage: The
desire among most Kosovars -- both Albanian and Serb -- for order.
</P>
<P>
   It may be volunteerism, more than U.N., EU and NATO muscle, that
will rebuild Kosovo. Last week, as shops were starting to re-open
and the first signs of normalcy appeared on the streets of
Pristina, ethnic Albanian Jakup Mehmeti strapped two traffic lights
to the top of his old Opel.
</P>
<P>
   He picked them up from NATO officials running the municipality
and was on his way to install them at an intersection. That was his
job 10 years ago, before the Serbs took over and fired him. He
volunteered to do it again while the United Nations gets organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody is going to pay me, I just want to do
it,'' said Mehmeti. ``I want to see my city safe and the traffic
better.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of ethnic Albanians taking the law into their
own hands, most are ready to find their justice in due course. All
you have to do is go to the provisional police station set up by
British troops, and you can see patient Albanians lined up for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs stole the inventory from Selim Gravalla's building company
and burned his house. But, he waited hours in line to report the
crimes last week, rather than take a match to the abandoned house
of the Serb he knows burned his.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he says. ``I do not want to be on their level. I had a
chance to do that a hundred times, but I have not broken even one
little thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, relief for people like Gravalla will come slowly.
Currently, NATO forces are so stretched thin that they are slow to
arrive to even life-threatening crimes in progress. At times,
looting has occurred before their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They pull suspected criminals into a legal system with no trials
or uniform laws. American, British, French, Italian and German
troops follow their own countries' procedures for temporary
detention.
</P>
<P>
   As for courts, de Mello last week swore in seven legal experts,
including three Albanians and a Serb, to begin appointing the
judges. The first judges will likely travel between NATO detention
centers, clearing the backlog of more than 150 detainees.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the question is what law to use. Yugoslav law will be the
foundation, except when it conflicts with international human
rights standards. For example, the United Nations will scrap
Yugoslav laws that allow long detentions for interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   In straightening out non-criminal disputes, the United Nations
is forming seven committees, made-up of Serbs and Albanians, that
will advise and mediate. Of immediate concern are the nearly
violent altercations taking place over employment.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians were purged of their government jobs from
universities, hospitals, factories and ministries when the Serbs
stripped Kosovo of its autonomy in 1989. They were also summarily
fired from private sector businesses such as major hotels and
restaurants. Since NATO came into Kosovo, the workers have been
gathering like ghosts at their old job sites demanding their jobs
back.
</P>
<P>
   Among other sites, NATO troops have had to seal off Pristina's
giant Grand Hotel and the government television complex to keep
violence from erupting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get back our offices and jobs,'' said Mehmet
Mehmeti, a-52-year-old former mining executive who has been driving
taxis since he was fired with 2,400 ethnic Albanian mine workers in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Their old mining office is now the arts building of a Serb-run
university, but that's where Mehmeti and about 30 other men have
been waiting daily while negotiations determine who gets to go back
to work.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what will happen to those owed pensions in the
public jobs, up until now controlled by the Serb-led Yugoslav
government. Also, the Serbs systematically destroyed identification
documents. U.S.-based Microsoft Corp. has donated computer
equipment to begin a re-identification program for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations will also be the final authority on education
in Kosovo, another issue that was contentious long before the NATO
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Since a Serb curriculum was imposed in 1990, most ethnic
Albanians have sent their children to the Albanian ``shadow''
school system. It was financed by Albanian donations.
</P>
<P>
   The system was hit hard during the Serb campaign of ethnic
cleansing this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Only halfway through an assessment of the 1,000 elementary
schools for ethnic Albanians, UNICEF officials have found that at
least 170 schools have been damaged by burning and looting.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools are destroyed. Some are booby-trapped, or worse. In
the United States, officials worry about guns near schools. In
Kosovo, two British soldiers were killed by unexploded NATO cluster
bombs near a schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there is a shortage of the estimated 18,000
teachers needed, as many are missing or refugees. UNICEF's Flaka
Surroi said it is unknown at this point who will pay teacher
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   After the schools are repaired, it's likely that the United
Nations will monitor curriculum and textbooks to make sure the
schools are not teaching ethnic hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Surroi would like to see some schools eventually integrated,
with Serb and Albanian children using the same buildings, as they
have infrequently in the past. An ethnic Albanian herself, Surroi
said she hopes someday they can even share bilingual education. In
that case, the United Nations would have surpassed all
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do that as an experiment within five years, but not
now,'' she says. ``It was partly segregation that brought us to
this situation now.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
