<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILROAD-KILLER-HNS &LR;      07-01 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILROAD-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS KNEW OF SUSPECTED KILLER BEFORE RELEASING HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department admitted Thursday that
immigration officers failed to detain accused killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez last month even though the police in Houston had
told federal agents that the man was a murder suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, something got screwed up along the way,'' said
Carole Florman, a Justice Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service also announced that a
Justice Department watchdog would investigate why agents along the
border deported the fugitive, who is charged with two killings and
is an suspect in six others.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston police informed INS officials in December that
Resendez-Ramirez was wanted for questioning in the death of a
Houston physician earlier that month. The police asked the INS
district office for any information it had on the man, Florman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, INS officials in Houston provided the police
department with background information and photos of
Resendez-Ramirez, Florman said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, INS officials said that the 39-year-old drifter, also
known as Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis, was deported to Mexico on
June 2 after being captured a day earlier by Border Patrol agents.
He was caught illegally crossing into the United States near Santa
Teresa, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The INS, which is part of the Justice Department, oversees the
Border Patrol. Florman said the INS had no explanation for why the
entire agency was not alerted about Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know who made the mistake, but a mistake was made in
communicating this information,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez was wanted for questioning in three killings in
Texas and one in Kentucky when he was detained on June 1. He also
is suspected in at least two slayings in Texas and two in Illinois
that occurred after he was deported.
</P>
<P>
   INS Commissioner Doris Meissner said Thursday she referred the
case to the Justice Department's inspector general, who
investigates abuses within the department and its agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Resendez-Ramirez case has raised serious questions about
INS' knowledge of the case and procedures used in encounters with
Resendez-Ramirez,'' Meissner said in a statement. ``These issues
include why Resendez-Ramirez had multiple entries in the (INS
computer) system and was not detained and whether INS knew about
Resendez-Ramirez's criminal activities after being contacted by
local law enforcement earlier this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said the agency also would review ``the effectiveness
of our current systems in an effort to avoid any similar situation
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS computer identification system _ called IDENT _ contains
information such as fingerprints and photographs of illegal
immigrants who are detained by INS officials. The system was
developed in 1994 to track illegal border crossers and became
widely used between 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the system is primarily a database about how many times a
person has illegally crossed the border, it does contain some
criminal background information, according to Meissner.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents also have access to the FBI's crime
database through a separate system but do not routinely run a check
on all of the 1.5 million illegal immigrants who are detained along
the U.S.-Mexico border each year.
</P>
<P>
   When people are detained by INS for illegally crossing the
border, their fingerprints are entered into the system for
identification. Before the system was installed, those caught
crossing the border illegally routinely used aliases.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez was detained by Border Patrol agents in Texas
and New Mexico nine times between January 1998 and June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is charged in the June 15 murders of George
Morber, 80, and his daughter, Carolyn Frederick, 52, in Gorham,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   He is a suspect in the deaths of:
</P>
<P>
   _ Christopher Maier, 21, in Lexington, Ky., on Aug. 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife Karen, 47, in Weimar,
Texas, on April 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Claudia Benton, 39, of Houston, on Dec. 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Josephine Konvicka, 73, of Fayette County, Texas, on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   _ Noemi Dominguez, 26, of Houston, on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe Resendez-Ramirez travels by freight train
because the deaths all occurred near train tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year officers investigating Benton's killing found
fingerprints on his car and sent them to the Texas Department of
Public Safety, which later matched the prints of Resendez-Ramirez.
The FBI issued a warrant for his arrest on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
