<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     07-01 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(af) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Company of Profit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bash'' is a smash. (But can it last?)
</P>
<P>
   With a trio of hot Hollywood actors, a hot Hollywood writer and
a batch of hot reviews, the evening of three short plays by Neil
LaBute has completely sold out its five-week off-Broadway run. The
producers are looking for ways to extend the show past July 24, its
closing date.
</P>
<P>
   The main obstacle is that the current cast can't stick around.
Calista Flockhart has to return to California to film her
television series, ``Ally McBeal.'' Ron Eldard, meanwhile, goes
directly from ``Bash'' to Broadway's ``Death of a Salesman,''
taking over the role of Biff on July 28. The third player, Paul
Rudd, is entertaining offers but could be available for an
extension.
</P>
<P>
   So the hunt is on for replacements. Eric Krebs, one of the
producers, would not say who was being sought, but an agent
involved in negotiations said Sarah Jessica Parker and Aaron
Eckhart, a veteran of LaBute's films, had been approached.
</P>
<P>
   The sell-out notwithstanding, ``Bash'' is not a huge moneymaker,
yet. Playing in the 199-seat Douglas Fairbanks Theater, the show
will certainly return its $120,000 initial investment by July 24,
but the profit will only be about $20,000, Krebs said. With an
extension, that number could very well increase, though Krebs said
a move to a larger theater was not being considered. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Positive `Side' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Has the ``Side Man'' gambit paid off?
</P>
<P>
   After enduring a string of money-losing months, the producers of
``Side Man'' have watched their sales surge since the drama won the
Tony Award for best play on June 6. Last week the show grossed
$189,449, its biggest week since early January, with crowds running
at a healthy 83 percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the miserable days of late April, when
audiences were running at less than 40 percent, and weekly losses
sometimes reached $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The play has also benefited from smart casting, including the
current addition of Scott Wolf, the young television actor who
plays the narrator and whose effect on the opposite sex seems to be
particularly dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott has an enormous following among young women,'' said Jay
Harris, one of the producers. ``There are literally droves of women
out front of the theater every night. And it's a joy to have them
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the show has landed another Hollywood star to fill the
narrator's shoes. Andrew McCarthy, a former Brat Pack member, has
been signed for 12 weeks beginning on July 19.
</P>
<P>
   The show is still far from recouping its initial $750,000
investment, and the coming weeks may prove critical to its
long-term success. But Harris said positive signs abound.
</P>
<P>
   The total advance sales for the play have doubled in the last
month, to about $300,000. And a $100,000 loan, taken out during the
fallow days of late spring, will probably be repaid by the end of
July. Between the sale of movie rights and royalties from regional
productions, Harris said, he is confident the play will eventually
return its investment. ``It would be sinful if a show like this
couldn't make money,'' Harris said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who's the Star? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking over a role in a hit show like ``Wit'' is never easy. And
when the role is the one played by Kathleen Chalfant, whose
portrayal of the stricken professor Vivian Bearing has been praised
to the moon, the task is downright daunting.
</P>
<P>
   But the play's producers say they have found a replacement who's
up to the challenge. She is Judith Light, a veteran actress perhaps
best known as Tony Danza's foil on the television sitcom ``Who's
the Boss?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women were deathly afraid to replace Kathleen because it's
been hailed as the performance of the year,'' said Bernard Telsey,
a producer and casting director for the play. ``But Judith came in
and really understood the role, and had the smarts and emotional
life to nail it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chalfant, who has played Vivian since the show's first
incarnation in New Haven two years ago, gives her final performance
on Aug. 8. Ms. Light begins on Aug. 10. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House, Darkly &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Anna Deavere Smith first decided to take a look at the
presidency and its relationship with the press, the Clinton
administration was in its early days, and Monica Lewinsky was still
in high school.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of on and off work, the first viewing of the
resulting piece, ``House Arrest,'' was in late 1997 at the Arena
Stage in Washington. But a month later Monicagate began, prompting
Ms. Smith to pull the piece from planned performances in Los
Angeles and Seattle, to enlarge President Clinton's role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened me up to something bigger,'' Ms. Smith said, ``which
is the question of how we know what we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Next March she will bring the piece to the Joseph Papp Public
Theater. But unlike workshop versions, which had full casts, the
Public's will feature Ms. Smith performing solo, a style in which
she rose to fame with ``Fires in the Mirror'' and later with
``Twilight: Los Angeles 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith said there was a bonus to adding more Clinton to the
mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love performing him,'' she said. ``He does these astonishing
linguistic things.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues'' may have been snubbed by
the Tonys, but it's not slowing down. On Sept. 8 the revue will
shift from Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theater to another
Broadway theater, the Ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call it the anti-``Via Dolorosa.'' Last summer, Marc Maron, a
downtown comic, took a trip through Israel equipped with a dry wit
and a balky video camera. His resulting monologue, ``Jerusalem
Syndrome,'' takes on pressing issues like the search for
spirituality and the search for the perfect pair of Nikes. The
show's at Nada 45, 445 West 45th Street, Clinton. Information:
(212) 581-6030.
</P>
<P>
   _ Impress your friends: The Right Size, a British comedy team
that was a hit at the Edinburgh Fringe festival (i.e., unknown in
the United States) opens a four-week run at P.S. 122 in the East
Village on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   _ The final rinse cycle has begun for ``Symphonie Fantastique,''
the abstract underwater puppet show developed by Basil Twist,
playing at Here, at 145 Avenue of the Americas, at Dominick Street,
South Village. Producers posted an Aug. 15 closing date this week.
</P>
<P>
   The watery spectacle, which completes a simultaneous run in San
Francisco on Sunday, will most likely go on tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
