</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-01 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HENLEY, CLASSIC BOATS TO CHERISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among motor boat enthusiasts, the vintage launch has always been
the queen of the waterways. Though its purpose _ to celebrate
idyllic river life _ may be frivolous, the boat is not a frivolous
enterprise. It must have beauty, history and fine wood patina, and
it cannot make waves, so it can be properly admired as it purrs
along.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds very English, it is.
</P>
<P>
   The finest old launches will be on display through Sunday in
England at the 150th Henley Royal Regatta, a highlight of the
British summer social calendar. Hundreds of rowing crews from all
over the world meet to compete on a bucolic reach of the River
Thames at Henley-on-Thames, 30 miles outside of London.
</P>
<P>
   There, the spectators are as much a part of the show as the
rowers. The tents are populated with men wearing brightly striped
coats or double-breasted blue blazers, cravats, white flannels and
straw boaters. The women don huge hats and fashionable summer
dresses; pants and shorts are outlawed, and skirts must fall below
the knee. No mobile telephones are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The food is as old-fashioned as the craft. There are cucumber
sandwiches, strawberries and cream, and lashings of Pimms No. 1
Cup. And there are tables, chairs and silver service. General
admission is 10 pounds a day, or about $16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really like a festival,'' said Colin Henwood, co-owner of
Henwood &AMP; Dean, a Henley boatbuilder who also restores old boats.
``People come along for the sights. It's a social and jolly time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a time to purchase a vintage boat.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, for the 14th year, will hold its annual Rivercraft and
Ephemera sale at Henley on July 10, the Saturday after the races.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regatta is a decorative and joyous occasion, and Phillips
has become part of it,'' said Dan Klein, the international
executive director of Phillips. ``Regatta week has enormous charm
and tradition. It's a celebration of rowing with all the style one
would like to see.''
</P>
<P>
   This year 53 boats are for sale, 12 of which will be afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boat collectors are like car enthusiasts,'' Klein said. ``The
boats are something to care for, cherish and love, like vintage
cars. Even the grandest people like to do a bit of varnishing, and
these boats are a 365-day commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction includes launches, boating trophies, marine
paintings and old boat models. Classifications vary, but Lionel
Willis, Phillips' boat specialist, said he considered a boat
``antique'' if it was 100 years old and ``vintage'' if built before
1930.
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic boat doesn't have to be particularly old, but it has
to have style, finish and be made and used in classic fashion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 231 lots at Phillips is a boat with a royal
provenance: It is a 1950s Albatross aluminum-alloy speedboat once
owned by Prince Philip, the duke of Edinburgh, who attended the
Henley Regatta last year. The boat is a 13-foot sports runabout
with a Ford inboard engine and was designed as a light, fast boat
for water skiing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were built when aluminum was a brand-new material, so
they were considered novel and sexy,'' Willis said. According to
Phillips, Brigitte Bardot, Aristotle Onassis and Prince Rainier all
had Albatrosses.
</P>
<P>
   The Albatross in the auction was on the Royal Yacht Britannia
until 1967, when it was transferred to Balmoral in Scotland. It was
sold to its present owner in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes with instructions from the captain of the
Britannia,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Willis added: ``The Britannia was a Navy ship. Everything had to
be done by the book, Navy fashion, including how to come up
alongside the yacht.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albatross is estimated to sell for $4,750 to $7,900.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage racing boats are another favorite collecting category.
</P>
<P>
   The rarest boat in the sale, Klein said, is Batboat II, a
21-foot-long hydroplane lake racing boat built in 1912 that is
named for its British designer, Montague Batting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't build very many of them, and they stopped making
them in 1915, so few survive,'' Willis said. Created for the
British International Trophy Races, Batboat II has a mahogany deck
with an open cockpit fitted with a mahogany bench seat.
</P>
<P>
   The boat finished first in the 1913 trials, and was then sent to
America where, Klein said, ``She was used for rum running on the
Hudson River during Prohibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimate: $9,500 to $14,250.
</P>
<P>
   The most elegant boat type in the sale is the slipper stern
launch, whose stern angles down to the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tapers off at the back like a sucked toffee,'' Willis said.
``It was designed by a man who lived on the Thames and wanted a
boat that had less wash, so he wouldn't swamp the punts and
canoes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These launches are classics,'' Klein said. ``They were
designed for little afternoon excursions, to see and be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is selling the Mayflower, a slipper stern launch made
in 1934 that is 30 feet long and fitted with four white Decoesque
movable lounge chairs. Willis said the owner was selling it because
she now wanted a boat ``with the lid on it,'' meaning a top for
shade. Estimate: $28,500 to $31,600.
</P>
<P>
   Americans like classic boats as much as the English do, though
Americans divide their loyalties into camps: power and sail; modern
and traditional, freshwater and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gilson of Madison, Wis., has been collecting old Gar Wood,
Chris-Craft and Hacker power boats for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love restoring wooden boats,'' he said. ``I like the smell
of the wood varnish and figuring out how to maintain the old
motors.'' He said he attended a classic boat show in March in Mount
Dora, Fla., and planned to go to another one in Lake Tahoe, Calif.,
in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reason to go somewhere to go boating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide speedboat show schedule is printed in Classic
Boating, a bimonthly published in Oconomowoc, Wis. On the East
Coast, Wooden Boat magazine of Brooklin, Maine, lists wooden boat
shows and events all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Boat lovers are a congenial lot. Several members of the East End
Classic Boat Society gathered on Sunday at the main dock of Sag
Harbor, N.Y., for the annual blessing of the fleet. The wooden
boats present included a Friendship sloop from Maine, a Beetle
catboat, a Monterey Clipper fishing boat from California, a Maine
peapod (a double-ended rowing skiff), a 12-foot Bahamian sailing
dinghy and a sailing dory.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Barker of Easton, Pa., who built the dory for sails and
oars, explained, ``you use the ash breeze when the wind goes
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The boaters were having a grand time trading stories and
cocktails. The blarney was nearly as classic as the boats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
