<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHTING A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUILLERMO KLEIN: ``Los Guachos II'' (Sunnyside).
</P>
<P>
   Record stores will file it under jazz, but there's nothing in
popular music right now like ``Diario de Alina Reyes,'' the lead
track from Guillermo Klein's second large-ensemble album. It's
constructed out of a series of rapid, beautiful melodies, and it
sounds as if Klein composed them without worrying about length; he
was going to find a way to fit them together.
</P>
<P>
   It's a three-and-a-half-minute jumble of sound, with Klein's
nicotine-stained voice opening up into hand percussion and muted
brass, doublings and triplings of vocal lines, some synthesizer
arpeggios, then (believe it or not) lyrics written in palindromes;
the tapes run backward for a sequence of the song, and then the
instrumentation opens up to a full band, with brass and woodwinds.
</P>
<P>
   It's rare to find jazz people experimenting with recording tape;
it's also rare to hear any music this brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, a young Argentine composer and pianist, has been playing
with groups of various sizes around New York for four years in
little clubs like Smalls and the C-Note; some good local musicians
are on the record, including the saxophonists Tony Malaby and Chris
Cheek, the guitarist Ben Monder, and the singer Claudia Acuna.
</P>
<P>
   He's literate in the rhythmic layering of music of Brazil and
Cuba, and some of the record sounds like an updated version of
Flora Purim's Brazilian fusion records from the 70s. Though he's
one of the most original big-band composers around, it may be his
gruff singing that ultimately gets him recognition; on tracks like
``Se Me Va la Voz,'' he shows the makings of a possible Paolo
Conte.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
