<HEADLINE>
(ATTN:
</HEADLINE>
 BC- brochtrup-theater-art words&AMP;ADD-NYT   CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: familiar Faces Glisten Above The Footlights 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By xxxxxx   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With photo
By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   angelique closes july 11, not this week &UR; gfbyline &LR;  By PETER MARKS
</P>
<P>
   Yet another name-brand star of the small screen is taking his
bows on a New York stage this summer. He's visiting through August,
or in other words, until he is due back on the set of his long-
running, Emmy-winning police series, Tuesday nights on ABC. In the
interim you can catch him in a little theater off Union Square,
where he is delivering just the sort of sensitive performance that
landed him a juicy part in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking, of course, about Bill Brochtrup.
</P>
<P>
   What's that you say? Name doesn't ring a bell? If there were any
justice, it would. Mr. Brochtrup plays the empath- ic, sad-eyed
clerk John Irvin, who greets the perps and the prosecutors at the
squad room door in ``N.Y.P.D. Blue.'' (He took a bullet during a
courthouse shoot- out in the season's two-part finale and earned a
promotion to the opening-cred- its roster of stars.) If the
television role is not proof enough of this actor's gentle
strength, his knockout work in ``Snake-H bit,'' David Marshall
Grant's deeply sat- isfying Off Broadway comedy-drama about days of
waning love and friendship in Los Angeles, should provide the sup-
porting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Brochtrup recently stepped into the play at the Century
Theater, replac- ing Geoffrey Nauffts in the pivotal role of
Michael, a gay Angeleno mourning the breakup with his lover and
playing host to his closest friends, a warring New York couple, an
actor and his wife. It is, simply put, a beautifully calibrated
per- formance that fits as snugly as cork to wine bottle with those
of the superb Christopher Garten as the actor and the sublime Jodie
Markell as the wife.
</P>
<P>
   The portrayal also taps nicely into an intensifying current in
New York thea- ter: the deployment of actors more fa-
 &UR; &AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP; &LR;  miliar from the pages of TV Guide than
Playbill, in productions across the city and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart, moonlighting from ``Ally McBeal,'' caught a
wave of favorable response to her portray- al of a jilted lover
driven to psychotic revenge in Neil LaBute's ``Bash.'' Scott Wolf,
the ``Party of Five'' heartthrob, is using his down time this
summer to draw a young crowd reared on Fox serials to Warren
Leight's Tony-winning ``Side Man.'' Wayne Knight, without his
television uniforms _ he played Newman the mailman on ``Seinfeld''
and is now Don the policeman on ``Third Rock From the Sun'' _ is a
vision in black as a vital part of the latest threesome in ``Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Attaching a television name to a theater venture is often a
marketing ploy. And while there is plenty of wonderful acting
across the cable channels, a veteran New York play- goer remains a
bit of a snob about the tube. You can't help wondering when you see
a famous television name on a Broadway marquee, ``Can that guy
really act?'' (``The Odd Couple,'' for instance, did wonders for
Tony Randall's pocketbook and visibility, but it was an impediment
to his being taken seriously in sophis- ticated theater circles
when he be- gan reviving the classics for his Na- tional Actors
Theater.)
</P>
<P>
   For whatever the reason television stars are attracted to the
stage _ to flex old muscles, to retool an image, to rekindle the
flame of professional passion _ they must overcome the vast impact
they have already made.  &UR; .................... &LR;  Whether widely
recognizable like Ms. Flockhart or hovering in our peripheral
vision like Mr. Brochtrup, their transitions to the stage require
them to erase even as they create.
</P>
<P>
   How successful is this season's class from the coast in making
us forget how well we know them? Pret- ty darned successful, it
seems.
</P>
<P>
   A few have had a bumpy time. Lisa Gay Hamilton, a stage-trained
ac- tress who now has a major role on ABC's acclaimed legal series
``The Practice,'' was ill served by ``Angeli-H que,'' a muddle of a
play that she left last month. The show closes on July 11 at the
MCC Theater.
</P>
<P>
   And others seem in a bit over their heads. The winsome Mr. Wolf
is not yet playing at the level of the rest of the exemplary ``Side
Man'' actors. But to be fair, they have been at it a lot longer
than he.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part the casting of the familiar faces has proved
felici- tous; in some cases, surprisingly so. Here, in alphabetical
order, are five of the cannier recent placements on- stage of
figures from our evenings in front of the set.
 &UR; gfsubhed &LR;  Bill Brochtrup
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Mr. Brochtrup to play Michael, a decent but
forlorn gay man who faces a series of per- sonal crises in
``Snakebit,'' was in- spired. That is in part because the role is
really not that much of a stretch for the actor, who portrays John,
a tenderhearted gay man fac- ing a personal crisis or two on
``N.Y.P.D. Blue.'' The major differ- ence is one of emphasis.
John's con- cerns are background noise on the television show;
onstage Michael's are front and center.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Brochtrup handles the step up in responsibility with a
leading man's aplomb and a keen ear for the playwright's acidly
funny dialogue. There isn't as much attitude in his performance as
there was in Mr. Nauffts's; the character's edges
 &UR; -------------------- &LR;  have been softened a bit, which al- ters the
balance of the relationships. Michael now seems more of a confi-
dant to the Jenifer of Ms. Markell, the sole holdover from the
original cast. And Mr. Brochtrup's more se- rene demeanor meshes
nicely with the work of Mr. Garten, a revelation as Jonathan, a
would-be star of ac- tion movies who browbeats Michael and reduces
his anxious wife to tears.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions of all involved in ``Snakebit'' reflect such a
high de- gree of accomplishment _ Guiller- mo Diaz, the fourth
member of the ensemble, is another worthy replace- ment _ that an
audience's past asso- ciations with these actors seem to melt away.
And Mr. Brochtrup wins our hearts anew because he wears his with
such refinement and com- passion.
 &UR; gfsubhed &LR;  Tony Danza
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a disaster. With a stage crowded with
unforgettable characters _ among them James Hazeldine's thrilling
Harry Hope, Michael Emerson's tragic Willie Oban, Katie Finneran's
wild-eyed Cora and perhaps most affectingly Paul Giamatti's
heart-rending Jim- my Tomorrow _ an audience mem- ber might be
forgiven for gazing up at the actor in fighting trim behind the bar
and wondering, ``What's the boxer from `Taxi' doing there?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mr. Danza is an authenti- cating presence in the huge
``Ice- man'' cast; when he speaks, Flat-H bush Avenue rolls right
up to your seat. Yes, as others have pointed out, he isn't the
subtlest performer. His barkeep, Rocky Pioggi, has perhaps a tad
too much of the gladhanding politician about him. Yet you want to
believe that Rocky has the oily charm to control the prostitutes he
swears he doesn't pimp for, as well as the thuggish toughness to
back up the threats in lines like ``I'd like an excuse to give you
a good punch in the snoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Danza, so accustomed to en- semble work from his years on
tele- vision, conveys these attributes with ease. You have to
admire this actor's  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  willingness to extend
and challenge himself. After a long run in sitcoms, he has
performed on Broadway in plays by Arthur Miller, credibly re-
placing Anthony LaPaglia in ``A View From the Bridge,'' and now a
play by Eugene O'Neill. In what other ways, one wonders, does Mr.
Danza plan to push the envelope?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gfsubhed &LR;  Polly Draper
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Draper's trajectory is the op- posite of Mr. Danza's. Her
training is stage-based, and it was only after years of theater
work that she was cast as the high-powered, heat-seek- ing Ellen on
``Thirtysomething,'' the signature yuppie drama series of the late
80's and early 90's. Now she is back onstage in New York, replacing
Natasha Richardson in ``Closer,'' Patrick Marber's partner-swapping
precis of sexual mores in the bed- rooms and chat rooms of
contempo- rary London.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the casting of an American, Mr. Marber tinkered
with his play, modifying the Britishisms and even tweaking the
staging of the final scene. The changes, alas, do not alter the
perception that ``Closer'' has lost some of its seductive vile-
ness in the metamorphosing journey from the West End to Broadway.
Still, Ms. Draper settles comfortably into Mr. Marber's world of
sex and faithlessness, a morally decayed re- vision of the dating
universe she in- habited in ``Thirtysomething.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anna, the fickle photographer drawn into the competing beds
of a dermatologist played by Ciaran L Hinds and the obituary writer
por- trayed by Rupert Graves, Ms. Dra- per looks smashing; you
believe that civilized men might start a fistfight over her. But it
is in her fleeting opportunities at comedy that she shows herself
off to best advantage. For all the play's sexual intrigue, what
works best for Ms. Draper is a funny speech about the secret bag-
gage men bring to a relationship.
 &UR; gfsubhed &LR;  Calista Flockhart
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Flockhart, by the magnitude of her stardom, had more to lose
than  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  most television stars in hazarding a
return to the stage. She had a potent weapon, though; she can act.
This was clear to anyone who knew her work before she landed on the
cover of Time. Her Natasha in Scott El- liott's ``Three Sisters''
at the Round- about in 1997 stamped her as a clas- sical performer
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Now that everyone is watching, what's the result? A hit play. In
Mr. LaBute's monologue-driven ``Bash,'' she portrays two women with
oppos- ing perspectives on homicidal vio- lence: one who relishes
it, another who wishes it away. Although the excellent Ron Eldard,
as a bland businessman making a horrific ho- tel-room confession,
is handed a more rewardingly complex story line, it is Ms.
Flockhart's perform- ances that pack them in nightly.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait of disturbance L evolves slowly; the triumph of her
turn as the disintegrating interroga- tion-room subject of ``Medea
Re-H dux,'' the first of the monologues, is in the sense of
misdirection. Ms. Flockhart's dead-eyed recounting of the story of
a life, couched in defen- sive language, casts her as victim. The
portrayal is so alive that you imagine her in motion constantly,
when in fact she is glued to the interview table.
 &UR; gfsubhed &LR;  Wayne Knight
</P>
<P>
   Who knew that Mr. Knight could work in such delicate brush
strokes? On ``Seinfeld,'' his Newman was a sort of Penguin to
Jerry's Batman, a mischievous comic-strip character with a demonic
grin and a compul- sion not to deliver the mail. As Mr. Knight
reveals so touchingly in his carefully modulated performance in
``Art,'' Newman is history.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the audience wouldn't like him back; a chord of happy
familiar- ity was struck during the play when Mr. Knight let slip
an evil laugh, Newman style. (Mr. Wolf triggered a similar buzz
among younger playgo- ers, mostly female, at ``Side Man,'' whenever
he smiled boyishly. L ``Soooooo cute,'' cooed a young wom- an
behind me who seemed to want to take him home.)
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Art'' trio also includes Buck Henry and George Segal
(these days a sitcom star himself, on ``Just Shoot Me''), both of
whom are limber and playfully into the game. But it is Mr. Knight
who makes the most in- triguing impression here. His Yvan _ the one
with the breakneck-paced monologue about the controversial wedding
invitation _ builds almost imperceptibly in power, up to the moment
Mr. Henry's Marc and Mr. Segal's Serge turn their anger at each
other on him.
</P>
<P>
   When Mr. Knight dissolves sud- denly in tears, immobilized by
the feeling that his world is collapsing, it is unthinkable that
there ever was a Newman at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
