<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-01 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT GIVES FIRST LADY LEEWAY TO DISAGREE ON POLITICAL ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton gave First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton the green light Thursday to publicly disagree with White
House policies in her bid to become the next senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The president's remarks came amid mounting political pressure in
New York for Mrs. Clinton to distance herself from provisions of
the Clinton administration's latest Medicare overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my wife decides to run for senator from New York, then some
of the disagreements that we've had in the past over decisions that
I've made as president, she may be constrained to state publicly,''
Clinton said in response to a question during a joint news
conference with visiting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   Political allies need not ``agree on all things,'' the president
said, adding: ``It would be a dreary world indeed if we all agreed
on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., on Wednesday criticized portions
of the latest White House Medicare plan, saying the proposed
revisions would hurt New York.
</P>
<P>
   If the first lady hopes to represent New York in the Senate, she
``has to defend New York interests,'' Schumer insisted, adding:
``There's a way to keep this plan intact and help New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton plans to notify the Federal Election Commission
next Tuesday that she is creating a fund-raising committee to
underwrite her continued exploration of a Senate campaign to
succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady plans a four-day, five-city tour of upstate New
York beginning next Wednesday that targets traditional Republican
strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   The president said his latest Medicare proposal would soften the
impact on teaching hospitals of earlier Medicare cutbacks. The
administration's latest version provides a $7.5 billion emergency
fund to enable Congress to offset hospital budget problems brought
on by changes in Medicare reimbursement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal bows to the concerns of ``not just people in
New York'' but elsewhere that cost cuts adopted by Congress in 1997
``were too severe'' and made it difficult for hospitals to
``maintain quality of care'' for uninsured patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton's latest plan would reduce Medicare
reimbursements to hospitals by $39 billion over 10 years _
including $3.2 billion cut from hospital reimbursements in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage the senators from New York or anyone else
who is concerned about this to bring those concerns (and) bring the
facts to the table, get it out in the open,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He urged lawmakers to ``embrace the idea of Medicare reform,
pass the fund and then allocate it as it should be allocated'' to
alleviate hospitals' budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's campaign spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said on
Wednesday that the first lady supports the president's Medicare
proposal but believes teaching hospitals should be protected from
potential cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton underscored her appreciation for the concerns
raised by New York's teaching hospitals during an address at
Hofstra University in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our teaching hospitals are the crown jewels of America's
health care system,'' Mrs. Clinton said, adding: ``It is only fair
and appropriate for health insurance plans to help pay for the
missions of our nation's teaching hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Jennings, the president's top health care adviser at
the White House, says the latest Medicare plan directly addresses
teaching hospitals' concerns about lost reimbursement for treating
the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The latest White House plan proposes carving out Medicare
reimbursements for the uninsured and paying the money directly to
hospitals providing the care rather than funneling the
reimbursements through the managed health care plans that have the
patients on their rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching facilities and academic health centers question
whether those dollars are passing through,'' Jennings said. ``We
think it's much more efficient to have those payments go directly
back to the provider.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
