<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL-BOOK-REVIEW-N     07-01 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOD'S FUNERAL': THE DEATH OF GOD, A CONTINUING SERIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 1908-1910 poem, ``God's Funeral,'' Thomas Hardy
proclaimed the death of God. ``Tricked by our own early dream and
need of solace,'' he wrote, ``we grew self-deceived'' and ``what we
had imagined we believed.'' Yet with ``Time's stayless stealthy
swing,'' he adds, ``uncompromising rude reality mangled the Monarch
of our fashioning, who quavered, sank; and now has ceased to be.''
</P>
<P>
   As A.N. Wilson observes in his absorbing new book, humankind,
``which had worshiped God or the Gods time out of mind, from the
era of the cave men until the French Revolution, went crazy and
threw off God'' some time in the late 19th century. The Victorian
era ``had created a climate for itself _ philosophical,
politico-sociological, literary, artistic, personal _ in which God
had become unknowable, His voice inaudible against the din of
machines and the atonal banshee of the emerging egomania called The
Modern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cohesive social force which organized religion had once
provided was broken up,'' Wilson writes. ``The nature of society
itself, urban, industrialized, materialistic, was the background
for the godlessness which philosophy and science did not so much
discover as ratify.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``God's Funeral,'' Wilson re-examines the ``Victorian Big
Fight'' between religion and science, faith and intellect, and
tries ``to make sense of it by getting to know the men and women
who were caught up in it.'' The approach, focused on interlinking
biographical sketches, is similar to that used in Wilson's earlier
study of the same period, ``Eminent Victorians'' (inspired,
needless to say, by Lytton Strachey's famous 1918 book of the same
name), and relies heavily on his gift for creating pithy,
insightful and often highly subjective portraits.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting book, drawing on Wilson's wide-ranging reading in
philosophy, literature and ecclesiastic history, is erudite and
expansive. While it may add little to the reader's overall
understanding of the period, its biographical portraits movingly
illustrate the terrible struggle many thoughtful individuals of the
era experienced in trying ``to choose between giving up
intellectual honesty or abandoning that spiritual and religious
dimension to life which, as far as we can discover from the
historians and anthropologists, is so fundamental a part of all
previous human experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson begins his study with the work of the Enlightenment
thinkers, work that contained the seeds of the Victorians' doubts.
He reminds us that Hume's skepticism brought into question the very
notion of Causation (and the image of a Designer behind the
Universe), while Gibbon's ``Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire''
made it difficult to admire many of the church's greatest saints
and popes, exposing them as ``morally absurd.'' Kant, he notes,
``demolished the traditional proofs for the existence of God and
left a moral imperative in the place of a spiritual enthusiasm,''
even as empiricism was underscoring ``the sheer unlikelihood, the
basic, common-sense improbability, of angelic apparitions, a
virginal conception, loaves and fishes which could be multiplied, a
human body which could rise from the tomb.''
</P>
<P>
   This, then, was the philosophical Weltanschauung that the
scientific advancements of the 19th century would help ratify.
Charles Lyell's ``Principles of Geology'' suggested that every
species, including the human, was ephemeral. And Darwin's theory of
natural selection suggested that species mutate, evolve and change,
and do so, in Wilson's words, ``within a system which requires for
its `explanation' no theory of volition by a creator _ no
Watchmaker, coming in from outside to `make' what is.''
</P>
<P>
   Such new scientific knowledge implied a bleak, pitiless universe
that operated according to its own laws _ a view echoed in many
respects by Marx, who argued that human society, culture and law
were all the products of economic forces, and who tried to
substitute the inexorable momentum of history for God's benevolent
protectorship.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1880s, as awareness of these ideas spread, agnosticism
moved from intellectual coteries in London to suburban Britain. Yet
as Wilson's portraits of individual Victorians so eloquently
attest, letting go of God was rarely easy. Carlyle, for one, wanted
to believe ``in a Supreme Lawgiver, in Duty and Morality, in a
personal Guide to life,'' but remained concerned that the Christian
religion had lost its credibility; he was convinced that faith was
intrinsic to the human temperament and worried that if it were not
directed toward one true God, it would be directed toward
disreputable idols.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson offers us sketches of Ivy Compton-Burnett, the writer
whose novels uniformly made the point that religion had had its
day; Algernon Charles Swinburne, the poet whose verse celebrated a
generation's liberation from ``the sexual constraints and
intellectual absurdities (as they saw things) of Christianity'';
and the novelist Samuel Butler, whose two great themes were the
``dismissal of Christianity and hatred of family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Having himself written 17 works of fiction (in addition to
biographies of Jesus, Tolstoy, C.S. Lewis and Milton), the
prodigious Wilson uses his narrative skills to invest his portraits
with a tactile, novelistic energy. He describes Marx as a character
out of Balzac, the fury of his inner demons erupting in a violent
vision of greedy capitalists and suffering workers clashing in a
historical drama. Shaw is dismissed as the ``prophet of the
sweatless armpit,'' while Carlyle is compared to A.A. Milne's
Eeyore, plaintive, dyspeptic and willfully gloomy.
</P>
<P>
   Like his hero Ruskin, Wilson is occasionally given to
intemperate judgments, and this book is seasoned with questionable
assertions. Wilson bizarrely characterizes the family of William
and Henry James as ``honest and openhearted.'' He makes the gross
generalization that in the Victorian era, ``boys did come to hate
their fathers,'' and he summarizes Freud's work as teaching us
``that neurosis can only be eliminated by overt hatred of our
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader can overlook such silly asides because of the overall
intelligence of this book and Wilson's own passion in dissecting
the decline in religious faith. Indeed, one senses that he takes
the subject personally, torn, like so many of the people he
profiles, between a determination not to commit ``intellectual
suicide'' and the belief that without religious emotion _ ``the
sense of the holy, the sense of the numinous, the feeling that
humankind is not alone'' _ the world is a diminished place.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wilson comes to the conclusion that ``the God-idea''
was not wrenched from human consciousness with the ease that so
many late Victorians predicted. He notes that the Christian ethical
ideal would retain immense potency in the 20th century and that
women and men _ as disparate as Martin Luther King Jr., Simone
Weil, Dietrich Bonhoeffer and Pierre Teilhard de Chardin _ would
decide to ``ignore the death of God in the 19th century'' and put
their trust in One who said, `I was dead, and see, I am alive for
evermore.'''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GOD'S FUNERAL'
</P>
<P>
   By A.N. Wilson
</P>
<P>
   402 pages. W.W. Norton &AMP; Co. $27.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
