<HEADLINE>
HEARST ACQUIRES THREE WEEKLY NEWSPAPERS NEAR ALBANY, N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Hearst Corporation has acquired three weekly
newspaper companies near Albany, N.Y. The newspaper companies are
The Advertiser, in Rensselaer County, The Journal Newspapers, in
Saratoga County and The Pennysaver, based in Saratoga County.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies will now comprise the new Capital Region
Weekly Newspaper Group (CRWNG), a division of Hearst Newspapers.
Hearst also publishes the daily Times Union in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition demonstrates The Hearst Corporation's
confidence in the vitality and economic health of New York's
Capital Region,'' said George B. Irish, president of Hearst
Newspapers and vice president of The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Smith has been appointed publisher of CRWNG,
reporting to Irish. Smith brings more than 30 years of newspaper
experience to CRWNG, most recently as director of sales and
marketing at This Week Publications, a Long Island, N.Y.-based
weekly newspaper group serving more than one million homes with 70
editions. Prior to that position, Smith was vice president of sales
and marketing at the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   The CRWNG publications were acquired from three separate,
privately held ownerships.
</P>
<P>
   The Advertiser (weekly distribution of 35,200 in Rensselaer
County) was founded by Albert Hayner more than 40 years ago. Hayner
will continue as adviser and consultant to The Advertiser. Alyson
Hayner Regan, his daughter, will continue her 22-year career as The
Advertiser's editor and office manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal Newspapers (total circulation of 27,050 in central
and southern Saratoga County communities) was formerly owned and
operated by Charles Hogan. The Journal Newspapers include The
Ballston Journal (circulation 2,350), a paid weekly newspaper which
celebrated its 200th anniversary in 1998; The Money Saver
(distribution 17,000), a free weekly newspaper in central Saratoga
County; and the Malta Messenger (circulation 7,700), a free weekly
newspaper in southern Saratoga County.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennysaver (distribution of 53,000 in southern Saratoga and
northeastern Albany County communities), was started in 1950 by
Richard and Jeanne Staffield. In 1973, the company was taken over
by their son, James Staffield. James Staffield will continue to own
and operate Staffield Printing of Clifton Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Newspapers, a unit of The Hearst Corporation, publishes
12 daily newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
