<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Museum Fills Gap in Dutch Paintings &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When J. Patrice Marandel, the curator of European painting and
sculpture at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, attended the
Maastricht art fair in the Netherlands four months ago, he spotted
exactly what he had been looking for to add to the museum's
permanent collection: a first-rate example of an Utrecht School
painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mocking of Christ,'' by the Dutch master Gerrit van Honthorst,
is a haunting image in which the artist used a candle to cast
shadows on the figures he painted, in this case to dramatically
depict the suffering of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   While it is a theme the artist explored several times and there
are at least five known versions of the painting, Marandel believes
this one is among the artist's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to the museum six years ago, I realized that we
really needed a painting of this school,'' he said. ``The emotion
in this picture and the dignified treatment of the subject make it
particularly special. It will be the museum's first Honthorst.''
</P>
<P>
   Painted around 1617, when the artist was in Rome working with
Caravaggio, ``Mocking of Christ'' had been unpublished and unknown
to scholars until Rob Smeets, a Milan dealer, exhibited it at the
art fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was known to Professor J. Richard Judson, who is writing a
new catalog raisonne of the artist's work,'' Marandel said. ``We
know it had been in a private Dutch collection.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of the gaps in its provenance, especially during the
middle years of the 20th century, Marandel said, he spent
considerable time confirming that at no point was it looted during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The painting was acquired for the museum through the Ahmanson
Foundation, based in Los Angeles, which has been the museum's
biggest benefactor in European paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The painting helps to flesh out the Caravaggesque pictures
already in the Los Angeles Museum County of Art's collection,
especially Georges de La Tour's ``Magdalen With the Smoking Flame''
(circa 1640) and Valentin de Boulogne's ``Musical Party'' (1626).
</P>
<P>
   The Honthorst will go on view in the fall, Marandel said, after
some minor conservation and restoration work.
</P>
<P>
   Biennale as `Gold Mine'
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several years the Venice Biennale is to go from a
government-run entity to a private profit-making organization, one
that will hold year-round arts events in all disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for joint ventures with private organizations
and corporations to help fund us,'' said Giovanna Legnani, the
general director of the Biennale, who is working with its
president, Paolo Baratta, to make the change happen. ``If we
succeed, we hope this will be an economic model that will be copied
at other Biennales around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government passed a law in February allowing the
Venice Biennale, which costs about $8 million a year to produce, to
become a private cultural organization. While the art world thinks
of it as an art fair that happens every two years, the organizers
of the Biennale actually oversee a host of other cultural
activities in Venice, including a film festival every September and
biennales in such fields as music, theater, dance and architecture,
which are held sporadically during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the name biennale, some occur every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Biennale is a gold mine that's never been exploited,'' Ms.
Legnani said. ``I have a mandate to make it profitable and
self-sufficient in four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been 100 percent financed by the Italian
government, Ms. Legnani said that in three years government funds
will account for only 40 percent of the budget and that over time
it will become totally self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   To lure corporations like Philip Morris to become sponsors, she
plans to emphasize the economic impact these events have on Venice,
which she believes insures high visibility for sponsors. Each year
about $3 million is made directly from the event's entrance fees
and catalog sales.
</P>
<P>
   About $10 million is generated from tourism, spent at hotels,
restaurants and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the Biennale's plans is a new theater on San Giorgio
Island, across the canal from San Marco, which would hold
year-round dance and performing arts programs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, plans also include keeping the gardens
at the tip of Venice _ where the 26 national pavilions are
clustered _ open all the time, beginning with a schedule of
programs in the Italian pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope other pavilions will follow,'' Ms. Legnani said.
</P>
<P>
   Not LA Style
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to art world speculation, Pace Wildenstein is not
closing its Beverly Hills gallery. But it is discontinuing its
exhibition program there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gallery is still open and there is art for people to
buy,'' said Arne Glimcher, the chairman of Pace Wildenstein.
</P>
<P>
   It will continue to stock work by the artists it represents,
including Agnes Martin, Chuck Close, Kiki Smith and Robert
Rauschenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pace Wildenstein opened its Los Angeles branch on Wilshire
Boulevard in 1995, the gallery has held more than 50 exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to come to the openings, but the Los Angeles life
style does not include gallery going, it's simply not part of the
culture.'' Glimcher said. ``We've done very well here, but not from
the shows.''
</P>
<P>
   The space, which was designed by the New York architect Charles
Gwathmey, never attracted the steady traffic that Pace
Wildenstein's two New York galleries _ on 57th Street and in SoHo _
have, even though Glimcher is particularly well connected in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A part-time producer and director for movies that include
``Gorillas in the Mist'' and ``Mambo Kings,'' he knows the many
modern and contemporary art collectors who make their money in the
movie business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still an art-buying life in Los Angeles,'' Glimcher
said. ``Just not a gallery-going one. People in Los Angeles prefer
to go to the gym.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
