<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURLING UP WITH A GOOD E-BOOK
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday July 8.)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been reading about electronic books, not the ones you order
by computer but the kind that you read on computer, and it's
starting to make me nervous. I feel like I should throw myself in
front of my bookshelf, clutch my book bag to my chest and shout,
``get back.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been talk for some time about online versions of books,
whole novels we can read off our computers and eventually little
hand-held computer books. But they always seemed so easy to
dismiss. Who's going to want to haul a computer to bed, to the
beach or balance one in a hammock?
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, as long as they are books, whether they're
on paper, tape or computer screen, maybe we shouldn't get too picky
about what form they take. At least people are reading.
</P>
<P>
   But I worry about my hard and softback friends and become
defensive when someone talks up the coming ease of e-books.
</P>
<P>
   Books on paper have personality. The ones on computer are
virtual books, digital versions of the real thing, one step removed
from an actual living, breathing book.
</P>
<P>
   I'm preparing my protest to convince myself. I know how fickle
we consumers are in terms of machines. We vow we will never give up
chatting with our favorite teller at the bank and look at us now,
disgustingly ATM-dependent.
</P>
<P>
   It happens. You read about some new cool, time saving, efficient
techno marvel and think ``nice, but who needs a car phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then you start to wonder if what you're really displaying is
curmudgeonly disdain for the modern world. Did they not also once
scorn the electric light bulb?
</P>
<P>
   But you like the old way. Why spend all that money on a CD
player when you have a perfectly fine tape deck?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, did they really think they could convince
people to give up their typewriters for video display terminals?
</P>
<P>
   So, there it is. Progress happens and before you know it you've
bought into it and you're telling the relatives they'd hear from
you a lot more if they'd get e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But e-M.F.K. Fisher?
</P>
<P>
   At this point I can't grasp the advantage of reading electronic
books over ones in paper except you don't have to turn the page. I
like turning pages. And then turning back. I like underlining and
writing comments in margins, which is blasphemous to some but it
makes the book even more my own. How do you make a computer book
your own?
</P>
<P>
   You can move words from a piece of paper to a screen but there's
something else that isn't transferable.
</P>
<P>
   How does a computer book smell? It doesn't smell clean and sharp
like a new book or have the dusty musk of an old one. But I worry
that there will be people someday who may not know to miss the
smell of books.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they also won't know to miss free floating in a book
store, waiting for something to jump out and say read me. Or how it
is to find a used book, creased and worn from another who loved it
and passed it on.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of computer books what will people put on their walls
and stack next to their bed? What will they lend to a friend?
</P>
<P>
   They're working hard to streamline electronic books so that you
can read them in the subway, even in the tub. Right now the
complaint is that the online choice of books is limited and that
the devices are heavy. In terms of real books, they weigh about the
same as a fat hardcover. But I bet they aren't as welcome in bed.
Hey, what happens if you fall asleep with the thing turned on?
</P>
<P>
   Improvements are being made, they say.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like the sound of it.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
