<HEADER>
A6350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES02-COX     07-01 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE PRESENTS EVERGLADES PLAN
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Let's get it done,'' Vice President Al Gore urged
Congress on Thursday as formally presented the administration's
$7.8 billion, 20-year plan for restoring the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by a bipartisan group of lawmakers, Gore declared the
10-volume, 4,000-plus-page plan ``reasonable and flexible'' and
predicted future generations would look at the result ``in awe and
wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Also taking part in the presentation, held in a meeting room a
few steps off the Senate floor, were a handful of committee
chairmen whose panels could determine the fate of the ambitious
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal aims at reversing decades of water management
efforts by diverting to the Everglades 80 percent of the water that
now flows to the ocean, while providing the rest to populous areas
along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of study, argument and negotiation, the
restoration plan presented Thursday _ called a ``restudy'' of the
Central and Southern Florida Project that built hundreds of miles
of canals and levees from the late 1940s to the early 1970s _ is
merely the latest step in the restoration process.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will probably hold hearings on the plan this year
before incorporating it into next year's Water Resources
Development Act. If authorized then, money for the initial projects
would not be provided before the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., said getting congressional support will
be difficult because the plan changes the usual relationship
between Congress and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Usually corps projects are authorized after detailed plans are
presented to Congress _ a process Graham compared to building a
house after seeing the architectural blueprints. In this case, the
Everglades plan is more like a road map, with the corps laying out
the destination and asking Congress to give it latitude to reach
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably going to be the biggest thing we have to
convince our colleagues, is to give the corps greater latitude,''
Graham said. ``What we're going to do is hold the corps answerable
to performance rather than a pre-approved process.''
</P>
<P>
   A key player in determining whether the Everglades plan will be
authorized in next year's water bill is Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I.,
chairman of the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee, who
was one of the few non-Floridians participating in Thursday's
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to act is now,'' Chafee said. ``We will do everything
in our committee to move this along swiftly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chafee noted that the plan's price tag might cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a program that is going to cost some money. Even for
someone in Washington, $7.8 billion is a fair sum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A more immediate hurdle looms this summer. Congressional
appropriators have earmarked far less for Everglades-related
spending for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 than the $151 million
the Clinton administration has requested. A House subcommittee this
week put the amount at $114 million; the Senate Appropriations
Committee has penciled in $90.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tipton, director of U.S. Ecoregion Conservation for the
World Wildlife Fund, noted that in previous years the
appropriations bills have initially set low levels for Everglades
spending but that the final amounts have been increased in
conference committee action. Tipton said he hoped for a repeat of
that pattern this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Clinton administration's point-man on Everglades
restoration, acknowledged the difficult path the restoration
project faces. The task now, he said, is to ``build a coalition
that brings everybody on board.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
