<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZIER-RACING-COLUMN-NY     07-01 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIER-RACING-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UPS AND DOWNS OF RESTRICTOR-PLATE RACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Mark Martin has had his troubles at
Daytona and Talladega, doesn't even really like to race there,
really.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely frustrating to know you, as a driver, can't
help out the car,'' Martin said as preparations began for Saturday
night's Pepsi 400 at the Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure, the driver plays a part in it,'' Martin went on.
``But I don't care what anybody says, certain drivers have good
restrictor-plate cars every single time.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't always been the case with Martin and the other four
teams in owner Jack Roush's stable of cars.
</P>
<P>
   If the Roush teams have a weakness, it has been their
performance in restrictor plate races.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's through no fault of their own. Other times, they
simply haven't had enough power to run up front.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Martin and the other strong Roush entry, driven by
Jeff Burton, were both caught up in the massive wreck started by
Dale Jarrett in February's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Burton ended up 35th, Martin 31st as a result of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Both had better luck at Talladega Superspeedway in Talladega,
Ala., Martin finishing third and Burton 11th although Burton had an
engine problem that affected the car when he had to slow it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won Talladega twice. I've won, and I've run in the middle of
the pack and I've gotten lapped,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've run all over the place and I know that it has a ton to do
with your car,'' Martin declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help the car, as a driver, nearly as much as you can
anywhere else where you have to let off the gas to get through the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, driver skill and experience plays about five times as
much a part of it as when you can hold it wide open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (racing at Daytona and Talladega) like driving down the
interstate,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has had a lot of ups and downs at the two
restrictor-plate tracks, which use metal inserts between the
carburetor and the intake manifold to limit the mixture of gas and
air reaching the engine, thereby cutting horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers complain that slows acceleration, making it difficult to
avoid wrecks and making crashes more serious because the cars tend
to bunch up in packs.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the drivers don't care for the plates, something
had to be done to slow the cars when they began running more than
200 mph at both Daytona and Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, the concern was keeping them from flying into the
stands if they wrecked.
</P>
<P>
   But the plates can cause problems for the drivers, and Martin is
one of those who has experienced the highs and lows of
restrictor-plate racing.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in bad wrecks, like the one at this year's Daytona
500, and he also won the fastest stock car race ever run, averaging
188.354 mph in the 1997 Winston 500 at Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``A restrictor-plate race is so unique, the win is such a unique
win because it's 100 percent credit to my team,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I feel proud for them, because I don't feel like I've got
anything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am what I am and I can't help 'em more than I can, and if
they can't give me a fantastic race car, I can't even contend to
win,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   (Patrick Zier is a sportswriter for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
