<HEADER>
A6361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAINED-GLASS-CEILING     07-01 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAINED-GLASS-CEILING-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE CLERGY HIT THE STAINED-GLASS CEILING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos of of Krieder, Scruggs and Storms are being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BOB ARNDORFER   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ The family, visitors one Sunday to
Gainesville's Emmanuel Mennonite Church, told the pastor after
worship that they felt welcome and had appreciated the service. But
they never returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `We have just one problem, and that is that you're
a woman,' '' said Heidi Kreider, 37, Emmanuel Mennonite's pastor
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   That experience isn't uncommon among female clergy, a new
University of Florida study indicates. Other clergywomen tell
similar stories of on-the-job bias.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist church near Tampa in which Valerie Storms
grew up, and where she was ordained in 1985, declined her offer to
preach while the regular pastor recovered from a heart attack.
Later, while between pastors, the same church also passed on her
offer to lead the flock until a replacement was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even got a reply,'' said Storms, 44, a chaplain at
Shands Hospital at the University of Florida since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Storms and other female clergy acknowledge that such resistance
to their ministries has eased over the years. Still, the findings
of a UF study of females in the ministry suggests the sanctuary
remains a bastion of sexism, or at least a place where
opportunities aren't always equal for women and men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clergywomen face the same conflicts as (other) professional
women, those of balancing work and family, social isolation and
having to win acceptance from peers and superiors,'' said Jesse
Schultz, a graduate student in sociology who did the study for her
thesis. ``But they also must interpret Scriptures that are biased
against women and struggle with a traditional male model in their
denominations.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on a 1995 survey of 190 ordained United
Methodist clergywomen. Schultz wrote the study with UF sociology
professor Constance Shehan and Marsha Wiggins Frame, former
associate pastor at Trinity United Methodist Church now at the
Denver campus of the University of Colorado, where she's a
professor in counseling psychology and counselor education.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz said the findings likely are similar for women clergy in
other denominations. The Rev. Melana Scruggs, ordained 12 years ago
in the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience has been that to lay people, once they know you,
there's not much difference whether you're a female or male
minister,'' said Scruggs, 38, pastor of Faith Presbyterian Church
in Melrose. ``Some of my colleagues in the ministry, however, are
still a bit slower to include women as colleagues.''
</P>
<P>
   She said women today make up about half the graduates from her
denomination's seminaries. Yet women graduates are more likely to
get a chaplaincy or interim pastorate, she said, while men more
often go to a church either as a fellow pastor or an associate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If men go to a chaplaincy, it's usually their choice,''
Scruggs said. ``That's not to say anything against chaplaincy ...
I'm just saying that for women it's difficult to get the first call
to a church. In our presbytery, I have until three months ago been
the only solo woman pastor in 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Clergywomen's limited opportunities has been called the
stained-glass ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Anne Robertson, however, is moving up.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson has left Trinity United Methodist Church, where she
has been associate pastor since 1997, and is headed to Dover, N.H.,
to pastor her own church. Before joining Trinity as minister of
nurture and discipleship, her first appointment after graduating
with honors from seminary in 1994 was as pastor of Cross City's
First United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Robertson spoke to the Gainesville Rotary
Club about the challenges of being a woman minister. She talked
about the difficulty of parking in a Gainesville hospital lot
reserved for clergy, and the frustration of having to justify her
right to park to attendants who thought she was a minister's wife
even though her name was on the pass and she had a clergy tag on
her car.
</P>
<P>
   Her second Sunday in Cross City, she said, a bra ``the size of
the Titanic'' was draped across the front steps of the church. A
male church leader earlier had told her, ``I don't believe you
belong here. I don't believe women should be preaching, and there's
a lot of us who believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice in her ministry, once in Cross City and once in
Gainesville, she said, she was told, ``If you preach in the nude, I
will (attend).''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said her Cross City congregation doubled during her
three-year ministry, and she was warmly accepted at Trinity. But
the successes she's had, she said, ``have come at a greater cost
because of my gender.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have to do more than convince a congregation they have
the gifts and graces to do the job,'' she said. ``They have to
convince a congregation they have a right to even try.''
</P>
<P>
   As a chaplain, Storms said, she has noticed that gender doesn't
matter so much to the sick. Although in her office she sometimes
has been mistaken for a secretary by a patient or family member,
she said, in a more clinical setting her ministry is what matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are in the hospital, they're so vulnerable and
sometimes scared,'' Storms said. ``I think in this setting it's
different because people are in a place they're not used to, and
they will talk to anyone who will offer a comforting word.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that clergywomen sometimes have to fight not
only people's attitudes, but Scripture itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the Scriptures are used as a firm argument that women
have no place as church leaders, clergywomen must take extra steps
to be taken seriously and earn trust,'' Schultz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you preach on passages that seem to exclude you?''
Kreider said. ``While that's a challenge I think women need to
confront, I choose not to preach on those passages. It seems like
it would be saying I have an ax to grind. But if people come to me,
I am willing to dialogue with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the study, clergywomen rated balancing work and family as
their biggest challenge. One minister surveyed said the thing she
wanted most to change was the expectation that the pastor is on
call 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Scruggs, a mother of two young children, said that while the
balancing act can be difficult, she hasn't found the same
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the congregation honors the fact that I'm a mother,
more than maybe it would for a male minister who is a father,'' she
said. ``I rarely get interrupted at home. I don't think that's as
true for men.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
