<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CUTS02-COX     07-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUTS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS VOW TAX RELIEF, BUT ARE UNSURE HOW MUCH
 &HT;    520&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gleeful over forecasts of a deluge of budget
surpluses, House Republican leaders celebrated Thursday with
promises of tax breaks for virtually every taxpaying household.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the good economic news, the leaders have yet to
forge a consensus among their own Republican members, and may have
to settle for more modest reductions.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty was apparent as House Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., described the reductions in only general terms at a rally
complete with red, white and blue balloons and catchy tunes from a
local fife and drum corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we commit ourselves to find a way to secure our retirement
programs, we all hope to commit ourselves to bring fairness to the
American tax code,'' he said without mentioning a precise amount.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican leadership set a goal of returning to
taxpayers all surplus revenues that are not part of the Social
Security trust fund. The Congressional Budget Office on Thursday,
coming close to rosy predictions made earlier this week by the
White House budget office, forecast the non-Social Security surplus
at $996 billion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   However, such upbeat news has yet to persuade moderate
Republicans to accept more than the $778 billion in tax cuts
already in the congressional budget, said Hastert spokesman John
Feerey. He said that the tax proposal would not be laid out until
after the leaders have struck a compromise bringing all of the GOP
members on board.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the tax-writing
Ways and Means Committee and a passionate tax-cutter, promised to
unveil major tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason for the surplus is that taxpayers are paying
too much, and they deserve a refund,'' Archer said. Otherwise, he
said, ``the politicians will most certainly spend it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the biggest reduction would be an unspecified
across-the-board reduction. ``I believe that it's wrong to deny
relief to everyone who has made this surplus possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also listed as targeted cuts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ending the so-called ``marriage penalty'' under which an
estimated 42 million people pay higher taxes than they would as
single people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax breaks for localities that put aside money for building
new schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax breaks to make health insurance more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ending the earnings cap for people who receive Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Greatly'' reducing taxes on capital gains (for transactions
as of Thursday).
</P>
<P>
   _ Cutting inheritance taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Republican tax-cutters face united opposition among Democrats in
the House. Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., promptly dismissed
the GOP proposals as ``totally irresponsible'' and charged that the
plan would make it ``impossible to deal with Social Security and
Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, ``How amazing that the same
House Republicans who claim we cannot afford prescriptions for
seniors and cannot afford to hold the managed health care insurers
accountable can now promise a trillion-dollar tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   The House tax cuts also face opposition in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But the new economic forecasts increased the prospects for a
bipartisan effort led by Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   With co-sponsorship of Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., the plan
would put many middle-income families who are now in the 28 percent
bracket into the 15 percent level for paying income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell is ``very supportive'' of the House efforts for more
substantial tax relief, according to his spokeswoman Laura Cox.
``But it is not particularly realistic,'' she said. ``That's the
reason we're pushing this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coverdell plan has received broad backing from the business
community, from the Senate leadership and from some Democrats, and
a companion bill has won bipartisan backing in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see a bill that moves,'' the aide said. ``The only
way we'll see any tax relief is if it gets passed and signed into
law. A little bit is better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
