<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6367 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIRARD-VIOLIN02-COX     07-01 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRARD-VIOLIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girard's latest, `The Red Violin,' strings together cultures and
eras
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Francois Girard didn't mean for his new film to have
such a high body count. The instrument made him do it.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for ``32 Short Films About Glenn Gould,'' an
elliptical study of the Canadian pianist, Girard returns to a
musical theme with ``The Red Violin,'' a melancholy, intimate epic
spanning three centuries as it follows the fate of a masterpiece of
carved wood and catgut.
</P>
<P>
   As Girard and co-screenwriter Don McKellar began to invent the
trajectory of the violin, they realized that its fictional history
was requiring human fatalities. ``There is a cumulative effect with
all those deaths, and in a way it is something we fought,'' he said
during a recent visit to Atlanta. ``This violin is so precious and
powerful and beautiful, nobody would give it away or sell it. So
the only way for it to move to the next character is to actually
kill the previous owner.'' He laughs. ``That's how we turned into
serial killers.''
</P>
<P>
   A Montreal Wunderkind who earned his rep as a savvy director of
art and music videos, Girard, 36, shot the concert film ``Peter
Gabriel's Secret World'' and directed an episode of ``Yo-Yo Ma:
Inspired by Bach.''
</P>
<P>
   Music has always been big in his life. He grew up playing the
piano but was never trained. ``I'm a self-taught piano bum,'' he
says. ``But in my work, since the very beginning, music has always
had a very important part. It's a very important language that can
carry a number of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of languages, ``The Red Violin's'' multiple locations _
the English and Italian countryside, Shanghai, Vienna and finally
Montreal _ resulted in a UN-like set of multiple languages. Girard
and McKellar had to find writers to translate their script into
Italian, Chinese, German and French, taking into account linguistic
conventions of time and place. The movie took 65 days to shoot,
stretched over five months.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the actors who play the violin in the film really could
play, including German child prodigy Christoph Koncz. For the
Chinese segment, actress Sylvia Chang took lessons until she could
knock off a tune on the instrument. ``I didn't care, because (the
character) was not a virtuoso, but the daughter of a virtuoso.''
</P>
<P>
   Actor Jason Flemyng, playing a lusty British composer called
Frederick Pope, had probably the hardest challenge. ``For Pope, I
had to go for the best actor and fix the musical problems after,''
Girard says. ``We used all sorts of (cinematic) tricks to sell him
as a virtuoso.'' Violinist Joshua Bell, who plays the solos on the
film's soundtrack, also gave Flemyng lessons in how to ``dance''
with the music.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were Flemyng's scenes that required him to pretend to
play the violin while simultaneously making love. ``The sex part he
didn't need to learn,'' Girard cracks. ``He had been there before.
But the two together, that was a bit of a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Glenn Gould,'' ``The Red Violin'' plays as a sort of
enigma, a layered exploration of a mystery that can't quite be
explained. ``The last thing I wanted to do was to come to some sort
of explanation,'' Girard says. ``I was more interested in the
opposite. I wanted to nourish the enigma.''
</P>
<P>
   So what, in the end, does the wayward violin represent? ``My
take on it is that it is a lost soul looking for understanding and
peace,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
