NYT-07-01-99 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6368 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-01 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. GEORGE W. MONEYBAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every other presidential candidate, including Vice
President Al Gore, would love to be in Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
generously-buffered boots.
</P>
<P>
   In four months, Bush raised an astounding $36.25 million in
campaign funds. Merely calling this amazing feat a record doesn't
do it justice.
</P>
<P>
   This is twice as much money as Gore has collected, nearly twice
as much as President Clinton raised for his re-election three years
ago during a similar period, and considerably more than the 11
other Republican candidates combined.
</P>
<P>
   No prior presidential candidate has ever raised this much money
this fast. No one has come even close.
</P>
<P>
   Money attracts other money. On the whole, it is better to have
money than not to have it. And Bush's fund-raising has only begun.
Heaven knows how much he will have in hand by the time the
Republican convention rolls around next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gobs of dough, which unsuccessful 1996 GOP presidential hopeful
Sen. Phil Gramm once called ``the mother's milk of politics,''
matters a lot in a campaign. (Gramm raised $20 million, remarkable
for a Texas senator of no particular achievement. It got him taken
seriously at first but didn't do him much good in the long run. The
milk went sour when the voters got a good look at him.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush, blessed with an attractive personality, is no Gramm.
Voters haven't yet had a good look at the candidate, but so far
they like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is awash in so much cash that he is likely to reject
the federal matching subsidies and accompanying spending limits
that have governed previous presidential campaigns. This will
enable him to conduct an expensive polling operation, saturate the
airwaves with commercials, rig straw polls, pay for expensive
strategists and fly first-class all the way.
</P>
<P>
   This independent route is virtually uncharted territory,
although megabucks media magnate Steve Forbes is underwriting much
of the cost of his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The few who have ignored the familiar federal campaign finance
system have not done well. Voters want their candidates to follow
bipartisan rules that standardize the political skirmishing and
offer the atmosphere of campaign fairness.
</P>
<P>
   There is bound to be some backlash against a guy on top who has
so many marbles he can end the game for everyone by refusing to
play. We do like underdogs in this country, unless they are the
hapless Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush's riches may not turn out to be the automatic
advantage they now appear to be. In politics, as in other areas of
life, there can be too much of a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush already is in danger of looking as though he is trying to
buy the election. If GOP rivals like the formidable Sen. John
McCain of Arizona can make money the central issue, Bush is in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Voters still don't have a very clear idea of who Bush is or
where he stands. Campaign funds that may now demonstrate widespread
support within the Republican establishment could later suggest
subservience to special interests impervious to the public good.
</P>
<P>
   Bush could quickly slip from being a vague ``compassionate
conservative'' into the role of shill for positions that happen to
please big contributors like the tobacco, gun and insurance
industries.
</P>
<P>
   An internal Bush campaign memo outlines the organizing plans of
zealous, well-heeled Washington lobbyists to tilt the Aug. 14 Iowa
straw poll toward Bush. Will Iowans be offended? We'll see. Busing
in workers and passing out goodies to stack straw polls is an old
political trick, known to work in the past for those with money to
throw around. It even worked briefly for Gramm in the last
election.
</P>
<P>
   But such highhandedness may be losing its charm. Voters like a
contest, not a coronation. This is not a monarchy, no matter how
distinguished the family dynasty from which Bush sprang.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush loses that straw poll, all his money will not compensate
for the loss of a sense of presidential inevitability that has been
the motor driving his momentum. He has been hauling in the bucks
because people want to be on the train before it leaves the
station. If they begin to suspect the locomotive lacks traction,
they will look for another train.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other GOP engines idling nearby, needing only the
oil of more campaign funds themselves. Chief among them is McCain,
whose campaign not only oozes leadership vibes but is centered on
his widely-cheered but unsuccessful legislative crusade for
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   McCain doesn't accuse Bush of doing anything wrong in raising
all that money. McCain, running a distant second in the GOP
moneybags sweepstakes at just over $4 million, would like to raise
more himself.
</P>
<P>
   McCain specifically targets the unlimited donations known as
``soft money'' that have distorted the election process by allowing
candidates to duck responsibility for issue-advocacy advertisements
touting their positions. So far, most of Bush's money appears to be
of the old-fashioned direct-contribution variety.
</P>
<P>
   But when McCain speaks, it is worth listening. And if he keeps
yapping about corrupt influence-peddling that ``sells the country
to the highest bidder,'' he is going to put the evils of big money
front and center in this campaign. And Bush, the candidate with big
money, is going to be on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   (Write to Marianne Means at means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
