<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6370 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-SOUTHPARK02-CO     07-01 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-SOUTHPARK02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foul ... and funny, crude and clever, nasty as it wants to be,
wickedly on target
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to the predictably unpredictable Trey Parker and Matt
Stone to deliver the first multiplex, pop-culture, blockbuster art
film.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut''
offers what you expect: crude animation, cruder humor. It's
probably the most offensive (and funniest) bit of celluloid to ever
make moviegoers shell out $7. But in its timely, sly,
self-referential way, the movie is more than that. It's a witty
cultural artifact that captures the here and now of American media
obsessions, circa June 30, A.D. 1999. It should be put in a time
capsule.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Stan, one of the interchangeable lumps of
foulmouthed animated childhood who wobble onscreen, ``This is about
more than fart jokes.'' (But without those jokes, this movie would
run only about 22 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park'' is a postmodern artifact, a movie about itself.
It will inevitably provoke the very kind of firestorm that its plot
revolves around. Simply put: Cartman, Stan, Kyle and Kenny sneak
their way into an obscenity-driven Canadian flick starring comics
Terrence and Philip. (The movie-within-a-movie's centerpiece is a
filthy, very catchy song, whose lyrics include virtually only one
printable word: ``uncle.'')
</P>
<P>
   Inspired, the kids go back to school and share their newfound
language skills with their classmates. This allows the filmmakers
to expand the potty-mouth vocabulary of their schoolkids into
smutty riffs of mind-blowing inventiveness and shock value. ``That
movie has warped my fragile little mind,'' Cartman says. It's a
tongue-in-cheek moment you know reflects Parker and Stone's own
disdain for the fad of blaming Hollywood for all social ills.
</P>
<P>
   The ``South Park'' movie doesn't work hard to upgrade its
proudly primitive animation on the big screen, though a couple of
computer-generated effects pop up. The movie is bigger mainly in
its escalation of gross-out and sexual humor. (It could double as a
psychological study on Parker and Stone's equal mix of fascination
and repulsion with homosexuality and anal sex.)
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park'' serves up a heaven full of big-breasted, naked
angels, lets Big Gay Al go full-frontal nude and takes us to a hell
populated with the likes of Adolf Hitler and George Burns. It's in
hell that the ever-slaughtered Kenny offers relationship advice to
a sensitive Satan and his sexually aggressive boyfriend, Saddam
Hussein. Satan's plans to conquer the earth result in a musical
number that splits into a quartet, genially mocking the first-act
finales of ``Les Miz'' and ``West Side Story.'' (The movie's many
sardonic song-and-dance numbers represent the final shovel of soil
dumped on the corpse of Hollywood's bright-eyed musical past.)
</P>
<P>
   As gleefully nasty as it is clever, ``South Park'' takes
potshots at Brooke Shields and Winona Ryder and those acting clans
the Baldwins and the Arquettes. It has a couple of dull stretches
in the last half-hour, and the ugly animation is wearing after a
point. But most of the movie is so irreverently wicked, it makes
you shudder to imagine the two minutes of footage that had to be
snipped to escape an NC-17 rating.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, kids are going to be scheming nonstop to see it.
</P>
<P>
   While it's doubtful that outraged American parents will launch
an actual war, as happens in the movie, ``South Park'' will likely
be the latest battlefield in the current war of words concerning
school violence and freedom of speech. In the past month we've seen
Louisiana legislation requiring public school students to address
adults as ``sir'' and ``ma'am'' and, more crucially, a move to
crack down on underage teens trying to sneak into R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park'' looks to be the ground-zero test case on whether
even the most aggressive box office workers and ushers can keep
kids away from stinky, irresistible candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of Trey Parker, Matt Stone, Mary Kay
Bergman. Rated R for profanity, gross-out humor and animated
nudity. At metro theaters. 1 hour, 21 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Foul and funny in equal parts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
