<HEADER>
A6372 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-WILDWEST02-COX     07-01 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-WILDWEST02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As a movie, `West' was a great TV show
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't second-guess Hollywood's recycling habits. Hey, a
``Brady Bunch'' movie? It seemed like a lousy idea, but the result
was smart and funny. An updated computer-generated version of
``Godzilla''? It sounded swell, but it stunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West'' retooled for the multiplex didn't seem like
either a great or a godawful idea. It was just a head-scratcher.
Did anybody really want to see the adventures of trigger-happy
James West and his inventor partner Artemus Gordon on the big
screen? Even with those roles played by Will Smith and Kevin Kline,
directed by Barry Sonnenfeld (``Men in Black''), and lavished with
a rumored $180 million budget, the resulting movie is a mediocre
mess.
</P>
<P>
   The flick opens with Smith romancing a young lovely in a water
tower, circa 1869. Establishing the movie's expensive slapstick
style, that tank gets knocked over, spilling Smith into the path of
some redneck white boys who start to address him using the ``n''
word before he clocks them quiet.
</P>
<P>
   That an African-American is playing the role created on TV by
white actor Robert Conrad becomes a forced, unfunny joke, steering
Smith into face-offs with folks who sling words like ``slave,''
``boy'' and worse at him. The plot hinges on an unrepentant
Southern aristocrat named Arliss Loveless (Kenneth Branagh), who
lost his legs, and other body parts, in the Civil War, and now
intends to dominate the United States with the aid of a giant
mechanical spider. (His delivery of veiled racist epithets at Smith
has to rank as the low point of Branagh's screen career.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's possible to harness racism as the engine of a
blockbuster action-adventure-comedy. But ``West'' can't pull it
off. By the time it's trying to wring humor out of a scene pitting
Smith against a lynch mob, you know the movie's four screenwriters
don't have a clue what they're doing. It's an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Queasy racial politics aren't the only problem. Absolutely
nothing clicks. Kline and Smith spark zero sparks of buddy
chemistry, and Salma Hayek is wasted as a spunky beauty searching
for her scientist dad. The jokes land with almost audible thuds.
The blue-screen work and the computer generated effects are obvious
and underwhelming. Oh, and the fight scenes are dull.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Avengers'' last summer (another big-budget Warner
Bros. project), the movie is a bizarre mix of overproduced camp,
sloppy pacing and tepid scripting. ``Wild Wild West'' is anything
but wild. It's a washout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh. Rated PG-13
for action violence, sex references and innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 47 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Weak weak work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
