<HEADER>
A6373 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAM-REVIEW02-COX     07-01 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAM-REVIEW02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Too many plot lines spoil Lee's overheated `Summer'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the ``Star Wars'' movies, Spike Lee's ``Summer of Sam'' is
set a long time ago in a galaxy far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically: New York City during the summer of 1977.
</P>
<P>
   That was the summer when a psycho named David Berkowitz finished
his killing spree. Berkowitz, who called himself the ``Son of Sam''
in notes that found their way to the press (in particular columnist
Jimmy Breslin, who appears here as a kind of soothsayer-narrator),
wasn't a very sophisticated killer. His modus operandi was
outlandishly simple _ mostly, he walked up to people in their cars
and blew their brains out _ but it was also very effective. And it
set off a frenzy of fear among the Big Apple's residents,
especially those living in the Bronx, Berkowitz's preferred
stalking ground.
</P>
<P>
   In this ``Sam,'' Berkowitz himself (Michael Badalucco) is a
veritable minor character. He's mostly shown rolling around his
cramped, trash-filled apartment screaming at the neighbor's dog to
quit barking.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Lee focuses on the guys (and a few gals) in a
predominantly Italian-American neighborhood in the Bronx for whom
it would already be a long, hot summer without the added stress of
a serial killer in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny (John Leguizamo), a womanizing hairdresser who's
constantly cheating on his sweet wife, Dionna (Mira SorvinoCQ),
happens to see two of Berkowitz's victims up close and becomes
convinced he could be next. Meanwhile, Vinny's best friend, Ritchie
(Adrien Brody), has traded John Travolta and disco for the Sex
Pistols and punk. He now sports spiked hair and affects a British
accent. This doesn't go down well with the neighborhood regulars,
who're becoming bat-wielding, list-keeping vigilantes as the Son of
Sam body count rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 8 million stories in the naked city,'' Breslin tells
us. ``This is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If only. ``Summer of Sam'' is at least five or six stories; the
summer of '77 is also, in Lee's mix, the summer of the blackout, a
crippling heat wave, Reggie Jackson's World Series, etc., etc.,
etc. The filmmaker wants to convey the feel of that time and place
by showing us everyone from the local mafioso (a wonderful bit by
Ben Gazzara) to an I'm-here-so-it-must-be-important TV anchor (Lee
himself, hilarious in an Afro and with an Afro-sized attitude).
</P>
<P>
   It's a nifty idea, one that Lee carried off to perfection in his
masterpiece, ``Do the Right Thing.'' But here it seems scattered
and unresolved, as if Lee had somehow gotten it into his head that
he ought to make a Robert Altman movie. He and his co-writers,
Victor Colicchio and Michael Imperioli, have the tough-funny
ambience of Vinny and his pals down pat. They achieve a real sense
of the city as it was in 1977 _ a mishmash of different scenes
ranging from CBGB's to Plato's Retreat to Studio 54. But they've
failed to give us anyone to care about. Vinnie, Dionna, even
Ritchie are as much caricatures as they are characters. When we
finally realize that Vinny and Ritchie's friendship is supposed to
really mean something _ a la Harvey Keitel and Robert De Niro in
``Mean Streets'' _ it's too late. The supposedly explosive ending
just hangs there without much effect.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, ``Summer of Sam'' is a badly flawed film full of
good intentions. By the time we get to what must be called the
movie's Mr. Ed Moment _ Berkowitz taking orders from a slobbering,
English-speaking black pooch _ Lee has lost his way and his
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Film buff note: As he did in ``Do the Right Thing,'' John Savage
has an ultrabrief cameo, as a guy rooting for the wrong sports team
in the wrong neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer of Sam''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Leguizamo, Mira Sorvino and Adrien Brody. Directed
by Spike Lee. Rated R for sex, violence, language and nudity. At
metro theaters. 2 hours, 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: This ``Summer'' is definitely long, but it's not so
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
