<TEXT>
<P>
   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, July 2. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-MEDICARE (Washington) _ Health maintenance organizations
said that they would increase Medicare premiums or cut benefits for
most of their 6 million elderly subscribers next year because they
considered federal payments to be inadequate. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Kosovo Polje, Yugoslavia) _ The destruction
inflicted by tens of thousands of NATO bombing flights is evident
in this ragged central Kosovo town, where the bleary Serbian faces
speak of a sea change in the Balkan equation: A decade after
Slobodan Milosevic envisioned it here in a speech that whipped up
Serb nationalism and helped cement his power, Greater Serbia is
dead. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and map.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GUNS (Undated) _ The California Legislature passes a
measure that limits handgun purchases to one per month. By Barry
Meier
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-SCENE (Kargil, Pakistan) _ The scene at the line
of control in Kashmir, where the two nuclear powers shoot it out.
By Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-IDENTITY (Halifax, Nova Scotia) _ Certain countries find
celebrating their own birthdays a bit awkward. Canada is one.
Canadians shoot off fireworks, and they hold parades, though they
never get as boisterous as their noisy neighbors to the south. That
may be because national birthdays like the one they mark Friday
inevitably invite reflections on a nation's character. And that can
be a squirmy subject for Canadians. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast) _ Northern Ireland talks resumed on
Thursday after a midnight deadline passed. Tony Blair, the British
prime minister, stays for more talks, canceling his scheduled
appearance in Edinburgh for the opening of the new Scottish
Parliament. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washington) _ The House is expected to vote on
legislation that overhauls the nation's financial system, repealing
the Glass-Steagall Act and the barriers that have restricted banks,
insurance companies and securities firms from going into each
other's businesses. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-EXPORTS (Washington) _ President Clinton ordered a
sweeping easing of export restrictions on computers and computer
chips, including to China, after determining that machines that
were considered supercomputers just a few years ago are now so
widely available that they are virtually impossible to control. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUV (New York) _ Despite congested streets, narrow roadways,
aging bridges and tunnels and polluted air that, in some respects,
make the New York area uniquely inhospitable to light trucks, the
region has become one of the nation's hottest markets for sport
utility vehicles. Now, state regulators are on the verge of
proposing new registration rules that could further increase the
number of heavy vehicles on area roadways. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
</TEXT>
