<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS04-COX     07-01 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With deft touch, memoirist makes `Stories' our own
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 4.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  I Could Tell You Stories: Sojourns in the Land of Memory by
Patricia Hampl. Norton. $23.
</P>
<P>
   There is an audience, almost a congregation, for whom the work
of Patricia Hampl is received with something close to devotion. It
is not the largest audience in publishing, but you wouldn't call it
a cult of any sort. Cults gather round shamans and sorcerers,
conjurers of sundry mysticisms. But mysticism _ need it be said? _
is not mystery, any more than mere reminiscence can claim to be a
memoir. The personal mysteries on which the memoir draws are
Hampl's abiding subject, and, as she writes in ``I Could Tell You
Stories,'' they lay upon us an impossible command. They impel us to
find in our experience a meaning whose truth is provisional at
most, never final and often in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Hampl tilled this rich soil in two earlier volumes, ``A Romantic
Education'' and ``Virgin Time,'' seeking the self-knowledge that
Augustine sought in his ``Confessions'' and Montaigne in his
``Essays.'' If this seems an exaggeration, consider the familiarity
of Augustine's aim. In the midlife crisis that produced his
``Confessions,'' Augustine wrote not so others would understand; he
wrote so he himself would understand: ``I come to meet myself,'' he
tells us, and who among us hasn't, at one point or another, set out
on the same journey?
</P>
<P>
   Journey from the outside in
</P>
<P>
   And for us, that journey opens to view the interior of a life we
had seen only from the outside, like a house that seemed tidy
enough but whose shades were half drawn. But we see, of course,
only what the inhabitant chooses to reveal, and that is the point
of her title. It traces back to a memory of riding a Greyhound bus
when she was in college. In the ``still-dark morning of a small
Missouri river town where the driver had made a scheduled stop at a
grimy diner,'' Hampl sees a handsome young man and a ``stout,
middle-aged woman in a flowered housedress'' kissing passionately
on the boarding platform. It seemed a ``conjunction of beauty and
improbability.'' They couldn't be lovers _ or could they? Moments
later the woman boards and, sure enough, plumps herself into the
seat beside Hampl. She leans out the window to blow a final kiss,
puts ``her arms snugly around her bag,'' gazes off and says, as if
to herself, ``Oh, I could tell you stories.''
</P>
<P>
   But what were those stories, and why has the memory stayed?
</P>
<P>
   As a literary form, the memoir has filled a vacuum created by
the inconsequentiality of so much of our fiction. But memoirs fall
into gradations like novels and other art forms, and we betray
something of ourselves by the choices we make. Where writer after
writer today lines up outside the public confessional, impatient to
unfurl the soiled linen of a private life, Hampl sits quietly in a
pew off to the side. Her voice is at once reflective and
conversational, and funny in ways that take you by surprise.
Describing her introduction to the birth control pill (``the
lozenge of personal revolution''), she writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I held the plastic circle in my hand. Enlightenment welled up
in me, the hilarity of revelation: It's so simple. The little pill
_ I marveled at its tininess, I bowed to medical science _ popped,
eagerly it seemed, out of its Day 1 slot. Imitating this
exuberance, I popped Day 1 lightly into my mouth, took a swallow of
water and let technology have its way with me. Today is the first
day of the rest of your life, right?''
</P>
<P>
   An intimacy in the first person
</P>
<P>
   As those words should suggest, enthusiasms of the moment are not
always what they seem. Hampl grew up Catholic in the Midwest,
coming of age in the '60s, and religion and politics are the
coordinates that have mapped her experience. The passage about the
birth control pill, for example, comes by way of introducing us to
her reading of Walt Whitman, one of her heroes. The transition is
not an obvious one, and I cannot say with assurance what the link
is (something about ``the idea of America''). But _ and this is the
important thing _ you have the double sense of Hampl's speaking to
you alone while writing (mostly) of herself.
</P>
<P>
   The contemporary memoir, Hampl writes, ``has reaffirmed the
primacy of the first-person voice in American imaginative writing
established by Whitman's `Song of Myself.' Maybe a reader's love of
memoir is less an intrusive lust for confession than a hankering
for the intimacy of this first-person voice, the deeply satisfying
sense of being spoken to privately.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken to privately: That is precisely Hampl's effect. Not
everyone uses the first person winningly, but (and contrary to
everything you were ever told in school) it connects writer with
reader. The two are bound by a certain charm, a word unfairly
suspect but one whose real meaning Hampl understands. ``Whitman
charmed me,'' Hampl writes. ``To speak, to write, without charm is
to make utterances without references to a reality outside
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Hampl's is the companionable charm that makes a bridge
between one self and another. If you had to list the details of her
life _ the isolated, chronological line items of a resume _ you'd
come up with surprisingly few. And yet you feel like you know her.
She has sorted through the ``broken, obscured images'' of that life
and given shape to what had been mystery. And then you realize how
familiar that mystery is. Much of it has been at the heart of your
life as well.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
