<HEADER>
A6380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT     07-01 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The potential for severe weather will rise Friday across parts
of high Plains as a volatile mix of ingredients come together
across the western Dakotas and northern Nebraska. With an
unseasonably strong jet stream flowing over the northwest quadrant
of the nation, a developing low pressure system will draw added
strength as it emerges from Wyoming Friday afternoon. In turn, very
warm and humid air will surge northward over the Plains, setting
the stage for clusters of potent thunderstorms to erupt across the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The sole check-and-balance on the system will be a layer of warm
air aloft that could act as a lid to suppress widespread
development. Nonetheless, large hail, damaging winds and heavy rain
are possible in spots. A few of the thunderstorms may develop into
`supercells,' giant, rotating storms with the capability of
spawning tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   These clusters of storms may consolidate into a large complex of
damaging storms as they move eastward, raising the risk of severe
weather and heavy rain across parts of the upper Mississippi Valley
Friday evening and night.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated but potentially strong thunderstorms will develop in
the Northeast as a weak disturbance pushes eastward. In its wake,
the stage will be set for a heat wave with high humidity to
commence over the weekend into early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, steamy, sultry weather will continue to stifle much
of the Southeast, with isolated by heavy thunderstorms offering
spotty, temporary relief but also raising the risk of flooding
rains.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wet Streak
</P>
<P>
   Three hundredths of an inch of rain fell at Atlanta on
Wednesday, marking the city's eighth consecutive day with
measurable rain. This string matches the record for the city's
longest rainy streak in June. Previously, matching June wet streaks
occurred in 1884, 1886, 1900 and 1927. The longest streak of
consecutive days with measurable rain in Atlanta, independent of
month, is 14, occurring twice in the month of July in 1916 and
1994. Late this June, the unwavering Bermuda high continually
pumped moist air into the Southeast from the Gulf of Mexico,
providing ample fuel for frequent rain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
