<P>
   COMPUTER-EXPORTS _ WASHINGTON _ Citing the need to protect U.S.
industry in a time of rapid technological change, President Clinton
on Thursday announced a loosening of controls on the exports of
powerful computers. (Deans, Cox News Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ WASHINGTON _ Final passage of a bill to limit companies'
legal liability for problems ties to the computer ``millennium
bug'' is expected Thursday, and President Clinton will sign it. The
industry is elated, while trial lawyers and consumer advocates are
angry. (Glass, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-RECYCLE _ Coca-Cola has instituted new procedures for
washing returnable bottles in Poland as part of its response to a
mold problem in its BonAqua brand, spokeswoman Sonya Soutus said.
Production of the bottles had been halted Thursday. Soutus said
full production of beverages in the returnable bottles could resume
as soon as Friday, with new bottle caps indicating the product
underwent the more rigorous washing. The company said laboratory
tests showed mold found in bottles of mineral water produced by
Coca-Cola in Poland posed no health threat to consumers. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FREE-PC _ What's the deal with these free PC offers? Are people
really going for it, even though they have to buy something else to
get the ``free'' computer? Shannon will look at the consumer side,
what people need to know, what's the difference between the various
offers and whether it's a good deal. (Shelton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COX-IMEDIA _ Cox Interactive Media (CIMedia) announced today
that David B. Hills has been named vice president of sales. The
announcement was made by Peter Winter, president of CIMedia. In his
new role, Hills will be responsible for overseeing all sales
operations for CIMedia's national network of 26 city sites and
three specialty sites. ``Dave's extensive traditional and new media
advertising expertise will be a tremendous asset to our CIMedia
team,'' said Winter. ``Our success depends on driving results for
our advertising customers and that is precisely what Dave has
achieved throughout his career.'' ``My objective is to help
advertisers meet their strategic business goals online and drive
the financial growth of Cox Interactive,'' commented Hills. ``I'm
excited!'' Hills, 43, is an 18-year veteran of Cox-owned TeleRep,
Inc., the nation's largest television sales representation firm
where he served as vice president/director of TeleRep Enterprises,
New York from 1987 to 1999. In that capacity, he was instrumental
in developing new advertising sales businesses. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   AQUA2 _ Bio Aqua Systems Inc. has filed a registration statement
to raise about $6 million in an initial public offiering. The Boca
Raton holding company owns a Chilean operation that makes fish meal
and is developing poultry vaccines, among other things. The Boca
office employs one person. (Waresh, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM2 _ Another piece of the Dunlap era will soon disappear
at Sunbeam _ a policy that required directors to own company stock
and that they be paid only in stock. At its annual meeting this
week, shareholders approved a payment plan for directors. (Sedore,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ Drive safely over the holiday. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 15.
</P>
<P>
   SHREDDERS _ An estimated 9 million shredders were sold in the
United States last year, according to Terri Considine, product
manager for Fellowes, an Itasca, Ill.-based shredder maker. At the
start of the decade, sales hovered around 100,000, manufacturers
say. ``People are scared. That's what it is,'' said David Joachim,
marketing director for Royal Consumer Business Products, which sold
nearly three million shredders last year. (Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED
</P>
