<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-DARLING-BOS &LR;      07-01 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-DARLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
R. CLEMENT DARLING JR., 71; A PIONEER IN VASCULAR SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED BOLTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. R. Clement Darling Jr. of Bourne, Mass., a pioneer of modern
vascular surgery, died Saturday from complications following colon
surgery at Massachusetts General Hospital. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Darling was born in Richmond, Calif., and raised in Taunton,
Mass., where his family ran the Laneway Farm. He joined the Marine
Corps in 1945 and was stationed in Beijing as well as Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   After his honorable discharge as a first lieutenant, Dr. Darling
attended Boston University and graduated in 1949. He then continued
his education at Boston University School of Medicine, graduating
in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Darling began his post-doctorate general surgery training at
Mass. General. He spent two years studying at Children's Hospital
before he returned to Mass. General for completion of his studies
in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   He then continued his training in cardio-thoracic surgery under
the guidance of Dr. Michael DeBakey at Baylor University in
Houston, where he perfected numerous techniques in the repair of
abdominal aortic aneurysms. In 1960, Dr. Darling returned to
Massachusetts and with Dr. Robert Linton pioneered and developed
the techniques for arterial reconstruction that are still in use
today. For the next 40 years Dr. Darling worked as an associate
professor of surgery for Harvard Medical School and chief of the
school's vascular surgery unit.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Darling was instrumental in the establishment of teaching
fellowships for vascular surgery in the United States. He also held
numerous patents for surgical instruments that he designed for
vascular surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Darling was one of the founders and presidents of the New
England Society for Vascular Surgeons. He was also a member of 39
major vascular and general surgical societies and was an invited
visiting professor at many universities, both in the United States
and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He was a consultant for the Army and had close ties with the
education of vascular surgeons in the Air Force. Dr. Darling wrote
more than 200 scientific articles and reviews and was on six
vascular surgery editorial boards.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement, Dr. Darling was a consultant for the
Division of Molecular Biology at Thomas Jefferson Medical School in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves three daughters, Dr. Cynthia Darling-Fisher of Ann
Arbor, Mich., Wendy Darling-Nickerson of Bourne, and Elisabeth
Darling-Botelho of North Falmouth, Mass.; a son, Dr. R. Clement
Darling III of Albany, N.Y.; and 11 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
