<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     07-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: virtual reality (Maslin). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `THE MUMMY,' starring Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, Arnold
Vosloo and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134
minutes). More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent
spoof (very loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror
classic), overloaded with cheesy special effects, suggests an
unwieldy hybrid of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Abbott and
Costello Meet the Mummy'' via ``Night of the Living Dead.'' The
intrepid adventurers who disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt that
carries a fearful curse are Fraser (playing a swashbuckling
American in the Foreign Legion), Ms. Weisz (as a plucky, wide-eyed
English librarian) and Hannah (as her twitty older brother). It's
all played for laughs. The only scary moments involve swarming
scarabs that burrow under the skin and do awful ``Alien''-like
things (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `NOTTING HILL,' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant. Directed
by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic notion
here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts might be
out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to bring her
together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome echoes
of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright, winsome
romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters themselves,
inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's burdens of being
world famous and desperately attractive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED VIOLIN,' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Jason Flemying,
Greta Scacchi and Don McKellar. Directed by Francois Girard (not
rated, 130 minutes). ``The Red Violin'' follows the colorful
300-plus-year journey of a priceless violin from its construction
in an Italian workshop in 1681 to a contemporary auction in
Montreal. As it makes its way from Vienna to England to Communist
China, the instrument becomes the inspiration for some richly
photographed historical tableaux. If the movie's narrative energy
is undermined by a plodding screenplay and wooden acting, the
music, composed by John Corigliano and played by Joshua Bell and
the London Philharmonia Orchestra, is sublime (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,' starring Liam
Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman and Jake Lloyd. Directed by
George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes). Stripped of hype and breathless
expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a happy surprise:
it's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the series and
offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions
that are even more plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of
``Jurassic Park.'' While the human stars here are indeed reduced to
playing action figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and
hordes of crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in
Lucas is given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise was funnier
and scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TARZAN,' with the voices of Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver, Rosie
O'Donnell and Nigel Hawthorne. Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris
Buck (G, 88 minutes). No need to wonder how this animated Tarzan
movie could improve on the 47 others that preceded it. Disney
animation turns the hero into a supple, long-haired hunk, lets the
apes talk to him, and whooshes through lush jungle settings with
exultant agility. This ``Tarzan'' is sprightly and likable in ways
that are hard to resist, with lively vocal performances, excitingly
kinetic animation and Phil Collins singing tunefully in the
background. Parents will stay awake, and children will be charmed
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,' &UR;  &LR; starring Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco
Zeffirelli (PG, 117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Smith)
who give ``Tea With Mussolini'' a patina of class obviously relish
chewing the scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted from a
chapter of Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of English
expatriate women living in Florence on the eve of World War II.
Smith, a quintessential British snob, is the leader of the pack,
nicknamed the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are shattered when
the Fascists rise to power and they find themselves carted off to a
Tuscan hill town, where they are held under house arrest. Cher is
her usual likable self as a free-spending, free-loving wealthy
American heiress and art collector who befriends the group
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `WILD WILD WEST,' starring Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Kenneth
Branagh and Salma Hayek. Directed by Barry Sonnenfeld (PG, 107
minutes). Another big, lavish movie with no there there. This
post-Civil War James Bondish contraption-happy sci-fi film is hard
to categorize, a quality not to be confused with originality.
Directed by Sonnenfeld without the deadpan-alien sensibility that
worked for ``Men in Black,'' this stylistic grab bag is similarly
kinky but a lot more chaotic, however heroically Smith, as a newly
hunky and debonair action hero, tries to save the day. Good-looking
but dopey, with an emphasis on toylike but vaguely ghoulish special
effects. A movie with that much potential kiddie appeal didn't have
to start in a bordello, either (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WINSLOW BOY,' &UR;  &LR; starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon
and Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G, 110
minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial
that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played with
unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it works
as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family of a
cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the consequences of
that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography is beautifully
lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch acting style sets
the film's tone and gives her suffragist character a sharp edge
(Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
