<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROCHTRUP-THEATER-ART     07-01 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCHTRUP-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: FAMILIAR FACES GLISTEN ABOVE THE FOOTLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yet another name-brand star of the small screen is
taking his bows on a New York stage this summer. He's visiting
through August, or in other words, until he is due back on the set
of his long-running, Emmy-winning police series, Tuesday nights on
ABC. In the interim you can catch him in a little theater off Union
Square, where he is delivering just the sort of sensitive
performance that landed him a juicy part in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking, of course, about Bill Brochtrup.
</P>
<P>
   What's that you say? Name doesn't ring a bell? If there were any
justice, it would. Brochtrup plays the empathic, sad-eyed clerk
John Irvin, who greets the perps and the prosecutors at the squad
room door in ``NYPD Blue.'' (He took a bullet during a courthouse
shootout in the season's two-part finale and earned a promotion to
the opening-credits roster of stars.)
</P>
<P>
   If the television role is not proof enough of this actor's
gentle strength, his knockout work in ``Snakebit,'' David Marshall
Grant's deeply satisfying Off Broadway comedy-drama about days of
waning love and friendship in Los Angeles, should provide the
supporting evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Brochtrup recently stepped into the play at the Century Theater,
replacing Geoffrey Nauffts in the pivotal role of Michael, a gay
Angeleno mourning the breakup with his lover and playing host to
his closest friends, a warring New York couple, an actor and his
wife. It is, simply put, a beautifully calibrated performance that
fits as snugly as cork to wine bottle with those of the superb
Christopher Garten as the actor and the sublime Jodie Markell as
the wife.
</P>
<P>
   The portrayal also taps nicely into an intensifying current in
New York theater: the deployment of actors more familiar from the
pages of TV Guide than Playbill, in productions across the city and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart, moonlighting from ``Ally McBeal,'' caught a
wave of favorable response to her portrayal of a jilted lover
driven to psychotic revenge in Neil LaBute's ``Bash.'' Scott Wolf,
the ``Party of Five'' heartthrob, is using his down time this
summer to draw a young crowd reared on Fox serials to Warren
Leight's Tony-winning ``Side Man.'' Wayne Knight, without his
television uniforms _ he played Newman the mailman on ``Seinfeld''
and is now Don the policeman on ``Third Rock From the Sun'' _ is a
vision in black as a vital part of the latest threesome in ``Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Attaching a television name to a theater venture is often a
marketing ploy. And while there is plenty of wonderful acting
across the cable channels, a veteran New York playgoer remains a
bit of a snob about the tube. You can't help wondering when you see
a famous television name on a Broadway marquee, ``Can that guy
really act?'' (``The Odd Couple,'' for instance, did wonders for
Tony Randall's pocketbook and visibility, but it was an impediment
to his being taken seriously in sophisticated theater circles when
he began reviving the classics for his National Actors Theater.)
</P>
<P>
   For whatever the reason television stars are attracted to the
stage _ to flex old muscles, to retool an image, to rekindle the
flame of professional passion _ they must overcome the vast impact
they have already made. Whether widely recognizable like Ms.
Flockhart or hovering in our peripheral vision like Brochtrup,
their transitions to the stage require them to erase even as they
create.
</P>
<P>
   How successful is this season's class from the coast in making
us forget how well we know them? Pretty darned successful, it
seems.
</P>
<P>
   A few have had a bumpy time. Lisa Gay Hamilton, a stage-trained
actress who now has a major role on ABC's acclaimed legal series
``The Practice,'' was ill served by ``Angelique,'' a muddle of a
play that she left in June. The show closes July 11 at the MCC
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   And others seem in a bit over their heads. The winsome Wolf is
not yet playing at the level of the rest of the exemplary ``Side
Man'' actors. But to be fair, they have been at it a lot longer
than he.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part the casting of the familiar faces has proved
felicitous; in some cases, surprisingly so. Here, in alphabetical
order, are five of the cannier recent placements onstage of figures
from our evenings in front of the set.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brochtrup
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Brochtrup to play Michael, a decent but forlorn
gay man who faces a series of personal crises in ``Snakebit,'' was
inspired. That is in part because the role is really not that much
of a stretch for the actor, who portrays John, a tenderhearted gay
man facing a personal crisis or two on ``NYPD Blue.'' The major
difference is one of emphasis. John's concerns are background noise
on the television show; onstage Michael's are front and center.
</P>
<P>
   Brochtrup handles the step up in responsibility with a leading
man's aplomb and a keen ear for the playwright's acidly funny
dialogue. There isn't as much attitude in his performance as there
was in Nauffts'; the character's edges have been softened a bit,
which alters the balance of the relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Michael now seems more of a confidant to the Jenifer of Ms.
Markell, the sole holdover from the original cast. And Brochtrup's
more serene demeanor meshes nicely with the work of Garten, a
revelation as Jonathan, a would-be star of action movies who
browbeats Michael and reduces his anxious wife to tears.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The contributions of all involved in ``Snakebit'' reflect such a
high degree of accomplishment _ Guillermo Diaz, the fourth member
of the ensemble, is another worthy replacement _ that an audience's
past associations with these actors seem to melt away. And
Brochtrup wins our hearts anew because he wears his with such
refinement and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Danza
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a disaster. With a stage crowded with
unforgettable characters _ among them James Hazeldine's thrilling
Harry Hope, Michael Emerson's tragic Willie Oban, Katie Finneran's
wild-eyed Cora and perhaps most affectingly Paul Giamatti's
heart-rending Jimmy Tomorrow _ an audience member might be forgiven
for gazing up at the actor in fighting trim behind the bar and
wondering, ``What's the boxer from `Taxi' doing there?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Danza is an authenticating presence in the huge
``Iceman'' cast; when he speaks, Flatbush Avenue rolls right up to
your seat. Yes, as others have pointed out, he isn't the subtlest
performer. His barkeep, Rocky Pioggi, has perhaps a tad too much of
the gladhanding politician about him. Yet you want to believe that
Rocky has the oily charm to control the prostitutes he swears he
doesn't pimp for, as well as the thuggish toughness to back up the
threats in lines like ``I'd like an excuse to give you a good punch
in the snoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Danza, so accustomed to ensemble work from his years on
television, conveys these attributes with ease. You have to admire
this actor's willingness to extend and challenge himself. After a
long run in sitcoms, he has performed on Broadway in plays by
Arthur Miller, credibly replacing Anthony LaPaglia in ``A View From
the Bridge,'' and now a play by Eugene O'Neill. In what other ways,
one wonders, does Danza plan to push the envelope?
</P>
<P>
   Polly Draper
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Draper's trajectory is the opposite of Danza's. Her training
is stage-based, and it was only after years of theater work that
she was cast as the high-powered, heat-seeking Ellen on
``Thirtysomething,'' the signature yuppie drama series of the late
'80s and early '90s. Now she is back onstage in New York, replacing
Natasha Richardson in ``Closer,'' Patrick Marber's partner-swapping
precis of sexual mores in the bedrooms and chat rooms of
contemporary London.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the casting of an American, Marber tinkered with
his play, modifying the Britishisms and even tweaking the staging
of the final scene. The changes, alas, do not alter the perception
that ``Closer'' has lost some of its seductive vileness in the
metamorphosing journey from the West End to Broadway. Still, Ms.
Draper settles comfortably into Marber's world of sex and
faithlessness, a morally decayed revision of the dating universe
she inhabited in ``Thirtysomething.''
</P>
<P>
   As Anna, the fickle photographer drawn into the competing beds
of a dermatologist played by Ciaran Hinds and the obituary writer
portrayed by Rupert Graves, Ms. Draper looks smashing; you believe
that civilized men might start a fistfight over her. But it is in
her fleeting opportunities at comedy that she shows herself off to
best advantage. For all the play's sexual intrigue, what works best
for Ms. Draper is a funny speech about the secret baggage men bring
to a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Flockhart, by the magnitude of her stardom, had more to lose
than most television stars in hazarding a return to the stage. She
had a potent weapon, though; she  &UR; can &LR;  act. This was clear to
anyone who knew her work before she landed on the cover of Time.
Her Natasha in Scott Elliott's ``Three Sisters'' at the Roundabout
in 1997 stamped her as a classical performer to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Now that everyone is watching, what's the result? A hit play. In
LaBute's monologue-driven ``Bash,'' she portrays two women with
opposing perspectives on homicidal violence: one who relishes it,
another who wishes it away. Although the excellent Ron Eldard, as a
bland businessman making a horrific hotel-room confession, is
handed a more rewardingly complex story line, it is Ms. Flockhart's
performances that pack them in nightly.
</P>
<P>
   The portrait of disturbance evolves slowly; the triumph of her
turn as the disintegrating interrogation-room subject of ``Medea
Redux,'' the first of the monologues, is in the sense of
misdirection. Ms. Flockhart's dead-eyed recounting of the story of
a life, couched in defensive language, casts her as victim. The
portrayal is so alive that you imagine her in motion constantly,
when in fact she is glued to the interview table.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Knight
</P>
<P>
   Who knew that Knight could work in such delicate brush strokes?
On ``Seinfeld,'' his Newman was a sort of Penguin to Jerry's
Batman, a mischievous comic-strip character with a demonic grin and
a compulsion not to deliver the mail. As Knight reveals so
touchingly in his carefully modulated performance in ``Art,''
Newman is history.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the audience wouldn't like him back; a chord of happy
familiarity was struck during the play when Knight let slip an evil
laugh, Newman style. ( Wolf triggered a similar buzz among younger
playgoers, mostly female, at ``Side Man,'' whenever he smiled
boyishly. ``Soooooo cute,'' cooed a young woman behind me who
seemed to want to take him home.)
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Art'' trio also includes Buck Henry and George Segal
(these days a sitcom star himself, on ``Just Shoot Me''), both of
whom are limber and playfully into the game. But it is Knight who
makes the most intriguing impression here. His Yvan _ the one with
the breakneck-paced monologue about the controversial wedding
invitation _ builds almost imperceptibly in power, up to the moment
Henry's Marc and Segal's Serge turn their anger at each other on
him.
</P>
<P>
   When Knight dissolves suddenly in tears, immobilized by the
feeling that his world is collapsing, it is unthinkable that there
ever was a Newman at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     07-01 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTICIPATION: THE NEXT MOVIE  
 SUMMER OF '77  
 A MYSTERY DEEPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Forget the summer! The most talked-about film of the
moment is ``American Beauty,'' a drama about a suburban family, set
to open in the autumn. Although only a few people have seen the
movie, the buzz about it has startled even Dreamworks, which made
it and has spent the last few weeks debating the details of how and
when to release it.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' is the film directorial debut of Sam Mendes,
who staged the recent London and Broadway revival of ``Cabaret''
and directed ``The Blue Room'' with Nicole Kidman. Mende, 33, a
British director, has already been offered several projects by
Steven Spielberg, one of Dreamworks' founders, but his next project
is to direct a new Stephen Sondheim musical, ``Wise Guys,'' on
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't quite believe this is happening,'' Mendes said,
referring to the interest in the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' stars Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening as an
upper-middle-class couple in an anonymous suburb whose marriage _
and lives _ are unraveling. Spacey's character works for a media
magazine from which he is about to be dismissed. His wife, an
ambitious real estate broker, treats him with indifference, if not
contempt, and has her eyes on a successful businessman played by
Peter Gallagher. Their daughter, a high school student, barely
talks to him.
</P>
<P>
   Their neighbors range from a strict Marine colonel with a
near-catatonic wife whose son is a drug dealer to two gay men. In
the film, which includes some very funny moments, the Spacey
character, called Lester, lusts after his daughter's seductive best
friend. He pursues his own personal makeover _ lifting weights,
telling people what he really thinks of them _ and, almost happily,
pays the price for it.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has told colleagues it's one of the best films he's
seen in years. After Ms. Bening saw the film, the actress was so
overcome that she is reported to have burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   The movie cost a relatively modest $15 million (the stars and
director lowered their fees but will earn a percentage of the
profits). The film will be released in New York, Los Angeles,
Boston, San Francisco and Toronto in late September and then open
on Oct. 1 in 700 other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Ball, a successful television comedy writer who wrote the
film, said the project began about two years ago when he switched
talent agents in an effort to break into movies. His new film
agent, Andrew Cannava, at the United Talent Agency, suggested he
write a ``spec'' script to show producers and studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted a new career in feature films,'' said Ball, a
producer and writer on the television show ``Cybill'' as well as
story editor of ``Grace Under Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball, who has a new ABC series, ``Oh, Grow Up,'' starting in the
fall, said he gave Cannava several ideas. ``They were pretty
standard romantic comedies, and then I told him a third idea, a
film difficult to define but one that interested me,'' Ball said.
``He said, `Go with the one that you have the most passion
about.'''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he finished writing the script, two producers, Dan
Jinks and Bruce Cohen, who knew Ball, took it to several companies,
and Dreamworks immediately expressed interest. ``It surprised me,''
Ball said. ``It did not seem to be the kind of script Dreamworks
would do. It was a little dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball, who is 41, grew up in Georgia, attended school in Florida,
``waitered tables and hung out on the beach in my 20s,'' then moved
to New York, where he worked as an art director at Adweek magazine.
In 1993 he wrote a play, ``Five Women Wearing the Same Dress,''
which was staged at the Manhattan Class Company in Chelsea and
caught the attention of Tom Werner and Marcy Carsey, the television
producers. They offered him a job as a writer on ``Grace Under
Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball, who is unmarried, said quietly: ``This film has some
deeply personal stuff. Frankly, I never thought it would get
produced.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendes said he was offered any number of movies after
``Cabaret.'' ``Because I'm a Brit I kept getting costume dramas and
anything with royalty,'' he said. ``Spielberg saw `Cabaret.' He
asked for a meeting in L.A. He handed me the script of `American
Beauty.' He said: `We just bought this. I can't explain what it is,
but you've got to read it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone who has seen the film or been involved with it,
Mendes said: ``It's a difficult movie to describe. When anyone has
a go at describing it, it sounds like some dreadful sitcom on
speed. It's not at all. It's so filled with loneliness. And beneath
the surface it's very funny. I read it straightaway twice. I
couldn't quite see how it could be done.''
</P>
<P>
   In the atmosphere after the school shootings in Littleton,
Colo., the film is also remarkably resonant; none of the portraits,
especially the teen-agers, are quite what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no judgments about any of these characters. They all
are deeply sympathetic and are never patronized,'' Mendes said.
``And this is hardly a film about suburban America. It could be
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Where Were You in '77?
</P>
<P>
   John Leguizamo, one of the stars of Spike Lee's ``Summer of
Sam,'' which opens Friday, was 14 years old in the summer of 1977,
when a psychopath dubbed ``Son of Sam'' by the tabloids went on a
killing spree that terrorized New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 14, living in Jackson Heights (Queens), it was a crazy
summer,'' recalled Leguizamo, a versatile film, television and
theatrical performer who plays a tormented and drug-addled Bronx
hairdresser in the movie. ``I had a three-piece rust suit. I was
trying to get into clubs in Manhattan like Roseland and Casablanca.
It was scary, though. He had shot some women in Queens. He had gone
after women with long dark hair. I still remember. Women were
cutting their hair short and dying it blond.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrien Brody, another star of the film who also grew up in
Queens, plays a spike-haired punk rocker struggling to escape the
confines of the Bronx; he was only 4 that summer and on a trip
across the country with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We escaped the heat,'' he recalled. ``But I remember people
talking about the Son of Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was an outgrowth of conversations between Lee and
Michael Imperioli, an actor who has appeared in several Lee films,
and Victor Colicchio, who has written and performed on the New York
stage for over a decade. All three share the writing credit for the
film. Leguizamo said the film was somewhat autobiographical for
Colicchio; it deals with people in Queens, mostly Italians,
reacting to the suspicion and panic generated by the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spike made us do a lot of research,'' Leguizamo said. ``He got
documentaries about that time. We read books. We hung out with cops
who were on the case. Frankly, I was having nightmares while I was
doing this movie. These were such senseless crimes. Nothing to do
with money or revenge. You can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   For his role, which called for considerable sexual candor, the
actor spent time studying Marlon Brando in the film version of ``A
Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to be as alive and free and instinctive and animal as
he was in that movie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leguizamo, whose character in the film dances at clubs with his
wife, played by Mira Sorvino, also watched videos of John Travolta
in ``Saturday Night Fever.'' He laughed. ``Me and Mira actually
wanted to do better than that,'' he said. ``But I was kicking her a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody, whose character also works as a porno dancer, said that
losing his inhibitions on film was probably the most difficult
element of the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing you learn early on is that, as an actor, you
have to overcome being self-conscious,'' he said. ``That ruins your
performance. When you're self-conscious, you're not free to have a
natural moment. And that's devastating for an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody, 26, was set to be one of the stars of ``The Thin Red
Line,'' Terrence Malick's World War II drama. But his role was
virtually edited out, which devastated him. ``It was a huge blow,''
he said. ``But maybe it's for the best. Maybe it all would have
been too quick for me. You have to suffer setbacks early on to keep
you humble. I'm humble now.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for `Eyes'
</P>
<P>
   The mystery that surrounds Stanley Kubrick's last film, ``Eyes
Wide Shut,'' deepens. Although the film opens on July 16,
practically no one has seen it, except for some top executives at
Warner Brothers, which produced it, some Kubrick associates and a
few editors and writers at Time magazine. The magazine put the
movie's stars, Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, on its cover this week
and made some rapturous comments about the film.
</P>
<P>
   But studios that believe in a movie generally show it early and
often to promote interest. When studios are nervous, they delay
early screenings as long as they can. And Warner Brothers is
showing the film to the press only two days before it opens.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, publicity people connected with the film said the
American version was still being edited to be less sexually
explicit than the European version. But the film has actually been
completed _ or nearly completed _ for months.
</P>
<P>
   Could ``Eyes Wide Shut'' be a disappointment, despite all the
hoopla?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
