<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHREW-THEATER-REVIEW-     07-01 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHREW-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE TAMING OF THE SHREW': IN MADCAP PADUA, GAGS RULE AN UNTAMED
`SHREW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(Editors: production notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pretending to have a good time can be awfully taxing.
And no place does the task appear more onerous these days than on
the stage of the Delacorte Theater in Central Park, where the
gamely energetic actors of ``The Taming of The Shrew'' are huffing
and puffing and all but pulling hamstring muscles in a strained and
groping struggle for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   They writhe and they whoop it up, trade punches, prance, dance,
screech, shriek, croon and caterwaul. Wouldn't you know it, they
even do cartwheels. Petruchio, who also gets a swift kick in the
groin once or twice, arrives for his wedding on a giant hobby
horse, dressed in spandex tights and toting a championship
wrestling belt. This proves entirely apropos. Although the
direction is credited to Mel Shapiro, this ``Shrew'' might indeed
have been put on the card by Vince McMahon of the World Wrestling
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous physicality is thoroughly compatible with the play; one
need only recall the voracious film version with Richard Burton and
Elizabeth Taylor for a demonstration of how feverishly Petruchio
and Kate can be made to gnaw and paw at each other. But the New
York Shakespeare Festival's new ``Shrew,'' which opened Thursday
night, the first of its two summer offerings in the park,
completely loses touch with the weirdly wonderful love story in the
obscuring tendencies of Shapiro's compulsive use of sight gags and
prankish improvisations. No dust settles on the production, it's
true. No meaning adheres to it, either.
</P>
<P>
   The actors become so caught up in their attention-craving
``moments'' that their characters wallow in shtick. Certainly,
``Shrew'' can be played for broad farce, yet when the farcical
elements are used as mere excuses for clownish snippets of
overacting, the play dissolves in a pool of cheap tricks, ruses the
director employs again and again. Why allow that crafty stage
veteran, Tom Mardirosian, playing Baptista, to perform a
ludicrously intricate jig not once but twice on the news of his
daughter's nuptials? Why encourage the priceless comedian Mario
Cantone, as Petruchio's servant, to deliver, in a voice that sounds
like monkeys being strangled, a shrill parody of his
last-angry-gay-man standup persona? And why, oh why, squander the
formidable skills of Allison Janney, whose Kate fulfills no
requirement of the story other than girl-beats-boy?
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who staged the hugely successful musical version of
``The Two Gentlemen of Verona'' in the park for Joseph Papp in the
early 1970s, clearly relishes the opportunity to reinvent in the
open air. His ``Shrew'' is a jazzed-up adaptation of Shakespeare's
bruising battle of the sexes that takes to heart the allusions to
the ``mad marriage'' at the play's core. All is indeed madness in
Shapiro's madcap Padua, camouflaged warmly by the designer Karl
Eigsti as the sloped patio of a grand palazzo, paved in Italian
tile and ornamented by a cupola.
</P>
<P>
   The noisy goings-on belie the courtyard's muted surface. Among
Shapiro's amplifications is a quartet of monks who sing lustily in
Italian. Electronic zippers flash an insipid English translation of
the lyrics, which include references to Viagra. The music, composed
by Mark Bennett, is supposed to get the audience in a carnival
mood, but what these religious characters _ who sound excellent, by
the way _ are doing in the play is never explained. They are
expediently dropped in, as if we were indiscriminate diners who
would feast on anything placed in front of us.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro finds more resonance in his retooling of the Christopher
Sly subplot, and that is thanks largely to Max Wright's canny
portrayal. The framing tale of Sly, the drunken tinker for whom the
players perform the story of the taming of the shrew, is often
excised by directors eager to cut to the sexually charged chase.
But here the director goes the opposite route, enlarging
Christopher Sly's role by borrowing from a contemporaneous play,
called ``The Taming of a Shrew,'' that completes the subplot in a
way Shakespeare's version does not.
</P>
<P>
   Wright seems to be developing a side business in lesser
Shakespearean clowns. His Andrew Aguecheek was a standout in
Nicholas Hytner's ``Twelfth Night'' for Lincoln Center Theater last
summer. His groaning Sly is not as crisply comic, but it's a more
physically deft performance. Padded and stuffed into oversize
trousers _ one of the seeming hundreds of garish costumes from the
sketch pads of Marina Draghici _ he looks like Humpty Dumpty in a
bad toupee. (Somehow, in the execution of an elegant collapse to
the floor, he compels the wig to flip cooperatively onto his face.)
</P>
<P>
   Although many of his colleagues are well spoken, few pull off
anything as accomplished. In Ms. Draghici's prom-gown vision, Erika
Alexander's Bianca looks fetching even if the portrayal is on the
neutral side. Peter Jacobson's dandy of a Tranio, a one-man fashion
show, seems prominent by default, and MacIntyre Dixon's old suitor
Gremio at least exudes the smoothness of accumulated stage wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't that much to say about the lackluster matchup of Ms.
Janney's Kate and Jay O. Sanders' Petruchio. They don't have much
chemistry, which is pretty fatal to ``Shrew.'' Sanders, a big lug,
offers a diligent, technically proficient performance; he hits his
marks without ever making much of one. His scenes with Ms. Janney
are no more or less passionate than those with, say, Cantone. He's
five parts bluster for every one of romance, and so he never really
manages to arouse our empathy.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone acquainted with Ms. Janney's work, in plays like ``A View
From the Bridge'' and movies like ``Big Night,'' knows of her
acting range. What's advertised less is her gift for physical
comedy; her amazing pratfall on the stairs of an inner-city school
was one of the scene-stealing moments in Mike Nichols' ``Primary
Colors.'' In ``Shrew,'' her agility is on display in the stampede
of Kate's anger, but all Shapiro knows to do with it is to unleash
it over and over. In the humiliating scene late in the play in
which Petruchio starves her and then demands she thank him, Ms.
Janney drops to the ground for yet another protracted tantrum. It's
a tiresome, and tiring, episode.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It may be that in egging on such histrionics, Shapiro intends to
distract us from the uglier and more controversial aspects of the
play, that is, the brutality of Petruchio's taming of Kate, and the
famous concluding speech in which Kate advocates wifely submission
to one's husband, ``such duty as the subject owes the prince.'' Ms.
Janney's delivery suggests a woman blissfully in love, whose
declarations surprise even her blushing Petruchio.
</P>
<P>
   The unironic treatment makes about as much sense as anything
else in this over-the-top ``Shrew,'' which runs nearly three hours
and, along the way, turns every character, highborn and low, into a
rude mechanical. The production is no heavy lift for an audience,
but it's no picnic, either. Or rather, it's the kind of picnic
where the host tells bad jokes and a boom box drowns out the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE TAMING OF THE SHREW'
</P>
<P>
   By William Shakespeare; directed by Mel Shapiro; sets by Karl
Eigsti; costumes by Marina Draghici; lighting by Brian MacDevitt;
sound by Tom Morse; composer, Mark Bennett; choreography by Naomi
Goldberg; fight director, J. Steven White; production dramaturg,
John Dias; production stage manager, James Latus; senior director,
external affairs, Margaret M. Lioi; associate producer, Wiley
Hausam; artistic associate, Brian Kulick; associate producer,
Bonnie Metzgar; general manager, Michael Hurst. Presented by the
Joseph Papp Public Theater/New York Shakespeare Festival, George C.
Wolfe, producer; Rosemarie Tichler, artistic producer; Mark Litvin,
managing director. At the Delacorte Theater.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Allison Janney (Katherina), Jay O. Sanders (Petruchio),
Olga Merediz (A Lady), Max Wright (Christopher Sly), Scott Denny
(Lucentio), Peter Jacobson (Tranio), MacIntyre Dixon (Gremio), Reg
E. Cathey (Hortensio), Erika Alexander (Bianca), Danyon Davis
(Biondello), Mario Cantone (Grumio) and Tom Mardirosian (Baptista).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EGYPT-HNS &LR;      07-01 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EGYPT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, MUBARAK SAY `TIME IS RIPE' FOR PEACE IN MIDDLE EAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak said Thursday they see new opportunities for peace in the
Middle East as Israel establishes a government more open to
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But Mubarak called on Israel's new Prime Minister, Ehud Barak,
to stop expansion of Jewish settlements and halt the retaliatory
bombings against Lebanon as a way to improve a soured atmosphere in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, during a joint news conference with Mubarak, declared
the ``time is ripe'' for peace and hinted the United States will
offer new ideas for reviving stalled negotiations. Clinton said he
hopes to meet with Barak soon, perhaps in days, as the Israeli
prime minister completes the formation of his coalition government
and assumes power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, we now have a real chance to move the peace
process forward in the Middle East,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak bemoaned the time wasted during the stalemate but added,
``Today, there is an opportunity which should not be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak said he also intends to meet soon with Barak,
Palestinian Chairman Yasser Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad
in hopes of ``creating the necessary atmosphere for resuming the
peace process without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's landslide victory in May was widely viewed as an
endorsement for a resumption of peace negotiations throughout the
region. Barak has expressed a willingness not only to resume
negotiations with the Palestinians but to return the Golan Heights
to the Syrians as part of a peace pact and to withdraw Israeli
troops from South Lebanon, where they patrol a security zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way for the Israelis to have lasting security is a
negotiated peace based on mutual respect. That is also the best way
for Palestinians to shape their own future on their own land,''
Clinton said. ``A negotiated peace is the best way for all the
people of the region to realize their aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak called for a moratorium on Jewish settlements on
occupied lands until talks resume. He said such an action would be
a step toward improving the atmosphere between Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will pave the way for the starting of final status
negotiations,'' Mubarak said, referring to the long-delayed talks
on the most delicate of issues such as the status of Jerusalem and
the status of a Palestinian state. Clinton also said the United
States opposes ``provocative settlement actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Various phases of the talks have been off track since Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin was assassinated by an Israeli extremist in
November 1995 following his approval of peace terms with the
Palestinians that returned some occupied lands. A series of suicide
bombings staged by Arab extremists helped usher in a more cautious
and conservative Israeli government, and negotiations lagged.
</P>
<P>
   After marathon negotiations at the Wye River meetings last year
in Maryland, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Arafat
agreed to a series of land-for-peace provisions but Netanyahu
suspended the pact within weeks because of internal opposition from
his coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall work closely with the United States and coordinate
our joint efforts in order to have the parties break the stalemate
and restore movement towards peace,'' Mubarak said. Egypt was the
first Arab nation to sign a peace accord with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak called on Israel to open negotiations with Syria while
it is still negotiating with the Palestinians. ``Progress on each
track facilitates movement on the other. The goal is to achieve
just, comprehensive and stable peace in the whole area,'' Mubarak
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Egyptians ``were alarmed'' by Israel's recent
bombing of civilian targets in Lebanon. The Israeli strikes were in
retaliation for attacks by Hezbollah agents in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak said Israel's actions ``only poison the atmosphere'' in
the region and he called on the nation ``to apply maximum
self-restraint in the crucial months ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   An Egyptian reporter congratulated Clinton on the president's
successful efforts in Kosovo to stop the ouster of ethnic Albanians
and to return the refugees to their homes. Perhaps, the reporter
asked, Clinton would do the same for the Palestinians who once
lived in Israel?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really good,'' Clinton said, acknowledging the
difficulty of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just look at it as a practical matter, the agreement
that is made in the end, whether refugees go home depends in part
on how long they've been away and whether they wish to go home,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like it if the Palestinian people felt free and were
free to live wherever they liked, wherever they want to live,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration pressured Arafat in May to avoid the
unilateral declaration of an independent Palestinian state on lands
formally occupied by Israel, but White House officials also have
made clear there is no opposition to a Palestinian state if it is a
negotiated issue with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged financial support for nations such as Jordan
which have absorbed large numbers of Palestinians over the decades.
The majority of Jordan's population is now Palestinian and the
oil-poor nation faces severe economic challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak praised Clinton for his efforts to secure a Middle East
peace accord. ``Under his leadership, the American contribution to
the cause of peace has reached a new high,'' Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
