<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K2-COX     07-01 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS APPROVES FINAL Y2K COMPROMISE
 &HT;    712. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress unfurled a legal umbrella Thursday over
the nation's high-tech companies to protect them from a potential
shower of lawsuits if they make a good-faith effort to solve the
Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Senate and the House approved the limited shield
legislation by lop-sided margins after President Clinton agreed to
sign a revised version that offers more protection to consumers who
fall victim to the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this bill is critical to meet a national priority,
and the president is prepared to sign it into law because it is
narrowly tailored to deal with litigation dealing with the Y2K
problem,'' White House spokesman Jake Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
   If not properly updated, some older computer systems could break
down in six months' time because they use only the last two digits
of the year to set dates. Some could read dates starting next
January as 1900, or perhaps shut down altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows at this time whether the Y2K issue is the most
exaggerated or the most understated problem of our time,'' Rep. Jim
Leach, R-Iowa, said on the floor of the House shortly before the
House cleared the bill on a 404-24 vote. Some three hours later,
the Senate approved the bill, 81-18, and sent it to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fair bill that reflects a bipartisan compromise,''
said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the Senate floor manager. ``It is a
victory for our nation and for our economy as we enter the new
millennium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But one opponent, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said, ``This bill
tells industry, 'don't worry, be happy.' It raises serious
constitutional questions and caters to the special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., ``The consumers are getting
the shaft. ... This is a shabby performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Moran, D-Va., noted that U.S. corporations will spend
upwards of $50 billion to reprogram computers to meet the Y2K
challenge. However, they might still be held liable for causing
economic damage, incurring legal burdens that Moran estimated
``could be in excess of $1 trillion.''
</P>
<P>
   Within some well-defined curbs and limits, involving 20 major
changes inserted at the last minute at the insistence of the White
House, the legislation is designed to deter a litigation bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal, said its House floor manager, Rep. Bob Goodlatte,
R-Va., is to have ``good working systems on January 1 of next year,
not a good lawsuit on January 1 of next year, and that's what this
legislation accomplishes.''
</P>
<P>
   In offering them a ``safe harbor'' from a variety of Year 2000
litigation claims, the bill won ardent backing from such trade
groups as the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, as well as from most
sectors of the high-tech industry. Some consumer groups, however,
objected.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sherman Joyce, president of the American Tort Reform
</P>
<P>
   Association, ``the White House and Congress should be commended
for putting aside their differences to reach an agreement on a
problem that could have been a disaster for America's courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bipartisan compromise enacted by Congress:
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies will get a 90-day grace period to fix a Year
2000-related failures. That consists of a 30-day notification
period and another 60 days ``to complete the proposed remedial
action or alternative dispute resolution'' before they can be sued.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most class-action suits would be heard in federal courts to
prevent plaintiffs from seeking out a friendly state venue to hear
the complaint. The class-action suits could still be heard in state
courts, however, if the plaintiffs do not seek punitive damages, if
they limit their claims to $10 million and if there are fewer than
100 members in the class.
</P>
<P>
   _ Punitive awards for Y2K damages would generally be capped at
$250,000 for defendants with a net worth of below $500,000 and
firms that employ 50 or fewer workers. But the cap would be waived
if ``the plaintiff establishes by clear and convincing evidence
that the defendant acted with specific intent'' to cause harm.
</P>
<P>
   _ Homeowners are ensured that nobody will lose a house by
missing a mortgage payment as a result of a Y2K glitch.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
