<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6410 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS &LR;      07-01 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE MAY ALLOW TAPED CONVERSATIONS IN CISNEROS TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge hinted strongly Thursday that he
would allow taped telephone conversations to be used as evidence
against former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros when the
government's conspiracy case goes to trial after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Angered at the pace of a pre-trial hearing, District Judge
Stanley Sporkin dismissed objections by defense lawyers that the
tapes made by Linda Jones, a woman with whom Cisneros had an
affair, were inadmissible because they are copies and not the
originals.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin said certain statements by Cisneros that were captured
on tape are being sought as evidence by the government to ``support
its case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a right to do that,'' said Sporkin, who accused
defense lawyers of ``complicating a simple case.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are crucial to Independent Counsel David Barrett's
case against Cisneros, 52, who is accused of orchestrating a
conspiracy with aides John Rosales and Sylvia Arce-Garcia to cover
up $250,000 in hush money he paid Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The three have pleaded not guilty. They have not attended the
two-week hearing here, which is expected to continue next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend Cisneros sought to hide the financial
arrangement with Jones, also known by her married name, Linda
Medlar, to protect his 1993 nomination to head the Department of
Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is the second Clinton administration Cabinet member to
face trial on charges of unethical behavior. Former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy was acquitted in December 1998 on charges of
bribery and accepting illegal gratuities.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 50, testified last week that she taped telephone
conversations with Cisneros out of fear that he would cut off the
payments.
</P>
<P>
   When Cisneros ended the payments, Jones went public with her
charges that he broke a verbal pledge to provide her $4,000 per
month. She filed a civil lawsuit claiming a breach of contract and
later settled for $49,000.
</P>
<P>
   She also went on a national television show in a paid interview
and accused Cisneros of lying about the payments to FBI agents
conducting a routine background investigation into his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Jones kept 88 tapes of telephone conversations made over the
course of several years. Prosecutors want to introduce 26 tapes
into evidence at the Sept. 7 trial.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was housing secretary from 1993 to 1996. He is
currently president of the Spanish-language television network
Univision, based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, the former mayor of San Antonio, was considered a
rising star in the Democratic Party until he publicly announced his
extramarital affair in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is the government's key witness in the Cisneros case. She
is serving a 3-1/2-year federal sentence for bank fraud, money
laundering and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Simon, a lawyer for Cisneros, solicited testimony Thursday
from the government's tape expert, Bruce Koenig of Manassas, Va.,
that the tapes were duplicates, and in some cases, ``copies of
copies of copies.''
</P>
<P>
   Koenig said alterations were difficult to detect on third-and
fourth-generation copies of tapes produced on non-professional
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Simon is urging Sporkin to throw out the 26 tapes the government
wants to use, arguing they were illegally made and then tampered
with by Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court cannot conclude with a reasonable probability that
the tapes haven't been tampered with,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Replied Sporkin: ``I can't accept your position here that,
because some tampering has gone on, there cannot be the
introduction of any tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge has signaled to prosecutors and defense lawyers that
portions of the tapes will not be published to protect the privacy
of third parties. Sporkin said conversations where third parties
were discussed were ``irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   But he pointedly told the defense that Cisneros' statements
about the payments were relevant and might be allowed into
evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
