<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING02-COX     07-01 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preparation key to safe holiday trip
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sunday will be the last Fourth of July this century.
You can bet that not only are the highways going to be
exceptionally crowded and the weather exceptionally hot, tempers
will be rising to triple digits as holiday travelers begin their
return home.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are making an out-of-state car trip or just a short
ride to a nearby lake or mountain retreat, don't spoil your or your
family's holiday by letting the summer heat and the boil of traffic
get the best of you. Try to remember that the real purpose of a
holiday is to give us all a chance to relax.
</P>
<P>
   That especially includes the time you spend behind a steering
wheel. Even if the thermometer is close to 100, the driver's seat
is a place where you not only can but should chill.
</P>
<P>
   While you can't control the behavior of other drivers, you can
do a lot to control behavior in you own vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with children? Smaller children will be entertained
with games or those slick new in-car video systems. Aftermarket
video systems can be found at many discount outlets for about $100.
While that may seem like a lot, it is significantly less than your
insurance deductible if you lose your cool, become distracted and
end up in a collision.
</P>
<P>
   Older kids might find that individual CD players with earphones
are the ticket to a peaceful and tranquil trip. Remember, both
video players and personalized CD players are for passengers only.
Driving is an active activity, not a passive one.
</P>
<P>
   As always, spend a few minutes checking your vehicle, before you
leave your house and before you start your return trip. Make sure
your gas tank is full, especially if you are traveling at night,
and be aware that 90-degree temperatures affect your fuel
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Also be sure to check your tires' air pressures. An
underinflated tire on hot pavement is a flat waiting to happen.
Give a quick glance to your coolant level, and check your oil.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, getting the oil changed for the trip wouldn't be a bad
idea. Heat is one of the prime causes of breakdown in lubricants.
As you are under the hood, take a peek at your belts and hoses.
Belt and hose failures are the No. 1 cause of breakdowns on modern
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   You think you've got emergency service covered just because
you've got a cell phone? You'd be surprised how many vacation areas
are out of cell range.
</P>
<P>
   Take a few moments to take care of car business before you hit
the road, and you'll not only have a happier Fourth, but a safer
one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
