<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6420 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX     07-01 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFIDENCE RUNNING HIGH IN BUSH CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Confidence is apparently running high in
George W. Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a fund-raising event that drew high-profile Silicon Valley
executives on Thursday, the GOP front-runner got a little ahead of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   He told the crowd he had been to California before, but this is
``my first trip as president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor quickly caught himself and corrected, ``the
soon-to-be president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping up his first tour of California as a presidential
candidate, Bush courted the titans of Silicon Valley by criticizing
White House policies on high-tech industries and laying out a
series of proposals to bolster America's computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bush proposed making the Internet a ``duty- and tariff-free
zone.'' He also called for expanded visas for skilled foreign
workers and legislative curbs on lawsuits stemming from the Y2K
bug.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Y2K computer problems, expected to cause some
computers to fail because they will interpret the year 2000 as
1900, could be ``the biggest potential ambulance chase in the
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, I will take the side of innovation
over litigation every single time,'' Bush told a packed crowd of
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused the Clinton administration of being tardy in
getting behind legislation on Y2K litigation.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington on Thursday, the House voted 404-24 and the Senate
81-18 to approve legislation to shield businesses from a potential
flood of Y2K computer-related lawsuits. The White House said
President Clinton will sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had threatened to veto the bill unless it had more
consumer protections, but a compromise was announced earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this administration, wisdom comes so rarely that we
should not complain even if it comes too late,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also pledged that, if elected, he would raise the number of
visas _ called H-1B visas _ allotted each year to highly skilled
foreign workers. Many high-tech companies say such a measure is
needed to combat labor shortages. The cap for 1999 is 115,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``America needs to be able to benefit from the immigration of
skilled workers,'' Bush said. ``The limit on H-1B visas should be
raised, Mr. President and Mr. Vice President.''
</P>
<P>
   Another change that Bush said he would pursue in the White
House: easing export controls to allow American companies to sell
encryption technology that is already available from foreign
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current technology export system doesn't work,'' Bush
said. ``We need to be smart enough and flexible enough to
distinguish between technologies that guide missiles and the
technologies that animate children's games.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming to Silicon Valley, Bush is going after an industry
that has been largely supportive, and provided campaign money, to
the Clinton-Gore team. Vice President Al Gore, who could face off
with Bush in the 2000 race, has been to California more than 50
times.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the executives who paid $1,000 each to hear
Bush speak were Republicans, many more have never been involved in
the political process, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Lane, CEO of Oracle, a California-based software
company, said many technology company heads feel disillusioned with
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's much more what the administration has not done,''
said Lane, a Republican. ``I think we're rushing to a new
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6421 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-2NDTAKE     07-01 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia: wonderfully well.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DESTRUCTION OF AN EAST-WEST BRIDGE
</P>
<P>
   Pec was once a beautiful town, threaded by bright streams,
backed by mountains. Like Mostar in Bosnia, and all that was most
lovely in the Balkans, it expressed the delicate interweaving of
Islamic and Christian architecture and traditions that was the
legacy of the Ottoman Empire, a power once referred to as
Turkey-in-Europe.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Pec is gone, another Balkan bridge between East and
West devoured in one of those paroxysms of destruction that have
made charred, shattered ruins the most pervasive symbol of
Yugoslavia's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Gjevdt Zajmi and his wife, Ganimete, trudge home, past abandoned
gardens with trees full of unpicked cherries, capsized trellises
with vines still clinging to them, dead animals and the blackened
windows that are the baleful eyes of so much Balkan ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians, the Zajmis were driven out on March 28, four
days after the NATO bombardment began, by three Serbian
paramilitary thugs in black masks. The same old story: from
Prijedor in northwestern Bosnia to Prizren in southwestern Kosovo,
``ethnic cleansing'' has few nuances.
</P>
<P>
   A painful odyssey through a mountain village, Montenegro and
finally Albania ensued, before this return. ``We know everything
has gone from the house, but we hope the house is still there,''
Zajmi says.
</P>
<P>
   As they turn into their street, however, hope evaporates.
Ganimete Zajmi takes in the scene and says simply: ``Vukovar.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Yugoslavia has now been sufficiently drawn-out for
certain acts, like the Serbian obliteration of the mixed Croatian
town of Vukovar in 1991, to pass into popular lore. Mrs. Zajmi is
right: The ruin is as unmitigated as in the town on the Danube.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The house was built 30 years ago. The couple's three children
were raised in it. The family planted the cherry tree that shades
the area behind what was the kitchen. Shared memories, a life,
really, lie in pieces in the rubble, and the thought of all this
abruptly causes the couple to break down in sobs.
</P>
<P>
   On a wall, the perpetrators have scrawled another conspicuous
emblem of Serbdom, the Orthodox cross with four C's (the Cyrillic
letter S) and standing for ``Samo Sloga Srbina Spasava'' _ ``Only
Unity Saves the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs were killing before,'' Zajmi, a mild man who worked
in an engineering plant, said. ``But when NATO came, they went
wild, screaming that we all had to leave. Only independence is
possible now. Nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Walking back toward the center of town, they encounter a friend,
Alma Dreshaj. She is one of few ethnic Albanians to have remained
in Pec throughout the NATO bombing, protected, as she explains, by
a kind Serb neighbor, Slavo Dedovic.
</P>
<P>
   Two men pass and overhear her words. They turn on her in rage.
``There are no good Serbs,'' one screams. ``How can you say such a
thing? They send our children to have their throats cut, and you
talk of a good Serb.'' He seems on the verge of striking Ms.
Dreshaj, but is restrained by the other man.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SYMBOLISM OVER SUBSTANCE
</P>
<P>
   As the time for negotiation ran out last March and Hill
explained that NATO would begin bombing, Milosevic shot back at
him: ``Anyone who does that _ bomb _ is going to spend the rest of
his life on a psychiatric couch.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Hill found the words extraordinary, coming, as they
did, from a man who has appeared so consistently destructive.
</P>
<P>
   The symbolism was apparently more important than the substance.
Just as the Serbs were ready to go to war in 1914 for the principle
that no Austro-Hungarian police be allowed onto their territory to
investigate the murder in Sarajevo of the Habsburg heir Archduke
Franz Ferdinand, so they would fight _ even suicidally _ to stop a
NATO deployment.
</P>
<P>
   During the bombing, the Serbian leader tried every ploy to stop
the bombardment _ making mischief with the Russians, co-opting the
mild-mannered Albanian intellectual Ibrahim Rugova, destabilizing
Macedonia, dividing the allies by playing on Serbian sympathies in
Greece and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But he also did the one thing _ the brutal eviction and killing
of Albanians _ that kept Western public opinion solidly behind the
78-day bombing and cemented the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real question whether, in the absence of the ethnic
cleansing, NATO would have been able to keep it up after a couple
of weeks,'' a Western official said. ``In a sense, his brutality
saved the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a possibly fatal misjudgment by Milosevic _ leading not
only directly to the Western protectorate that masks and in some
ways promotes the provisional Albanian government by the KLA in
Kosovo today, but also, perhaps, to his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have seen Milosevic recently _ including Hill, Gen.
Wesley Clark and the Swedish financier Peter Castenfelt _ have
found him extraordinarily out of touch, surrounded by mediocre
aides, living in a world of complete unreality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic kept saying to me, we just need seven days to wipe
out the Kosovo Liberation Army,'' said Clark, the commander of NATO
forces in Europe. ``He absolutely failed to see that this kind of
movement does not work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, Hill informed the Yugoslav president of Serbian
atrocities he had observed in the Kosovo town of Malisevo,
including paramilitary forces systematically burning Albanian homes
and stores.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic looked very upset. He stood up, put his hands in his
pockets and started pacing. Hill recalls him saying: ``There is no
excuse for that, even if the Serbs in Kosovo are very angry. I
accept responsibility. One of the most important tasks of a
democracy is to protect its minorities.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of discourse has been part of Milosevic's rule for 12
years now. For in the end _ beyond the all-important media control
and the propaganda, beyond the secret police and the loyal
kleptocracy _ his survival can only be explained by his
extraordinary ability to convince many Serbs that they are victims,
that others, not they, are to blame for all that has befallen them.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality of Yugoslavia's breakup and Milosevic's legacy
is a hard one: while Slovenia, Croatia and probably now Kosovo have
carved ethnic states out of the ruins, the land of the Serbs
continues to shrink. On Kosovo field today, a patch of land sacred
to the Serbs, a French parachute regiment has deployed, but most
Serbs are too poor, isolated and misinformed even to care.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER MIGRATION
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Serbs now huddle at the church of Pec, the old
Serbian patriarchate with its frescoes that speak of the great
flowering of medieval Serbian civilization in this region.
</P>
<P>
   Their cars are lined up, ready to leave for good if and when
Italian NATO forces in Pec are ready to escort them out. And many
of their minds, it seems, are made up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6422 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-3RDTAKE     07-01 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia: are made up.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We have been here for 700 years, and now NATO bombs and the
Albanians have driven us out,'' said Dragutin Martinovic, the
director of a factory for medicinal alcohol. And what of the
rampage against Albanians' homes? ``All the homes were destroyed by
NATO bombs,'' Martinovic said. ``We did nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a terrible sadness in the sight of all these Serbs
slumped over old stones in the grounds of their church, their
bundles beside them, awaiting some new migration in the long
Serbian history of migrations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 years ago, in 1689, Patriarch Arsenije led tens of
thousands of Serbs north and west from Pec to escape the Turks in
an earlier flight that has become part of Serbian myth.
</P>
<P>
   The themes of such myth remain unchanged _ long suffering,
heroic isolation, irrational valor, victories in defeat. Perhaps
the Kosovo debacle will now be added to the panoply of heroism and
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   But unchanged, too, it seems, after 12 years of Milosevic's
rule, is the inability to make these myths coincide with a reality
that is stable rather than one that is merely destructive and
self-destructive because it exists principally to preserve
Milosevic's own power.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When Milosevic came to Kosovo exactly a decade ago and spoke to
hundreds of thousands of Serbs gathered in a frenzied celebration
of rediscovered post-Communist identity, his inspiration was a
battle lost by the Serbs to the Ottoman Turks but later turned into
a beacon of Serbian national redemption through defeat. The battle
marked the start of the Serbs' successful struggle to preserve
their Orthodox faith during centuries of Islamic rule by the Turks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the time, with communism collapsing, it was a clever
speech that Milosevic made to us in 1989,'' said Jovo Popovic, a
former president of the Pec town council also waiting to leave.
``He said we deserved glory because from the Turks to Tito, we had
suffered injustice. As for the speech's effects, however, just look
around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Mauro del Vecchio, the Italian general commanding NATO
troops in Pec, believes these ``effects'' can still be reversed.
``We will not take Serbs out,'' he said. ``In fact, we are
escorting them back from Montenegro. We cannot allow one form of
ethnic hatred to replace another now that the Albanians are back.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments are noble enough. But the future of Kosovo seems
to lie more in the determined expression of Ramiz Norici, who has
left his restaurant in the Bronx to fight for the Kosovo Liberation
Army in his native Pec.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the legal army of a soon-to-be-independent Kosovo,'' he
said, squatting by the ruins of his family's home. ``The Serbs have
always killed us. Why should we trust them now?''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In effect, because the West waited for years to decide that
Milosevic was at the heart of the problem in the Balkans, it has
ended up trying to build a Western model in one of the corners of
the Balkans where multiethnicity and tolerance are least
conspicuous and on the back of the victory of what amounts to an
Albanian peasant uprising led by orphaned Marxists and a motley
crew of others.
</P>
<P>
   But these are heady times in the Balkans. They bring Javier
Solana, the secretary general of NATO, to dismal Pristina to be
mobbed in the streets and to say: ``We want to include this area in
the beautiful house of Europe, a place of tolerance, looking to the
past rather than the future.''
</P>
<P>
   His words reflect a unanimous Western decision to invest
massively in the Balkans and to try, after many years, to treat the
problems of Yugoslavia's destruction in an overall rather than a
piecemeal manner and so extend the zone of European stability
southeastward. But can it work?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to work,'' Hill said. ``Balkan fatigue in Western
nations is at an extreme level. We are all sick of it and we know
this is the last chance.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, both Milosevic and President Franjo Tudjman of
Croatia were made partners in the Dayton accords that ended the war
they had helped to prosecute, despite records of atrocities
committed by both their forces. Now the West has changed tack in a
way that suggests it means business in the Balkans, and has stated
straightforwardly that Milosevic must go.
</P>
<P>
   But the residue of eight years of destruction is bitter indeed
and the moderate center in Kosovo hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rugova has been marginalized. Another moderate, Fehmi Agani, has
been murdered by the Serbs. The victory of the Kosovo Liberation
Army has been the victory of Drenica farmers and expatriate
hard-liners over the urban intellectuals of Albanian society in
Kosovo. It has been a victory of the
independence-then-perhaps-democracy school over the few who held
that democracy should come first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albanian history is in many ways the history of clans and
families and an inability to establish relationships, loyalties or
institutions beyond them,'' a Western official said. ``How you
steer this society into the Western family is not easy to see, but
we are going to have to try.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Much turns on whether the Kosovo Liberation Army will give up
all its weapons to NATO as it has promised to do.
</P>
<P>
   Clark believes that the Albanians fighters ``are about 70
percent OK'' But he added that there were many hard-liners of whom
NATO had to be wary, adding, ``We are not out of the woods in this
part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Zequir, who will not give his last name and calls himself the
commander of the 134th brigade of the Kosovo Liberation Amry, has
left his wife and two children in Switzerland to come and fight. He
stands in his brand new flak jacket beneath a ``UCK-NATO'' sign in
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is certain that Western countries will assist
Albanians _ but not, it seems, in the way the West envisages.
``NATO countries will help us with arms,'' he says. ``That is no
problem. I came to fight so that my children could live in one
country, together with all Albanians, and know their language and
culture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0702-     07-01 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0702-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, MUBARAK PLEDGE TO JUMPSTART STALLED MIDEAST PEACE
PROCESS
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying Israel's incoming government offers the best
chance in years to end four decades of Arab-Israeli bloodshed,
President Clinton and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak pledged
Thursday to mount a coordinated diplomatic offensive to seize the
fresh momentum for Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hopes to welcome incoming Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak to the White House later this month.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Barak, whose Labor Party won a decisive
parliamentary victory in elections May 17, to ``take a deep
breath,'' and grasp the fresh possibilities for Mideast peace
created by the shifting political winds sweeping Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know you've got to do something, without which you
cannot succeed in serving your people in the long run, it's better
to do it sooner rather than later,'' Clinton told reporters during
a joint White House news conference with Mubarak, considered a key
figure in the success of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the difficulty that lies ahead for Barak, Clinton
added, ``It's better to just take a deep breath and go on and do
what you think has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   As a starting point, Clinton said Barak should put an end to
controversial Jewish settlements in disputed West Bank territories
to send the signal that he is prepared to translate political
support for peace into concrete measures aimed at restoring
confidence and building trust between Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also urged Barak to move quickly to enter into so-called
final status talks with the Palestinians, saying the parties should
be able to hash out the contentious issues of Jerusalem's future
and Palestinian statehood within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Israel have sent us a loud message that they
want the (peace) process to be kept alive, and they want it to be
seen through,'' Clinton said. ``I think the chances of success are
now greater.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, Barak added new support to the pro peace coalition
government he expects to put into place next Wednesday, and he
extended an olive branch to Yasser Arafat, saying he wants to meet
with the Palestinian leader immediately after taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who was in Lisbon, responded to the offer with caution,
saying he would watch Barak's actions over the next few days for
signs of a good-faith effort to move forward with the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, Barak's emerging coalition government claimed a
solid majority of 75 seats in Israel's 120-seat Parliament, the
Knesset. Additional Knesset members not expected to join the
coalition but regarded as likely to support Barak's policies on the
peace process would bring his voting strength to a commanding 90
members.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Clinton, should lend a forceful constituency to
Israeli measures aimed at resolving the territorial disputes near
the heart of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed Barak's support for the six-year-old Oslo peace
accords, which provided a blueprint for a comprehensive Mideast
peace based on Israel handing over occupied territories on the West
Bank and Gaza to Palestinian control in return for Palestinian
efforts to combat anti-Israeli terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The Oslo process, which was essentially reaffirmed during
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations Clinton hosted last fall at the
Wye River Plantation in rural Maryland, has been stalled for most
of the past 2 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, valuable time has been wasted,'' said Mubarak.
``Today, there is an opportunity which should not be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding his vote of confidence in the goodwill of the incoming
Barak government, Mubarak said he hopes to meet soon with Barak,
Arafat and Syrian President Hafez al-Assad to try to generate a
groundswell of diplomacy on several fronts at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake to assume that movement should be
confined to one track at a time,'' said Mubarak, the most
influential leader in the Arab world. ``Progress on each track
facilitates movement on the other. The goal is to achieve just,
comprehensive and stable peace in the whole area.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Egypt took the first perilous step toward peace with Israel 20
years ago, when then-president Jimmy Carter brokered the Camp David
accords between the two countries' leaders, Menachem Begin of
Israel and Anwar el-Sadat of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, who was elected following Sadat's assassination by
Islamic militants in 1981, is regarded by the Clinton
administration as critical to advancing the peace process. He is
particularly valued as a moderating influence capable of helping to
bridge gaps among Palestinian, Syrian, Lebanese, Israeli and
American positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Egypt is where the peace process started,'' said White House
spokesman P.J. Crowley. ``They are, in many ways, the cornerstone
of the peace process, and we have no doubt that President Mubarak
himself can play a very pivotal role ... once Barak is sworn in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak ripped the outgoing Israeli government headed by lame
duck Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, however, saying ``we were
alarmed,'' by Israel's aerial bombing of Lebanese positions last
week in retaliation for rockets fired into Israel from Lebanon by
the militant Islamic group, Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such actions only poison the atmosphere in the region,'' said
Mubarak. ``We call upon Israel to apply maximum self-restraint in
the crucial months ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0702-     07-01 0948
