<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RIVALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR TAKING HEAT FOR HIS PRODIGIOUS FUND-RAISING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that Gov. George W. Bush has been crowned the
fund-raising king of Campaign 2000, his rivals want to make sure
that he pays a price for financial success.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush collected more checks for his record-shattering $36.3
million campaign war chest Thursday, critics tried to turn his
achievement into a negative. President Clinton questioned Bush's
commitment to campaign finance reform. Some Republican rivals cast
Bush as a tool of special interests and ridiculed his claim to be a
Washington outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is self-mutilation that Bush is engaged in. He's stepped
into a big bear trap,'' said Juleanna Glover Weiss, a spokeswoman
for candidate Steve Forbes. She said Bush will enter the year 2000
nominating contests with ``all the special interests and lobbyists
hanging around his neck.''
</P>
<P>
   But aides to other Republican candidates and outside observers
scoffed at the notion that Bush could suffer a voter backlash for
raising more money than any candidate in U.S. political history.
</P>
<P>
   ``With $36 million, you've got to look real hard and deep to
find a downside,'' said an aide to conservative commentator Pat
Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush added to his financial advantage Thursday with a
fund-raiser for high-tech executives on the final day of a four-day
swing through California.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline, a daily political newsletter, noted that a
minimum-wage worker would have to spend more than 7 million hours
on the job to match Bush's total. If the candidate's dollars were
laid end to end, they would stretch 3,438 miles, enough to go from
New York to San Francisco with more than 400 miles of bills left
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fund-raising success is breathtaking,'' said Russ Verney,
chairman of the Reform Party. ``He's got all the infrastructure and
all the money to coast over the finish line with nobody even in his
wake. I don't see how anybody in that field can put a dent in
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, himself no slouch at fund-raising, downplayed the
impact of Bush's campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money may be important,'' the president said at a news
conference, ``but ideas are even more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also served notice that Bush can expect to come under
fire from Democrats if he follows through with plans to ignore
federal campaign spending limits. Bush is expected to escape the
restrictions by turning down federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although the decision would cost his campaign about $16.8
million in federal dollars, it would free him to raise and spend as
much as he wants from individual donors. Clinton said a decision by
Bush to avoid federal limits would show that the Texas Republican
is ``hostile'' to campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will have to make up their minds about
whether this is an important issue or not,'' Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage of the campaign, the only candidate who competes
with Bush financially is Forbes, a millionaire publisher who spent
about $37 million of his own money on his unsuccessful 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidates who are at the low-end of the fund-raising
scale will probably be gone soon,'' said Jack Pitney, a political
science professor at Claremont McKenna College in Claremont, Calif.
``Forbes is the exception because he can write his own checks.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
