<HEADER>
A6442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-RATINGS-NYT &LR;      07-01 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SEES NO SHORT CUT TO A LESS VIOLENT MEDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The topic before a packed auditorium at the New
School in Greenwich Village was ``Violence in America: Reel Life
vs. Real Life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the discussion Wednesday evening by a panel of seven mostly
arts-oriented writers, lawyers and creative types was more First
Amendment versus Second Amendment, with a clear bias in favor of
curbing guns rather than free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The forum, sponsored by the Creative Coalition, a nonprofit
advocacy group representing members of the arts and entertainment
sector, was a reflection of the growing unease about violence in
the media since the killings at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo. But if the gathering revealed anything, it might have been
that it is much easier to express anxiety about violence in the
media than reach a consensus on what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling around the country, you get the clear sense that
parents are upset and confused and that people who have been
apathetic are beginning to become vocal,'' said John Fund, an
editorial writer for The Wall Street Journal who described himself
as the panel's token conservative. ``Maybe it doesn't go any
further than that. But I think a conversation is definitely
starting.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation Wednesday was a somewhat chaotic one that
veered from guns to V-chips to one audience member's question about
whether it was an immoral act to be a guest on the Bob Grant or Don
Imus radio shows.
</P>
<P>
   The other panelists were actor, producer and director Stanley
Tucci; television producer Linda Ellerbee; Deborah Forte, executive
vice president of Scholastic Entertainment; film director and
writer Peter Bogdanovich; Dr. Alvin Poussaint, a psychiatrist at
Harvard Medical School, and lawyer Martin Garbus.
</P>
<P>
   Poussaint said there was ``overwhelming evidence'' that violence
in the media had real-world reverberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like air pollution, it affects the most vulnerable part of
society _ it's like asthma,'' he said. The problem, he said, is the
``lethal mix'' of guns, violence, other social ills and a society
drenched in violent media.
</P>
<P>
   But Garbus and others said that there was no way to censor
violence in the media except through self-censorship by people in
news and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the conversation turned to curbing guns rather than
curbing violence in the media, with several of the panel members,
particularly Garbus and Bogdanovich, questioning the practicality
in today's world of the Second Amendment's protection of private
ownership of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the gun sparring, there were condemnations of the degree to
which violence has become an accepted part of the entertainment
mix. Tucci lamented the disparity in resources between the small,
personal films he tries to make and the shoot-'em-up blockbusters
that open on thousands of multiplex screens each week.
</P>
<P>
   Bogdanovich compared the megatonnage of violence in modern films
with the understated use of it in the Fritz Lang film ``M,'' in
which Peter Lorre plays a child murderer. He said that the 1931
film, with its off-screen violence and chilling, dramatic staging
(a child's ball rolling out from behind a bush, a balloon flying
into the air), was far more powerful and effective than the
explicitly bloody movies of today.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as pointed out by actor William Baldwin, one of the
co-hosts of the gathering, it will be hard to change the situation
as long as there is an economic incentive for violence-drenched
blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called show business, and the operative word is
business,'' said Baldwin, president of the Creative Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Even given American society's short attention span, Poussaint
said, there is something striking about the current mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between Columbine and other events is that it's
about white suburban kids,'' he said. ``We have 21,000 homicides a
year in this country, but this time we can't say it's ghetto kids,
it's poor kids, it's single-parent households. We can't explain it
away in the usual ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
