<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAUTY-DANCE-REVIEW-N     07-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLEEPING BEAUTY': A TALE OF THREE AURORAS AND OF MANY `BEAUTIES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had the Kirov Ballet opened its season with Diana Vishneva and
Andrian Fadeyev leading the cast of its new production of ``The
Sleeping Beauty,'' the initial impression might have been somewhat
different. Nor would it have been wrong to start off with Altynai
Asylmuratova, New York's favorite Kirov ballerina since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   As the second and third performances of ``Sleeping Beauty''
showed, these are superb and nuanced performers, careful to remind
the audience that beneath the sprawling visual richness of newly
restored parades of courtiers and fairy tale characters lies the
story of Princess Aurora and her awakening.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vishneva and Fadeyev made their New York debuts as Aurora
and Prince Desire on Tuesday night, after the opening on Monday at
the Metropolitan Opera House; Ms. Asylmuratova was seen with
Fadeyev on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   All knew how to inhabit their roles and, more important, to
bring the focus back to classical dancing. Tchaikovsky, as
composer, and Marius Petipa, as choreographer, certainly had
spectacle in mind when they created ``The Sleeping Beauty'' in 1890
in St. Petersburg. But if the ballet has survived as the jewel of
the Russian Imperial Ballet, it is not because of its story or its
decor in different productions; it has endured because of its
glorious score and its set pieces of classical choreography by
Petipa. These may vary in detail from company to company, but no
one will claim that the Rose Adagio, for the young Aurora and four
suitors, does not come down from Petipa.
</P>
<P>
   It is Petipa's already modern abstraction of emotion through
pure classical dance, so different from the style of Romantic
ballets, that these casts understood perfectly. Ms. Vishneva's
dramatic Aurora was imbued with the dynamism and force of her
strong technique; unlike the first Aurora, Svetlana Zakharova, who
would probably be more at home in Balanchine's ballets, she used a
loose-hipped high leg extension not for effect but as part of a
clearly shaped classical phrase, and knew the value of a soft plie
in landing from a jump. In this case, the idiom was not distorted,
only made to look contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   High leg extensions are not essential to Ms. Asylmuratova.
Thinner and more mature than when her youthful mystery first cast a
spell in her dancing with the Kirov and as a guest with American
Ballet Theater, she retains her gift for pulling the viewer into
her poetic world. Her Aurora was a princess from the start, regal
but not affected, a modest child. As a vision in Act II, she was
different, careful not to push but still articulate in her dancing.
She knew how to emphasize the difference between our first and last
view of Aurora. In Act III, her style was grander, showing us the
beauty awakened to maturity and love in her wedding pas de deux.
</P>
<P>
   A baby-faced Prince wreathed by a wig of golden ringlets,
Fadeyev made the Desire interesting. His mime and expression
defined a seeker, an innocent in quest of an ideal. An attentive
and fine partner, he was also admirably precise in his double air
turns and fluent classicism in Act III.
</P>
<P>
   The divertissement in that act Wednesday afternoon offered a
surprise. In the Bluebird Pas de Deux, given here in choreography
that resembles Soviet versions more than those seen in the West,
Anton Korsakov suddenly came into his own with a series of powerful
leg beats and the height he had not shown on opening night. He
partnered Irina Zhelonkina, whose refinement and amplitude of shape
made the most of choreography that plays down sparkle in favor of
lyricism.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as elsewhere, one can question the lack of stylistic unity
in this production. Although the attempt was to restore
19th-century passages, the mime is often out of the codified
classical canon and the notation used as a tool derives from
productions after 1903. On another level, the fairies in the
prologue keep to an uninflected style that clashes with the way the
principals dance.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography for Aurora's variation in Act I, moreover,
adhered to the Royal Ballet version when Ms. Asylmuratova danced,
but this was not true in other performances. The blandness of the
Lilac Fairy's new solo in the Prologue did not hinder the gracious
acting of Daria Pavlenko (Tuesday) and Veronica Part (Wednesday).
In Act II each wore the lilac-decorated helmet and chiton of the
old photographs.
</P>
<P>
   The production's impact is visual, thanks to the elaborate sets
and the added variety of differentiated units of dancers. Young
violinists kneel to support Aurora in her arabesques in Act I, and
the retinues of the fairies and guests in the prologue and Act III
add to the charm in the storybook divertissement. Polina Rassadina
and Maxim Khrebtov are excellent in the Cinderella vignette, and
the ogre has been restored to a Tom Thumb episode.
</P>
<P>
   The newly acquired layers of music and character dance tell us
how full the stage of ``Beauty'' once looked. The effect is rich
and less than dynamic: how to make the classics come alive to a
modern audience is still the question.
</P>
</TEXT>
