u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      07-01 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS GRILL NATO SUPREME COMMANDER ABOUT KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's triumphant general in the Kosovo war
received less than a hero's welcome Thursday from US senators, who
criticized the lack of readiness for a ground invasion, poor
intelligence estimates and the now open-ended mission of American
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extensive public assessment of NATO's 11-week air
war, Supreme Allied Commander Gen. Wesley Clark told the Senate
Armed Services Committee that the allied troops believed the war
was a ``very just cause.'' He called the battle ``a testament to
political unity and the will of NATO members to stand up to the
humanitarian tragedy'' inflicted on ethnic Albanians by Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But the four-star general said the future of the Balkans depends
on the whether Milosevic remains, and his assessment was the
Yugoslav leader retained ``formidable power.''
</P>
<P>
   In his review of the lessons of the war, Clark underscored the
potential difficulties of politicians interfering with generals. In
perhaps the most dramatic example, Clark revealed that political
leaders prevented NATO forces from intercepting some 200 Russian
troops who made their way to the Pristina airport on June 11,
causing a diplomatic and military impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said others ``at levels above mine'' decided against
blocking the Russians, even though NATO had enough advance warning
to do so. When the hearing ended, Clark pulled two senators aside
and apparently expressed his displeasure about the decision. The
Russian move led to negotiations that gave Russia a larger role in
the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, told the Globe that US officials were among those who
asked NATO not to stop the Russians. ``There was a fair amount of
push, especially from the State Department, in not wishing to
create a situation for (Russian President Boris) Yeltsin that would
untenable for him domestically,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing NATO-Russian airport standoff was emblematic of the
uncertainties of the conflict, which ended suddenly after 78 days
of bombing and widespread atrocities committed by Serb troops
against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's still unfinished work in bringing peace to the province,
coupled with deep animosity toward the Clinton administration among
many Republicans and lingering doubts about NATO's tactics,
contributed to Clark's mixed welcome.
</P>
<P>
   It stood in absolute contrast to the standing ovations given by
Congress to the last returning American war commander, Gen. H.
Norman Schwarzkopf, who delivered a stirring 20-minute tribute on
May 8, 1991 to both houses of Congress. Schwarzkopf told lawmakers
then the American forces ``were the thunder and lightning of Desert
Storm. We were the United States military and damn proud of it!''
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Clark suffered through the indignity of being
caught in Washington traffic and then entered a huge Senate hearing
room a few minutes late to find only six of the 19 committee
members at their seats. (Thirteen eventually appeared.) And when
Clark finally answered the last question more than three hours and
no ovations later, only two senators were left. Spectators numbered
11.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the hearing was set from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job well done,'' said Senator John W. Warner, committee chair
and Virginia Republican.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Warner barreled ahead with a series of critical
questions about the decision not to ring Kosovo with NATO ground
troops before the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did that send a message to Milosevic of less than full resolve
on the part of NATO? Would so many Kosovar Albanians have died or
been driven from their homes if a NATO invasion force had not only
been planned, but also prepositioned and ready to strike? Would the
air campaign have been less than the 79 days?'' Warner asked.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he presented a ground troops option to the alliance,
but ``there was simply no consensus on the part of the nations'' to
assemble an invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   Warner's Republican counterparts poured on other doubts, even as
they offered their personal praise for Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Senator James M. Inhofe of Oklahoma: ``I do think that we have
abused and we have lied to the public as to the atrocities that
(were) taking place'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jeff Sessions of Alabama: ``I think it is important to
note that the horrible ethnic cleansing, the destruction and
devastation rendered by the Serbian military, did, in fact, occur
after the bombing started, after we had made threats for weeks
about bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats, in contrast, lavished praise upon the
general. Senator Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut was perhaps the
most effusive, saying of Clark, ``it seems to me . . . that the
good Lord endowed you with some extraordinary personal
capabilities. . . .And they were all tested here: your ability as a
military strategist and leader, tactician, but also honestly your
ability as a diplomat to work within NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, leaning forward in his chair, his voice filling the hall,
didn't shy away from the critiques. He acknowledged that the job is
far from done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do recognize that in many respects, the hardest part of the
job lies in the days ahead,'' he said of NATO's peacekeeping
mission, which will include 7,000 Americans among about 55,000
troops.
</P>
<P>
   The general declined numerous times to estimate the length of
the peacekeeping mission. He indicated that much depended on the
future of Milosevic. For now, he said, Milosevic didn't appear to
be seriously threatened by any opposition inside Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Under close questioning by Senator Olympia J. Snowe, a Maine
Republican, about the state of the Yugoslav military, Clark said
that NATO bombers struck only one-third of Milosevic's forces. The
rest of the army ``was deployed, dispersed, and in hiding
throughout the rest of Serbia, or in some cases in Montenegro, in
many cases close to civilian targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, said Clark, ``retains formidable power in Yugoslavia,
and he's an expert at dividing the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowe also questioned battlefield damage assessments. A Globe
reporter, in two weeks of extensive travel throughout the province,
saw only three destroyed Yugoslav military vehicles _ two tanks and
one armored personnel carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand by the figures that we released on confirmed battle
damage,'' Clark said. ``That was 110 tanks, 210 armored fighting
vehicles and 449 artillery and mortar tubes.'' He did say that
pilots hit some ``dummys,'' or fake military equipment built by
Yugoslav troops as decoys.
</P>
<P>
   Clark answered his last question close to 1 p.m. and stayed for
a few minutes to discuss the Pristina airport situation with Warner
and Senator Carl Levin, a Michigan Democrat. The general threw his
arms in the air and had a hard time keeping his voice down, despite
the presence of a group of reporters nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Then he strode out. He had arrived late Wednesday after a
13-hour plane ride. He had taken his usual morning swim Thursday.
He had only come to Washington in the first place for a few
consultations and his annual four-hour physical, which he will
undergo Friday at Walter Reed Medical Hospital. The senators were a
late addition to the schedule. And here they had grilled him, even
made him miss lunch.
</P>
<P>
   It must have rankled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' Clark said, ducking his head into his
chauffered black sedan. ``I think some nice things were said. Maybe
the difference here was that we didn't have the buildup that we had
leading to Desert Storm. Maybe I need to provide greater
clarification in the days ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
