<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERTELSMANN-MEDIA-NYT     07-01 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERTELSMANN-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BERTELSMANN, A SLIGHT TILT AWAY FROM FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUTERSLOH, Germany _ Reinhard Mohn, the 78-year-old patriarch
who has controlled Bertelsmann AG for nearly four decades, began a
cautious process Thursday of making the world's third-largest media
conglomerate less of a family business.
</P>
<P>
   But only slightly so.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to keep the empire firmly in private control, Mohn
turned over his voting rights to a new six-person board that
includes two Bertelsmann executives and at least one member of his
family.
</P>
<P>
   The move ensures that Bertelsmann, which owns properties as
diverse as European television broadcasters, the American publisher
Random House and interests in online services like
Barnesandnoble.com, retains one of the world's most curious
corporate structures.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's stock was transferred by the Mohn family
to a charitable foundation in 1993. But Mohn, a fifth-generation
descendant of the founding family, kept control of all voting
rights. The charitable foundation is entitled only to a stream of
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mohn turned over his voting rights to a new company
that will in some ways resemble an American board of directors: It
will have a mix of Bertelsmann executives and outsiders and set the
basic strategic direction.
</P>
<P>
   That is different from standard German companies, where a
management board of top executives holds most of the power and the
``supervisory board'' _ made up of executives, union
representatives and outside directors _ is usually quite weak.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new structure at Bertelsmann, control will rest with
six people: Bertelsmann's chief executive and another top
executive; two outside directors from Bertelsmann's supervisory
board; one family member and one employee representative.
</P>
<P>
   Mohn, a trim and energetic man who looks younger than his years,
will also be on the board.
</P>
<P>
   The new design means that over time the Mohn family will have
very limited say over the company. Much of the power will reside
with Bertelsmann's top executives, who have been drawn from outside
the family since Mohn retired in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike typical German supervisory boards, each member of the
Bertelsmann group will have a veto on major strategic decisions. As
a result, nonexecutives could wield considerable influence.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann's current chief executive is Thomas Middelhoff, 45,
who rose through the company and took over the top position in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Mohn said his main purpose was to preserve Bertelsmann's
``continuity and independence,'' arguing that the company's
structure and culture are unique in Germany and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann's most prominent feature is its decentralization.
Neither Mohn nor his successors have run Bertelsmann's collection
of businesses like an investment portfolio; instead, they have
championed the idea that each business should be managed as an
individually accountable entrepreneurial venture.
</P>
<P>
   During his own reign as chief executive, Mohn was famous for
delegating authority. When facing a major decision, he demanded
one-page summaries of the issues and was known to complain when
they stretched to two pages.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Bertelsmann has accumulated more than 300 separate
business units and about 600 ``profit centers,'' which generated a
large cash flow and allowed the company to finance its growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the soaring stock values for Internet companies are forcing
Bertelsmann to adopt new approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann recently sold part of its stake in the online
bookstore Barnesandnoble.com, and it is considering similar public
offerings of minority stakes in other subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Mohn and other Bertelsmann executives Thursday reiterated
their longstanding refusal to turn Bertelsmann itself into a public
company. They even fretted over the implications of letting
subsidiaries go public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of consequences from taking a company on the
stock exchange, and we have to consider them very carefully
beforehand,'' said Siegfried Luther, Bertelsmann's chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of the public offerings, Luther said, was to
create a form of currency other than cash that could be used to
finance other acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Internet companies, it only makes sense to make
acquisitions through stock swaps rather than cash,'' he said. ``But
that isn't at all the case with a book publisher. We bought Random
House for cash and that worked wonderfully well.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of Bertelsmann's decentralized operations, Mohn made it
clear that the corporation would remain very closely held.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could imagine himself outvoted, he said, ``I think
it is improbable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
