<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAM-DEMOLISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING OF MAINE DAM CELEBRATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Maine _ For the first time in US history, a government
demolition crew began destroying a dam against the wishes of its
owner, bringing down a barrier that for 162 years had prevented
salmon, sturgeon and other fish from going upstream to spawn.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of often bitter legal disputes over the future of
the Edwards Dam on the Kennebec River, a single backhoe finally
struck the killing blow, punching a hole Thursday in a temporary
earthen stretch of the dam as 1,000 specators cheered or stared in
awe at the torrent of silty brown water rushing through the breach.
</P>
<P>
   And, while environmentalists, sportsmen and Maine politicians
celebrated a rebirth of one of the Northeast's most ecologically
important rivers, federal officials said the breaching of the
Edwards Dam signals a new era in which hundreds of dams whose
environmental damage outweighs their economic good could be removed
when their licenses expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big national story,'' said Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, watching the Kennebec surge through the newly cut gap in
the 915-foot long dam. ``It's the beginning of a totally new
chapter of river restoration . . . All of Maine is entitled to a
victory lap today and I hope they'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The removal of the dam, expected to be completed around
Thanksgiving, will be a boon for 10 species of fish that live at
sea but swim up the Kennebec to spawn, opening up 17 miles of river
until the next dam upstream in Waterville. In addition, fish-eating
birds such as the osprey and eagles that circled over the
proceedings Thursday should eat better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for the Kennebec River, the fish, Maine's
recreation economy, and everyone who appreciates a free flowing
river,'' said Brownie Carson, executive director of the Natural
Resources Council of Maine, which helped lead the coalition that
pushed for the dam's removal.
</P>
<P>
   But Maine Gov. Angus King, a longtime supporter of the dam's
removal, warned that the transition to a free-flowing river will
take time. Initially, he said, the water level above the dam will
drop, exposing mud flats and washing debris such as the remnants of
long-ago log drives downstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next four or five years are going to be ugly,'' he said,
``But, in time, nature will heal.''
</P>
<P>
   In important ways, Thursday's celebration reflects how much
American attitudes toward rivers have changed since the 19th
century Industrial Revolution, when rivers were a source of both
power and a place for waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta itself was once a mill town, with a main street whose
businesses faced away from the river, while the nearby Edwards Dam
powered a cotton mill that provided 700 jobs. The Kennebec was so
polluted that windows in the state Capitol building had to stay
closed on hot summer days, and a paper company conducted log drives
on the river until the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But Edwards Manufacturing closed in the early 1980s, leaving
nothing but empty brick buildings and the dam, which generated a
modest 3.5 megawatts of power, barely enough juice for a town of
2,000. As the remaining industries on the river reduced pollution,
biologists began to question the wisdom of allowing a dam that
provided so little benefit to block so many fish from getting
upstream.
</P>
<P>
   The only concession to the fish was a 12-inch-wide polyvinyl
chloride pipe that literally sucked fish out of the water with a
vacuum pump and dumped them into an open bin to be trucked to
another river. Though the rudimentary system worked for alewife,
bigger fish such as salmon and sturgeon that can grow up to eight
feet simply didn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of organizations and top politicians called for the
dam's removal in 1989, but the owners, blessed with a contract to
sell their power at well above the market rate for electricity,
didn't want to give up their license. Instead, Edwards
Manufacturing applied for a new 50-year federal license that would
allow them to triple the electricity output.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Edwards Dam became a protracted test case for the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which licenses the nation's
75,000 dams and, before Edwards, had never ordered one removed.
Though 126 dams had been removed across the country in modern
times, according to the group American Rivers, none were ordered
removed by FERC.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Kennebec Coalition _ comprised of the Natural
Resources Council of Maine, American Rivers, Trout Unlimited, and
the Atlantic Salmon Federation _ turned the tide with a 7,000-page
report that documented the value of removing the dam. A
free-flowing Kennebec would produce at least $48 million worth of
economic benefits a year from increased sportfishing alone, the
coalition argued, while boosting the population of endangered
salmon and sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the turning point. FERC had never seen anything like
that,'' said Carson, referring to the 1996 study.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, FERC ordered the dam removed at the expense of
Edwards Manufacturing Company. But, under a compromise, Bath Iron
Works agreed to pay the $2.5 million dam removal cost in exchange
for the right to expand its shipworks downstream in sturgeon
habitat. In addition, upstream dam owners on the Kennebec agreed to
pay $4.75 million for fish restoration in exchange for delays in
installing fish ladders at their dams.
</P>
<P>
   Some denounced the compromise as an environmental sellout, but
Gov. King said the deal was actually an act of generosity by the
Edwards Manufacturing Company. ``They had a strong legal case that
could have extended the process for years,'' said King. ``Instead,
they chose the path of statesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, King said, the removal of the dam is a bittersweet
occasion because the Edwards Dam is a symbol of Maine's industrial
past. ``We are celebrating a removal, but we also should celebrate
the history as well,'' said King.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, as music from a folk trio filled the air and
Augusta residents crowded the riverbanks to see the
much-anticipated dam breaching, the atmosphere seemed mainly
festive.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation, H.E. Sargent had knocked out a 70-foot stretch
of the concrete and timber dam and replaced it with an earthen
cofferdam that would be much easier to demolish on cue. Then, a
backhoe dug a trench to allow water over the cofferdam, and the
river's swift current quickly swept it aside, turning the whole
river downstream milky brown from the silt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The river today is being returned to the people,'' said Terry
Garcia, assistant secretary of commerce for oceans and atmosphere,
predicting that other dams will eventually follow suit. ``There are
many others, perhaps hundreds, who have outlived their
usefulness.''
</P>
<P>
   However, neither Garcia nor Babbitt wanted to talk specifics,
perhaps because the next dam controversy is on Oregon's Snake
River, where four big hydro-electric dams prevent the salmon from
spawning. The administration has not yet taken a position on
environmentalists' call for the dams' removal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
