<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-Y2K-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY AIRLINE COMPUTERS 95% READY FOR YEAR 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials of the US airline industry said Thursday that 95
percent of the computer systems used to move passengers _
everything from maintenance records to reservation systems _ have
been repaired to deal with the Year 2000 problem, and the rest
would be finished by summer's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airline industry is in really great shape, and we will be
ready to fly on Dec. 31, and Jan. 1,'' Carol Hallett, president and
chief executive of the Air Transport Association, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Federal Aviation Administration, which is
responsible for certifying planes, pilots, airlines and keeping
planes safely separated in the sky, said that it appears it had met
its June 30 deadline of making all 628 computer systems Y2K
compliant. Of that number, 424 are considered ``mission critical.''
Some 65 alone involved air traffic and needed changes to make them
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has hired an independent auditor to review the
compliance, and is also waiting for the Department of
Transportation's inspector general's office to ``validate'' the
work. Once those reviews are complete _ sometime later this month _
the FAA will formally announce its year 2000 progress, a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   While on-board aircraft computer systems had already been deemed
compliant by Airbus and Boeing, airlines and airports had hundreds
of computer systems to check. Hallett said that the airlines spent
more than $700 million and two years solving ``small problems as
well as big problems'' related to how computers will function when
they read the year date change from ``99'' to ``00''. Some
computers, unless repaired beforehand, may malfunction when the
year changes because they will read the date change as the year
1900 instead of 2000. Hallett said the industry's joint task force
will spend the rest of the year testing the repaired systems.
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, President Clinton's assistant and chairman of the
President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion, said the airline
industry _ often ruthlessly competitive _ came together quickly and
cooperated to solve the problems. ``One of the secrets of their
success is their willingness to work together, sharing experiences
with products and fixing things and testing.''
</P>
<P>
   One area where less information is available is overseas
airlines and airports.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the US State Department is expected to begin issuing
travel advisories about specific countries and the ability of their
airports and air traffic control systems to o deal with the Year
2000 computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   And the International Air Transport Association, which represent
more than 200 airlines, is surveying its members. That information,
however, will not be made public and passengers may not know which
foreign airlines are having problems until they start canceling
flights when they print new schedules later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hallett, however, said US and Canadian airlines will be ready to
fly within the United States and Canada, and will not fly to any
place that is not safe.
</P>
<P>
   Hallett said major airports have been working hard to make sure
everything from jet bridges to airport lighting functions properly
and said she believes the nation's airports will have finished
their work by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston's Logan International Airport 90 percent of the
aviation-related systems have been made complaint, and 88 percent
of those have been tested. The airport expects to have every
aviation system but two finished this month. The remaining ones
will be finished in the fall when a vendor is scheduled to work on
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
