<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-CABLECAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20 DIE IN CABLE CAR ACCIDENT IN FRENCH ALPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Twenty people died Thursday when a gondola in the Alps
in southeastern France ran off a supporting cable and plunged 262
feet to the ground.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victims were on their way to work at the Plateau de Bure
radiotelescope observatory 7,952 feet up a mountain, said Dominique
Germain of the tourist office in St.-Etienne-en-Devoluy, near Gap.
The accident occurred shortly after 7 a.m. on a clear day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cable car, installed in the early 1980s and said to have had
a safety inspection a year ago, broke loose 1,500 feet into its
20-minute run up the mountain, Remi Caron, the senior French
administrative official in the area, told reporters there. The car
was fully loaded and was smashed to bits when it fell on a rocky
slope below. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims are workers and employees of local companies who
were going up there for the day,'' Germain said. ``We are all in
mourning.''
</P>
<P>
   He said only observatory workers used the car.
</P>
<P>
   St.-Etienne Mayor Jean-Marie Bernard said officials did not know
why the car had fallen. The authorities began a formal
investigation of possible criminal negligence.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The accident was the worst cable car disaster in France.
Interior Minister Jean-Claude Chevenement and Employment Minister
Martine Aubry flew to the village Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The observatory belongs to a French company, the Institute of
Millimetric Radio Astronomy, which is jointly run by the
government-financed French National Scientific Research Center, the
Max-Planck-Gesellschaft of Germany and the National Geographic
Institute of Spain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its five interferometer radiotelescopes, high above most
atmospheric pollution in a part of the Alps that receives extremely
little precipitation, pick up radio emissions that let scientists
learn about the formation of stars and galaxies and interstellar
matter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The crash followed a series of Alpine disasters over the winter
and into the spring, including a snowslide Feb. 9 near Chamonix
that killed 12 people and a fire in the highway tunnel March 24
under Mont Blanc in which 41 people died. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty skiers died last year when a U.S. Marine plane flew into
a cable in Cavalese in northern Italy and sent the gondola carrying
the skiers crashing to the ground. A military jury acquitted the
pilot of manslaughter charges but convicted him of obstruction of
justice and conspiring to destroy a cockpit video that could have
provided evidence in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
