<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6462 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAURA-ASHLEY-BOS &LR;      07-01 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAURA-ASHLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTREPRENEUR READY TO REVIVE LAURA ASHLEY BRAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Just because his newly formed company completed its
purchase of Laura Ashley's North American retail chain for only a
dollar Thursday, don't think that Laura Ashley fashion is passe or
worthless, said company president Paul Ng.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 15 years after the death of designer Laura Ashley, the
brand she created with floral prints and an English countryside
feel is poised for a comeback, Ng claims _ and a comeback means
Laura Ashley's US headquarters should stay in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Though it lost $64 million in 1997 and 1998, Ng predicts the 94
stores that will now be operated by his Laura Ashley North America
Inc. can be profitable in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura Ashley was the first lifestyle brand,'' he said.
``Before Tommy Hilfiger and J. Crew, there was Laura Ashley.''
</P>
<P>
   But skeptics say middle-aged American women won't buy Laura
Ashley apparel and home furnishings as they did 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura Ashley's image is outdated,'' noted John Macht of the
Macht Group, a retail consulting firm in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ng and a company that employs 50 people in Boston
think they have a strategy for a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Partly with the backing of affiliates of the MUI Group, a large
Malaysian conglomerate, Ng helped form his private company, which
bought the North American stores from Laura Ashley Holdings, the
British company founded by designer Ashley. MUI is also a big
shareholder in publicly traded Laura Ashley Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   According to published reports, the sale was partly motivated by
a lenders' ultimatum to Laura Ashley Holdings: Sell the
unprofitable North American retail chain or no more loans.
</P>
<P>
   Above the $1 sale price, Ng will pay the British retailer, which
retains its European stores and manufacturing operations, royalties
on North American sales and licensing revenues.
</P>
<P>
   During some of the company's uncertain days, there was talk that
Ashley's Boston office might move to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans for any moves now, according to Ng, who said
the Laura Ashley brand still has cachet; its problems were
logistics, marketing, and management.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid 1990s, Laura Ashley Holdings made a series of
blunders when it centralized planning and rapidly opened larger
stores without upping manufacturing capacity, Ng said.
</P>
<P>
   The results were often a shortage of merchandise _ or the wrong
kind of merchandise. Woolen sweaters meant for damp English winters
wound up in Texas stores in August, Ng said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Laura Ashley clothing often came in English sizes.
Those sizes, which are measured differently from US sizes, left
American customers confused and dissatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Once stores relied on Laura Ashley Holdings for nearly all
merchandise. But under Ng, the newly independent chain plans to
farm out some manufacturing to other apparel plants.
</P>
<P>
   That should end shortages. It should also mean broader
assortments and clothing suited and sized to American tastes.
</P>
<P>
   While the new company formally took over retail operations only
Thursday, Ng has been running the chain for a year, brought in
after MUI bought a stake in Laura Ashley Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Ng has closed 15 underperforming stores, narrowing the chain's
losses from $39 million in 1997 to $25 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sales fell from $132.2 million in 1996, the chain's last
profitable year, to $107.6 million in 1998. The chain may near the
break-even point in 1999 on projected sales of $65 million. Once it
gets lean and mean, the chain plans to grow again, possibly to 200
stores. An e-commerce site is also in the works.
</P>
<P>
   But some wonder whether the brand can be revived.
</P>
<P>
   London retail consultant Richard Hyman told the Associated Press
last month: ``If someone can come along and turn around Laura
Ashley, it will be one of the most incredible turnarounds I'll have
seen in my time in the industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
