<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tailwind producer sues CNN
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ April Oliver, the former TV producer fired by CNN
after it retracted her report on Operation Tailwind last year, sued
CNN and parent company Time Warner Inc. in Fulton County State
Court on Thursday, seeking $106 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, Oliver claims she was wrongly dismissed and alleges
defamation, intentional interference with contract, intentional
infliction of emotional distress, fraud and conspiracy. She is
seeking $6 million in actual damages and $100 million in punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is similar to one Oliver filed in May against CNN
and a countersuit she filed against a retired Army general who was
a source for the story, both in federal court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any suit she files has to be filed here, (according to) terms
of her employment agreement,'' said her lawyer, Neeli Ben-David.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and co-producer Jack Smith were fired by CNN in July 1998
after CNN aired their story ``Valley of Death,'' alleging use of
nerve gas by U.S. military personnel in Laos in 1970. CNN
apologized for the story but has never said it was false, and
Oliver and Smith maintain that it is true. Several other lawsuits
have been filed against CNN by Tailwind veterans; some have been
settled and some are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Phil Kloer contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
