<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-DISARM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAPONS TURN-IN WILL COST SINN FEIN LEADER SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Martin McNulty spent time on the HMS Maidstone, the
same British prison ship that once held Sinn Fein leader Gerry
Adams, so he is partial to the former IRA commander who now heads
the republican movement's political operation.
</P>
<P>
   McNulty, 44, is a strong supporter of the peace process into
which Adams has steered his former comrades-in-arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-five percent of the people around here don't want to
see the guns back on the street,'' McNulty said, referring to his
West Belfast neighborhood, an Irish Republican Army stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   But wanting the guns to stay silent is not the same thing as
turning them in. And if Adams delivers on the promise he made
Thursday, he will lose some longtime supporters like Martin
McNulty.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Adams and Sinn Fein's chief negotiator, Martin
McGuinness, McNulty says, ``If they say, `Turn in the weapons,'
that's the end of their political careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at the Felons Club, a private bar and social club where
membership is gained by serving time for IRA activity, McNulty's
conditional loyalty underscores the difficulties facing Adams and
McGuinness as they try to coax their former comrades in the IRA to
turn in weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process is stalled over the demand by the Ulster
Unionists that the IRA begin turning in weapons before Sinn Fein is
allowed to sit in a power-sharing cabinet that will oversee the
work of the new Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein argues that under the Good Friday Agreement of 1998,
the power-sharing government should be formed before the disarming
of paramilitary groups is completed. But the IRA has repeatedly
ruled out any prospect of turning in weapons, saying that would
amount to a surrender it never made.
</P>
<P>
   Adams Thursday confirmed that, in an effort to break the
stalemate, Sinn Fein was committing itself to getting the IRA to
turn in its weapons by next May, as called for in the Good Friday
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair called Sinn Fein's gesture
part of a ``historic, seismic shift in the political landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams described it in different terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have created huge difficulties for ourselves,'' he said.
``Republicans are asking, `What have Gerry Adams and Martin
McGuinness done?' ''
</P>
<P>
   They have, it could be answered, broken the last republican
taboo by saying the IRA must disarm to keep the peace process
alive. They are arguing that Sinn Fein's gaining political power
will do more for its constituents than guns could ever do.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with former and current IRA members suggest that the
republican leadership has not prepared ordinary rank-and-file
members of the organization for the prospect of turning in weapons.
As one IRA man put it, ``It's never been brought up.''
</P>
<P>
   But republican sources insist that the people who lead the
movement, from the seven-member IRA Army Council to mid-level IRA
leaders, have been briefed on the strategy and support it.
</P>
<P>
   So determined was Sinn Fein to gain international support for
its gesture that McGuinness traveled to Washington May 5 to explain
to President Clinton what Sinn Fein was prepared to do to end the
dispute over IRA weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers here are divided on Sinn Fein's intentions.
An Irish diplomat said he believed Sinn Fein had made a commitment
it cannot deliver because it was so confident that the unionists
would reject the compromise and be blamed for intransigence by
Blair and the rest of international opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, believe Sinn Fein would not gamble on something
as sensitive within the movement as weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinn Fein would not make a commitment it can't deliver,
especially on this,'' says Stephen Grimason, political editor of
the BBC in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Within the IRA, there is no issue right now more sensitive than
its weapons, which go to the core of the group's existence. In
1969, when the Troubles exploded, loyalist mobs simply walked in
and took over Catholic neighborhoods in Belfast. Nationalist
families were burned out while the mostly Protestant police stood
back and did nothing. The IRA, which had been dormant for years,
consisted of a bunch of old men with a few rusty guns. Graffitti
went up in nationalist areas suggesting that IRA stood for I Ran
Away.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyhanded treatment by police of civil rights marchers and
the refusal of the police to stop loyalists while simultaneously
cracking down on nationalists breathed life back into the new
Provisional IRA, which built up an arsenal and vowed never to be
caught unarmed again.
</P>
<P>
   But senior members of the republican movement recognize that the
political muscle that awaits in a power-sharing government eclipses
anything that 30 years of guerrilla war could achieve.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it took the IRA 30 years to kill some 300 members
of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, which it blames for imposing a
system slanted against Catholic nationalists; by ending its war,
the IRA can cut the need for more than half of the 13,000-member
force without firing a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   It is that kind of thinking that Adams, McGuinness and the rest
of the Sinn Fein leadership have been pushing on senior members of
the IRA, paving the way for turning in weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Felons Club, Martin McNulty and other men who have
served prison sentences for IRA activity said they believe
unionists are using the weapons issue as an excuse for not sharing
power with Catholic nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want us back on our knees,'' said McNulty. ``The
nationalist people will never be back on their knees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
