<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-DISNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG TO CONTINUE TALKING TO DISNEY ABOUT BUILDING THEME PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Keeping its people in suspense, Hong Kong announced
Thursday that it would extend talks with Walt Disney Co. on
building a theme park here until the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Disney and Hong Kong confirmed that they were in
negotiations to build a park. It would be Disney's second theme
park in Asia, and would signify a major expansion of the company's
dealings with China, which regained sovereignty over this former
British colony two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While officials said they had made significant progress in the
talks, they were not in a position to sign an agreement by June 30
_ the date the government had hoped to have a definitive deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say there have been holdups,'' said Mike Rowse,
Hong Kong's commissioner of tourism and the chief negotiator with
Disney. ``But we're talking about hundreds of pages of documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowse declined to say what needed to be resolved. But he noted
that the two sides had to agree on many questions: the design of
the park, the surrounding roads and rail links, and the land
reclamation needed to build a park on a remote bay on Lantau
island, west of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   And that leaves out the most critical issue: How much would
Disney pay for the land? Newspaper reports here said it has
demanded the 430-acre site free of charge _ in addition to low-cost
loans, electricity and water.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rowse said the extension was not a setback, he had been
pushing hard to complete a deal by June 30. One official involved
in the talks said that if Hong Kong missed that date, it would
delay the project a year. The reason is that the project requires
the endorsement of Hong Kong's legislature, which is about to go
into recess.
</P>
<P>
   The extension did not surprise some experts here, who have
watched Hong Kong's efforts to woo Disney with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult, complicated negotiation that involves
more people than just Disney and Hong Kong,'' said Ian K. Perkin,
chief economist of the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Perkin said a deal would probably have to include a consortium
of local property developers. One developer, Sun Hung Kai
Properties, has been rumored to be in preliminary talks with
Disney.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Disney and Hong Kong would have to clear a deal
with the Chinese government. Several other Chinese cities _
including Shanghai and Hong Kong's neighbor, Zhuhai _ have
expressed interest in a Disney park. It is not certain that the
authorities in Beijing have decided to give Hong Kong preference.
</P>
<P>
   If officials here seem sensitive about a Disney deal, it is
because they have stoked public expectations. A Hong Kong
Disneyland has come to be regarded as an elixir for the depleted
economy. Announcing a deal with Disney Thursday would have carried
an extra dose of symbolism since this is the second anniversary of
Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
   To sustain the momentum of the talks, Rowse said the city's
government would submit a revised zoning plan for Lantau island,
which would turn it into a tourist center with a brand-name theme
park. It has shelved plans to build a container port on the site
where the park would go.
</P>
<P>
   With Hong Kong's economy showing signs of recovery, that could
be a costly trade-off. ``If there is a sudden surge in trade, and
traffic in the port picks up again, where are you going to put the
capacity?'' Perkin asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
