<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Camel for Adults? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The people who brought you Joe Camel, eager to fend off
accusations of marketing to children, are now sponsoring
explorations of the art world's farthest frontiers. The line
between philanthropy and marketing, however, can be as hard to find
as the sites of some of the cultish events they underwrite.
</P>
<P>
   On June 26, for example, the Camel brand was ubiquitous at an
art-and-fashion installation (don't ask) organized by the Creative
Time arts group inside the cool, eerie spaces of the Brooklyn
Bridge Anchorage on the Brooklyn side of the East River in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   A Camel logo was projected onto the floor and printed on
brochures and cocktail napkins. Signs announced that smoking was
allowed. A woman with a clipboard asked those entering whether they
were smokers; if so, she gave them T-shirts, note pads and
schedules of other events, all for answering a few questions about
their smoking habits and signing up for mailing and e-mail lists.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, R.J. Reynolds, through its Camel brand, has
backed events in four cities. ``This is about sponsoring innovative
artists, and it is also about marketing our product,'' said Carol
Crosslin, a Reynolds spokesman. In about 10 minutes, she noted at
least five times that the events were restricted to those 21 and
older.
</P>
<P>
   Allen R. Myerson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How to Corral an Expanding Tax &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The alternative minimum tax, enacted 30 years ago to make sure
that every rich person pays some income taxes, is increasingly a
burden on the middle class. But fixing it is easy, according to a
report by the staff of the Congressional Joint Committee on
Taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Years of inflation have so distorted the tax that taxpayers with
as little as $27,404 in adjusted gross income can be subject to the
AMT. this year, but that gets little play from Washington
politicians polishing their images as tax cutters.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, virtually no one making $75,000 to $100,000
paid the tax. But this year, the committee estimated, one in eight
AMT taxpayers will be in that income group. Some middle-class
taxpayers who are affected by the AMT will not get the full
$500-a-child tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   The fix? Index the tax for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   If that is done now, the committee estimated, the 823,000
taxpayers who will pay the AMT this year will grow to just one
million in 2009, instead of the nine million projected otherwise.
If no changes are made, AMT revenues in 2009 will be $19.8 billion,
up from $3.6 billion this year. But if indexing is adopted now,
revenues will rise to only $5.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV04-     07-01 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GROWING ROSTER OF THE UNRETIRED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ariz.)   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1983, Jack and Elaine Wyman sold their advertising agency in
San Francisco and retired to Scottsdale, Ariz. He was 62 and she
was 57; they looked forward to relaxing after a lifetime of work.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen months later, they were back in San Francisco, starting
a new ad agency from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We retired because we thought it was the thing to do,'' Wyman
said. ``But it wasn't for us. We were bored.''
</P>
<P>
   They're still going strong. In 1997, they moved the business
back to Scottsdale, a city they had always liked. Although they
still have a few advertising clients, their major interest has
shifted to writing and publishing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, they started Doer Publications to publish their first
book, ``Retired? Get Back in the Game!'' Their second book,
``Married ... in Business,'' is a guide for husbands and wives who
want to start a business together. They are now preparing to
publish books by other authors.
</P>
<P>
   Do they plan to retire a second time? ``No, never again,'' said
Wyman, who is now 77.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wyman, 73, added, ``We learned our lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Wymans have more in common with the baby
boomers than with their own generation. According to a 1998 survey
by AARP, 80 percent of boomers plan to keep working at least part
time after they retire. Only 12 percent of those over 65 who are
still working full time say the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   A Social Security Administration survey on the issue _ based on
beneficiaries who retired between mid-1980 and mid-1981 _ was done
in the early 1990s by Dr. Howard Iams, a demographer with the
agency's research office. He found that only 10 percent of the
retired men and 8 percent of the women had returned to work after a
year of not working. If the AARP survey of boomers is even a
general indicator, however, those percentages could swell.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reasons for returning to work are boredom, as in
the case of the Wymans, and financial need.
</P>
<P>
   But those who are under 70 and collecting Social Security might
think twice: For every $3 that retirees between 65 and 70 earn
beyond $15,500 this year, their Social Security payments will be
cut by $1 _ essentially a penalty tax on working. The earnings cap
will rise to $17,000 next year and to $30,000 by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Those retiring early _ between 62, the minimum age to receive
Social Security, and 65 _ lose $1 for every $2 they earn beyond
$9,600, until they reach 65. That cap is also scheduled to rise,
but not as fast; it is projected to be only $10,680 by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Only people who are at least 70 are entitled to full benefits,
no matter how much they earn.
</P>
<P>
   For self-employed retirees, there is a greater burden,
regardless of age. They must pay not only the usual Social Security
taxes of 7.65 percent of net earnings, but also an equal percentage
as the employer's share, for a total of 15.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So those who work after retirement because they need the money,
especially if they are not enamored of their jobs, could wind up
with lower incomes and less satisfaction than they had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   The Wymans, who love what they do, have never much worried about
any of this. ``I know people are concerned about taxes,'' Mrs.
Wyman said. ``But wouldn't you rather have the income that requires
you to pay the taxes than to not have it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' Wyman added, ``it's important that you love what
you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those who avoid the Wymans' mistake by never
retiring. They put off collecting Social Security until 70 and can
keep earning with no penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the former New York Mayor Edward I. Koch, now 74, spoke
at New York University's journalism school shortly before embarking
on yet another career _ as a television judge on ``The People's
Court.'' His talk was laced with comments on the virtue of work.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, packed into a crowded elevator with some of the
students and faculty, Koch continued to answer questions. ``When
are you going to retire?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never!'' Koch bellowed. ``It's a terrible idea. Don't ever do
it. You'll be sorry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
