A6475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GORE-BOS &LR;      07-01 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE'D BE UNPERTURBED BY GORE CAMPAIGN CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Thursday promised to ``take no
offense'' if Vice President Al Gore begins criticizing Clinton's
decisions in the course of his campaign for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also acknowledged that if his wife, first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, decides to run for the Senate from New York, some
of their private disagreements over policy matters might become
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way democracy works,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president, speaking at a joint news conference with visiting
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, promoted Gore as the more
qualified choice as his successor. And, while careful not to knock
Gore's Democratic challenger, former New Jersey Senator Bill
Bradley, Clinton did not praise him either, saying Bradley has not
told the American public what he would do if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   During some of his most expansive public comments to date on the
shape of the 2000 presidential race, Clinton took a swipe at Texas
Governor George W. Bush, who this week smashed all fund-raising
records by raising nearly $36.3 million in four months. In the
process, Bush left Gore supporters, who have Bradley nipping at
their fund-raising heels, worried. Bradley raised $11.5 million,
narrowly trailing Gore's $18.2 million for the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said if Bush opts out of accepting matching federal
funds for his campaign _ and the spending limits that go with that
money _ then he would be in lock step with a Republican Party that
is ``unanimously hostile'' to overhauling the campaign finance
system. ``They don't believe in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the American people are going to have to make up their
minds whether this is an important issue to them or not,'' Clinton
said. ``Money may be important, but ideas are even more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   On that score, he said Gore is ``as nearly as I can determine,
the only candidate of either party who has yet actually told the
American people what he would do if he got elected.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mubarak standing beside him as the two leaders pledged new
energy at reigniting peace efforts in the Middle East, Clinton was
relaxed and verbose when the questions turned to presidential
politics, clasping his hands and resting them atop the lectern and
crossing his feet.
</P>
<P>
   When an Egyptian reporter asked Clinton a question by referring
to ``so little time before the next American elections, which are
just around the corner,'' the president frowned and mouthed,
``seventeen months?'' indicating that he indeed was counting the
time before the November 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied recent news articles about tension between him
and Gore _ brought about by the vice president's efforts to
distance himself from the scandal-tarred president _ saying he was
``frankly bewildered by those reports.''
</P>
<P>
   After those articles appeared, aides to Clinton and Gore
directed their staffs to ``knock it off,'' with respect to talking
about problems with Gores's campaign or offering opinions about
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly do not know what the source of the stories are. But
they are not in my heart or my mind,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore formally announced his campaign for president two
weeks ago, he told Tennessee reporters that there had been many
occasions when he has disagreed with Clinton over the past 6 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Clinton said that if Gore ``disagrees with a decision
that I make as president during the next year and a half, then, of
course, he will have to say so. And I will take no offense at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he didn't ask Gore to become vice president so he
would always agree with him. ``It would be a dreary world, indeed,
if we all agreed on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``If my wife decides to run for senator from New
York, then some of the disagreements that we've had in the past
over decisions I've made as president'' may become relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, he seemed to give Mrs. Clinton a chance to put some
distance between herself and his administration on Medicare policy,
acknowledging disagreements among some teaching hospitals in New
York, Massachusetts and California over proposed budget cuts. Those
hospitals and other health-care providers complained the cuts would
be too severe and make it difficult for them to maintain quality
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage the senators from New York or anyone else
who's concerned about this to bring those concerns, bring the facts
to the table,'' Clinton said. He added: ``I do think that's a
legitimate issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he wasn't surprised that Bradley had raised a
respectable $11.5 million. And he denied that he was trying to get
in a dig at Bradley by mentioning his failure so far to outline his
vision as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said himself that he has not laid out his case for
being president and said that he wants to wait till the fall to do
it,'' Clinton said. ``I am not `digging' him. I have nothing bad to
say about him. That is a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to say that Gore deserved credit for saying why he
wanted to be president and what he would do if elected.
</P>
<P>
   But, he was asked, is Bradley qualified to be president?
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will have to decide who's qualified and
who's not,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a unabashed endorsement of Gore, he added, ``There is
nobody in the race who is running, or who could run, who has had as
much experience in as many different ways'' as Al Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
