<HEADER>
A6476 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-MOTOR-HOMES-ART     07-01 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-MOTOR-HOMES-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEETWOOD AMERICAN EAGLE: PROOF THAT YOU CAN TAKE IT WITH YOU
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif., Ind., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
(af) 
By MICHELLE KREBS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIGHTON, Mich. _ When Americans take to the road, a lot of them
want a home away from home. Consider that recreational vehicles are
not just hot, they are sizzling like the burgers on the nation's
grills this holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, sales of these vehicles, including pop-up campers and
luxurious travel trailers, reached the highest level since 1978.
Within the segment, sales of motor homes _ those big, bus-like
modules designed specifically as living quarters on wheels _ had
their best year in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   And studies of consumer trends suggest that RVs will grow more
popular as baby boomers age. Already, people in their 30s and 40s
are outnumbering senior citizens among buyers, according to the
Recreational Vehicle Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   After my one and only test drive of a motor home _ the
38-foot-long, $250,000 Fleetwood American Eagle, I understood the
attraction. A vehicle like this provides most of the creature
comforts of a suburban home even as one attempts to commune with
nature. But I found it much easier to enjoy my motor home when it
was parked safely rather than ominously on the move. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American Eagle is a product of Fleetwood Enterprises Inc. of
Riverside, Calif., and is assembled in Decatur, Ind. When it
lumbered up in front of my house I was struck by its size.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was twice the length of the 2000 Ford Excursion,
which will supplant the Chevrolet Suburban as the longest
noncommerical vehicle on the road. And the American Eagle is nearly
nine feet wide _ broader than the Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a lot of space to accommodate all of the amenities of
this rolling road house.
</P>
<P>
   Though the floor space is only 350 square feet, it feels roomier
than most apartments I've lived in. And it was far more elegantly
decorated than my own suburban home. (Of course, it costs almost as
much as some four-bedroom Colonials in my neighborhood.)
</P>
<P>
   Belying motor homes' crushed-velvet, shag-rug stereotype, the
test vehicle was outfitted in warm beiges and browns accented with
splashes of green. Creamy leather sofas that convert into beds
lined both sides. The floor of the living room was covered with
plush carpet. The galley had marble tile; hardwood is optional. For
privacy, the windows had miniblinds; a drape pulled across the huge
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The cushy driver and passenger seats swiveled to make them part
of the living room. Between them, a 20-inch Sony television
electrically glided up from its wooden cabinet. Above, a Sony audio
system was stowed behind glass doors.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen had all the necessities of a luxury home: oven and
cooktop, microwave, double sink, side-by-side refrigerator with ice
maker, Corian countertops and a large pantry with slide-out baskets
and adjustable shelves.
</P>
<P>
   A two-seat breakfast nook unfolded into a table for five. And
speaking of expanding: Park the American Eagle on a flat area, push
a button and one wall extends out several inches to add interior
space.
</P>
<P>
   Black walnut cabinets, like an airliner's overhead bins, lined
the upper walls. A cedar wardrobe was built in near the bathroom,
which had a commode, sink and shower stall as well as a combined
washer-dryer. Air-conditioning and dual propane furnaces promised
year-round comfort.
</P>
<P>
   The king-size bed consumed most of the bedroom. In contrast to
the dark wood of the living room, the bedroom had whitewashed oak
cabinets. Depending on the furniture configuration one orders, the
American Eagle sleeps up to six people.
</P>
<P>
   Space was brilliantly used throughout the cabin, and no nook or
cranny was wasted. Huge, roll-out storage trays beneath the motor
home, like those on a Greyhound bus, accommodate coolers, bikes and
canoes.
</P>
<P>
   I gained even more respect for the Fleetwood's size when I slid
into the driver's seat. The large, flat steering wheel and hissing
air brakes reminded me of a school bus. Indeed, it is about that
large, and as the longest vehicle I have ever driven, the American
Eagle also was the trickiest to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Fleetwood was kind enough _ or smart enough _ to send a company
representative to give me some training. I hope that the people
buying these motor homes are getting some driver's ed as well.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing various operations, from flushing the waste
holding tank to unrolling the outside awnings, my instructor
insisted that we go for a spin. It was no quick trip around the
block, despite the potent 8.3-liter, 325-horsepower diesel engine
(with an incredible 915 foot-pounds of torque) and six-speed
automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour-long practice session which included the basics of
cruising, parking and backing up, my teacher declared me ready to
hit the road. I was not so confident.
</P>
<P>
   I still crept along, never comfortable with the sensation of
this heavy vehicle swaying from side to side like a boat. Turning,
which requires meticulous care and long-term planning, was a
genuine adventure. I prayed that no cars would be at the stoplight
when I had to perform one of these sweeping maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   The large outside mirrors and rear-view camera (which displays
images on a TV screen where a rear-view mirror would ordinarily be,
and also transmits sound from outside) helps you keep tabs on your
surroundings. Still, a Volkswagen could easily get lost in the
blind spots. I shuddered at the thought of driving one of these if
I were two or three decades older, when I presumably would have
even less less peripheral vision.
</P>
<P>
   In possession of this latter-day Conestoga wagon, a trip to the
wilderness seemed in order. But first, a practice run to the gas
station. My 11-year-old daughter served as front-seat spotter,
making sure I didn't wipe out any mailboxes or gasoline pumps.
</P>
<P>
   A $50 diesel purchase did not appreciably move the needle on the
fuel gauge. The vehicle has a 150-gallon tank, a necessity since it
goes less than 10 miles on a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   With my two children, my neighbor and her two boys aboard, we
headed out at dusk to the Brighton State Recreation Area, where
officials had assured me there were spots large enough for this
motor home. An hour later, after a few wrong turns, it was
pitch-dark. Yet another wrong turn put us on a narrow, tree-lined
dirt path that proved to be a dead end. I had to turn around.
</P>
<P>
   Near tears, I said, ``I can't do this.'' The children,
frightened by what I had gotten us into, were wailing. But my
neighbor, serving as calm, collected co-pilot, leaped out and
reassured me ``You can do this,'' her enthusiasm transmitted
through the rear vision system. She patiently guided me as I inched
forward and backward. And, yes, I did it _ what a sense of
accomplishment!
</P>
<P>
   We meandered through the campground in search of a spot that
looked large enough. None did, but we pulled into one anyway.
Campers huddled around bonfires, staring and shaking their heads.
No doubt they were muttering about my novice driving and about our
mobile mansion, ostentatiously out of place among their pup tents
and pop-up trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated tries, I couldn't pull close enough to the
electrical outlet and septic receptacle to hook up, so I gave up.
The holding tank would have to hold out, or public rest rooms would
suffice. We cranked up the generator, but the noise was so
embarrassingly loud that we shut it down quickly. We roughed it on
battery power.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we rumbled past the tents as people gawked, and
took the route home with the fewest turns. I was thrilled to pull
up to the curb at my house, leaving the American Eagle for a driver
to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   The rolling house on wheels provided all the first-class
comforts one could want, but for me, there is no place like home _
a home permanently anchored to a foundation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A fancy rig that can seem as big as all outdoors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
