<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PART TIME, FULL SPEED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)After being on maternity leave for six months, I
have returned to work half time for half pay _ in theory, at least.
My company, however, has something of a workaholic culture, and I
have two fears: first, that I will face pressure to work nearly the
full week despite the reduced salary and, second, that even after I
return full time in a few years, I will forever be on the Mommy
Track, with raises and promotions scarce. Any advice?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would love to tell you that in this age of two-career and
one-parent families, telecommuting and increased productivity, the
business world has mastered the issue of part-time and flexible
work. But that would be a lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are an awful lot of part-time workers who, in actuality,
work more than a 40-hour workweek,'' said Ellen Galinsky, president
of the Families and Work Institute, a nonprofit group in Manhattan
that researches changes in the workplace and the family.
</P>
<P>
   The problem crops up even in companies with the best intentions,
said Jacqueline Church, a consultant with WFD, a human resources
firm in Boston. The cause, she said, is often that companies have
no idea how to evaluate performance: ``The boss says, `Well, that
person looks really busy and she works long hours, so she must be a
good employee.'''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to part-time workers, said Sara Horowitz,
executive director of Working Today, a Manhattan organization that
promotes flexible work arrangements, ``there is often the subtle
but present feeling of, `Is she pulling her weight?'''
</P>
<P>
   To combat misperception, talk to your supervisor about his _ and
your _ expectations. Focus on concrete goals, Ms. Horowitz said,
and define how you will be evaluated on them. If your boss and
colleagues have evidence that you are meeting these goals, they
won't fret so much about whether you are working 20 hours a week or
50.
</P>
<P>
   When talking with the boss, try to focus on the benefits of your
arrangement for the company, not just for you. ``You may even be
able to offer the company some sort of lessons in streamlining work
or reducing redundancies,'' Ms. Church said.
</P>
<P>
   You will need to work harder to stay in touch with co-workers.
``So much in life is about personal relationships you build up,''
Ms. Horowitz said. ``This is something you have to worry about. So
much of a promotion is dependent on it.''
</P>
<P>
   And look for ways to keep people informed of your achievements _
a particularly important point for women, since men are often
better at self-promotion. ``When you do something that makes a
contribution, let it be known that you are the one who did it,''
Ms. Galinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, balancing is likely to remain difficult after you
return full time. ``Once you have children, you want to be able to
have balance in your life,'' Ms. Horowitz said. And, in a company
that values workaholism, an unwillingness to work 70-hour weeks
could indeed keep you on the Mommy Track. It may be time, she said,
to start looking for more flexible employers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
