<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-PRESS-BOS &LR;      07-01 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRIS-LEWIS HINTS AT WILLINGNESS TO SETTLE MALPRACTICE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Donna Harris-Lewis said Thursday she is ``open'' to
the idea of settling the malpractice case against her late
husband's chief cardiologist, Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., but that a
settlement offer would have to be high enough to secure her
children's future and cover the cost of the just-completed trial.
</P>
<P>
   Any additional money, she said, would be donated to the Reggie
Lewis Foundation and to research the cardiac condition that killed
the Celtics star at age 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been cast as being greedy, but that isn't true,'' said
Harris-Lewis, who has accused Mudge and two other doctors of
failing to diagnose her husband's heart condition. ``I'm not
looking for anything for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As for exactly how much she would be willing to settle for, she
said, ``I haven't thought about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis spoke with reporters in a series of back-to-back,
one-on-one, 30-minute interviews at the Boston hotel.
</P>
<P>
   There was a shrine-like aura to the rented hotel suite, stocked
with pastries and orange juice, where Harris-Lewis sat from morning
until late afternoon, facing the press corps that for the past week
has prodded her to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Resting on one easel was a color poster of her late husband, his
muscular physique rippling as he dribbled down the Boston Garden's
parquet floor. On another, an oversized black-and-white photo
showed the smiling couple in younger days.
</P>
<P>
   And seated in front of them was Harris-Lewis, wearing a
conservative beige suit and the same crucifix that hung around her
neck every day of the seven-week trial prompted by her husband's
death.
</P>
<P>
   The case ended in mistrial last week after a jury cleared two
doctors of malpractice but deadlocked on whether Mudge provided
negligent care.
</P>
<P>
   A deadlock resulted because some jurors ``didn't have the
courage'' to find Mudge negligent because they were ``worried about
not ruining his reputation,'' Harris-Lewis speculated.
</P>
<P>
   She rebutted speculation that the threat of a retrial is simply
a legal strategy meant to encourage an out-of-court settlement,
insisting that her vow to try the case again is ``not a ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis denied that Mudge ever told her and her husband
that he had reached two diagnoses _ one, the benign fainting
disorder he announced at a press conference, and the other, a more
serious heart arrythmia.
</P>
<P>
   Had the couple been told such news, she said, they would hardly
have been so jovial at the public event, where television cameras
captured the pair chatting happily and waving at friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie and I were there laughing and talking,'' Harris-Lewis
said. ``Do you think for one minute that if there was a chance he
had a life-threatening arrhythmia we would be laughing? There's no
way.''
</P>
<P>
   She also called Mudge's claim that Lewis confessed his cocaine
use to him two weeks before his death ``highly suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would Mudge be the one person Reggie would make this
confession to?'' she said. ``He had a mother who had a substance
problem, he had friends, he had family.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what had been accomplished by the trial, despite its
inconclusive outcome, Harris-Lewis said that ``the Reggie that we
all know and love remains that same person,'' a caring husband and
father, a talented athlete, a committed philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   What has yet to be achieved, she said, is ``the doctors taking
accountability and responsibility for Reggie's death.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, she added, is why she is willing to endure the mental
toll of returning to court: ``No emotional or psychological damage
could be worse than losing your husband.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
