<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-STRATEGY-ART-     07-01 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-STRATEGY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE NEWSLETTER PAGES AND INTO THE MARKETPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
(af) 
By MARK HULBERT  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   But can they invest in the real world?'' That is the question
that uncharitable money managers use to dismiss successful
investment newsletter editors. After all, it is one thing to beat
the market on paper. It's quite another to do so when running a
mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of charity notwithstanding, the question is important;
many newsletter editors also run mutual funds. If successful
editors do not perform as well in the real world as they do on
paper, their strategies should be called into question.
</P>
<P>
   But if their real-world performances match those of their
newsletters, it means that their funds can be convenient vehicles
for investors who otherwise would have to assemble portfolios,
stock by stock, to match their gurus' picks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are many reasons to avoid the do-it-yourself
approach. First, the sheer length of some newsletters'
``recommended'' lists can be daunting: there are 100 stocks, for
example, on the ``buy'' list of the Value Line Investment Survey, a
top-performing newsletter. Even though it is possible to match a
newsletter's performances without buying every recommended stock,
many people would jump at the chance to invest in a mutual fund
that would do all the work for them _ if they could be assured of
the same return.
</P>
<P>
   The frequent changes in newsletter recommendations also pose a
difficulty for investors. Many editors update their advice between
issues, sometimes daily, by recording telephone messages that
subscribers must call in to hear. Few investors have the time or
the discipline to check all those updates _ even though doing so
could be rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   For those and other reasons, it is good news that, with only a
few notable exceptions, newsletter editors who manage funds do as
well in the real world as they do with their model portfolios _ or
even better.
</P>
<P>
   I was able to identify 20 mutual funds managed by newsletter
editors that use investment approaches with at least a family
resemblance to those recommended in the newsletters. Seven of the
funds have done better than the corresponding newsletter's
performance over the same period, as calculated by The Hulbert
Financial Digest, while 13 did worse.
</P>
<P>
   The divergence was greater than 10 percentage points a year in
only five cases, and in all but one of those five, the fund did
better than the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that does not mean that all funds managed by
newsletter editors beat the market. Many of them don't _ just as
many newsletters don't. Rather, the point is that the performances
of most of these editors' funds are in line with those of their
newsletters' model portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that some of those funds lag behind the market may
reflect the difficulty faced by all advisers in sustaining good
performance.
</P>
<P>
   But what about funds whose performances are significantly
different from their newsletters' portfolios'? Consider the three
mutual funds managed by Michael Murphy, each of which has performed
much better than the model portfolios he maintains in his
newsletter, California Technology Stock Letter.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Hulbert Financial Digest, the model newsletter
portfolios lost 19.9 percent to 30.2 percent, annualized, from
early 1997 through May 31. By contrast, the annualized losses of
the funds have been in the single digits.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively poor performance of the model portfolios can be
traced to a large investment in late September 1998 in stock index
put options, which turned out to be hugely unprofitable. Murphy's
funds did not make the same investment.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy says he misstated the amount of recommended puts when he
recorded a phone message that subscribers called in to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Absent that particular trade, the performance of the model
portfolios in his letter would have been much closer to that of his
funds.
</P>
<P>
   (Because many funds managed by newsletter editors have less than
$30 million in assets, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher, they are not listed in the mutual fund tables
in The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   Another example of diverging performance is seen in some of the
funds managed by Louis Navellier. whose flagship newsletter is MPT
Review. One fund performed better than the newsletter, the other
three worse. That is because MPT Review covers a range of stock
sizes while each of Navellier's six domestic funds focuses on a
particular market capitalization category or investing style.
</P>
<P>
   His other newsletter, Louis Navellier's Blue Chip Growth Letter,
which focuses on large-cap stocks and combines growth and value
characteristics, returned 27 percent, annualized, from January 1998
through May 31 of this year _ landing between the performances of
his two large-cap funds, Navellier Large Cap Growth and Large Cap
Value, which returned 31.9 percent and 25 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The divergence in performance was relatively small in the
remainder of the cases I studied. And there are myriad factors to
explain the differences, like the necessity of managing cash flows
in an open-end mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Also, newsletter editors who manage funds have fiduciary
responsibilities to both their subscribers and their fund
shareholders, though in practice they have broad latitude in
deciding whether their fund acts before or after their newsletter
publishes a stock recommendation. Another consideration is mutual
fund expenses, which drag down returns.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, editors do not always buy the same stocks for their
funds that they recommend in their newsletters. Value Line's equity
funds are an example. While Value Line's flagship publication, the
Value Line Investment Survey, is one of the top long-term
newsletter performers, the mutual funds offered directly by Value
Line follow only loosely the service's stock-ranking system. On the
whole, the performances of the funds have trailed the newsletter's.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't the funds pay more attention to the ranking system?
One reason, said Samuel Eisenstadt, research chairman of Value
Line, is diversification, which sometimes requires owning stocks
that are not in the top ranking. Another is the potential market
impact if the funds acted immediately upon every change in the
stock rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the 100 Group 1 stocks have small market caps, and we
couldn't buy them without driving the market for them crazy,'' said
Eisenstadt, referring to the newsletter's top-ranked stocks. Stocks
that have recently joined Value Line's Group 1 would shoot up even
more than they already have, while downgraded stocks would suffer
even more.
</P>
<P>
   The underperformance of Value Line's funds, however, should not
make you doubt the real-world value of Value Line's ranking system.
Consider the performance of another Value Line mutual fund that is
available only through a variable annuity or other insurance
product.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Value Line Centurion fund, it can be bought only
through Guardian Investor Services. Its return is quite close to
what The Hulbert Financial Digest calculates for a portfolio that
invests in the 100 top-ranked Value Line stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The fund started in November 1983, and from the beginning of
1984 through May 31 of this year produced a 15.7 percent annualized
return, versus 14.3 percent for the ranking system itself and 16.9
percent for the Wilshire 5000.
</P>
<P>
   Given the difficulties in following a newsletter, and the only
modest outperformance they generally report, why not opt for the
convenience of a mutual fund? Concern about funds' market impact is
the primary reason. Yet this is a significant worry only when
investing in the smallest-cap stocks, where a fund's market impact
will be greatest.
</P>
<P>
   You might therefore want to follow Jim Collins's newsletter, OTC
Insight, with an annualized return of 23.7 percent from Oct. 31,
1992 through May 31, rather than invest in his Dominion Insight
Growth fund, which returned 16.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   How to decide if a newsletter editor's funds are right for you?
Assuming that the fund's performance is in line with the
newsletter's, your decision should be based on the newsletter's
entire record. That is because the letter will have a longer track
record than the fund. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies usually appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
