<HEADER>
A6485 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-RATINGS-2TAKE     07-01 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-RATINGS-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE WILD FUND KINGDOM, ANYONE CAN WEAR A CROWN  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In kindergartens these days, all the children are special.
You're special if you have blue eyes, but also if you have brown
eyes. You're special if you like cookies. You're even special if
you live in a house, although not any more special than if you live
in a car.
</P>
<P>
   The world of mutual funds is not so very different. Nowadays,
more and more funds are finding ways to trumpet their specialness.
Thanks in part to the proliferation of mutual fund categories and
rating services, more funds than ever can portray themselves as
excelling at something while keeping a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for instance, Lipper Inc., which tracks mutual funds,
expanded from 8 to 14 the number of categories it uses to classify
funds. In doing so, it followed in the footsteps of Morningstar
Inc., another provider of mutual fund data, which scrapped its 36
fund ``objectives'' three years ago in favor of 50 fund
``categories.'' They include flavors like specialty technology,
high-yield bonds and small-capitalization value.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the moves eliminated some ambiguities. (Weren't all
funds, after all, interested in ``capital appreciation''? And how
did ``growth and income'' differ from ``equity income''?) And they
permitted fairer and more useful comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   But like the subdivision of baseball's National and American
Leagues into regional divisions, the better to produce more
champions and more playoff games, the subdivision of funds helps
players that need to show they're near the top of the heap _ by
simply providing more heaps.
</P>
<P>
   Categories aren't the only area where mutual fund information is
expanding. Ratings of funds abound, too, and seem to be growing in
direct, if not geometric, proportion to the number of funds.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings are published not only by Lipper and Morningstar, but
also by Business Week and a host of other publications. Value Line,
which once confined itself to stocks, ranks funds these days, too,
as do a passel of newsletters, some of them focusing on single fund
families. Standard &AMP; Poor's and Moody's Investors Service once
jousted over bond ratings: now they do the same over funds.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a tendency to focus on ever shorter periods of
time: Some newspapers give prominent display to one-month, or even
one-week, returns.
</P>
<P>
   But does it really matter whether a fund is first in its class
in Grasping Magazine's rating of Southeast Asian mid-cap value
funds for the three-year period ended April 30?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. For all the sound and fury over who is No. 1 in
any year or any category, a growing body of discouraging evidence
suggests that it makes little difference.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that funds that outperform for a year or two
rarely maintain any lead over their peers. Most funds tend to
revert to the mean; hardly any consistently trump unmanaged index
funds over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Burton Malkiel, author of ``A Random Walk Down Wall Street'' and
an advocate of index investing, wrote recently that ``the fund
managers who beat the index in one period are unlikely to do so in
the next.'' Among other things, he noted that broad market indexes
regularly outperform about two-thirds of actively managed mutual
funds and that the the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, in particular,
beat 9 of 10 active managers over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   To put this in stark perspective, he wrote, ``Over the past 30
years, a $10,000 investment in the index would have grown to
$311,000 (after expenses); in the average general equity fund, the
same investment would have grown to $171,950.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of studies confirm that obsessing over mutual fund
performance is largely a waste of time. One report, issued in March
by the Financial Research Corp. of Boston, found that from 1988 to
1998, the average performance of funds placing in the top 10
percent of their peer groups in one year almost invariably fell
back toward the middle the next year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' the study found, ``out of the 40 quarterly periods
measured, only once did the average performance of top-decile funds
place into the first quartile in the subsequent year.'' (That was
in the first quarter of 1991.)
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Research study also found that Morningstar's
closely watched five-star rating system didn't matter much either,
because there wasn't much difference in the subsequent performance
of funds awarded three, four or even five stars. The study's
conclusion: ``Past investment performance fails miserably as an
indicator of future performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Another study, by Christopher R. Blake, an associate professor
of finance at Fordham University's Graduate School of Business and
Matthew Morey, assistant professor of economics at Fordham, found
Morningstar ratings of equally dubious usefulness, except for funds
given one star. Such rock-bottom ratings, over several different
five-year periods, turned out to be reliable indicators that a fund
will continue to underperform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this research, several avenues of academic inquiry
remain unexplored. For instance, if all the money spent by
investors on fund information were invested in a low-cost index
fund, how much would it be worth after 10 years? Or 20? Or 30?
</P>
<P>
   And given the apparent futility of professional fund management,
how much would America's gross domestic product increase if all the
spending on active mutual fund management were diverted to more
productive ends? Just think of all the costs associated with
fund-switching, not to mention 800 numbers and Web sites,
record-keeping and postage.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by a patriotic impulse to safeguard our nation's
economic health, I decided to look into this question. Based on
average cost and fund asset data from the Investment Company
Institute, I calculated that Americans will spend about $60 billion
this year on mutual fund management fees, sales loads and other
charges. Assuming that $10 billion of this is well-spent (a
generous assumption, based on the performance of most funds), that
translates to $50 billion a year in waste, or more than half of 1
percent of GDP _ roughly the entire annual output of Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, some characteristics of funds do appear to have
value as indicators of future performance, although they are not
the factors many funds crow about. For example, the study by the
Financial Research Corp., which looked at 766 funds from the former
Lipper categories of Growth, Growth and Income, and Capital
Appreciation, found that size really is important.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, the study showed, stock funds with
smaller asset pools have outpaced their larger competitors by 0.8
percent annually. ``Portfolio size is indeed an effective screening
tool,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The same study also found that funds less than five years old
tended to turn in above-average performance and that those older
than 10 years turned in below-average returns. The authors suspect
that this is a corollary of the size issue, since newer funds tend
to be smaller.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, small funds tend to become large, perhaps in
part because of that very performance advantage. The small funds
that remain small tend to be the underperformers, which can't draw
much new money. But while strong performance brings in new assets,
the study found that ``top-selling funds deliver slightly
below-average performance downstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, all this makes me wonder why fund marketers don't trumpet
the ``world's tiniest mid-cap blend fund with a mediocre decile
record since its inception less than three months ago.'' Maybe they
should.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     07-01 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GRAF SHOWING SHE'S NOT YET OVER THE HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, Germany)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Conventional logic, and even John McEnroe's
convoluted brand, suggested that Steffi Graf was not going to have
enough fluidity in her muscles and fuel in the tank at the end of a
long, soggy day. She walked out onto Center Court, into the
gloaming, the sky offering only enough time to finish a set. But it
happened to be the third set with Venus Williams, 19, finely tuned,
long-limbed and ready to run.
</P>
<P>
   A tall order, even for Graf, McEnroe's ``tennis goddess'' and
mixed doubles partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, it was easier to suddenly get up and play,''
McEnroe had said, as the rain fell Thursday and Graf whiled away
another Wimbledon afternoon. ``As you get older, you have to keep
on revving up, do your stretching, figure out when to eat. I think
it affects the older guy more.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf, on the other hand, is obviously no old tennis guy and no
ordinary aging gal. Indisputably one of the greats in tennis
history, she gave us another demonstration of why she could, by
Sunday, join another elite club: the association of 30-year-old
Grand Slam champions. In the twilight, in a drizzle, she cranked up
the engine for the fourth time in seven hours, broke Williams'
serve and landed in her 10th Wimbledon semifinal with a 6-2, 3-6,
6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   She also insisted on keeping her mixed doubles date with
McEnroe, making no rare concession to age. ``No way,'' she said,
when asked if she would drop out.
</P>
<P>
   This persistent second-week rain has made life hard on everyone.
I heard it poured back home in New Jersey, but my rain is worse
than yours. When it rains at Wimbledon, there is nothing to do but
eat and feel old.
</P>
<P>
   They make you feel droopy around the eyes by showing classic
Wimbledon matches on BBC. As the tarps were being rolled on and off
and back on the various courts Thursday, Martina Navratilova was
trying to take the net against Chris Evert again in the 1978
women's final. If Graf wasn't reading and Williams watching her own
first-set rerun on another channel in the women's locker room,
these two might even have shared a few laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Wood racquets. Patty-cake serves. Soft ground strokes landing
three feet short of the baseline. I often brag about having covered
some of the great Chris-Martina wars, but I wouldn't share this
information with, say, Alexandra Stevenson, simply on the ground of
dating myself. And come to think of it, maybe Graf wouldn't have
found the old stuff so funny, either. I seem to recall sitting on
Center Court for Evert's last Wimbledon appearance, a 1989
semifinal against a stalwart young German whose forehand made sure
Chrissie had no doubts.
</P>
<P>
   From one era to another, the high quality of Thursday's match
was a tribute not only to the racquet technology but also to the
evolution of women's conditioning. After all the numbing starts and
stops, there were Graf and Williams in a tense third set, in severe
conditions, conducting a grass-court clinic. The moon ball, thank
goodness, is as dead as the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the many breaks that we had, I think it's unbelievable
tennis today,'' said Graf, and even Williams agreed it was the best
losing match she had played.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Boris Becker was of the opinion that the weather
disruptions had robbed him of his service timing. The three-set
defeat to Patrick Rafter sent Becker, at 31, home to look for the
perfect German sunset. Graf wasn't getting any younger waiting in
the locker room Thursday, having turned the Big Three-Oh on June
14, days after she unmade Martina Hingis' psyche and summer in the
French Open final.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. No matter how Graf has reinvented herself after numerous
ailments and setbacks, that doesn't officially qualify her for the
30-and-Over club. These memberships are becoming increasingly rare.
The last time a 30-plus woman won a Grand Slam was in 1990, when
Navratilova won here, at 33. Evert's last Grand Slam victory was in
1986, at 31, in Paris. Jana Novotna, 29 when she broke through here
last year, Thursday looked like a tennis geriatric in her
straight-set surrender to Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Lendl was 30 when he won the Australian Open in 1990, as
was Andres Gomez, who that year won the French. The oldest
modern-era player to win a Grand Slam? Ken Rosewall was 37 when he
won the Australian in 1972, which is encouraging news for Patrick
Ewing more than it is for the modern male tennis star.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked Graf about outslinging a young gun, she
laughed and said, ``You're really on about this age thing, eh?''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added: ``I don't think very often about age. The body
tells me sometimes, but otherwise I go out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   She made a startling play in the ninth game of the final set,
charging clear across the court to bend low and lift the perfect
lob over a 6-foot-1-inch opponent who was poised for a volley. Graf
didn't win that game, but within minutes the chair umpire was
saying, ``Time,'' and the remaining fans cheered and Steffi Graf
stood tall and served herself out of a seven-hour ordeal. Then more
rain began to fall, and the ``tennis goddess'' went home to bed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
