<HEADER>
A6489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING02-COX     07-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. sets referendum on video poker for Nov.
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Voters in South Carolina will decide Nov. 2 whether
the state should keep more than 30,000 licensed video poker
machines, derided by critics as the ``crack cocaine'' of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   If voters decide to keep video poker, new laws would tax the
license holders 25 percent on their gross profits. Last year, video
poker made a gross profit of $729 million on total sales of $2.5
billion, according to reports the industry made to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, video poker will die June 30 next year.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, South Carolina makes $60 million off the games _ all
of that on license fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great we're finally recognized as a legitimate business,
legitimate enough to have regulations,'' said Fred Collins of
Greenville, whose company is a titan of the video gambling
industry. A recorded message for callers on hold tells potential
customers they can be instructed how to maximize ``every square
foot in your business.''
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous video poker machines are found in nearly every
convenience store, restaurant and bowling alley in the state.
Several operators run video malls dedicated exclusively to the
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entertainment,'' Collins said. ``They identify with the
video aspect of it. We grew up with television.''
</P>
<P>
   State legislators agreed on a ballot question in the wee hours
Thursday morning after the House had failed six times to pass the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   A key issue for gambling opponents is the daily payout. Current
law limits players to $125 a day per gambling session. The lower
the payout, the lower the temptation to play for long stretches,
opponents argue.
</P>
<P>
   But the law is ``widely'' flouted, said Frank Quinn, a Columbia
doctor who testified on the effects on video gambling before the
federally funded National Gambling Impact Study Commission. Two
players, he said, played every day for almost a month, pumping in
$20 a hand and hit a $22,000 jackpot. Gov. Jim Hodges, a Democrat
whose fall campaign received millions from the gambling industry,
vowed to reform what he called a ``video poker mess.''
</P>
<P>
   If residents vote to continue video poker, the limit would rise
to $500, which opponents said was tantamount to deregulation.
Hodges, among others, said the $125 ceiling was unenforceable. The
referendum would require license holders to plug their machines in
to state monitoring systems, which would check for violators.
Republicans considered the measure to be deregulatory but, despite
a slim majority in the House, couldn't block the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get it and this is the next best thing,'' said
Speaker David Wilkins, a Greenville Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, whose business generates more than $100 million a year
in video poker income, said the taxes threaten license holders. He
said people doing a marginal business with the machines already are
moving on to other things.
</P>
<P>
   An average machine generates $25,000 in gross profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that are against video poker are primarily the
politicians and the print media,'' Collins said. ``The general
public could care less. They say let me spend my dollars on
entertainment the way I choose, don't tell me what's good for me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
