<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOPOKER02-COX     07-01 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOPOKER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power to video poker machines cut off in Louisiana
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONZALES, La. _ At one minute before midnight Wednesday, Eula
Ordoyne was punching the plastic buttons of a video poker machine
at the Cajun Circus Casino, a truck stop east of Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   At one minute after midnight, she was staring at a black screen
where a message glowed in green letters: ``Temporarily out of
order: $0.00.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing temporary about the machine's shutdown.
More than 4,800 of Louisiana's 15,000 video poker machines went
dark and became illegal just after midnight Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 local elections, 33 of the state's 64 parishes voted to
outlaw video poker as of July 1, 1999. Despite numerous court
battles that stretched into Wednesday afternoon, the machines are
illegal in a patchwork of parishes around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling opponents are claiming a small victory. This is
believed to be the first time since legal gambling spread from Las
Vegas that any community has kicked it out once it became
entrenched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy they are turned off,'' said C.B. Forgotston, a New
Orleans attorney and a vocal gambling opponent. ``I would be much
happier if we had voted out poker in the entire state. But this is
a victory of historic proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   For regular customers and employees at the soon-to-be-closed
truck stop casinos, it was a somber night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' Ordoyne said. ``I come here two or three times a
week. I like the atmosphere, and I've won quite a bit. I've lost
more than I've won, but the odds are better here than in some
places. But I'll just go to another parish and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cajun Circus Casino _ a smoky room with 50 machines and a bar _
had a party for its regulars, with jambalaya and free drinks.
Employees hugged each other and said goodbye to favorite customers.
</P>
<P>
   The machines went dead despite several lawsuits and appeals to
the Legislature to keep the games going. Local governments, fearing
the loss of revenue, asked the Legislature for a new vote, but were
denied. The video poker industry went to court arguing that the
1996 vote was unfair because the Legislature barred the industry
from pooling resources to campaign. That law was struck down by the
state Supreme Court, but only 17 days before the election. The
industry says there was not enough time to mount a successful
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   No court would agree to stop the scheduled shut-off of the
machines, but state judges have agreed to hold hearings on the
claims in two lawsuits. One hearing is set for today. The U.S.
Supreme Court will decide in October whether to hear arguments in
yet another suit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, places like Cajun Circus must close. ``We put nine
people out of a job tonight,'' said Andrew Flood, director of
gaming for Silver Bear, which owns Cajun Circus and two other truck
stop video poker outlets. As of Thursday, only one of the three
remained open. ``And Ascension Parish is losing $1.4 million in
revenue from gaming here. This was important to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The machines remain legal in 31 parishes, including much of the
New Orleans metro area. Voters elected to keep the large riverboat
casinos in Baton Rouge, Lake Charles, Shreveport and outside New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Marcus, a supervisor at Cajun Circus, said she will move
to Port Allen, about 30 minutes away, to work at the remaining
Silver Bear casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here almost 10 years,'' she said. ``I have kids in
school here, but it's just too far a drive. We have to move.''
</P>
<P>
   The gamblers are losing one of their favorite hangouts. One
couple met and eventually got married in the casino, Flood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big disappointment,'' said Pete Weidlein, a traveling
salesman who stops here when he's in the area. He smoked a cigar
and greeted some friends as they walked to the bar. ``We still have
Indian casinos, riverboat casinos, and the lottery, but now many of
our local places are gone. This is where people meet and see each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   To gambling opponents, however, video poker is one of the more
insidious forms of gambling. Where they are legal, the machines are
everywhere, from truck stops to convenience stores, bars and
restaurants. In New Orleans, most people are within walking
distance of a video poker machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the crack cocaine of gambling,'' Forgotston said. ``It is
so pervasive and so readily available.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wednesday turned to Thursday, there were only a few
gamblers left inside Cajun Circus. Flood took a microphone and bid
farewell.
</P>
<P>
   A minute after midnight, the Louisiana State Police, using a
computer program in Baton Rouge, shut off 4,847 machines statewide.
</P>
<P>
   For those who didn't know when to fold 'em and walk away, a
ticket was issued so they could collect any earnings won before the
machines cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boom, that's it,'' Flood said with a sigh. ``It's as
anticlimactic as that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
