</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA DENIES IT IS IN TALKS WITH PAKISTAN ON KASHMIR CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ India is not involved in ``any negotiations''
and ``not even consultations'' with Pakistan, said Indian External
Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh on Thursday, rebutting speculation
in both nations that behind-the-scenes diplomacy was under way to
end the violent crisis in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Such speculation gained credence in the news media after former
Pakistani Foreign Minister Niaz Naik went to New Delhi on Sunday
and met with Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning to Islamabad, Naik said his visit had been a
private one, but then he spoke in the manner of an envoy in a
Tuesday interview on a BBC radio program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that a deal is in the offing, but efforts are
being made in that direction,'' he said, referring to measures that
might end the fighting between Indian troops and about 700 invaders
who have crossed the so-called Line of Control into India's side of
Kashmir. Those soldiers are holed up in bunkers well-concealed in
the rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   India asserts the interlopers are mostly Pakistani army regulars
aided by Islamic militants. Pakistan denies any part in the
incursion.
</P>
<P>
   During the radio program, Naik grew increasingly specific,
saying that he and Vajpayee had discussed having the two nations'
directors of military operations ``prepare a schedule of a
so-called withdrawal, the timing, and the methodology, et cetera,
and once that's done, if the two prime ministers can agree with the
time frame, the whole thing can be wrapped up as early as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, in an interview, said Naik's comments amounted to little
more than wishful thinking, that the former official had ``gone
back and given a certain interpretation of what he hopes, what he
wishes to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far as India is concerned, its position has been explicit:
the present escalation has been caused by armed intruders mounting
aggression from north of the Line of Control and the easiest way to
de-escalate it is for Pakistan to pull back the intruders,'' Singh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if some understanding could ever be reached about a
scheduled withdrawal, he answered, ``No understanding is required
about pulling back to where you have come from.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani response to any suggestion of an orchestrated
pullout has been equally acid. ``Withdraw from where?'' Zameer
Akram, a spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks of Singh, who is the guiding hand in India's foreign
policy, seem to indicate that seven weeks of intense fighting and,
by Thursday's count, 207 dead Indian soldiers have not brought New
Delhi toward any mood for conciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Indian battalions continue to launch painstaking attacks up the
forbidding mountains in efforts to wrest the invaders from places
whose names have in a short time become part of the nation's
vernacular: Tiger Hills, Tololing, Three Pimples.
</P>
<P>
   To date, India has kept its forces from crossing the Line of
Control, an act of restraint that has been applauded by the United
States and other nations, many of which have been open in blaming
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   These reins ``place us under grave military and tactical
handicaps,'' Singh said.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan, too, has been eager to win international support
during the crisis. Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif returned
from China late Wednesday after ``very productive'' meetings,
according to Pakistani Foreign Minister Shamshad Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
   However productive the sessions, a statement released Thursday
by China's Foreign Ministry pointedly refused to take sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sincerely hope that both India and Pakistan can earnestly
respect the Line of Control in Kashmir, resume negotiations as soon
as possible and seek a fair and reasonable settlement of all their
differences,'' it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
