<HEADLINE>
ACROSS A MOUNTAIN DIVIDE, INDIANS AND PAKISTANIS SPEAK WITH GUNS,
NOT WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT THE SHINGO RIVER, Pakistan _ The Pakistani and Indian
soldiers eye each other warily from observation posts on jagged
Himalayan mountain ridges that scratch across the soft blue sky
like an electrocardiogram.
</P>
<P>
   They are arrayed on either side of the so-called Line of Control
that divides the Pakistani- and Indian-held portions of the
disputed territory of Kashmir. For almost two months now, they have
been engaged in an ever-intensifying exchange of ear-splitting
artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
   They occupy one battleground in the armed conflict that has
embroiled these most hostile of neighbors since India accused
Pakistan of sneaking into Indian territory and occupying some of
the majestic peaks that tower over a crucial military supply line
just a few miles from here.
</P>
<P>
   The Pakistani and Indian soldiers are so close that they can
shout to each other across the dry stream bed that separates them.
But since this latest conflict over Kashmir _ a breathtakingly
beautiful place that both countries want _ the Pakistanis have only
called out once to the Indian side, and that was to say they had
the bodies of six Indian soldiers to hand over.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the only sounds that have echoed through the
mountain ranges are the booms of artillery and mortar fire, from
percussive explosions that sound like a fireworks finale to a deep
rumbling like thunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only guns are speaking now, not we,'' said Lt. Col. Nawaz
Herl, who commands a unit of 800 men here for the Pakistani army
along a 20-mile-long stretch of the Line of Control that is just
north of the worst of the fighting in Indian-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   His remark could just as well apply to the governments of India
and Pakistan as to the soldiers in this spot. Up to now, the
leaders of the two nations, which both became declared nuclear
powers a year ago, have found no common ground for resolving a
conflict that they fear could escalate to a wider war.
</P>
<P>
   India insists that Pakistan must withdraw the forces it says
Pakistan is supporting in Indian territory before any progress can
be made. But Pakistan denies that it has any control over the men
who are battling India for control of mountain peaks in the Kargil
and Dras sectors of Kashmir. Rather, Pakistan says, these men are
Muslim freedom fighters seeking Kashmir's right to
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread skepticism in Western capitals over
Pakistan's assertions, officers stationed here say their intense
shelling across the Line of Control into Indian territory is not
intended to provide cover for hundreds of holy warriors battling
thousands of Indian troops. Rather, the Pakistanis say, they have
more than tripled the number of rounds they fire each day in
retaliation against India's increasingly heavy pounding of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not assigned any task to assist the mujahideen,'' said
Herl, as a representative of the Pakistan army's public relations
office stood on the sidelines listening. Pakistan, an Islamic
state, only offers the Muslim warriors inside Kashmir its political
and diplomatic support, not its military might, Herl added.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani and Indian soldiers have been posted here on peaks
around the khaki-colored Shingo River since the early 1970s after
India and Pakistan signed a detailed series of maps that defined
the Line of Control following India's defeat of Pakistan in 1971 in
the third war that the two nations have fought.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Pakistani soldiers wearing jaunty berets loaded
artillery shells into cannon-like guns and fired into Indian
territory, shouting, ``God is Great'' with each blast.
</P>
<P>
   A little over a mile from here, in the tiny, impoverished hamlet
of Basal Chu, refugees from the shelling talked of their miseries.
Ten-year-old Ali Mohammed, playing with a group of raggedly dressed
boys, said mournfully, ``I used to go to school, but not anymore
because we left our village.''
</P>
<P>
   Men said the fighting has hurt their ability to earn a living by
harvesting the barley they grow on small, jewel-like terraced
plots.
</P>
<P>
   ``My village has been emptied because of heavy shelling by
Indian forces,'' said Mohammed Hussain. ``We didn't lose any men.
We holed up in caves. We were not able to cut our crops.'' He ran
away from his home in the village of Bethel to stay with relatives
in Basal Chu.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the shells have landed in Basal Chu's barley fields and
the river that shushes past it, but have not hit the homes that
cling to the mountainside. Herl said he sees little point in the
endless shelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fire is not of any much purpose, except destruction and
harassment,'' he said. But he blamed India for starting the
fighting, and said, ``Naturally, I have to respond. I have to give
a befitting reply.''
</P>
</TEXT>
