<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT SAYS HOLBROOKE IS LIKELY TO BE CONFIRMED DESPITE SNAGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Miss.)   (rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With at least three senators blocking a final vote
to confirm Richard Holbrooke as the chief American diplomat at the
United Nations, Senate majority leader Trent Lott said Thursday
that the nomination ``has some problems right now'' but that
Holbrooke was still likely to be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of only one of the senators blocking the nomination
is known publicly: Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who has said that
he will prevent a vote on Holbrooke's nomination until the State
Department resolves an unrelated dispute with an employee described
as a whistle-blower.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Lott, apparently referring to the move by
the senators to block a vote, said that Holbrooke ``has some
problems right now and we'll have to see how that works out.''
Asked if he believed Holbrooke would be confirmed eventually, he
replied, ``Eventually, I think he probably will be.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Mississippi Republican said that at least
two other senators had followed Grassley's lead on Wednesday in
requesting a hold on Holbrooke's long-stalled nomination. The
nomination had been approved by the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee on a voice vote only hours before.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, John Czwartacki, said he did not know the
identify of the other senators, nor their reasons for blocking a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate rules intended to encourage consensus, individual
senators can ask the majority leader to put a ``hold'' on a
nomination indefinitely. And they can ask that their identities not
be made public.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Clinton administration official said the administration
was unsure why lawmakers aside from Grassley had decided to block a
vote on the nomination but described the holds as the ``typical
horse-trading'' that comes before a congressional recess. The
Senate is expected to begin its July 4 recess on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of folks up there trying to break him loose,''
the official said of Holbrooke, adding that White House officials
``don't really know what's behind some of the holds that have been
put on him; they're not national security issues for the most
part.'' He said he suspected that lawmakers will try ``leveraging
Holbrooke for things they want in particular bills.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Grassley said the senator was insistent that
his hold will remain in place until the State Department reaches an
accommodation with Linda S. Shenwick, a budget analyst at the U.S.
mission to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shenwick, a $120,000-a-year lawyer, has said she is being
transferred out of her job in New York against her will because she
repeatedly leaked damaging information to members of Congress and
to reporters about waste and abuse at the United Nations and at the
American mission.
</P>
<P>
   The spokeswoman, Jill Kozeny, said that Grassley had received a
letter from the State Department this week in which the department
said that ``Senator Grassley should not be involved in the Shenwick
matter because a process is established to resolve it and is
currently under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shenwick has filed protests over her transfer with the Merit
Systems Protection Board, a federal agency that is supposed to
protect whistle-blowers.
</P>
</TEXT>
