<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magic continues with paperback `Midnight'
 &HT;    By Don O' Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after its publication in 1994, ``Midnight in the Garden
of Good and Evil'' went from being a book to a phenomenon. John
Berendt's Gothic tale of a Savannah murder in the midst of
eccentrics, drag queens and society folks sold 2.5 million copies
in hardback and set a record by staying on The New York Times
Bestseller List for 216 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It also spawned a Clint Eastwood film and a documentary and
boosted tourism in the city by an estimated 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the paperback edition of ``Midnight'' set to be
launched Tuesday during a daylong celebration in Savannah, Berendt
is still a little puzzled by his enormous success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to analyze it,'' Berendt said in a telephone interview
from his home in New York. ``Apart from the book itself, which I
think was a good story, it was the word of mouth. The promotability
of the characters and the city was very important. When you have
extraordinary characters who are living and who are willing to talk
to the press, and you have a great historic, American city _
beautiful, magical _ that the country is basically unaware of, then
they want to go there. That may be why the book became an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Books hopes the magic continues. The publisher has
printed 400,000 copies of ``Midnight'' in a $13 paperback edition
and is sending Berendt on yet another national tour. (He'll be at
Borders Books &AMP; Music in Buckhead at 7 p.m. July 19 to sign books
and meet fans.) After that, Berendt says, he will continue to
search for his next project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been researching some ideas without committing myself,''
he said. ``I'm still looking at a story I found in Venice. I'm not
sure whether it's a book or part of a book or a long article for
The New Yorker. It's along the lines of that great novella by Henry
James, `The Aspern Papers.' That was fiction, of course, and this
is nonfiction, but it's remarkably similar.''
</P>
<P>
   (In the James novella, an unscrupulous American editor is
obsessed with obtaining a dead poet's papers from his mistress by
seduction, deception, burglary or any other means.)
</P>
<P>
   Berendt admits that the success of ``Midnight'' looms large over
his choice for his next book, but he insists that that is not the
reason he hasn't started another project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most fun I had was the seven years it took me to write the
book. What happened since has been extremely rewarding, but that
book was a labor of love. I hope to find something else that does
the same. It would be foolhardy to go into the next book with the
idea that it would be another `Midnight.'''
</P>
<P>
   And what were his thoughts on the Eastwood movie, which bombed
with critics and moviegoers alike?
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it,'' he said. ``It bought me a townhouse in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   Repackaged Morrie: When Morrie Schwartz's book ``Letting Go''
was published in 1996, it sold 6,000 copies. A respectable number,
but not a best seller by any means. So why is Walker &AMP; Co.
reissuing the book with a new title _ ``Morrie: In His Own Words''
_ and a new cover? Well, because Morrie is now famous. Schwartz, a
professor who died of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's
disease), is the subject of Mitch Albom's best seller, ``Tuesdays
With Morrie.'' The book of reminiscences with Schwartz about his
philosophy of life and his views on death has sold nearly 1.9
million copies and occupies the No. 2 spot on The New York Times
Bestseller List. Walker &AMP; Co., counting on the popularity of
Albom's book to boost sales, has printed 30,000 copies of ``Morrie:
In His Own Words.''
</P>
<P>
   Revisiting a sex symbol: Marilyn Monroe has been the subject of
numerous biographies and photographic books, but now the film
legend will be the central character in a novel by Joyce Carol
Oates. Scheduled for publication in April by HarperCollins' Ecco
Press, ``Blonde'' is described as a fact-based fictional account of
Monroe's relationships with the Kennedys, Joe DiMaggio and Arthur
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   More ``GWTW'': Fans of ``Gone With the Wind'' can read even more
about the movie this fall when Herb Bridges, an author and
collector of items relating to the book and film, comes out with
``Gone With the Wind: The Three-Day Premiere in Atlanta.'' The
Georgian's book will focus on Dec. 13-15, 1939, when Atlanta was
invaded by Hollywood. The photographic essay includes Clark Gable,
Vivien Leigh and other stars, as well as Atlantans who turned out
for the premiere and the grand ball.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O' Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
