<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYTONA-TOURISM02-COX     07-01 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTONA-TOURISM02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida tourism back after costly '98 fires
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The thick black clouds hovered on the
horizon before splitting suddenly, dumping torrents of rain that
sent tourists dashing for cover.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody here was complaining.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, everyone was praying for rain as the worst outbreak
of wildfires in Florida's history turned one of the summer's most
lucrative months into a smoke-shrouded tourist no-show.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 crisis climaxed the July Fourth weekend with the
cancellation of the Pepsi 400 stock car race at Daytona
International Speedway, wiping out an event that annually attracts
more than 250,000 free-spending race fans. Worried officials shut
down a 125-mile stretch of Interstate 95 and evacuated an entire
county as thousands of exhausted firefighters struggled to contain
the blazes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, hoteliers and merchants are relieved to report that
the summer rains _ and the stock-car racing fans _ are back.
``We're back to normal with a lot of people in town,'' said Patrick
Welsh, owner of the Beach House motel. ``That's good, because last
year we more or less lost July, and normally that's our busiest
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments are echoed around town, where the memory of
1998's disaster still lingers in the minds _ and pocketbooks _ of
many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was going great for the first six months,'' said
Darrell Hunter, a city commissioner who runs a bar and arcade on
the beachfront boardwalk. ``But I dropped 80 percent in July, and
you just can't get that back. You can never make that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's normally dry winter and spring turned as arid as
Arizona in 1998. Temperatures hit record levels, with unheard-of
highs in the 90s in April and May and triple digits in June.
</P>
<P>
   By June, hundreds of wildfires sparked by lightning or arsonists
raged from the Panhandle to the Everglades, although large areas
were spared.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida's Atlantic coast was hit hardest. Blazes raced
through the timberlands, threatening and, at times engulfing, new
housing developments sold to buyers attracted by the forested
landscape. The firefighting army came perilously close to losing a
major battle when three large fires converged just north of Daytona
Beach in late June. Gov. Lawton Chiles closed I-95 from
Jacksonville south to Titusville, and ordered Flagler County's
40,000 residents out of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really frightening,'' said Daytona Beach shopkeeper Avi
Nachmani, who saw sales at his T-shirt store plummet. ``It really
killed our business. There was smoke everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The crisis passed in mid-July as firefighters managed to contain
the most dangerous blazes. Slowly the dry weather pattern broke and
afternoon deluges returned _ although lightning from the storms
continued to spark new fires.
</P>
<P>
   Race officials rescheduled the Pepsi 400 to October, allowing
merchants to recoup some of their losses. But many reported they
lost business anyway, as families weren't able to take kids out of
school for an October vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a year later, some businesses are still feeling lingering
effects from the fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't booking ahead like they normally do,'' said Jody
Kinberger, whose family owns the 20-room Dream Inn. ``They're
waiting until the last minute to make sure nothing happens like
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest casualties of fire-scared 1998 was the
fireworks business, which normally rings up a Fourth of July
bonanza. Officials outlawed the sale of all fireworks during the
crisis, and towns across the state canceled their displays out of
fear of sparking new blazes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it was like closing the mall the week before
Christmas,'' said Pat Moran, who manages Phantom Fireworks in
Daytona Beach. ``But fortunately this year we've had plenty of
rain. We're gearing up for the mad rush.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
