<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGON-CON02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yes, DragonCon's cultists anything but conventional
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a meeting room on the lowest level of the Hyatt
Regency on Thursday, two kids were playing dueling Jedi knights
with imaginary light sabers. ``Tchoo! Tchoo!'' went young Jedi Nick
Mimms, a 10-year-old from Tucker, mimicking the sound of clashing
``Star Wars'' weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the lobby, George Lukach had a real saber, and a
real plumed hat, and a leather vest, and everything else the
well-dressed musketeer is wearing to DragonCon '99, the enormous
fantasy convention and festival running in downtown Atlanta through
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Normally an assistant manager at a Barnes &AMP; Noble in Norwalk,
Ct., Lukach is 35 but was enjoying his play-acting every bit as
much as Nicholas. When women approached for a posed photo, Lukach
would bend to one knee and chivalrously kiss an outstretched hand
while Instamatics flashed.
</P>
<P>
   DragonCon is almost literally its own universe, a black hole
that sucks in everything in pop culture that has ever been labeled
``cult following,'' populated by people who put the fan in fanatic.
It's ``Star Wars'' and ``Star Trek,'' Pokemon and ``Xena,'' comic
books and the Internet, Monty Python and Austin Powers, ``Buffy''
buffs and fairy worshippers, Dungeons &AMP; Dragons and GWAR, a
high-camp, high-decibel rock band that plays ``Carnival of Chaos''
at midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the biggest (fantasy conventions) in the
country, because it's not just one thing, like just 'Star Wars' or
just comic books,'' said Cindy Haverfield of Bloomington, Ind.
``Everybody and his brother comes to DragonCon.'' Haverfield was
selling swords and knives at her booth, the Dragon's Claw, and had
a small metal dragon peeking out of her cleavage.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Kramer, chairman of DragonCon, who has a black beard so bushy
an Ewok could hide in it, says 40,000 fans are expected this year.
Admission is $25 for a one-day pass and $60 for a four-day pass.
Registration is in the Hyatt Regency, and the ever-growing festival
sprawls between the hotel (home of panel discussions and guest
speakers like revered sci-fi writer Anne McCaffrey) and the Atlanta
Apparel Mart's Exhibit Hall (home of miles of aisles of stuff for
sale, from ``Twin Peaks'' posters in Spanish to Dr. Who dolls).
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother has been going for five years, and I'm tired of him
rubbing my face in all the cool people he's met,'' said Emily
Livingston, a 15-year-old sophomore from Douglasville (GA.). She
sported a sprinkling of face glitter, a curly swirl of blue
eyeliner out to one temple and a Sailor Moon T-shirt. Her friend
Amber Sloan, checking out a huge display of comic books with Emily,
wore a small button that read ``Free Your Inner Alien.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of author McCaffrey, who rarely makes convention
appearances, is one of the big buzzes this year. Also appearing are
three stars of the ``Batman'' TV series: Adam West (Batman), Yvonne
Craig (Batgirl) and Frank Gorshin (the Riddler.)
</P>
<P>
   ``After the costume party Saturday night, that's when it really
gets pretty wild,'' said Lara Putnam, who drove to Atlanta from
Phenix City, Ala., to put on a wig and an enormous blue ball gown
and pretend to be ``Morgana Firehair,'' an Irish sorceress based on
a Dungeons &AMP; Dragons character. Identity can be a shaky concept
sometimes at DragonCon _ ``What's your real name?'' is something
heard among people meeting in the Hyatt Regency lobby _ and the
idea of being in and/or out of costume is rarely a simple one for
many of the fans in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban moms in Disney World T-shirts wheel kids in strollers
past guys with multiple piercings and Charles Manson T-shirts.
Claire Gray of Venice, Fla., is her own creation, ``Drama Queen'' _
white mask, cardboard crown and homemade red velvet robe. There are
men in vinyl pants and makeup; a woman in fairy wings and elf-ears;
bustiers, fishnet stockings, lace-up boots, Goth-punk crossover and
a black T-shirt that reads, ``I'm Not Shy, I'm Just Studying My
Prey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mainly just come to people-watch,'' said Lukach, the
musketeer in the lobby. In his 18th-century rig, he seemed like a
man from another time. But one in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Website: http://www.dragoncon.org.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   DragonCon 1999
</P>
<P>
   Through Sunday. $25 per day ($20 on Sunday). Register 8 a.m.-11
p.m. at Hyatt Regency Atlanta, 265 Peachtree St. N.E.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more information: www.ajc.com/links
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
