<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old trick speeds lighthouse relocation
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Cape Hatteras Lighthouse is moving at the speed of
slippery soap.
</P>
<P>
   On the black and white-striped beacon's unexpectedly rapid
journey inland to safety, workers are using bars of Ivory soap to
grease the steel tracks along which the lighthouse is moving.
</P>
<P>
   Bar soap is handy, of course, on stubborn zippers and squeaky
kitchen drawers. House movers have used it for years to slide
buildings onto truck trailers.
</P>
<P>
   On North Carolina's Outer Banks, moving officials credit the old
trick with helping speed the lighthouse past the halfway point in
its 2,900-foot trip away from crashing Atlantic waves.
</P>
<P>
   The 128-year-old lighthouse is now beyond the oceanfront dunes
that would be vulnerable to overwashing by waves during a
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is moving so well with the Ivory soap as a lubricant
that it almost rolls itself,'' said Randy Knott, chief engineer
with Atlanta-based Law Engineering and Environmental Services Inc.,
the lead engineering consultant on the lighthouse project.
</P>
<P>
   The steel track's beams are so slippery, Knott said, that the
4,800-ton lighthouse has had a tendency to roll backward in its
slightly uphill trip, until it is braced by hydraulic jacks.
</P>
<P>
   Initially crews planned to use a graphite-based dry lubricant.
Officials feared that sand would blow onto the sun-softened soap,
creating friction between the steel beams and the steel rollers on
top of which the lighthouse is riding.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't been a problem, and officials aren't sure why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know whether it is the heat or humidity or what, but
we are not getting sand on the rollers,'' said Joe Jakubik, project
manager for International Chimney Corp., the project's contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The 108-foot-tall landmark's $11.8 million rescue has gone so
smoothly that officials are predicting it will arrive at its new
foundation about July 10.
</P>
<P>
   When the move started June 17, officials said the trip would
take four to six weeks, with hydraulic jacks pushing the tower 70
to 100 feet a day. But some days the lighthouse has traveled more
than 200 feet, cutting its travel time by a week or more. It is
scheduled to reopen to the public Memorial Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Expert House Movers, a subcontractor, has saved time in the way
it resets the hydraulic jacks, Knott said. The jacks push the
lighthouse along the steel tracks for a distance of 5 feet, at a
virtually imperceptible speed of 1 to 2 inches a minute. At that
point, the jacks move forward for the next 5-foot move, and
hydraulic plates hold them in place.
</P>
<P>
   Expert House Movers had planned to carry out that process
manually, a time-consuming effort requiring workers to unbolt and
rebolt the jacks to the steel tracks. ``It is now a tremendously
efficient process,'' Knott said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
