<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton gives Hillary
Rodham Clinton the green light to publicly disagree with White
House policies in her bid to become the next senator from New York.
The president's remarks come amid mounting political pressure in
New York for the first lady to distance herself from provisions of
the Clinton administration's latest Medicare overhaul. By STEWART
M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
campaigns in the capital of high technology, telling computer
industry executives that he supports permanent tax credits for
research and development, and says he backs raising the cap on the
number of skilled workers who could immigrate to the United States.
By R.G. RATCLIFFE. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUSH (Washington) _ President Clinton, referring to the
record $36 million Texas Gov. George W. Bush collected in four
months, suggests he Bush will be hostile to campaign finance reform
if the Republican candidate decides not to seek matching funds. He
also discounts any tension with Vice President Al Gore. By NANCY
MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EGYPT (Washington) _ President Clinton and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak say they see new opportunities for peace in
the Middle East as Israel establishes a government more open to
negotiations. But Mubarak urges Israel's new leader, Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak, to stop expansion of Jewish settlements.
By NANCY MATHIS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUTS (Washington) _ Armed with new forecasts of a growing
budget surplus, House Republican leaders unveil a tax-cut package
that would lower federal income rates across-the-board and give
married couples a tax break. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-KILLER (Washington) _ Saying that ``something got
screwed up,'' a Justice Department official says that immigration
officers failed to detain accused killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez
last month even though the police in Houston had told federal
agents that the man was a murder suspect. By MARK HELM. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-HEARING (Washington) _ A federal judge implies that he
will allow taped telephone conversations to be used as evidence
against former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros when the
government's conspiracy case goes to trial after Labor Day. By GARY
MARTIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Houston) _ The Texas Supreme Court rules
that a Houston anti-affirmative action activist can sue the city
for changing the wording on a ballot initiative designed to end
preferences. Edward Blum and the Houston Civil Rights Initiative
accused the city of trying to ensure the defeat of the referendum.
The case heads back to the trial court, which has already indicated
it would declare the election void. By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ In a decision that could renew
debate over the legal fees in the state's settlement with the
tobacco companies, the Texas Supreme Court rules that lawyers who
commit ethical violations can be required to forfeit all or part of
their fees, even if their clients aren't harmed. The ruling stems
from a $190 million settlement of claims from a 1989 chemical plant
explosion. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-LIABILITY (Austin, Texas) _ An injury from a fraternity
game of paintball has led to a court ruling that may mean the
sponsors of sporting events for children can be held liable for
injuries incurred on amateur fields all over Texas. By CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MARINES (Gnjlane, Yugoslavia) _ Struggling to make their
section of Kosovo safe for both returning ethnic Albanian refugees
and the frightened Serbian minority, the U.S. Marines who arrived
here less than two weeks ago are coping with guns, with people who
carry guns, and with people who fear guns. It is not an easy task.
By RICHARD MERTENS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-ACQUISITIONS (New York) _ The Hearst Corporation has
acquired three weekly newspaper companies in the Albany, N.Y.,
area. The newspaper companies are The Advertiser, in Rensselaer
County, The Journal Newspapers, in Saratoga County and The
Pennysaver, based in Saratoga County. The three companies will now
comprise the new Capital Region Weekly Newspaper Group, a division
of Hearst Newspapers. Hearst also publishes the daily Times Union
in Albany. By The Hearst Newspapers. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ With Texas Gov. George W. Bush awash
in an astounding $36 million in campaign cash after only four
months of fund-raising, the question arises: can this be too much
of a good thing? There is a danger that he may look as though he is
buying the election. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON (Wimbledon, England) _ In quarterfinal action at
the Wimbledon tennis championships, rain wreaks havoc with the
schedule and has organizers looking at possibly extending the
tournament until Monday. By DALE ROBERTSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ In their final home game before the
All-Star break, the Houston Astros fail to complete a three-game
sweep by losing to the St. Louis Cardinals 10-4 in the Astrodome.
By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-RURAL (Washington) _ To win back the House in 2000,
Democrats will have to rely on Democratic anti-abortion and pro-gun
conservatives running in rural districts that were fertile
Republican turf for decades. This strategy, which helped Democrats
chip away at the GOP majority in 1998, was thrown into doubt
recently when a prominent Democrat, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I.,
said the party had ``written off the rural areas'' in 2000. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TUITION-REVOLT (Mexico City) _ Wearing camouflage
fatigues, his waist-long hair in a ponytail and a Fu Manchu
mustache offsetting dark eyes, Ivan Alcantar, 24, looks the part of
a moody young revolutionary. Since April 20, the history and
philosophy major has been part of a student strike that began over
plans to charge tuition at the National Autonomous University of
Mexico, the largest in Latin America with nearly 270,000 students.
By SUSANA HAYWARD. (Already filed.)
</P>
