<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DENIES TENSIONS WITH GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Mad at Al Gore? Whatever gave you that idea?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Thursday that he was ``bewildered'' by
reports of personal and political friction between him and the vice
president but said there were bound to be disagreements between
them on matters of policy as the presidential campaign unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   The president was responding to recent accounts of tension
between the two men over Gore's efforts to distance himself from
the president's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Aides and advisers to Clinton said he was angered and hurt by
the apparent zeal with which Gore has disavowed the president's
personal conduct. Clinton knows he did wrong with Ms. Lewinsky and
does not need to be reminded of it by the vice president, one close
Clinton adviser said in an interview with The New York Times last
week. Another adviser described Clinton as ``livid'' at Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asked Clinton about the accounts at a news conference
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly do not know what the source of the stories are,''
Clinton said. ``But they are not in my heart or my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He praised Gore's announcement for the presidency two weeks ago
and said the vice president was doing a good job of explaining what
he would do if he were elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I want him to get out there,'' the president said.
``And if he disagrees with a decision that I make as president
during the next year and a half, then, of course he will have to
say so. And I will take no offense at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, while disclaiming any role as a ``political
handicapper,'' said that Gore's rival for the Democratic
nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley, had shown an impressive
ability to raise money but had not put forward any ideas about how
he would govern the country. Bradley raised about $11 million for
his campaign in the first six months of the year; Gore brought in
more than $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he didn't intend his remarks as a ``dig'' at
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has said himself that he has not laid out his case for
being president,'' Clinton said. ``I am not `digging' him; I have
nothing bad to say about him. That is a fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I personally have always believed that you should begin by
saying why you want the job because you are asking people to hire
you to do things _ and I think the vice president deserves a lot of
credit for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then went on to list Gore's qualifications for the
presidency, including service in Congress and in the executive
branch, expertise on foreign policy and arms control matters and
``vast experience'' on domestic policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides that,'' Clinton said with a laugh, ``he's been a
journalist _ the vice president! You've got to think that counts
for something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
