</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCA-COLA-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA ANNOUNCES PARTIAL RECALL IN POLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.) (rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following the discovery of mold inside one batch of glass
bottles earlier this week, the Coca-Cola Co. is recalling all of
its soft drinks in the same-sized bottles in Poland, the company
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The recall affects an estimated 170,000 cases of Coca-Cola,
Coca-Cola Light, Fanta and Kinley tonic water, as well as Bonaqua
mineral water, where the problem was originally noticed in 0.33
liter bottles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mold was discovered first in Bonaqua, but it turns out
it's in the bottles,'' said Rob Baskin, a Coke spokesman in
Atlanta. There have been no reports of illness.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bottles were in warehouses when the recall began, he
said. Still, about 25 percent of them had to be retrieved from
stores and other places that stocked them. ``It's largely in the
hotel, cafe and restaurant trade,'' Baskin said. The recall affects
about 12 percent of the Coke soft drinks sold in Poland, he added,
and the recalled bottles will be replaced with plastic bottles.
</P>
<P>
   The company that bottles Coke products for the Polish market is
Coca-Cola Beverages, which last month said it would merge with
Hellenic Bottling, a longtime Coke bottler based in Athens, Greece.
The merger would create the second-largest bottler in the Coke
system. The largest is Coca-Cola Enterprises, which has
responsibility for Belgium, France, the Netherlands and Luxembourg,
where Coca-Cola had the biggest recall in company history last
month after hundreds of people reported feeling ill after drinking
Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of in shock that all these things are happening
simultaneously,'' said Caroline Levy, a beverage analyst for
Schroder &AMP; Co., who lowered her second-quarter earnings estimates
for Coca-Cola to 39 cents from 41 cents on Thursday. ``It's a blow
to the brand equity, at least in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said Wednesday that the recalls in Europe reduced
second-quarter sales by 1 percent to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coke products are to begin appearing again on Belgian store
shelves Friday, the company said. It will be four to six weeks
before products are as widely available as they were before the
government-ordered recall, which removed and destroyed 15 million
cases of soft drinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
