<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-TAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR STILL LOOKING FOR A CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Taylor was home Thursday, his first day of free agency,
patiently awaiting to hear about his future. Boston? Still a
possibility. But with 27 other National Hockey League teams in the
mix, there are many possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't talked to my agent yet,'' said Taylor, reached in
the afternoon by telephone, ``but we've heard there are a few teams
interested. I've heard Rangers, and a few others, too . . . but I'm
going to leave all that to my agent.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Taylor, he wants to sign a three- or four-year
pact, be it in Boston or elsewhere. He can't pinpoint the money,
but suspects it will be between $1 million per year at the low end
and twice that at the high.
</P>
<P>
   ``My No. 1 priority is to come back to Boston,'' said Taylor,
the pivot in the Bruins' checking line, with wingers Rob DiMaio and
P.J. Axelsson. ``But I think, given the situation, I have to look
at all options.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is this: Taylor made $675,000 last year, which is
approximately 50 percent below the league's average pay. Given that
he is a 10-year pro, making less than the league average, as of
12:01 a.m. Thursday he became a Group 5 free agent _ free to cut a
deal anywhere, with the Bruins retaining no right to match the
offer or receive compensation if he were to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other clubs are going to talk to him,'' said Bruins president
Harry Sinden. ``I've talked to some of those clubs myself, and I'm
sure they're asking themselves what we did: can they afford to pay
a checking center much more than he's already making?''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins recently made Taylor a one-year offer with a 10
percent raise over last season, a standard qualifying offer for
someone of his age (30) and with his time in the league. He didn't
respond to the offer and the sides haven't negotiatied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand it, really,'' said Taylor. ``Maybe they
want to see what the market is . . . I'm kind of at a loss to know
what they're thinking. I'd hoped we would have had something done
by now, but maybe they didn't want to outbid themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bruins have made plans to move forward without
three other veterans, including forward Ken Baumgartner and
defensemen Grant Ledyard and Dave Ellett.
</P>
<P>
   Baumgartner had one year left on his deal, worth $675,000 for
the 1999-2000 season, as did Ellett ($1.6 million). Cutting them
free will save the club approximately $760,000. Ledyard, who made
$750,000 last season, did not have a deal in place for the upcoming
season. All three now are free to sign elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sinden, coach Pat Burns, who in general favors
veterans over inexperienced players, was not troubled by the roster
moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat suggested part way through the year that I ask waivers on
Ellett, because he wasn't using him much,'' said Sinden. ``We did
that, and he cleared. He likes both (Baumgartner and Ellett) a lot,
and feels they're the kind of character players he needs on the
team. We're going to lose that now, and the question is, do we have
the people to sustain it? They're both excellent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Up front, the Bruins will look to the likes of Shawn Bates Eric
Nickulas, Landon Wilson, and perhaps a couple of other Providence
Bruins, Marquis Mathieu and Andre Savage, to fill the Baumgartner
and perhaps Taylor voids.
</P>
<P>
   In back, they have Mattias Timander ready to plug in to Ellett's
spot and will audition Jonathan Girard, their top pick in the '98
draft. If signed, Nick Boynton, their top choice in last Saturday's
draft, also would get ample opportunity in September's training
camp to fill Ellett's job.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Bruins continue to emphasize youth. After bottoming
out in the 1996-97 season, they've restructured their club around
the draft, which costs less and, they believe, pays bigger
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden sounded doubtful that the Bruins will extend offers to
any of the high-profile free agents, the most intriguing of whom is
Theo Fleury, the electrifying forward who finished the season with
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scared away by the $8 million or $9 million a year he's
looking for,'' said Sinden, referring to Fleury. ``I'd be very
surprised if we did anything, but I'll talk to Pat (Burns) and get
his input on a couple of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendel Clark and Dave Andreychuk, both of whom played for Burns
in Toronto, are unrestricted free agents. Sinden said he'll talk to
Burns about both. If either wanted to come to work for, say, a low
base salary and performance bonuses, then something could be worked
out here in the Hub of Hockey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baumgartner figured he had a day of reckoning coming with the
Bruins. ``But I expected that would be at the end of September, in
training camp,'' he said. ``Neither Dave (Ellett) or myself
expected to be bought out.'' The Bomber has a few options: 1. find
another playing job; 2. play in Switzerland (he played there years
ago and still has a Swiss passport); 3. apply to business school;
4. explore opportunities with the NHL Players Association . . .
Sinden said the club explored trade opportunities for Dmitri
Khristich during Saturday's draft at the Vault. ``We tried a number
of scenarios,'' he said. ``But nothing so far. Everyone tells me
what a good player he is, but no one wants him. And he is a good
player, but you just never know how he'll play on a given night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
