<HEADLINE>
GOP OUTLINES TAX CUTS AMID PROJECTED BUDGET SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans beat the drum Thursday for
cutting capital gains, inheritance and income taxes, a package
Democrats criticize as favoring the wealthy and harmful to critical
federal programs such as health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leadership outlined a proposal to cut government revenue
an estimated $1 trillion over the next decade as the Congressional
Budget Office reported that the federal budget surplus over the
next 10 years will total $996 billion _ not counting Social
Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO report, which shows trends similar to forecasts earlier
this week by the administration's Office of Management and Budget,
says the budget surplus over the next decade will total $2.9
trillion when Social Security surpluses are included.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason for this surplus is because taxpayers are
paying too much, which is why they deserve a refund,'' said Rep.
Bill Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee and
chief architect of the GOP's proposed tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a fife and drum band, Archer and about 60 GOP lawmakers
marched out of the Capitol behind Speaker Dennis Hastert, crossed
Independence Avenue and filed into a House office building where
the Ways and Means Committee Room had been decorated with red,
white and blue balloons, and rows of U.S. flags.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans denounced President Clinton's plans for spending
the $1 trillion surplus, although the president said he would
discuss a tax cut. Then, they outlined their plan to cut tax rates
across the board and provide relief from estate taxes, capital
gains taxes and the so-called ``marriage penalty'' paid by
two-income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't cut taxes now and the money stays in Washington,
the politicians surely will spend it,'' said Archer, R-Texas, whose
tax-cut plan also would increase the amount people could contribute
to Individual Retirement Accounts and would extend soon-to-expire
business tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the largest surplus in history,'' Hastert said, a
small U.S. flag hanging from his breast pocket. ``As we commit
ourselves to finding ways to secure our retirement programs, we
also commit ourselves to bringing fairness to the tax code.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on earlier budget-surplus forecasts, Republicans had
agreed to push for $778 billion in tax cuts over the next 10 years.
With the higher, revised estimates by the CBO and the
administration's Office of Management and Budget earlier this week,
Archer and the conservative House leadership decided to boost their
proposed tax-cut package.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the details are fleshed out, Archer's expanded tax
package drew fire from Democrats who want to increase spending on
education and defense after securing long-term funding for Medicare
and Social Security. In addition, the sheer size of the
trillion-dollar bottom line of Archer's proposed tax cut faces
problems from the White House, the Senate and moderate House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., called the plan
``totally irresponsible and misplaced in terms of its goals''
because it does not attack the national debt and would not put
additional money into education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really have left out the important priorities that we
ought to be dealing with,'' Gephardt told reporters. ``We do need a
tax cut. It can be far less expensive than this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Democrats have proposed tax reductions, but not
across the board. ``It's a responsible tax cut. It's targeted to
middle-class families. (The Republican's) trillion-dollar tax cut
is designed primarily for the wealthy,'' Gephardt said. ``We don't
think that's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat's tax-cut plan, similar to one proposed by
President Clinton earlier this year, includes targeted tax cuts
such as a $1,000 credit for taxpayers who care for a disabled
family member and a $500 credit for parents who care for infants at
home. The Democrat's package would total about $300 billion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, director of the president's National Economic
Council, said the White House would not support parts of the
Republican plan, such as the capital gains tax cut, which favors
upper-income Americans who can afford to invest in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tax cut that helps more moderate families increase their
personal savings rates is a far-higher priority,'' Sperling said.
``We have no intention at this time of supporting a new capital
gains tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton remains open to negotiating a cut in taxes once
the future of Social Security and Medicare are guaranteed and the
national debt is factored into any plan for spending the projected
surplus. ``Within the framework of achieving these objectives,
obviously I'll be working with the Congress to achieve them,''
Clinton said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch Wednesday, moderate Republican House members
cautioned Hastert that they could not support basing the fattened
tax package on the improved budget-surplus projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do a tax cut, you're going to have to live with the
consequences of that,'' said Rep. Michael N. Castle, R-Del., a
leader of the House moderates, regardless of whether the
projections come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have a very large tax cut,'' Castle said, referring
to the $778 billion tax package previously agreed to by
Republicans. ``My own personal vote is we should not increase the
tax cut at all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
