<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATORS FOCUS ON REACHING ARMS COMPROMISE BY FRIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Frustrated yet again in their attempt to break the
political stalemate here, the British and Irish governments said
they will make one final push Friday to fashion a compromise that
would revive the stalled peace process in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   While Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican
Army, pledged to get the IRA to disarm, the Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble insisted he needed the IRA to make a statement
promising to turn in its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The offer by Sinn Fein to guarantee that the IRA would disarm
was widely seen as a major shift in principle, but unionists
dismissed it as an empty promise. Unionists demanded that Sinn Fein
put the promise in writing, something Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
said was not possible because of ``the delicate nature of these
negotiations.'' After the talks adjourned Thursday night, however,
Sinn Fein released a written declaration to undertake disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Amid recrimination on both sides, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, said they would wrap
up their weeklong effort to save the Good Friday Agreement before
Saturday. Blair had insisted the final deadline was two days ago,
but government officials said the two leaders believed there was
enough chance of success to extend the deadline to Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, government officials said a long-awaited report will be
released Friday on whether disarming of paramilitary groups,
including the IRA, is possible. The report by John de Chastelain, a
retired Canadian general, had been delayed since Monday while Blair
and Ahern tried to get a deal between Sinn Fein and the unionists.
</P>
<P>
   The peace process has been stalled, and the Good Friday
Agreement threatened, by a long-running dispute between Sinn Fein
and the Ulster Unionists, the largest party in Northern Ireland.
Unionists refuse to allow the formation of a power-sharing
government with Sinn Fein until the IRA begins turning in its
weapons. Sinn Fein says their participation in government is not
linked under the Good Friday Agreement to disarming, which is
supposed to follow the creation of the 12-member cabinet to
administer local government.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern have sought to find a compromise to the dispute,
which threatens to kill the agreement they brokered last year,
ushering in the most peaceful period in Northern Ireland in 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   As London handed power back to local parliaments in Wales and
Scotland Thursday, Blair tried desperately to do the same in
Northern Ireland. The devolution of power to local assemblies is a
major aim of Blair's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Blair canceled plans to attend the opening of the Scottish
parliament in Edinburgh to remain here overseeing negotiations,
demonstrating the commitment to finding a settlement in Northern
Ireland that has been his biggest domestic priority since taking
office in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Blair reconvened the negotiations at Castle Buildings on the
grounds of Stormont in East Belfast by proclaiming there had been
``huge progress,'' despite the stalemate that had led him and Ahern
to work beyond the ``absolute final'' deadline he had set for
midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern suggested the parties were close to agreement, and that
only a few more hours were needed. But his prediction proved overly
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The two protagonists _ Sinn Fein and the Ulster Unionists, who
represent middle-class Protestants _ began the day by accusing each
other of being disingenuous. Trimble insisted that his party had
received no formal offer by Sinn Fein committing itself to disarm
the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   But while admitting he had not written down Sinn Fein's offer
because of the sensitivity of the arms issue among IRA activists,
Adams said the unionists were lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rejected our proposals hours before the deadline,'' Adams
said. ``We have moved our position, and it has not only been
rejected but misrepresented.''
</P>
<P>
   While Trimble is said to be demanding guns up front to hold off
mass defections from his own party, Adams said that agreeing to
work actively for disarming the IRA created ``huge difficulties''
for Sinn Fein within its own constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said unionists were using weapons as a smokescreen. He
said several of the unionist negotiators were opposed to the Good
Friday Agreement and were trying to wreck it by making the arms
dispute unresolvable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about guns,'' he said. ``This is about those who
are against change. We have met with a negotiating team that
includes people who are against what they are supposed to be
negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair said all parties had said they were committed to forming a
power-sharing government, and bringing about the disarmament of
paramilitary groups. But he said the manner of disarming would be
left to the commission headed by de Chastelain.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said the gestures being made by unionists and republicans
amounted to ``historic, seismic shifts in the political
landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the governments were ``prepared to give legislative
backing'' to sanctions that would be applied if unionists balked at
sharing power or the IRA balked at disarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``If decommissioning doesn't happen, they are out,'' he said of
Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   But, seeking to reassure nationalists, Blair insisted that
unionists do not hold a veto over progress in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire civilized world won't understand if we can't put
this together and make it work,'' said Blair. ``This is the thread
by which the future of Northern Ireland hangs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern said it would be ``unforgivable'' to let the peace process
unravel over the timing of the formation of a power-sharing
government and disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has been in telephone contact with party
leaders, agreed, saying, ``It is a very difficult problem for the
parties, but it will be very hard for the world to understand if
this breaks off. To call it a tragedy would be a great
understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke with Adams by telephone Thursday, had been
briefed on Sinn Fein's plan to seek IRA disarmament on May 5, when
Sinn Fein chief negotiator Martin McGuinness visited Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
