</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BANDS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sydney Olympics officials renege on invitation to high school
bands
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett and Diane Stepp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than 400 metro Atlanta student musicians have
been counting on being part of the 2000 Olympics' opening ceremony,
but Australian national pride may have shattered their travel
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic organizing officials in Sydney decided against including
1,500 American and Japanese amateur musicians in a U.S.-style
marching band after Australian citizens protested, the leaders of
two Georgia high school bands have been informed via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Students from Walton High School in Cobb County and Fayette
County High School wereto perform before 115,000 people _ and a
television audience of more than 1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The two bands were the only ones from Georgia participating, and
joint rehearsals were to begin next month for the September 2000
event.
</P>
<P>
   Then came an e-mail from World Projects Corp. of California,
contracted by Sydney officials to recruit the musicians. The
message was that there was a problem ``and it looks like we can't
go,'' said Mike Back, Walton's band director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shocking,'' he said. ``The minister of the Olympics,
because of pressure from the Australian people, evidently decided
not to use foreigners. Our parents are concerned and the kids are
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the Sydney Morning Herald, the director of
ceremonies said he wanted to create a band that would play while
athletes marched. ``He wanted people aged 18 to 21 who could
perform theatrically and march to set patterns, and the U.S. was
the only place where they were available in large numbers,'' the
article said.
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper article quoted a musicians union official, John
McAuliffe. saying, ``It seems to be incredible that these (Olympic
organizers) can be so crass about ignoring Australian performers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the president of World Projects said Australian
officials are now working on other ways to involve the students. An
article in today's Herald said Olympics organizers now plan to
offer the students ``lesser Olympic roles,'' such as ``performing
at the village or on the boulevard outside the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know the full details of (the organizers' plans) but
we do expect to learn those details during the site inspection
visit on July 4 in Sydney and Bathurst,'' William R. Lutt, World
Projects president, said in a faxed statement.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was to cost $3,600 per person, plus the cost of
shipping their musical instruments. The schools were to start
fund-raising efforts this fall, and some parents had begun making
partial payments.
</P>
<P>
   Because students would miss the second and third weeks of school
in September, Olympic organizers were to arrange for band members
to have tutors in Sydney, and for Internet access to their
classroom teachers back home. Study halls had been arranged between
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette County High has received corporate donations to help pay
for the trip, said Principal Gary Phillips. ``We've had a number of
calls,'' he said. ``One parent told me this morning that they'd
already paid $850. If we really are kicked out, there's a lot of
money that's going to have to be refunded.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Raney, a vice president with World Projects, said
Thursday that restitution would be made to bands that have made
financial payments toward the trip if it is canceled. ``From our
point of view we're very disappointed and a bit frustrated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Terry, 17, who plays trumpet in the Fayette band, said he
has always wanted to go to Australia and was looking forward to the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' he said. ``It would
have been really cool to go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
