<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUV-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE LATE, A REVOLUTION ARRIVES ON NEW YORK'S ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A promotional video for the GMC Yukon shows G. Richard Wagoner
Jr., the president of General Motors, telling his chauffeur to take
a shortcut across Manhattan. The driver cuts the wheel, and the
Yukon, a giant sport utility vehicle, responds, weaving through
traffic, slaloming between safety cones, riding up on the sidewalk
and, finally, careering around a truck on a narrow street.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and its competitors have launched marketing
campaigns to convince residents that the latest sport utility
vehicles are nimble enough for the rigors of metropolitan New York,
and local drivers apparently agree.
</P>
<P>
   Despite congested streets, narrow roadways, aging bridges and
tunnels and polluted air that, in some respects, make the New York
area uniquely inhospitable to light trucks, the region has become
one of the nation's hottest markets for sport utility vehicles.
Sales have doubled since 1994, and they show no signs of slowing.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators are on the verge of proposing new registration
rules that could further increase the number of heavier vehicles on
area roadways. Pickup trucks, now relatively scarce in the region
and usually licensed only as commercial vehicles, would become much
easier for residents to license, and new rules would allow them on
many roads and bridges where they are now banned.
</P>
<P>
   Yet highway engineers, safety experts and environmental
regulators say that sport utility vehicles and pickups pose special
safety and environmental issues for metropolitan New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York City is going to have a problem with them,'' said
Raymond Heimbuch, retired president of Clarke and Rapuano, the big
Manhattan road design company that laid out many of the city's
parkways over the last six decades. He worries that the big
vehicles were not anticipated when the narrow lanes and tight
curves of the city's roads and bridges were built. With traffic
often bumper-to-bumper, he said, it is troublesome that sport
utility vehicles are so tall that they block car drivers' views of
7-foot stop signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of situations, there's no doubt about it, that
are going to be made worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no reliable safety statistics, current state
officials acknowledge that the region's older roads, particularly
those that cannot be easily upgraded, are poorly suited for sport
utility vehicles. ``It's hard to drive one down those parkways,''
especially if a driver speeds, said Robert Dennison, the state
Department of Transportation's Hudson Valley regional director.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the changing mix of vehicles could threaten the
region's air quality, which is already polluted. ``As the fleet
gets heavier, it will have more of an impact on our air,'' said
Steven Flint, state chief of vehicular air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators have imposed some of the strictest air
pollution rules in the nation for cars but have largely ignored the
larger light trucks. As a result, the state allows big sport
utilities and pickups to emit more than five times as much
pollution per mile as cars _ a wider disparity than in all but
three other states.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the big vehicles have an undeniable appeal for many
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Kieran Higgins, a construction manager in Manhattan, recently
chose a black Dodge Durango sport utility as his company vehicle
because he wanted a lot of room to carry his files and laptop
computer from site to site. The vehicle has the optional four-wheel
drive, which makes it 2 inches taller and several hundred pounds
heavier, but Higgins said that he had never used it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sell it as a package with leather seats and rear air
conditioning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's most prominent user of a sport utility vehicle is
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whose official vehicle is a green 1993 GMC
Suburban. ``Frequently he has staff members in there, and he
conducts meetings,'' said Sunny Mindel, a spokeswoman. ``It has the
space.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehicles have even made inroads in New York's taxi fleet.
The city's Taxi and Limousine Commission approved the use of Ford
Explorer sport utility vehicles as taxis three years ago. Honda
Odyssey and Isuzu Oasis minivans were also approved. As of this
spring 39 cabdrivers were using Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the region's parkways, among the oldest in the nation,
have been rebuilt over the last several decades with wider lanes,
particularly on Long Island. But many of the most traveled still
have lanes that are a foot or two narrower than the federal
standard of 12 feet. Tall, wide vehicles are a problem in narrow
lanes because car drivers cannot see around them or over them.
</P>
<P>
   And some New York-area roads and bridges, notably the Garden
State Parkway and the Brooklyn Bridge, have weight limits set many
years ago to exclude commercial trucks. Still, these limits are now
flouted routinely by drivers of full-sized sport utility vehicles,
which weigh up to twice as much as mid-size cars.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Expedition, Lincoln Navigator, Dodge Durango, Lexus
LX-470, Toyota Land Cruiser, Cadillac Escalade, GMC Yukon,
Chevrolet Tahoe and Chevrolet Suburban all exceed the weight limit
on the Brooklyn Bridge, for example. But city officials say they
have a problem with ticketing large sport utility vehicles because
few drivers know how much their vehicles weigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I don't have an entire bridge full of stopped
Tahoes, I don't have a problem,'' said Henry D. Perahia, the city's
chief bridge engineer. Even if the 116-year-old bridge were covered
entirely by full-size sport utility vehicles, it would likely
suffer limited structural damage, he said, adding, ``I don't think
you'd have a collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes now under way in metropolitan New York's fleet of
vehicles are particularly dramatic because light trucks are late
arrivals in the city. This was the result of a combination of
regulations, found nowhere else in the country, that strongly
discouraged residents from buying pickups. Sport utility vehicles,
a recent fad, are exempt from these rules, even though most sport
utility vehicles are modified pickup trucks, and are lumped
together with pickups for many federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Since before World War II, New York state has required that all
open-bed pickup trucks be registered as commercial vehicles. At the
same time, New York state parkways and a few bridges, notably the
Brooklyn Bridge, ban vehicles with commercial plates. New York City
even requires that all vehicles with commercial plates carry the
name and address of the owner in 3-inch-high letters on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Driving an open-bed pickup in the New York area can require
lengthy detours, so few people buy them. The two most popular
vehicles in the country are the Ford F-150 and Chevrolet Silverado
pickup trucks, each of which easily outsells the most popular car,
the Toyota Camry. Yet in New York City plus Westchester, Rockland
and Putnam counties, all pickups together accounted for only 1.7
percent of new vehicle registrations last year, compared with 18.8
percent nationally, according to R.L. Polk &AMP; Co., which tracks auto
registration data.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, sport utility vehicles made up 19.2 percent of the
new vehicles registered in this area last year and 19.9 percent if
Nassau, Suffolk and Bergen are included, compared with 16.1 percent
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   With so many big sport utility vehicles already in use, Gov.
George Pataki's Office of Regulatory Reform is quietly reviewing a
proposal to give buyers of all but the largest pickup trucks a
choice of registering their vehicles as commercial vehicles or as
passenger vehicles, which is the category for cars and most
minivans.
</P>
<P>
   David Bradley, the office's acting director, said that the new
rule would probably be issued for public comment soon.
</P>
<P>
   The change would make it much easier for people in and around
New York to buy and drive pickups. Automakers have lobbied
strenuously for the rule change.
</P>
<P>
   The original notion was to restrict commercial activity and
prevent trucks piled high with merchandise from reaching
residential neighborhoods in the city and suburbs. But pickup
trucks with a hard cap over the bed have long been exempted from
these rules. They can be registered as personal vehicles and can be
taken on parkways, which were originally intended for recreational
driving and often have sharp curves so that drivers can admire the
landscape ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   Most sport utility vehicles are essentially pickup trucks with
factory-installed roofs over the bed and extra rows of seats, so
they are exempt from the current rules. Sales of sport utility
vehicles have already doubled in New York and its suburbs since
1994, rising faster than in the rest of the country, according to
R.L. Polk. Because a sport utility vehicle typically costs $10,000
more than a comparably sized car, the trend has been most
noticeable in affluent neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to keep the boom going, automakers have increased their
spending on ads for these vehicles in metropolitan New York by 119
percent over the last four years. ``In terms of driving, in New
York City a sport utility vehicle makes sense _ they're tough,
you've got good visibility, you're surrounded by yellow cabs,''
which are relatively low and easy to see over, said Mark Schirmer,
a spokesman for Land Rover, which sells more Range Rovers in the
New York area than anywhere else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   There are few statistics on the involvement of sport utility
vehicles in crashes in the region. State forms for traffic
accidents require the police officer to note whether a vehicle with
passenger or commercial license plates was involved. But if the
vehicle was a passenger vehicle, the form does not require the
officer to note whether it was a sport utility vehicle, a minivan,
a car or the occasional pickup with a covered bed.
</P>
<P>
   While engineers have tried to modernize New York's road system,
there are limits on what can be done. Construction costs are high.
Straightening some sharp curves would require tearing down homes or
even, in the case of the twisting Jackie Robinson Parkway in
Brooklyn, paving over sections of cemeteries. And several area
parkways have historic significance, notably the Bronx River,
Taconic State and Merritt Parkways, which means that
preservationists have sought successfully to limit alterations.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who speed in sport utility vehicles on these roads pose
a particular problem for highway engineers, because these vehicles'
weight and high centers of gravity make them harder to control in
turns and more vulnerable to rolling over if they strike curbs,
guard rails or other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Domenico Annese, 80, who helped design several local parkways,
said that he drove the Saw Mill River every day and routinely saw
sport utility drivers speeding and unable to stay in their lanes.
``They're straddling the yellow line and fishtailing a little bit
and they're putting on the brakes in the middle of the curves, and
that's bad,'' he said. ``People have a false sense of security in
the bigger vehicles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
