<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER, DEFYING A TREND, SAYS SALES FELL 5 PERCENT IN JUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Surprising analysts, DaimlerChrysler AG said Thursday
that sales of its Chrysler-brand vehicles declined in June, which
had been expected to be one of the auto industry's best sales
months ever.
</P>
<P>
   Combined sales of the Dodge, Chrysler, Plymouth and Jeep brands
fell 5 percent from a year ago, to 255,496 cars and trucks. Sales
of the company's Mercedes-Benz vehicles, however, rose 8 percent to
create the third-best month in history.
</P>
<P>
   Minivan sales were off 19 percent, mostly because inventories
were low after strong sales in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big fall-off in minivan sales accounted for the drop in
our total sales,'' Jamie Jameson, DaimlerChrysler vice president
for sales and marketing operations, said in an interview.
``Minivans had a huge month in May, and we sold out of hot-selling
minivan models. We're restocking our shelves right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But DaimlerChrysler sales were lower in a number of categories
other than minivans. Car sales dropped 14 percent. Sales of almost
every car model, including the Neon introduced this spring, showed
double-digit decreases. Only the Chrysler 300M and LHS, Dodge
Intrepid and low-volume Plymouth Prowler and Dodge Viper posted
increases. Truck sales were flat, while sales of sport-utility
vehicles, the Jeep brands and Dodge Durango, rose.
</P>
<P>
   Jameson noted that industry sales in the similar 1998 period
were extraordinarily high because Chrysler and Ford Motor Co.
offered incentive programs to match one that General Motors Corp.
had introduced. The programs expired at the end of last June.
</P>
<P>
   A different strategy by GM last month may have hurt
DaimlerChrysler sales, said David Healy, an auto analyst with
Burnham Securities Inc. in New York. In June, GM began aggressive
incentives that Healy estimated amounted to as much as $2,000 a
vehicle. But unlike the highly publicized GM Owner Loyalty program
last year, which covered all models nationwide, the most recent
round of incentives vary by region and by model.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM has been adding heavily but quietly to its incentives, and
that might have stolen from Chrysler sales,'' Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Ford are due to report their June sales on Friday. Both
are expected to show sales that are flat or up only modestly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite DaimlerChrysler's June sales decline, last month was
still its second-best June in history. The automaker set records
for second-quarter and first-half sales.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sales for the month are predicted to rise. Healy
forecasts a gain of 2 percent or 3 percent, for an annual rate of
17.5 million to 18 million total cars and light trucks. ``It will
be one of the best months ever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other reports Thursday, Toyota said it had its best sales
month in history, as well as best second-quarter and first-half
sales. The company's just-introduced Tundra, which is intended to
compete head-on with full-size pickup trucks from Detroit's
automakers, was off to the fastest start of any vehicle Toyota has
ever introduced, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Honda set records for June and the first six months.
Sales of its new Odyssey minivan rose 268 percent, even though the
vehicle is still in short supply for it.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan, which is in the midst of a new product blitz with this
spring's introduction of a new Xterra sport utility, Crew Cab
pickup truck and midsize Maxima car, had higher sales in June, too.
</P>
<P>
   European automakers also continued to report year-over-year
sales increases. Volkswagen recorded its best June since 1973 and
its best month since May 1979. VW's sales rose on the strength of
its redesigned compact Jetta and higher sales on its midsize Passat
and New Beetle. The company's Audi unit reported its best June
sales since 1987 and its best first-half since 1986. Every model in
its line recorded sales increases.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover, a unit of BMW, reported its strongest sales month of
1999 and its best first half ever, paced by its redesigned
Discovery sport utility.
</P>
<P>
   Also reporting sales increases Thursday were Kia; Isuzu; Saab,
which is 50 percent owned by GM; Subaru; and Volvo, a Ford
subsidiary. Mitsubishi sales declined.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Wednesday by the Federal Reserve Board to
increase a key interest rate is not expected to slow the sizzling
vehicle sales. ``We think it's full speed ahead for the foreseeable
future,'' Jameson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
