<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUGAR-ATHLETICS-BOS &LR;      07-01 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUGAR-ATHLETICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON BUSINESSMAN MUGAR AMONG POTENTIAL ATHLETICS BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For two decades he has been considered a potential
owner of the Red Sox, but Boston businessman David G. Mugar has
decided, at least for now, to try to buy a piece of the Oakland
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Mugar, and his family, have been named as part of a long list of
investors seeking to buy the troubled American League franchise.
The Mugars, including sons Jonathan and Peter, are limited partners
in Oakland Investors LP which has been designated the prospective
owner of the team by government officials in Oakland, who have been
seeking a new owner for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But does that end the speculation about Mugar and the Red Sox?
Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   Several sports business experts said Thursday that obtaining
partial ownership of one franchise before moving on to own another
one, is a well-traveled path in professional sports. And Mugar did
not close the door on that possibility Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never say never,'' said Mugar, who was busy preparing
for the fireworks display he produces annually on the Charles River
to celebrate Independence Day. ``But my main interest here now, if
our group is approved, is helping to build a championship team for
the City of Oakland. And making a commitment to provide the best
management we can for that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I am concerned, the Red Sox are John Harrington's.
They belong to John Harrington and his group, and I will do
anything I can to support him and to insure that the new Fenway
Park, as proposed, is built.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Mugar and the Red Sox Hall of Famer Carl Yastrzemski
pursued a share of the ownership of the team, in a titanic struggle
among the late Jean Yawkey, John Harrington, Buddy LeRoux, Haywood
Sullivan, Rogers Badgett. Had LeRoux won out, Mugar would likely
have joined him as part of the partnership controlling the Red Sox.
But Yawkey, Harrington and Sullivan triumphed, and Harrington still
presides over the team today.
</P>
<P>
   As the Red Sox attempt to accumulate financing for a $545 new
stadium project, considerable speculation centers on how much of
the tab the current ownership can afford. Some observers have
suggested that the current ownership group might require a
financial partner, but Harrington has repeatedly denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need one for this project,'' Harrington said, in an
interview last month. ``I think when our financing package is
finalized you will see a significant private investment in this
project _ one of the largest private investments made by any
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mugar, a millionaire whose family's money comes from
having owned the Star Market chain and a number of lucrative real
estate deals since then as part of Mugar Enterprises, is looking
forward to his potential participation in the ownership of the
Oakland team. Leading the effort is Robert Piccinini, who owns and
operates the California-based Save Mart Supermarkets, and Andy
Dolich, a former executive of the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all arisen in the past few weeks, frankly,'' Mugar
said. ``My son John will complete his masters at Tufts in another
month or so, and a good friend of his has been Andy Dolich's son.
They played on the Tufts baseball team together for a number of
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy Dolich mentioned to his son about being involved in this
group trying to purchase the A's,'' Mugar said. ``His son mentioned
it to my son John, and John mentioned it to us, as to whether we
might be interested _ and the answer was yes. And here we are. It's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes other, significant Boston players. Game Plan
PLC, a local investment bank that includes Robert Caporale, was
secured as a financial adviser to Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum
Authority, in part, to help find a new owner for the Athletics.
Fleet Financial Group would finance the purchase for Oakland
Investors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other limited partners is Hall of Fame slugger Reggie
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The current saga of the Oakland Athletics is a tortured tale of
an ownership that wants to get rid of the team and a city and
county that want to insure that Major League Baseball stays in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Investors LP, is seeking to purchase the team for $122.4
million from Steve Schott and Ken Hoffman. The price was worked out
in a settlement with the city of Oakland and Alameda County that
stipulates the sale must close by September 21. If not, Schott and
Hofmann retain ownership, with the prospect that the team might be
moved.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the process is approval of the sale by Major
League Baseball, which could occur as soon an owners' meeting on
Sept. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
