<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUSH-HNS &LR;      07-01 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS GORE'S IDEAS, NOT BUSH'S MONEY, THAT'S IMPORTANT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Offering his two cents on George W. Bush's $36.2
million, President Clinton said Thursday that Al Gore's ideas, not
the Texas governor's money, will win the presidential election in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton criticized Bush for considering bypassing federal
campaign spending rules, suggesting the governor would join
Republican leaders in their hostility toward campaign finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, hosting a news conference with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, stepped into the 2000 presidential contest when asked to
comment about Bush's record-setting $36.2 million war chest and
about reports that Bush may avoid requesting federal matching funds
so he can spend an unlimited sum.
</P>
<P>
   Bush not only has raised 10 times the amount of his Republican
rivals but nearly twice as much as Vice President Gore who
generated $18 million for his Democratic campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's the ideas, not the money, that's important, Clinton
responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership of the Republican Party in general are
unanimously hostile to campaign finance reform. They don't believe
in it,'' Clinton said. ``If he (Bush) did that, he would have that
in common with the other leaders who won't permit us to bring the
(campaign finance reform) bill to a vote, or to try to pursue what
I believe are needed changes in the campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are going to have to make up their minds
whether this is an important issue to them or not. I think the most
valuable commodity in an election ... even more valuable than
money, is ideas,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that the most important thing, therefore, that I
have seen in this election so far is that Vice President Gore is,
as nearly as I can determine, the only candidate of either party
who has actually told the American people what he would do if he
got elected,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton demurred when asked if Bush has wrapped up his
party's nomination. ``How do I know what the Republicans are going
to do in their nominating process? I don't have a clue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, a spokeswoman for Bush, said, ``The Democrats must
be very nervous about the tremendous grass-roots enthusiasm Gov.
Bush is generating all across America to have the incumbent
president of the United States directly attack a Republican who has
not even won his own party's nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said that in four months Bush has been able to attract
contributions from 75,000 Americans. Bush has voiced support for
more disclosure of campaign donations but has not embraced specific
legislation pending in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very unusual to attack a Republican who has not
even won his own party's nomination,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will decide next month whether to take federal matching
funds and be bound by a state-by-state spending limit. There is a
total spending limit of about $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's withering financial prowess sparked a bipartisan emphasis
on the ``it's the ideas; not the money'' response.
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidate Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire who in
his 1996 campaign spent $37 million of his personal money, said he
will match Bush's spending. ``We'll make sure our message gets out
there. I'm not going to put a number because I want to keep him and
others guessing,'' Forbes told CNN. ``I think they are afraid more
of my ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Underdog conservative Gary Bauer, said, ``If elections could be
bought, (Texas billionaire) Ross Perot would be ending his second
presidential term. So I think, at the end of the day, ideas matter
and I think the ideas I have are much more in line with Republican
voters than this sort of mushy comments we're hearing out of
Austin, Texas, right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments in support of Gore sparked questions about
whether it was a slap at former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, the
vice president's only Democratic challenger. He has raised a
surprising $11 million in his challenge for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a dig at Sen. Bradley. He has said himself that he
has not laid out his case for being president and said that he
wants to wait until the fall to do it. But I personally have always
believed that you should begin by saying why you want the job
because you are asking people to hire you to do things and I think
the vice president deserves a lot of credit for doing that,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's promotion of Gore's candidacy comes amid White House
denials of any rift between the two. Gore reportedly was miffed at
Clinton for calling a New York Times reporter and offering the vice
president tips on campaigning while Clinton reportedly was steamed
at Gore for the latter's attempt to distance himself on moral
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton insisted he was bewildered by such reports. ``I
honestly do not know what the source of the stories are. But they
are not in my heart or my mind,'' he said, praising Gore's
presidential announcement address last month.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he expected Gore and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, should she run for the New York Senate seat, to
distance themselves from some of his decisions and he welcomed
their differences of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he disagrees with a decision that I make as president
during the next year and a half, then, of course, he will have to
say so. And I will take no offense of that,'' Clinton said. The
president said the same of true for his wife should she run for
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the first lady may have to state publicly her
disagreements over decisions he has made as president. ``And that's
the way democracy works,'' he said. ``It would be a dreary world,
indeed, if we all agreed on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he did not select Gore to be vice president
so he would agree with everything he did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
