   ``We don't need one for this project,'' Harrington said, in an
interview last month. ``I think when our financing package is
finalized you will see a significant private investment in this
project _ one of the largest private investments made by any
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mugar, a millionaire whose family's money comes from
having owned the Star Market chain and a number of lucrative real
estate deals since then as part of Mugar Enterprises, is looking
forward to his potential participation in the ownership of the
Oakland team. Leading the effort is Robert Piccinini, who owns and
operates the California-based Save Mart Supermarkets, and Andy
Dolich, a former executive of the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all arisen in the past few weeks, frankly,'' Mugar
said. ``My son John will complete his masters at Tufts in another
month or so, and a good friend of his has been Andy Dolich's son.
They played on the Tufts baseball team together for a number of
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy Dolich mentioned to his son about being involved in this
group trying to purchase the A's,'' Mugar said. ``His son mentioned
it to my son John, and John mentioned it to us, as to whether we
might be interested _ and the answer was yes. And here we are. It's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes other, significant Boston players. Game Plan
PLC, a local investment bank that includes Robert Caporale, was
secured as a financial adviser to Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum
Authority, in part, to help find a new owner for the Athletics.
Fleet Financial Group would finance the purchase for Oakland
Investors.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other limited partners is Hall of Fame slugger Reggie
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The current saga of the Oakland Athletics is a tortured tale of
an ownership that wants to get rid of the team and a city and
county that want to insure that Major League Baseball stays in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Investors LP, is seeking to purchase the team for $122.4
million from Steve Schott and Ken Hoffman. The price was worked out
in a settlement with the city of Oakland and Alameda County that
stipulates the sale must close by September 21. If not, Schott and
Hofmann retain ownership, with the prospect that the team might be
moved.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the process is approval of the sale by Major
League Baseball, which could occur as soon an owners' meeting on
Sept. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
