u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMOS-CUTBACKS-BOS &LR;      07-01 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-CUTBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS WILL CULL 250,000 MEDICARE MEMBERS JAN. 1, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Blaming lower federal payment rates, HMOs nationally
will drop a quarter-million Medicare subscribers on January 1,
industry officials said Thursday. But the 228,000 Massachusetts
elders who belong to HMOs will be largely safe from such care
disruptions _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   The exception will be some residents of southeastern, central
and western Massachusetts who will have to pay monthly premiums of
$30 to $50 if they want to remain in the state's two largest
Medicare HMOs, Tufts Health Plan's Secure Horizons and Harvard
Pilgrim Health Plan's First Seniority. Up to now, Medicare HMOs
have managed on federal payments alone, without charging
subscribers any premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon's Senior Plan will continue to be premium-free for its
34,000 members. Officials of Blue Cross-Blue Shield of
Massachusetts, which enrolls about 16,000 elders in its HMO Blue,
refused to divulge details of the year 2000 plan it filed this week
with Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Except for First Seniority _ which announced last month it would
cease providing coverage to 3,500 members in western Massachusetts
_ Massachusetts HMOs are staying in the Medicare program. But all
are raising the amounts that members must pay out of pocket,
especially for prescription drugs, and some are reducing other
benefits too.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all Medicare HMO subscribers in Massachusetts _ if not
nationally _ will end up paying more out of their own pockets for
prescription drugs, as health plans struggle to tame pharmacy costs
rising at around 15 percent a year. Especially costly will be
high-priced brand-name drugs that have cheaper and equally
effective alternatives _ in the HMOs' judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Massachusetts elders will also begin to notice
higher charges and erosion of their HMO benefits beginning in
January, a trend that industry leaders said will affect virtually
all 6.2 million subscribers in Medicare HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, First Seniority's 68,000 members will pay $50 if
they go to the emergency room but don't require hospital admission,
twice the current hit. The plan will no longer pay half their
routine dental bills, either, although members will get a discount
from dentists' normal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the nation, HMOs are raising premiums, raising
copayments, raising deductibles, cutting back benefits, and blaming
Medicare payments,'' said Geoff Wilkinson of Massachusetts Senior
Action Council, an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are convinced that rising prescription drug costs are
more a factor in these cutbacks than the Medicare payments, but
it's hard to cost that out,'' Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim, which may lose up to $30 million on its First
Seniority plan this year, is the most aggressive in seeking more
money from its 68,000 elderly subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   First Seniority members in Barnstable and Bristol counties will
have to pay $50 a month if they want to stay in the program next
year, while members in Plymouth and Worcester counties will pay $30
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Without those new premiums, said Harvard Pilgrim chief executive
Charles D. Baker Jr., his HMO would have had to stop offering
Medicare plans in much of Massachusetts. ``Barnstable, Bristol, and
Worcester (counties) were up for grabs,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollees in Tufts' Secure Horizons who live in Barnstable and
Bristol counties will be charged $30 a month, while those in
Hampden county will have to pay $35 monthly.
</P>
<P>
   All changes are subject to approval by federal Medicare
officials. HMOs had to file their plans for 2000 Thursday with the
federal Health Care Financing Administration, which runs Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, when HMOs announce their Medicare plans for
2001, ``it's not at all unlikely that members will have to pay
premiums'' wherever they live, said Patty Blake of Secure Horizons,
the state's largest Medicare HMO with 97,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, Blake said, is that Secure Horizons projects its
federal Medicare payments to fall eight percent while its costs of
providing care will rise by five percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials insist that Medicare payments to HMOs are too
generous. ``Studies continue to show that Medicare managed care
plans are still being overpaid,'' said Nancy Ann DeParle,
administrator of the Health Care Financing Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignani, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, rejected DeParle's assertion as out-of-date. ``Health plans
that are overpaid don't leave the program and cut benefits,''
Ignani said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The health plan association released results of a survey of 23
large Medicare HMOs enrolling about 4 million of the 6.1 million
Americans enrolled in such plans.
</P>
<P>
   Ignani said HMOs serving 250,000 elders will drop out of the
Medicare program January 1, bringing to about 700,000 the number
dropped since last October. ``This program is in crisis,'' Ignani
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
