<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      07-01 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF ELIMINATES VENUS WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Call it a long day's damp journey into night.
</P>
<P>
   It was a drama in four uneven acts and uncertain intermissions
for two heroines, antagonists Steffi Graf and Venus Williams,
clawing at each other. With the yellow lights of the scoreboard and
silver blinks of spectators' flashbulbs illuminating the tense,
darkening amphitheater, the match had unfolded across seven hours,
a microcosm of Graf's turbulent career _ often derailed,
ever-renewed, with yet another triumphant ending.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, at 30 the grande dame of Wimbledon's Centre Court, with
seven championships in her satchel, and itching for an eighth, had
``never gone through anything quite like it. The stopping and
starting for the rain, the hardest of my (10) quarterfinals here
because of Venus. I couldn't believe we could keep up at such a
level with the interruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, green as the grass underfoot when it comes to playing
tennis on the stuff, is nevertheless a quick study. She pushed and
prodded Graf to the heights after a flat start, came within two
points of extending the plot into Friday, but couldn't quite keep
up, 6-2, 3-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Had Williams, cornering Graf at 15-30 in the last game,
splintered the victor's serve there, it would have been a
to-be-continued situation. The clock shone 8:12 of a dim, dank
evening. But the kid made three errors and the weird day, so
frustrating to players and 30,223 patrons, squished to a close in
one more downpour.
</P>
<P>
   So much water, so much waiting _ and merely two results where
eight were intended in singles. Lindsay Davenport, showing total
disregard for royalty, deposed 1998 queen Jana Novotna, 6-3, 6-4,
to join Graf in the semis, though on the other side of the draw.
They appear destined for a championship showdown Sunday, when both
men's and women's finals are to be played if the truculent weather
behaves.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else, including five-time champ Pete Sampras, was left
hung up, some high and wet with matches in various states of
progress, others, like Pete, never out of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds and clouds converged on the venerable tennis ballpark,
and the gloomy, greasy clouds won. Again. But there was hope every
time showers relented and the heroic grounds crew responded to the
referee's command of ``Take it off!'' by removing the tarpaulins.
</P>
<P>
   This happened over and over, and each time a little more was
seen of such as Graf, Williams, the reigning Novotna, Davenport,
and the startling kiddies, qualifiers Alexandra Stevenson, 18, and
Jelena Dokic, 16.
</P>
<P>
   As persistent showers tormented the quarterfinalists, the
luckiest lady on the grassy runway was Davenport, the 6-foot-3-inch
US Open champ: she came off fairly early with the first result of
the day. Fitting her thundering groundies into openings in the
atmosphere and along the lines in Court 1, Davenport dethroned
Novotna is a crisp 67-minute performance of only two acts,
separated by a one-hour intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The rest weren't so fortunate, stranded in various states of
disarray, their emotions stripped by the disjointed
on-again-off-again rhythm. France's Nathalie Tauziat, finalist a
year ago to Novotna, leads 17-year-old Croatian Mirjana Lucic, 6-4,
3-3. Stevenson started brilliantly against the intransigent Dokic,
victimizer of Martina Hingis, but is way behind in the second, 6-3,
1-5. Todd Martin and Patrick Rafter are locked at 3-3. Tim Henman,
the most famous English Tim since the tiny Cratchitt, has leaped
all the way to a 1-0 lead over Cedric Pioline by winning his serve.
</P>
<P>
   Believing in herself as never before, Davenport continued her
stranglehold (6-0) over Novotna and is ``starting to get the feel
for grass. I've lost the last two times I was in the quarters here.
I was upset with myself when I didn't serve it out at 5-3, but
really pleased I immediately broke her to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On match point, Lindsay uncharacteristically headed for the net
behind a dinky chipped forehand. ``It wasn't much, but I figured
she'd have to pass me.'' She didn't. Novotna's backhand landed just
over the baseline and the queen was dead at 3:10.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if theirs would be the sole result. At that time
Venus and Steffi were in the midst of an all-day excursion that
began at 1:06.
</P>
<P>
   Their four acts went like this:
</P>
<P>
   I _ Steffi wins the first set; trails, 2-3, in the second.
</P>
<P>
   II _ Venus wins the second set and leads, 1-0, in the third.
</P>
<P>
   III _ They're even at 2-2 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   IV _ The core, the fifth and sixth games, before Steffi emerges
a waterlogged winner.
</P>
<P>
   During their last dressing room sojourn, drying out by reading a
book about the Sahara Desert, Graf ``figured I had to be
aggressive.'' Stubborn baselining, backboned by her wondrous
forehand, wasn't enough. Streaking in for volleys on the critical
points, she cracked Williams to 3-2, and held to 4-2 through the
excitement of four deuces and three break points. She was ``happy
the way I played break points'' _ saving 12 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have been the aggressor in those games myself,''
Williams said correctly. ``There were more rain delays than I ever
dreamed of, but I was OK. The conditions, the lack of light didn't
bother me. But Steffi has the will; she's famous for it. But I'll
keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be No. 1 one day,'' Graf praised her adversary. ``It
was incredible the shots she ran down. I've never seen anybody with
such lateral movement.''
</P>
<P>
   They were dashing, bashing combatants who saved a miserable day
with magnificent shotmaking in the concluding stages of an
engagement that lasted 1:55 in playing time. Give them rave
notices, but can anyone take center stage from Steffi?
</P>
<P>
   A Wimbledon that began with such sunny promise the first week
has been jammed into a mess that may not end until Monday, or even
Tuesday. Sampras, thus far untested, is now faced with the
goliathan Mark Philippoussis, and the prospect of three matches in
as many days to keep his title and establish himself as the male
player of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Graf already has done that in her precinct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
