<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-PC02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free PCs deals legit, but not always best
 &HT;    By Shannon Shelton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Computer costs have consistently been falling over the
past few years. But at two popular computer stores Thursday, it
appeared PCs had reached their lowest price ever _ free.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy and Circuit City, the nation's No. 1 and 2 computer
retailers, have unveiled a nationwide promotion offering a free PC
with the purchase of an Internet service package from a
store-chosen provider.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect to go to either store without your wallet and
walk out with a new PC. Consumers have to pay for the CPU up front,
then send for a rebate check after installing the Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   At both stores, that means buying a PC worth about $400 or more,
then purchasing a $19 to $22-per-month Internet service for three
years to get a $400 rebate. The deals also don't include monitors
or printers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stewart, national spokesperson for Richmond, Va.-based
Circuit City, said even though buyers have to send for the money,
ultimately they'll still end up with a free computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to get Internet service, you have to pay for it
anyway,'' Stewart said. ``With this program, you get the service
and a personal computer. I don't know how you can argue this isn't
a free PC.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Fernando Mujica, an Atlanta resident shopping for a
computer at Circuit City, thought the work involved in getting the
``free'' PC wasn't worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty annoying to send for the money,'' Mujica said.
``The catch to this deal is bigger than it appears.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry McCracken, a senior writer for PC World magazine, said
``free PC'' deals usually leave a lot to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these deals look very compelling,'' McCracken said.
``You're signing up at one set price for several years when prices
are falling for Internet connection. In addition, there are hot new
technologies, such as cable modems and DSL, coming along to offer
quicker Internet connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of stiff penalties, consumers could indeed feel locked
into a contract they may want to break sooner than the termination
date.
</P>
<P>
   At Circuit City, a buyer who ends the service within a year will
have to pay back the $400 and be subject to a $50 fee. Best Buy has
similar penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Smith, president of the Atlanta Better Business Bureau, said
although this promotion is legitimate, potential buyers should make
sure that they understand all the terms and that the offer fits
their needs. ``This seems to meet the standards on the use of the
word 'free' because they have disclosed the terms of the deal,''
Smith said. ``But consumers should comparison shop to see if the
items are competitively priced and see if they are really receiving
a value.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 3 p.m. at an Atlanta Circuit City, computer department
supervisor Germaine Nash said some shoppers had been asking about
the free PC offer. He expected purchases to pick up more in the
evening and over the weekend, when store volume normally increases.
</P>
<P>
   As for the customers who were looking around at that time, none
seemed particularly drawn to the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Romain Murenzi, a Clark Atlanta University physics professor
searching for a computer to take on an educational trip to Rwanda,
said he was shopping anyway and wasn't drawn by the offer. ``I'll
be more than happy to take a look at it, but if it's not the best
deal, I won't get it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE GIVEAWAY DEALS
</P>
<P>
   A number of Internet access providers are giving away ``free''
computers or rebates on more expensive machines. Here are some of
the deals:
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumers will receive a $400 rebate for 36 months of Internet
service from Prodigy, which costs $19.95 per month. Customers must
install the Prodigy service to receive the rebate check.
</P>
<P>
   _ Best Buy says the $400 price will cover the cost of many
entry-level PCs, making them essentially ``free.'' The rebate does
not cover the cost of a monitor or printer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Customers can also purchase shorter Internet plans _ one year
nets a $100 rebate, and two years earns $250.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancellation rates apply.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit City
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumers must purchase 36 months of Internet access from
CompuServe at $21.95 a month. After installing the service,
customers can then send for a $400 rebate check that should arrive
in 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rebate applies to any PC purchase, as long as the
CompuServe program is installed. Circuit City is offering a PC from
emachines for $474. emachines is offering a $75 rebate. With both
rebates, the computer becomes ``free.'' Again, monitors and
printers are not included.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancellation rates apply.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
