<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEM-CELLS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEOLOGIANS DEBATE ETHICS OF EMBRYONIC STEM CELL RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is research on human embryonic stem cells ethically justified?
Theologians have a clear answer _ in fact quite a few of them,
depending both on their faith and their relative position within
it.
</P>
<P>
   The research, made possible by a discovery in November, provokes
a stark moral choice: the primordial cells can give rise to all
kinds of human tissue, making them potentially priceless as tools
to repair aging and ailing bodies. But in most cases a human embryo
must be destroyed to obtain them.
</P>
<P>
   That clash of values has generated some richly dissonant
conclusions. ``The prospect of government-sponsored experiments to
manipulate and destroy human embryos should make us all lie awake
at night,'' said a position paper issued this week by Sen. Sam
Brownback, R-Kan., and endorsed by Catholic and Protestant
opponents of abortion. ``That some individuals would be destroyed
in the name of medical science constitutes a threat to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Patients Coalition for Urgent Research, a consortium of
more than 20 disease advocacy organizations responded that stem
cell research should proceed ``in order to speed the day when
millions of sufferers will find relief from the ravages of
catastrophic illness and disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback's statement represents only one position, though an
important one, on a spectrum of theological views. Many, but not
all, Catholics believe that from the moment of conception the
embryo merits full protection as a person. The two principal
sources of embryonic stem cells _ spare embryos from fertility
clinics and aborted fetuses _ are both unacceptable, in this view,
because they involve the intentional destruction of an individual.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish analysis, on the other hand, holds that embryos
outside the body have no moral status. In this view, spare embryos
present no problem as a source of stem cells, nor do aborted
fetuses provided that the abortion took place for ethically
acceptable reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Spare embryos, the principal source of embryonic stem cells, are
the unavoidably surplus unions of sperm and egg produced in
fertility clinics. The embryos are often stored for years and
ultimately discarded. Inside the embryo, which at this stage is
just a hollow sphere, rests a clump of about 100 cells known as the
inner cell mass. These cells, when cultured in the laboratory, are
the embryonic stem cells, and because they will grow and divide
indefinitely, a handful of embryos could provide a profusion of
stem cells.
</P>
<P>
   These circumstances may obscure but not alter the fact that an
embyro is destroyed in generating stem cells. In a draft report, in
language to which several scientific members objected at a meeting
this week, the National Bioethics Advisory Commission said, ``As
long as embryos are destroyed as part of the research enterprise,
researchers using embryonic cells (and those who fund them) will
generally be directly or indirectly complicit in the demise of
embryos.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of guilty complicity stems from the premise that an
entity tantamount to a person has been destroyed. This is the
official Catholic position, as represented by the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, and is also held by some
Protestants. ``The availability of the embryos does not justify
their use,'' said Nigel Cameron, a Presbyterian at Trinity
International University in Deerfield, Ill. ``Here is one of us,
however primitive,'' he said, referring to the embryo, ``and the
question is whether members of the human species should be treated
as other than ends in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a considerable range of views among both
Protestant and Catholic ethicists who testified before the National
Bioethics Advisory Commission in May. Within both faiths, some
believed the interests of the embryo were paramount; others said
that the moral status of the early embryo was sufficiently
uncertain and that research should go forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within the Catholic tradition a case can be made both against
and for such research,'' Margaret Farley, professor of Christian
ethics at Yale University, told the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Although the National Conference of Catholic Bishops has argued
against the use of spare embryos and aborted fetuses on the grounds
that embryos are equivalent to people, ``a growing number of
Catholic moral theologians, for example, do not consider the human
embryo in its earliest stages (prior to the development of the
primitive streak or to implantation) to constitute an
individualized human entity,'' Ms. Farley said. The primitive
streak, which appears 14 days after conception, marks the first
appearance of the nervous system and the earliest possible
stirrings of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we are still learning about the realities of what
this entity the embryo is,'' Ms. Farley said in an interview, ``and
therefore we need to be open about its moral status.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There may be a period of time before the embryo becomes
individualized _ up to a certain stage it can split into twins, for
example. If so, ``then you can say that in those early days it
doesn't have to be protected as if it were a human being,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jewish analysis of embryonic stem cell research, there is
no problem in using spare embryos from fertility clinics, said
Rabbi Elliot Dorff, a professor of philosophy at the University of
Judaism in Los Angeles. The sperm and egg, and early embryos
derived from them, ``have no legal status whatever in Jewish law
when they are outside the womb, because they have no potential for
becoming a human being,'' he said. Medically beneficial research
with the embryos is therefore ``very much to be encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorff, who has written a book on medical ethics, noted that in
Jewish law the fetus is not regarded as a fully fledged human being
until it emerges from the womb, until which point the mother's
health takes precedence. For its first 40 days of existence the
fetus is seen ``as if it were water,'' the Talmud says.
</P>
<P>
   A second way of deriving human embryonic stem cells is from the
so-called germline cells obtainable from aborted fetuses. Abortions
are by and large prohibited by Jewish law, but there are cases when
they are required or permitted. ``If a fetus were aborted for good
and sufficient reason, we could use its stem cells for saving other
people's lives,'' Dorff said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorff, a Conservative rabbi, said there was a spectrum of
opinion from Orthodox to Reform Judaism about the permissibility of
abortion, but the differences did not extend to stem cell research.
``The Jewish tradition has had a virtual love affair with medicine
for 2,000 years because it has seen the physician as God's agent
and partner in the ongoing act of healing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
