<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING SURPLUS UNLIKELY TO YIELD BIGGER TAX CUT, REPUBLICANS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Del., N.M., Ohio)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the projected federal budget surplus having
grown substantially since they first set their budget plans earlier
this year, Republican leaders in Congress said Thursday that they
would rethink their tax and spending proposals but would not
necessarily channel the entire windfall into a bigger tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The party's leadership in both the House and the Senate said the
new surplus projections made them more determined to pass a tax cut
of historic proportions despite the opposition of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But they backed off suggestions that they would expand their tax
cut to $1 trillion over the next decade, up from $778 billion under
their original plan. Instead, they said, the new surplus
projections provide an opportunity to divide the additional money
among a variety of needs, including a bigger tax cut, shoring up
Medicare and possibly easing a tight squeeze on spending for
domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office projected Thursday that the
total budget surplus over the next decade would be $2.9 trillion,
$293 billion higher than it estimated three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the surplus comes from excess Social Security payroll
taxes, which both parties have agreed should be off limits when it
comes to financing tax cuts or new spending. The non-Social
Security portion of the surplus _ the part they consider available
for tax cuts and spending _ will be $996 billion over the next
decade, the budget office said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget office's figures were slightly lower than projections
released on Monday by the White House's Office of Management and
Budget, which estimated the 10-year non-Social Security surplus at
$1.08 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton laid out a plan on Monday that would allocate $250
billion over 10 years for tax cuts in the form of incentives to
low- and middle-income families to save more for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He would allocate the remaining $758 billion over 10 years to
Medicare ($374 billion), increased military spending ($127
billion), a broad array of domestic spending ($127 billion) and new
spending specifically for education and children's programs ($74
billion). An additional $132 billion would go to interest payments.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have not yet come up with a specific plan for how
they will spend the money. Prior to the new budget projections,
they had intended to use virtually all of the non-Social Security
surplus over the next decade to pay for their $778 billion tax cut.
They said they would develop a plan before Congress returns from
its July 4th recess in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said on Tuesday that he would like to use every penny of
the non-Social Security surplus for tax cuts. But on Thursday _ at
a rally where he unveiled a list of tax-cutting ideas to the
accompaniment of a fife and drums corps _ he said only that he
would use ``a major portion of the available surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., said all of the newly projected
non-Social Security surplus for next year _ estimated by the
Congressional Budget Office at $14 billion _ should go to
increasing the size of the tax cut. Before the new projections,
there was no non-Social Security surplus next year, meaning any tax
cut would not have taken effect until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Roth, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, said the
additional money from the non-Social Security surplus in ensuing
years should be used first to help shore up Medicare and make
available a prescription drug benefit within the health insurance
system for the elderly and disabled. The drug benefit is a
cornerstone of Clinton's new Medicare proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, agreed that Congress should set aside money from the
non-Social Security surplus for Medicare. Domenici said he was also
open to the idea of using some of the new-found money to help ease
tight caps on spending that have made it all but impossible for
Congress to pass the appropriations bill necessary to keep the
government operating.
</P>
<P>
   Republican members of the appropriations committees in both
chambers have been pressing the party's leadership for months to
ease the caps, saying the alternative is gridlock. But their pleas
have only exacerbated the rift between the party's fiscal
conservatives, many of whom were elected on promises of slashing
spending, and those Republicans who consider themselves more
moderate or pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was willing to risk ``internal strife,'' Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Budget Committee and a
presidential candidate, warned Republicans who are seeking to ease
the spending caps that they ``should not continue to operate under
the illusion that they can spend more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said he might be willing to negotiate a deal with Clinton
on new spending programs, but only in return for the Republicans'
getting a very large tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can give the president a few shekels,'' Kasich said, ``but
he's going to have to pay the price of giving power back to the
American people'' in the form of tax cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
