<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-ANALYSIS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retooling Bulls one of draft's winners
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Much of the pre-NBA draft talk about trades was just
that _ talk. At least, that's how it looks. The league has a
moratorium on consummating deals until Aug. 1, meaning that team
officials can work on trades but not execute them until then.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the draft, as always, produced some winners and
losers _ and others. Here is a recap:
</P>
<P>
   Winners
</P>
<P>
   Chicago: The Bulls began their rebuilding with the solid Elton
Brand of Duke with the No. 1 pick and fortified their frontcourt
with defensive demon Ron Artest of St. John's. Those two could be
together for years to come. With about $13 million in salary-cap
space, Chicago still has room to be the big player in the
free-agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota: While Kevin McHale already has done a remarkable job
with the Timberwolves, considering defections by All-Star Tom
Gugliotta and Stephon Marbury in consecutive years, the team was
upgraded again with the selections of dead-eye shooting forward
Wally Szczerbiak with the sixth pick and point guard Willliam Avery
of Duke with the 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta: The troublesome position of point guard was filled by
talented rookie Jason Terry with the 10th pick. The Hawks could not
go into next season with Mookie Blaylock as the floor leader, and
Terry's presence and speed injects new blood and tempo.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland: The team with no coach did itself some good in
acquiring the backcourt of the future in Andre Miller (No. 8) and
Trajan Langdon (No.11). Miller is a point guard with poise, scoring
ability and passing skills. Langdon is the ideal complement, a
spot-up shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Miami: At No. 25, the Heat got a talented forward in Tim James,
who played collegiately at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Losers
</P>
<P>
   Dallas: Someone please explain how Don Nelson keeps a job. A
flop everywhere he has been the past five years, the general
manager/coach cast his ineptness again on the Mavericks. This time,
Nelson took Wang Zhi-Zhi of China with the 39th pick. Zhi-Zhi is
7-feet-4 with no discernible skills. Then Nelson traded with San
Antonio for the rights to high schooler Leon Smith.
</P>
<P>
   New York: With Artest available, the Knicks went for someone
named Frederic Weis, a 7-2 center from France. Call this an
overreaction to San Antonio's inside dominance in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto: Not sure what the Raptors were thinking by dealing
promising high schooler Jonathan Bender with the No. 5 pick to
Indiana for reserve big man Antonio Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Maybes
</P>
<P>
   Washington: The Wizards got insurance for a Mitch Richmond
departure by taking Richard Hamilton of UConn with the seventh
pick. Hamilton is the real deal, but he reminds some people of
former Georgetown star Reggie Williams. And that's frightening,
seeing as Williams was awful as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix: The Suns surprised everyone by taking forward Shawn
Marion in the lottery with the ninth choice. Marion has skills, but
no one projected him so high.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Clippers: By all accounts, Lamar Odom could be a force. But
he's a Clipper, which means anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
