<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6553 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SAM-SPI &LR;      07-01 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SAM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIKE LEE'S `SUMMER OF SAM' CAPTURES HYSTERIA THAT GRIPPED NEW YORK
CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNODL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since I happened to spend much of the summer of 1977 in New York
City, I feel qualified to report Spike Lee's ``Summer of Sam''
nails with almost eerie perfection the particular hysteria that
gripped the city during that season's ``Son of Sam'' murder spree.
</P>
<P>
   The film is basically the latest in a succession of late-'70s
nostalgia pieces, a cycle that includes ``The Last Days of Disco,''
``Boogie Nights'' and ``54.'' (It even has ``Boogie Nights'' on the
soundtrack, and has a scene at Studio 54 _ as if to play tribute to
the growing iconography of the era.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's by far the best of these late-'70s movies: It's more
stylistically and thematically audacious than its predecessors, and
more journalistically accurate. It's easily Lee's most accomplished
and satisfying movie since ``Malcolm X.''
</P>
<P>
   The script mostly follows the plight of Vinny (John Leguizamo)
and Dionna (Mira Sorvino), a young Bronx couple whose latent
marital problems come rising to the surface after one of Vinny's
back-seat infidelities just happens to take place near the scene of
the first of a epidemic of random murders committed by a nut case
who leaves letters calling himself ``Son of Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also Vinny's childhood pal, Ritchie (Adrien Brody), who
splits from his Italian neighborhood to become a part-time male
stripper and prostitute and a full-time, grotesquely mohawked, Sid
Vicious-style punk who finds a kind of grace when he falls in love
with Ruby (Jennifer Esposito), the good-hearted neighborhood slut.
</P>
<P>
   As the ongoing murder spree and a ferocious heat wave fan the
city's paranoia throughout the summer, Vinny _ convinced the killer
is after him personally _ becomes unhinged, while Ritchie's
unorthodox lifestyle convinces his vigilante-minded neighborhood
toughs that he must indeed be the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lee traces the impact of the murders on the rest of
New York, sends his characters out to catch some of the flavor of
the period (including an orgy at Plato's Retreat) and follows the
growing madness of the real serial killer, David Berkowitz, to the
point of dramatizing his delusion that he was ordered to do the
killings by a demonic talking dog.
</P>
<P>
   As always with Lee, a good portion of the mainstream movie
audience is likely to find the movie too sexually raw and
foul-mouthed to endure; and some of his quirkier moves simply don't
work: _ his decision, for instance, to cast himself as an
incompetent, comic-relief television reporter with a 6-inch Afro.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, Lee's characters and scenes ring
amazingly true, and the film, which opens and closes with
funny-but-perceptive commentary by columnist Jimmy Breslin, does an
extraordinary job of making the late-'70s spring to life, while
making us realize that it's as psychologically removed from our own
late '90s as the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   As much as any film Lee has made, this one is filled with
wonderful supporting actors in rich supporting roles _ Patti
LuPone, Bebe Neuwirth, Mike Star, Anthony LaPaglia, Michael
Rispoli, Michael Badalucco and Ben Gazarra (as a mob boss who
orders a hit on the unknown killer) are all memorable and
multidimensional.
</P>
<P>
   In his first movie with a predominately white cast, Lee seems to
have abandoned the anger, racial stereotyping and self-righteous
moralizing that have marred so many of his earlier films. All his
characters are viewed with genuine compassion _ especially Vinny
and Dionna, whose marriage is shown to be a tragic victim of a
fraudulent macho-sexual sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the film is brilliant. Lee's control and
storytelling flair have never seemed more assured and there are
moments so powerful and thrilling we feel we're in the hands of a
master filmmaker at the peak of his powers.
</P>
<P>
   Summer of Sam. Directed by Spike Lee. Screenplay by Lee, Victor
Colicchio and Michael Imperioli. Cast: John Leguizamo, Mira
Sorvino, Adrien Brody and Jennifer Esposito. Touchstone. 137
minutes. Rated R for explicit sex and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
