<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6554 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GUNS-ART-2TAKES     07-01 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GUNS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA PASSES LAW LIMITING HANDGUN PURCHASES TO ONE PER MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California Legislature Thursday approved a measure to limit
handgun purchases to one a month, making it the largest state to
pass a measure that gun-control advocates say would reduce the flow
of guns to criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control proponents and some law-enforcement officials have
long argued that sharply limiting the number of revolvers and
pistols that can be bought at one time is a major step in helping
close off the illegal gun market. The authorities say that
intermediaries for gun traffickers often buy several firearms at
once from federally licensed dealers, and the guns are then resold
to criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, a person who passes a background check can
buy an unlimited number of guns at one time and as often as they
wish. Three states _ Maryland, Virginia and South Carolina _ have
passed laws limiting handgun purchases to one every 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   In California, about 41,000 of the approximately 183,000
handguns sold in 1998 went to people who bought more than one
handgun at a time, according to data compiled by state regulators.
In some instances, the purchases involved eight guns or more.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, has not said whether he will sign
the bill, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the strongest measures in the country to shut
down the flow of handguns to the black market,'' said Luis Tolley,
a lobbyist for Handgun Control, an advocacy group. ``We hope
California's action will encourage other states and Congress to
adopt similar measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the legislation was the first setback for the
National Rifle Association after its recent success in defeating a
congressional proposal that would have strengthened federal laws on
firearm sales at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   But while advocates like Tolley applauded the passage of the
California bill, the impact of similar measures elsewhere has been
mixed. The new bill, like others that exist, applies only to
handguns, not to rifles.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement authorities in Virginia, which enacted a
one-handgun-a month measure in 1993, said that the law had reduced
the illegal trafficking of guns bought from dealers in the state.
But traffickers have simply turned elsewhere for weapons or
criminals have found other strategies to buy guns in Virginia,
federal and state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a notorious case in 1995, for instance, 15 members of the
Norfolk State University band fraternity, Kappa Kappa Psi, were
recruited by gun-runners to buy handguns one at a time from area
gun stores. The traffickers eventually shipped 100 handguns to
Washington, where many were used in crimes, according to newspaper
accounts published at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the impact of laws restricting handgun purchases to
one every 30 days has been far less harsh than predicted by dealers
and pro-gun groups like the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Marcus, the owner of Bob's Gun and Tackle Shop in
Norfolk, Va., and the president of the Virginia Firearms Dealers
Association, which opposed the Virginia law when it was proposed,
said that the law had not reduced sales. In addition, he said, the
number of customers who have complained about having to wait 30
days to buy more than one handgun has also been small.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that if the numbers bear out that there has been a
reduction in illicit trafficking, then I would have to say that
this is a positive,'' Marcus said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, licensed gun dealers must file a report with
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the federal agency
that regulates the manufacture and sale of guns, when an individual
buys two or more firearms from that dealer during any five-day
period. An ATF spokesman said that the agency receives some 1,500
to 1,800 reports each week, or up to 100,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   But connecting those multiple sales to handguns seized by the
police or recovered in connection with crimes is complicated. While
ATF data suggest that only about 1.3 percent of the crimes traced
by the agency since 1994 were determined to be part of a multiple
sale, that figure may be understated because the agency only began
to centralize multiple sales records in 1995, said Joseph J. Vince,
a former top ATF official.
</P>
<P>
   Vince said that the impact of a few states adopting such laws
would likely be small because illegal gun traffickers would either
go elsewhere or buy weapons from unregulated places like gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Helsley, the California representative for the NRA, said
that the group opposed the measure because it believed the bill did
not provide law-enforcement officials with any additional
crime-fighting tools.
</P>
<P>
   Helsley said that California already had a 10-day waiting period
before a handgun buyer can pick up a firearm, giving officials
ample opportunity to check on the buyer's background.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have what is arguably the most sophisticated system in the
United States, and the reason we are supposed to have this new law
is because it doesn't work,'' Helsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, California lawmakers twice defeated bills similar to
the one passed Thursday. But Tolley, the lobbyist for Handgun
Control, said that the tide turned in the bill's favor when it was
passed by the California state Assembly just days after the
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right before Littleton, I was saying we were three or four
votes short,'' Tolley said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Littleton shootings, President Clinton announced that
he backed the concept of restricting handgun sales to
one-per-month. But such a proposal never received serious
consideration in the recent congressional debate over firearms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
