<HEADER>
A6559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-N     07-01 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 04,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAYS-BEFORE-THEATER (Modena, Italy) _ ``The Days Before: Death,
Destruction and Detroit III'' was originally conceived as a piece
about the Apocalypse, and its 12 scenes are filled with bizarre
imagery and stylized movement. Each includes an excerpt read by the
actress Fiona Shaw from Umberto Eco's novel ``The Island of the Day
Before,'' the texts seemingly unrelated to the onstage action.
Robert Wilson, who conceived, designed and directs it, calls ``The
Days Before'' ``a celebration of humanity.'' Originally
commissioned by the Lincoln Center Festival, it will have its world
premiere in New York on Wednesday. By Anne Midgette. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ASSAYAS-FILMS (Paris) _ Olivier Assayas is someone who believes
in spontaneity and openness to the world. One of the most
significant talents among the new generation of filmmakers working
in France, he is known for his mobile, often handheld, camera style
and for his probing explorations of young people's lives. Assayas'
new film, ``Late August, Early September,'' which opens on
Wednesday, is a loosely structured, evocative depiction of a group
of thirtyish Parisians who are drawn together by the untimely death
of a slightly older writer friend. The film, shot in the spring of
1998, has proved to be Assayas's most successful in France so far,
winning praise last fall at both the Toronto and New York film
festivals. By Laura Winters. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-BALLET-DANCE (Undated) _ Going forward by looking back
may be bad advice, but American Ballet Theater has danced better
and better the more it has concentrated on the past _ a
19th-century repertory. Four of the seven full-length ballets in
the company's recent season at the Metropolitan Opera House were
French and Russian classics created more than 100 years ago. The
20th century did intrude, chiefly through the questionable transfer
of Kenneth MacMillan's ``Anastasia'' (1971) from the Royal Ballet.
To see Ballet Theater at its best, however, was to see it in
``Giselle'' and ``La Bayadere.'' By Anne Kisselgoff. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BORIS-GODUNOV-OPERA (New York) _ Modest Mussorgsky wrote ``Boris
Godunov'' twice. The first version, composed at white heat in 1868
and 1869 to a libretto adapted from Pushkin, comprises seven
tableaux organized into four acts and lasts barely two hours. It
was submitted to the directorate of the Imperial Theaters in 1871.
The directors were impressed but asked for changes, including a
substantial female role. A second ``Boris,'' completed in 1872,
consists of a prologue and four acts, and lasts almost three hours.
Today, at the Metropolitan Opera and elsewhere, ``Boris'' is often
performed with Mussorgsky's original vocal and instrumental parts.
But what we usually (at the Met, always) hear is a conflation of
1869 and 1872. This results in a panoramic ``Boris'' longer than
either version Mussorgsky composed: an abundance of marvels but,
arguably, not a finished product. By Joseph Horowitz. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OAR-ALBUM (Undated) _ Alexander (skip) Spence, who died in
April, recorded ``Oar'' in December 1968, an album of songs he had
written in Bellevue Hospital. He produced it himself and played all
the instruments himself. Released on May 19, 1969, ``Oar'' showed
one of the bleakest undersides of the '60s. It was a snapshot of
mental illness, a portrait of bitter isolation in a time of
communal celebration. On Tuesday, Sundazed Music will reissue a
remixed and remastered version of the album with 10 bonus tracks.
By Karen Schoemer. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE-CUBE-ALBUM (Undated) _ The Chicago Underground Trio's
new record, ``Possible Cube,'' is an act of creative destruction.
It is a graceful collage of free jazz and art rock. By Adam Shatz.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANK-O'HARA-ART (Undated) _ Frank O'Hara proved that friendship
is an art form all its own, as a new exhibition reminds us. The
show, ``In Memory of My Feelings: Frank O'Hara and American Art,''
opens next Sunday at the Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles
and remains on view through Nov. 14. An appealingly sentimental
affair, it rounds up some 100-odd works by 25 members of the O'Hara
gang _ from canonical Abstract Expressionists (Willem de Kooning,
Franz Kline, Philip Guston) to underrated figurative painters
(Fairfield Porter, Alice Neel, John Button) to celebrated Pop Art
pioneers (Jasper Johns, Claes Oldenburg) to at least one essential
eccentric (Joe Brainard, who took his cue from comic strips before
giving up art to devote himself full-time to reading Victorian
novels). By Deborah Solomon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   UNCLE-SAM-ART (Undated) _ Contrary to popular belief, Uncle Sam
wasn't born on the Fourth of July but on Sept. 13, 1766, in
Arlington, Mass. And he had many guises before James Montgomery
Flagg painted a stern, white-haired man proclaiming,
ungrammatically, ``I want YOU for U.S. Army.'' Uncle Sam's namesake
was Samuel Wilson, a meat packer who settled in Troy, N.Y., and
supplied food to American troops during the War of 1812. According
to legend _ and to an eyewitness report published in The New-York
Gazette and General Advertiser in 1830 _ a workman joked that the
letters ``U.S.'' on Wilson's shipping crates stood for ``Uncle
Sam'' Wilson. The anecdote spread and led to the patriotic symbol
now reproduced in political cartoons, advertisements, posters and
fine art. By Sarah Bayliss. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   LA-REBUILD-ARCH (Los Angeles) _ Seven years after the Los
Angeles riots shook Southern California and the world, the words
``South-Central'' still evoke the open wounds of urban decay and
social dislocation. But here on a wide swath of once-grand Vermont
Avenue at 81st Street, seedlings of renewal are taking root this
summer. Against all odds, 36 mustard-colored, stucco town houses _
half of them built above storefronts facing the street and the rest
around an interior court _ are filling up with first-time
homeowners, most of them single mothers. In the process, Vermont
Village Plaza is testing anew the possibilities of the New Urbanism
of its award-winning architect, Daniel Solomon. By Todd S. Purdum.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-RKO-281 (Undated) _ When Orson Welles made his masterpiece
``Citizen Kane'' in 1941, it was no secret that the film's
protagonist, Charles Foster Kane, was a barely fictionalized
version of William Randolph Hearst, the newspaper magnate whose
enormous empire was then beginning to falter under a barrage of
debts. But there was a drama behind the drama, as Welles _ then
just 25 and swelled by the arrogance of youth and genius _ found
himself up against the full force of Hearst's fury. Hearst was
desperate to stop the film, no matter what the cost, and nearly
succeeded in having it destroyed before it had ever been released.
Now the story of their battle is to be the subject of its own film.
``RKO 281,'' which takes its name from ``Citizen Kane's'' working
title at the RKO studio, will have its premiere on HBO in November.
By Sarah Lyall. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
