<HEADER>
A6561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-PROFILE02-COX     07-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-PROFILE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Professor's plants are a labor of love
 &HT;    By Meggen Lindsay
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ He gently stooped and cut the last stem for his
bouquet, careful not trample on the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Bela Bognar's wife April usually would be with him in the garden
_ she plants the flowers and he does the vegetables _ but she is in
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight he will take the flowers to her room, along with the
pictures he took of her garden, so she can visualize its progress.
This has been his routine all of June, after April suffered an
aneurism on the first of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hoping she will be out of the hospital by August,'' he
said. ``She misses her garden, so I bring her huge bouquets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bognar, who responded to our May 27 HomeLife survey, wrote about
his garden and his memories of gardening in vivid detail, making it
clear how much care he devotes to his vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is a fixture at his wife's side, he takes time every
afternoon to return to his Casstown country home to take care of
the gardens _ the flower gardens, the small vegetable plot in the
back yard, and his own garden, spanning the size of four tennis
courts, located on his neighbor's farm.
</P>
<P>
   And what a garden it is.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with rows and rows of vegetables, or ``veggies'' as he
calls them, there are more than 200 tomato plants, 500 pepper
plants, cucumbers, zucchini and lettuce by the bushel.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter he converts his front porch into a greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very quiet and cold in the beginning (of February), but
life soon begins as over 2,000 seeds emerge,'' he said. ``Some dig
downward and some push upward, all wanting to see the light.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are species from Europe that Bognar, a native of Hungary,
gathered on his travels. Bognar is passionate, almost scholarly,
when discussing his vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I'm trying a new line of tomatoes not known in
America: they are the Crimean tomato, brought over by Russian
refugees,'' he said, checking his dictionary to be certain of the
spelling.
</P>
<P>
   He's not as confident when it comes to his wife's gardens,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do the the veggies only,'' he explained. ``I don't even know
the names of the flowers that April has.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the 68-year-old Wright State gerontology and social
work professor, the father of local filmmaker Steven Bognar, tends
to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Loading buckets into his pickup, Bognar fills them and waters
his garden, using a system he has perfected throughout his years of
gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can empty one can before another is filled,'' he reported.
``If I time it right, I can usually water all of the plants in my
garden in three hours.'' The flowers take another two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he has had some help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone stopped by yesterday and watered the east garden,'' he
said. ``Some good Samaritan helps me. . . . Everybody has been
trying to help me. The best thing they can do is water.''
</P>
<P>
   ognar and his wife give most of what they grow away _ to St.
Vincent De Paul's homeless shelter, the Salvation Army, their
church, and to anyone else hungry for fresh vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that I grow goes to good causes,'' he said. ``I don't grow
for myself to make a profit, I grow for pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bognar's garden produces hundreds of tomatoes, he
doesn't even like them _ he feeds others with them instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturdays, I take big buckets of vegetables to (St.
Vincent's) shelter,'' he said. ``I've been doing this since it
opened 18 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bognar does sell any of his vegetables, the proceeds go to a
Hungarian scholarship fund he began for Wright State University
students. He has earned $8,000 for the scholarship from garden
sales and donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an irony in this,'' he said. ``I was to retire before
my wife took sick ... I even had my party with over 200 people
there... Now I can't afford to retire _ I have too many other
considerations and benefits to think of. But now I will continue to
raise money for my scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Most days, however, they don't bother to sell their vegetables.
April keeps a blackboard outside during the summer that states:
``Today's free perennials are ...'' and there is a table set up
with free vegetables and flowers for people driving past their
house, a 130-year-old schoolhouse that he and his wife restored
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice,'' Bognar said. ``We are outside most of the time
and people always stop to talk with us. People always want
gardening advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, 'The lecture you pay for, the veggies are
free,''' he laughed. ``People want me to tell them all I know about
gardening from 60 years in just one minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Bognar knows about gardening came from his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had gardens where I grew up in Hungary,'' he said.
``I followed my mother all around her garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never stepped on a single plant, and when I asked her why,
she told me, 'You never want to hurt the ones you care for.' I have
to admit that after all my years of gardening, I have not yet
reached such a communion with my garden, but I continue to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
