<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOOPLIFE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOOP LIFE' NEEDS TIME IN TRAINING CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So I'm sitting in the newsroom with a friend, trying to come up
with ideas for a TV series that would make it easy for the
producers to feature a multiracial cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about something about a pro basketball team?'' my friend
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. You can't possibly do an accurate portrayal of pro hoops
with only high-fivin' white guys.
</P>
<P>
   But before we can sell the idea to anyone but ourselves, Tom
Fontana and Barry Levinson, two of TV's hottest auteurs-du-jour,
put their imprimatur on ``The Hoop Life,'' a new series beginning
Sunday on Showtime pay cable.
</P>
<P>
   Like a team starting slowly so it can peak for the playoffs,
``The Hoop Life'' looks like a train wreck at the start of its
95-minute premiere. Some of the acting by supporting cast members
is downright obvious, the way it would look if I were part of the
cast. And no matter how good the basketball action is, it's still a
simulation that looks like a simulation. Director Kevin Hooks could
have cut the hoop scenes by half without losing anything but a lot
of film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hoop Life'' centers on three players _ an aging veteran
portrayed by Mykelti Williamson, a philandering big man played by
Rick Peters, and a wide-eyed teenage phenom played by Cirroc
Lofton. They play for the New England Knights of the United
Basketball Association, and their coach is a grumpy, lumpy sort
played by Dan Lauria.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Lauria seems more suited to the National Football
League than to the Armani-suited corps de coaching common in the
National Basketball Association. Ah, but this is the United
Basketball Association. Maybe they don't have a dress code.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, everything else about ``The Hoop Life'' is faithful
to the NBA ethic, if that's the right word. There are agents and
managers, sex-happy groupies and strip clubs, fancy cars and
fancier homes, all powered by the enormous sums paid to young men
whose maturity levels are stuck somewhere between the fourth grade
and the fourth dimension. And because this is pay cable, the
language is quite accurate and the groupies are quite naked.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first episode, I was mildly interested in what
happens down the road, particularly to Lofton's character, Curtis
Thorpe. But I'll lose no sleep if I miss the next 20 episodes,
either. ``The Hoop Life'' is likely to appeal to hormone-charged
males who'd love to identify with this line, spoken by the cousin
of Peters' high-scoring character, if you get my drift: ``Greg,''
he says, ``you're 25 years old, you're a millionaire, women who
only want sex are throwing themselves at you constantly. You're
doing what any man in your situation would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out basketball is a contact sport.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoop Life. New drama series about professional basketball
players. Starring Mykelti Williamson, Cirroc Lofton, Rick Peters
and Dan Lauria. Premieres Sunday on Showtime. Parental guideline
rating: TV-MA.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
