<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SAVING PUBLIC COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By A.M. ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For weeks, I have had the most important report on
the most important university in the life and future of New York
City. But I did not read it. I just glared at it.
</P>
<P>
   The cover put me off, hard _ ``The City University of New York:
An Institution Adrift.'' Another attack on the publicly financed
college that led me to work I have loved ever since? Who needs it?
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My City College was an intellectually and academically elite
school attended by students with family income ranging from not
much to very not much. Eventually it was grouped legislatively with
16 other senior and community colleges into the City University of
New York _ which now carries the hopes of the 200,000 students who
attend it.
</P>
<P>
   I knew CUNY has had deep faults and problems since it opened the
doors to all high school graduates in 1969. Academically it has all
the cachet of a herring.
</P>
<P>
   I also knew that the color palette of the student body has
changed from almost entirely white to 72 percent other shades. For
most of their families, CUNY was the first college, and blessed.
</P>
<P>
   I resented the nastiness of the criticism of CUNY, like Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's advice to the students to learn how to work. Try
working for food, clothes, carfare at night while working for
graduation credits by day. You just won't have the energy left for
polo.
</P>
<P>
   When I did read the report after a few weeks, the glare
disappeared. This is a report written under the leadership of
Herman Badillo, recently appointed chairman of CUNY by the mayor,
and Benno Schmidt Jr., former president of Yale.
</P>
<P>
   My eyes softened when I realized the goal was not to eliminate
CUNY or shrink it _ as some students and teachers fear _ but to
restore some of its academic glisten, so graduates would again help
lead the city and profit from its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the most valuable qualities of the report were three
varieties of respect. Perhaps the most important: the tone of
belief in what students could do for themselves and the city if
CUNY gave them the dignity of higher goals of achievements, not the
sub-college standards that are good enough now.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the respect of pledging ``absolute commitment'' to
CUNY's ``historic organizational mission'' to provide first-rate
college opportunities for all New Yorkers academically able to take
advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   Third: proposals to help those not ready because of the failure
of New York's elementary and high school system to teach so many
students more than a humiliatingly low level of writing, reading
and arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   The most important step is the first step: to establish and help
students reach acceptable goals not only in college but before they
enter it.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all American colleges provide remedial courses. But
CUNY's load and the lack of standards of remedial achievement for
the college bound drag down CUNY with too many students unqualified
for higher education. The report proposes that remedial classes be
held not in the four-year senior colleges but in the community
colleges, and that passing them must be the requirement for senior
colleges _ with national standard entry tests to come.
</P>
<P>
   The way things are in New York, the elementary and high school
system often prepares students for failure in college. The report
proposes widening the emergency remedy now in some schools: CUNY
teachers using summers and other free time for tutorials in
reading, writing and mathematics in high schools and the late
grades of elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   That will cost money _ about $10 million _ and so will other
proposals. The end of ``social promotion'' in elementary schools, a
cockamamie, basically political idea, that shoves all students on
to the next grade, ready or not. Technological unification for
planning throughout CUNY, a kind of remediation for management.
</P>
<P>
   Writing an important report is difficult; getting the money out
of politicians for achievement, not stagnation, that's really hard.
</P>
<P>
   They must remember that when CUNY opened its doors wide in 1969,
it did not switch its goals from achievement to mediocrity and
failure. Open enrollment has worked out for those who had
qualifications, not for those who did not. This report is not an
attack on public higher education, but the opposite _ an effort to
improve and protect it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
