<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glavine lifts Braves' spirits with complete-game win
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Braves came back to America through the front
door Thursday night. And Tom Glavine held it open for them.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta opens what should be a fun-packed weekend at Shea
Stadium tonight, when the occasion might well have been a dirge.
Glavine threw a complete-game 4-1 victory at Montreal Thursday,
managing a split in the kind of series that can alter a season.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no altering this fact: Glavine now has beaten the
Expos 13 times in a row. And with the club's bullpen given a day's
liberty, the two excruciating late-inning losses earlier in the
week gained some distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there today more so trying to pitch some innings to
give those guys a break,'' said Glavine, who won his fourth in a
row to reach 7-7. ``It wasn't because I was afraid to get 'em in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine worked the last seven innings with a swelling left hand,
after Manny Martinez smashed a one hopper off his palm in the
third. Although the swelling eventually hindered the grip on his
fastball, Glavine remained effective, aided by two double plays. He
retired the last eight men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our young players were like meat for him,'' Montreal manager
Felipe Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough, man,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``I've seen
him pitch when he's had a lot of problems in the last 10 years.
Today was pretty tough, too. ... And I didn't use the bullpen ...
Two days rest with (John) Rocker is great for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves stranded 13 runners, but they scored immediately on
Ryan Klesko's two-out, two-run double in the first. The RBIs gave
Klesko nine in six games and switched the topic from the last two
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're really upset, because you got the feeling you're going
to win and they beat you,'' Klesko said. ``You just got to let it
go. Obviously, you're mad that night, but when this team comes to
the park the next day, with the pitching staff we got, if we score
some runs, we got a good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss also returned from the disabled list to
drive in a run in the fourth and test his injured quadriceps muscle
on several fielding plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a new defensive back in the game,'' Weiss said.
``They went deep on me right away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
