<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-N0TES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping Weiss off DL may be difficult task
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Walt Weiss came off the disabled list Thursday. The
bigger trick is keeping him off.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves shortstop was 1-for-4 with an RBI in the Expos finale
and said he felt no ill effects after spending nine innings on the
National League's most brutal playing surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably be a little while before I'm confident about
exploding down the line or really taking off,'' Weiss said. ``I
figure it'll take a few days of cautious running until you get to
that point where you don't have a problem. Then you just forget
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not hesitate in racing behind second to make a
tough play on a Orlando Cabrera grounder in the fifth, Weiss hasn't
been able to forget about the sore quadriceps muscle since joining
the Braves last year. He never was disabled in 1998, but he
appeared in just 96 games, primarily because of the quadriceps
strain in his right leg. He strained the same muscle running out a
single in Milwaukee on May 26 and has spent the subsequent 23 days
on the DL. Already this year, he has missed 33 games.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox said he has no plan to increase reserve Ozzie
Guillen's playing time in order to give Weiss more downtime. While
Weiss was on the DL, Guillen hit .333 with eight doubles and three
stolen bases. But Cox did not sound as if he envisions the two
shortstops sharing the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play it by ear,'' Cox said. ``Use common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Training and conditioning personnel have just about run out of
help for Weiss. Strength and conditioning coach Frank Fultz might
try a slide board next, to stretch the muscles in his leg. But
Weiss not only grades out, pound for pound, as one of the strongest
players on the team, he also is one of the most flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to me, because we've tried too many different
avenues of strategy already,'' Fultz said.
</P>
<P>
   To open a spot, Mark DeRosa was optioned to Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Risin' Simon
</P>
<P>
   Rookie first baseman Randall Simon recorded his first four-hit
game, a double and three singles, off three Expos pitchers. A
disappointing .256 season in Richmond last season _ his sixth year
in the organization _ put his future with the franchise in
question, but his response this summer has been impressive. He
enters the New York series hitting .330.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to be here and show I can play at this level,'' Simon
said. ``I know that Big Cat (Andres Galarraga) is not here, but I
know he's looking, and I got to make him proud of me for what I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Braves have worked with Simon to make him more
selective at the plate, they appreciate his aggressiveness, which
he never lost even when his average dipped to .232 in mid-June. In
the 14 games since, he is 21 for 44 (.477), and he closed out the
Montreal series 8-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   Pelican brief
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have extended their player development contract with
the Class A Myrtle Beach Pelicans of the Carolina League through
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
