<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-HAWKS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks suddenly get younger
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Very eager and appearing terribly young, the three
draft picks sat at a table Thursday in a meeting room of the Omni
Hotel. They wore Hawks caps and grins, eyes sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   You can say this much for the new Atlanta players. They are
bright and feisty, a little cocky, but so fresh from the classroom
each wanted to thank the ``administration'' for drafting him. If
anyone questions their ability to play the game, they are ready to
take issue.
</P>
<P>
   Take center-forward Cal Bowdler, who played at Old Dominion in
the mid-level Colonial Conference. ``I came from a small Class A
high school to play Division I,'' the No. 17 pick said. ``I'll work
hard and keep getting better now that I'm in the NBA. I can't wait
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks general manager Pete Babcock says he has no question about
the talent level of any of the three:
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 10 pick Jason Terry, who led the Pac-10 in scoring, steals
and assists at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bowdler, a 6-10, 255-pounder who scored 23 points against
North Carolina last season.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 20 pick Dion Glover of Georgia Tech, who suffered a
serious knee injury last fall.
</P>
<P>
   And while Terry is well-known and figures to have a bright
future in the NBA, Babcock needed to explain his decision to take
Glover, who played only as a freshman at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had stayed in school another year as I urged him to do,
he would have been a top 10 pick next season,'' Babcock said.
``When we got to the 20th pick, there was simply no way I was going
to pass on a top 10 player.'' The Hawks' roster appears far from
ready. The club's 15-man roll includes seven players between 20 and
24 years old.
</P>
<P>
   It is increasingly apparent that some of the veteran names are
going to change. Forwards Duane Ferrell, newly reacquired from
Golden State, and Ty Corbin have only an outside chance of making
this team. Corbin, who will be 37, has a ``make good'' deal for
next season with a buyout, the only way the Hawks could pay him for
services rendered after two years on a minimum contract.
</P>
<P>
   Babcock acknowledges serious trade conversations with three
teams. He said talks were of such a sensitive nature he would
neither confirm nor deny any name.
</P>
<P>
   Portland is believed to be one of those teams, and Steve Smith
is reportedly involved.The chief player Portland wants to move is
shooting guard Isaiah Rider, who has one year remaining on his
contract at $5.4 million. Since Smith goes to $7.3 million next
season with the Hawks, it would take more than one player to
balance the trade.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith is the epitome of professionalism and a dynamic
scorer, Rider is flamboyant and a chronic problem with an arrest
record and a history of walking out during games and arriving late
to practice. For an organization that preaches good citizenship, he
would appear to be the anti-Hawk.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rider is not the only Blazers guard who could be up for
trade. Jim Jackson had a loud argument with coach Mike Dunleavy in
the locker room during the Western finals and is unhappy. Too, the
club has a deep stable of young big men, including Brian Grant and
Jermaine O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   No deal can be completed until Aug. 1, by league rule.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
