<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CLIMB DESPITE RISE IN INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Overcoming an early stumble, stock prices climbed
steadily Thursday to finish with sizable gains despite a rise in
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock
index explored record territory for the second straight day, while
the Dow Jones industrial average advanced 95.62 points to jump back
over the 11,000 mark. It closed at 11,066.42, within 41 points of
its May 13 peak.
</P>
<P>
   A report of strong activity at the nation's factories last month
combined with some second thoughts about Federal Reserve policy to
drive interest rates higher as investors awaited the government's
release Friday on June employment.
</P>
<P>
   But the rate increase subsided as the day wore on, and Treasury
yields finished just slightly higher, with the yield on the 30-year
Treasury bond at 6 percent, up from 5.96 percent on Wednesday. The
price, which moves in the opposite direction from the yield, fell
18/32 to 89 20/32. Stock traders took the rate rise in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock and bond markets seem to be taking different
views,'' said Timothy Ghriskey, senior portfolio manager at Dreyfus
Corp. Bond people, he said, are impressed by the fact that Federal
Reserve rate increases are rarely one-shot exercises and that it
was not all that encouraging that the Fed dropped its bias to
tighten while raising rates Wednesday. The Fed has traditionally
done this, he added, albeit without an immediate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market participants, on the other hand, were largely
persuaded, Ghriskey said, that the Fed was merely taking back an
extra rate cut tied to global turmoil and that the economy would
keep bounding ahead, as implied by the manufacturing figures
released by the National Association of Purchasing Management.
</P>
<P>
   There was no clear pattern in the day's brisk stock trading,
however, with the technology-heavy NASDAQ composite rising 20.06
points, to close at 2,706.18, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index rising 8.25 points, to close at 1,380.96.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is reacting well'' to the week's economic reports
and the Fed action, said Paul Rich, a trader at BT Brokerage.
``This is real positive, real institutional, too,'' he added,
expressing confidence that the imminent start of the quarterly
earnings-report season would give a further lift to stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The volatility index of the Chicago Board Options Exchange
skidded to 19.80, the lowest so far this year, from 21.01 on
Wednesday, an indication of reduced worry among investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can think of anything that's going to spoil the
picnic,'' said Lawrence Cavanagh, an options specialist at Value
Line.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor, drug and oil stocks were among Thursday's biggest
winners. Intel, the biggest chipmaker, gained 3 3/8 to 62 7/8,
aided by inclusion in Lehman Brothers' annual list, published
Thursday, of its 10 favorite stocks for the next 12 months. The
investment house also chose KLA-Tencor, whose products are used in
chip manufacturing; it spurted 4 1/16 to 68 15/16. Motorola gained
3 9/16 to 98 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly, another Lehman stock, rose 3 1/4 to 74 7/8, Pfizer 1
1/16 to 37 3/8 following a three-for-one-split, and Merck 1 5/8 to
75 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic-Richfield paced the oils, rising 3 3/8 to 86 15/16
while Texaco, Chevron and merger-partners Exxon and Mobil all
gained between 1 and 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks, which after the close on Wednesday said expansion
costs would shrink earnings for rest of the year, was a prominent
casualty, skidding 10 5/8 to 26 15/16. Nike was also punished after
warning of lower domestic orders while reporting an eight-fold
quarterly profit increase.
</P>
<P>
   In its first day of trading, Yankee Candle Co., a maker of
scented candles, jumped 6 1/8 to 24.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume retreated to 828.6
million shares from Wednesday's 1.1 billion, the fourth-heaviest
ever, as advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by 1,694 to
1,383. New 52-week highs were made by 108 stocks, new lows by 40.
</P>
<P>
   The other seven Lehman picks for the year ahead were America
Online, AT&AMP;T, Firstar Corp., Ford, General Instrument, Microsoft
and Tyco International. The ``uncommon values'' list soared 51.2
percent in the year that ended June 30, more than double the 21.1
percent returned by the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
