<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS PALESTINIANS SHOULD BE ABLE TO SETTLE WHEREVER THEY
WANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that Palestinian
refugees should be able to settle ``wherever they want to live,''
startling Israeli officials with what appeared to be a significant
shift in U.S. policy on one of the Middle East's most contentious
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking at a news conference with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, said he would like it if the hundreds of thousands
of Palestinian refugees scattered around the Middle East ``felt
free and were free'' to live wherever they chose.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate disposition of the refugees is one of the thorniest
issues in Israeli-Palestinian negotiations and is expected to be
one of the final matters settled when talks resume later this year.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Clinton was asked to compare his views
on resettling Kosovo refugees with Palestinian settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just look at it as a practical matter,'' the president
said, ``the agreement that is made in the end, whether refugees go
home depends in part on how long they've been away and whether they
wish to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will also depend on what the nature of the settlement is:
How much land will the Palestinians have? Where will it be? How
does it correspond to where people lived before?'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded his answer with a statement that alarmed supporters
of Israel: ``And I would like it if the Palestinian people felt
free and were free to live wherever they liked, wherever they want
to live.''
</P>
<P>
   White House and State Department aides immediately denied that
Clinton meant to alter existing U.S. policy on refugee
resettlement, which has deemed the matter one that should be
resolved solely by the Israelis and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   One State Department official told officials with the Israeli
embassy immediately after the news conference that Clinton had
spoken imprecisely, according to an Israeli official, and had not
intended to signal a new direction for Mideast policy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Taken at face value, the president's words indicate that the all
Palestinians should be able to return ``home'' _ even if that is
core Israeli territory, said Robert Satloff, director of the
Washington Institute for Near East Policy, a group sympathetic to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a significant statement,'' Satloff said. ``Even if you
were to look at it in its most benign context, it still is an
articulation of American policy on an issue that heretofore we
haven't spoken on. Substantively, it takes U.S. policy into a new
territory much closer to the traditional Palestinian approach to
resolving the refugee issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration policy aides insisted that the president
intended no change in policy or emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Jewish-American groups will say this represents a
departure, but it doesn't,'' said a senior foreign policy aide,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``He specifically said the
resolution would depend on refugees themselves and the shape of the
agreement they reached.''
</P>
<P>
   In other remarks, Clinton and Mubarak expressed pleasure and
relief at the election of Ehud Barak as Israel's prime minister
after three and a half years of grudging progress on Palestinian
issues and domestic political paralysis under the defeated Israeli
prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again,'' Clinton said in his opening remarks, ``we now
have a real chance to move the peace process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak echoed him. ``In the months ahead, we'll be looking
forward to reviving the peace process which has been stalled for
some time,'' the Egyptian leader said. ``Unfortunately, valuable
time has been wasted. Today there is an opportunity which should
not be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli embassy official said that Barak did not need to be
reminded of the lack of progress between Israel, the Palestinians
and neighboring states over the past several years. Barak intends
to act quickly after he and his new government are sworn in,
probably next week, the official said, speaking on condition he not
be identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Barak needs to hear that,'' the official said,
referring to the importunings of Mubarak and Clinton to act quickly
to restart talks with the Palestinians. ``I think Barak wants to
move, on both the Syria-Lebanon track and on the Palestinian track.
He wants to do it, it's part of his program, that's what he was
elected to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he would meet with Barak ``within days'' to
begin to thaw relations between the United States and Israel and to
discuss ways to restart peace negotiations. Aides later said
Clinton meant that he would meet the Israeli prime minister within
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said that he intended to visit Washington shortly
after he talks office for a one-on-one conversation with the
president. White House aides and Israeli officials said that the
meeting would probably take place sometime after July 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
