<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL REPUBLICANS THWART CLINTON ON NEW TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ind., Md., N.J.)  (rk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the second time in three months, congressional
Republicans have voted to block the Clinton administration's plan
to hire 100,000 new teachers and reduce class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   In a straight party-line vote, Republicans on the House
Committee on Education and the Work Force Wednesday defeated a
Democratic amendment to an education bill that, among other things,
would have authorized $1.2 billion in the next fiscal year to
finance the initiative. The amendment offered by Rep. Matthew G.
Martinez, D-Calif., was defeated 23-21.
</P>
<P>
   The committee then passed a bill sponsored by Rep. Howard P.
McKeon, R-Calif., that left it up to local districts whether to
spend a total of $2 billion a year either on hiring more teachers
or providing additional training to current teachers. The bill
passed by a vote of 27-19, with two Democrats, Reps. Tim Roemer of
Indiana and Rush Holt of New Jersey, voting with the Republican
majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration wants to put 100,000 new teachers into
classrooms, but requiring this would force states and local school
districts to put many unqualified teachers in the classroom,'' said
Bill Goodling, R-Pa., who is the committee's chairman. ``We allow
schools to decide whether they should use the funds to reduce class
size or improve the quality of their existing teachers, or hire
additional special education teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative aimed at bringing classes down to 18 students in
the first three grades has been a major point of contention between
the White House and congressional leaders for both policy and
political reasons. The issue emerged as a major sticking point as
Clinton and congressional Republicans tried to hammer out an
omnibus spending bill just before last fall's election.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent a politically unpopular government shutdown,
congressional Republicans agreed to the 100,000 teacher initiative
and provided money for one fiscal year to hire the first 30,000
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But in March, Republicans considering an education bill in the
Senate and the House voted to transfer money for hiring teachers
over the next five years into other programs. After the White House
threatened to veto the education bill, the Republicans dropped
their efforts to shift money away from the class-size initiative,
though the education measure was enacted without the money for
hiring more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   This weeks' action indicates the Republicans remain firm in
their opposition to allowing Clinton's class-size initiative to
pass.
</P>
<P>
   That opposition stems in part from policy differences. Clinton's
plan focuses on low-income rural and inner-city school districts.
The Republican proposal would spread federal dollars around to more
well-to-do suburban school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is a direct attack on those schoolchildren who most
need federal help,'' said Rep. William Clay, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the measure is caught up in presidential politics,
people from both sides acknowledge privately. The White House is
hoping to make the teacher initiative a major theme in the coming
campaign. The Republicans would like to deprive it of that theme in
a way that shows they care just as much about education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
