<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIF-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS TO CURRY FAVOR IN SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Encroaching on political turf that Vice
President Al Gore has cultivated for years, Gov. George W. Bush
ventured into Silicon Valley on Thursday to fatten his already
flush campaign treasury and to unveil proposals favored by the
technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor departed from his standard text to make an
aggressive pitch to the computer titans in the room, a group with
growing political influence that both political camps are wooing.
He chided President Clinton and Gore, among other things, for not
allowing American companies to sell sensitive high-technology
products overseas when those products are available from
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our best companies feel frustrated that they cannot sell some
of their products abroad even when equipment technology is sold by
foreign competitors,'' he said at a breakfast attended by about 500
people.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, in a step the administration has been headed
toward for some time, the White House announced an easing of export
restrictions on high-powered computers, which computer makers had
lobbied for aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also criticized the administration for not loosening
immigration restrictions that would allow technology companies to
recruit more workers. He suggested that the administration had
moved too slowly to embrace a bill in Congress that would limit
lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer breakdowns. And he
advocated lower taxes for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters paid $1,000 apiece to hear Bush's pitch for the
Republican presidential nomination at the breakfast meeting here or
at a dinner on Thursday night in San Francisco. In all, he took in
$1.7 million from the two events, contributing to a total of $5
million from California this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, we were one of the first states to protect the
technology industry from Y2K legislation _ the biggest potential
ambulance chase in the millenium,'' Bush said. ``I'm pleased to see
that our current president may be signing a bill of some form that
came out of Congress. In this administration, wisdom comes so
rarely that we should not complain even if it comes too late. But
I'll tell you this, from the very beginning I will take the side of
innovation over litigation every single time.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor also advocated an increase in the number of highly
skilled workers allowed into the country under visas known as H1-B,
a move adamantly opposed by labor unions. He said the cap of
115,000 workers for this year has already been reached, and that
could damage companies facing a shortage of computer engineers and
software technicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The limit on H1-B visas should be raised, Mr. President and
Mr. Vice President,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the closest Bush came to directly taking on Gore, the
leading candidate for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign advisers said they had considered lambasting the
vice president head on. But ultimately, they said, they decided _
and Bush concurred _ that there would be no gain in directly
attacking Gore this early and at a time when polls show he is far
less popular than Bush. They said the outpouring at the event here
on Thursday would speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be disingenuous to say there wasn't some
discussion,'' one Bush adviser, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said of the talks about whether to go after Gore. ``But
the basic feeling was that we have our own agenda to lay out.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, Bush's national finance chairman, disputed that the
campaign had invaded Gore's territory. ``That's a myth,'' he said
as donors dined on quiche and sausages. ``It was never his turf.
It's one of the great myths of America _ and we're demonstrating
that this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he stuck to his own agenda for the most part, Bush could
not resist referring to Gore's famous gaffe that he had invented
the Internet. He incorporates a line about that in virtually every
speech _ and it was particularly well received on Thursday.
Democrats, he said, ``no more invented prosperity than they
invented the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Romash, the deputy chairwoman of the Gore campaign, said
the vice president was not threatened by the outpouring here for
Bush. ``This is one of those places where he has support and we
have a lot of support,'' Ms. Romash said. ``We're pleased with the
level of support we're receiving.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Gore has long held a deep interest in computers, many
software financiers are Republicans. And Bush has some ties of his
own to the industry. In Texas, he has assiduously tapped executives
in the ``Silicon Hills'' of Austin, where many software and
semiconductor companies are based.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks on Thursday morning, Bush went out of his way to
cite Silicon Valley again and again _ far more than he has other
regions on this last day of his three-day swing up and down
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredibly fascinating place,'' he said. ``To me, it
means more than a V-chip or an area or a spot on the map,'' It's a
piece of the spirit of America. It not only talks about new
technologies that shape our lives, but it speaks about daring, and
enterprise _ and the ultimate American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other proposals, Bush called for freeing the Internet from
duties and tariffs; proposed a permanent federal tax credit for
research and development and reduction in marginal tax rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
