<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ADVISERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE HIRES MORE ADVISERS AFTER RIVALS GAIN IN FUND RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore hired several new advisers
Thursday, a day after learning that both his Republican and
Democratic competitors for the presidency had raised surprising
amounts of cash in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   While a Gore spokesman said that the hirings had nothing to do
with the fund-raising figures, one source close to the campaign
described Gore aides as ``catatonic'' over the news that Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner, had taken in $36
million so far and Gore's Democratic challenger, former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, had raised $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's cache was well shy of the the Gore campaign's $18.5
million but considerably better than expected in a race against a
sitting vice president. A second source said the Gore campaign was
particularly concerned by the Bradley numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore spokesman, Chris Lehane, said the hirings had been in
the works well before the campaign numbers were released.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane insisted that no one at the Gore campaign was
``catatonic.'' ``I would say, `nonchalant,''' he said. ``The Gore
campaign is exactly where it hoped to be, and Republicans almost
always outraise Democrats.'' Asked about Bradley's numbers, he
said, ``I'll let other people evaluate other campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a statement, Lehane also said that ``Gore campaign
chairman Tony Coelho was brought in to build a team, and he is
doing just that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho is bringing in Celinda Lake, a pollster, and has hired
Gore's old friend Carter Eskew as senior media adviser _ a
surprising addition because Gore's longtime media adviser, Bob
Squier, and Eskew are former business partners who had a famous
falling out several years ago. Eskew, a consultant for tobacco and
pharmaceutical companies, will not be replacing Squier, Lehane
said, adding that their specific roles are not yet clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is leaving,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Gore adviser who has worked with both Squier and Eskew in the
past said, ``Despite their other differences, the reality is they
share a longstanding personal interest in Al Gore's career. I'm
sure there's some discomfort,'' for the two to find themselves
working together again, he said, ``but it always felt funny for one
of them to be involved and not the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Also hired Thursday was Lauren Choi, a policy adviser formerly
with the Treasury Department. Lehane said other additions to the
campaign staff would be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Squier nor Eskew returned calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
