<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6586 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-LIABILITY-HNS &LR;      07-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-LIABILITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COURT DECISION COULD HIT ATHLETIC SPORTS SPONSORS HARD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a ruling that could make hundreds of amateur
sports sponsors recheck their safety lists, the Texas Supreme Court
held Thursday that a former college student could sue a fraternity
for injuries he suffered in a fraternity-sponsored game.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in Texas, the high court held that athletic
sponsors are not entitled to the same protections against lawsuits
as the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The court decided that Edward Lockwood Moore III, who was
blinded in one eye during a 1992 paint-ball ``war game'' while he
was a student at Stephen F. Austin University in Nacogdoches, could
sue the event sponsor, Phi Delta Theta fraternity, which Moore had
accused of providing inadequate safety gear or instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine a sport or recreational activity whose
participants, sponsors, coaches and venue providers will not be
affected,'' said Justice Craig Enoch, one of three justices who
unsuccessfully argued for a hearing on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the court majority, without comment, upheld a 1997
decision by the lst Court of Appeals in Houston, which ruled that
Moore was entitled to a trial of his lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the Supreme Court had agreed to hear the
fraternity's appeal of the Houston appeals court decision. But, in
an unusual move and without explanation, the court changed its mind
Thursday and upheld the lower court.
</P>
<P>
   There was no majority opinion, but three justices _ Enoch,
Nathan Hecht and Priscilla Owen dissented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fears of critics of the Texas Supreme Court, this
ruling demonstrates that the court continues to be interested in
protecting consumers' rights,'' said Ken Hoagland, a spokesman for
Texans for Lawsuit Reform. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``One can hope, however, that the Supreme Court believes that
gloves, catcher's masks and knee pads are sufficient safety gear
for softball and baseball games commonly sponsored by charitable
organizations.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Moore's attorney, R.L. ``Pete'' McKinney of Houston, said he
will now go back to the district court, which initially dismissed
his client's lawsuit. The fraternity had argued that it was not
liable for Moore's injury under the state's ``competitive contact
sports doctrine.''
</P>
<P>
   That defense recognizes the inherent risk accepted by
participants in a sport. A player is liable only if he hurts an
opponent through reckless or intentional conduct not connected to
actual play.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1st Court held that sponsors of amateur athletic events
should be held to a higher standard, and now the Texas Supreme
Court has agreed.
</P>
<P>
   While players may get caught up in the ``spirit of the
contest,'' sponsors and other non-participants ``have the benefit
of reflection before they act,'' the appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said the decision means that sponsors must provide
proper equipment and take ``ordinary care'' in how events are
conducted. ``All it does is put a burden of ordinary care on the
sponsor of an event,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ruling shouldn't change how most little leagues and
other amateur sports organizations operate.
</P>
<P>
   South Texas College of Law professor Paul McGreal agreed that
``it doesn't look like that big of a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   By not rendering a full decision that might have given guidance
to lower courts across the state on the subject, McGreal said, the
Texas Supreme Court opted without explanation not to hear the case
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Others were not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys who had read the appellate court's ruling said that
Thursday's Supreme Court decision not to hear the case will need to
be taken seriously by youth associations that sponsor sporting
events such as baseball little leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Those groups now have the potential to be sued if participants
are injured during events, the attorneys said. Not all sponsors
will be affected, however. For example, a company that provides a
youth sports association with the money to sponsor a team would
have little exposure to liability, attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will this have a chilling effect on sponsor of youth sports?
It could,'' said one Austin trial attorney who had read the opinion
but did not want to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   In the paint-ball game in which Moore was injured, his lawyer
said, players were provided with only thin plastic ``laboratory
goggles'' loosely fastened with a rubber band, rather than heavier,
more protective gear.
</P>
<P>
   The game was part of a fraternity ``rush'' activity to recruit
new members. Moore's goggles snagged on a tree limb, and he was hit
in the eye by a paint-ball fired by an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said Moore now lives in Houston and works as an
emergency medical technician in the Nacogdoches area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
