<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-640(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE TAKES UP FINANCIAL OVERHAUL MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Calif., N.Y. Ga., Mass.)  (jw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers who want to deregulate the nation's
financial system won an important test vote Thursday as the House
of Representatives debated a measure that would remove the last
remnants of Depression-era laws that have largely kept banks,
securities firms and insurance companies from entering one
another's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The 227-203 vote, which enabled the sponsors to bring the
measure to the floor, broke largely along party lines as the House
prepared for a final vote later Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is endorsed by the White House, although administration
officials and many Democratic lawmakers criticized some new
provisions Thursday that they said would make it easier for
insurance companies to disclose confidential health information
about patients, weaken laws against money laundering and not do
enough to prevent discrimination by insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the House, the bill will be forwarded to a
congressional conference committee, where the lawmakers will
attempt to reconcile it with a different version that the Senate
adopted two months ago over the objections of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers have moved the bill swiftly through the House by
pushing aside several contentious issues that could still doom the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's debate held the promise of producing a historic
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental precept of this bill is that it will end the
artificial restraints on commerce embodied in 65 years of law,''
said Rep. James Leach, R-Iowa, who is chairman of the House Banking
Committee and was one of the main authors of the legislation. He
said it would ultimately save consumers at least $15 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   House approval would mark the first time that both chambers of
Congress in the same legislative session have approved measures
repealing the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933. That landmark law
reflected the view that the close affiliations between banks and
securities firms had been a primary cause of the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The Glass-Steagall Act restricted the securities activities of
national banks and prohibited investment banks from engaging in
commercial banking activities. Over the last 12 years, those
restrictions have eased considerably as judges and regulators have
interpreted the act more loosely.
</P>
<P>
   Their rulings have enabled the rise of some enormous financial
conglomerates. But many federal and state restrictions remain, and
they either limit the expansion of such conglomerates or make it
prohibitively expensive for affiliations between investment banks,
commercial banks and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate bills eliminate most of those
remaining restrictions. Among the provisions of the legislation
considered Thursday night by the House:
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies that engage in any activities that are ``financial
in nature'' would be able to affiliate under a holding company.
Insurance underwriters and real estate developers would not be
permitted to be in subsidiaries of the conglomerates but would have
to operate as affiliates. By structuring such companies in this
way, both the Federal Reserve and the Treasury Department would
have important roles in regulating conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restrictions would continue to limit industrial companies from
owning banks.
</P>
<P>
   _ The legislation authorizes the establishment of a new banking
institution, the wholesale financial institution, that has the
powers of a national bank but could only accept deposits of more
than $100,000 and would not be federally insured.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new federal crime would be created that outlaws the practice
of using trickery and pretending to be a customer to obtain
confidential bank information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Banks would be required to post surcharges on their automated
teller machines.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill has been criticized by the administration and
many Democrats because it takes away the Treasury Department's
regulatory authority over nationally chartered banks and heavily
dilutes the requirements that all banks make loans to minorities,
inner-city neighborhoods, rural areas and others traditionally
denied access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic supporters of the House legislation either withdrew
their support Thursday or raised criticisms of the measure after
many of the items they had thought were in the legislation aimed at
protecting minority borrowers and the privacy rights of all
consumers were removed by the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all voted for this legislation in committee because we were
able to have strong community reinvestment provisions because of
consumer protections and because of strong antiredlining
provisions,'' said Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., the ranking member of
his party on the banking committee. ``Once those items eroded, so
did our support.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, the House measure had not faced any of the
partisan bickering that pervaded the Senate legislation. The House
bill was co-sponsored by leading Republicans and Democrats and it
was largely embraced by the Treasury Department after it rejected a
proposal by Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve,
that would have the effect of taking regulatory authority away from
the Treasury and giving it to the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's debate was steeped in partisan wrangling after
House Republicans stripped the measure of a provision that would
have prohibited insurance companies affiliated with banks from
discriminating against poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The practice, known as redlining, is already against the law for
banks. A provision pre-empting state insurance laws and extending
the prohibition to the insurance industry passed earlier this year
in the House Banking Committee by a single vote. It was sponsored
by Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republican leadership decided late Wednesday to strip
the Lee Amendment and not allow further consideration of it by the
full House, Democrats who had supported the legislation defected in
mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a good job in fostering conditions in which our
capitalist system can flourish and it's in our interest that our
capitalist system flourish,'' said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass. ``But
can we try to do a little bit for those who are being left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats also complained that the legislation did not go
far enough in protecting the privacy interests of bank customers
and patients. And in one of his final acts in office, Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin criticized an amendment to the Bank Secrecy
Act proposed by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., that would eliminate the
requirements that banks report suspicious money transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are now required to report all transactions of more than
$10,000 to the federal government as part of the secrecy act, which
is intended to discourage tax evasion and money laundering. The
amendment criticized by Rubin would raise that amount to $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The House ultimately defeated the Barr amendment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
