<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6594 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-MEDICARE-N     07-01 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON GIVES FIRST SIGN OF POLICY DIFFERENCE WITH PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of the New York Times.)  
(mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the first public indication of a policy difference between
Hillary Rodham Clinton and her husband, the first lady Thursday
joined New York labor and political leaders in pressing White House
officials to scale back proposed Medicare cuts that could hurt New
York hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, taking a break from preparations for her possible
campaign for the Senate from New York, met in the White House with
the New Yorkers, President Clinton's chief of staff and a senior
health care adviser. Mrs. Clinton was responding to the invitation
of Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., who has asserted that the
president's proposed cuts could cost teaching hospitals in New York
billions of dollars a year and ``risk the very fabric of our health
care system.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, her spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said the first lady
had ``expressed her interest in trying to alleviate the
difficulties'' facing teaching hospitals. Ms. Berry said the first
lady spent most of her 20 minutes at the meeting listening, and she
and other White House officials played down the notion that the
Clintons were in conflict over a major aspect of one of Clinton's
biggest policy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Mrs. Clinton's decision to accept Schumer's
invitation and join the meeting, which was held across the hall
from the Oval Office and at the center of the West Wing of the
White House, clearly put her in the public position of appearing to
join some of the most powerful forces in New York politics in
fighting budget cuts that Clinton has advocated, first to balance
the budget and than to help finance changes in the Medicare
program. Mrs. Clinton's associates have long suggested that the
first lady would seek opportunities to draw differences between
herself and her husband, and suggested that this issue was the
ideal one to do it with.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's stroll to the Roosevelt Room came at a time when
she has embarked on an effort to construct her own political
identity as she prepares for a possible race to succeed Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who is retiring at the end of 2000. She
rented a campaign headquarters near Madison Square Garden on
Thursday, and plans to formally create an exploratory committee
next Tuesday, before beginning a four-day trip across central New
York state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at a press conference Thursday at the White House,
suggested that he was sympathetic to concerns by teaching
hospitals, in New York and elsewhere, that some of his
budget-reduction initiatives had been too severe on them. He said
he was looking for ways to rectify that, and noted that his
Medicare plan proposed earlier this week included a $7.5 billion
fund directed particularly at teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage the senators from New York, or anyone else
who's concerned about this, to bring those concerns, bring the
facts to the table, get it out in the open _ then embrace the idea
of Medicare reform, pass that fund, and then allocate it as it
should be allocated,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the merits of the complex issue notwithstanding,
Clinton seemed at once resigned and appreciative of what both his
wife and Vice President Al Gore, who is running for president, have
been doing in recent days as they draw away from the man who has
for seven years been the dominant figure in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore disagrees with his actions over the next year and a
half, Clinton said wistfully, ``then of course he will have to say
so. And I will take no offense at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if my wife decides to run for senator from New York, then
some of the disagreements that we've had in the past over decisions
I've made as president she may be constrained to state publicly
because they will be relevant to the future,'' the president
continued. ``And that's the way a democracy works.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this issue was ideally suited for Mrs. Clinton to
draw some distance. For one thing, it gives her a chance to appear
to be in a position of helping one of the central aspects of New
York's health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   It also allowed her to strike a public allegiance with Dennis
Rivera, president of the union representing 150,00 health workers
and one of the most influential forces in Democratic politics in
New York state. Rivera has already been working behind-the-scenes
to help Mrs. Clinton prepare for the campaign, and he was delighted
Thursday at her presence at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are elated with the meeting,'' Rivera reported afterwards.
``We had the enthusiastic support of the first lady. She clearly
understands the problems that the teaching hospitals in New York
state are facing. She's committed to help us find solutions to the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that she will get the assistance of the president of
the United States in this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry, Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, declined to say whether
Mrs. Clinton would do that, and described her commitment as a
general one to the future of teaching hospitals. ``The effect of
these meetings is she wants to try to assure that they don't have
any undue burdens,'' Ms. Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer offered generally high praise of Clinton's Medicare
plan, which, most notably, would for the first time provide
reimbursements for prescription drugs. He was critical, though, of
part of the way the president would finance that, the reduced
Medicare reimbursements for teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said the president's plan would cost New York hospitals
$39 billion in the next 10 years, on top of reductions that were
brought about as part of the 1997 budget-balancing act. The meeting
Thursday, which was lead by John Podesta, the White House chief of
staff, was intended to persuade the White House to roll back that
policy, Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said that Mrs. Clinton was clearly supportive of that
effort during the meeting. ``I made the major pitch but Mrs.
Clinton chimed in,'' Schumer recounted Thursday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
