<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA TALKS HALT, TO MUCH TEETH GNASHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Marathon talks to resolve the
disarmament impasse that threatens the province's peace settlement
broke off early on Friday. But a spokesman for Prime Minister Tony
Blair said they would resume on Friday morning and end with a
statement on the ``way forward.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second day that the grinding negotiations had gone
into the early morning and the fifth straight day that Blair and
his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, had spent trying to find a
compromise between the Ulster Unionists, the Protestant party that
is the province's largest, and Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had set midnight Wednesday as the ``absolute'' deadline
for settling the dispute but relaxed the date, his spokesman said
late Thursday, because ``we do not believe the gap is
unbridgeable.''
</P>
<P>
   That was an optimistic view shared by few people in the air of
gloom and disappointment at the Stormont Castle Buildings as the
participants drove off into a rainy night.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's spokesman said a long-awaited report on disarmament by
Gen. John de Chastelain of Canada, chairman of the an international
commission on the issue, would be presented to the negotiators on
Friday morning. The two governments will receive position
statements from the parties and are to decide what promise the
combined views hold for moving on to the next steps in the process
laid out in the April 1998 peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The general expectation was that a decision would be taken to
postpone further negotiations until after the summer months of
sectarian parades that have been flash points of tension.
</P>
<P>
   The most volatile the marches is scheduled for Sunday. It is the
procession of the Protestant Orange Order from Drumcree Church.
</P>
<P>
   The government-appointed Parades Commission on Monday prohibited
the parade from passing into the Roman Catholic area, and the
police and British troops have been building trenches and
barricades in the town, in County Armagh, to enforce the ban.
</P>
<P>
   The talks on Thursday began at noon, after having adjourned at 4
a.m., and Blair warned that the public was becoming frustrated with
the bewildering deadlock and would have no sympathy for failure.
``The entire civilized world will not understand if we cannot put
this together and make it work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with a similar sense of exasperation and urgency, Ahern
told reporters that failure would be ``unforgivable and
unexplainable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an awful lot to gain and a frightening amount to
lose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-fought accord of April 1998 creates a series of
power-sharing institutions intended to end the violent conflict
between the majority Protestants and the minority Catholics of this
British province that has cost more than 3,200 lives in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists are demanding that the IRA begin to disarm
immediately, to take part in the crucial next step of the
settlement, the creation of the executive cabinet that will run the
new Northern Ireland Assembly. But Sinn Fein leaders refuse to make
that pledge, saying the accord calls for no such preconditions.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, President Clinton called Gerry Adams, president
of Sinn Fein, and David Trimble, head of the Ulster Unionists, to
reinforce the need to achieve a resolution promptly. A spokesman
for Blair said Clinton had made it clear ``that the U.S. and the
wider world will not understand if we don't get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the guerrillas' disarmament has been the principal
obstacle to a settlement since paramilitary groups began declaring
cease-fires and expressing interest in a political solution five
years ago. It was sidelined in the final days before the April 1998
accord and has now come back with the power to derail the overall
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists have taken their stand on disarmament at a
critical moment, because the creation of the executive, on which
Sinn Fein has two seats, signals the moment that the new
legislature in Belfast can assume its powers from the British
government in London.
</P>
<P>
   Blair had set the first deadline in the hopes that the transfer
could occur on Thursday, when new legislatures in Scotland and
Wales took on their legislative authority. Instead, Blair had to
cancel his own appearance in Edinburgh, where the queen was leading
inaugural celebrations of the Scottish Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said he was staying in Belfast because of the ``huge
progress'' already made and the ``historic, seismic shifts in the
political landscape'' already brought about by the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein has made a proposal that entails a commitment to
achieve disarmament by next May, the date set out in the original
agreement, with a first turnover of weapons by December. The
organization insists that it has to be allowed to take up
immediately the two positions its vote count in the legislative
elections entitled it to in the 10-member cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists offered counterproposals on Thursday
afternoon that insisted on actual disarmament, not just the
promise, as the condition for letting Sinn Fein into the
government. Touching on the deep distrust between the political
parties, Trimble said, ``Sinn Fein promises are not bankable.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair acknowledged the differences but said that the British and
Irish governments had offered the Unionists ``absolute fail safe
legislative guarantees'' that any party failing to live up to its
promises to disarm would be expelled from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said the problem was ``was no longer a basic principle
dividing the parties, but one of sequencing and time.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``This is the slender thread by which the future of
Northern Ireland hangs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
