<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARBUCKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS CREAM STARBUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Investors Thursday blasted Seattle coffee retailer
Starbucks for its announced plan to branch out into new retail
businesses and a new forecast of lower earnings, beating back its
share price as much as 41 percent at one point.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock fell $10.63 to close at $26.94, rebounding
from a session low of $23.44. Starbucks Wednesday announced its
plans for more Internet businesses and said it expects to earn only
54 cents a share for the fiscal year ending in September, below the
Wall Street consensus of 60 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent investors wild. Starbucks was the most actively
traded Nasdaq stock, with 73 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks Chief Executive Officer Howard Schultz told analysts
that the company is counting on acceptance of the Starbucks brand
at its 2,300 coffee shops to carry over to new Internet ventures,
including on-line sales of gourmet foods, cooking utensils and
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects the company will form a new subsidiary to
handle the new lines of business he sees as necessary for Starbucks
to grow beyond the packaging and brewing of coffee beans.
</P>
<P>
   But Chuck Hill of Boston-based First Call Corp., which polls
analysts, said 17 of the 20 analysts who follow Starbucks see
problems percolating next year for the coffee giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six of the 17 lowered their recommendations for the stock,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, it seems to be that the analysts see it (low
earnings) as longer lasting than the period being mentioned. The
new consensus is that there will be a 14 percent haircut on next
year's expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   In his conference call with analysts, Schultz said that any
shortfall experienced was ``relative only to the high expectations
we placed on ourselves'' and he advised them to ``expect
considerable improvement'' in the future. He stopped short of
forecasting fiscal 2000 performance, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am one of a small group of traditional bricks-and-mortar
retailers who understands the (Internet) as well as any CEO of a
bricks-and-mortar company and I am bringing all that experience,
all those skills and all those relationships to bear to make sure
we win and win big,'' Schultz told analysts.
</P>
<P>
   He said he delivered 80 consecutive months of positive financial
reports, and will lead Starbucks ``ahead of the curve'' onto the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks said sales at stores open at least a year rose 7
percent last month. Revenue rose 30 percent to $170 million from
$131 million.
</P>
<P>
   But earnings began to slip as the company was starting up the
new Internet ventures, including hiring to operate it, Schultz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks experienced substantial drops in its stock price
before. Its stock lost about half its value during a two-month
stretch last year, falling as low as 14.375 on concerns that its
earnings growth would slow as it plunged into international
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rebounded after sales in its coffee shops and Asia and
elsewhere caught on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
