<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COURT RULING COULD HAVE IMPACT ON TOBACCO CASE LAWYERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a decision that could renew debate over legal
fees in the tobacco lawsuit, the Texas Supreme Court ruled Thursday
that lawyers who commit ethical violations can be required to
forfeit all or part of their fees, even if their clients aren't
harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn, who has been investigating the
$3.3 billion awarded five private lawyers for helping Texas obtain
the $17.3 billion settlement with the tobacco industry, said the
ruling was potentially relevant to the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has not decided what action, if any, he could take
against the attorneys, who were hired by his predecessor, Dan
Morales.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Silver, a University of Texas law professor who is a
consultant to the five lawyers, said he would be ``astounded'' if
the ruling ``has any implications for the tobacco case at all.'' He
said the ruling applies to cases with multiple plaintiffs, not to
suits brought by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruling, which was unanimous, stemmed from a
1989 explosion at a Phillips Petroleum plant in Pasadena, Texas,
that killed 23 workers and injured hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
   One suit resulted in a $190 million settlement for 126
plaintiffs and a contingent fee of more than $60 million for their
five attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   But 49 of those plaintiffs later sued their lawyers for alleged
professional misconduct. Among other things, the plaintiffs accused
the attorneys of failing to fully investigate individual claims and
of forcing their clients into accepting the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys _ F. Kenneth Bailey Jr., David Burrow, Wayne
Reaud, Walter Umphrey and John E. Williams Jr., who then practiced
in the same firm _ denied any misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Umphrey and Reaud of Beaumont and Williams of Houston, all of
whom later represented Texas in the landmark lawsuit against
tobacco companies, settled with the Phillips plaintiffs. But the
other two lawyers, who practice in Houston, appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Supreme Court said an attorney's duty to his client is
violated by ``disloyalty, not any resulting harm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An agent's (lawyer's) compensation is not only for specific
results but also for loyalty,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court returned the dispute to a state district
court, where the Phillips plaintiffs will have an opportunity to
make their case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who has called the legal fees in the tobacco case
``excessive,'' said the court decision means that ``lawyers can't
place their interest in receiving a fat fee above their duty to
their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was watched by lawyers on both sides of the tobacco
fee dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schenkkan, an Austin attorney, filed a brief in the case on
behalf of Texans for Reasonable Legal Fees, a coalition of civil
justice reform and other business groups formed to fight the
tobacco fees.
</P>
<P>
   Silver argued, in a separate brief that he said was unrelated to
the tobacco case, that fees forfeiture should require proof that
the clients were harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The $3.3 billion in legal fees is to be paid by cigarette
makers, and the tobacco companies have said that a reduction in
legal fees wouldn't increase the size of the state's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the lawyers' critics have contended that the
attorneys put their own interests over those of the state by
negotiating a separate pile of money for their fees.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who succeeded Morales after the tobacco suit was
settled, hasn't ruled out the possibility of suing the lawyers for
breach of fiduciary responsibility to the state. But he insisted
Thursday that he hasn't decided his next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be one of the options, but I don't want it to
appear that I have reached a pre-ordained conclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schenkkan said he was ``delighted'' with the Supreme Court
ruling. He said it ``highlights the importance of General Cornyn's
investigation into possible breaks of fiduciary duty by the
plaintiffs' lawyers hired by Dan Morales.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Cornyn accused Morales of falsifying
documents to help a sixth lawyer, Marc Murr of Houston, also obtain
hundreds of millions of dollars in legal fees. Murr is a longtime
Morales friend.
</P>
<P>
   Murr withdrew his claim after Cornyn made his allegations, but
Murr's relationship to the tobacco case is being investigated by a
federal grand jury in Austin. Other lawyers say Murr did little
work on the tobacco suit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
