<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABR-MARKETPLACE-2NDTA     07-01 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABR-MARKETPLACE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to ABR's.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no logical reason for ABR's stock price to have traded
for more than $25.50 after June 7, yet it did, closing at $26 on
June 24, then inching steadily upward, to $29.6875 on Tuesday.
Traders speculated Thursday that those moves could have been caused
by short covering, in which investors who had sold ABR shares they
did not own, in expectation that the price would fall, were forced
to buy them back before the stock stopped trading altogether to
limit their losses.
</P>
<P>
   As of mid-June, only 14,504 ABR shares had been sold short, but
that number might have grown this week as ABR's share price edged
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Wednesday, the last day of the second quarter and the
day that the Russell indexes were reconstituted, ABR shares surged.
In the first hour of trading, they moved as high as $35; they then
soared in the last half hour, briefly hitting $100 before closing
at $90.06.
</P>
<P>
   Between 3:30 and 4 p.m., only one block of 10,000 shares changed
hands on the Nasdaq market, accompanied by several blocks of 1,000
to 2,400 shares. But in late trading, at 4:24 p.m., two huge
blocks, of 52,200 and 35,000 shares each, changed hands.
Immediately after those trades, the share price dropped to $72,
from $90.06. Daily volume totaled 273,500 shares, more than half
the 488,000 shares still in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   ABR was not the only stock affected by trading related to
changes in the Russell 2000 index. Shares of two other companies
that some traders thought might be included in the index _ Pitt-Des
Moines Inc. and Chaparral Resources Inc. _ also soared on
Wednesday, only to retrace their gains Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet investment bulletin boards on Yahoo, Silicon
Investor and the Motley Fool, correspondents speculated that day
traders had also climbed aboard the ABR bandwagon once they were
alerted to the sharp jump in the stock's price and volume. Some
people who portrayed themselves as day traders posted notes saying
they had bought shares in the $30s and sold them in the $80s or
$90s. Those reports could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   For each of those ABR trades, though, someone paid a hefty price
and someone else reaped the rewards. It is likely that the most
sophisticated market participants _ those who were able to discern
quickly that ABR shares would soon be worth no more than $25.50
each _ gathered some of the profits at the expense of
less-sophisticated investors.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also likely that someone who thought a buying strategy
was the height of sophistication _ enter the orders into a computer
and push a button _ was, in fact, the ultimate buffoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
