<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-PLACE-750(2TAK     07-01 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-PLACE-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Wash., N.Y.)  
 MARKET PLACE: A FLUKE THAT MADE A STOCK MOVE LIKE BRAIN
WAVES  (jw) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Somewhere a portfolio manager is cursing a blue
streak, and a few day traders are probably counting their profits.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkable demonstration that financial markets can move
faster than brain waves, shares of a small company called ABR
Information Services more than tripled on Wednesday, rocketing as
high as $100 apiece on what appears to have been a colossal mistake
_ one borne out of the popularity of the investment strategy known
as indexing or simply a case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as news of the grand faux pas circulated on Wall
Street, the shares retraced their outsize gains, falling $62.06, to
$28. Yet even that price appears to be unreasonably high. In the
next three weeks, the few hundred thousand shares of ABR that are
still in circulation will be worth no more than $25.50 each in cash
because of the company's acquisition by the Ceridian Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday night, no one had come forward to acknowledge
having bought the stock by mistake, and Nasdaq market officials
were investigating the unusual trading.
</P>
<P>
   Traders, though, held forth with two theories of what happened.
The most plausible is that a fund manager near the close of trading
on Wednesday entered an order to buy all the stocks in the Russell
2000 index, including ABR, which provides payroll, benefits and
other human resource services to companies. Wednesday happened to
be the one day of the year that stocks are added to or deleted from
the index. Not realizing that ABR Information shares would soon
stop trading altogether because the company had been acquired, the
buyer started a chain reaction that forced up the price of the
relatively few shares that remained in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The other possibility also has to do with the annual changes in
the Russell 2000 index, but it suggests an even bigger blunder by
some investment manager. This theory is that a buyer entered the
wrong stock symbol on a trade ticket, substituting ABRX, the symbol
for ABR Information Systems, for ABGX, the symbol for Abgenix Inc.,
a biopharmaceutical company that is expected to be in the Russell
2000 index when the final list is issued next week. Stocks being
added to the index tend to get an initial boost as investors who
track the index buy them.
</P>
<P>
   ABR executives, who were preparing to ride off into the sunset
after selling the company for more than $730 million, are
scratching their heads over the stock's brief surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had done something to merit it, but we didn't,''
said James MacDougald, chairman of ABR. When Nasdaq market
surveillance officials called to ask what might be the cause of the
strange trading, he said he told them he ``didn't have any idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The tale began early last month, when Ceridian, the corporate
services company formerly known as Control Data, bought control of
ABR, based in Palm Harbor, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Ceridian had offered to buy all of ABR's 28.2 million shares for
$25.50 each, and shareholders responded by offering up 98.3 percent
of the total, all but about 488,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Tender offers often do not attract all of a company's shares,
some of which languish in safe deposit boxes. Shareholders who
forget or choose not to participate in such an offer do not lose
out, however; they receive the right to the stated amount of cash
whenever their stock is turned in.
</P>
<P>
   The tender offer expired on June 7, about the time that the
Frank Russell Co., the Tacoma, Wash., financial data company, was
drawing up its preliminary list of companies to be added to and
deleted from its most popular indexes: the Russell 1000 index of
large-capitalization companies and the Russell 2000 small-cap
index. Those changes take place each year on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ABR was already part of the Russell 2000, accounting for less
than 0.1 percent of the index. Though the company had already
agreed to be acquired and most of its shares had been removed from
circulation, Russell's index experts knew that the deal would not
close until mid-July. Allowing for the slight possibility that the
acquisition would not be completed, Russell did not schedule ABR
for removal from the index on June 30. Instead, ABR is to be
removed when its shares stop trading. Ceridian, the acquiring
company, is part of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index of large
companies, as well as the Russell 1000.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three weeks of June, Russell released lists, and
several revisions, of the companies it did expect to add to its
indexes. Those included Abgenix, the stock with the ticker symbol
similar to ABR's.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
