</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-POKER-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 STATES ACT TO LIMIT SPREAD OF VIDEO POKER MACHINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., S.C.)  (jw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two Southern states took steps Thursday to control the
spread of video poker machines, which have brought impulsive
gambling to the dark corners of thousands of gas stations,
convenience stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight Wednesday, Louisiana shut down 4,874 of its
15,000 poker machines, the result of a 1996 referendum allowing the
state's parishes to choose whether to keep them. It was believed to
be the nation's largest single shutdown of a form of legalized
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   And in South Carolina, which has 34,000 machines, more than any
other state, the state Legislature approved a plan Thursday that
would give voters a chance to prohibit the machines statewide in a
November referendum. If the voters allow it to continue, video
gambling would be more closely regulated than before, and the state
would collect a hefty tax on its earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling opponents, who have long called the machines the
``crack cocaine'' of gambling because of their convenient,
addictive nature, celebrated the day as a rare retrenchment in the
industry's rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we knocked out more than 4,000 machines, and got the
opportunity to knock out 34,000 more,'' Tom Grey, director of the
National Coalition Against Gambling Expansion, said Thursday. ``It
doesn't get much better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was unclear just how much of a retreat had really taken
place. Many South Carolina officials expect the video gambling
industry _ which has become the state's most potent political force
_ to mount a multimillion-dollar political campaign to convince
voters it should stay in business. If gambling survives the Nov. 2
vote, it will be limited by the new regulations, but will begin
contributing an estimated $180 million a year in taxes to the state
budget, which will quickly make the state dependent on gambling's
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forces of organized gambling completed their purchase of
South Carolina,'' said state Rep. John Graham Altman, R-Charleston,
and an ardent opponent of gambling. ``We're no longer a sovereign
state; we're an occupied territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents were particularly upset that the industry won its most
coveted prize: an increase in the maximum jackpot payable by the
machines to $500 per sitting from the current $120 a day. That
could attract large numbers of new gamblers to the machines, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry did have to make a few concessions. Minors will
no longer be able to play the machines, which will also be closed
on Sundays. A statewide computer system will monitor the integrity
of the machines, making certain that a 25 percent tax is collected,
and owners will be subject to new background checks. And no site
can have more than five machines, which will restrict the spread of
the casino-style parlors, often at the state's borders, that now
have scores of machines under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a decade, video gambling has transformed South
Carolina's landscape. It is now impossible to drive through any
rural or urban area without encountering signs for the machines,
which also lure players from neighboring states. Many gamblers are
from low-income families, and there have been numerous stories of
people who have lost their paychecks while mesmerized by the
electronic games of poker, blackjack and keno.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has also reshaped the state's politics, with alliances
among proponents or opponents more powerful than party
affiliations. Gov. Jim Hodges, a Democrat, who received half his $6
million campaign treasury from poker interests, sounded relieved
that the issue, which had riven the Legislature like no other in
recent memory, had finally been sent away to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I think everyone recognized this was a fair
plan,'' Hodges said early Thursday morning when the plan finally
passed the House after being rejected six times before.
</P>
<P>
   Several leaders of the state's gambling industry, which took in
$2.5 billion last year, also said they were satisfied with the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is Louisiana was somewhat more decisive. In 1996,
33 of the state's 64 parishes, as counties are known, voted to ban
video gambling machines in a statewide referendum.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The industry quickly went to court, but was unable to stop the
shutdown. Now the state and local governments will lose an
estimated $72 million in taxes, and some restaurants that have
relied on gambling for income have threatened to close.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the parishes that banned the machines are in rural
areas, but the ban includes several cities, among them Baton Rouge
and Lafayette. The machines will still be legal on the riverboat
casinos that are moored throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   And the gambling industry has not given up. It will be back in
court on Friday to assert that it was unfairly kept from getting
its message to voters in the 1996 election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
