<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      07-01 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC WAS ALERTED ABOUT FRAUD SUSPECT IN '91, LAWYER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLEDO, Ohio _ Seven years ago, as federal securities regulators
here were working to close a fraud case against a seemingly
insignificant money manager, they received a warning from a local
lawyer: The manager, Martin Frankel, was lying to them.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being destitute, as Frankel was maintaining in his
settlement talks with the regulators, he secretly controlled
millions of dollars, the lawyer told them. Not only that, the
lawyer said, but Frankel had moved money into a Swiss bank account
and was using a series of aliases as he made expensive purchases
through dummy companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I passed this information on to the SEC,'' said the lawyer,
Terry Davis, who at the time was pursuing a civil suit against
Frankel on behalf of several investors. ``They would have had to
have known about that information, because we sent them papers.''
</P>
<P>
   But it appears the SEC did little to follow through on the
leads, according to people who have reviewed the record of the
case. Within months, the SEC settled its case against Frankel,
barred him from the securities industry and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Today, that inaction looms large. Frankel is now at the center
of one of the largest insurance fraud investigations in history _ a
suspected scheme that relied on using Swiss bank accounts, dummy
corporations and aliases.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the SEC said it would not comment on what
information was available about Frankel in the early 1990s or on
whether it received documents and reports from the Toledo lawyers.
But agency officials defended their handling of the case, calling
it a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the maximum relief available,'' said Richard Walker,
director of enforcement at the SEC. In settling the case, Frankel
agreed to pay more than $200,000 and accepted a permanent bar from
the securities industry.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel has been missing since May 5, when firefighters were
called to his mansion in Greenwich, Conn., and found smoldering
documents stuffed in fireplaces. Federal prosecutors say they think
he fled because a scheme to drain cash from insurance companies he
controlled was in danger of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still struggling to understand the full
boundaries of Frankel's business dealings, which spanned several
states and at least two continents. But it seems increasingly clear
that the current case has its roots in the financier's first brush
with federal law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all a continuation of a scheme that was begun back
then,'' one person who has reviewed Frankel's business records
said. ``It was all just a scam that went on too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, who was born in Toledo and worked at Dominick &AMP;
Dominick, a small brokerage firm in the city, found a new partner
in 1987 and founded the Frankel Fund.
</P>
<P>
   It attracted some investors, but by 1988 it got into trouble,
prompting close scrutiny by the SEC into whether Frankel had
misrepresented his investing record and used client cash for
expenses like rent.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Frankel appeared to be cooperative in the agency's
inquiry, turning over records and voluntarily submitting to
questions. But when the SEC demanded his bank records and other
financial data, he balked. After investigators threatened to go to
court to force him to produce the records, Frankel settled the case
on what seemed to be harsh terms.
</P>
<P>
   But now it appears that Frankel may have gotten the better of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly filed SEC documents appear to show that Federal
regulators focused their inquiry largely on the Frankel Fund, which
was only one of Frankel's investment concerns. A larger pool of
money that Frankel used to start his new career in the insurance
industry was left unexamined, records show.
</P>
<P>
   Former associates say that much of the money Frankel raised in
Toledo came from a company called Creative Partners Inc., an
investment fund he started in 1989. The company was not registered
with federal or state securities regulators, but within a year,
brochures for the fund boasted that it had already ``outperformed
every publicly traded mutual fund in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with a group of 8 to 12 part-time salesmen, Frankel
built up a multimillion-dollar investment chest in less than three
years, former staff members say. Selling limited partnerships for a
minimum of $10,000, the fund lured more than 100 investors and grew
to as much as $13 million by 1991, according to William Stevenson,
who worked as a consultant at Creative Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Several investors say there were at least four funds with 35
people in each with a minimum $10,000 investment, and Walter
Rothschild, a former employee, said one man had invested $500,000
in the fund. Indeed, Frankel once boasted in a brochure that in
1991 he was managing more than $63 million in the fund. No public
records exist about the holdings of the Creative Partners Fund.
</P>
<P>
   There was several aspects of Creative Partners' operations that
could have attracted scrutiny from the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Its assertions on performance appear to have been
exaggerated and the firm was not registered, as Federal securities
law requires.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the Toledo lawyer, said he brought the existence of
Creative Partners to the attention of federal regulators in 1991.
No enforcement action was ever taken against the fund.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1991, just as the SEC case against him was
drawing to a close, Frankel turned to the insurance industry. With
several million dollars in seed money, he established the Thunor
Trust, the investment vehicle he used to begin his acquisition of
insurance companies through the purchase of a controlling stake in
Franklin American Life Insurance Co. of Nashville in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Cash taken from the insurance companies may, in turn, have
helped Frankel cover his tracks in Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he closed the Franklin deal, he repaid the investors
in Creative Partners with handsome profits and then gave them back
their original investment. The fund, he said, was to be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and another lawyer at his firm, Shumaker Loop &AMP; Kendrick,
said that SEC officials made some inquiries, even after the
agency's case was resolved with Frankel in July 1992. But he said
the agency appeared to lose interest in a man who at the time was
considered a small-time money manager who had defrauded a handful
of investors in 1987 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Had the agency begun an aggressive investigation in the early
1990s, there was much it might have discovered about Frankel's new
business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   For example, just a few months before the case involving the
Frankel Fund was finally concluded, he apparently formed a new
company called Bloomfield Investments Limited, using an alias.
</P>
<P>
   The incorporation papers list a 25-year-old trader named Eric
Jensen as its president and David Rosse _ a name often used by
Frankel as an alias _ as a director. The company had offices in
Chicago and Geneva, and assets of more than $8 million when it was
formed in April 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen could not be reached for comment, but his mother, who
lives in Iowa, said that he knew Frankel but had not been in touch
with him for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomfield Investments, which was incorporated in the British
Virgin Islands, is important to investigators because they say that
in March and April, Frankel wired about $74 million of insurance
money to Bloomfield through the Stamford, Conn., branch of the
Union Bank of Switzerland, and the Banque SCS Alliance in
Switzerland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
