<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALISA TANG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does it Melt in Your Heart? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of intensive promotional marketing that has become
de rigeur for animated films and children's TV shows: T-shirts,
plush toys, hats, a fan club.
</P>
<P>
   But for a candy commercial?
</P>
<P>
   The people at Mars say M&AMP;M's, the colorful candy-coated
chocolate drops that ``melt in your mouth, not in your hand,'' and
the wisecracking animated versions that appear in the company's
commercials, have long had a devoted following of fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have shrines to M&AMP;M's, rooms full of M&AMP;M's
items,'' said Pat D'Amato, public relations manager for the
company's M&AMP;M/Mars division. ``We wanted to provide them with
interesting contests, offers and premiums which no one else has.''
</P>
<P>
   So late last year the company's marketers dreamed up the M&AMP;M's
Brand Inner Circle, a ``loyalty program'' now being promoted in
newspaper inserts. For $19.95, members get a ``limited edition''
candy dispenser, shaped like two M&AMP;M's characters, and a quarterly
magazine, Inside the Shell, ``written'' by the characters, with
M&AMP;M's recipes and offers for everything from jackets to golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ms. D'Amato wouldn't say how many people have signed up,
she said the program was achieving its marketing goal. ``We want
these loyalists to be able to continue to be brand advocates,'' she
said. And Mars is pretty sure nobody will fill their candy
dispensers with Reese's Pieces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6630 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-ABELN-ART     07-01 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-ABELN-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAWYER OPPONENTS CAN LIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Pa., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (Eds: Please note sub for BIZ-PROFILE-GALLO)  
 (af)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe Lewis Carroll's Red Queen was right: Sometimes it really
does take all the running you can do to keep in the same place.
</P>
<P>
   Maura J. Abeln, general counsel for Owens Corning _ the
front-and-center defendant in asbestos litigation _ is finding that
out the hard way. For more than a year, she has fought off every
potentially lethal attack on the settlement process she worked out
so painstakingly with some 80 plaintiff's law firms ready to
litigate more than 200,000 asbestos claims.
</P>
<P>
   She waited, breath held, until the Supreme Court overturned a
class-action suit against Owens-Corning's Fiberboard subsidiary two
weeks ago, enabling Owens Corning to add Fiberboard's cases to its
settlement plan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's back into the breach again. Ms. Abeln spent much of
Thursday testifying before the House Judiciary Committee, which is
considering legislation that could steer plaintiffs back into the
courts . She seamlessly melded compassion with practicality, in
hopes that her settlements will be grandfathered out of any law.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we want is to stay out of the fray and continue with our
own program,'' Ms. Abeln said. ``I've got to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   She is protecting the Owens Corning National Settlement Program,
a method for settling asbestos claims on the basis of how long
claimants were exposed to an Owens Corning product, and how severe
their disease has become. She has traveled the country, meeting
with plaintiff's lawyers and hammering away at their distrust.
</P>
<P>
   She used humor _ lawyers found stuffed pink panthers, Owens
Corning's consumer logo, in their mailboxes, and one received a
gift-wrapped peace pipe. She used facts _ she showed them Owens
Corning's books, trotted out its executives to answer questions and
laid out what the company could pay and how quickly it could pay
it.
</P>
<P>
   And, against all odds, she won the enemy over. ``I've had as
many feuds with industry lawyers as anybody, and Maura is
remarkable,'' said Fred M. Baron, of Baron &AMP; Budd in Dallas.
``She's like a rodeo cowboy, she gets on that horse and stays with
it, no matter how much it bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the cowboy is not the first metaphor brought to mind
by Ms. Abeln _who is intense rather than devil-may-care. A
43-year-old with a ready smile, she has a way of making anyone
believe she is listening, absorbing and processing their every
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of Maura's, and it's hard for a plaintiff's
attorney to say that about a corporate attorney,'' said John D.
Cooney, a partner at Cooney &AMP; Conway. ``She is blunt,
straightforward and invites you to believe her.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, when Ms. Abeln claims to understand the plaintiff's
point of view, she means it. Her father, a foreman in a copper
tubing plant in Reading, Pa., died of emphysema in 1986. ``He'd
come home with copper dust on his shoes, and that might have been
the cause,'' Ms. Abeln said. ``I see things from the plaintiff's
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abeln recalls her childhood as short on cash for luxuries _
she sold shoes and doughnuts in high school to help raise money for
college expenses _ but long on the belief in self-betterment. Her
mother did not go to college until she was 47, then worked in
various social work jobs until she died at 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was quite the feminist, giving me copies of Ms. magazine
when I was just 15,'' Ms. Abeln said. She said her mother also
encouraged her to go to Vassar, ``because she wanted me in an
environment that showed what women could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abeln caught on quickly. She had honor-society grades and
was involved in the college newspaper and in sports like field
hockey and softball. She won a Rhodes scholarship in 1976, the
first year that women were accepted. She studied economics at
Oxford, married and divorced, then accepted a full scholarship to
study law at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Miami seemed a permanent home. She married one of
her law professors, had two children, and later built a thriving
banking law practice as a partner for Baker &AMP; McKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, though, woes in the banking market left her practice in
turmoil _ just as her mother died of breast cancer and her marriage
disintegrated, leaving her to raise her small children alone.
</P>
<P>
   When General Electric Co.'s plastics division in Pittsfield,
Mass., invited her to be its general counsel, she jumped. ``I
needed to do something different, and Pittsfield seemed a nice town
that was closer to my brother in Allentown, Pa.,'' she recalled.
Moreover, she was getting married again, to someone willing to stay
home with her children, and she would be the youngest general
counsel of any GE division. She was sold.
</P>
<P>
   She got her first taste of personal injury claims when she
handled GE's silicon breast implant litigation. But Benjamin W.
Heineman Jr., GE's general counsel, remembers her more for her
ability to work with people. ``She built one of our finest global
legal staffs,'' he recalled. ``She knows how to inspire loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   She also knows how to impress the brass. Glen H. Hiner was
running GE Plastics when Ms. Abeln joined. He left six months later
to become Owens Corning's chief executive, but Ms. Abeln had
already made a lasting impression. When he realized that Owens
Corning's asbestos situation had gotten out of hand, he came
calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd polarized the plaintiffs bar into a solid position
against us,'' he recalled. ``I knew Maura was smart and had a good
business sense. But I also knew she could rally people to her
side.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Abeln came on board in February 1998, jury verdicts
were turning against the company, just as its insurance money for
asbestos claims was running out. ``I have the most important job in
this company after Glen's,'' she said. ``If we kept trying to delay
cases and deferring payments, we could not survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Her future? Divorced again, she is getting married next June, to
Steven Smith, a software consultant. And, ``I most certainly want
to be a CEO some day,'' she said. Hiner's take on that? ``I
wouldn't discount the possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
