<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JULY 2
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-HASSAN-MOROCCO-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 27,
about King Hassan II of Morocco misstated the year that King Farouk
of Egypt was overthrown. It was 1952, not 1956.
</P>
<P>
   BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 29,
about legislation to limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer
failures misstated a provision dealing with class-action suits. The
agreement between the White House and Republicans in Congress would
require that suits involving more than 100 plaintiffs or seeking
more than $10 million in damages be filed in Federal court rather
than state courts. The agreement does not prohibit such suits
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MEXICO-STEEL-NYT (moved on Monday, June 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, June 28,
about Altos Hornos de -Mexico, a steel company, misstated its
relationship to The Chase Manhattan Bank. Chase has $2.2 million in
loans outstanding to Altos Hornos, guaranteed by the United States
Export-Import Bank. Chase is not one of Altos Hornos's large
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-CARR-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 30)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Allan Carr sent by the New York Times News
Service on Wednesday, June 30, misstated the title of a 1977 film
starring John Travolta, whom Mr. Carr selected for the 1978 film
``Grease.'' The 1977 film was ``Saturday Night Fever,'' not
``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
