<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6632 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-MEDICARE-1STLD-WR     07-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-MEDICARE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO'S PLAN TO RAISE PREMIUMS OR DROP BENEFITS FOR MEDICARE
SUBSCRIBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs lede to clarify ambiguity; grafs 3-5 to add details of
Clinton's plan and add name of trade association; 9th graf to
delete redundancy)  (rm) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health maintenance organizations will increase
Medicare premiums or cut benefits for most of their 6 million
elderly subscribers next year because they consider federal
payments to HMOs inadequate, a trade association for the managed
care industry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the association said, at least 250,000 Medicare
beneficiaries will be forced out of HMOs because their plans are
curtailing service areas or dropping out of Medicare. Some of these
beneficiaries may find other HMOs, as the health plans continue to
enroll new members, but many people will find their old doctors are
not members of their new health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions seem to undercut a key part of President Clinton's
latest Medicare proposal, which depends on competition among HMOs
to make the program more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Further, while Clinton's plan calls for Medicare to cover
prescription drugs starting in 2002, many health maintenance
organizations that already provide such coverage said they intended
to cut back drug benefits for Medicare patients next year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the deadline for HMOs to tell the federal
government if they plan to participate in Medicare next year and,
if so, what their premium and benefit packages would be.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs surveyed by the trade group, the American Association of
Health Plans, reported that they were increasing premiums for 1.5
million Medicare beneficiaries next year. Richard I. Smith, vice
president of the association, said that premiums would increase by
more than $20 a month for 930,000 beneficiaries, including 400,000
people who will see increases of $40 or more.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, federal auditors have repeatedly
asserted that Medicare was overpaying HMOs, which now care for
about 16 percent of the program's 39 million beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   However, Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association
of Health Plans, said: ``Overpaid plans don't leave the program.
Overpaid plans don't cut benefits to beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Federal
Health Care Financing Administration, said, ``We're disappointed
that HMOs are making decisions that will force some Medicare
beneficiaries to change their health coverage and at the same time
scaring them about their Medicare benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   HMOs pulled out of more than 300 counties in 22 states early
this year. The changes directly affected more than 400,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   With next year's withdrawals, Ms. Ignagni said, HMOs will have
dropped more than 650,000 people _ about one of every 10 Medicare
beneficiaries in such plans.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials insist that health plans are simply making
business decisions. Michael Hash, deputy administrator of the
Medicare agency, told Congress last month that ``a certain amount
of market volatility must be expected when relying on the private
sector to serve beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DeParle said HMOs that remain in Medicare ``will be paid
more in 2000 than in 1999 _ about 5 percent, on average,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many studies have found that Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs are,
on the average, healthier than those in the original
fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs receive a fixed amount of federal money for each Medicare
beneficiary, regardless of what the person's care costs. Consumer
advocates say some HMOs try to fatten their profits by selectively
recruiting healthy beneficiaries and shunning sicker patients.
Health plans deny that they engage in this practice.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries dropped from an HMO can return to the
original fee-for-service Medicare program or enroll in another
managed care plan if one is available where they live. But Medicare
beneficiaries say the experience of being dumped by an HMO is
traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., who is chairman of the Health
Subcommittee of the Commerce Committee, said the Medicare HMO
program was facing a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Congress takes action to correct this problem, the
consequences will be devastating for Medicare beneficiaries,
especially low-income seniors,'' Bilirakis said. ``Many will lose
the option of participating in a Medicare managed care plan
altogether. Others will face increased out-of-pocket costs or a
reduction in benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   About 55 percent of Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs have incomes
less than $25,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   HIP Health Plans is pulling out of the Medicare program in the
Tampa, Fla., area represented by Bilirakis.
</P>
<P>
   Some Medicare beneficiaries join HMOs even as others leave.
Government data show a small net increase in the number of people
in Medicare HMOs this year, but the industry says enrollment is
growing much more slowly than in the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office has sharply reduced its
projections of Medicare HMO enrollment. Elderly people have become
acutely aware that HMOs can drop out of the Medicare market, and
that is ``likely to reduce the willingness of some Medicare
beneficiaries to enroll in plans in the next few years,'' the
budget office said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Congressional Budget Office said that
unanticipated cutbacks in Medicare payments to many HMOs ``will
impede their ability to offer the additional benefits, such as
prescription drugs, that were expected to encourage more people to
enroll.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American Association of Health Plans hired the firm of Peter
D. Hart Research to conduct the survey. It received responses from
23 HMOs serving 4 million beneficiaries, or two-thirds of those in
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare HMOs must cover at least the services offered in the
fee-for-service program and usually offer additional benefits. The
secretary of health and human services can approve or reject the
mix of premiums and benefits devised by a private health plan. But
if she disapproves, the HMO does not have to participate in
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Beneficiaries in health plans and in the traditional Medicare
program normally pay a monthly premium of $45.50, which is deducted
from their Social Security checks. HMOs may charge additional
premiums for items not covered by the standard Medicare program,
like prescription drugs, eyeglasses, hearing aids and preventive
care.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of the Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs are not
paying any extra premiums this year. For more than half of the
people who do pay extra premiums, the amount is less than $40 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the survey indicated that most Medicare HMOs were
increasing co-payments for prescription drugs or reducing the
amount of drugs for which they would pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
