<HEADER>
A6637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-MAYOR-INDICT-2T     07-01 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MAYOR-INDICT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
LITTLE-KNOWN PANEL SPELLS HEADACHES FOR A SAN DIEGO MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It is made up of 19 ordinary citizens, most of them
retirees, and has a paid staff of one. It operates in solemn
secrecy and has sweeping authority to investigate public agencies
and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Its roots reach back to the Norman Conquest. And even if most
Californians have no idea what it does, it set the political
establishment of the nation's sixth-largest city squarely on its
ear last week.
</P>
<P>
   The headline here was bold and grim _ ``Jury Charges Golding
With Misconduct'' _ and on the surface the news for Mayor Susan
Golding could hardly have been worse. The San Diego County grand
jury had charged her with ``willful misconduct'' in her campaign to
build a new baseball stadium downtown, touching off a
quasi-criminal process that could lead to a trial and, in the worst
case, her removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The reality was considerably more complex. The grand jury that
leveled the accusation against Golding was not a prosecutorial
panel of the sort that routinely hands up criminal indictments but
instead a civil grand jury, a little-understood California
institution that functions more like a citizens' watchdog group,
albeit one with subpoena power. And this grand jury's accusation
against the mayor, the first such charge against a San Diego
official in this century, has brought harsh new scrutiny to a
127-year-old system whose critics say is past its time.
</P>
<P>
   Every county in California has such a grand jury, a panel of 19
volunteers who apply for the job, sit for a year and are selected,
in part at random, by judges. These juries are charged, among other
things, with issuing reports on fraud, waste or mismanagement by
public officials or institutions like hospitals and jails, while in
most cases separate grand juries are impaneled as needed to hear
criminal cases. The civil grand jurors have virtually no permanent
staff and are paid nothing but minimal expenses, and their work is
typically noted and then filed away with little fuss or fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually they get a day's worth of press and then they sit
there,'' said John K. Van de Kamp, former Los Angeles County
district attorney and state Attorney General. ``But once in a
while, you'll hear of a grand jury that's really at odds with
county administrators and gets into conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a thousand years, grand juries and their predecessors
have served an important role as community watchdogs. But grand
juries in fewer than half the states retain any formal vestige of
that role, and ``no other state has the same emphasis'' as
California, said Sara Sun Beale, a professor at Duke University Law
School who is a national authority on grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   This San Diego County grand jury, whose yearlong term expires
this week, has ruffled feathers and rankled a wide range of local
officialdom, faulting everything from the county jail's medical
treatment of inmates to the manners of the district attorney's
office and issuing four reports alone harshly critical of the
city's plan to build a new ballpark for the Padres, which was
approved by nearly 60 percent of voters in a referendum last fall.
The jury's work reflects the skepticism of its foreman, a
71-year-old retired Army intelligence officer named Peter DiRenza.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can tell you is that we were impaneled into
this grand jury to do a job, and that is oversee the county of San
Diego,'' DiRenza said. ``And that's what we've tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To many public officials here, DiRenza and his colleagues amount
to a runaway train, armed with a mantle of judicial solemnity they
do not deserve. The grand jury issued its charge, known formally as
an ``accusation,'' against the mayor without even consulting the
district attorney, Paul Pfingst, who is required by law to review
it to determine whether it merits the equivalent of a trial that
could bring her removal. Alternatively, Pfingst may ask a judge to
dismiss the case if the evidence _ so far still secret _ does not
support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that what this grand jury has accused the
mayor of are illegal acts,'' said the independently elected city
attorney, Casey Gwinn. ``They're not even improper. If a grand jury
could get an elected official removed for this, it would be
unbelievable. They're accusing her of acting like a mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the jury's accusations against the Republican mayor do
seem tenuous. In one count, it faults her for failing to fill
vacancies on a citizens' watchdog commission that oversaw public
utilities, arguing that by doing so she effectively killed the
panel and let money earmarked for burying overhead power lines be
diverted to other purposes. The city attorney counters by saying
the commission was essentially defunct in any case, its role
overtaken by the statewide deregulation of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury's other charge is that Ms. Golding agreed to
support a $4 million appropriation for the San Diego County
Hotel-Motel Association's visitor marketing program in exchange for
its backing of her proposal to build the new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But the city gives no money directly to the association, only to
the Convention and Visitors Bureau, which handles the marketing
efforts, and the mayor can make such decisions only with the
support of the City Council. As it happens, officials say, Ms.
Golding was absent on the day the Council approved the
appropriation and did not even cast a vote.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While the jury has not yet publicly spelled out precisely what
it found so objectionable about the mayor's actions, the
implication is that it was offended by what it considered unseemly
political horse trading.
</P>
<P>
   Details in support of its charges are not to be made public
until next week, about the time Ms. Golding faces the equivalent of
an arraignment. But the foreman, DiRenza, does say that the inquiry
began with a tip last fall, and rejects any suggestion that he or
his colleagues are engaging in some sort of vendetta against the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   DiRenza also says the grand jury acted without consulting the
district attorney because it had taken the matter to the district
attorney's office for an initial review and investigators there had
said there was nothing they could do. ``Being an investigator for
30 years,'' he said of his Army intelligence career, ``I just knew
there was something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney, Pfingst, declined to detail any such
initial consultations, saying they would be a subject of his
official review. But he said he was disappointed that the grand
jury ``clearly did make a deliberate decision not to consult with
our office'' about the formal accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said a state appeals court decision in a similar
case strongly suggested that Ms. Golding might be immune from any
such grand jury action resulting from the performance of her
official duties.
</P>
<P>
   In that 1996 decision, the appeals court threw out a grand jury
accusation against two members of the Orange County Board of
Supervisors stemming from that county's municipal bankruptcy. The
court ruled that just as public officials were immune from lawsuits
over their official actions, so they could not face a grand jury
accusation for official acts or omissions that were not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real issue here as to whether the mayor is simply
immune,'' Pfingst said.
</P>
<P>
   Gwinn, the city attorney, also questions whether the grand jury
even has jurisdiction in such matters in a city like San Diego,
whose charter lays out its own system of removing the mayor for
official misconduct, through a recall election. He says the civil
grand jury, a Gilded Age reform institution intended to check
special interests' power over local government, may well have
outlived its function in an era of open-meeting laws, public
disclosure and media scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Van Nuis, a paralegal who served on last year's civil
grand jury in San Diego, has since decided that the institution
should probably be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``About halfway through the term, it started to occur to me that
you pick your own research topics, so they tend to be issues that
are of concern to you personally and not necessarily the
community,'' she said. ``Most of the grand jurors already had ideas
of what they wanted to write, which is sort of the problem. It
takes on a patina of respectability that I don't think is
warranted. I wrote three reports, and if they'd never been written
the republic would still be standing. These are basically opinion
pieces from people who think their opinion really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   But that, Gwinn said, is not how the public reads the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my dealings with people since this broke,'' he said, ``the
basic reaction is, `This is the grand jury, she must be guilty, she
must have done something wrong.' And every person I've talked to
among the general public does not focus on the specifics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
