<HEADER>
A6640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAZA-SETTLEMENTS-ART-     07-01 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAZA-SETTLEMENTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAZA DILEMMA: BOYCOTT OR PAYCHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT24) has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVE DEKALIM, Gaza Strip _ Slapping mortar onto the wall of a
new house in this Jewish settlement studded with stucco homes and
palm trees, Rifat Jarjua, a Palestinian construction worker,
acknowledged the other day that he was in a hopeless bind.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, a Palestinian, building houses for Israelis on
land he considers to have been taken from his people. On the other
hand, he said, he had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person has to earn his daily bread,'' said Jarjua, 28, who
lives in neighboring Khan Yunis and has two children. ``We have no
other job opportunities, so we're forced to work here. If the
Palestinian Authority wants us to stop working in settlements, it
should give us other jobs. We're trapped between the fire and
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarjua is one of an estimated 11,000 Palestinians who work in
Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, building the
very communities that Palestinian leaders have called a cancer
strangling prospects for an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Palestinian Authority has mounted a
campaign to stop the laborers from working at the settlements,
trying to root out a phenomenon that has become entrenched over
more than 30 years, strengthened by Israeli border restrictions
that prevent many workers from reaching jobs in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The boycott campaign was prompted, Palestinian officials say, by
a sharp increase in Israeli settlement activity in recent months
that has included expansion of existing settlements and erection of
more than a dozen new outposts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unprecedented ferocity of the settlement onslaught obliges
all of us to stop all forms of work in the settlements,'' the
Palestinian cabinet said in a statement. ``The leadership appeals
to everyone to halt work at the settlements, because settlement is
a danger that threatens Palestinian national existence.''
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper announcements, readers have been urged to submit
names of Palestinian building contractors carrying out work in
settlements, and the Palestinian Contractors Union urged its
members to stop working ``on these projects that steal land and
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In the largely Palestinian-governed Gaza Strip, where access to
Jewish settlement enclaves can be more easily controlled,
Palestinian police officers have seized identity cards from
laborers heading for settlements and warned them to stop working
there. Laborers have also been visited in their communities and
cautioned not to show up for work.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish settlers in the Gaza Strip say that in telephone
conversations with workers who are now staying away, they have been
told about stronger pressure: tire slashings, beatings, detentions
and violent questioning by the Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has succeeded in deterring workers from reaching
three small Gaza Strip settlements surrounded by Palestinian-ruled
territory: Netzarim, Morag and Kfar Darom. The absent Palestinians
have been replaced by workers from Romania and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned the page and moved on,'' said Shlomo Kostiner, a
settler from Netzarim and a spokesman for the local settlement
council. ``This is only going to hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   But enforcement of the boycott has been less effective at Neve
Dekalim and the rest of the Katif bloc of settlements, the largest
Israeli enclave in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the boycott has been virtually unenforceable in
the West Bank, where there are only limited areas of Palestinian
control and access to the settlements cannot be blocked by the
Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the boycott campaign is moral persuasion, asserted
Khalid El-Khatib, secretary of the National Committee to Defend the
Land and Confront Settlement, an umbrella organization of several
political groups.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Gaza, Khatib said that the argument made to
the laborers is that Palestinian work in settlements is a
self-defeating absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demand a halt to settlements,'' he said. ``The European
Union and Israeli peace groups say they will boycott goods
manufactured in settlements. The U.S. government calls them
obstacles to peace, and yet our workers and contractors are working
there, cooperating with the expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not putting food on the table, because in our
society relatives help each other in hard times, preventing
hunger,'' Khatib continued. ``The problem is that land is being
stolen daily. Do you want your land or a piece of blood-soaked
daily bread? You can't make peace without land.''
</P>
<P>
   Khatib said efforts are under way to create other jobs in
Palestinian-governed areas, particularly in the private sector,
where priority would be given to workers who have quit their jobs
at settlements. A boycott of work at the settlements would create
an urgent unemployment problem that would compel the Palestinian
Authority to find immediate solutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Khatib's vision remains a distant prospect. The struggling
Palestinian economy cannot provide enough jobs, and thousands of
laborers from the West Bank and Gaza Strip continue to stream daily
to work in settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Muhammad, 42, a father of 12 who works in Neve Dekalim,
scoffed at the Palestinian Authority's boycott appeal. There are
not enough construction jobs in his town, Khan Yunis, he said, and
the pay for such work is significantly lower than the $25 a day
that workers can earn at the Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't tell us not to work here without giving us other
jobs first,'' he said. ``If people are forced to sit at home, there
will be trouble in Khan Yunis _ they'll go out and throw stones.
Forget politics. People want to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
