<SLUG> BC-2QSTX-2QSTX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Net Chip Firms Strike Stock Gold  &HT;     By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Investors channeled their Internet passion away from content
providers and into Internet backbone companies during the second
quarter of 1999.
<P>
   The 10 Bay Area firms with the highest stock price gains during
the quarter almost all provide chips and equipment for the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common theme (behind these gains) is corporate spending on
communications equipment and on people who supply chips to
communications companies,'' said Michael Murphy, editor of the
California Technology Stock Letter in Half Moon Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Bay Area companies saw their stock prices rise by an
average of 23 percent during the three months that ended on June
30, according to a survey of 393 local public firms by Davis Skaggs
Investment Management.
</P>
<P>
   That was significantly better than the 6.7 percent rise in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index and the 9.1 percent rise in the Nasdaq
composite during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 highest-rising local stocks included four semiconductor
firms that sell chips for communications or networking equipment _
MMC Networks Inc., National Semiconductor Corp., ESS Technology
Inc. and Telcom Semiconductor Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That was a marked contrast to 1998 and the first quarter of
1999, when the fastest-rising stocks included Internet content
firms like Excite, Yahoo and Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are looking at chip stocks as a safer and surer way
to get on the Internet bandwagon,'' said Arun Veerappan, a senior
technology analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``The
Internet is powered by the chips that these kinds of companies
produce.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area's Top 10 also included four other firms involved in
communications equipment _ Network Peripherals Inc., Metricom Inc.,
Netopia Inc. and DSP Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Network Peripherals, a Milpitas firm with 150 employees, had the
biggest stock gain of any local firm during the quarter _ rising
from $5.31 to $19.38, an increase of 265 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Network Peripherals' gains were triggered in part by its
announcement of several products targeted at the ``gigabit
Ethernet'' market _ switches that will let companies link their
in-house computer networks at speeds up to 1 billion bits per
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past year, we refocused away from legacy businesses
of 100 megabits into the gigabit arena,'' said company president
William Rosenberger. ``This is a very, very hot market.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, the two worst-performing local
stocks tracked by Davis Skaggs were both biotech firms that
suffered unexpected business setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Depomed Inc. of Foster City saw its stock drop from $10.06 to
$3.13 during the quarter _ mostly because its major partner,
Bristol-Meyers Squibb, decided not to use the drug-delivery
technology Depomed had been developing.
</P>
<P>
   And Scios Inc. of Mountain View saw its stock fall from $9.06 to
$3.25 during the quarter, after the Food and Drug Administration
declined to approve one of its drugs and ordered the firm to do an
additional yearlong clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
