<HEADER>
A6651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-DONATE-580(2TAKE     07-01 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DONATE-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S BIG BANKROLL AND WHAT IT MEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ariz., N.J., Iowa, N.H., Calif., N.Y., Ohio)  (jw) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush's outsized, $36.3 million campaign
war chest, more money than any candidate has raised so early in any
presidential election season, was the driving subject of
conversation Thursday among candidates and political experts who
said it would have an inevitable impact on his competitors and
reshape the landscape of campaign finance for the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, joining several Republicans, sought to
portray the Texas governor as the candidate of big money, showing
that overflowing coffers can bring related political baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's huge bankroll almost certainly means that he will forgo
federal matching funds in the presidential primaries and the
spending limits that come with them, several Bush advisers say.
Thursday, a top campaign adviser to Vice President Al Gore, who has
raised $18.5 million, said his campaign would abide by the spending
limits.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the multimillionaire Republican candidate Steve
Forbes, who eschewed matching funds in 1996 and was again expected
to spend millions of his personal fortune to finance his candidacy,
Bush will probably be the only other candidate to refuse federal
matching funds. He was expected to make an official decision about
how he would finance his campaign later this month.
</P>
<P>
   If the governor refuses matching funds, he can spend whatever he
likes in the early primary and caucus states, while all the other
Republican and Democratic candidates will have to abide by the
strict state-by-state spending limits that apply to candidates who
accept federal matching funds. In Iowa, where the first caucuses
will be held early next year, the spending limit will be about $1.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, where the first presidential primary of the
2000 campaign will be held, the spending ceiling will be about $6.6
million, according to Sharon Snyder, a spokeswoman for the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates who accept matching funds will have to cap their
overall spending in the primaries at a figure somewhere near $33.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants, campaign workers and campaign finance
experts were all reaching Thursday for just the right lopsided term
to describe the Bush campaign's unprecedented fund-raising coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievably big number,'' said Kenneth Gross, a
former FEC official. ``Distressing'' was the adjective chosen by
Roger Witten, a lawyer who stood before the Supreme Court to help
defend the post-Watergate election laws, including the use of
public money and spending limits in presidential elections that
were meant to curb the political money chase.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Clinton said that if Bush
rejected federal spending limits he would be lined up with
Republicans who were ``unanimously hostile'' to changing campaign
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican consultants said the image of being the
big-money candidate could also hurt Bush and perhaps help Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., who has made the campaign finance issue a rallying
cry for his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Berman, a Republican fund-raiser who supports Bush, said
McCain might benefit in the short term. But the biggest effect of
Bush's money, Berman said, is to further dampen the fund-raising
prospects of his rivals. ``It basically means that the air supply
has been shut off to all the second-tier candidates,'' Berman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If the pace of Bush's fund-raising holds up, the $16.7 million
or so that the governor would not receive in federal matching funds
would amount to a small part of his campaign budget. Furthermore,
not being bound by spending limits means that Bush probably will
still be flush long after other candidates have hit the primary
spending ceiling or run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   With primaries scheduled in early March in a number of expensive
states, including California, New York and Ohio, it is quite
possible that other candidates will have gone broke or hit the
ceiling by then. That could leave almost five months in which Bush,
and possibly Forbes, would be the only candidates with campaign
money to burn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bob Dole, the presumptive Republican nominee, hit the
spending ceiling in April. In the months left before the general
election, the party tried to prop up his candidacy by spending
millions of dollars on issue advertising that prominently featured
Dole. The Democratic Party also spent millions on such
advertisements, although the Clinton-Gore ticket did not have a
primary challenge and opened an insurmountable lead over Dole in
those spring and early summer months.
</P>
<P>
   With the prospect of either Gore or former Sen. Bill Bradley,
D-N.J., facing a similar plight next year, several Democratic
fund-raisers said the Democratic National Committee was increasing
its fund-raising. But Marla Romash, deputy chairwoman of the Gore
campaign, insisted that it would have the resources necessary to
``win the primaries and win the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   A party's ``soft money,'' the large contributions that fall
outside federal election law limits, can be used to finance issue
advertising. Soft money is expected to play a bigger role than ever
in the 2000 general election. The Republican and Democratic
nominees will each receive $67.3 million in public money after the
nominating conventions. (If Bush is the Republican nominee, he is
expected to accept federal financing for the general election.)
Then the candidates do not raise any more private donations. But
the parties continue to raise money from private donors. In 1996,
soft-money fund raising by the Democratic and Republican parties
exceeded $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview on Wednesday, McCain predicted that a
billion dollars in soft money would be spent in the 2000 elections,
and called for passage of campaign finance legislation that he has
introduced to ban soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's network of Pioneers, a group of wealthy Republicans who
have been collecting $1,000 checks for him in the last several
months, could quickly be converted to a soft-money team of
fund-raisers for the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, has established himself as the most
successful party fund-raiser in history, and he is busily raising
soft money for the Democratic Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
