<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6656 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASK-ASK_SFCHRON &LR;      07-01 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASK-ASK </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 3 Firms Skyrocket With IPOs  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Three more Bay Area companies launched their stocks into the
financial stratosphere yesterday.
<P>
   Ask Jeeves Inc., a Berkeley search engine service than lets
users pose their questions in plain English, more than quadrupled,
shooting from an offering price of $14 to close at $64.94. The
company, which raised $42 million by selling 12 percent of its
stock to the public, suddenly has a market value of $1.58 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One Inc., a Walnut Creek company that allows firms to
buy products and services over the Internet, nearly tripled in
price, jumping from $21 to $61. The company sold 15 percent of its
shares for $63 million and ended the day with a market value of
$1.39 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Clarent Corp., a Redwood City seller of Internet phone systems,
rose 70 percent to $25.50 from $15 and is worth $670.7 million
after selling 15 percent of the company to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Internet companies are starting off July at the same
sizzling pace they ended the first half of the year. Through the
end of June, 42 Bay Area firms, most of which are Internet related,
went public with an average gain of 138 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Like those IPOs, the three companies that went public yesterday
are not yet profitable. Ask Jeeves lost $4.9 million on $1.1
million in revenues in the first quarter. Commerce One lost $12.3
million on $2.1 million in sales and Clarent lost $5.5 million on
$6.7 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   But their growth prospects are tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves answered nearly 1 million questions per day in April,
and the number of users has more than quadrupled from 425,000 last
September to about 2 million. The company connects users to its
public Web site www.ask.com and tries to direct them to the exact
page that answers their questions. If that fails, it provides
matching Web pages from other search engines such as Yahoo,
WebCrawler and AltaVista.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Jeeves works very well answering the most popular
questions,'' said Danny Sullivan, editor of
www.searchenginewatch.com, which tracks online search services.
``It's not artificial intelligence or software that makes it work
so much as humans (at Ask Jeeves) who find the right links and the
right relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you ask a question about President Clinton, Ask
Jeeves might ask if you want to find out where you can listen to
the Linda Tripp tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves CEO Robert Wrubel said about half the company's 200
employees are editors and researchers who have put about 7 million
questions in the company's ``knowledge base.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Ask ``Why is the sky blue?'' or ``What's an IPO?'' or ``What's
the going rate for a Honda?'' and you get specific, detailed
answers.
</P>
<P>
   But if you ask ``Who said `May you live in interesting times?'''
you will get gibberish. Instead of an answer, Ask Jeeves queries if
you want to know what time it is in Africa or where can to find a
planting map for early May. By contrast, AltaVista quickly links
one to more-appropriate sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask Jeeves isn't perfect,'' said analyst Sullivan. ``But none
of the search engines are.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrubel said that Ask Jeeves keeps adding to its universe of
questions and links to online answers and aims to be ``the first
Internet butler'' that serves up appropriate answers quickly and
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it started a national advertising campaign. In
addition to revenues from banner ads on its public web site, Ask
Jeeves sells its easy-to-use question answering services to
companies such as Bell South, Compaq and Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves is not the only search engine company to go public
recently. GoTo.com, a Pasadena Internet search service that
operates a bit like an online Yellow Pages that lets lets companies
pay for the right to be listed first in search results, has jumped
from $15 to $36.50 since its IPO June 18.
</P>
<P>
   While Ask Jeeves lets people search the Internet, Commerce One
lets companies buys telecommunications gear office supplies and
other products. The company estimates that the business-to-business
e-commerce market will expand from $109 billion this year to $1.3
trillion in 2003. Competitor Ariba Inc. of Sunnyvale has more than
quadrupled from $23 to $105 since its IPO June 23.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
