<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6658 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLS-WELLS_SFCHRON &LR;      07-01 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-WELLS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Wells Distances Itself From Steel Company 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Wells Fargo has lowered its profile as lender to a steel company
accused of unfair labor practices, in what could lead to an end of
a costly and embarrassing union boycott of the San Francisco bank.
<P>
   The bank said yesterday that it has stopped acting as the leader
of a group of lenders that extended $125 million to Oregon Steel
Mills, which refused to take back hundreds of Pueblo, Colo.,
steelworkers after a 1997 strike. Wells Fargo remains a lender to
the company.
</P>
<P>
   The United Steelworkers of America, which has led a 19-month
boycott against Wells Fargo, said the move could prompt it to call
off its campaign but only if the bank takes more action to pressure
Oregon Steel. ``We're hopeful this is a first step,'' said boycott
coordinator Eric Lerner.
</P>
<P>
   The union claims that the boycott has triggered withdrawals of
some $1.2 billion in deposits from the bank; however, Wells Fargo
says it has lost much less.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Wells Fargo insisted that it isn't reducing its
relationship with Oregon Steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``For business reasons, the company restructured the loan,''
said spokeswoman Kathleen Shilkret. ``We are still extending
credit. Bowing to pressure would cause a dangerous precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Once loan terms are set, the leader of a loan syndicate
essentially is an administrator. In an extraordinary move, Oregon
Steel now is carrying out that function itself instead of having a
bank do it, Shilkret said.
</P>
<P>
   Union representatives said it's possible the arrangement is
cosmetic, letting Oregon Steel continue to get credit without
having any lender designated as leader. ``If it's a smoke screen,
we will escalate,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   First Interstate originally led the group of banks that made the
Oregon Steel loan. Wells Fargo inherited the leader position in
1996, when it bought the Los Angeles bank.
</P>
<P>
   After Oregon Steel replaced its unionized workforce, the
Steelworkers tried to hit back by targeting Wells Fargo,
threatening Oregon's source of financing.
</P>
<P>
   The boycott became one of the most visible ``corporate
campaigns'' of recent years. That's an increasingly common union
tactic of pressuring companies to settle labor disputes by
appealing to customers, shareholders, lenders and the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   As the boycott gathered steam, Wells Fargo protested that it
shouldn't be dragged into a labor dispute involving one of its
customers. Boycott supporters maintained that the bank was taking
the company's side by lending it money.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Union Bank of California and its corporate
parent, Japan's Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, withdrew from the Oregon
Steel syndicate though the two banks said their move wasn't a
response to the boycott. Canada's Scotiabank also stopped lending
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, as Oregon Steel's loan was scheduled for
renewal, a union member and two supporters, California Assemblyman
Scott Wildman, D-Los Feliz, and Rick Tuttle, City of Los Angeles
Controller, met with Paul Watson, the bank's corporate banking
chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him it wasn't a good business practice'' to lend to a
company that was using replacement workers, Wildman said.
</P>
<P>
   Wildman, who is chairman of the Joint Legislative Audit
Committee, said he didn't threaten state sanctions against the
bank, such as the withdrawal of pension fund investments.
</P>
<P>
   But people close to Wells Fargo said the intervention of the
lawmaker was a pointed reminder of pro-union sentiments in
Sacramento, where the Legislature and governor's office are both
controlled by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The union said it now will try to find out whether Wells Fargo
is willing to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will ask political and community leaders who have been
go-betweens between the union and Wells Fargo to see if the bank is
willing make any more moves,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
