<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-BEATING-NYT &LR;      07-01 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GIRLS HELD AFTER WOMEN IS BADLY BEATEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A 25-year-old woman was severely beaten in the head
by two teen-age girls on Tuesday after complaining that their car
was blocking the street. She remained in a coma Thursday in a
Northern Virginia hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities in Prince William County, where the incident
occurred in a generally quiet, middle-class neighborhood of
Woodbridge, said it was unusual for girls to commit so brutal a
crime, although the county police said violence by teen-age girls
and young women was on the rise throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever had anything like this with girls
involved,'' said Sgt. Kim Chinn, a spokeswoman for the Prince
William County Police Department. ``But we have noticed in the last
several years that more young girls are becoming involved in crime,
and more in violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ebert, the commonwealth attorney for Prince William County,
said in an interview Thursday that the two girls had administered
``an unusually brutal beating with little justification.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls, Teresa Hattie Dixon, 18, and a 16-year-old girl whose
name was not released because of her age, were arrested shortly
after the beating and are being held without bond. Charged with
aggravated malicious wounding, they could be sentenced to life in
prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the incident began shortly after a car in which
the victim, Natalie Giles Davis, was riding with her two young
children and two other young cousins were passengers left the Davis
house to attend a church service.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Davis drove her car around a stopped vehicle, heated
words were exchanged between her and the two suspects, who were on
the sidewalk with three friends, Chinn said. Mrs. Davis drove on,
and the five girls followed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Davis and the 16-year-old girl left their cars and got into
a fight, which Ms. Dixon joined, the police said. Mrs. Davis' head
was pounded against the sidewalk, the police said, and was also
kicked.
</P>
<P>
   Ebert said he intended to ask the court to try the younger girl
as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokeswoman, Janice Moore, described Mrs. Davis'
condition as critical. Charles Davis, 27, the injured woman's
husband, said doctors had told him her life was in danger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
