<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6661 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-APPLE_SFCHRON &LR;      07-01 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-APPLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Apple Sues Maker of Candy-Colored iMac Look-Alike Computer 
 &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Apple Computer sued the maker of an iMac look-alike yesterday,
charging that Future Power and Korean conglomerate Daewoo filched
the candy-colored iMac's industrial design.
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in San Jose, attempts
to block sales of the $799 Windows-based knockoff and seeks
unspecified actual and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   It contends that E-Power _ a translucent, curvy PC with built-in
monitor and Internet connections _ bears more than a striking
resemblance to the iMac's space-age look. Future Power just debuted
the machine last month at PC Expo in New York; it was slated to
ship in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a universe of original designs that Future Power and
Daewoo could have created for their computers, but instead they
chose to copy Apple's designs,'' Steve Jobs, Apple's interim chief
executive, said in a statement. ``We've invested a lot of money and
effort to create and market our award-winning designs, and we
intend to vigorously protect them under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Santa Clara's Future Power, an 8-month-old startup,
said they have ``not seen a copy of any legal filing and will not
have any comment until that time.''
</P>
<P>
   At PC Expo, Future Power executives had said they discussed the
teardrop-shaped computer's design with lawyers, and were confident
it did not violate Apple's intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is unusual in the PC industry because it centers on
the industrial design of a PC. In the past, Apple has sued over
intellectual property, such as its famous lawsuit against Microsoft
for copying the ``look and feel'' of the graphical user interface
of the Macintosh operating system in Windows. It eventually lost
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, high-tech lawyers said Apple could pursue a tactic
called a ``trade dress'' lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple is likely to argue that its distinct packaging was
ripped off, and that confuses the market,'' said Rich Gray, an
intellectual-property attorney in San Jose. ``They've spent a lot
of time and money establishing the distinctive look of the iMac.''
</P>
<P>
   A trade dress claim, based on a product design's particular
``look and concept,'' was established by the Lanham Act of 1946,
also known as the Trademark Act. In 1992, Taco Cabana, for example,
successfully protected the appearance and decor of its restaurant
chain, much as it would a trademarked word or logo, when it
successfully sued Two Pesos for stealing its motif.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Apple had employed the trade dress strategy in its
graphical-user interface case against Microsoft, it would have
won,'' said Jack Russo, a Palo Alto attorney specializing in
computer litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-maker is especially protective about the iMac, a
hip-looking, heavily promoted consumer machine that helped fuel a
dramatic financial turnaround at Apple. More than 1 million units
have been sold since it began shipping last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Like its more recognizable Mac counterpart, E-Power comes in
five colors (emerald, ruby, topaz, sapphire and amethyst) and an
all-in-one packaging. The iMac is available in a similar palette
but with fruit names: blueberry, grape, strawberry, tangerine and
lime.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only external features distinguishing the two
machines is that E-Power comes with a floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   Future Power is a joint venture backed by Daewoo Telecom, a
subsidiary of the Daewoo Group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
