<DOCNO> NYT19990701.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTA-RECORDS02     07-01 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTA-RECORDS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Olympics official agrees to open all but 8 boxes of
records
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just as Billy Payne officially closed the door
Thursday on the Atlanta Olympics, he pledged to open to the public
all but eight boxes of records from the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said he still wants to keep the disputed documents under
wraps, but he did agree to give a congressional committee
``unfettered access'' to those boxes, which he says contain
personal memorandums and correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Tom Bliley (R-Va.), chairman of the House Commerce
Committee, which is investigating possible corruption in the
Atlanta Olympic bid, would not agree to keep the sensitive records
from the public. In a statement, Bliley said he had ``gone as far
as we can to address their concerns without adversely affecting our
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee says Payne's claim that the papers are personal is
unfounded, and it has demanded in a strongly worded letter that it
be allowed unrestricted access.
</P>
<P>
   The documents in the eight boxes are the subject of the Georgia
Amateur Athletic Foundation lawsuit against state Attorney General
Thurbert Baker and The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, which argue
that the Olympic records are subject to the Georgia Open Records
Act. GAAF owns the records.
</P>
<P>
   Payne had allowed federal investigators to examine the
controversial papers, but he had forbidden them from making copies,
because he feared lawmakers would release them to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have reviewed those documents extensively, and we have
asked them not to copy them until the litigation is completed,''
Payne said during a news conference in the rotunda of the Metro
Chamber of Commerce, overlooking Centennial Olympic Park. ``They
refused that request, so we have complied totally and completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne sent a letter to the House Commerce Committee on Wednesday
saying the foundation would ``cooperate fully.'' But he requested
that the documents in the boxes ``not be disclosed to third
parties'' unless the committee determines them relevant in a
hearing or report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our day in court to prove our case,'' he said. A court
hearing is scheduled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.), who chairs the subcommittee leading
the investigation, welcomed the announcement of cooperation, even
if it came only after the threat of a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know all too well the path Salt Lake City organizers
chose,'' Upton said in a statement. ``Taxpayers deserve to know if
the same thing happened in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Olympic officials said that the 5,700 boxes of documents
to be released will prove that no wrongdoing was associated with
the bid for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this thing broke in Salt Lake City, people started to
wonder about Atlanta and saying, 'Billy, say it ain't so,''' said
A.D. Frazier Jr., former chief operating officer with the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games. ``Well, I'm here to say that it
ain't so.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the eight boxes, all records will be open for
inspection beginning July 19, the third anniversary of the '96
Opening Ceremony, Payne said. The boxes are stored at ACOG
headquarters, the Atlanta History Center and several private
storage facilities. The committee still has to work out a procedure
for viewing the records, which will include retrieval, access and
copying fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every record of the Olympic Games is available for your
inspection,'' Frazier said. ``I beg you to spend the rest of your
life going through those boxes. Have fun. The donor information and
private foundation information is all that is left out, and
Congress has access to that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, which was called to announce the formal
dissolution of ACOG, Frazier reported that its books are balanced
and that any money left in a $12 million contingency fund would be
turned over to the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   While touting the successful conclusion of a 12-year odyssey
that began with Payne's dream of bringing the world's biggest
sports event to Atlanta, the Olympic officials acknowledged
disappointment that the Salt Lake bribery scandal has tarnished
their accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so proud of everything that happened here, and we
wonder why somebody wants to make us ashamed of it, or that there
is something we ought to apologize for,'' said Andrew Young, ACOG
co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The former mayor defended the group's actions and expenses
during the bid process and noted that the money spent on lobbying
fell far short of their competitors' tab.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people to think with $6 million we could out-bribe people
who admittedly spent $15 million in Toronto, $25 million in
Melbourne and $35 million in Athens _ you know better than that,''
said Young, who also is GAAF chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Young, a former U.S. House member and U.N. ambassador, also has
some harsh words for the committee investigating Atlanta's bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the Congress . . . could do business with
one-hundredth of the competence that we demonstrated here, they'd
learn a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
