<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LAD     07-01 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CROWDED STRETCH RUN IN HORSE OF YEAR RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Winning the Hollywood Gold Cup on Sunday
thrust Real Quiet into Horse of the Year contention _ which says a
lot about the state of the campaign for racing's top honor.
</P>
<P>
   At the season's midpoint, there are a lot of candidates but no
George W. Bush or Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wide open,'' said trainer D. Wayne Lukas, whose
near-Triple Crown winner Charismatic is the choice here for Horse
of the Half-Year but is injured and retired and thus a long shot
for next January's vote. ``You're going to need the next six months
(to narrow down the contenders).''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, eventual Horse of the Year Skip Away had won four major
races from Florida to Maryland to California by now.
</P>
<P>
   In '99, only the dominant 3-year-old filly Silverbulletday has
won as many as three Grade I's, and her thumping by colts in the
Belmont Stakes set back her Horse of the Year chances.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, who won the Pimlico Special in May, is one of two
males in the 3-year-olds-and-up division with two Grade I's to
their credit, although his overall record this year is only 2 for
5. The other multiple-Grade I winner is Gulfstream Park and Oaklawn
handicap winner Behrens, who beat Real Quiet in the Massachusetts
Handicap, their only meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens races in Monday's Suburban Handicap at Belmont Park.
Real Quiet is expected to stay sharp by running in the Aug. 7 San
Diego Handicap at Del Mar. Then the two leaders in the ``NTRA
Champions on Fox'' series would square off in the Aug. 29 Pacific
Classic at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, '98 Belmont winner Victory Gallop, second to Behrens
in this week's NTRA poll, is aiming for the Aug. 1 Whitney at
Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 6 Breeders' Cup Classic at Gulfstream looms as the
championship-decider. Six of its past 12 winners were Horses of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   If none of the older horses takes command, it could be a year
for a dominant figure from a minor division, like '97, when a
splintered vote went to undefeated 2-year-old Favorite Trick.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possibilities: 3-year-old General Challenge, planning
to use the July 18 Swaps Stakes at Hollywood Park as a springboard
to the Pacific Classic; 2-year-old filly Chilukki, a brilliant 3
for 3 for Bob Baffert; 6-year-old Yagli, 2 for 2 in Grade I turf
races; 4-year-old filly Banshee Breeze, unbeaten in three starts;
and 4-year-old filly Manistique, 4 for 5 but winless outside
California in her career.
</P>
<P>
   Six more months, it'll all be settled.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: The five Hollywood Park stakes Saturday, Sunday and
Monday include the Beverly Hills Handicap, in which Julio
Canani-trained Tranquility Lake will be odds-on for her fourth
straight front-running victory on turf after beginning her career 2
for 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julio's improved this horse 10 to 15 lengths,'' said owner
Martin Wygod, who moved the 4-year-old to Canani last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sub-standard: Puerto Madero, fourth and last in the Hollywood
Gold Cup, favored his left front ankle the next day. Richard
Mandella said X-rays were negative and the Chilean-bred was
scheduled for further examination.
</P>
<P>
   But a new physical problem probably wouldn't explain three
straight indifferent performances since his Donn Handicap win.
Puerto Madero trained sharply and looked great in the paddock.
Maybe the 5-year-old simply has lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up: Budroyale, the 6-year-old ex-claimer whose
earnings went over $1 million with the Gold Cup's second-place
purse of $200,000, will try softer competition next time in the
Aug. 22 Longacres Mile at Emerald Downs near Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've followed our hearts with this horse, (and) that's a race
I've always wanted to win,'' said owner Jeffrey Sengara, who is
from Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsammy out: Emile Ramsammy, having his best meet since joining
the Southern California circuit in 1998, expects to miss the rest
of the Hollywood Park season after fracturing his right collarbone
Sunday at Woodbine Race Course near Toronto. He was fourth in the
standings here with 30 winners in 143 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just bad luck,'' said Ramsammy, hurt when his mount broke
down and fell in the race following his third-place finish aboard
Bobby Frankel-trained Euchre in the Queen's Plate.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsammy took over the assignment because Mickey Walls, who won
Canada's premier race aboard Woodcarver, was tied up with
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Sad ending: The death of Three Ring, who flipped and fractured
her skull in the Belmont Park paddock before Sunday's Mother Goose
Stakes, has to rank high on the long list of racetrack tragedies.
Trainer Eddie Plesa said the Grade I-winning 3-year-old filly
seemed to panic when she stepped on a downward slope in her
saddling stall.
</P>
<P>
   Owners are emotionally prepared for the worst to happen while
their horses are racing. But while they're being saddled?
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring has been buried at owner Barry Schwartz's Stonewall
Farm in Granite Springs, N.Y. A $770,000 earner since being
purchased privately for $250,000 as a 2-year-old, she was not
insured, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   Can he say that? Michael Wrona might have achieved a
race-calling first when he said the favorite in Sunday's Hollywood
Park nightcap, running at the back of the pack at the time, faced
``a hell of a task.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as it came out of my mouth, I thought, `What did you
just say?''' Wrona said of the profanity. ``That's one I'll try not
to repeat. I hope nobody was offended.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
