<SLUG> BC-VALUJET-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINTENANCE FIRM'S LAWYER EXPECTS INDICTMENTS IN VALUJET CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., Mo., Texas, Ga.)  (jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The lawyer for an aircraft maintenance company
involved in the crash of Valujet Airlines Flight 592 in the
Everglades three years ago said Thursday that he believed it was
likely that the company and some of its employees would soon be
indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal indictments after plane crashes are extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, a DC-9, crashed on May 11, 1996, shortly after
takeoff from Miami, killing all 110 people on board. The National
Transportation Safety Board traced the cause of the crash to a fire
in the forward cargo hold started by reactive chemicals in old
airplane parts, oxygen generators, which had been removed from
another Valujet plane by the maintenance company, Sabretech.
</P>
<P>
   Sabretech delivered the parts to the ramp where Flight 592 was
being loaded for its trip to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The company and the airline have been under investigation by
federal and Florida authorities for possible violation of laws
governing labeling and shipment of hazardous materials, and of
environmental laws. A spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Miami, Alicia Valle, said she could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Miami-Dade state attorney's office, Donald Ungurait, a
spokesman, said, ``We do have an ongoing investigation that
accompanies the federal investigation and in other ways is purely
independent, under state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It involves all of the potential parties who were involved in
the activity surrounding the Valujet tragedy,'' Ungurait said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not say if indictments were expected.
</P>
<P>
   But the maintenance company's lawyer, Kenneth Quinn of
Washington, said, ``I have no reason to believe that the
government, after an exhaustive three-year investigation, is going
to do anything other than indict, unless we can reach some kind of
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there's any evidence of any willful or criminal
behavior connected to this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, a former general counsel of the Federal Aviation
Administration, said he believed that an indictment would hurt
future air safety investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the FBI and homicide detectives are going to show up on
site as they have in the TWA and Valujet cases,'' he said, ``I'm
sure any lawyer in their right mind would tell companies and
employees not to cooperate, without a guarantee of immunity.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the safety board had also found fault with Valujet
and FAA inspectors and that if his clients were indicted, those
parties should be, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Steven Marks has represented the families of 28
passengers on the plane. ``We believe, based on the discovery we've
taken on the civil side,'' he said, ``that the conduct was of such
an egregious nature that it would justify a punitive damage
finding, which in Florida is essentially the equivalent to
manslaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five of the cases have been settled, Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the crash, Sabretech was a subsidiary of a
privately held St. Louis company, Sabreliner. The company closed
the Miami shop and re-opened in Orlando, Fla., but eventually
closed that, too, and a shop in Amarillo, Texas. Sabretech's assets
were sold to Aviation Management Systems Inc. of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Valujet renamed itself Airtran Airways. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-01-99 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
