<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AFTER 4 YEARS, U.S. WOMEN SURVIVE ANOTHER DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ There was no room for error, not after nearly
four years of smarting. To earn their way back to the semifinals of
the Women's World Cup, the Americans had to survive dangerous
Germany, 3-2, Thursday night in the steamy casserole dish of Jack
Kent Cooke Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the part we love _ win or lose,'' Julie Foudy, the
loquacious midfielder, had said.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everything had been engineered for the Americans in
their home country. They had the easiest travel schedule, a fairly
logical meander toward the West Coast if they could win Thursday
night, while the Chinese had to put their twanging hamstrings in
airplanes for coast-to-coast treks.
</P>
<P>
   Even the official 1999 Women's World Cup video was a veritable
celebration of Yankeedom _ barely a reference to the perhaps
inconvenient, but certainly indisputable, fact that the Norwegians
are defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   Since they lost to Norway, 1-0, on an early and devastating goal
in the semifinals in Sweden in 1995, the American women had been
waiting to get back to the semifinals. They would have to win
Thursday night. There was no option of a tie, as there had been in
the three games of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friendlies are nice,'' Foudy said about the long list of
international matches, ``but this is what the World Cup is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans made a stunning mistake in the fifth minute
Thursday night when Brandi Chastain made a bad pass past goalkeeper
Briana Scurry for an own goal and a 1-0 Germany lead.
</P>
<P>
   The wise old Michelle Akers moved forward as the American
offense launched into gear, and a hard shot was deflected to
Tiffeny Milbrett, who tied the score in the 16th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The home team was shocked again in the first minute of extra
time and a German oompah band played a rendition of ``Roll Out the
Barrel,'' its gusto fueled by 2-1 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain tied the score in the 49th minute, bellowing with what
looked like relief. Then Joy Fawcett, the most underrated of the
longtime regulars, nicked in an exquisite header in the 66th minute
to give the United States the lead and a berth in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency of the game (followed by Brazil-Nigeria) was based
on four years of waiting _ maturation by the Chinese, retooling by
the Norwegians, tapping the national genius by the Brazilians. The
key phrase is ``four years.'' That is a long time to smart.
</P>
<P>
   Four years make the World Cup. Four years give it the bite, the
tension, the anticipation. In the eccentric little sport of
American football, a Super Bowl is played once every year, but it
somehow seems more frequent than that. In real football _ soccer _
four years go by for the big one. The rest of the world knows how
to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is, why would anybody want to tinker with this
system? Oddly enough, Joseph ``Sepp'' Blatter, the president of the
world soccer body, known as FIFA, has been making some rather
radical pronouncements about holding the men's (and by projection,
the women's) cups every two years, on the rather dubious assumption
that more is better.
</P>
<P>
   Revision cannot happen any too soon, so the men will hold their
next one in 2002 in Japan and South Korea, while the women will
have to wait until 2003, perhaps in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's game was held out in the suburbs rather than at
RFK Stadium in Washington, after RFK officials demanded the final
game or they would not participate. They should have understood
that FIFA has been fixated on the Rose Bowl since the huge crowds
at the 1984 Olympic tournament and the 1994 men's World Cup. When
the RFK people declined, the Cooke officials jumped right in _ and
Thursday night reaped the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was to operate with a downsized capacity of
41,110 Thursday night, but as the American women captivated
America, the demand for tickets grew, and officials opened the
upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was huge, and supportive, but the American players had
a tough assignment against the second-place finisher from the
strongest group in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, finalists in 1995, wear the same white and black,
or all green, uniforms as the German men's national team _ and are
also disciplined athletes who are never to be counted out of a
game. Like the Americans, they had been waiting four years to get
back. Four years is what makes this event so special. Why do we
have to keep reminding the soccer officials about this?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
