<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH RAIN AND GLOOM, GRAF DELIVERS VICTORY OVER WILLIAMS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ The darker it got, and the longer it
dragged on, the more impassioned the Wimbledon quarterfinal between
Steffi Graf and Venus Williams became. Graf, the seven-time
champion, had a statement to make in her rain-infested contest with
Williams, the 19-year-old American whom Graf has deemed worthy to
inherit her mantle. But not until Graf is ready to relinquish it.
</P>
<P>
   So after seven hours and four rain delays, Graf grabbed a lethal
service break to lead 3-2 in the final set, then fended off three
break points to hold for 4-2. She wound up advancing to her 10th
career Wimbledon semifinal with a 6-2, 3-6, 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played unbelievable tennis, and that's what counts to me,''
Graf said. ``Everyone that came in the locker room _ you know,
Virginia Wade, Pam Shriver _ was saying it was an incredible match,
and that's how I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Graf used the occasion of her 22nd Grand Slam
victory last month at the French Open to announce her retirement
from that event. As for this one, her favorite, Graf hasn't yet
completed her mission and won't even if she wins here this year: an
eighth Wimbledon crown would leave her one major short of tying
Margaret Court's Grand Slam record of 24 singles titles. And while
Graf doesn't give the record books as much deference as Pete
Sampras does, she does crave another title at Wimbledon, which she
last won in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Graf called this the most difficult quarterfinal she has ever
played, not only because it had to be played in fits and starts,
but also because Williams put up such a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the game,'' said Graf, whose formidable forehand and
hissing backhand slice didn't scare Williams. ``She got some balls
I thought were over.''
</P>
<P>
   Another American, third-seeded Lindsay Davenport, had a faster
outing. With a barrage of passing shots and heavy artillery from
the baseline, Davenport beat the defending champion, Jana Novotna,
in just 65 minutes, 6-3, 6-4, to achieve her first Wimbledon
semifinal. Davenport, who made her Grand Slam title breakthrough at
the 1998 U.S. Open, also put herself one victory away from
reclaiming the No. 1 ranking from Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grass-court game is getting better every year,'' said
Davenport, who is now 6-0 against Novotna, the stylish 30-year-old
Czech net-rusher. ``I think for some people today this is a huge
upset, and in some ways it is, but in other ways I knew I could do
it going out there. Did she play her best tennis? Probably not, but
maybe that was because I didn't let her.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna was realistic about the demise of her title defense:
``Every player has one player, a particular player that you don't
really like to play against, and in my case, Lindsay is that
player,'' she said, ``simply because she has a very good serve and
very powerful ground strokes, and I just get overpowered.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Williams didn't get overpowered by Graf, she was the
more uncomfortable performer when, at 7:30 p.m., the two were
summoned back onstage a final time with Graf on the verge of
holding serve to level the third set at 2-2. And then, in the fifth
game, when Williams netted a forehand that sent the game to deuce
instead of giving her a 3-2 lead, the teen-ager began to press. Her
forehand volley blooper gave Graf a break point, and the German
converted it with a vicious one-two forehand punch: the first shot
made a perfect diagonal and pulled Williams into the corner, and
though the American somehow managed to send a reply back across the
net, Graf was ready to intercept it with a pulverizing
down-the-line forehand.
</P>
<P>
   Too rattled to convert any of the three break points she held in
the next game, Williams, who watched replays of the unfinished
match during the rain delays, watched the match fade away with the
light.
</P>
<P>
   As camera flashbulbs flickered like fireflies in the Center
Court stands and the gloom was complicated by a light drizzle, Graf
served for the match. The marathon ended moments later when
Williams muscled a down-the-line forehand wide at 40-30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have played better on some key points, been more
aggressive on break points, but time ran out,'' said Williams.
``I've played some pretty good matches and still lost, so this
definitely will go on the record.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two women's quarterfinals failed to reach a resolution
by the time play was officially abandoned at 8:30 p.m. Their
contestants were doomed to spend the night in suspended animation
after spending most of the day in a vigil as they waited in vain
for the showers to pass.
</P>
<P>
   In a confrontation guaranteed to give Wimbledon's women's
semifinal round its first qualifier in tournament history,
86th-ranked Alexandra Stevenson, the San Diego teen-ager who turned
her back on a UCLA scholarship by turning professional here,
claimed the first set from 16-year-old Jelena Dokic of Australia,
6-3. But Dokic was up 5-1 and serving for the second set at 40-30
when their match was halted by darkness.
</P>
<P>
   In the other quarterfinal, last year's runner-up, Nathalie
Tauziat, led 17-year-old Mirjana Lucic, 6-4, 3-3. Three of the
eight women participating Thursday _ Lucic, Dokic and Stevenson _
were playing in their first Slam quarterfinals. Lucic upset Monica
Seles in the third round, and Dokic crafted a historic upset of
top-seeded Martina Hingis in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the men's quarterfinals got onto court, and neither
made significant progress: sixth-seeded Tim Henman led 38th-ranked
Cedric Pioline, 1-0, and second-seeded Patrick Rafter was locked up
at 3-3 against eighth-seeded Todd Martin. The 30-year-old Pioline,
a Frenchman who reached the final here in 1997, is the only
unseeded player left in men's quarters.
</P>
<P>
   With none of the men's quarterfinals decided and more stormy
weather predicted for Saturday, Wimbledon officials seemed resigned
to a women's final on Sunday: the men's and women's finals have not
shared the same day since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling committee hadn't yet contemplated the unwanted
contingency of a Monday men's final, a scenario last resorted to
when Stefan Edberg defeated Boris Becker in 1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
