<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RULING MAY CLEAR WAY FOR NEW VOTE ON ANTI-AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
PROPOSITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: optional trim, optional ending included) 
 
By JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Texas Supreme Court ruled Thursday that
affirmative action foe Edward Blum is legally justified in
challenging the city's rewording of his November 1997 ballot
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The court also ruled that a state district court has the
authority to prevent the city from using vague and misleading
language, but cannot stop an election. The mixed decision could
clear the way for a new vote on the anti-affirmative action
proposition that voters rejected, thereby upholding Houston's
Minority and Women Disadvantaged Business Enterprise program.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling returns the legal dispute back to state District
Judge Sharolyn Wood's court, where Wood, a Republican, threw out
the results of the Proposition A referendum in a preliminary ruling
last year that is not yet final. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In 1997, Blum collected more than 20,000 signatures on a
petition to place his measure on the ballot. The measure called for
abolishing the use of racial and gender preferences in granting
city contracts, using language almost identical to the 1964 federal
Civil Rights Act. Blum also based his language on California's
Proposition 209.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Bob Lanier, an affirmative action proponent, and City
Council rewrote the measure over Blum's strenuous objections so
that instead, it asked voters if Houston should end its affirmative
action program. Voters rejected the measure, 54 percent to 46
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this really means is the voters here in the city of
Houston are going to finally have the opportunity to vote on the
initiative that 20,000 people signed to end racial preferences and
end discrimination,'' Blum said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Zummo, a lawyer for the city, said Blum and his
supporters are far from assured of a new election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I think the other side still has to prove the
rewording of the ballot language changed the outcome of the
election,'' Zummo said. ``They haven't done that, and until they do
that they aren't entitled to another election.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Lee Brown, whose election as the first black mayor aided
the defeat of the proposition because of record black voter
turnout, said in a statement issued late Thursday that he was
confident the contracting program would survive another election.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, our position has been that the ballot
language was clear and easily understandable, which is why the move
to eliminate affirmative action was defeated by Houston voters,''
Brown's statement said. ``With the majority of Houstonians
supporting us, I am certain that we will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the core issues at stake in the case remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   The justices ruled in Thursday's decision that Blum does have
legal standing to challenge the city's rewording of his ballot
proposition without ruling on the merits of his case. The court,
however, also noted the city has the authority to alter such ballot
language, but not to the extent that it misleads voters.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also ruled that a state district court has the
authority to prevent the city from using vague and misleading
ballot language, but not to stop an election.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the city's rewording is vague and misleading as Blum
contends is a matter for Wood's immediate consideration _ and the
judge has already ruled the wording on the ballot did not reflect
the intent of those who signed Blum's petition.
</P>
<P>
   If she enters a final order determining that the ballot measure
was vague and misleading, a new election on the measure could be
called.
</P>
<P>
   Two years before the election, Lanier and City Council
significantly strengthened the Minority and Women Disadvantaged
Business Enterprise program, which directs about 20 percent of the
city's $1 billion annual contracting program to qualified firms
owned by women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Blum, who is co-chairman of the Houston Civil Rights Initiative,
argued the city's program perpetuates discrimination by granting
preferential treatment for women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
The proposition originally submitted by Blum read: ``The city of
Houston shall not discriminate against, or grant preferential
treatment to, any individual or group on the basis of race, sex,
color, ethnicity or national origin in the operation of public
employment and public contracting.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lanier's urging and over Blum's objections, City Council
changed the wording to:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shall the charter of the city of Houston be amended to end the
use of affirmative action for women and minorities in the operation
of city of Houston employment and contracting, including ending the
current program and similar programs in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   Blum and his supporters immediately challenged the rewording in
the courts, touching off a legal odyssey on a range of issues that
include jurisdiction over election matters, proper legal standing
to pursue litigation, ballot rewording and the sanctity of election
results.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Tad Halbach in October 1997 rejected Blum's
attempt to block the referendum, siding instead with the city,
which argued that Halbach lacked jurisdiction on the matter until
after the election concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city also argued that Blum lacked legal standing
to pursue the case, an opinion that was subsequently affirmed by
the 14th Court of Appeals. The Supreme Court ruling overturned the
appellate court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Who has the final authority on the wording of a ballot
initiative remains unclear. The Texas Supreme Court opinion does
not address the merits of either Blum's or the city's version of
the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   In rewriting Blum's measure, Lanier contended that Blum's
original wording did not convey the true intent of the petition
drive and ballot initiative, which was to dismantle the city's
contracting program.
</P>
<P>
   Blum said he objects to inclusion of the phrase ``affirmative
action'' in the city's version of the ballot measure. Blum said
``affirmative action'' is a ``nebulous phrase'' without legal
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Wood has scheduled a hearing in the case for later this month,
and has yet to issue a final ruling in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Given the timing of the latest decision, it appears unlikely the
legal issues will be resolved in time for the matter to appear on
the upcoming Nov. 2 city elections, said Alan Magenheim, a lawyer
for Blum.
</P>
<P>
   But, Magenheim said, the justices' ruling should go far in
clarifying the rights of voters and elected officials in the arena
of initiative and referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city will now have to honor the wishes of voters and put
the language on the ballot significantly similar those offered by
the voters,'' Magenheim said. ``Although the Supreme Court's ruling
is not determinative of how a new election will turn out, it will
ensure the next election will be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, a federal appeals court threw out a Houston
federal judge's order banning affirmative action contracting at the
Metropolitan Transit Authority. The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruled the issues surrounding the challenge to the program
by the Houston Contractors Association must be decided in a full
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's program, which is modeled on the city's, had been
halted by U.S. District Judge Lynn Hughes in a 1997 summary
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
