<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENNSYLVANIA: GORE IS FOLLOWED BY AIDS PROTESTERS 
NEW YORK: FORBES PASSES THE HAT AMONG COMMON FOLK 
NEW HAMPSHIRE: CANDIDATES DELIVER LAUGH LINES AT GALA
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., N.Y., N.H., N.J., Texas, Utah, Tenn.)  (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has more than enough problems on the
campaign trail these days, what with the Republican front-runner,
George W. Bush, in front of him in the polls and fund-raising and
his only Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey,
beginning to pick up traction in the rear. Now add to that the
noisy AIDS protesters who have begun showing up at just about every
major campaign stop, more than 3,000 of them when Gore passed
through Philadelphia on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Their complaint is that Gore, who frequently speaks out on
health issues, is the Clinton administration's point man when it
comes to helping the pharmaceutical industry make big money off of
AIDS drugs. ``Gore's greed kills!'' they chant when he begins to
speak or starts to work a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the protesters assert that Gore has done nothing
to make it easier for people with AIDS in Africa, most notably
those in hard-hit South Africa, to obtain AIDS drugs developed in
the United States. The protesters say the drugs are so expensive
that most African patients cannot afford them.
</P>
<P>
   They want Gore to take the lead in lowering the cost by
persuading U.S. drug companies to allow African companies with low
manufacturing overhead to make and sell AIDS drugs. They also want
him to persuade U.S. trade officials to drop opposition to South
African trade laws that pressure multinational American drug
manufacturers into making the drugs more available.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, aware that the issue could affect two important Democratic
constituencies, gay and black voters, insists that he is working
hard to find a solution to the problem. Shortly after the protests
began, he arranged for protest leaders to meet with White House
officials who work on AIDS issues.
</P>
<P>
   But he notes that the problem of drug costs is especially
complicated because patent and trade laws protect U.S. drug
companies, and he points out that the cost of developing new drugs
often accounts for a good part of their high price.
</P>
<P>
   After the Philadelphia demonstration, Gore issued a statement in
which he said he fully supported efforts to make new and cheaper
AIDS drugs available in Africa, so long as the efforts ``are done
in a way consistent with international agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders welcomed that statement but said the
demonstrations would continue until U.S. policy actually changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We await further movement,'' said one of the movement's
organizers, Eric Sawyer of New York.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES PASSES THE HAT AMONG COMMON FOLK
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1996, Steve Forbes spent $37.5 million of his personal
publishing fortune on his first run for the presidency. And he says
he is ready to do it again the second time around, if necessary,
which well may be the case given that he is still down in the
single digits in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Forbes is trying to raise some money the old-fashioned
way, too. Rather than write another personal check, he recently
held a $1,000-a-plate dinner in New York that pulled in more than
$1 million, and he has begun mass mailings that appeal for cash,
even if it is as little as $25.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble down at the bank?
</P>
<P>
   Not really, Forbes says.
</P>
<P>
   What he is trying to do, he explains, is build up grass-roots
involvement in his campaign and thereby demonstrate that
Forbes-for-President is not just a one-man movement or, to put it
more precisely, one rich man's movement. It is very important, he
says, to show that there is a solid base of people who are willing
to invest in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives credibility,'' he adds, noting that once people
contribute cash to a campaign they are likely to follow up by
voting for the recipient and, in many cases, will give a second and
third time and maybe even volunteer to do campaign work.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has a long way to go to match the $36.3 million that Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas raised over the past four months. But he is
nearing the $3 million mark, which is roughly average for most of
the Republican field.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   CANDIDATES DELIVER LAUGH LINES AT GALA
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire says it is determined to hold the first Election
2000 primary, even if it has to hold it in 1999. Maybe. Maybe not.
A lot of other states are jockeying to grab some of that
first-in-the-nation glory.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the New Hampshire primary's past, not its future,
that was the focus of a $500-a-plate gala on Wednesday night in
Washington to raise money for the Library and Archives of New
Hampshire's Political Tradition. The library, in the New Hampshire
capital, Concord, holds an extensive collection of election
campaign papers, buttons and other paraphernalia, some of it dating
back nearly 50 years to the earliest primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Four hundred political addicts showed up for the event,
including seven current White House hopefuls. Some of them,
including several never previously accused of being yuksters, got
off some lines that might not be prime archival material but
nevertheless provide some light insight into the kinds of people
who are running this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore on Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, brand new in
the race and given almost no chance of ever catching up:
</P>
<P>
   ``Orrin Hatch called to say he'd be late and we should start
without him. I think we already did.''
</P>
<P>
   More Al Gore, this time playing off an old Ronald Reagan primary
debate line and the fact that the gala was being held in a
taxpayer-financed building, and working in a play on a recent Gore
gaffe about inventing the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``So we can all say, `I paid for this microphone.' But I'm the
only one who can say I invented this microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee, recalling the response
from a factory worker on a cigarette break who, upon learning that
Alexander was running for president, blew a mouthful of smoke at
him and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all we need, another president.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Smith, himself a New Hampshirite but thus far well
out of the running in money and the polls, offering a campaign
ditty:
</P>
<P>
   ``Single digits, no name ID, so say the polls. But there's many
more Smiths than Bushes and Doles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
