<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILKILLER-INS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS CAUGHT SERIAL-KILLING SUSPECT 12 TIMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Marisa Taylor and Steve Stein 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Angel Leoncio Reyes Resendiz, suspected of committing a
string of slayings, has been caught by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service at least 12 times since 1976, INS
Commissioner Doris Meissner acknowledged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Reyes, whom the FBI identifies by one of his aliases, Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez, wasn't detained for prosecution when he was last
apprehended in June because the INS computer database was not
complete and did not list all his apprehensions, she said.
Undocumented immigrants can be caught crossing the border up to
eight times in Santa Teresa, N.M., where he was apprehended, before
they are prosecuted, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner, speaking at a Dallas news conference, defended her
agency's ability to apprehend undocumented immigrants suspected of
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we look at a case like this, and it's horrifying
that somebody like this could exist and could be at large,''
Meissner said. ``My reaction was, `Did something fail here?' And I
want to know if it did, what it was and what can done about it so
it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Meissner requested the U.S. Justice Department's
Office of the Inspector General to investigate the Border Patrol's
last encounter with Reyes, which was June 2 in Santa Teresa, a
community near El Paso. He was released to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now can see, piecing various parts of the story together,
that he has been in our custody on numerous occasions,'' Meissner
said. ``Obviously, had we known that in Santa Teresa at the time,
we would have acted upon it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyes is on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list in connection with
eight homicides, including five in Texas. The first slaying he is
suspected of committing was in 1997 in Kentucky, and the most
recent were two slayings June 15 in Illinois. Authorities believe
that Reyes has a history of riding rail cars across the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Teresa, Border Patrol agents do not keep undocumented
immigrants in custody for deportation until they have been caught
eight times, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Supervisory Assistant U.S. Attorney John Crews in New
Mexico said most immigrants caught in Santa Teresa are not detained
for a deportation hearing until they have been caught 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   Crews would not explain the discrepancy other than to say the
practice is an internal policy matter.
</P>
<P>
   The policies regarding deportation vary from city to city,
federal officials said. In El Paso, immigrants are held for
deportation hearings after their fifth apprehension. In McAllen,
they are detained after their third apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   Each Border Patrol sector is different, said George Garza, the
Border Patrol agent-in-charge of the McAllen station. ``In some
sectors, it might overload the court.''
</P>
<P>
   If undocumented immigrants have been formally deported in the
past, they are usually detained and prosecuted immediately, Crews
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reyes was formally deported three times between 1985 and
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The INS database, known as IDENT, has been criticized as flawed
because it is not directly linked to other federal, state and local
criminal databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS has spent more than $65 million on a system that does
not protect the public,'' U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio,
chairman of the House Immigration Subcommittee, said during a news
conference Wednesday in Washington. ``The Border Patrol knows, too
late, about Resendez-Ramirez.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents say it takes time to research each case if they want more
details.
</P>
<P>
   The INS database is designed to enter each apprehended
immigrants' name, photograph and fingerprints. But in July 1997,
about 47 percent of the undocumented immigrants apprehended by
agents along the Southwest border were not entered in the database,
according to a report from the Justice Department's Office of the
Inspector General. The report also states that the INS did not
enter into the database that names of 59 percent of undocumented
immigrants deported in fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The IDENT system has more than 400,000 criminal names of
undocumented immigrants and 85,000 of those have been apprehended
based on background checks, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IDENT system is a system that has worked very, very
effectively at the border,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration authorities have also been perplexed by the shifting
identities of Reyes, who has used several names. But INS officials
aren't sure why the system, including fingerprinting, didn't catch
his identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person has used a large number of aliases. There have
been very significant changes in his appearance,'' Meissner said.
``And so the systems that we have for checking this information
have contained information in various pieces, but it did not come
together as fully as it might have.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner was in Dallas to launch a Border Patrol recruiting
initiative. Because of difficulties in hiring enough Border Patrol
agents, INS has trained the best agents to recruit potential
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the news conference was focused almost entirely on Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Steps have been taken to catch the slaying suspect if he is ever
in the Border Patrol's grasp again, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI most-wanted list is now part of the INS' computer
database.
</P>
<P>
   A $125,000 reward is being offered for information that leads to
Reyes' arrest and conviction. Residents in Lexington, Ky., and in
the Texas towns of Weimer and West University Place have put up
$75,000 of the reward. The FBI is offering the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect was born Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis in Izucar de
Matamoros, in the state of Puebla, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Don K. Clark, agent in charge of the Houston division of the
FBI, is heading the search for Reyes, code-named Operation Train
Stop. Several agencies are part of Operation Train Stop, including
Lexington, Ky., police and the Jackson County, Ill., Sheriff's
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The command center, which is staffed around the clock, has
received 4,000 calls since June 8. Calls to the command center have
resulted in what the FBI is describing as 1,500 ``good leads.''
</P>
<P>
   The toll-free telephone number at the command center is (800)
889-8161.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
