<SLUG> BC-COCKTAILS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: COCKTAIL TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was quite a party for a regular Friday afternoon:
limbo dancers on Second Avenue, a steel-drum band and nonalcoholic
samples of Malibu Rum drinks like Malibu Conga Punch. Then, a lucky
few took specially equipped free ``fantasy buses'' to the Hamptons,
the trendy vacation area on eastern Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The event last week was one of several big promotions that
United Distillers &AMP; Vintners, the nation's largest liquor company,
and a unit of Diageo PLC, are creating this summer to tap into what
the company believes is a new willingness by consumers to try mixed
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Some call it a return of the classic cocktail. Others link the
phenomenon to the new ``lounge culture,'' where swing music, 1960s
mod clothes and Rat Pack style are all the rage. Still others
credit weightier factors like a strong economy and a growing
population of people turning 21, the legal drinking age.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the liquor industry is celebrating the
trend with a wide range of promotions for special cocktails,
ranging from classics like the Canadian Mist Fizz to the more
unusual Baileys Mudslide or the Chocolate Martini. And to get
consumers' attention without the benefit of television advertising
_ which most liquor marketers for various reasons still do not use
_companies use everything from zany ideas like Malibu's ``Limbo for
Your Lunch'' to Internet advertising and promotional partnerships
with radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to be able to get directly to consumers to
try our brands,'' said Derek Blackburn, United Distillers' vice
president for customer marketing in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   For many brands, summer is a key time to create promotional buzz
about a drink because people are out more at bars and restaurants,
especially the young and image-conscious whose word-of-mouth can
make a new cocktail a hit.
</P>
<P>
   For Jose Cuervo Tequila, United Distillers is introducing a
Cuervo Nation Bus tour. A bus covered in Jose Cuervo graphics and
carrying a Cuervo Crew that will distribute free Cuervo merchandise
to consumers, will visit key markets in the Northeast. All stops
will be announced on radio and in Internet advertising. United
Distillers is also giving away free trips to its Cuervo Nation, a
small Caribbean island that it owns for promotional reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Baileys Original Irish Cream _ best known as a winter drink _ is
pushing frozen and iced drinks like the Baileys Mudslide and
Baileys Iced Capuccino, using a sweepstakes and bar events that
include taking digital photos of customers and then sending them
via e-mail. To get attention, Baileys also plans to place carved
ice furniture one hot day in a strategic location in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   While each actual promotion reaches just a few hundred people
personally, the idea is to get the word out with image makers and
bartenders about a ``hot'' drink. Literally dozens of drinks have
become popular via word-of-mouth over the years, whether it was
Corona Extra Beer, the Fuzzy Navel of the 1980s or today's
Cosmopolitan, a new twist on the martini.
</P>
<P>
   ``For drinks marketers it's important to get the trade behind a
new recipe or product,'' said David Ross, managing editor of Market
Watch, an industry magazine. ``And you have to get out there using
the old-fashioned shoe leather. Building a brand takes a lot of
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the hoopla is hype. Still, statistics do show evidence
that cocktails are making something of a comeback. After years of
declining volume, liquor consumption is up _ albeit slightly _ to a
total of 335.8 million gallons in 1998, a rise of just under 2
percent, according to the Distilled Spirits Council, a
Washington-based trade group.
</P>
<P>
   The industry had been in decline since 1981, because of growing
anti-alcohol sentiment, the fitness craze and a decline in the
number of young people. It bottomed out in 1995 at 326.7 million
gallons from a high of 449.5 million gallons in 1981, the spirits
council said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, prognosticators say volume will continue to grow for at
least several more years largely because of the ``echo boom,'' the
children of baby boomers who are now turning legal drinking age.
Frank Walters, Market Watch director of research, said his research
showed a direct correlation between a sharp rise in the number of
people turning legal drinking age and growth in the industry. In
fact, the last time he saw such growth was in the 1970s when the
largest number of baby boomers reached the legal drinking age.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Forman Corp., based in Louisville, Ky., said it was trying
to reach the young adult market through capitalizing on the retro
``lounge culture'' by distributing three swing music CDs with
750-milliliter bottles of Canadian Mist Whisky, the nation's
top-selling whisky import. Included with the CD is a packet of
drink recipes that include classics like the Manhattan and the
Whisky Sour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical to refresh the consumer category again and again
because 25-year-olds have a way of turning 35,'' said Dan Kelley,
Canadian Mist's vice president-brand general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Forman may have a tough sell. While so-called white goods
like vodka and rum are enjoying growth and lifting the overall
market, brown goods like bourbon and whisky are generally still
experiencing sluggish sales volume. One reason: Some say brown
goods are tougher to drink because they are an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   Still, younger people do seem to like the accouterments
surrounding cocktails _ the stirrer, the shaker, the special
glassware.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has played a part in the return of the classic cocktail
which has been ongoing for some years,'' said Jim Schleifer,
Absolut's marketing director at Seagram Americas in New York.
``It's the whole ambience of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mott's Inc., the juice company that also makes cocktail mixers
like Roses Lime Juice, said its research found a whole `cocktail
culture' of mostly 20- and 30-something people who enjoy the ritual
of mixing drinks, but prefer a lighter taste than some of the
classics. That insight led the company, a unit of Cadbury Schweppes
PLC, to develop Austin Powers' Shagadelic Shakers, premixed
nonalcoholic drinks in individual plastic shakers that re-create
the sound and feeling of a bar shaker once ice is added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our big insight was that cocktails have made a big comeback,
but that cocktails have changed,'' said Mike Judlowe, Mott's vice
president for marketing. ``The economy is good, people are older,
and people are drinking _ like anything else it's cyclical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
