<HEADER>
A6822 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     07-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AW-SHUCKS: NOLAN RYAN SIMPLY UNFORGETTABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ As his date with baseball immortality neared,
Nolan Ryan was at his down-home, everyman best yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of shuck-and-jive athletes, the humble Ryan is still
100 percent aw-shucks.
</P>
<P>
   So what can you say after a career that spanned 27 seasons and
included 324 victories? What can you say about a work ledger that
listed seven no-hitters and 5,714 strikeouts?
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask Nolan. He confessed yesterday that he hasn't yet
prepared his July 25 Hall of Fame acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, I'm not a speech giver,'' Ryan said with a
country blush.
</P>
<P>
   He has been informed that some previous Hall of Fame inductees
have taken as long as a full hour to render their words of
acceptance. That news seemed to pain Nolan beyond Advil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think mine, then, will be somewhere between two
minutes and an hour ... probably closer to the two minutes,'' Ryan
assessed.
</P>
<P>
   The midday news conference at The Ballpark in Arlington was
called to give the media one last chance to visit with Ryan before
he heads for Cooperstown, N.Y., for the induction. There were no
groundbreaking pronouncements _ Ruth Ryan's husband is not what
you'd call a rolling barrel of surprises.
</P>
<P>
   And it was no shock that current Rangers management plans to
honor Ryan with a weekend of festivities during the July 30-Aug. 1
Kansas City series. Nearly six years since he threw his last pitch,
in other words, Nolan is still filling seats for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Some athletes get a day named in their honor. But Arlington
Mayor Elzie Odom has proclaimed it Nolan Ryan Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, he is still citizen Ryan. Rancher, banker,
father, ex-ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that one of the nicer things about finally being
selected to the Baseball Hall of Fame is that he no longer has to
wince every time somebody introduces him as a ``future Hall of
Famer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never comfortable with that,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan recalled yesterday that he never even gave the milestone
much thought until he heard former Houston teammate Don Sutton
talking about a goal of reaching 300 wins. Sutton pointed out that
no pitcher with 300 or more career victories has ever been denied a
place in the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never thought of that before,'' said Ryan, who himself
was approaching 250 wins at the time.
</P>
<P>
   No. Nolan Ryan has never had a gold necklace that read, ``Future
Hall of Famer.'' Or ``7 No-Hitters.'' Or even a bumper sticker that
rightfully proclaimed, ``I whupped Robin Ventura's butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Not his style. The beauty of Nolan Ryan is that, for the most
part, he has no style. No pretenses. No flash.
</P>
<P>
   The headlock he put on Ventura in August 1993, was an episode
that Ryan said ``embarrassed me when it happened.'' He was
surprised to learn later that ``there was a generation that sort of
felt I represented something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Nolan said, blushing again, ``that when I was an
active player, I didn't realize that so many people looked at me as
a relic.''
</P>
<P>
   We knew better, of course. Ryan was 42 when he joined the
Rangers before the 1989 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to be here for one year,'' he repeated yesterday.
``I ended up playing for five.''
</P>
<P>
   He was destined to be a Hall of Famer even before he arrived
here. But it was in those five seasons that Ryan ascended to the
ranks of folk hero and legend. It remains a sad footnote that he
never got to pitch in The Ballpark in Arlington, retiring six
months before it opened.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in so many ways, The Ballpark is The House That Nolan Ryan
Built. His signing in 1989 filled seats and stirred long-suffering
fans' hopes. Suddenly, after Ryan was a Ranger, it was fashionable
to go watch the Rangers play again.
</P>
<P>
   Without Nolan, maybe there would have been no Ballpark in
Arlington yet. With no Nolan, the Rangers today might be a prairie
version of the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Ryan was able to visit the Baseball Hall of Fame to be
briefed on what lay ahead. Museum officials even showed him where
his own plaque would hang.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that quiet personal tour that Nolan admitted it all
began to sink in. He saw the scroll of all-time pitching leaders in
victories (324) and strikeouts (5,714) and felt humbled to see his
name listed so high.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan saw the museum's impressive display of no-hitters, and then
realized that, with seven, he merited a display case all his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a neat feeling,'' Nolan said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect much more oratory than that when the great day
arrives in Cooperstown later this month. Speeches, as he reminded
yesterday, are not his thing.
</P>
<P>
   As local relics go, he was the best there ever was.
</P>
<P>
   One last road trip, Nolan Ryan. It was five years that we won't
ever forget.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
