r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-01 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDRO MARTINEZ CHASING 30 WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tommy Lasorda said it. You can look it up.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 19, 1993, he lauded the acquisition of Delino DeShields
by declaring, ``As an everyday player we feel he will be more
valuable to us than the relief pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The relief pitcher Lasorda was alluding to was Pedro Martinez.
Six years later, the mere mention of the name is enough to make a
grown Los Angeles Dodgers fan cry.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers' blue chippers falter, Martinez's stock has
taken off like one of his 95 mph fastballs. Over the past few
years, Martinez's right arm has outperformed Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The skinny kid with the wild control that Lasorda and the
Dodgers unloaded went to Montreal, became a starter and, three
years later, a Cy Young Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   He was part of another transaction, in the winter of 1997, and
wound up in Boston where he won a second Cy Young in 1998. This
year he's tracking Denny McLain the way Mark McGwire did Roger
Maris last summer.
</P>
<P>
   If a broker misgauged a commodity as badly as did Lasorda, you'd
hand over what's left of your portfolio to somebody else. The
Dodgers not only have stuck with Lasorda, they're having him scout
talent.
</P>
<P>
   And people wonder why the Dodgers are getting such horrible
returns on their payroll dollars?
</P>
<P>
   Before Kevin Brown and Mo Vaughn and Mike Piazza, Martinez was
the highest-paid player in baseball. The Red Sox shelled out $75
million over six years for his services. It's looking like a
brilliant investment, what with Martinez posting a record of 19-7
in 33 starts in 1998 and starting this season 14-2.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old will try to collect his 15th win tonight, at
Chicago. Fifteen wins would bring Martinez halfway to immortality.
Since 1930, only three major-leaguers have reached the 30-win
milestone in a season. The last to do it was Detroit's McLain in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   A victory tonight would put Martinez ahead of McLain's madcap
pace. McLain, who was 24 in 1968, notched his 15th win on July 3.
Appearing regularly on three days' rest, he made 41 starts and
finished 31-6.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, like most pitchers of this era, will be blessed to get
34 starts. So in shooting for McLain's mark he has even less room
for error than when he's aiming for today's postage stamp-sized
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's not that wild of a pitch, casting Martinez in the
company of McLain and Dizzy Dean and Lefty Grove.
</P>
<P>
   Like the ex-Tigers right-hander, Martinez is getting tremendous
bat support. The Tigers averaged seven runs in games McLain
pitched. The Red Sox are averaging 5.5 with Martinez on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty wins belongs on the Mount Rushmore of baseball
milestones, alongside batting .400 and hitting safely in 56
straight games and slugging 70 home runs. They're all feats that
would seem utterly impossible if not for the fact somebody had gone
and set them in stone.
</P>
<P>
   McLain seemed an unlikely character to carve out a piece of
history. ``The kid never seemed to care enough,'' Bill Rigney once
said of the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   No question, McLain was the Dennis Rodman of his day. He was as
hard to read as his slider. His hair color alternated between red
and blond. He drank Pepsis by the case. He played the organ as
sweetly as Nancy Bea Hefley.
</P>
<P>
   He jetted to Vegas whenever the West Coast schedule permitted.
He loved to gamble. (The addiction would end his career in 1970 and
send his life in a spiral that ultimately landed him in prison.)
One writer in 1968 described him as ``a cigar-chomping, oral
compulsive.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all else, McLain liked to talk. His mouth got him into
trouble in 1968. The two-time Cy Young winner made the mistake of
telling a visiting writer that the fans in Detroit ``are the worst
I've ever seen anyplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Next thing the pitcher knew, one fan had placed a smoke bomb in
his car. Luckily for McLain, it malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   You should know the fans target Martinez's car, too. They
bombard it every time he tries to drive away from Fenway, pledging
their love and pleading for more autographs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the man poised to be the next McLain couldn't be more
different than him.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is so quiet, he slipped out of the clubhouse last
weekend before reporters could ask him about his outing against the
White Sox. In his place he left a handwritten note that said, ``I
felt good, physically and mentally. The day belongs to my teammates
for their offensive production. Thank-you. Love, Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after Martinez struck out 16 batters on the way to a
6-4 win over Atlanta, he gave all the credit to his catcher for
calling the right pitches. Whatever the reason, he has done little
wrong this season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is averaging 112.9 pitches per outing and he has 165
strikeouts, both of which are league highs.
</P>
<P>
   And Lasorda thought Martinez wasn't strong enough to survive in
the big leagues?
</P>
<P>
   If you ask us, ex-Dodger Brett Butler called it right when, on
the day Martinez was jettisoned to Montreal, he said, ``I'm blown
away that they traded probably one of the best pitchers we had on
the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the start of a bear market for the Dodgers, though it
would be a few years before the rest of us would get wise to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
