A6829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-GUGGENHEIMER-NYT     07-01 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUGGENHEIMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDOLPH GUGGENHEIMER, 91; SAVED COMMUNITY HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Randolph Guggenheimer, a Manhattan lawyer who helped
spearhead the development of a community hospital serving the
residents of Harlem, died on Thursday at his home in Manhattan. He
was 91.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hospital for Joint Diseases moved from Madison Avenue
and 124th Street in 1979, Guggenheimer and Eugene L. McCabe, a
management consultant, worked together to insure that hospital
services would continue in the old building, which was renamed
North General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheimer had been a board member of the Hospital for Joint
Diseases, but he opposed the decision to move because he believed
very strongly that Harlem needed a hospital. ``I thought, `I'm a
New Yorker, I was born in New York, I love the city, and there is
nothing there but Harlem Hospital, which is insufficient,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial crises threatened North General's existence several
times, and at one early point, the National Health and Human
Services Employees Union asked its members to continue working
despite a missed pay period. McCabe and Guggenheimer recruited
public officials, philanthropists, bankers, leaders of major
medical institutions and local businessmen to take care of the
foundering hospital's unpaid bills and to raise both money and
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Both Guggenheimer _ who served as the hospital's only trustee
for a time _ and McCabe were tireless in pursuing funds, and helped
to engineer a New York state bond issue of $150 million for a new
building that would serve the impoverished and medically deprived
area. At the time, many small community hospitals, overwhelmed with
the unexpected demands of AIDS patients and crack addicts, were
being closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make financial sense,'' said Mario Cuomo, who as
governor of New York approved many of the grants and loans to build
North General. Cuomo described the hospital's creation as ``a
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The state called the rebuilding of the hospital ``the largest
public-private construction project in the history of Harlem.'' In
1991, the new 200-bed North General, the only minority-operated
hospital in the state, opened its doors at Madison Avenue between
121st and 122d Streets. The nonprofit hospital specializes in
treatment for diabetes, cancer and hypertension.
</P>
<P>
   Several years later, the institution added 300 units of
condominium housing for low- and middle-income residents of Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Both Guggenheimer and McCabe took pride in the fact that the new
building was completed for some $15 million less than the amount of
their state bond financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we called up the state and asked what we should do with
the surplus money, they didn't know what to say,'' Guggenheimer
once recalled. ``It had never happened before. They finally told us
to keep it to avoid complications.'' The money was used to build an
annex.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe was president of the hospital and Guggenheimer was board
chairman, a position he held for some years. He maintained an
office in the hospital until his death. An annual award in his name
was established by the trustees in 1998, to be given to a member of
the hospital staff for excellence in community service.
Guggenheimer received the United Hospital Annual Distinguished
Trustee of the Year award and, in 1991, was honored by Mayor David
Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe died of cancer at the age of 61 in September 1998,
</P>
<P>
   In his dedication to Harlem, Guggenheimer followed the example
of his mother, Minna Schafer Guggenheimer, who from 1918 to 1964
produced the annual summer concerts at Lewisohn Stadium on the City
College campus. The concert series was a diamond in the New York
cultural scene for years, bringing major performers to the
neighborhood at admission fees of less than a dollar. Lewisohn
Stadium was torn down in 1966, two years after Mrs. Guggenheimer's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph Guggenheimer was born in Manhattan on Nov. 14, 1907.
His father, Charles S. Guggenheimer, was a partner in Guggenheimer
&AMP; Untermyer, a law firm his own father had founded.
</P>
<P>
   Minna Guggenheimer, a philanthropist known to New Yorkers as
Minnie, raised money, engaged artists and handled negotiations for
the stadium concerts. She attended most of them, and was famous for
her informality and completely uninhibited intermission speeches.
On one occasion, a royal guest got lost and wandered into the wings
as he was about to be introduced. Mrs. Guggenheimer chased after
him, yelling, ``Here, Prince! Here, Prince!''
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheimer was educated at the Morristown Preparatory Academy
in New Jersey and received a Bachelor of Arts degree from Yale
University in 1928. He graduated from Harvard Law School in 1931,
joined the family law firm and later became a partner. In 1932 he
married the former Elinor Coleman. She has been a member of the
City Planning Commission and commissioner of consumer affairs, and
was a founder of several national and international women's
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenheimer enlisted in the U.S. Air Force in 1942 and served
as executive officer of a fighter squadron in Europe during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, he was active in a number of organizations,
including the Jewish Child Care Association and the Mount Sinai
Hospital School of Nursing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two sons, Charles and
Randolph Jr., and a sister, Sophie Untermeyer, all of Manhattan,
three grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
