<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MASTER PLAN FOR THE EVERGLADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Thursday delivered to Congress a detailed
blueprint for the most ambitious environmental restoration project
ever undertaken in this country. The plan's basic purpose is to
restore the historical flows of fresh water that once made the
Everglades one of the world's most wondrous and biologically
diverse ecosystems. It is the product of six years of work by the
Army Corps of Engineers, scientists and environmentalists. But its
fate, and that of the Everglades, now rests with legislators in
Washington and Tallahassee. It is they who must provide the money _
nearly $8 billion over 20 years, shared equally between the federal
government and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That seems a lot, but then again, Congress owes the Everglades a
lot. Fifty-plus years ago, following back-to-back hurricanes that
put much of South Florida under water, Congress ordered the corps
to drain a half-million acres south of Lake Okeechobee with a vast
web of levees, canals and pumping stations. This massive project
kept Florida's booming east coast free from floods and safe for
development, and provided the rich soil for the state's sugar cane
industry. But it blocked the southerly movement of clean water,
drying up the Everglades, killing off much of the area's fabled
wildlife and degrading the rich fishing grounds of Florida Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The corps now hopes to set things right by recapturing and
rerouting most of the fresh water that is now wastefully flushed
out to sea _ 1.7 billion gallons every day. Its design includes
reservoirs to store the water, new canals to direct it southward,
artificial marshes to filter pollution from the cities and farms,
and the purchase of land to create buffer zones between people and
nature. The new system would also provide a secure supply of
drinking water for South Florida's exploding population.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is much improved over December's preliminary version,
thanks mainly to pressure from environmental groups, timely
intervention by senior officials at the Interior Department and the
White House, and the open-mindedness of Michael Davis, who oversees
the Corps of Engineers. The original plan favored the projected
needs of Florida's cities. The final plan is not perfect and will
require careful scientific monitoring to make the necessary
adjustments down the line. But it greatly increases water flows to
the Everglades, gives priority to projects that will help the
ecosystem and contains a written guarantee that nature will come
first during the life of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Financing the project will require a serious political
commitment from Florida's governor, Jeb Bush, who must master a
state legislature that often pays more attention to special
interests than to the interests of the Everglades. It will also
require help from Congress, which until last year had generously
underwritten engineering and land acquisition projects begun in
anticipation of the corps' comprehensive plan. But along with many
other federal programs, Everglades-related initiatives are now
being squeezed to meet Congression-ally mandated budget caps _ caps
that seem increasingly nonsensical in view of the projected budget
surpluses. Congress needs to think again. What is at risk here is
an extraordinary and irreplaceable national asset that happens to
be dying. Preserving and protecting it could serve as a model to
the world.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
