<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-SENTENCING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUOTING GOTTI'S FATHER, PROSECUTORS SEEK LONGER TERM FOR SON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (rk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors asked a judge Thursday to impose
the maximum possible prison sentence of more than seven years on
John A. Gotti, citing his refusal to admit that he was the acting
boss of the Gambino crime family and his failure to meet a deadline
for paying a $750,000 fine after his racketeering and extortion
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In April, on the eve of his trial, which could have led to a
sentence of 20 years, Gotti, 35, pleaded guilty to reduced charges
and faced a term ranging from 6 years and 10 months to 7 years and
3 months. Federal prosecutors detailed their reasons for requesting
the maximum term in a pre-sentencing memorandum laced with
sarcastic references to Gotti's reluctance to acknowledge the
existence of the Gambino organization or to concede that his
father, John J. Gotti, was the previous boss of the family.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum disclosed that John J. Gotti, 58, criticized his
son's lack of leadership. In 1991, the elder Gotti was sentenced to
life in prison without parole on federal murder and racketeering
charges, including being the boss of the Gambino family, said by
prosecutors to be the nation's second-largest Mafia group.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 29, 1998, three weeks after JohnA. Gotti, who is known
as Junior, was indicted, his father expressed disappointment with
his son's judgment and conduct. The elder Gotti made the remarks in
a conversation with his daughter, Victoria Gotti Agnello, and his
brother, Peter, at the Federal Penitentiary in Marion, Ill. All of
Gotti's prison visits are tape-recorded by prison authorities with
his knowledge, and a transcript of parts of the conversation were
made public Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Gotti, the prosecutors said in the memorandum, was
dismayed that his son had delegated to subordinates ``ministerial
tasks'' that he should have undertaken as the acting boss of the
Gambino family. The prosecutors supported their assertions by
noting that in the 1998 conversation, the elder Gotti asked, ``Why
do you need all these butlers and waiters for?''
</P>
<P>
   In the same conversation, according to a transcript, John J.
Gotti said he was stunned to learn that investigators, in a raid on
one of his son's offices in Queens, had found $358,000 in cash, a
promotion list of names that prosecutors said were new Mafia
members and an unregistered handgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what he gives them to hang their hat on,'' the elder
Gotti is quoted in the transcript. ``Funny money in the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same conversation, Gotti said his son should have placed
the money in a safe deposit box or in the care of a lawyer and
should not have kept the list of names.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent reference to contentions by the younger Gotti's
lawyers that he had been indicted because of his father's
conviction as a Mafia leader, the elder Gotti is quoted as saying:
``You can't blame it on last names.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum from Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in the
Southern District, was sent to Barrington D. Parker Jr., a federal
district court judge in White Plains who will sentence Gotti on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gotti, the prosecutors said, in pleading guilty to a charge of
being the head of a criminal enterprise, ``did not acknowledge that
the enterprise in question was the Gambino crime family.''
According to law enforcement officials, the elder Gotti has banned
Gambino family members who plead guilty from admitting they belong
to the Mafia group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
