<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ALBANY'S VACATION FROM INACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 2:
</P>
<P>
   New York's state government has taken gridlock to a new level.
Budgets in Albany used to be delayed until some other critical
deadline forced an agreement. But now even those triggers are not
enough to make things work. On Wednesday night, cuts in the state
Medicaid program lapsed, sticking the state and localities with
tens of millions of dollars in unexpected bills. Protections for
New York City loft tenants expired, terrifying many long-term
residents with limited incomes. But nothing happened. The
Legislature went away for a vacation and a ``cooling off'' period.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gov. George Pataki's staff sometimes jokes that the
state would save money running on emergency appropriations forever,
these delays are unsupportable. In New York City, the schools are
playing a dangerous but unavoidable game by presuming that money
for new prekindergarten programs and reduced-size classes in
September will eventually be approved, and risking financial
catastrophe if it is not. Other school districts are trying to
prepare their tax bills in a void.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the Legislature and Pataki seemed to have reached the
point that a more functional government would have got to in early
spring. A final budget agreement seemed near, perhaps in time to
break the logjam and pass other critical time-sensitive
legislation. But talks collapsed over the issue of Medicaid. The
Legislature had approved rather stiff cuts in the state's
reimbursement program to hospitals and nursing homes in 1995, and
Pataki had proposed new economies this year. The state's largest
hospital workers' union, led by Dennis Rivera, has been running
harsh ads against Pataki, portraying him as an enemy of the old and
the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The state should not be making a new assault on the health care
system at a time when New York's hospitals are already under siege
by the federal government and HMOs. Pataki may have already given
up on his new cost-cutting agenda. But if he has not, he should do
so quickly. The Democratic Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, is
pressing for an end to the old cuts as well. He should not try to
turn back the clock. Controlling Medicaid costs has always been
important in a state where the bill for treating the health care
needs of the poor is enormous and ever-expanding.
</P>
<P>
   But if it takes some reasonable concessions to get a budget deal
done, Pataki should compromise as a gesture of good will. Right now
the old cuts have expired anyway, pleasing the hospitals but
burdening the state with $82 million in unexpected costs over the
next three months alone. Local governments will have to pay about
$50 million extra. The meter is running.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping the pay of state legislators when they fail to pass a
budget on time does not seem to have worked. They have not got
their salaries since April, but most of them seem more cranky than
cowed. Pataki, whose bad relationship with Silver is central to the
impasse, still gets his salary. But he should perhaps be barred
from making any more out-of-state speaking trips to brag about New
York's fiscal achievements until the state has a functioning
budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
