<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESILIENT AMERICANS SURVIVE SCARE, ADVANCE TO SEMIFINALS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ The confused, disorganized American defense
continued its maddening habit of early breakdowns Thursday night in
the Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain did the unthinkable and put a shot into her own
goal in the fifth minute. Briana Scurry, the goalkeeper, spent the
first half glaring at her teammates with the molten stare of a
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has shown remarkable resilience as the
World Cup favorites, never displaying signs of panic or despair.
The team is strikingly fit and confident, and it overcame its early
disorder with two second-half goals to defeat Germany, 3-2, in a
quarterfinal match at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium witnessed by
President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With this nervous victory, the Americans advanced to the
semifinals on Sunday in Palo Alto, Calif., against Brazil, a 4-3
overtime winner over Nigeria. But the age and lack of speed in the
defense has left any potential title suddenly uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal was scored in the 66th minute, seconds after
Shannon MacMillan had replaced Julie Foudy in midfield. With a goal
and two assists against North Korea on Sunday, MacMillan had made a
case for becoming a full-time starter. Thursday night, immediately
after she entered, she placed a line drive of a corner kick into
the penalty area, and defender Joy Fawcett headed it in for a 3-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the second half started, down by 2-1, the Americans
huddled near midfield to discuss the urgency of the moment. This
was the knockout phase of the tournament. One defeat and they were
gone long before anyone had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   It took only four minutes for the United States to gain its
equilibrium. Mia Hamm, who had been marked deftly by Sandra Minnert
in the first half, lofted a long corner kick that carried beyond
the far post and deflected off the German defender Steffi Jones.
The ball bounced free six yards in front of the goal and Chastain
redeemed herself by nearly going into a slide and hammering it into
the net. Chastain then fell on her back and put her arms in the
air, as much in relief as celebration.
</P>
<P>
   It was Chastain's early error that continued what has become an
agonizing custom for the Americans. Thursday night, they suffered
two early defensive breakdowns. The first merely provided a scare;
the second resulted in the embarrassment of the United States
putting a shot into its own goal.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes into the match, Fawcett, often considered the
world's top defender, headed a pass back to Scurry. But the pass
was too soft and Germany's top scorer, Birgit Prinz ran onto the
ball. Only a desperate scramble by Scurry, who sprinted 14 yards
off her line to smother the ball, prevented a goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth minute, a lack of communication between Scurry and
Chastain resulted in the most unforgivable of mistakes _ an own
goal. Chastain easily intercepted a pass from the German midfielder
Maren Meinert inside the penalty area, but she appeared not to look
up as she played the ball back to Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, Scurry had vacated the goal mouth, charging
upfield. Chastain, who should have cleared the ball, got a stricken
look on her face as it rolled instead toward an empty net. Carla
Overbeck, the American captain, sprinted furiously toward the goal
line, attempting a rescue, but the ball rolled unimpeded into the
net to give Germany a stunning 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In a first-round game, the confused American defense had
surrendered a goal to Nigeria after two minutes, then scored seven
unanswered goals, but Germany was too well organized for such
capitulation. Victory for the Americans appeared suddenly
precarious, as did continued public interest in the World Cup and
the future possibility of a women's professional league.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans are not easily rattled, and they kept moving
forward, creating chances to tie the score. In the 16th minute,
Michelle Akers fired a shot from 20 yards that pounded off the
torso of Meinert and bounced into the penalty area. The German
defense, already down one player after an injury took Bettina
Wiegmann out of the match briefly, reacted slowly, and Tiffeny
Milbrett pounced on the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   After a nervous start to the World Cup, Milbrett had regained
her status as the Americans' most reliable scorer, with two goals
against Nigeria and a productive second half against North Korea.
Thursday night, she sprinted onto the loose ball and blasted it
from 12 yards out, placing it underneath Silke Rottenberg, the
charging German goalkeeper, who had no chance for a save. In the
16th minute, the Americans had equalized at 1-1. But the tie would
not hold.
</P>
<P>
   As the first half went to extra time, the American defense found
itself out of position again. Parlow was a step slow, and Chastain
was caught flat-footed, as Wiegmann, a specialist on free kicks and
penalty kicks, took a pass from Sandra Smisek and rocketed a
left-footed shot from 22 yards inside the left post, beyond the
arms of the diving Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans had not surrendered a goal in the second half
of their three previous matches, and thanks to a more cohesive
defense and a vigilant Scurry, they did not again Thursday night.
And now they move to the semifinals, apprehensively, barely. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
